<SLUG> BC-DOCTOR-INDICTED-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER DOCTOR CHARGED IN DEATH OF 3 PATIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, S.D., Colo., Ill.)  By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Everywhere Michael J. Swango went, it seemed,
death soon followed. In medical school, as a young intern, as a
doctor, many of the patients he saw died. But he always managed to
find new posts _ even after he was convicted of trying to poison
several co-workers by putting ant-killer in their doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the case with the doughnuts, the authorities never
charged him with any violent crimes. But federal investigators here
said Tuesday that they had enough evidence to charge Swango with
the 1993 murders of three patients who were under his care at a
Veterans Affairs hospital in Northport and with a pattern of fraud
dating back to 1984 when, court papers charge, he killed a patient
in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The officials charged Swango _ who was to have been released
this Saturday from a federal prison in Colorado where he has served
a 3 and a half year sentence for fraudulently obtaining the
Northport post _ after exhuming the three New York patients and
finding poisons in their bodies. In some cases, the court papers
charge, Swango falsely claimed that he had obtained ``do not
resuscitate'' orders from relatives of his victims in order to make
their murders easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of using his medical license to become a healer,
Swango embarked upon a career as a killer,'' said Loretta E. Lynch,
the U.S. Attorney for the Eastern District of New York. ``Through a
web of lies and deception, Swango inveigled his way into the
confidence of hospital administrators across the country and the
world. Once in their trust and in their employ, he utilized his
skills to search for victims and take their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Swango, 45, could face the death penalty. His
lawyer, Randi Chavis, did not respond to repeated messages. In the
past, Swango has maintained his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   The three murder charges stem from incidents in 1993, when
Swango was hired as a medical resident by the Stony Brook Health
Sciences Center after lying to the admissions office, saying that
his previous conviction for poisoning stemmed from a ``barroom
brawl.'' As a Stony Brook intern, he was assigned to the Veterans
Affairs Medical Center in Northport.
</P>
<P>
   He had worked there for three months when Stony Brook officials
learned about his criminal past _ which had been featured in
newspapers and on national television _ and fired him. Stony Brook
officials said at the time that they had determined that no harm
had come to the 147 patients he treated there.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials disputed that Tuesday. They charged Swango
with killing three patients with lethal injections while at the
Northport hospital: Thomas Sammarco, 73; George Siano, 60, and Aldo
Serini, all of Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Stony Brook, Patrick Calabria, refused to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also charges Swango with assaulting a fourth
patient there, Barron Harris, by injecting him with paralyzing
medication. Harris, who was 60, then fell into a coma and later
died.
</P>
<P>
   There may have been many more victims, investigators said. Lynch
said that prosecutors believe that Swango may have been involved in
a number of other murders across the globe, from Ohio to Zimbabwe.
But she declined to speculate on how many there might be.
</P>
<P>
   In the indictment, though, prosecutors paint a portrait of a
serial killer who began in his very first job out of medical
school. After that, they charge, he lied and misrepresented himself
to obtain other medical jobs where he could kill again.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Blind Eye: The Terrifying Story of a Doctor Who Got Away
With Murder'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1999), James B. Stewart, contends
that the Swango case highlights the reluctance of the medical
profession to screen or sanction its own. ``The case shows that the
medical establishment will blindly trust the word of a fellow
doctor over the word of other witnesses, and that the medical
profession cannot adequately police itself,'' Stewart said Tuesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Stewart writes in the book that questions were raised about
Swango when he was a medical student at Southern Illinois
University: classmates called him Double-O Swango, joking that he
had a license to kill, because of the large number of his cases
that ended in deaths.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, as a medical resident at Ohio State University
Hospital, Swango was accused of causing a patient to have a seizure
after injecting something into her intravenous tube. The patient,
Rena Cooper, survived and told hospital officials about the attack,
but they did not believe her. The hospital found no evidence
against Swango, though a subsequent report on its investigation by
the dean of the university's law school found that the hospital had
not been thorough.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's indictment _ which was unsealed in federal District
Court here _ mentions the attack on Cooper and says that Swango
``murdered, attempted to murder and assaulted patients'' while at
Ohio State University Hospital. It also says that he murdered
Cynthia McGee, 19, in 1984 by giving her a potassium injection that
caused her heart to stop.
</P>
<P>
   David P. Ferguson, the associate vice president for university
relations, said that Ohio State had done its best to arrive at the
truth. ``We could all benefit from the clarity of hindsight,'' he
said, ``but we feel what we did was appropriate and diligent at the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Swango was not allowed to continue his residency there for a
second year. When he left, he returned to his native Illinois and
found work as an emergency medical technician with the Adams County
Ambulance Service. While there he was convicted of lacing his
co-workers' doughnuts and coffee with an arsenic-based ant-killer.
Five people became ill, but no one was killed.
</P>
<P>
   He was sentenced to five years in prison, but served only two.
</P>
<P>
   His sentence raised eyebrows in Ohio, where officials took
another look at his residency and found ``circumstantial evidence''
but no proof that he had committed crimes. When he got out of
prison, officials charged, Swango used false names and false
documents to try to get a number of medical positions. He was
rejected from the Ohio Valley Medical Center; hired by a Veterans
Hospital in South Dakota, but fired when his past became known, and
then hired by Stony Brook.
</P>
<P>
   After Swango was dismissed by Stony Brook in 1993, he went to
practice medicine in Zimbabwe _ where the authorities have issued a
warrant for his arrest on charges that he poisoned seven patients,
five of them fatally.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested in 1997, while stopping over in Chicago en route
to a new job as a doctor in Dharan, Saudi Arabia. He pleaded guilty
to making a false statement to Stony Brook officials, and went to
prison.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, the Department of Veterans Affairs and prosecutors,
meanwhile, began building their case against him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
