<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-FUNDRAISER-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFLUENCE-PEDDLING TRIAL BEGINS FOR A PATAKI FUND-RAISER 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Asserting that a ``pipeline'' of political corruption
stretched from Gov. George Pataki's campaign headquarters to the
highest levels of the state criminal justice system, a federal
prosecutor charged Tuesday that a volunteer fund-raiser had
illegally promised favorable parole rulings for three felons in
exchange for donations to Pataki's 1994 election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the fund-raiser, Yung Soo Yoo, called the
government's accusations ``a fairy tale'' and argued there was no
connection between the campaign donations and the parole of the
sole prisoner who was released.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer insisted that Yoo, a New Jersey businessman who was
often asked by the Republican Party to raise funds among
Korean-Americans, was simply ``trying to do a good deed'' by
advocating the prisoners' release, and that he was caught in the
unfortunate crosswinds of political interest.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Yoo stems from a two-and-a-half-year federal
investigation into accusations that Pataki officials used the
promise of early parole to help fill the governor's campaign
coffers. While the federal prosecutors overseeing the investigation
have repeatedly said there is no evidence that Pataki participated
in or had knowledge of the various crimes alleged, the case has
proved embarrassing for his administration, which has sought to
eliminate parole entirely and has made it tougher for violent
felons to win release on parole.
</P>
<P>
   The opening statements in the campaign corruption trial, which
began Tuesday in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn, presented starkly
different versions of the dealings among Yoo, officials close to
Pataki and the families of the three felons, John Kim, Bo Young
Chung and James Jhang. The three were convicted of several crimes,
including armed robberies and attempted murder.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors contend that Yoo acted illegally by
promising the families that he would use his political clout to get
their sons paroled if they donated more than $36,000 to Pataki's
election campaign. But Yoo's lawyer, Nicholas DeFeis, contended
there was no influence-peddling plot, in part because Kim, the only
one to eventually be released, was qualified under state guidelines
for parole.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In her opening statement Tuesday, Margaret Giordano, who is
prosecuting the case for the U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn,
laid out a detailed map of how the families' desire for their sons'
parole traveled through Yoo to officials in Pataki's campaign
office, the State Office of Community Affairs and the State
Division of Parole.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano said this ``pipeline'' was possible because Yoo was
friendly with Patrick Donahue, Pataki's campaign finance director,
and Grace Koh, who worked as a liaison to Asian constituents in the
Community Affairs office.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano said that before the 1994 election, Yoo and Donahue
secretly met with the families and promised to work to secure
parole for the three prisoners in exchange for the donations.
``Give me three more months and I'll make good,'' Giordano quoted
Donahue as saying to the families.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Koh nor Donahue has been charged in connection with the
case. Donahue's lawyer, Thomas Puccio, did not return phone calls
Tuesday seeking comment. Andrew Lawler, Koh's lawyer, was
unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   After Pataki took office, Giordano said, Koh ``sent signal after
signal'' to officials of the parole board, who received her message
clearly: ``The governor's office is calling and John Kim better be
released.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Giordano said, Koh assembled parole documents for
Kim and sent them to Brion D. Travis, the chairman of the parole
board. Giordano added that Travis then held a secret meeting with
one of his deputies, Ronald Hotaling, in which, according to the
government, Travis said he was ``getting a lot of heat from the
governor's office'' about Kim's release.
</P>
<P>
   Hotaling, who pleaded guilty in the case last year, relayed the
message to a pair of parole commissioners, the government said, who
eventually decided to release Kim in April 1996. One of the
commissioners, Sean McSherry, was found guilty in August 1999 of
lying to a federal grand jury about the case. The other
commissioner, Leo S. Levy, was charged last month with misleading
investigators in the case.
</P>
<P>
   In his opening statement, DeFeis said that Kim was released not
because of any illegal intercession by Yoo, but because he was an
``ideal candidate'' for parole. DeFeis said Kim's parole file
contained a recommendation for parole from the officer who arrested
him on armed robbery charges in Queens years ago and a similar
letter from one of his victims.
</P>
<P>
   DeFeis also contended it was the prisoners' families, not Yoo,
who were attempting to secure parole for the men through bribes.
``They are the bribers and the intended corrupters,'' DeFeis said.
``They were the ones who went to Yoo with bad intentions.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoo, he said, was interested only in doing a good deed. And in
return, DeFeis said, ``he received nothing for this _ not public
office, not a dime, nothing but aggravation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
