<SLUG> BC-FBN-IRVIN-FAME-TEX </SLUG>
 
TAYLOR GOT ELECTED TO HALL, SO IRVIN'S A SHOO-IN (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that Michael Irvin has officially called it a career, the
biggest question is where does he go from here.
</P>
<P>
   If this was any other football player, the answer would be
obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Football immortality.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin's football accomplishments as the best wide receiver in
Dallas Cowboys history dictate that five years from now he should
join Steve Young and Dan Marino as members of the Pro Football Hall
of Fame Class of 2004.
</P>
<P>
   His numbers, 750 catches for 11,904 yards and 65 touchdowns in
12 years, are indisputable.
</P>
<P>
   Both the catches and yards rank among the top 10 in NFL history.
He is third in 100-yard games, with 47. His 15.9-yards-per-catch
average is better than any of his peers did in the 1990s; Jerry
Rice was second at 15.3 yards per catch.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, Irvin rose to the occasion in the clutch. He
kept the chains moving on third down, caught tough passes over the
middle and proved to be a game breaker in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Toss in the fact that Irvin was not only a member of three Super
Bowl title teams but the actual driving force behind them, and it
seems ridiculous to doubt that Irvin's Hall of Fame resume would
pass the litmus test of greatness in any era.
</P>
<P>
   But Irvin didn't play in any era. He came along during the
high-tech age of sports when Monopoly-money salaries and
intensified media scrutiny have proved to be a combustible mix.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin _ who ate cereal with water as a child because his family
(he has 16 siblings) couldn't always afford milk _ thoroughly
enjoyed the spoils of his career with cars, suits, jewelry and fur
coats. He played hard on the field and partied hard off of it.
</P>
<P>
   This brings us to that fateful night in 1996 when Irvin was
busted in a Irving hotel room with drugs and a couple of strippers.
He pleaded no contest to felony drug possession and was sentenced
to four years deferred probation.
</P>
<P>
   For that, Irvin has been labeled as the poster child for the
bad-boy image that has smudged the sports landscape in recent
years. Moreover, there are those who plan to use character
questions to block his entrance into the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Those people, however, should be flagged for piling on, as they
are undoubtedly using a recanted rape allegation and a
training-camp fight in a dorm room as fodder for their position.
</P>
<P>
   The woman who alleged rape went to jail after admitting she made
the whole thing up. The Cowboys, the NFL and Irvin's probation
officials ruled that the dorm tussle that left guard Everett McIver
with a cut on his neck was unfortunate and regrettable, but not
criminal.
</P>
<P>
   The facts are that Irvin is guilty of only one damning
transgression. And that slate has been wiped clean now that he has
completed probation and regained all rights and privileges as a
regular citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Should Irvin continue to be punished for a crime even after
paying his debt to society?
</P>
<P>
   Also, to use that incident against Irvin would mean that the
lessons learned from last year's Hall induction of former New York
Giants linebacker Lawrence Taylor have been ignored. Not only did
Taylor flunk multiple drug tests during his NFL career, but he has
been arrested twice on drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his bust is in the Hall of Fame because his on-field
exploits warranted his induction.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto for Irvin, who never drew the NFL's ire by flunking a drug
test and whose status as one of the hardest workers in franchise
history serves as proof that his off-field dealings never
interfered with his commitment to the team.
</P>
<P>
   Now, let the five-year wait begin. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
