<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-IRVIN-IMAGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRVIN WASN'T THE BEST, SO IMAGE CAN HURT CHANCES OF ENSHRINEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Irvin is one of the Dallas Cowboys' all-time greatest
players. By definition, that should make him one of the NFL's
all-time greatest players.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing is ever that simple with Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, who retired Tuesday because of a spinal condition, caught
almost everything thrown his way for 12 years. However, he isn't
likely to catch a break from the 38 writers and broadcasters who
elect players into the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is an indictment of the voters rather than Irvin.
Lawrence Taylor once called them ``old phonies'' unfit to judge
him. But that is exactly what they do.
</P>
<P>
   The selectors are the judge and the jury of the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Irvin pleaded no contest to second-degree felony
cocaine possession in exchange for four years of deferred probation
and a $10,000 fine. There also was a recanted rape allegation that
saw his accuser sent to jail for lying, and a training-camp fight
that left offensive lineman Everett McIver with a cut on his neck.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike baseball, which has punished Pete Rose for his gambling
problems, football's Hall of Fame has no criteria for citizenship
in its bylaws.
</P>
<P>
   But former Minnesota Vikings defensive end Carl Eller, a former
drug addict who was accused of sexual assault last year, is
unlikely to ever be rewarded for his five All-Pro selections and
his six Pro Bowl appearances that spanned a 16-year career. Draw
your own conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   And though Taylor was arguably the NFL's greatest linebacker,
his election in his first year of eligibility was not unanimous.
Taylor twice was charged with drug-related offenses after his
retirement from the New York Giants in 1993, including pleading no
contest to purchasing $50 worth of crack cocaine from an undercover
police officer in St. Pete Beach, Fla., in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Despite backlash from some selection committee members for his
off-field problems, Taylor was rewarded for what he did on the
field when he earned football immortality last year.
</P>
<P>
   But it isn't only Irvin's drug bust that might prevent him from
getting a bust in Canton.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin will never be mentioned as the NFL's greatest receiver. He
was a great player, but being a great player is not nearly enough
to assure election into the Hall. Call it the politics of football.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Youngblood, one of the NFL's all-time great defensive ends,
has been waiting and waiting and waiting for his induction.
</P>
<P>
   Sacks were not recognized by the NFL as an official statistic
until 1982. Youngblood played from 1971-84, so the NFL credits him
with the 24 sacks he had in his last three seasons. But Youngblood
had 126.5 sacks before that. His 150.5 total sacks are surpassed in
NFL history by only Reggie White (192.5), Deacon Jones (173.5) and
Bruce Smith (171).
</P>
<P>
   Youngblood, who played with the Los Angeles Rams, survived the
final cut to six in his first year of eligibility, which is as
close to the Hall doors as he has come in 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin is tied for 10th in NFL history in career receptions with
750 and ranks ninth in receiving yards at 11,904. He also has three
Super Bowl rings. Is it enough for the 80 percent approval
necessary?
</P>
<P>
   James Lofton played 16 seasons. He made All-Pro four times. He
played in eight Pro Bowls and three Super Bowls. Only Jerry Rice
has more receiving yards than Lofton's 14,004, and Lofton ranks
ninth in receptions.
</P>
<P>
   So why isn't Lofton in the Hall of Fame? Lofton doesn't have a
Super Bowl ring, but Lynn Swann and John Stallworth each have four,
and they aren't enshrined.
</P>
<P>
   It might be easier to get through the eye of a needle than into
Canton.
</P>
<P>
   That means Irvin should expect induction into the Cowboys' Ring
of Honor. He can only hope for induction into the Hall of Fame. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
