<HEADLINE>
ALL-STAR FORMAT NEEDS REVAMPING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ (begin ital)Today's All-Star, No-Bull edition of
The Sporting Muse:(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   - If Major League Baseball begins to fret about the public's
attention span and interest in the All-Star game, it only has
itself to blame.
</P>
<P>
   The game's importance and relevance has been watered down
considerably the last few years for a variety of reasons --
expansion that has swelled rosters to 30-plus including injury
replacements, free agency that sends players flying across league
lines, and interleague play that has removed the special,
once-a-year atmosphere that was the game's focus.
</P>
<P>
   In the era before cable television and free agency, the All-Star
game was the only chance to see Stan Musial and Ted Williams on the
same field. Or even in a more contemporary time, a career A.L.
player like Reggie Jackson against a career National Leaguer like
Pete Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this stat: Of the more than 60 players elected or added
to the all-star team, including those who opted out due to injury,
25 of them have played in both leagues during their career,
including both starting pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe it's time to change the format and take advantage of
baseball's diversity. A U.S. versus the World format would
definitely give the game some bite.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the starters, reserves and replacements who made the
2000 rosters, here's how the lineups for Tuesday's game might have
looked with that kind of format:
</P>
<P>
   World: P, Pedro Martinez (Dominican Republic); C, Ivan Rodriguez
(Puerto Rico); 1B, Andres Galarraga (Venezuela); 2B, Roberto Alomar
(P.R); 3B Tony Batista (D.R.); SS, Edgar Renteria (Colombia); LF
Vladimir Guerrero (D.R.); CF, Bernie Williams (P.R.); RF Sammy Sosa
(D.R.); DH, Magglio Ordonez (Venezuela); Closer, Mariano Rivera
(Panama).
</P>
<P>
   Aside from those 11 players, there were seven other players from
other countries on the field in Atlanta, including Cincinnati's
Danny Graves, who was born in Vietnam, and Florida's Ryan Dempster,
who is Canadian.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.: P, Randy Johnson; C, Mike Piazza; 1B, Mark McGwire; 2B,
Jeff Kent; 3B, Cal Ripken; SS, Alex Rodriguez; LF, Barry Bonds; CF,
Ken Griffey Jr.; RF, Jermaine Dye; DH, Darin Erstad; Closer, Trevor
Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's this: A West versus East game that would also break
league barriers and embrace continental drift. Again, using the
2000 rosters, how about these teams, sprinkling in players from the
Caribbean into the East team?
</P>
<P>
   East: P, Martinez; C, Piazza (Philly); 1B, Todd Helton
(Tennessee); 2B, Alomar or Ray Durham (North Carolina); 3B, Chipper
Jones (Florida) or Ripken (Maryland); SS, Derek Jeter (New York) or
Rodriguez (Florida); LF, Gary Sheffield (Florida); CF, Griffey
(born in Philly, raised in Cincinnati); RF, Carl Everett (Florida);
Closer, Derek Lowe (Michigan).
</P>
<P>
   The opponent could even be an all-California unit.
</P>
<P>
   West: P, Johnson (Walnut Creek, USC) or David Wells (Torrance);
C, Jason Kendall (Torrance) or Mike Lieberthal (Glendora); 1B,
McGwire (Pomona, USC) or Jason Giambi (West Covina, Long Beach
State); 2B, Kent (Bellflower); 3B, Troy Glaus (Tarzana, UCLA); SS,
Nomar Garciaparra (Whittier); LF, Barry Bonds (Riverside); CF, Jim
Edmonds (Fullerton); RF, Brian Giles (El Cajon); Closer, Hoffman
(Bellflower).
</P>
<P>
   That's not even all the all-stars who hail from the state --
there's also Ryan Klesko (Westminster), Jermaine Dye (Vacaville),
Mike Sweeney (Orange), Darryl Kile (Garden Grove) and Jeff Cirillo
(Pasadena).
</P>
<P>
   Some people would consider it politically incorrect and
exclusionary, but I'd be fascinated by an all-star format that
honored the Negro League and the barrier Jackie Robinson broke and
create a team of African-American stars.
</P>
<P>
   It would at least put a sense of spectacle back in the All-Star
game. And where does it say a little controversy is bad? ...
</P>
<P>
   - Tuesday's game was deadly dull. The absence of the McGwires
and Ripkens undoubtedly was a letdown, not that any of their
replacements were wanting. Part of the blame has to go to the crowd
in Atlanta, which isn't known for being raucous, unless they're
doing that dreaded Tomahawk Chop.
</P>
<P>
   And allow me to be the first to express relief that it never
reared its ugly chant.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from seeing Derek Jeter have a nice game and Chipper and
Galarraga do well in front of the home crowd, the game was a
non-event. Most poignant moment: The camera catching the Angels
Troy Glaus yawning during the eighth inning. ...
</P>
<P>
   - NBC's coverage was as mundane as the game. I miss Bob Uecker,
who may not have been much of an analyst but would could be counted
on to drop a few good one-liners or zingers.
</P>
<P>
   Airing tape of dugout conversations was nice, but this is the
kind of event that screams for a live microphone on a few players
who could lend commentary to the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Like, how about a microphone on injured pitcher Greg Maddux, who
could talk about how he would pitch Jeter? Or a mic on Giambi
talking about what it's like to face Johnson or Tom Glavine?
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has personality, but humdrum affairs like Tuesdays say
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   - Best line of the night, from NBC's Bob Costas: ``If you're
scoring at home, stop.'' ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
