<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-ROSTER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS SEEK MIX OF OLD AND NEW TO BUILD ON SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let the guesswork begin.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Mavericks just completed their five-day minicamp for
rookies, free agents and selected veterans, and one thing seems
certain: nearly half the roster will be overhauled when the 2000-01
season begins in November.
</P>
<P>
   So the question becomes, who will make the cut for the new-look
Mavs?
</P>
<P>
   Barring possible trades, six holdovers appear to be locks to
return, and the four rookie draft picks also seem assured roster
slots. That leaves two spots on the 12-man roster open, plus two or
three more spots for players likely to be carried on the injured
list.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs' two best players, All-Star guard Michael Finley and
ever-improving forward Dirk Nowitzki, are nearly untouchable. Any
hopes of fielding a contender are contingent on building around
those two, owner Mark Cuban has said.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Steve Nash, center Shawn Bradley, free-agent power
forward Gary Trent and small forward Cedric Ceballos also figure in
next season's plans.
</P>
<P>
   Contract issues make Nash and Bradley nearly untradeable _ Nash
has more than five years remaining on a deal paying him more than
$5 million per season, while Bradley enters the last year of his
contract paying him more than $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Trent, who had a breakout season two years ago before missing
nearly all of 1999-2000 with injuries, is expected to re-sign with
the team Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos, the Mavs' third-leading scorer, shuffled in and out of
the starting lineup last season. He will likely come off the bench
this season.
</P>
<P>
   The four rookies _ guard Courtney Alexander, and forwards Etan
Thomas, Donnell Harvey and Eduardo Najera _ also have roster spots
virtually clinched, but their roles this season should vary
greatly.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas and Alexander expect to see big minutes, with Thomas
providing a needed physical presence up front and Alexander, a
backcourt scoring boost off the bench as Finley's apprentice.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey remains a raw talent and could see time on the injured
list. He missed much of minicamp with a strained groin muscle. ``He
could be the next Dennis Rodman, without the hair,'' Mavericks
assistant coach Donnie Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Najera has impressed coaches with his all-around play, but
finding minutes for him could be difficult. Najera is also making
the switch from college power forward to NBA small forward,
prolonging his adjustment period to the pro game.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the rookies, the Mavs picked up two veterans on draft
day through trades. Point guard Eric Murdock, from the Los Angeles
Clippers, and forward John Wallace, from New York, strengthen the
bench. Mavs coach Don Nelson has told Murdock, who missed 42 games
last season and recently had an MRI done on his right knee, that he
will back up Nash.
</P>
<P>
   Add it up and that makes 12. So where does that leave free
agents Hubert Davis and Greg Buckner, who both contributed greatly
last season, centers Bruno Sundov and Hot Rod Williams, and guards
Damon Jones and Robert Pack?
</P>
<P>
   Sundov, Williams, Jones and Pack appear to be on the way out. If
the Mavs can't trade Williams and Pack, the team will have to
absorb their contracts, more than $6 million combined this season.
Williams probably would retire, while the oft-injured Pack would
try to sign elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Sundov set himself back by missing minicamp with a sprained left
ankle and Jones has been told to look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Buckner, a restricted free agent, has received a three-year,
$2.5 million deal with Vancouver, leaving his return questionable.
The Mavs had offered Buckner a contract starting at about $500,000
per year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the money, Buckner is looking for more playing
time and the Mavs appear loaded in the backcourt. Cuban said he
would probably match the offer, but in doing so the Mavs would
expend valuable cap room next year and part of their salary-cap
exceptions this season.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the league's 3-point shooting percentage leader last
season, is a safer bet to come back, though he's listening to
offers from several teams. The Mavs have offered a one-year deal
between $3.5 million-$4 million, while Davis would prefer the
security of a three or four-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs, who have a $2.25 million salary-cap exception, are
also in the hunt for a backup center. They have expressed interest
in free agents Scot Pollard (Sacramento), Jahidi White (Washington)
and Brad Miller (Charlotte). Gheorghe Muresan, the 7-foot-7 free
agent who spent the past two seasons in New Jersey and is playing
on the Mavs' summer-league team, is also a possibility. MINICAMP
SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs' summer-league team left Monday to play an 11-game
schedule, beginning Tuesday in Long Beach, Calif., and concluding
in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them to realize that this is a full-time job, there's
no break from now until October,'' owner Mark Cuban said.
``Everybody wants to get better and that's what's important to
me.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
