<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSOURI-POLL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST POLL SHOWS BUSH SURGING AHEAD OF GORE IN MISSOURI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Up by only two points in February, Republican
George W. Bush has surged to an 11-point lead over Democrat Al Gore
in Missouri, one of the key swing states in the presidential race,
according to a new poll.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, commissioned by The Kansas City Star, showed Bush
leading Gore by 48 percent to 37 percent as the candidates approach
their party conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Third-party contenders barely registered. Reform Party candidate
Pat Buchanan attracted 2 percent support, as did Green Party
nominee Ralph Nader, the consumer advocate. Undecided voters
totaled 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's strong showing is considered significant because of
Missouri's standing as one of the nation's most reliable
presidential bellwether states. Missouri voters have picked every
presidential winner but one _ Dwight Eisenhower in 1956 _ in the
20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is expected to do well in the South and West, with the
exception of the West Coast. Gore is expected to do better in the
Northeast. Political observers say Gore will have to win most of a
belt of key states that includes Pennsylvania, Ohio, Michigan,
Illinois and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   In national polls that draw responses from all states, Bush is
ahead in virtually every recent poll, although the margin of his
lead varies. A Gallup Poll conducted for CNN and USA Today in late
June had Bush up over Gore 50 percent to 38 percent, with Nader
drawing 6 percent and Buchanan 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another late-June survey for Fox News had Bush leading by the
smaller margin of 42 percent to 37 percent, with Nader at 7 percent
and Buchanan at 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In February, before the Missouri primary, the Texas governor led
the vice president in Missouri by 44 percent to 42 percent, a
statistical tie, when a survey by The Star asked about a potential
race between Gore, Bush and Buchanan. At the time, however, Sen.
John McCain of Arizona and former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey
were still in the primary contest.
</P>
<P>
   The trend shown by the latest poll pleased Bush aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the poll reflects the strength of Governor Bush's
leadership message on reforming Social Security, rebuilding the
military and being a different kind of Republican,'' said Bush
spokesman Tucker Eskew. ``That has enormous appeal in Missouri and
across the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Gore dismissed the poll as relatively
meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Polls at this point are just snapshots in time,'' said Gore
aide Jano Cabrera. ``It's July. People are focused on...hanging out
with their kids, planning vacations. At this point, the last thing
they're thinking about is the issues and the experience of the
candidates, which will come later.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Gore has been the subject of critical news
stories that have questioned the direction and focus of his
campaign. Also receiving coverage was Gore's involvement in
questionable fund-raising practices in the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Since the earlier poll, Gore's unfavorable recognition rose 7
points as Bush's dropped 6 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results don't surprise me, because Gore has taken a lot of
negative publicity lately and so it's evidently had an effect,''
said St. Louis University political scientist Ken Warren.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 624 registered voters who said they vote regularly
was conducted by Mason-Dixon Polling &AMP; Research Inc. of Washington
from Thursday to Monday. The poll had a margin of error of plus or
minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Mason-Dixon found that Bush led in all areas of Missouri,
although his leads in the state's two largest cities _ Kansas City
and St. Louis _ were about the margin of error. Those cities are
considered traditional Democratic strongholds.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the four rural regions, he led by at least 8 points,
with his largest lead coming in the GOP-dominant southwest
Missouri, where survey respondents favored Bush by 2 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush has stuck to a positive message, a consistent
message, and he hasn't had to change who he is or what he believes
in in order to respond to the latest poll or focus group,'' Eskew
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore spokesman Cabrera said the race would tighten once
voters began to examine Bush's plans for tax cuts and changes in
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   In another positive sign for Bush, the poll showed the governor
leading among both Missouri men and women. In 1996, Republican
nominee Bob Dole had a particularly difficult time attracting women
to his fold, and the resulting gender gap undermined his chances of
defeating President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was up over Gore among women by 44 percent to 41 percent
and among men by a sizable 52 percent to 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst, political scientist Barbara Sinclair of the
University of California at Los Angeles, said Bush's chief campaign
theme of ``compassionate conservative'' is paying off.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's managing to project a somewhat softer, more caring
image'' that sells well with women, Sinclair said.
</P>
<P>
   Men are backing Bush because males are most likely to agree with
a central GOP belief that people should get ahead on their own,
Sinclair said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And everything from tax cuts to being strong on defense and
pro-gun tends to be more appealing to men,'' she added, referring
to some of Bush's core ideas.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush's lead continues, one question will be whether other GOP
candidates in Missouri can expect to enjoy a coattails bump at the
polls, courtesy of their popular presidential candidate. The state
is the site of highly competitive races for the U.S. Senate,
governor and a slew of other statewide offices.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans shouldn't count on too much, said professor
Warren of St. Louis University. A bounce from a winning
presidential contender tends to be statistically insignificant, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most times, candidates running statewide or for Congress win
or lose on their own merits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
