u s BC-BBO-ALLSTARS-NYT &LR;      07-12 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETER LEADS AMERICAN LEAGUE TO VICTORY IN ALL-STAR GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Derek Jeter tucked his jersey into his uniform pants
and listed the people who were at the All-Star Game to watch him
start for the American League on Tuesday night. Jeter mentioned his
parents, his sister and three of his friends from New York, shaking
his head as he talked about securing enough decent tickets. But
Jeter should not have stopped his list at six.
</P>
<P>
   Beside Jeter's family and friends, there were 51,317 other fans
who were at Turner Field to watch him. It happened that way because
the game that was missing marquee players like Mark McGwire, Ken
Griffey Jr., Alex Rodriguez and Pedro Martinez, and was being
called the All-Scar Game, developed into another perfect stage for
the amazing Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter stroked three hits, knocked in two runs and scored one run
to power the American League past the National League, 6-3, and
became the first New York Yankee to be voted most valuable player
in the All-Star Game since the award was instituted in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre chose his shortstop as the starter after
Rodriguez sustained a concussion last Friday, and Jeter poked a
two-run single off the New York Mets' Al Leiter in the fourth
inning to break a 1-1 tie in helping the A.L. win the game for the
fourth straight year. Leiter wound up the losing pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``This definitely means a lot,'' Jeter said before the game.
``At this position, especially in our league, you never know if you
might get another chance to start. I have to cherish it. You never
know if you'll get a chance again.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter will undoubtedly get another chance. Yogi Berra, Mickey
Mantle, Roger Maris, Reggie Jackson, Thurman Munson, Dave Winfield,
Reggie Jackson, Don Mattingly, Rickey Henderson, Paul O'Neill and
Mariano Rivera have played in All-Star Games as Yankees over the
last 38 years, but none ever claimed the award that Jeter did on
Tuesday night. After all the attention on who was not playing,
Jeter made sure that fans noticed who was playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``No player likes to see a player get hurt, especially in a game
like this,'' Jeter said of the missing players. ``But there are
still a lot of good players in this game.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans lined up outside Turner Field early on a steamy day.
Some had their tickets, some were searching for tickets and most
were eager to watch the finest players in baseball. Well, they were
eager to see most of the best players in baseball. The list of
injured players was stunning for its size and stature.
</P>
<P>
   Players like McGwire, Griffey, Rodriguez, Martinez, Cal Ripken
Jr., Mike Piazza, Barry Bonds and Greg Maddux are not
once-in-a-lifetime All-Stars. They are future Hall of Famers and
the kind of players fans thirst to watch in this game each July.
But all eight, plus Manny Ramirez, were spectators this time.
</P>
<P>
   If Roberto Alomar's bruised right elbow had prevented him from
playing second base for the American League on Tuesday night, there
would have been at least one player for all nine positions on the
All-Injury team. Atlanta's Bobby Cox, the National League manager,
lamented that some fans would not get to see ``their heroes and
superstars.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were still plenty of stars on hand, and plenty of
excellent performances. Jeter doubled in the first inning, the only
blemish off Randy Johnson in Johnson's eight-pitch cruise through
his only inning. David Wells was crisper as he whiffed two in two
shutout innings, throwing 23 of his 27 pitches for strikes and then
hanging out with his 8-year-old son, Brandon, in the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I enjoy the spotlight for the fact that I'm afraid to
fail,'' Wells said. ``I want to be the hero.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Jeter. The A.L. loaded the bases against Leiter in the
fourth on a walk, Travis Fryman's single and Barry Larkin's error.
With one out, Jeter, the Yankee, faced Leiter, the Met. The two
opposed each other last Friday when the Yankees beat the Mets, 2-1,
at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter had spoken to Alomar earlier in the game about trying to
resist swinging at Leiter's cut fastball, a pitch that starts out
over the plate and dives in hard on right-handed batters. Leiter
threw the cutter on the first pitch. Jeter could not resist, and he
blooped it over Larkin for a two-run single that put the A.L. ahead
to stay, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hit it well,'' said Jeter, who had struck out in his
other two All-Star at-bats before Tuesday night and decided to
swing early in the count. ``I just hit it in the right place.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown, the N.L.'s third pitcher, had scant control as the
A.L. took a 1-0 lead in the third. After Jim Edmonds sprinted to
the center-field warning track and made a gorgeous basket catch
over the shoulder on Mike Bordick's 395-foot fly ball, Brown looked
lost. The $105 million pitcher with the mean streak had a wild
streak.
</P>
<P>
   He walked Alomar, and Jeter squirted a single over second base
for his second hit. Bernie Williams grounded to third for the
second out, but Brown walked Jason Giambi on a 3-2 pitch to fill
the bases. Brown then fell behind by 3-0 on Carl Everett. The crowd
booed. Brown rebounded to pump two high fastballs by Everett, but
he unleashed another high fastball for ball four to score the first
run.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the third, Chipper Jones quickly tied the score
when he belted James Baldwin's 2-0 fastball to left-center field
for a homer. Since Jones was playing on his home field, he rounded
the bases with a huge smile. When he touched the plate, he used
both hands to point to the fans behind the plate. He became the
13th All-Star to homer in his own ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome,'' said Jones. ``I mean, it's every little
boy's dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones made a bid to be the hero when he had one of the three
singles off Oakland's Jason Isringhausen to chisel the deficit to
3-2 in the fifth. But Isringhausen retired Sammy Sosa on a fly ball
to center and got Jeff Kent on an infield pop to preserve a one-run
lead and keep Jeter's two-run single as the most important hit of
the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get butterflies before the game,'' Jeter said. ``It's a
situation where you've got the best players in baseball here. You
want to have fun, but you also want to do well. But the No. 1
priority, I think, is just to come out here and give the fans a
good show.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
