<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREFIGHTERS: BEWARE OF WATER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Fort Bragg, Calif., Volunteer Fire
Department recently special-ordered a very large pair of fire
boots.
</P>
<P>
   VFD secretary Vanette St. John opened the package, inspected the
boots and found a tag that read: ``Avoid getting wet.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the Fort Bragg VFD forgot to specify that they are
 &UR; not  &LR; one of those outfits that fights fires by beating them out
with Ping-Pong paddles.
</P>
<P>
   IN A SIMILAR vein, I was strolling around Pac Bell Park one
recent game and came upon a booth near the bleachers where salesmen
were trying to collar folks into applying for a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Their gimmick was that if you filled out the application, they
gave you a nifty baseball glove. Free!
</P>
<P>
   I was fairly sure these were not mink-lined, $250 Barry
Bonds-model gloves, but they looked fairly cool, so I signed
aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Took glove out of bag, noticed that the leather had the supple
feel of a pack of cigarettes. Saw large stamped warning on glove
that glove is not be used for playing of baseball. Pushed on web.
Web laces snapped.
</P>
<P>
   So if you get one of these gloves and give it to your kid _ and
who else would you give it to, your mother-in-law? _ be sure to
tell the kid to make sure to carry a small bag to collect broken
teeth.
</P>
<P>
   I know credit card firms do sleazy things, like asking you to
send them money every month if you charge stuff on the card, but
this is low.
</P>
<P>
   MUNI BUSES have advertising placards inside, and sometimes the
placards carry ``Streetfare'' poems, created by folks like you and
me and printed by Muni for the cultural edification of us all.
</P>
<P>
   So Elizabeth Chur looked twice before she realized this one poem
was not Muni issue, but was slapped up there on the ad space by
some underground poet. It was titled ``Muni Haiku 13,'' and it
went:
</P>
<P>
   ``Apology is/unnecessary when no /schedule exists.''
</P>
<P>
   Chur notes that the last line is one syllable short of a haiku,
unless you use the British pronunciation ``shed-u-ul.''
</P>
<P>
   MISTAKES MADE here, fresh daily, although I prefer to think of
them as amusing bloopers &AMP; blunders that could be the basis of a
humorous TV show, if only I could get Ed McMahon and Dick Clark to
host it.
</P>
<P>
   First up, Ruger guns (Or should that be firearms? Or
constitutionally approved devices for control of a run-amok
government?) are  &UR; not  &LR; foreign-made, since they are made in
Connecticut. But you have to agree, they  &UR; sound  &LR; foreign. But then
so does Haagen-Dazs.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of ice cream, the original Swensen's ice cream parlor
is indeed still in operation, at Union and Hyde, but that happens
to be on Russian Hill, not in Cow Hollow.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Gallagher passes along a trivia note about Cow Hollow:
Octavia Gough was a dairyman's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Starting now, I assume nothing. I once assumed that Cow Hollow's
name might have come about because that area was once a gathering
place for artists to bring large wooden carvings of cows and then,
using special tools and secret techniques, hollow them out.
</P>
<P>
   Got time for one more correction? David Bell tactfully notes,
``It's the Amish who raise barns in a day, not the Quakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that just like the Quakers, holier than thou, to think
they're above such folderol as helping a neighbor raise a barn?
</P>
<P>
   THEY CAN'T get enough culture up there in wine country.
</P>
<P>
   Meadowood Resort's annual Opera on the Lawn Thursday (ticket
sales open to the public) won't be just any old opera that you can
hear at any old opera house. Maestro Richard Williams and S.F.
Opera director Richard Harrell have co-created a special
for-this-gig-only performance.
</P>
<P>
   Superb dining and wining and opera-buffing. And if this doesn't
go over, next year Meadowood will probably say the heck with it and
put on a tribute to Grand Funk Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   JEFF KENT of the Giants and Jason Giambi of the A's were in the
starting lineups of last night's All-Star Game, thanks to the
dogged efforts of Bay Area voters.
</P>
<P>
   The local fans stuffed the ballot boxes via the Internet. And
there were folks like the man  &LR; husband and wife who sat in their
Lower Box 106 at Pac Bell Park, night after night, hand-punching
thousands of ballots for Kent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Chicago politics,'' a Giants exec told me, ``but for
a good cause.''
</P>
<P>
   And how about that All-Star Home Run contest Monday night? The
TV announcers did a magnificent job of turning a glorified batting
practice session into the shelling of Ft. Sumter.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to have those guys broadcast one hour of my life, to
make it seem exciting.
</P>
<P>
   AND SPEAKING of sports ... It's a shame that Bill Rojas got
bounced out of another big-time job.
</P>
<P>
   The rumor is he's the leading candidate to be the next coach of
the Golden State Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   WARNING: This column is not suitable for swatting of flies
and/or mosquitoes. It may leave dangerous and unsightly ink stains
on walls, and may be harmful to flies and/or mosquitoes. Properly
folded, however, this column can be used to catch baseballs.
Consult your local origami master.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
