<SLUG> BC-MISSIONS-RESTORATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUNDATION BEGINS $50.5 MILLION EFFORT TO RESTORE
CALIFORNIA'S  MISSIONS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARL NOLTE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A San Francisco foundation has begun a $50.5
million campaign to restore the 21 Spanish missions that are among
the oldest and least understood institutions in the West.
</P>
<P>
   The missions, which flourished in the years before the American
flag flew over California, are viewed either as relics of a
romantic vanished past or symbols of European imperialism that
destroyed the native culture.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is more complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I stand outside Mission San Jose, I tell people that it's
true that the way of life of my ancestors no longer exists because
of the presence of this colonial institution,'' said Andrew Galvan,
an Ohlone Indian who is helping raise money to preserve the
missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, when I go inside I see the place where my
great-great-grandfather was baptized.
</P>
<P>
   ``These missions were built by Indians and for Indians,'' Galvan
said. ``We are all connected to these missions, as a spiritual
home, as a symbol of the survival of a people, or as a symbol of
oppression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find myself in an odd juxtaposition,'' said Galvan, who is
an archaeologist interested in the 3,000-year history of his
people.
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of the end of the world of the Indian people came
in 1769, when the first Spanish mission was founded in San Diego.
When the last mission was founded, by the Mexican authorities at
Sonoma in 1823, the Franciscan padres had a string of 21 missions,
each a day's journey apart, connected by a road called El Camino
Real.
</P>
<P>
   They had converted thousands of the California Indians, but
thousands more died of disease, of overwork or of the shock of
cultural contact with the Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   The missions were really the beginning of modern California, for
better or worse.
</P>
<P>
   The missions introduced modern agriculture to California, built
irrigation ditches, introduced the growing of grapes and the first
orange trees. The style of the missions _ whitewashed adobe with
graceful bell towers and arches _ has been widely copied in public
buildings and homes.
</P>
<P>
   Entire small cities _ like Santa Barbara _ have embraced the
mission style. Even a national fast-food chain _ Taco Bell _ uses a
modified mission-style building.
</P>
<P>
   But the old missions have a lot of problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The missions need help,'' said Rick Ameil, president of the
California Missions Foundation, a private group that is raising
money for restoration and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The list is long and the price tag is high.'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has a list of repairs, seismic work, projects and
other items that totals $50.7 million, ranging from $5.1 million at
La Purisima Conception near Lompoc to $500,000 for Mission San
Carlos Borromeo in Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the missions need seismic work. Some, like the famous
and beautiful Mission San Juan Capistrano, are crumbling away under
the onslaught of time. San Juan needs $5 million in repairs.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, Mission San Jose, founded 203 years ago in what
is now Fremont, has a portion of the original adobe that Ameil says
``is in such bad shape that the city of Fremont has ordered it
either closed or demolished.''
</P>
<P>
   The building is the oldest in Alameda County. The cost of
repairs and other work is $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Mission San Francisco de Asis, usually called Mission Dolores,
has had a problem with beetles that have eaten the wooden statues
and part of the building's paneling. The foundation gave Mission
Dolores $25,000 last week as a 224th birthday present, but the
total cost for an overhaul is $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   One of the worst, Ameil says, is Mission San Miguel, one of the
best preserved of all the missions and centerpiece of the small
town of San Miguel on Highway 101 just south of Paso Robles. ``San
Miguel is in very bad shape,'' said Ameil. ``One earthquake would
probably take that place down.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two of the 21 missions are funded by a government agency,
Ameil says. All of them are short of money. ``There is no one
entity looking after the long-term restoration and preservation
needs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The missions have had a curious history, both hated and loved.
The first U.S. citizens to visit California thought the life of the
Spanish and Mexicans romantic and indolent. ``In the hands of an
enterprising people,'' wrote one of them, ``what a place this would
be.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Gold Rush transformed California after 1849, the native
Hispanics, who called themselves Californios, were pushed aside.
The Indians were simply exterminated by the Americans _ the Indian
population fell as low as 30,000 in 1860, according to some
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Annals of San Francisco'' the American historian Frank
Soule wrote of the old California, ``Even in the least frequented
corners of the earth is there a nation so stupid, of such
contracted ideas, as weak in both body and mind as the unhappy
Californians, ... better, a thousand times better that the missions
... should be ruthlessly swept away.''
</P>
<P>
   The missions did in fact crumble away, until the 1880s, when
Helen Hunt Jackson in her novel ``Ramona,'' and Charles Fletcher
Lummis, sought to romanticize the old missions. Jackson wrote of
the happy Indians toiling to the sound of the mission bells, and
Lummis called the missions remnants of ``the sleepy Spanish past,
... of the old days of romance.''
</P>
<P>
   Lummis, one of the grand promoters of California, founded a
magazine called ``Land of Sunshine'' and became so enamored of the
Spanish days that he began dressing as a Californio and calling
himself ``Don Carlos.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lummis attracted the attention of Phoebe Apperson Hearst,
who persuaded her son, publisher William Randolph Hearst, to take
up the cause of the missions.
</P>
<P>
   The old buildings, many of them in ruins, were acquired, rebuilt
and remodeled in a sort of new golden age of the missions.
</P>
<P>
   By 1913, Hearst and Rep. Joseph R. Knowland, owner of the
Oakland Tribune, bought Mission San Francisco Solano in Sonoma from
a private owner for $13,000. It is now a state park.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the missions became icons of an older
California, and were visited by schoolchildren and tourists.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1980s, however, native activists presented a revisionist
history of the missions, and accused the Spaniards and mission
founder Junipero Serra of racism and genocide.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is probably somewhere in between, but the past is
closely mingled with the present.
</P>
<P>
   California Missions Foundation president, Ameil, is a descendant
of Felipe Santiago Garcia, who came to Mission San Diego in 1774.
Garcia served in five missions and had 21 children. One of them,
Ameil says, was the first European child born in what was then Alta
California.
</P>
<P>
   Ameil recruited Galvan to serve on his board.
</P>
<P>
   Galvan says he wants to be sure ``the Indian story is not
forgotten in the mission story.''
</P>
<P>
   He was at Mission Dolores in San Francisco for its 224th
birthday celebration recently and led a prayer to the four
directions of the world in the churchyard. ``There are 5,000 Ohlone
burials in that yard,'' he said, ``And it was important that
someone like me should lead a prayer for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
