r n BC-UCBERKELEY-REBATE-SFC     07-12 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UCBERKELEY-REBATE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 UC BERKELEY OFFERING $500 REBATE FOR EARLY GRADUATION  &HT;     By Tanya Schevitz 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY _ Attempting to accommodate the first wave in what is
expected to be a deluge of new students, the University of
California at Berkeley is offering its seniors a $500 rebate if
they attend summer school and graduate in August instead of
sticking around another semester.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat here at my desk and I thought to myself, `Now what would
get my attention if I were a senior?' '' said Gary Penders,
director of summer sessions, ``It seems to be working.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, 316 students have applied for the graduation payoff, and
there is still time for others to sign up for the program, which
runs through August 11.
</P>
<P>
   Their graduation will help make room for the 400 extra students
UC expects in the fall as children of Baby Boomers _ now moving
through junior high and high schools _ spill into universities and
cause enrollment to begin a steady climb.
</P>
<P>
   The early graduation proposal is the first of its kind in the
10-campus UC system and could become a model program. UC is already
throwing around a proposal to offer students who graduate in four
years a rebate on their last regular-term fee _ about $2,000,
Penders said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is one way to expand. The university is trying to
accommodate more students,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With California struggling to find a way to deal with a tidal
wave of students projected to crash into the state's colleges and
universities in the next 10 years, UC needs to more than triple its
summer enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   The system is expected to make room for 63,000 additional
students _ including 4,000 at UC Berkeley _ by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Fox, executive director of the California Postsecondary
Education Commission, hailed the campus' creativity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no one answer to the tidal wave of students, so we
need a variety of responses,'' Fox said. ``Anything that shortens
the time to degree is good, and if it is the rebate that motivates
the students, I think it is a great idea.''
</P>
<P>
   The summer sessions at UC are currently self-supporting, funded
by the student fees, making classes more expensive than the regular
semester.
</P>
<P>
   One course can cost between $800 and $900, while a full load in
the regular semester is about $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gov. Gray Davis has included $34 million in next year's
state budget to lower summer school fees and help the UC and
California State University campuses run year-round. Still,
students need an incentive to give up their summer jobs and travel.
</P>
<P>
   The lure of money worked for UC Berkeley senior Teresa
Rodriguez, who will finish up a double major in English and
physical anthropology this summer. Until she heard about the
program, she did not even know students could graduate in the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I wasn't sure that I was going to go. I made an
almost instantaneous decision after I found out about it,'' she
said of the rebate. ``It is a lot of money that you don't expect
for something that is a benefit anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   She will use her ``reward'' to visit a few graduate schools she
is considering for a doctorate program and will spend the fall
studying for the admissions exam instead of sitting in classes.
</P>
<P>
   She said the $500 was not the only advantage to summer classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a lot more relaxed, and there is a lot more interaction
in class,'' she said. ``Instructors tend to explore different
things.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer, about 9,400 UC Berkeley students, about 40 percent
of the undergraduates _ are in campus classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Another incentive for students to attend the summer sessions is
a change in the eligibility requirements for the Low Income Grant
Program. While last summer only students who received less than
$1,000 a year in family support for their education were eligible,
this year the threshold has been raised to $3,000, increasing the
pool of eligible students.
</P>
<P>
   The rebate program came out of the Expanded Enrollment Steering
Committee, a group of UC Berkeley administrators and faculty
members who have been studying ways of accommodating more students
on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought if we could convince them to do this, we could both
attract more students to the summer sessions and ultimately we
could admit more students in the fall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
