<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: RINGS MAKE JETER FIRST AMONG EQUALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Honus Wagner, Ernie Banks and Cal Ripken played in
three different eras. They were the best at their position in those
eras. Imagine if Wagner, Banks and Ripken played in the same era.
That mental exercise shouldn't be too difficult. Just look at the
present era and think Alex Rodriguez, Nomar Garciaparra and Derek
Jeter. They are a conglomerate of shortstops the baseball world has
never seen at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, Garciaparra and Jeter were all in Atlanta Tuesday
night on the same team, the American League All-Star team.
Rodriguez was elected to start but recently suffered a concussion
and couldn't play. Jeter started in his place and capitalized on
the opportunity, rapping a double and two singles, scoring the
A.L.'s first run for a 1-0 lead and driving in the next two against
Al Leiter for a 3-1 lead, all in the space of his limited night's
work of four innings at the start of the 6-3 victory. He was named
the game's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't take it for granted,'' the Yankees' shortstop said
of his All-Star performance. ``You never know if you're going to
come back.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear Mike Bordick talk, the All-Star game will be a perennial
part of Jeter's schedule. Bordick was here, too. Baltimore's
shortstop, he was named to eplace Rodriguez on the A.L. roster. The
collective shadow of Rodriguez, Garciaparra and Jeter looms so
large that Bordick wouldn't ordinarily even be noticed. He
understands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to be able to take ground balls out there with those guys
is a great thrill,'' Bordick said. ``As a player and a fan, I'd
want to see Alex on the field as well. It's unfortunate. I feel
good that I was next in line and got this opportunity, but I'm
upset that Alex got hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Bordick laughed. ``People,'' he continued, ``have been asking me
were you upset you weren't on the All-Star team? With Alex and
Nomar and Derek, no, I wasn't upset at all. These are the guys who
have been the superstars at that position ever since they've been
in the league and they continue to be consistent that way and doing
their superstar thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Bordick has no ego problem and certainly no illusions
about his place vis-a-vis the terrifically talented threesome, it
seemed to his listeners like a good idea to ask Bordick to offer
his view and assessment of his contemporaries. However laudatory he
was about all three, he kept coming back to Jeter, who has never
been elected an All-Star starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alex is certainly doing things, setting a precedent like Cal
did,'' said Bordick, who plays alongside Ripken, now a third
baseman. ``Cal was the best-hitting shortstop in the game, a
power-hitting shortstop. It seems like Alex is carrying it to
another level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Derek Jeter isn't going to have enough fingers for all the
rings he's going to be wearing. With him as the Yankee shortstop
and an incredible leader, not only does he do things consistently,
putting up good numbers offensively, but defensively he's the one
that keeps getting better out there. And Nomar Garciaparra, Ted
Williams said he could be the best hitter of all time. These three
guys are incredible. The thing about them is they do it every day
and every year, year in and year out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bordick was asked what he sees when he watches them play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively, all three guys are different,'' he said. ``Alex
is deceptive for as much ground as he covers for as big as he is.
Sometimes it doesn't look like he's even moving, but he's covering
so much ground he gets to these balls deep in the hole or up the
middle and has an incredibly strong arm. Nomar throws from
different angles and his body's all over the place, but he has that
incredible gracefulness. Derek is just as well rounded as all of
them. It seems like he can do it all out there, as far as the
range, the arm, jumping and throwing. All three of them are just
incredibly fun to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   If he could, Bordick added, he would meld them all together and
``make an incredible cyborg out of them.'' But he can't create that
supersupersuper shortstop. So which of the three does he think is
No. 1? He did not respond immediately. He thought for a few
seconds, then a few seconds more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``I don't know.'' But in the end, it
was the rings that made his decision for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Derek Jeter, to me, offensively is certainly consistent,''
Bordick said, then abandoned his effort to define his No. 1 by
dissecting the elements of each one's game. ``He's got the rings
and that certainly puts him apart from the others.''
</P>
<P>
   The rings are the three World Series rings Jeter has earned in
his four years with the Yankees. The Yankees, in his young career,
have gone to the World Series so often Jeter thinks that's a
routine part of their schedule. But, Bordick was reminded, Jeter
hasn't won those rings by himself, by his play at short or at bat.
He has had help from his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly,'' Bordick responded, ``but he's part of the
backbone, in the middle of that field. He's showing his leadership
skills and really taking hold of that team. I think the players
rally behind him and Bernie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, when I watch Derek Jeter, I see him getting better
and better. I'm not saying the other guys aren't getting better and
better. It's just the rings that really put me on Derek Jeter's
side. Pretty impressive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
