<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9689 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-ALSIDE-C0     07-12 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-ALSIDE-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jays' Wells compiling hefty All-Star resume
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Facing Sammy Sosa with two out in the first inning and
Jason Kendall with two out in the second, David Wells resorted to
curveballs that floated to the plate seemingly in slow motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get ahead in the count,'' Wells said, ``you can throw
anything up there. If you show you've got command of your pitches,
they can't sit on a certain pitch. And I had a good curveball
working.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa and Kendall each watched the pitch break over the plate for
a called third strike that quelled early National League scoring
ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get these guys with their bats on their shoulders,''
Wells said, ``it's a nice feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a feeling Wells has had all season. His two scoreless
innings Tuesday for the American League epitomized his performance
to this point. He earned the start with a 15-2 record that includes
an eight-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   He was undaunted by the imposing lineup the National League
trotted out. In three All-Star appearances, Wells has not given up
a run in 4 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Though halfway there, Wells isn't talking about a 30-win season.
And despite a late-career surge _ the 37-year-old left-hander has
66 victories over the past 3 1/2 seasons _ Wells doesn't entertain
the notion of making the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``All (the Hall of Fame) is going to get is my hat and that
jersey (from his perfect game two years ago),'' he said. ...That's
good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The two innings of work were enough for Wells, but he did have
one regret _ he didn't get to bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been nice,'' he said. ``Get up there and swing
for the fences. Knowing me, that's probably what I would have done.
Just go out there, hit any pitch _ anything straight, I had a
chance. You have a wrinkle in it, no way.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) it's fun up there, getting a bat in your hands. As a
pitcher, you never know _ you can probably win a game that way.''
</P>
<P>
   AL and New York Yankees manager Joe Torre had a different
approach: ``Joe said: `Just take three (strikes),''' Wells
recalled. ``I said, `OK, right.'''
</P>
<P>
   Wells was more excited about his Toronto Blue Jays' playoff
prospects. They are in a virtual tie with the Yankees for first in
the AL East.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees are right there; we're right there,'' he said. ``I
think the best pitching wins. With the young staff that we have,
they don't know what they have yet. I see it. It's a matter of
these guys putting it together, because they have tremendous arms.
Once they find command of their pitches, oh, boy, this could be a
good year for Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
