<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9690 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-LEDE-COX     07-12 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-LEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American League too much for National League
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For three isolated reasons, the American League won
the 71st All-Star game Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The AL was better on the mound, more consistent at the plate and
better in the field.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Derek Jeter went 3-for-3 with two RBIs and one run as
the night's MVP, leading the AL to 6-3 victory, its fourth straight
and 10th of the last 13 Midsummer Classics. The NL was outhit 10-9
(three extra-base hits to one) and gave up a critical unearned run
in the fourth on a botched double-play ball to Barry Larkin. The AL
never trailed. The NL has been outscored in this game, 29-13, since
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The game was attended by 51,323 fans, 1,261 more than Turner
Field's listed capacity. They saw Jeter become the first Yankees
player to ever win the All-Star MVP award.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in a game like this, you have to be in the right place
at the right time,'' Jeter said. ``I was very fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been watching that ever since he came to the big
leagues,'' said NL manager Bobby Cox, whose All-Star record dropped
to 1-4. ``Somebody in the clubhouse asked me if he was getting
better. I think he was this good when he first came up. That's why
he's here. He's an All-Star.''
</P>
<P>
   They can't blame this one on the Braves. Chipper Jones drove in
the National's first run with a third-inning homer. Andruw Jones
drove in the second with a fifth-inning single. Tom Glavine worked
a 1-2-3 fifth. Andres Galarraga, in one of the night's sweetest
moments, was welcomed to the plate with a standing ovation and
later singled.
</P>
<P>
   It would not be nearly enough. The NL was held hitless from the
fifth through the eighth, although Steve Finley drove in one run in
the ninth. But by then, the Americans had removed all drama with a
three-run ninth, with San Diego's Trevor Hoffman slapped around for
three consecutive singles.
</P>
<P>
   The National had closed to 3-2 in the fifth, and Atlanta fueled
it. Following Gary Sheffield's lead-off walk, Chipper Jones
produced his third hit of the night and Andruw Jones, in his first
All-Star at-bat, singled up the middle to score Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine was summoned to work the top of the fifth, and the
Braves left-hander became the first pitcher all nigt to retire the
side in order. Jones' homer was the only of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome,'' he said. ``I mean, it's every little boy's
dream.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't Al Leiter's. With New York Mets left-hander on to work
the fourth for the Nationals, Larkin's glove helped make a mess of
what had been a 1-1 game. After a walk to Jermaine Dye and a single
by Travis Fryman, pinch-hitter Mike Sweeney of Kansas City rolled
one to shortstop that took a quick hop as Larkin dropped his glove,
skipping off the heel.
</P>
<P>
   The error loaded the bases for Jeter, who produced his third hit
in three at-bats, driving in two runs with a single up the middle
for a 3-1 lead. Jeter knew what pitch Leiter would throw, did not
particularly want to offer at it and was hardly impressed with the
result.
</P>
<P>
   ``A cutter. I mean, he does it every time I face him,'' Jeter
said. ``I try to lay off it. I didn't hit it well. I just hit it in
the right place.''
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones had tied the game 1-1 in the third and made a
little history, too. He sent a 2-0 pitch from James Baldwin over
the center field wall, becoming the 13th player to every hit a home
run in his home park. He joins Hank Aaron on that list, who hit one
in Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   The night's foremost ovation belonged to Galarraga, who had the
packed house standing by the time he got to the plate in the second
for his first at-bat. Making his first All-Star start only nine
months after completing cancer treatments, Galarraga doffed his
helmet before drilled David Wells' first pitch on a line to left
field. Everett was able to glove it with just four steps.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga later singled in the fourth before coming out for
pinch-runner Todd Helton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't be something better than today,'' Galarraga said,
``to be with this team, to play this game today.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
