<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9691 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GALARRAGA-COX     07-12 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALARRAGA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Galarraga braces for the best at the All-Star game
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - No more regrets over what this All-Star Game wasn't.
That kind of thinking can be so wasteful anyway, as almost any
cancer patient will tell you.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints over all the players who no-showed Tuesday night
were to be washed away in a torrent of appreciation for one player
you couldn't have kept away with a sore knee or a restraining
order.
</P>
<P>
   Andres Galarraga was braced for the best. ``The exhibition game
in Venezuela, when there were so many cheers, my eyes got wet and I
tipped my hat five or six times. My first time back in Atlanta, my
eyes got wet then, too. And it probably will happen again in this
game,'' the Braves' healed first baseman said in anticipation of
Tuesday's emotional welcome.
</P>
<P>
   It began from the moment he walked out during the pregame parade
of players and their children. As he crossed the outfield with one
daughter in his arms, holding another by the hand and one more
trailing, the crowd sought him out and threw the first huzzahs his
way.
</P>
<P>
   No All-Star received a louder, longer Turner Field ovation
during the introductions than he _ who could hope to? How good was
it? It might have been even more sustained than what greets John
Rocker on his dash out of the home bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   So much talk of failed body parts, of heads and knees and backs
that cost this evening. What this All-Star Game didn't lack was a
heart.
</P>
<P>
   The National League starting roster well represented the power
the perseverance. Last year at this time, Galarraga was wrapping up
another round of chemotherapy on the non-Hodgkin's lymphoma in his
back. He had swollen to 40 pounds over his playing weight and lost
his hair while retaining his hope.
</P>
<P>
   Also throw into the syrupy mix of the All-Star elixir _ good for
what ails you _ the catcher's tale. Jason Kendall's year ago was
spent, ``on the couch, heavily medicated with my foot up.'' In
other words, the Pittsburgh catcher was pretty much your typical
home viewer.
</P>
<P>
   Last July 4, trying to beat out a bunt, misstepping at the bag,
Kendall suffered a ghastly, Ruffian-style dislocation of the right
ankle. The replays of him grasping his leg, with his foot dangling
as if unconnected to him, are still haunting. ``If the bone wasn't
sticking out of the skin, not as much would have been made of it,''
he now says, matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   For those players who missed the show, too bad. For Kendall,
``This time of year always felt like a holiday to me _ like
Halloween (granted, not an official holiday) or Easter. To be
playing in this game again is awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   These little stories within the grander game have helped elevate
it once more. Hey, everybody loves a good resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   To another, wider audience, Galarraga spun his tale of faith, of
being cleansed by a divine dream that made him know all would be
well. Making it back to the All-Star Game was but one more element
in some heavenly plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great story that puts a smile on your face,'' said
Yankees and American League manager Joe Torre.
</P>
<P>
   And we're going to gripe about Mark McGwire's aches?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we complain about too many little things. Sometimes
we go 0-for-4 and we're not driving somebody in, we get so angry
about that. Now when I go 0-for-4, I'm not happy, but I don't feel
angry or like hitting someone. That situation made me feel much
better, more patient, more relaxed,'' Galarraga said.
</P>
<P>
   Applying that to the moment, an All-Star Game found its place
and gained some peace Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
