<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9695 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-SPACE-STATION1-HNS &LR;      07-12 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-STATION1-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PROTON ROCKET FINALLY LOFTS SPACE STATION MODULE INTO
SPACE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Russian-made crew module for the U.S.-led international
space station thundered into orbit Wednesday from Central Asia,
leaving behind a two-year legacy of delay and doubt about the
country's allegiance to the project.
</P>
<P>
   Secured atop a towering Proton rocket, the 43-foot module that
is intended to serve as the living quarters for future residents of
the slowly developing space station soared from the Baikonur
Cosmodrome in Kazakhstan at 11:56 p.m. CDT Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The module represents the first major Russian contribution to
the $100 billion, 16-nation space station assembly effort. A poor
economy that provided only a trickle of government funding for the
module delayed the liftoff by 27 months, raising doubts about
Russia's willingness to participate in the massive project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen a huge amount of work go into this program,'' said
NASA's Mark Geyer, the station program's planning manager.
</P>
<P>
   As the orbital outpost's third major component, the crew module
would follow the launching of the first modules that were joined in
Earth orbit by a U.S. and Russian space shuttle crew in December
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Once linked to the previously launched modules, the Russian crew
habitat will furnish the growing orbital outpost with living
quarters and life support systems for three astronauts and
cosmonauts. Commanded by American Bill Shepherd, the first resident
crew is tentatively scheduled to lift off for a stay of three to
four months in late October.
</P>
<P>
   Also known as Zvezda, for ``star,'' and its Russian technical
designation, service module, the multifaceted habitat would also
add critical new control and propulsion capabilities. When
augmented by a U.S. crew habitat in a half-dozen years, Zvezda
would continue to function as the cornerstone of the international
station's large Russian segment.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes as planned, the unpiloted crew module will circle
the Earth until late July 25, when propulsion and navigation
systems on the two previously launched modules carry out a
challenging automated rendezvous and docking about 240 miles above
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The interim period will allow ground control teams in Russia to
adjust the altitude of the new module, test its control, navigation
and power systems to improve the odds of a successful linkup, said
Valery Ryumin, space station program manager for RSC Energia, the
Russian aerospace company that will supervise the linkup.
</P>
<P>
   The station's first segments have enough fuel for at least two
automated docking attempts.
</P>
<P>
   If neither is successful, Russian cosmonauts Genadi Padalka and
Nikolai Budarin will be standing by in Russia, prepared to launch
to the crew module aboard a Soyuz rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Once aboard the new crew habitat, they would orchestrate a
manual docking of the three modules.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be quite sure that if it is necessary, they will be
able to perform the task with a quite high probability of
success,'' said Yuri Malenchenko, a veteran cosmonaut and colleague
of Padalka's and Budarin's. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The joining of the three modules should trigger an
unprecedented flurry of space station construction activity.
Fifteen construction, supply and crew transport missions are
planned in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   The flights will boost the station's electrical power
production, add and equip the bus-sized American science laboratory
as well as provide an airlock to ease the many spacewalks that will
be required to complete the assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Full assembly will require at least another 40 U.S. and Russian
rocket launches with major components over the next five to six
year.
</P>
<P>
   The station's global participants envision that when fully
assembled, the new outpost will provide enclosed laboratories for a
range of physics, biology and medical experiments. They also plan
to use its high-altitude vantage point for environmental studies of
the Earth and tests of hardware for future human space exploration.
</P>
<P>
   Russia was invited to join the United States, Europe, Japan and
Canada as a station partner in 1993. Transforming the former Cold
War rivalry into a cooperative partnership has proven difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The original plans to launch the crew module in April 1998
slipped as the Russian government was unable to furnish the funding
in the midst of economic and political upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as the financial difficulties began to ease last year, the
35-year-old Russian Proton rocket experienced a pair of launching
failures in spite of its 98 percent record for success.
</P>
<P>
   The Proton losses were traced to poor workmanship of rocket
engine components in the economic and political turmoil that
accompanied the break up of the Soviet Union and the transfer of
its space program to the Russian republic.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the launch of Zvezda, uncertainly looms over Russia's
ability to carry out its other pledges to the station.
</P>
<P>
   The most crucial are a steady supply of Progress cargo capsules
with fuel and supplies for the station as well as the three-man
Soyuz capsules that will be parked at the station to serve as
lifeboats.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership hopes to offset the pressure. NASA's shuttle
will likely take on more of the cargo hauling duties. The Europeans
and Japanese intend to develop a Progress-style cargo spacecraft of
their own.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
