<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9696 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-HURTS-COX     07-12 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-HURTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some injured stars no-shows, but most attend
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A few hours before Tuesday's All-Star Game, Barry
Bonds filmed pregame a ctivities at Turner Field, including batting
practice, with a camcorder. If it was not clear before then, it was
then: the San Francisco Giants outfielder would be one of many
All-Star spectators instead of participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing great,'' Bonds said. ``I wish it could be different,
but it's not. So, I'm here to enjoy a great event. It's great to
play in these games. But if you can't, it's good to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   A thumb injury forced Bonds to miss the Midsummer Classic. Bonds
sounded frustrated when continually asked about his availability,
saying the team ``told me I'm out. To be honest, I'm tired of
talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was hard not to talk about the stars who watched. Chicago
Cubs right fielder Sammy Sosa was one of only four NL starters
selected by the fans who was able to start. In addition to Bonds,
injuries shelved Mike Piazza, Mark McGwire and Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Injuries happen; they are a part of the game,'' Sosa said.
``But it's good to see so many guys who could not play come to the
game anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey participated _ and lost to Sosa _ in the home run derby
Monday, but he was not on hand for Tuesday's game. McGwire was a
no-show, too.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Mariners shortstop Alex Rodriguez suffered a concussion
and injury to his left knee in a collision Friday with Los Angeles
Dodgers shortstop Alex Cora. Rodriguez did not like the idea of
being a spectator, but he did find something positive about the
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm optimistic the concussion will make me a smarter person,''
he joked.
</P>
<P>
   An MRI indicated there was no serious damage sustained in the
collision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed not to be able to play here, but I consider
it a blessing in disguise to have this happen now,'' Rodriguez
said. ``I would rather miss the All-Star Game and have a few days
to recover than face missing another four or five games of the
regular season.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I came to support the American League. That's the
least I could do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' Greg Maddux was in uniform, although getting hit in
the right shoulder by a batting practice line drive Saturday
prevented him from participating. The big absentee was Baltimore
Orioles third baseman Cal Ripken Jr., who has a back injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cal is Cal,'' Giants second baseman Jeff Kent said. ``You
can't really replace him. I know there are a lot of the big names
who couldn't play because of injuries. Everyone wants to see the
big stars, I understand that. But there are a lot of great players
in this game, so the other way to look at it is that there were
chances for some lesser-known players to get some of the
limelight.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Derek Jeter, the New York Yankees shortstop who would be
named the game's MVP: ``If you can't play, you can't play. But it's
great that the guys who can't play came to be here anyway. There's
nothing like the All-Star Game, so I would come, too, if I couldn't
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
