<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUMMER-LBPT </SLUG>
 
SUMMER LEAGUE STUNNED BY McRAE'S DEATH 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SEAN KEARNS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Players, coaches and scouts watched and played five Summer Pro
League basketball games Tuesday, but many minds were on Conrad
McRae, the 29-year-old former Syracuse star who collapsed on the
court at UC Irvine and died the day before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shook me up personally,'' said Eddie Elisa, who played with
McRae on New York city summer leagues. ``It was on my mind all day
yesterday and this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Elisa, a forward on the Seattle SuperSonics summer league team,
he also played against McRae overseas. In the Sonics 91-90 loss to
the Lakers Tuesday, he had eight points in 17 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of McRae's death is inconclusive, said Rod Thomas, a
supervising deputy with the Orange County Coroner's office. The
coroner's office will be conducting toxicology tests, which will
hold the results for at least a couple months.
</P>
<P>
   McRae had a history of health problems. While signed to a 10-day
contract with the Denver Nuggets, he collapsed during warmups
before a game against Golden State on April 12, 199.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to playing on the Magic summer league team, McRae had
signed a medical waiver and didn't indicate any previous health
problems, an NBA source said.
</P>
<P>
   Questions on McRae's health were referred to his agent, Mitch
Frankell. Phone calls to Frankell were not returned. The Magic
released a statement expressing condolences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're shocked at the news of the tragedy,'' said John Gabriel,
Magic general manager. ``Our thoughts and prayers are with his
family.''
</P>
<P>
   McRae, known for his athletic ability and being in good shape,
was practicing with the Orlando Magic for the Summer Pro League at
UC Irvine on Monday when he collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic wrapped up the two-hour practice with a running drill
called 17s. It's a drill where players run from sideline to
sideline 17 times. Normally the drill is timed to hit under a
minute. In this case the drill wasn't timed players said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an experience I witnessed first hand,' said Matt
Harpring, a forward on the Magic who was at the practice. ``When
you think about it, you think it's surreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he fell the trainer went out and did CPR right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Harpring added, ``It was kind of weird. It was kind of out of
the blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Due to McRae's death, the Magic pulled out of the Summer Pro
League. The team and players left Southern California Tuesday
morning. The SPL scheduled was reworked so there are still five
games a day.
</P>
<P>
   The practice at UC Irvine was the first for the Magic. McRae had
met the team in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Harpring said the trainer ran out right away and found no pulse.
There was a summer camp going on nearby and those trainers helped
out as well.
</P>
<P>
   The paramedics arrived on the scene shortly after, Harpring
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him laying there at the end,'' said Mike Miller, the
Magic first round draft pick and No. 5 overall selection. It was
Miller's first practice with the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Both Miller and Harpring said that McRae didn't appear to have
any problems leading up to the running drill.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA has had a number of tragedies over the past year.
Minnesota Timberwolve guard Malik Sealy and Charlotte Hornet Bobby
Phills both died in traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
   McRae played last season for Trieste in Italy. He averaged 10.9
points and 11 rebound a game. He played in 30 games and averaged
35.4 minutes a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very nice kid,'' said Dick McGuire, director of
scouting for the New York Knicks. The Knicks had McRae in for a
mini-camp. ``I don't know what you can think except to for feel
sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   McRae, 6-10, from Brooklyn, N.Y. played at Syracuse from
1989-1993, averaging nearly 13 points a game his senior season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a great guy,'' said Bill Curley, who played at Boston
College and faced McRae. ``He was a good kid. He always had a smile
on his face.''
</P>
<P>
   Madsen still out
</P>
<P>
   Laker first round draft pick Mark Madsen missed his third
straight game on Tuesday with a right wrist injury. Madsen first
hurt the wrist in a pre-draft workout when he was hit on the wrist.
</P>
<P>
   He went through four workouts with the Lakers before the wrist
began to seriously bother him. The Lakers have been holding him out
and Madsen said he is day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really anxious to get out there and play,'' Madsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey to D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Former UCLA guard Toby Bailey is off to join the Washington
Wizards summer league team at the end of this week. The Wizard are
playing summer league games in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   He is preparing for his stint with the Wizards on the Nutriola
team at the Summer Pro League. He had 16 points on 6 of 11 shooting
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey said he had taken a couple weeks off to recover from
tendonitis in his knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to get my timing back before I go to
Washington,'' said Bailey, who played last season with the Phoenix
Suns.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas in the house
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Mavericks made a summer league splash Tuesday
displaying four rookies in a blowout win over the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Equally impressive were forward Etan Thomas, the 12th overall
pick; Courtney Alexander, the 13th overall pick; Donnell Harvey,
the 22nd overall pick; and Eduardo Najera, the 38th overall pick.
</P>
<P>
   The game could have been a battle of rookies but none of the
Clippers four draft picks are playing in the Summer Pro League.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
