<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-CART-TMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CART RACE IN MAY GIVES TMS A 2001 SWEEP OF U.S. CIRCUITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ CART's high-tech race cars will team up with
Texas Motor Speedway's high-banked racetrack beginning in 2001,
when the 1.5-mile quadoval in Fort Worth will play host to every
major American racing series.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of the open-wheel Championship Auto Racing Teams
FedEx Series to TMS' schedule on Sunday, May 6, 2001, was announced
Tuesday by Eddie Gossage, the track's executive vice president and
general manager, and Bobby Rahal, CART's interim president and
chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is the culmination of a dream that we've been wanting to
put together for some time. It's a great day,'' Gossage said during
a news conference at The Movie Studios at Las Colinas. ``Next
season, it'll be the single greatest racing season in the history
of motorsports that any speedway has ever been able to put
together.''
</P>
<P>
   The inaugural CART Texas 600k, the first race of a three-year
sanctioning agreement, has been booked as part of a three-day
weekend that currently is all open-wheel. The schedule will include
a race for the Dayton Indy Lights Championship, CART's top
developmental series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is going to be a great event,'' said Rahal, a
three-time series champion, current team owner and member of CART's
board of directors. ``These are the world's fastest cars, so what
that's going to be like on this place is going to be something to
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of CART, TMS has firmed up five major
motorsports event weekends at the paved track, an increase of one
over 2000. Beginning in late March/early April, TMS will play host
to the NASCAR Winston Cup, Busch Grand National and Craftsman Truck
series; the open-wheel Indy Racing Northern Light Series, the
American Le Mans Series and BFGoodrich Tires Trans-Am Series. The
latter two series will compete on a 2.5-mile layout that combines
the oval and an infield road-course under construction.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the new Texas Motor Speedway Dirt Track will play
host to the Pennzoil World of Outlaws Series for Sprint Cars, the
Hav-A-Tampa Late Models and the Wrenchhead.com National Dirt Track
Series for motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other speedway in the world can boast of a schedule that we
can at Texas Motor Speedway now,'' said Gossage, seated on a dais
along with Rahal and 1996 CART champion Jimmy Vasser.
</P>
<P>
   Vasser, of Target/Chip Ganassi Racing, said he was eager to make
his first visit and turn his first wheel through TMS' 24-degree
banked turns. TMS will become the highest-banked track in the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we're ready to come here and put on a good show,''
said Vasser, anticipating a reduction in the 900-plus horsepower
currently cranked out by CART's turbocharged V-8s. ``CART's working
on that package right now, probably a horsepower reduction and some
aerodynamic drag issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come to Fort Worth and show our product, I think it's going
to be great, not only for CART and our racing teams, but for the
fans in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The CART race here will be televised by ABC. CART's addition is
a testimony to the series' desire to break into a Fort Worth-Dallas
market that historically has posted strong TV numbers even though
TMS has played host to Tony George's rival Indy Racing League since
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our objectives at CART is to align ourselves with the
best markets and the best racetrack promoters in the business,''
said Rahal, who was selected by CART's directors to replace Andrew
Craig after the latter's forced resignation on June 16. ``For all
kinds of reasons, it made sense for us to come down and work with
Eddie to put this together.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said the talks that resulted in this agreement
accelerated on June 22, just prior to a CART board of directors
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote them a simple one-page, three-paragraph letter saying
we want to have a CART FedEx Championship Series race, and we think
we'll fill the place,'' Gossage said. ``He (Rahal) went before the
board.''
</P>
<P>
   The IRL has competed at TMS twice a year since 1998, and has
drawn the largest crowds outside of the Indianapolis 500 at the
Indianapolis Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been rumors of this the last couple of years,'' said
Rahal, the 1986 Indy 500 champion. ``And it was just a matter of
understanding the promoter, how strong they are here; understanding
the market, how strong it is; understanding we're now working with
our cars to make them race-able anywhere the opportunity exists.''
</P>
<P>
   The event at TMS will give CART two in Texas. CART has competed
on a temporary street circuit through downtown Houston since 1998.
The Texaco/Havoline Grand Prix of Houston is scheduled for Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Rahal said the 2001 schedule, which is expected to grow from 20
to 22 races, was nearing completion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 90 percent there,'' Rahal said. ``I would suspect that
in a week to 10 days we'll have it done.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
