<HEADLINE>
CART INTENDS TO SLOW CARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The open-wheel cars of the Championship Auto
Racing Teams FedEx Series are the fastest in the world, boasts
interim CART president and CEO Bobby Rahal.
</P>
<P>
   And when CART runs its first race at Texas Motor Speedway next
May 6, it probably will record the fastest laps in the five-year
history of the 1.5-mile superspeedway with the 24-degree banked
turns. But even Rahal admits ``the fastest cars in the world'' need
to be slowed down before next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of all the type of circuits that we run on you are
going to see some type of power reduction,'' said Rahal, a
three-time series champion and team-owner who took the position
when Andrew Craig resigned under pressure last month. ``I think it
is important for us to have the fastest cars in the world and we
can still have the fastest races with 150 less horsepower. We don't
need over 900 horsepower at around 1,500 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Rahal and Eddie Gossage, executive vice president and general
manager of TMS, announced Tuesday that the series will run the
inaugural Texas 600k on May 6, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Under current CART rules, the open-wheel cars powered by
turbocharged eight-cylinder engines produce more than 900
horsepower. That would allow drivers to reach speeds of 230 mph at
TMS, even with the drag-inducing Handford Device mounted on the
rear wing.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest track the series currently races on is the two-mile
California Speedway, which is banked at 14 degrees. CART regular
Mauricio Gugelmin of PacWest Racing Group recorded a lap at 240.942
mph in Fontana, Calif., in 1997. It remains the fastest official
lap in auto-racing history. Gugelmin also ran a practice lap at
242.333 mph before qualifying, the fastest unofficial lap in
auto-racing history.
</P>
<P>
   Rahal said CART officials are discussing methods to take away as
much as 150 horsepower from the V-8 engines for next season, and
modifying the rear wings. But to do so, Rahal has to convince four
competitive engine manufacturers _ Ford-Cosworth, American Honda,
Mercedes-Benz and Toyota _ that such a move is the right course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surprisingly it has not been tough at all and they have been
very good about it,'' Rahal said. ``They are extremely competitive,
but they understand the most important thing we have to create is
the right product. We think the technical aspect is important for
our brand, and understanding what they want to achieve and what we
want to achieve, they have been very positive about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rahal added he was not sure what speeds the cars would produce
at TMS. Even with a horsepower reduction, speeds still could reach
220 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Those speeds are fine with Jimmy Vasser, the 1996 series
champion. Vasser said the 24-degree banking at TMS could produce
some interesting racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``TMS promotes good side-by-side, wheel-to-wheel racing,'' said
Vasser, who drives for Target/Chip Ganassi Racing and is teammate
to reigning CART and Indianapolis 500 champion Juan Montoya.
``Certainly our cars are very, very fast, but any kind of racing
that close at those speeds is thrilling, not only for the fans but
for us in the seat.''
</P>
<P>
   CART limits the amount of testing by individual teams, but Rahal
said CART cars could test at TMS this fall. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
