<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9705 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBO-ALL-STAR-HNS &LR;      07-12 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALL-STAR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Jeter's star shines brightest
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ New York Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter has three World
Series rings and a Rookie of the Year award to show for his brief
major-league career, which spans less than five full seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He has been on the cover of GQ, dated Mariah Carey and become
arguably the best player on the most storied team in baseball. And
if Jeter has a to-do list, he can scratch another item off it after
leading the American League to a 6-3 victory over the National
League on Tuesday night in the 71st annual All-Star Game at Turner
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter, who was 3-for-3 with a double and two singles, did
something Tuesday that no Yankee ever has done. Not Roger Maris.
Not Don Mattingly. Not even Mickey Mantle.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter became the first player in Yankees history to be named
Most Valuable Player in an All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of hard to believe,'' said AL manager Joe Torre, who
manages the Yankees. ``We've had some great, great players through
the years, and it's hard to believe no one ever won it.''
</P>
<P>
   The MVP honor and everything Jeter has accomplished in his short
time in pinstripes has some lumping him with Yankees legends. Jeter
bristles at that suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to play a lot of years to be considered a Yankee
great,'' he said. ``Hopefully I can play for a few more years and
continue that debate. But this is just my fifth year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very fortunate to have been at the right place at the
right time in a great organization. Down the road _ that's when you
sit back and reflect on your career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really sit around and think about that kind of stuff
right now. In due time, I'll realize how special it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter had struck out twice in his only two All-Star at-bats
prior to Tuesday's breakout, which included hits against Randy
Johnson, Kevin Brown and Al Leiter _ three of the nastiest pitchers
in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically had the same game plan against everyone,'' Jeter
said. ``I'm a free swinger. I think it's known around the league _
maybe both leagues. I wanted to at least put the ball in play.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're facing three guys like that, you want to swing
early in the count. If you fall behind, you're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Braves third baseman Chipper Jones would have been the
likely MVP choice if the NL had won the game. The reigning NL MVP
was 3-for-3 with a home run before a hometown crowd of 51,323.
</P>
<P>
   The game was played in an NL park and in typical NL style, but
the AL All-Stars managed to win for the fourth consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto Blue Jays 15-game winner David Wells started for the AL,
pitching two scoreless innings. AL starters have a string of eight
consecutive scoreless innings, dating to 1996 when Cleveland's
Charles Nagy allowed a pair of runs in the game, which was in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Wells allowed two hits and struck out Cubs slugger Sammy Sosa
and Pirates catcher Jason Kendall on slow-breaking curveballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get ahead in the count, you can throw anything up
there,'' Wells said. ``If you show you've got command of your
pitches, they can't sit on a certain pitch. I had a good curveball
working tonight; it's a blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, however, White Sox righthander James Baldwin, who
pitched one inning and allowed a run on two hits, who was credited
with the victory.
</P>
<P>
   NL starter Johnson, who pitched for the Diamondbacks on Sunday,
worked just one inning before leaving the game.
</P>
<P>
   Reds reliever Danny Graves also pitched a scoreless inning
before the AL broke through against Brown in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers righthander walked three batters, including Red Sox
outfielder Carl Everett with the bases loaded to force home the
first run of the game. The wild spell was rare for Brown, who is
averaging just 1.9 walks per nine innings this season with Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The NL tied the score in the bottom of the inning on Jones'
two-out solo homer off Baldwin. Jones became the 10th player to hit
a home run in an All-Star Game played in his home park, the first
since Cleveland's Sandy Alomar did it in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome,'' Jones said. ``I mean it's every little boy's
dream. It's not often that a player gets to play on his home field
in an All-Star Game, much less start.
</P>
<P>
   ``To go out there and hit a home run was just awesome. I can't
explain it. It was something I'll never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Mets lefty Leiter, who took the loss, allowed the first three
batters he faced to reach base in the fourth, and an error by Reds
shortstop Barry Larkin prolonged the inning, which was highlighted
by Jeter's two-run single up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hit it well; I just hit it in the right place,''
Jeter said. ``He's a tough pitcher. When he throws the ball, it
seems like it's going to go down the middle, and it runs off your
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The NL picked up another run in the fifth on an RBI single by
Braves center fielder Andruw Jones. The hit scored Dodgers
outfielder Gary Sheffield, who had led off the inning with a walk
against Athletics closer Jason Isringhausen.
</P>
<P>
   The AL scored three insurance runs off Padres closer Trevor
Hoffman in the ninth inning. Arizona's Steve Finley added an RBI
single in the ninth to complete the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
