   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, July 12.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FASCIST-ARCHITECTURE (Rome) _ The Italian government is going to
sell some of the jewels of Fascist architecture which has upset
Romans, who now treasure it after years of despising it. By
Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ In an aggressive bid to
topple the Republicans' fragile six-seat majority in the House of
Representatives, House Democrats have built and substantial
financial advantage over the Republicans. By Don Van Natta Jr. and
John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   VOTERS (Washington) _ A study of primary voting patterns shows
much more importance is attached to endorsements and debates than
experts had thought. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-DRUGS - With the battle over prescription drugs
shifting to the Senate, the chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee has broken with House Republicans and will propose a
government-administered program to offer drug benefits to all
Medicare recipients, senators of both parties said Tuesday. By
Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PRIVATE-SECTOR (Jiaxing, China) _ China has been marching
on the road of economic reform for more than two decades now, but
its private sector remains a tiny slice of an economy still
dominated by government-owned organizations. Entrepreneurs are
systematically shunned by China's banks, discriminated against by
regulators and barred from entering many industries. Barriers to
capital formation keep most private businesses from providing more
than a handful of jobs, but there is growing pressure to change
that. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   EMPLOYEE-THEFT (Undated) _ In virtually every sector of the
economy, and in businesses of all sizes and shapes, from shoestring
non-profits to giant corporations, employee theft is rising
sharply. Spurred by the gold-rush mentality of the late 1990s,
emboldened by technology and quick to prey on the loose financial
controls at start-ups and small companies, workers at every rung of
the corporate ladder are stealing more money than ever before,
fraud examiners say.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   JANUS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily column: Looking at Janus
Capital, the nation's hottest seller of mutual funds, which will be
spun off from its parent, Kansas City Southern Industries. By Danny
Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   NET-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Ask anyone in the direct response
industry to describe e-commerce, and you're bound to get the same
response: Internet retailing is simply another kind of direct
marketing, not fundamentally different from the catalog and club
businesses that have long made their money selling directly to
consumers. But, at least until recently, many online sellers did
not agree. When making advertising decisions, they viewed theirs as
a business apart, a totally new endeavor with new rules or, more
accurately, no rules. By Bernard Stamler.
</P>
<P>
   VARIG-SILVA (Sao Paulo) _ A profile of the new president of
Varig, Brazil's largest airline, Ozires Silva, a former top
executive at Embraer, the nation's leading exporter. By Jennifer L.
Rich.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-COWS (New York) _ Is it time to call a halt to the cow
invasion of New York? By Sarah Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   ROME-MUSEUM (Rome) _ Arts Abroad: Forcibly separating a mother
from her young children is always heartbreaking. It is even harder
when they have been together 500 years. But that is what has
happened here, where a bronze, ``The She-Wolf'' of the Capitoline
Museums, has been separated from her legendary (and also bronze)
children, Romulus and Remus, for an exhibition celebrating the myth
of the founding of Rome. The exhibition, which runs until Oct. 15,
inaugurates the opening of a new area of the Capitoline Museums,
renowned for their collection of ancient Roman sculptures. By
Elizabetta Povoledo.
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-MEMOIR (Undated) _ A professor's literary sleuthing
has stripped away a veneer of fiction from the a harrowing
Holocaust novel, ``Jakob Littner's Notes from a Hole in the
Ground,'' published in 1992 by the German writer Wolfgang Koeppen,
and given the book new standing as fact. By Ralph Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   TV-DAISY-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Pull My Daisy'' kicks off the
``Reel New York'' series. By Kathryn Shattuck.
</P>
<P>
   ARTS-AWARDS (Undated) _ The American painter Ellsworth Kelly,
the French sculptor Niki de Saint Phalle, the British architect
Richard Rogers, the German composer Hans Werner Henze and the
American composer and lyricist Stephen Sondheim are the recipients
of the 12th Praemium Imperiale Awards, presented by the Japan Art
Association for outstanding achievement in the arts. The recipients
were announced Tuesday at a ceremony at the Tate Modern in London.
By Kathryn Shattuck.
</P>
<P>
   GORKY-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Black Angel: the Life of Arshile
Gorky,'' by Nouritza Matossian (Overlook). By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Maureen Dowd looks at the upcoming
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Paul Krugman on the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBO-BERKOW-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on
George Steinbrenner's rant against the Mets. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-BISTOS (Paris) _ The word bistro is used as promiscuously
in Paris as the word deli is used in New York. Bistros in the true
sense _ the name comes from a Russian word meaning quick _ were
riding high when I first ate my merry way around the French capital
in the 1960s. Happily, Paris is a conservative city, slow-changing
and resistant to ``progress,'' and quite a few of the genuine
articles survive. Lovers of the sturdy, copious, grandmotherly
cooking that marks a true bistro pass favorite addresses from hand
to hand, like Russians in the Communist era exchanging samizdat
manuscripts. The guidebooks may forget, but die-hard bistro owners
and clients, Frenchmen and foreigners alike, tend the flame. By
R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DUCASSE (New York) _ A freewheeling account of a night at
Alain Ducasse. A critic's notebook by William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH-STEAK (Undated) _ French steak: what makes it so
wonderfully different. By Anthony Bourdain.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: Tuna with onion confit.
By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   PEAS (Undated) _ Peas: Heirloom varieties and ways to exploit
them. By Melissa Clark.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (Undated) _ The column: Lobster with peach coleslaw.
By Michel Richard.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ The column: The ravages (and recovery?) of
Pierce's Disease. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
