<HEADLINE>
SPARKS' STREAK ENDED BY PORTLAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ It was probably going to end sometime, but
the Sparks weren't counting on their 12-game win streak ending at
the Forum to the expansion Portland Fire Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In a wild ending, the Sparks couldn't come up with the big shot
as Mwadi Mabika's desperation 3-pointer with two seconds to play
missed the rim as Portland sent a franchise-low crowd of 4,460 home
disappointed with 80-77 loss at the Forum .
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks trailed by 10 with less than six minutes to play, but
they pulled within 78-77 when Mabika putting back a miss by Lisa
Leslie with 42 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Sophia Witherspoon, who had a spectacular game to score a
game-high 29 points, missed a layup and Leslie grabbed the rebound
and called timeout with 19.5 seconds to play. Following the Sparks
last timeout, Leslie passed the ball inside to DeLisha Milton, who
missed a layup.
</P>
<P>
   With 6.5 seconds on the clock, Vanessa Nygard, who had 13 points
for the Fire, made two free throws to make it a three-point game.
Mabika got the ball at the top of the key, but her shot was too
long to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks, who hadn't lost at home in nine games, are the last
team in the WNBA to lose on their home court. Now they have two
days to prepare to host the three-time defending champion Houston
Comets, who are on a 9-0 tear to lead the league at 18-2. The
Comets host Sacramento today before coming to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean the end of the season, we gave a valiant
effort, we knew the team was coming in and they're one of the most
dangerous teams,'' Sparks coach Michael Cooper said. ``They had
nothing to lose, they got into their rhythm and we just couldn't
stop them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks are 16-3, with two of their losses coming at the
hands of Western Conference expansion teams. They lost their second
at Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Sparks won at Portland, 70-57. Then the Fire had
their starting center, Sylvia Crawley, in the game. But Crawley,
the second leading scorer, sat out Tuesday with an ankle injury
suffered in Portland's last win against Washington. They were also
missing their No. 3 scorer Alisa Burras, who was out with a
sprained right knee. But it didn't hurt the Fire's chances.
</P>
<P>
   Witherspoon just picked up her game a notch and made up the
difference. She scored 17 of her 29 points in the first half. She
was 10 of 17 from the field, including 4 of 5 from the 3-point
line, where Portland shot 60 percent (9 of 15).
</P>
<P>
   The Fire (6-12) shot 54 percent from the field, despite a 54
showing from the free throw line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to come out and be aggressive and just play our
game,'' Witherspoon said. ``We felt a sense of calm down the
stretch as a team. We stuck together and did not come apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Mabika led four Sparks in double-figures with 22 points. But it
wasn't enough. Leslie picked up three fouls in the first half and
drew her fifth with 11 minutes to play in the second half. She saw
only 24 minutes of action, which didn't help the Sparks' cause.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks made their first four shots to go ahead 9-6, but the
Fire wasn't far with the hot hands of Witherspoon, who scored 17 of
her teams 41 first-half points. Nine of her points came from the
3-point line, where she was perfect with three and the team was 7
of 11 from long distance. Tara Williams and Michelle Marciniak
scored from beyond the arc in the final minute as the Fire took a
41-36 margin into the break.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
