<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS' JETER STAR OF STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the course of the past week, the All-Star Game had
degenerated into the Some-Star game, with injuries cutting down
some of the brightest flowers in baseball's garden.
</P>
<P>
   It fitting, then, that the man most responsible for the American
League's 6-3 victory Tuesday night at Turner Field was part of the
AL's second line of attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' Alex Rodriguez was voted in as the starting
shortstop by the fans. But when Rodriguez was decommissioned by a
concussion and knee injury suffered Friday night, Derek Jeter
stepped to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   While he was there, the Yankees shortstop drilled hits in his
first three at-bats, scoring one run and driving in two.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the shortstop situation in the American League,'' Jeter
said after being named the game's MVP, ``you never know if you will
go to the All-Star Game, much less start in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, Jeter and Nomar Garciaparra all have their backers
for the title of best shortstop in the league. The fans liked
Rodriguez this year. Fate liked Jeter, who got his first-ever start
in an All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps starting is what it's all about for Jeter. He'd struck
out twice in two previous All-Star Games, both times serving as a
backup. But given the opportunity by fate to start, Jeter came up
big on a hot (86 degrees), muggy night that just seemed to get
hotter and muggier as the night went along, weather that is
something of a tradition in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter doubled in the first off former Mariner Randy Johnson. He
singled off Kevin Brown and subsequently scored on Brown's
bases-loaded walk to Boston's Carl Everett in the third. But it was
in his fourth-inning at-bat that Jeter defined the game.
</P>
<P>
   Pitted against the Mets' Al Leiter with the bases loaded, Jeter
didn't dodge the spotlight. He fought off a tough cut fastball,
lofting it into center field for a single and two runs. It was no
bullet, but it was just what was needed for the AL to break a 1-1
tie. The hit put the AL ahead for good and led directly to Jeter
being the first Yankee ever _ and this is hard to believe _ to be
named MVP of the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking into consideration all the great players that have been
in the Yankee organization, who wouldn't be surprised?'' Jeter
said. ``But in a game like this, you have to be in the right place
at the right time. I was very fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically had the same game plan against everyone,'' Jeter
said. ``I'm a free swinger. I think that's known around the league,
maybe both leagues. I'd struck out in my only two All-Star at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I wanted to at least put the ball in play. But when you're
facing three guys like that, you want to swing early in the count.
If you fall behind, you're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter was never in trouble. Leiter and his National League
teammates were.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, it seemed Jeter would be all the offense the AL
would need or get, before coming up with three runs in the ninth to
put the sloppy game out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   For a group of All-Stars, the level of play could have been
much, much better, Jeter notwithstanding. Both sides made two
errors, and it was an unearned run, thanks to an error by Reds
shortstop Barry Larkin in the fourth, that was the difference in
the game until the AL scored its final three runs.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rodriguez was limited to the pre-game introduction
ceremony by his sore right leg, thus liberating Jeter, both of the
other Mariners on active status got a chance to play. Indeed, 29 of
the 30 players on the AL roster played, with only Cleveland
left-hander Chuck Finley held out in case the NL came back.
</P>
<P>
   That never happened, in small part because Seattle's Aaron Sele
pitched a quiet fourth. A starter by trade, Sele had only made it
to one other All-Star Game, in 1998, and that night he didn't
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Sele gave up a one-out single to Andres
Galarraga, but the hometown hero didn't get beyond first base, as
Jim Edmonds fouled out and Jason Kendall grounded out to short.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of fun, but it was a lot different, too,'' Sele
said. ``As a starter, you don't know how to prepare to pitch one
inning. Would I warm up too much? Not enough? Would I be too tired
from pitching (seven innings) Saturday?
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked out fine, but I breathed a big sigh of relief when
it was all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele was so caught up in getting his job done, he forgot to take
the obligatory souvenir baseball with which he'd retired Kendall.
</P>
<P>
   No problem. Sele and pal Derek Lowe, the one-time Mariner now
pitching for Boston, got one that had been used from the game-ball
bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it stays around the house long enough,'' Sele said,
breaking into a coast-to-coast grin, ``it will definitely become
the ball I used.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle designated hitter Edgar Martinez was in the on-deck
circle when the seventh ended. It seemed that his opportunity to
get an at-bat might vanish there, but Yankees manager Joe Torre
manipulated his lineup so Martinez could pinch-hit in the eighth
against Bob Wickman.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez picked out the second pitch he saw and lashed it,
driving a bullet to center, but he couldn't get the ball past the
Braves' Andruw Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was throwing good,'' Martinez said. ``I was looking for
anything I could drive, and I got a good pitch to hit. I hit the
ball real good, but (Jones) ran it down.
</P>
<P>
   The only damage the NL was able to do the rest of the way came
in the fifth inning, when A's closer Jason Isringhausen, pitching
too early in the game by the looks of it, walked Gary Sheffield to
open the inning, then gave up back-to-back, one-out singles to
Atlanta's Chipper Jones and Andruw Jones.
</P>
<P>
   That put the potential tying run at second, but Isringhausen
induced a fly ball by Sammy Sosa and a foul pop fly by Edgardo
Alfonzo, keeping the AL up 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones gave the NL its first run, ripping a solo homer
off eventual winning pitcher James Baldwin of the White Sox with
two out in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome,'' Jones said when asked how it felt to homer
in front of the home crowd. ``I mean, it's every little boy's
dream. It's not often that a player gets to play on his home field
in an All-Star Game, much less start.
</P>
<P>
   ``So to go out there and hit a home run, you know, it was just
awesome. I can't explain it. It was something I'll never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones' exploits notwithstanding, NL hitters didn't fare well
against AL hurlers.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe, Detroit's Todd Jones and the A's Tim Hudson pitched almost
flawless ball in the sixth, seventh and eighth, setting the stage
for the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   With Padres closer Trevor Hoffman pitching, the AL broke the
game open. Ray Durham and Garciaparra opened the ninth with
singles, and the Twins' Matt Lawton snookered a hit-and-run single
through the right side for a run.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox's Magglio Ordonez got a second run home by
delivering a textbook sacrifice fly to center, and the Angels'
Darin Erstad capped the three-run inning with an infield dribbler
that brought Lawton home.
</P>
<P>
   With the lead 6-2, the Yankees' Mariano Rivera no longer had a
save situation. But he was able to put the NL away despite
Garciaparra's throwing error _ the fourth defensive miscue of the
game _ which set up Steve Finley's run-scoring hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come here, you want to have fun, but you want to win,
too,'' Martinez said. ``I got an at-bat, Aaron pitched a good
inning and we won.''
</P>
<P>
   Such are the joys of summer for the boys of summer.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
