</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALL-STAR-HUMMER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big Cat, Kendall bring a dose of perspective
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No more regrets over what this All-Star Game wasn't.
That kind of thinking can be so wasteful anyway, as almost any
cancer patient will tell you.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints over all the players who no-showed Tuesday night
were to be washed away in steady waves of appreciation for one
player you couldn't have kept away with a sore knee or a
restraining order.
</P>
<P>
   When Andres Galarraga spoke, nothing but eagerness and
excitement tumbled out. ``I was like a little kid going to the
field today,'' said the Braves' healed first-baseman. And with
cause, for regardless of outcome or performance, he was the obvious
centerpiece of a game between baseball's best available stars.
</P>
<P>
   It began from the moment he walked out during the pregame parade
of players and their children. As he crossed the outfield with one
daughter in his arms, holding another by the hand and one more
trailing, the crowd sought him out and threw the first huzzahs his
way.
</P>
<P>
   No All-Star received a louder, longer Turner Field ovation
during the introductions than he _ who could hope to? How good was
it? Up in his box, Braves general manager John Schuerholz was seen
being practically physically lifted out of his chair by the
reception.
</P>
<P>
   So much tr elixir _ good for what ails you _ the catcher's tale.
Jason Kendall's year ago was spent, ``on the couch, heavily
medicated with my foot up.'' In other words, the Pittsburgh catcher
was pretty much your typical home viewer.
</P>
<P>
   Last July 4, trying to beat out a bunt, misstepping at the bag,
Kendall suffered a ghastly, Ruffian-style dislocation of the right
ankle. The replays of him grasping his leg, with his foot dangling
as if unconnected to him, are still haunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big difference, though. I dislocated an ankle, (Galarraga) was
fighting for his life,'' Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   Such stories within the grander game have helped elevate it once
more. Hey, who doesn't love a good resurrection?
</P>
<P>
   To another, wider audience, Galarraga spun his tale of faith, of
being cleansed by a devine dream that made him know all would be
well. Making it back to the All-Star Game was but one more element
in some heavenly plan.
</P>
<P>
   And we're going to gripe about Mark McGwire's aches?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we complain about too many little things,''
Galarraga suggested this week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
