<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 09:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9807 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-ALL-STAR-MVP-COX     07-12 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALL-STAR-MVP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jeter makes history for Yankees
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not Ruth. Not Gehrig. Neither DiMaggio nor Mantle. Not even
Yogi. The only New York Yankee to win the most valuable player
award in an All-Star Game? Derek Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to believe,'' the Yankee shortstop said. ``Look at
all the Yankee greats over the years. You figure at least one of
them would win one.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest great one did. Playing in his third consecutive
All-Star Game, hitless in the first two with strikeouts in his only
two at-bats, Jeter was perfection Tuesday. He went 3-for-3,
including a two-run single in the fourth inning off losing pitcher
Al Leiter that gave the American League the lead for good in its
6-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Then he was given the MVP award, a singular event for baseball's
most tradition-rich team. ``With all the history books that have
been written by a lot of Yankees, it's hard to believe,'' said
winning manager Joe Torre of the Yankees. ``You couldn't want a
more proud individual to be the first one up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter started only because his close friend, Seattle's Alex
Rodriguez, suffered a concussion Friday, and Torre chose his own
shortstop over Boston's Nomar Garciaparra ``because Nomar started
last year and I think it's a big thrill for a youngster to start
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot,'' Jeter said. ``The shortstop position in the
American League, you never know if you're going to get a chance to
come to the All-Star Game, much less get to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Much less start. Much less become the first Yankee to be named
MVP. Especially after striking out twice the past two years.
Instead, Jeter, already considered the Prince of the City back in
New York, gave another princely performance in the town that's fast
becoming his second city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's a great stadium,'' Jeter said of Turner Field.
``You can see very well at the plate. We played some very important
big games here against the Braves, in the postseason, regular
season, now this game here. I don't know what to tell you. I guess
it's just good fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   Or good hitting and preparation. Jeter was determined not to
fall behind in the count, as he quickly had in his two previous
All-Star at-bats. He came out swinging: first doubling off Randy
Johnson in the first inning; singling off Kevin Brown in the third
and scoring the night's first run; and finally lacing a Leiter cut
fastball in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically had the same game plan against everyone,'' Jeter
said. ``I'm a free swinger. I think it's known around the league,
both leagues. I wanted to at least put the ball in play.''
</P>
<P>
   He did, every time. Already, the 1996 AL Rookie of the Year, a
three-time world champion in just four years in the big leagues,
Jeter is now an All-Star MVP. And already a Yankee great?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' he said. ``You've got to play for a lot of
years before you're considered a Yankee great. This is my fifth
year. Hopefully, I can play for a few more years, then start that
debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
