<HEADER>
A9809 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN12-COX     07-12 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Joe Belle inspired all he met
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ This is not a time for pettiness, but I can't
help feeling peeved that, until last fall, I appear to have been
the only person in town who didn't know Joe Belle.
</P>
<P>
   If he was Mr. UD, Mr. Personality and all that, don't you think
he could have taken the trouble to call me up?
</P>
<P>
   I wish to God, at any rate, that when I met the beloved UD
administrator it was for any other reason than what it was: A
feature story about his fight against a rare and deadly form of
brain cancer.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, it is a rare privilege to have known a man like
Joe, who died Sunday at 50: A man whose love of life, love of
family, become even deeper when faced with losing them.
</P>
<P>
   No, this isn't going to be one of those ``good comes out of
tragedy'' epiphanies. It's true, as close friend Steve Yuhas
eulogized Tuesday, ``that the past 14 months have been a gift from
God to all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Much good has come from Joe's illness and the inspiration he has
given so many. But much, much more good would have come out of
having Joe around for the next 40 years or so.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'm still in the anger phase. That's a luxury Joe didn't
allow himself as he endured three surgeries and a grueling medical
regimen, while continuing to work until several weeks ago. ``People
say, `Aren't you mad at God?''' Joe said. ``I don't have time to be
mad at God now. I need him.''
</P>
<P>
   Once I got to know Joe, he speedily made up for his previous
neglect. He wouldn't let me linger for very long in my safety zone
as a reporter. It was almost impossible to know him without knowing
him as a friend.
</P>
<P>
   So I joined hundreds of other mourners at Joe's funeral Tuesday
morning at St. Albert the Great Church in Kettering. Nearly every
face in the overflow crowd was tear-streaked. ``It was a real
tribute to Joe that we had to open both sides of the church
today,'' Pastor Jim Manning greeted the mourners.
</P>
<P>
   How could one man make such an impact on so many?
</P>
<P>
   It's something more than his irresistible wit, at once biting
and gentle. Something more, even, than the infectious exuberance of
this 5-foot-5 Italian leprechaun with a Paul Bunyan-sized zest for
living.
</P>
<P>
   Even when facing death, he put others first. In accepting UD's
Lackner award, which recognizes individuals who exemplify the
Marianist sense of hospitality, his first words were of wife, Barb,
``the pillar of our family.''
</P>
<P>
   When I visited him for the last time, on July 4, Joe was clearly
in pain, unable to eat. ``I'm ready,'' he said, ``but the Lord
won't take me.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking was clearly an effort, but he made the effort _ and his
thoughts were on his visitors. He wanted to make sure we sampled
the homemade pasta Aunt Martha made the night before.
</P>
<P>
   No one had expected him to awaken from the coma into which he
had fallen the Friday before. But he did, as if willing himself to
give his loved ones the gift of a goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   He even organized an impromptu champagne toast the Monday before
his death, inviting dozens of close friends to share the bottle of
Millennium champagne left over from New Year's It was, in short, an
Italian wake that the Irish could envy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even before the disease, Joe acted each day as if it were a
blessing to be alive,'' Yuhas said in his eulogy.
</P>
<P>
   Then he stopped himself, realizing he had belabored the obvious:
``But if you knew Joe, you know that.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right; he didn't need to tell us. We knew.
</P>
<P>
   For those who knew Joe Belle, it's a lesson not likely to be
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
