<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-HIV-GEL (Durban, South Africa) _ A much-anticipated study
testing Nonoxynol-9 _ a common spermicidal gel _ to prevent HIV
infection not only failed to protect women from the virus, it
apparently helped promote new infections among Thai and African
prostitutes. The findings, released Wednesday at the 13th
International AIDS Conference, are a blow to efforts worldwide to
come up with a germ-killer that could be used by women to protect
themselves against HIV. By ULYSSESS TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   JUMP-ROPE (Troy, N.Y.) _ When Tahira Reid was in the third grade
at Public School 97 in the Bronx, she entered a contest in which
students had to make a poster of something they wished they had.
Reid drew a picture of two poles with ropes and a girl jumping in
the middle. Now 23, Reid is one of the creators of the Double Dutch
Jump Rope Machine, and she and her partner hope to find investors
for the device. By KRIS WORRELL.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-BASTILLE (San Antonio) _ While watching fireworks last
week, it came to me. Why stop the festivities on the Fourth of
July, for an entire year, when another holiday that's rich with
party possibilities follows right on its heels? You guessed it _
that would be July 14, Bastille Day, the anniversary of French
independence. By BONNIE WALKER.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-ATHEIST (San Antonio) _ For the third time since April
1999, federal agents searched a remote Texas Hill Country site for
the remains of vanished atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair and two of
her children. And for the third time, they came up empty-handed. By
JOHN MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-COLLEGES (Austin, Texas) _ The next Texas city with a
flagship university could be Dallas, Houston _ or San Antonio. A
report presented to a Texas state university regents committee this
week suggested that Texas, which lags behind other large states,
like California, in terms of the number of top-shelf research
universities, needs to develop more. By RUSSELL GOLD.
</P>
<P>
   RAPE-DIARY (San Francisco) _ A former UC-Berkeley student who
spent nearly two years in prison for a rape he has denied
committing has been granted a new trial by an appellate court that
said the jury should have heard evidence from the alleged victim's
diary. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   TORTURE-EXTRADITION (San Francisco) _ In the courts' first look
at a law against torture, the federal appeals court in San
Francisco says judges can enforce a ban on extraditing foreigners
who face likely torture in their homelands. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-WRESTLING (Pasadena, Calif.) _ While you can take your shots
at the World Wrestling Federation _ an adult product that bills
itself as an adult product yet continually markets to children _
there's no denying that it's one of the most important shows on
television. Not only did it save UPN (which had no soul to lose),
but it continually held the top ratings slots on cable on USA
Network. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-VIDEO-REVIEW (Undated) _ The action in Wes Craven's
``Scream 3'' can be effectively gut-grabbing, and screenwriter
Ehren Kruger cranks out some good one-liners. Even so, this is a
numbingly formulaic wind-down of a once-witty concept: poking fun
at horror-film cliches while slyly employing them. By BRUCE
WESTERBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-HMOS (Houston) _ Seven of the 10 managed-care companies
that offer Medicare HMO plans in Texas are abandoning the business
next year along with about 200,000 customers. The managed-care
providers say they are forced to pull out because of low
reimbursement rates from the federal government combined with high
pharmaceutical and administrative costs. Here are ways to cope if
you lose coverage. By SHANNON BUGGS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NINERS (San Francisco) _ The San Francisco 49ers have done
day-to-day business without a true president for the past two
years, but now they are set to name a former toy company executive
to take over the franchise. By BRUCE ADAMS.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-HAMMER (San Jose, Calif.) _ Being the second-best hammer
thrower in the United States confers no special status for Kevin
McMahon. He throws the darn thing, he has to retrieve it. It's like
playing fetch with your dog . . . minus the dog. By JOHN
CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ You could call it ``rage rage,''
and I've got a bad case of it. Whenever a new rage comes along, I
get ticked off. First it was road rage, and I was angry because I
had written about it for years but hadn't invented that catchy
term, calling it ``car wars'' instead. The next rage was ``air
rage,'' those cases in which airline passengers go bonkers and
abuse or attack flight attendants. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Back when I was so smitten with
this town that I'd weep like a long-lost lover on touching down at
San Francisco International Airport, re-entry from a road trip or
vacation was always a breeze. Nowadays, re-entry takes time and a
concerted effort. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-SAFETY (San Francisco) _ PG&AMP;E swears its Diablo Canyon
nuclear power plan is safe, despite documented problems. But the
bottom line for me is the fact that if Diablo Canyon blows up,
melts down or goes sideways, it could be the equivalent of a
homicidal next-door neighbor, fallout-wise. Chernobyl comes to
mind. By SCOTT WINOKUR
</P>
<P>
   FOSSIL-FUEL (Oakland, Calif.) _ Given the absence of bold ideas
in Washington, the burden of innovation must be shouldered by
cities and local governments. That's why Oakland has decided to
send a message to the rest of the country that the moment has
arrived for breaking America's fossil fuel addiction. By JERRY
BROWN.
</P>
<P>
   WONG-COLUMN (Piedmont, Calif.) _ Norman Mineta's nomination as
Commerce secretary in the last six months of the Clinton
administration was widely hailed by Asian American political
activists. And, from a symbolic perspective, well it should be. By
WILLIAM WONG.
</P>
<P>
   ALEXANDER-HAMILTON (Danville, Calif.) _ Would we be better off
if our politicians were geniuses? July 12 is the anniversary of the
death _ in a pointless and tragic duel _ of a man who was exactly
that: an American genius. Alexander Hamilton (1755-1804) _ author,
general, founding father and the first secretary of the Treasury _
provides an excellent example of what genius in government is all
about. By CYNTHIA BASS.
</P>
</TEXT>
