<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GRAPEVINE: News, notes and gossip from the industry
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   World Championship Wrestling may not have put together the best
pay-per-view, but Sunday's ``Bash at the Beach'' could go down a
historic event.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks leading up to the show, Hulk Hogan had been missing in
action, despite being a headliner in a world title match with
champion Jeff Jarrett. Also missing at the same time was WCW
creative guru Vince Russo. Why were they both missing? Were they
trying to rework Hogan's contract or was Hogan looking to leave WCW
and start his own organization? Rumors are rampant on the Internet,
but chance are the events at ``Bash at the Beach'' were probably
staged.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Hogan had to say recently on ``The Love Sponge''
radio show in Tampa, Fla., where he is a frequent guest in his
hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Russo approached Hogan about losing to Jarrett by
disqualifcation after destroying Jarrett. Russo changed his mind
and then gave a different ending. That ending didn't sit well with
Eric Bischoff and he and Russo got into an arguement. Bischoff
stormed out of the meeting. Hogan told Russo that he would lose to
Jarrett if he could get out of his WCW contract. Russo argued with
Hogan and WCW top man Brad Siegel was called. Siegel said Hogan was
not going to be let out of his contract, but that he had a creative
control clause in his contract, so Russo should let Hogan win.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett and Russo went to the ring, then Hogan went to the ring.
Russo told Jarrett to lay down in the ring and for Hogan to go
ahead and pin him if he wanted the belt so badly. Hogan said he
asked Jarrett why he was doing this. He told Jarrett he should get
up and they should fight to make Russo look bad. Jarrett said he
was just following orders and Hogan pinned him.
</P>
<P>
   Russo came out a second time to announce that Jarrett was still
the WCW championand displayed the old WCW belt (Hogan was given a
new replica belt) and would defend the title later in the evening
against Booker T. Hogan said he tired to get to the ring during
Russo's announcement, but we held back by security. He later tried
to talk to Russo again, but was escorted out of the building by
security.
</P>
<P>
   While the Russo promos had a real feel to them, something just
smells fishy about how it all went down. First, the amount from
``insider'' information on the Internet leading up to the ``Bash''
with Hogan claiming he's talking to FOX, claiming he didn't want to
lose to Jarrett and might no-show the event. WCW has used their own
group of insiders to send out information they want the fans to
have, while it is far from the truth. Second, it was played up
throughout the ``Bash'' that Hogan might not be there. Third, when
Russo came down to the ring before the match you knew from the look
on his face what was going to happen. When Vince McMahon really
double-crossed Bret Hart at the ``Survivor Series'' in 1998, he
didn't telegraph the move. Fourth, why did Jarrett have a back-up
belt, unless you knew you were going to need it? Fifth, Hogan's
comments on the radio show the next day was a hard sell after the
fact. Sixth, no one at WCW will say anything about it for ``legal''
reasons. And finally, whenever something is played as a ``shoot''
(real) it usually isn't.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason to believe it was real is because of the match
between Booker T and Jarrett. There were a lot of rest holds and
they talked their way through the match, so you could tell they
hadn't practiced.
</P>
<P>
   _ In other WCW show at the ECW Arena being the final one are not
true. Owners of the arena are trying to sell it, but have not found
a buyer over the past six months, so chances of it being sold soon
are not good. ECW has three more shows scheduled already. ECW has
also scheduled its first venture into Canada for Sept. 9 in
Ontario. ECW is also looking into putting on a show in England next
year. England is one of a few European countries that televises
ECW.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
