<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Yorker looks at high-risk orphans
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New Yorker ($3) offers a diverse _ and unusual _ array of
articles in its July 17 issue. Atlanta author Melissa Fay Greene
visits the New York clinic where Dr. Jane Aronson reviews videos of
high-risk orphans from Russia and Eastern Europe and advises
prospective parents who want to adopt the children. The parents'
reactions to the evaluations vary greatly, Greene writes. ``Some _
already in love with a photograph or a video _ want a rubber stamp
for their decision, and are outraged if they don't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other articles of note include Timothy W. Ryback's discovery
that many of Adolf Hitler's relatives are living _ very quietly _
in New York City, and Burkhard Bilger's interesting Letter from
Kentucky about the local custom of eating squirrel brains. A virus
much like that of mad-cow disease is now threatening the culinary
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More Harry: Newsweek ($3.50) adds more fuel to the Harry
Potter frenzy this week with an excerpt from the new J.K. Rowling
novel, ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire.'' In addition,
reviewer Malcolm Jones examines the Potter phenomenon and offers
his opinion on the literary quality of the books. ``Rowling's
novels are probably the best books children have ever encountered
that haven't been thrust upon them by an adult,'' he writes.
``Rowling may not be as magisterial as (J.R.R.) Tolkien or as
quirky as (Roald) Dahl, but her books introduce fledgling readers
to a high standard of entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More than smoke: Things continue to change at Cigar Aficionado
($4.95). In an effort to broaden its appeal, the magazine has
expanded its coverage to include articles even nonsmokers can
appreciate. The August issue features a cover story on widow Bo
Derek (no, she's not dating Ted Turner); columns about the
Olympics, Jesse Ventura and classic cars; and a fascinating article
on Cuban-American exiles' attitudes toward Fidel Castro. Not
surprisingly, writer Jonathan Kandell found mostly hatred. One
exception was Alfredo Duran, a 63-year-old lawyer who took part in
the Bay of Pigs invasion in 1961 and spent two years in a Cuban
prison. Duran thinks it's time to start a dialogue with the
dictator.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More Bo: Ms. Derek, 43, proves she's still a ``10'' in the
August issue of Vanity Fair ($3.95) by posing for a revealing photo
spread for Herb Ritts. Also in this issue are a cover story on
Heath Ledger, Aussie co-star of ``The Patriot''; a report from Seba
votes from readers and food industry members. The Top 5, in order,
are Chops, Bluepointe, Nava, Canoe and Pricci. Also included in
this issue is Domicile, a mini-magazine about decorating and
interiors that takes readers into the home of Karin Jones, Atlanta
Brave Chipper Jones' former wife. Located in the Country Club of
the South, her 10,000-square-foot house boasts 20-foot
floor-to-ceiling palladian windows.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
