<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WRESTLING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A GOOD, CLEAN FIGHT ON TV 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Critics have gotten this whole wrestling
thing wrong. As far as the WWF is concerned, violence, sex and
misogyny are certainly in-bounds. But don't accuse the
entertainment behemoth of not having standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there are limits,'' said Linda E. McMahon, president
and chief executive of the World Wrestling Federation and wife of
chairman-cartoon villain Vince McMahon.
</P>
<P>
   Wait until you hear what they are:
</P>
<P>
   ``In the World Wrestling Federation, we don't kill anyone. We're
not shooting people. Nor are we giving the impression that we're
killing anyone or knifing anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   This sophisticated woman, who presents herself with the
gentility befitting her Southern roots, said this to a roomful of
reporters without a dram of mirth or humor. She was serious. C'mon,
people, her tone implied, isn't that enough?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certainly a matter of personal preference and choice,''
she said at the Television Critics Association Press Tour.
``Clearly there are critics of our product. Clearly there are those
who do not like our product just as there are many who don't like
the ballet, opera or other entertainment options.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling, on par with ballet and opera, all said without so
much as a hint of a grin. That's wonderful theater.
</P>
<P>
   While you can take your shots at the WWF _ an adult product that
bills itself as an adult product yet continually markets to kids
(taking notes, tobacco industry?) _ there's no denying that it's
one of the most important shows on television.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did it save UPN (which had no soul to lose), but it
continually held the top ratings slots on cable on USA Network.
</P>
<P>
   But on the cable side, the WWF is jumping this fall to TNN, a
move that will cost the outfit ratings at the start but give it a
strong promotional vehicle, since the country station (which is
going toward more sports programming) is part of MTV Networks and
CBS-Viacom. ``Rock video'' will take on a whole new meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Also, expect specials to pop up on CBS, not to mention XFL
football games when the new WWF league premieres next winter on NBC
and UPN.
</P>
<P>
   This move is an entertainment rarity in television: a prime-time
show in its prime jumping networks. In most cases where shows have
shifted, it was at an end of a run, and the results were usually
poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our expectations most certainly are to start equal to what the
WWF has done at USA,'' said Brian Hughes, TNN vice president of
programming. ``There is huge support for this sports entertainment
property in the way of marketing, not only in our air but off air
and across the Viacom family.''
</P>
<P>
   Some advertisers are getting leery of wrestling (7-Up and
Coca-Cola are among those who begged off of UPN's ``WWF
Smackdown!''), and the genre has a history of going into decline in
popularity before inevitably bouncing off the mat.
</P>
<P>
   But clan McMahon _ conducting what Linda McMahon calls ``the
largest focus group that ever happens'' in packed arenas four times
a week _ have been able to tap into a vein that has put wrestling
on a historic upswing. As far as they are concerned, those kids
they are not marketing to will still be the fans of tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Even Mrs. McMahon would smile over that.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   NBC last week aired an unpromoted ``Freaks and Geeks'' marathon,
which came out on top in its time slot among the Big Three networks
in terms of demographics. Forget it: The great freshman drama is
still canceled.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox Family Channel will air all 18 episodes of the show _
including three episodes never before seen _ starting with
back-to-back episodes at 8 p.m. (Eastern) Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   The drama's cancellation, especially in light of the weak slate
of new shows coming this fall to NBC and the other networks,
becomes more and more infuriating. In future years, look for this
show to be remembered as fondly as ``My So-Called Life,'' another
teen drama that died too young a death.
</P>
<P>
   Executive Producer Judd Apatow said the show was shopped around
to other broadcast networks before it was ultimately abandoned.
``It was a real complicated process,'' he said. ``We said, `Who
wants us?' and they said, `None of us.'''
</P>
<P>
   Apatow said he was concerned that shows like ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' and ``Survivor'' have created the attitude among
networks executives that only shows that could become the next
landscape-altering megahit should be pursued.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible trend for shows like `Freaks and Geeks,''' he
said. ``We're never going to change television. As I go in to pitch
(different) shows for next season, my pitch is, `Please let me make
the show that makes you feel less dirty about the other (stuff) you
are putting on.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Good luck on that ever flying.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
