r e BC-VIDEO-REVIEWS-HNS &LR;      07-12 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NOT MUCH TO SCREAM ABOUT IN HORROR SPOOF PART III 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRUCE WESTERBOORK  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director Wes Craven insists he made this third ``Scream'' out of
devotion to ``closure.''
</P>
<P>
   Devotion to money is more like it. The first ``Scream'' didn't
need a single sequel, much less two.
</P>
<P>
   By coughing up the same characters and situations yet again,
this franchise becomes what its original movie mocked: just another
hackneyed hack-'em-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scream 3'' has the same old black-robed, white-masked murderer
arising to kill and kill again, this time in Los Angeles. He's
stalking the cast and crew of ``Stab 3,'' a film based on the first
Scream's story.
</P>
<P>
   Whiny victim junkie Neve Campbell has retreated to rural
seclusion, but somehow the script rationalizes a reason for her to
charge into the Los Angles, where the body count mounts
predictably.
</P>
<P>
   Courteney Cox Arquette, David Arquette and others also return,
as does the usual array of false-alarm jolts (we stopped counting
at six) and phone calls from the killer, who is using a gizmo to
alter his voice.
</P>
<P>
   Among the few fresh elements, Parker Posey is a hoot as a
hysterical actress playing a TV reporter in ``Stab 3.'' Some
surprise cameos also pepper the mix.
</P>
<P>
   The action can be effectively gut-grabbing, and screenwriter
Ehren Kruger cranks out some good one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, this is a numbingly formulaic wind-down of a once-witty
concept: poking fun at horror-film cliches while slyly employing
them.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Craven and company become the cliche.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make you want to scream _ not ``Help!'' but
``Enough!''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Woody Allen _ secret agent?
</P>
<P>
   No, but MGM is using its James Bond approach for Allen's catalog
of films on that label.
</P>
<P>
   This week brings the ``Woody Allen Collection,'' an eight-movie
gift set on VHS ($99.98) and DVD ($234.98). Titles also are sold
individually ($14.95 for tapes, $19.98 for discs).
</P>
<P>
   They focus on Allen's early career, from 1969 to 1980.
</P>
<P>
   He directed all eight entries: ``Bananas,'' ``Everything You
Always Wanted to Know About Sex,'' ``Sleeper,'' ``Love and Death,''
``Annie Hall,'' ``Interiors'' (a Bergmanesque drama in which he did
not appear), ``Manhattan'' and ``Stardust Memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Only ``Annie Hall'' has been on DVD previously.
</P>
<P>
   Not included from the same era are ``What's Up, Tiger Lily?'',
the Japanese spy film for which Allen added new dialogue; ``Take
the Money and Run''; and ``Play It Again, Sam,'' directed by Herb
Ross (and also sold by another label, Paramount).
</P>
<P>
   But largely these are the crop's cream, especially the one-two
punch of ``Annie Hall,'' the popular Oscar winner as 1977's best
picture, and ``Manhattan,'' its bookend.
</P>
<P>
   Allen disdains awards, as indicated by a line in ``Annie Hall''
and the fact that he stayed in New York to play clarinet at a club
the night the film won its awards.
</P>
<P>
   So don't expect him to agree with Oscar and anoint ``Annie'' as
his favorite work. Rather, his pet picture seems to be
``Manhattan.''
</P>
<P>
   Want clues? Only ``Manhattan'' never has been telecast without
letterboxing, thus preserving Gordon Willis' exquisite
black-and-white cinematography.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, among the eight new DVDs, only ``Manhattan'' is
featured in just letterboxed form. The other films are offered
full-frame on one side of the disc and letterboxed on the other.
</P>
<P>
   In part because of that distinction, only ``Manhattan'' has a
picture disc with artwork on one side.
</P>
<P>
   Extras are minimal. Each disc has a booklet and theatrical
trailer, as well as language options for dubbing and subtitles.
These can be oddly varied: You can hear ``Annie Hall'' in French
and Manhattan in ``Spanish,'' but not the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. This is the heart of Allen's best work, when his
ideas were fresh, his humor wasn't vulgar or mean-spirited and his
relationship-challenged New York neurotics were at their most
endearing.
</P>
<P>
   Most lovable among them is Oscar winner Diane Keaton's Annie,
yet even she is eclipsed by another character: New York itself in
``Manhattan.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorgeously photographed and beautifully scored with music by
George Gershwin, ``Manhattan'' is the ultimate valentine to Allen's
beloved town. As he says in the intro, it was his town, and it
always would be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 1234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9884 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-MEDICARE-HMOS-HNS &LR;      07-12 1506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-HMOS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WAYS TO MANAGE UPHEAVAL IN MANAGED CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SHANNON BUGGS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Seven of the 10 managed-care companies that offer
Medicare HMO plans in Texas are abandoning the business next year _
and about 200,000 customers.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of those stranded and in search of new coverage
live in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The managed-care providers have said they are withdrawing from
the Houston market and others across the nation because low
reimbursement rates from the federal government combined with high
pharmaceutical and administrative costs have pushed their profit
margins below acceptable levels.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, as private-sector, publicly traded companies, the
health maintenance organizations have the right to decide when and
where they want to do business and an obligation to their
shareholders to base those decisions on sound financial strategies.
</P>
<P>
   But the upheaval in the Medicare HMO market has left 6.5 million
retirees, the disabled and their families nationwide anxious about
their financial futures.
</P>
<P>
   By the time HMO coverage ends for many of them on Dec. 31, these
Medicare recipients will have several possible replacement
alternatives that may or may not duplicate the coverage they got
from their HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   The first option is to do nothing prior to your HMO coverage
ending. You will automatically be enrolled in the original Medicare
plan, a fee-for-service plan that is managed by the federal
government through the Health Care Financing Administration.
</P>
<P>
   That plan is divided into two parts: Medicare A covers
hospitalization, and Medicare B covers doctors' bills. But neither
portion covers prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   This year, participants pay a $776 deductible for each hospital
stay of 60 days or less before the hospital coverage begins and a
$100 deductible each year before the medical coverage starts,
according to HCFA.
</P>
<P>
   People typically sign up for Medicare HMOs to get the
prescription drug coverage that they can't get through Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The best bet for getting prescription coverage is to switch to
another Medicare HMO.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, in Houston, there will be only one HMO choice in
2001: PacifiCare Health Systems' Secure Horizons.
</P>
<P>
   This year, that plan does not charge a premium above the monthly
Medicare premium of $45.50 that's deducted from Social Security
checks.
</P>
<P>
   That money is paid directly to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   It requires participants to make co-payments of $6 for each
doctor visit, $5 for generic drugs and $20 for brand-name
prescriptions. The prescription coverage is limited to $1,200 each
year.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is no guarantee that the benefits, co-payments or
coverage levels will be the same next year.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs have the right to adjust their plans each year, and they
are not required to offer prescription coverage with Medicare HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   As the only state-approved managed-care company that has agreed
to renew its Medicare contract in Houston, PacifiCare can expect a
big boost to its enrollment and its expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect to see all 107,000 (former HMO participants in
Houston) sign up, but we want to give them that option,'' says Tony
Salters, a PacifiCare spokesman. ``At some point _ not now _ we may
have to say that the physicians cannot handle all the people who
want to enroll. ``PacifiCare will announce by Sept. 15 the details
of the coverage costs and benefits. However, it is highly unlikely
the company would drop prescription coverage from its Secure
Horizons' plan or dramatically increase its fees.
</P>
<P>
   Especially, since Amcare Health Plans of Texas is seeking state
approval to bring another Medicare HMO to the Houston market,
according to the Texas Department of Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   People who want to swear off all HMOs because they fear all
plans eventually will leave the Medicare market do have other
options.
</P>
<P>
   They can buy Medicare supplemental insurance, which is also
called Medigap. There are 10 standard policies, labeled A (the most
basic and least expensive) through J (the most comprehensive and
expensive).
</P>
<P>
   The average costs range from annual premiums of $500 to nearly
$7,000.
</P>
<P>
   But the maximum prescription coverage is $3,000 each year, which
is a 50 percent match after the policy holder pays $3,000 for
medications and a $250 deductible.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone being pushed out of an HMO will have the guaranteed
right to buy policies A, B, C and F from any health insurance
company that offers the coverage in the state. That means you can
get the coverage regardless of your medical history and without a
waiting period.
</P>
<P>
   There is a caveat for people under age 65 on Medicare, which
includes the disabled. They are only guaranteed the right to buy
policy A.
</P>
<P>
   There are eight insurers that will sell this group other Medigap
policies. For more information in Texas, go to www.tdi.state.tx.us
to get the rate guide or call an automated order line at
800-599-7467.
</P>
<P>
   However, none of the four guaranteed policies offers
prescription coverage.
</P>
<P>
   You would have to buy plans H, I or J to get that. And it is
rare for insurers to ``guarantee issue'' those policies. So, you
will have to be in good health and without a pre-existing condition
to qualify for coverage.
</P>
<P>
   There is a loophole for HMO participants who have been eligible
for Medicare for less than 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   They have the right to enroll in any of the 10 Medigap policies
or HMO plans. Only people with end-stage renal disease would be
restricted to policies A,B,C and F.
</P>
<P>
   Another coverage option is to sign up for the new private
fee-for-service plan.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Life Insurance Co. offers the only one in Texas.
However, it does not offer prescription coverage and it is not
available to residents in the Houston metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another option is to call your former employer to see if any
health insurance benefits are available to retirees. However, most
companies have been dropping such plans. Also, some retiree health
plans have been connected to Medicare HMO programs that are pulling
out of the state.
</P>
<P>
   If those alternatives don't work for you, check to see if you
qualify for a Medicare assistance program.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Texas administers four federal programs that pay
part of your Medicare out-of-pocket expenses, such as premiums,
deductibles and co-insurance payments. The money you save from that
can be used to pay for prescriptions, but the plans do not cover
medications specifically.
</P>
<P>
   Each program has different income requirements. Check out
``Medicaid Programs'' at
www.dhs.state.tx.us/pro-grams/Elderly/index.html or call the state
Department of Human Services at 512-438-3280.
</P>
<P>
   The only federal program that does pay for prescriptions is
Medicaid, which also is administered by states.
</P>
<P>
   For elderly and disabled Texans to qualify for Medicaid, they
also have to be eligible for Supplemental Security Income, or SSI,
or the Medicaid Nursing Program, which limits individuals' monthly
income to $1,536 and couples' to $3,072.
</P>
<P>
   Later this summer, everyone affected by the HMO withdrawal will
get a letter from their managed care company by Oct. 2. It will
detail all of the options available to you based on where you live,
your medical condition and how long you've been eligible for
Medicare. The letter should include your name and the date it was
written.
</P>
<P>
   It is extremely important that you hang on to the letter and its
postmarked envelope. You may need it to prove how you lost your
coverage and when you were notified.
</P>
<P>
   HMO participants who want coverage beyond original Medicare have
two 63-day windows to change their coverage, according to state
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The clock starts ticking when you receive the letter on your
options.
</P>
<P>
   The second window opens when your HMO coverage expires on Dec.
31.
</P>
<P>
   However, at that point you may be left with fewer options, since
other HMOs may have hit their enrollment capacity by that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's best to begin gathering information now, even though we
don't know what these HMOs will be offering next year,'' says Norma
Plascencia Almanza, coordinator of a Texas Medicare benefits
counseling program.
</P>
<P>
   ``You also need to talk to your doctors to see what they plan to
do, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, adult children should check with parents living in other
Texas towns or out of state about announced HMO changes and
research options.
</P>
<P>
   Get more information on the various choices by calling the
Health Care Financing Administration at 800-633-4227 or visiting
www.medicare.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Also contact the Texas Department of Insurance at 800-252-3439
to get more local information. And call the Texas Department on
Aging at 800-252-9240 to get a booklet detailing your choices, or
visit www.aarp.org.
</P>
<P>
   If you are outraged by the predicament you have been placed in
by the HMO pullout, contact your elected representatives. Now, is
the time to let your senators and representatives know how you
feel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
