<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: My form for presidential politics
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I stopped by my doctor's office this week for
help with an insurance form, still trying to get reimbursed for a
medical bill I paid last December.
</P>
<P>
   That was back when I last had pneumonia. The doctor cured me,
but it looks like I'm going to die of frustration waiting for the
insurance company to pay me what it owes me.
</P>
<P>
   I can remember, not so many years ago, when my medical insurance
paid off like an ATM machine. Now, the least little jot or tittle
out of place, and you are flat out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you never hear back from them. When you call to ask,
they say there's no record that you ever filed.
</P>
<P>
   They tell you to resubmit. You resubmit and then they tell you
that their records show your request had been submitted earlier.
Grrr.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I chatted briefly with my doctor. He figures me for a
Democrat. I figure him for a Republican. We get along just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you going to be covering the convention,'' he asked, his
tone a bit mischievous, ``where our next president will be
nominated?''
</P>
<P>
   I said, `yes-sir-ree, no doubt about it,' I was going to be
covering the national political convention where our next president
would be nominated.
</P>
<P>
   That's because, I told him, I'll be covering both the GOP
convention in Philadelphia and the Democratic convention in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   So it is for a journalist _ everybody's friend.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor said it ought to be fun. Well, yeah, it ought to, but
I'm not so sure it will.
</P>
<P>
   A long time ago I was given this piece of political advice, from
a doctor, as I recall: Party with the liberals, vote with the
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   I've done it both ways over the years and, with the accumulation
of years being what it is, have just about partied out with either
party.
</P>
<P>
   My personal presidential voting record goes back to 1964, LBJ
and Goldwater. Had the voting age been 18 early on instead of 21, I
could have voted in the JFK-Nixon race.
</P>
<P>
   I would have supported Kennedy, impressed as I was by the first
of the televised presidential debates, which probably I wouldn't
have even watched except that it was a journalism class assignment
at college.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, I came back to the dorm and announced to my roommates
that Kennedy would be the next president. That was one of the few
times I was right about a presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Counting up, I've voted for the winner three times and the loser
six. But two of the three being Nixon, I'm not sure how I should
count those.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, to my way of thinking, was a pretty good president on the
big issues, and a really bad president on the little things.
Reagan, I would say, was just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   My only other winner was Clinton in 1992, but four years later I
was so disgusted about the China money that I gave (Bob) Dole my
vote, knowing all the while I was throwing it away.
</P>
<P>
   Gore or Bush? Don't know, haven't decided.
</P>
<P>
   I've never met Gore, not being a Buddhist nun.
</P>
<P>
   But when Bush was in his first term as governor, I sat at the
same table with him at an editors' luncheon in Austin where he
spoke. It's like most everybody says: he's as nice a guy as you'll
meet.
</P>
<P>
   Do nice guys make good presidents? I don't know. Was Carter a
good president? Was Reagan?
</P>
<P>
   So, Gore or Bush? Just tell me how which one can straighten out
my medical insurance reimbursements. Grrr.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; Website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
