<HEADER>
A9891 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-12 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RANTING AGAINST THE RAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Call it ``rage rage,'' and I have a bad case of
it. Whenever a new rage comes along, I get ticked off.
</P>
<P>
   First it was road rage, and I was angry because I had written
about it for years but hadn't invented that catchy term, calling it
``car wars'' instead. Arnold Nerenberg, a psychologist in Irvine,
Calif., came up with ``road rage'' in 1997, and a ``10-step
compassion program'' to overcome it.
</P>
<P>
   The name stuck, compassion for fellow drivers didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The next rage was ``air rage,'' those cases in which airline
passengers go bonkers and abuse or attack flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   This got me mad because it seemed the fault lay with airlines
and airports, which treat passengers like prisoners of war without
a Geneva Convention. Behavior is bound to deteriorate after long
waits followed by confinement with squalling kids to the left, fat
guys in shorts to the right and trays of fatty melted matter in
front.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants have launched a campaign against air rage, but
the Federal Aviation Administration says violent incidents in the
air have declined nationally.
</P>
<P>
   The next trend was ``cell phone rage,'' in which people grab
loud talkers' cell phones and break them. That teed me off because
it seemed too rational to be called rage.
</P>
<P>
   The latest rage is ``sports rage,'' and because some idiot
hockey dad allegedly beat another hockey dad to death we all have
to read the deep insights of sports rage experts.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there are sports rage experts, many of them sports
psychologists. I asked a longtime sports reporter what sports
psychologists do, and he said, ``Wait by the phone for a reporter
to call.''
</P>
<P>
   Terrorism experts, whose phones have gone silent with the
decline of terrorist rage, might consider changing fields. After
the hockey rage death, at least one sports psychologist's phone was
ringing off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Zaichowsky, a professor of sports psychology at Boston
University and former hockey player, told the Los Angeles Times
that sports rage is similar to road rage, ``anger, mixed with an
uncontrollable need to be physical.''
</P>
<P>
   For that, you get a doctorate.
</P>
<P>
   In the New York Times, Zaichowsky was quoted as saying that
parental involvement had a deleterious effect on youth sports. He
said that when he was a kid, parents were minimally involved and
now ``parents drive the kids to practice and games, and as things
have gotten more organized, the stakes are higher.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean to pick on this guy for answering the phone and
stating the obvious. After all, journalists were the ones who
called him, asked the obvious questions and printed the obvious
answers.
</P>
<P>
   If there's one thing newspapers and television need more than
violence, it's a trend. The question to ask, at least for anyone
afflicted with rage rage, is whether the nation faces a new threat
from sports rage.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the National Association of Sports Officials
says their reports of violence by parents at sports events have
increased markedly in the last few years. He said the association
now offers its members assault insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the father and coach of a Little Leaguer in Florida
broke the jaw of a 13-year-old umpire. Last year a Virginia mother
slapped a 14-year-old official during a soccer game.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the cases reported. The once-celebrated soccer mom is
now feared and scorned.
</P>
<P>
   We've always known about those Little League dads, and anyone
who knows hockey knows that hockey parents can be as intense as the
sport. Now the phrase ``hockey dad'' connotes a killer.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the stigma facing a hockey dad who happens to be a
postal worker.
</P>
<P>
   The rage phenomenon is popular because it fits everyone's
preconceptions. If you're upset by a general loss of civility in
society, the various rages provide extreme examples.
</P>
<P>
   If you dislike the automobile, airline travel or controlling
parents, you can point to rage as the natural result.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe in punishment, lawsuits, pledges, religion,
old-fashioned values or hippie non-competitiveness, you have an
answer to society's problem with rage.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, it's not clear that rage is a national problem,
at least statistically. Violent crime in all categories has
declined, and it's not even clear how much havoc has been caused by
the mother of all rages, road rage.
</P>
<P>
   The American Automobile Association says that nationally the
number of accidents caused by road rage increased from a reported
1,129 in 1990 to 1,800 in 1996, just before the term was invented.
</P>
<P>
   That's only three road rage accidents per month per state. But
the phrase ``tip of the iceberg'' comes to mind, when you consider
all the near-misses caused by anger in any one day on San Francisco
streets alone.
</P>
<P>
   We've all felt rage of the road, air or sports variety, and some
of us have felt it within ourselves. That's the appeal of rage as a
trend. We don't need a rage expert to tell us it's there.
</P>
<P>
   We certainly don't need another kind of rage. I'm getting old
and teed off, and please don't tell me about age rage.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
