<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S GOOD ABOUT PLAYING THE TOURIST
</HEADLINE>
  By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   As we puzzled our way through a
menu that appeared to be heavy on duck liver when all we wanted was
pommes frites, someone warned we were beginning to act like
tourists. Someone else pointed out that our cover was long blown,
seeing as how our French is not so tres hot, and one of us was
wearing socks with sandals.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is that not the worst? To be in a place where you have to
apologize and hold out a handful of change for the toll taker,
don't understand the answer even if you can manage the question,
can never seem to find the toilet, take copious photos of
strangers' clotheslines, and then have someone suspect you of not
being a native?
</P>
<P>
   Friends from Michigan who joined us in France said they were
trying not to act like Fudgies. A Fudgie is what the locals call
tourists who come to their part of the state on a maniacal mission
to buy boxes of Mackinac Island fudge.
</P>
<P>
   I thought that was pretty funny and wondered what we in Northern
California might call tourists who flock to our parts.
Merlot-heads? Crabbies?
</P>
<P>
   We all decided this thing about not wanting to be taken for a
tourist must come from being lumped in with that stereotyped
out-of-towner who blows into another country and grumbles loudly
about stores closing at night and not being able to find ice for
their cooler.
</P>
<P>
   However, we agreed, were it not for us spending our tourist
dollars in another country and their people spending their tourist
francs in ours, we might all have auto factories down the street
instead of charming old inns with red geraniums at the windows.
</P>
<P>
   As long as you're adaptable, what's wrong with being taken for a
tourist? Why pretend to know it all when you don't?
</P>
<P>
   Admit you're clueless. How many stamps does a postcard to the
United States take? Where does the soap go in the washing machine?
Does the kiss-kiss greeting go left cheek-right cheek or
right-left? (Left to right.)
</P>
<P>
   As the world shrinks and the global community grows, we tourists
are reminders that there are some borders that cannot be easily
crossed.
</P>
<P>
   Where would the fun be if we all ate dinner at 6 p.m. and knew
how to adjust the shower head? If everyone's market was a Safeway
and everyone's restaurant a Red Lobster, what would be the point of
ever leaving home?
</P>
<P>
   The unknowing tourist gets to make wonderful discoveries _ apple
and gorgonzola pizza, for example _ and see how the rest of the
world dances.
</P>
<P>
   After the third day of rain we headed south toward Spain, hoping
for sun. We drove into a French town near the Spanish border and
parked near a square. A band, dressed in black pants and gold
shirts, was starting to set up.
</P>
<P>
   People had gathered and when the music began we noticed a few in
the crowd start to shuffle their feet. With pointed toes they
softly pawed at the dirt, but held back, like shy children at a
ballroom dancing class.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually many were making the same movements and they started
coming together, clasping hands overhead and forming a circle. A
woman in a go-to-church suit, a younger one in jeans and high
heels, men in berets, an occasional teen-ager. Different people
would walk up and break in, matching the dancers' feet.
</P>
<P>
   The dancers didn't shout or kick up their heels. They simply
continued their small, delicate movements and smiled at one
another. Soon almost everyone in the square was dancing, leaving
only a few to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Later we spotted three of the dancers having a beer under a
yellow umbrella and asked them to tell us what had happened out in
the square. The dance is called the Sardana, explained one woman in
French, writing the word down for me. She called it a dance of
Catalan identity, a symbol of their culture. Another said it is
about solidarity and in Spain under Franco the dance became a sort
of people's protest.
</P>
<P>
   We apologized for our poor language skills and tried to tell
them we had never seen anything so lovely, that it was so darned
moving, it begged tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans?'' they asked. We said we're from California.
Tourists. They smiled.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
