<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NIRVANA ON THE BAY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Back when I was so smitten with this town that
I'd weep like a long-lost lover on touching down at San Francisco
International Airport, re-entry from a road trip or vacation was
always a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   No matter where I'd been _ to the Midwest to visit family or to
London to cover the effect of IRA terrorists on British tourism _
I'd mush my forehead against the plane window, peer down as we came
in over the San Francisco Bay and remember, ``Other places really
DO make me love you best.''
</P>
<P>
   The first whiff of cool, salt air as I stepped outside of the
San Francisco airport never failed to give me a thrill. The first
few days of maneuvering around town always lulled me into the same
smug state of satisfaction:
</P>
<P>
   Lucky, clever me. I lived and worked in the greatest city in the
whole New World.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, re-entry takes time and a concerted effort.
</P>
<P>
   From the Winchester Mystery House chaos of the airport to the
horn-blowing hell drivers of downtown, it is far easier to remember
what is wrong with San Francisco _ what we don't have, have too
much of or simply aren't _ than it is to remember why my heart ever
leapt upon returning.
</P>
<P>
   Now I have to work not to focus on the negatives.
</P>
<P>
   The dirt. The incompetence. The arrogance of the young rich. The
desolation of the street-bound poor. Billboards screaming from
every available wall. The noise, the disappearing views, the
grinding traffic, the overall feeling of dangerous IMBALANCE.
</P>
<P>
   But work I do because this is my home.
</P>
<P>
   If the positives _ the natural beauty, the human kindness, the
divine diversity _ no longer come to me unbeckoned, I'm willing to
search them out.
</P>
<P>
   Often this requires just keeping my eyes open, lifting my head
out of a book on the bus or actually looking into the face of a
poorly trained but hard-working young waiter or store cashier.
</P>
<P>
   The point is to be awake for the human connection, to see the
poignancy, vitality or profundity hidden just below the surface of
the ``ordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the old man on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   On my first work morning back from vacation, he called to me as
I was about to board a bus for downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask him to wait, please!'' he hollered from a half-block away.
</P>
<P>
   Working two canes, he hurried along the sidewalk in a painful
side-to-side gait. The effort seemed Herculean.
</P>
<P>
   Climbing aboard the bus, breathless, the man said, ``Eh, I've
lost my speed.'' But his smile _ radiating with good cheer and
humor _ told the real story:
</P>
<P>
   By God, he'd made it, and it was a great day.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes my re-entry searches for San Francisco's positives
entail more sophisticated work.
</P>
<P>
   Like Wesla Whitfield's opening night.
</P>
<P>
   A transplant from Smalltown, USA, as so many of us are,
Whitfield has made herself a major name in the international world
of cabaret singers. When she plays New York, it's in celebrated
(and sold out) rooms like the Algonquin Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, she and her husband and accompanist, Mike Greensill, always
come home to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this past week, Whitfield, Greensill and their bassist,
Ken Miller, opened a three-week run at the York Hotel's Plush Room.
The first-night crowd was filled with connoisseurs of the cream of
American standards, the songs of giants like Harold Arlen, Irving
Berlin, Jerome Kern and Cole Porter.
</P>
<P>
   As always, Whitfield delivered the goods. In spades. And, after
the show, she and Greensill moved to the hotel bar to receive
kisses, kudos and hugs from a receiving line that snaked out into
the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I can live here for 32 years and have a sort of
career and know everybody in the audience by name,'' Whitfield said
the next day. ``That wouldn't be true in any other city in this
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco is such a tiny city, but with all the amenities
of a great big one.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most of us, Whitfield confessed, she and Greensill
sometimes ``play this real estate game,'' picturing what kind of
mansion they could get elsewhere for the price of their Bayview
District home.
</P>
<P>
   But it's just a game. It always will be.
</P>
<P>
   Said Greensill: ``We really can't imagine living any place else
but here.''
</P>
<P>
   To which I say, ditto.
</P>
<P>
   I may not be moved to tears every time my plane lands these
days, and it may take me a little longer to remember why, but, the
truth is _ lucky, clever me; I still believe I live in the greatest
city in the whole New World.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
