<HEADER>
A9901 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-12 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DIVERSITY SHOULD INCLUDE ASIAN-AMERICANS, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WILLIAM WONG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Norman Mineta's nomination as Commerce secretary
in the last six months of the Clinton administration was widely
hailed by Asian-American political activists. And, from a symbolic
perspective, well it should be.
</P>
<P>
   If confirmed by the Senate, the former California congressman,
now a senior executive with defense contractor Lockheed Martin,
would become the first Cabinet member of Asian ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   Asian-Americans have long felt politically excluded because of
past legal discrimination and relatively small numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Only now, with sharp population growth and more experience,
Asian-Americans are participating in mainstream politics in larger
numbers. This change is acknowledged by Mineta's nomination,
although it has the appearance of a political crumb.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta has long been a political pioneer _ as San Jose mayor in
the early 1970s and as a member of the House of Representatives
from 1974 to 1995. His personal story tugs at the heart. Along with
120,000 others, he and his family were locked away in U.S.
relocation camps during World War II solely because of their
Japanese ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Mineta could have broken the symbolic racial barrier
eight years ago. Newly elected President Clinton offered him the
job of secretary of Transportation. Mineta turned him down because
he was in line to become chairman of the House public works and
transportation committee _ a more powerful position, he felt, than
secretary of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   His dilemma at the beginning of the Clinton administration
illustrated the paucity of experienced Asian-American political
figures at the national level.
</P>
<P>
   Asian-American candidates for possible Cabinet jobs in early
1993 were Mineta and Robert T. Matsui, another U.S. representative
from California, a Japanese-American with less seniority.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Asian-American political activists hungered for a
Cabinet appointment, especially after Clinton said he would name a
Cabinet that ``looked like America.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mineta turned him down, Clinton filled his senior team with
white men, white women, African-Americans and Hispanics, but no one
of Asian descent.
</P>
<P>
   Racial symbolism has its limits. In our multicultural democracy,
where some groups are emerging from subjugated status, racial
politics are a fact of life. But soon, underrepresented groups like
Asian-Americans should pay a lot more attention to what politicians
who look like them actually stand for and do.
</P>
<P>
   That is beginning to happen. San Francisco is a perfect example.
It is only within the past two decades that Asian-Americans have
served on that city's governing Board of Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are three supervisors of Asian descent, but rivalries
and disagreements among the three override the symbolism of ethnic
pride. In many ways, they have gone beyond racial politics and
mostly practice politics as usual, based on ideology, personal
feelings and ego.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, a few more Asian-Americans politicians _ such as
Gary Locke, the governor of Washington, and David Wu, a U.S.
representative from Oregon _ have emerged. Their high profile helps
boost the perpetually sad-sack morale of Asian-American political
activists, but symbolic value has a short half-life.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, some Chinese-Americans are chagrined that Wu, a
Democrat, opposed normal trade status for China. Chinese-American
Republicans, in lively e-mail exchanges, jabbed at Wu's stance,
which was shared by a majority of House Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Asian-Americans are such a diverse lot that a handful of
political leaders can't be expected to represent their wide
interests and still have credibility with the 96 percent of
Americans who are not of Asian descent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is wongink(at)earthlink.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
