<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-TRAITHLON-LAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TRIATHLETE SALLY EDWARDS, LAST IS BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no telling who will win the local stage of the Danskin
Women's Triathlon Series Sunday at Lake Pearl in Wrentham, mass..
There is no doubt, however, as to who will finish last.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Edwards, a 16-time Ironman finisher, Triathlon Hall of
Fame member and pre-race training instructor, has dibs on last
place. She has run in each Danskin event since its inception in
1990, yet for six consecutive years, has seen the backside of every
finisher at each.
</P>
<P>
   It's her job. She's what folks in triathlon call a sweeper, a
designated slowpoke. She purposely finishes behind the back, and
therefore, no other runner has to put up with the dread and
embarrassment of finishing last.
</P>
<P>
   The Sacramento, Calif., resident, a Danskin national
spokesperson and one of the sport's most celebrated figures (she
has published five books on triathlon) said she got the idea of
coming in last after coming up injured before a Danskin race in New
York six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The injury didn't prevent her from running, but it figured she
would likely finish last. So she asked Danskin representatives if
she could do so officially. After years of finishing first (or
close to it), bringing up the rear gave her an entirely different
perspective on triathlon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea of what happens in back of the pack,'' said
Edwards. ``All of those people struggling, and no one wanting to
finish last.''
</P>
<P>
   She is slated to run at Wrentham, which will be the third
installment of the seven-city series. Other cities include San
Jose, Calif.; Orlando, Fla., and Austin, Texas. More than 50,000
have competed in the women-only event since its inception. Danskin
officials say it is the only multi-sport series for amateur female
athletes in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The race is open to participants ages 14 and older and is
structured for both first-time and experienced competitors. The
course will be a .75K swim (approximately a half-mile), a 20K bike
race (about 11 miles) and a 5K run (3.1 miles). The event is
scheduled to begin at 7:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Even with pre-race instructions, you're bound to have many folks
struggling to keep up with the pack. Danskin officials have
attempted to make certain those who finish last get as much
satisfaction from having completed the course as those who battle
for first (races usually take about three hours to complete).
</P>
<P>
   That's where Edwards comes in. She said among the things she
discovered in coming in last was that those at the back of the pack
continue to work as hard to finish as anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a highly competitive person,'' said Edwards. ``I've been
racing for 30 years. I've crossed hundreds of finish lines first.
And this is, without a doubt, the most deeply gratifying experience
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   It is quite a difference, she said, going from competing at the
top level of triathlon to purposely running, biking, and swimming
slow. That's similar to an NBA shooting whiz participating in a
3-point shooting contest with a few amateurs and deliberately
clanking attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big believer in heart-rate monitoring,'' said Edwards.
``My heart rate never goes over 100 beats per minute during the
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not physically strenuous, but emotionally it is
extremely difficult, because you're telling yourself'' you are to
finish at a pace slower than that which you're capable.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said she now races competitively only in winter and
fall. As Danskin's national spokesperson, her competitive races
cannot interfere with Danskin races, which run throughout the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   But the triathlon record-holder said she's stored up memorable
moments as a designated sweeper that she never would have
experienced in competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks ago, at the Danskin Triathlon in San Jose, there was
a woman right in front of me as we approached the finish line,''
Edwards said, ``and she asked if we could go hand in hand as we
crossed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a large crowd which cheered us. And, the woman told
me that she was 72 years old, that she was never much of an
athlete, and that she had lost 80 pounds training for the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `This is the happiest day of my life.' When you
realize that someone has had 72 years of happiness, for that one
moment to be the happiest of her life, that's pretty moving.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
