<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-INSURANCE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAY FLANNEL INSURERS HEAD FOR CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANTHONY FLINT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Already a latecomer to the Internet party, the buttoned-down
denizens of the insurance industry are still struggling to fit in.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies have been too busy fixing outdated computer
systems to look ahead. Others were slow to anticipate that the
industry's 1950s-era paperwork system was ripe for an Internet
overhaul _ at least as much as brokerage or banking.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the late start, it seems clear the $3 trillion
industry is in store for some seismic changes. The question is
whether the slow-and-steady approach will help or hinder.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say there are two basic scenarios for the day when more
individuals and businesses shop for insurance products online. In
one, brokers become extinct, as consumers deal directly with
brand-name insurance companies or comparison-shop in e-commerce
marketplaces. Simple products such as auto or home insurance
increasingly are being bought this way.
</P>
<P>
   Others say brokers are here to stay, and that insurance
customers of all kinds need the hand-holding and advice that agents
provide. Apparently clicking lacks a certain gravitas when
contemplating one's own demise and choosing life insurance, for
example. Companywide benefits are famously complicated, requiring
broker guidance, not to mention the new annuities hybrids starting
to roll out in the boundary-blurred financial services marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   With brokers a vital part of the distribution system, the
Internet will have its biggest impact in a business-to-business
context, by cutting waste and speeding up transactions. One
Massachusetts company betting on that outcome is StarNex Inc. of
Wrentham, mass., part of a new crop of facilitators that can
organize the flow of information, cut through legendary paperwork,
and help brokers and carriers work better together.
</P>
<P>
   There are no shortage of strategists, Internet experts and fresh
business-school graduates willing to oversee the insurance
industry's new economy makeover. The problem, analysts say, has
been the insurance industry itself. Carriers are just now replacing
old computer systems, well behind brokerages and banks, and they
are behind in the online world as well.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers, meanwhile, are looking at slashed commissions,
continuing a love-hate relationship with carriers, and worried they
may yet be left out.
</P>
<P>
   True, it's the insurance business. These are not exactly wild
and crazy guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional insurance companies had their hands in the
sand as the Internet distribution of products grew,''said Louis S.
Harvey, president of Dalbar Inc., the financial services rating and
research firm. ``Within financial services, they are the last
bastion.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurance transactions on the Internet are on the rise, but the
traffic is still modest. A Forrester Research Inc. report this year
found that less than 1 percent of consumers buy insurance online,
though researching insurance is very popular. Forrester predicts
that online insurance sales could reach $14 billion by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Like many others, Dalbar's Harvey believes that the insurance
companies must find a way to make more efficient use of the
nation's estimated 175,000 brokers, rather than cutting them out
entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the brokers the cash register doesn't ring,'' he said.
``It takes a person to deliver an inherently negative message;
every insurance product is fear-based. That has never sold
effectively without someone there to make the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The process today, though, is anything but efficient. Agents
talk with customers and get a variety of quotes from carriers, by
phone and fax. For life insurance, customers need to get a medical
examination. Perhaps 30 days later, they may put their signature on
a policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do things instantaneously now,'' said Harvey. ``That's how
we do banking, that's how we buy stocks. Insurance is still back in
the '50s.''
</P>
<P>
   The current process is costly to carriers as well, with
commissions often soaking up the entire value of the first year's
premium.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no shortage of frenzied activity to change the
situation. It's just that the online insurance scene is at the
moment is profoundly confusing, with no single approach _
``disintermediation'' or otherwise _ rising to dominance.
</P>
<P>
   Currently there is a hodge-podge of insurance supermarkets such
as InsWeb, Fidelity's Insurance.com, and Quicken, and virtual
insurers such as California-based eCoverage. At John Hancock, the
shopping and research side of the equation falls to the separate
Signatory Group; John Hancock Insurance Co. sells insurance to all
distributors, Signatory and everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   StarNex, by contrast, seeks to use the Internet to make the
existing relationship between brokers and carriers more efficient,
said chief executive John Unipan. Founded in 1998, StarNex created
BrokersPortal.com ``to enable brokers and companies to transact
business and find specific information quickly,'' Unipan said.
``We're going to be the intermediary and the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Unipan acknowledges ``There has been a lot of chaos, the
beginnings of different kinds of business models maneuvering in
this space. But agents and brokers are going to be present in
substantial portion of the business for next several years _
particularly for more complicated coverages like commercial or
company benefits. So we thought that was the place to start,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those trying to disintermediate got all the press, in all
industries, but the business-to-consumer model is not taking hold
as much as predicted,'' said StarNex chief marketing officer Jim
Kerley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now insurers are trying to focus on their core business,
realizing it goes through traditional organizations. The second
wave of change may not be as glamorous because it's not as
disruptive,'' Kerley said. ``But if we can make the broker more
efficient, we can by definition make the carrier more efficient. We
want to enable the broker and the carrier to maintain a
relationship, use the Internet for efficiencies, rather than have
the Internet eliminate those relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy certainly seems wise in this summer of Internet
discontent, with business models everywhere failing to live up to
hype. And in that respect, a glacial pace may end up being the
insurance industry's best asset. At least for now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
