<HEADLINE>
IN THE US, A CHANCE FOR REFUGE FOR SUDANESE BOYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are known as the lost boys, several thousand young Sudanese
men who have spent their adolescences on the run, fleeing war,
famine, and slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Now, according to officials at the State Department and the US
Catholic Conference, the US government will soon admit most of the
young Sudanese men as refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church, which runs the largest refugee resettlement
program in the country, will help many find a home in several
American cities.
</P>
<P>
   For at least the past decade, these young men, children of two
tribes of Sudanese cattle herders, have been orphaned and wounded,
forced into military service and involuntary labor, and shuttled
from country to country.
</P>
<P>
   The 3,000 to 4,000 young men are victims of one of the world's
most prolonged conflicts, a 17-year religious war that produced a
humanitarian crisis described as the worst in the world today.
</P>
<P>
   The men are expected to be one of the most challenging groups
encountered by resettlement officials because of their disrupted
childhoods. Most of them spent years without any semblance of the
social structure imposed by adults. They have had little education,
they have had no exposure to urban life, and they will be moving to
cities without large communities of Sudanese immigrants who might
ease their transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This group is going to be different because, unlike a Cuban
refugee or a Bosnian refugee, they're going to come here with zero
English, zero work skills, and most of them will find a doorknob a
fascinating technological gadget because they come from a very
primitive rural milieu,'' said Joseph Doolin, president of Catholic
Charities in Boston. ``But we believe that everyone has the
intrinsic right to a decent life, and as part of an international
organization _ the church _ we work to improve the opportunities
and the life that individuals have.''
</P>
<P>
   Sudan has been engulfed in civil war between the Muslim north
and the Christian and animist south for 17 years, during which more
than 2 million people have died, mostly from starvation, and
another 4.5 million have been displaced.
</P>
<P>
   The US government and human rights groups have accused the
Islamic party, which seized power in the Sudan in 1989, guilty of
supporting terrorism and committing genocide through massacres,
slavery, and ``calculated starvation,'' by eliminating sources of
food and then preventing access to aid.
</P>
<P>
   The humanitarian crisis in the Sudan is arguably the world's
most dire. Representative Christopher H. Smith, a New Jersey
Republican, said last month that the situation in the Sudan ``may
well be the most widespread, systematic, and brutal crimes against
humanity being committed anywhere in the world today.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a State Department official who asked not to be
identified, the Sudanese men are mostly members of the Dinka and
Nuer peoples, ethnic groups who live along the Nile in southern
Sudan and have an economy based on cattle herding. The young men,
many of whom are orphans, fled Sudan to avoid forced conscription
or slavery.
</P>
<P>
   The men spent the late 1980s in Ethiopia, were expelled by that
country back to Sudan, and eventually fled to Kenya, where they
have been living in a refugee camp since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is the boys, based on what they have gone
through, have no prospects for returning back to where they came
from,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has agreed to consider for resettlement most
of the Sudanese young men, based on a recommendation by the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, and is now beginning to
conduct interviews to make sure those recommended are eligible and
do not pose a security risk.
</P>
<P>
   Once they arrive in the United States, perhaps beginning this
year, they will be cared for by one of 10 resettlement agencies, of
which the Catholic Church is the largest. Since 1975, the Catholic
Church has resettled about 800,000 refugees in the United States,
about one-third of all refugees during that period, according to
Marie Quinlan, a spokeswoman for the National Conference of
Catholic Bishops.
</P>
<P>
   The largest groups of refugees have been from Vietnam and other
parts of southeast Asia, from Bosnia and other parts of eastern
Europe, and from Cuba and Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic Charities in Boston resettles about 300 refugees each
year, including a small handful of Sudanese refugees over the last
several years. The agency, using mostly federal funds, houses,
feeds and trains refugees, with a goal of providing them the
language, work and life skills so they can live on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been lost boys for their entire childhoods,
wandering around on foot, avoiding bombs and bullets and also
avoiding being drafted into one army or another, and once they got
situated they kind of established their own little family units,''
said Claire Carroll, director of refugee and immigration services
for Catholic Charities of Boston. ``Our goal will be to help them
become completely self-sufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Sudanese are thought to be Catholic, but the church
resettles refugees regardless of religious affiliation and does not
use its refugee resettlement programs for proselytization,
according to church officials.
</P>
<P>
   A specialist on international issues who recently visited Sudan
lauded the effort to bring the refugees to the United States, but
said the world must do more to help end the civil war there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got millions of displaced people, it's easy to say
that taking a few thousand people out isn't very important, but
then you'd end up doing nothing,'' said Elliott Abrams, chairman of
the US Commission on International Religious Freedom. ``Ultimately,
this can't be the main answer, because you can't take all those
displaced people out of the country, but if you ask, `Where is the
leadership of tomorrow's Sudan?' maybe among those 3,000 to 4,000
boys who are now going to get an education you'll find it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9917 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      07-12 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB ADVENTURES; THE SELF-MADE MAN BEHIND `SURVIVOR' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PRAGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many parts of Marc Andreessen's past are almost cliche by now,
but when he was doing it, it was brand new. He was one of those
superyoung Internet savants who helped created something
(Netscape), got bought out (by AOL), made millions, and then fell
off the radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   But as evidenced by his prominence in two tech magazines now on
newsstands, including as Wired's cover boy for August, Andreessen,
29, is back, and with business plan that is wholly untypical of the
times: He's in it for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   As Wired writer David Sheff explains it, Andreessen and his
comrades at Loudcloud were casting about for the next great
computer breakthrough and thought they'd found it, only to be
beaten to market while they assembled the nuts and bolts to support
it.
</P>
<P>
   Aware that it could easily happen again, they decided to create
a generic framework first, and then just plug in their idea when
they got it. And that's when they got it: They would be the ones to
help others get to market quickly; they would tend to the Web, and
their customers could stick to their knitting.
</P>
<P>
   That in itself is no big deal; plenty of people provide Web
hosting. What Loudcloud offers, Sheff explains, is greater
automation, embodied in Opsware, software that enables Loudcloud
``to put up a new Web site with a keystroke or two.'' To an
ordinary end user, that seems very nice but not exactly rocket
science, but analysts say it could all be very big.
</P>
<P>
   What's unmistakeably revolutionary in this economy's
built-to-flip atmosphere is Loudcloud's approach to building a
company, covered not only in Wired but in a Red Herring ``case
study,'' essentially a short essay by Andreessen. He says he wants
to build something lasting, to be able ``to look back and realize
that I was at the creation of something great.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of his method is to place import on every hire, driven by
his Law of Crappy People, which holds that the worst employee hired
at any level becomes the standard for that level. Loudcloud's ninth
employee was a recruiter, and the emphasis on personnel continues:
Employees are reviewed _ and get to review their supervisors _
every 90 days, because ``these days, who can even remember what
happened six or nine months ago?'' cofounder and CEO Ben Horowitz
says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another, quite different man-of-the-moment is Mark Burnett, the
arrogant cuss behind ``Survivor,'' CBS's
sort-of-but-not-really-reality show burning up the summer airwaves.
He is profiled in the July/August National Geographic Adventure,
which initially seems an odd place to read about a TV producer, but
it quickly begins to make sense.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-1990s, writes Gretchen Reynolds, he has been
leading the charge for what is being touted as ``the faster-growing
team sport in America,'' adventure racing, in which competitors who
are plopped down in some outrageous environment compete to return
to civilization first.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett brings to mind Pete Rose, admirable for his hard work
and accomplishment but not particularly likeable. He came to the
States nearly penniless 18 years ago, not well educated, skilled
only in what he learned as a British commando, and knowing only one
person.
</P>
<P>
   But within six hours, he says, he had been hired as a nanny, and
within four years, Reynolds writes, had ``married a pretty blonde,
had a son, then another, and bought a big house not far from where
he used to babysit.'' Then he attended a course given by the
motivational Merlin Tony Robbins, he says, and the world became his
playground.
</P>
<P>
   His success has spawned, or released, a grating imperiousness.
Asked, for example, about his charges on ``Survivor,'' he is
contemptuous: ``Too bad the folks on the show couldn't really make
it on their own. We're going to have to give them rice and things
to keep them going. They'd die otherwise. From where I sit, there's
only one person I know of who could survive on the island on his
own. Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Surviving alone, of course, is the only way he could do it: If
he were on the show, he'd be quickly voted off so the others didn't
have to put up with him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brill's Content for August brings the very best sort of tale
that the media criticism magazine can hope to offer, the story
behind the now-famous photo of Elian Gonzalez's being taken from
the home he'd been staying in in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Written by Amy Bach, Steven Brill, and Julie Scelfo, the account
profiles the photographer, Alan Diaz, and explores the very murky
ethical currents that led to Diaz's being inside the house at the
moment of the government's raid. It is sympathetic but questioning,
and fittingly for a picture painted in shades of gray, draws no
firm conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Some elements of the story are not contended. Diaz is a
hard-working Cuban-American who came to photojournalism as a
vocation more than as a calling. Also not in contention is that his
doggedness is a primary reason he got the access he did; it's the
other reasons that present the difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon for journalists to develop relationships with
subjects during a long-term story, especially when, as Diaz was
doing, they camp outside the subjects' house for weeks on end. But
even from afar, it's not always clear when that relationship has
compromised a journalist's objectivity, and that is Brill's
Content's chief question:
</P>
<P>
   By getting close enough to the family to win their trust, did
Diaz cease being an impartial observer? There's no doubt that,
given the chance, any photographer or reporter would have accepted
an invitation to be inside when the action went down, and anyone
would have been proud to capture the image.
</P>
<P>
   Judgments about how Diaz came to be there will continue, and
ultimately will determine whether the photo deserves a place in the
pantheon of great photojournalism, or is merely propaganda.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
