<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GONSALVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLY GONSALVES WAS NOT JUST A HISTORICAL FOOTNOTE IN SOCCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Soccer has emerged as the most popular participant sport in the
United States. Its national teams consistently qualify for World
Cup finals and the country has a credible, if unambitious,
professional league.
</P>
<P>
   All this seems to be a recent, burgeoning phenomenon, devoid of
roots. But in fact, those roots were on the way to being
established and soccer was thriving before the Great Depression,
when the American Soccer League was the highest-paying league in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   The ASL imported most of its players from Europe, offering
financial and/or political sanctuary, but soon began producing
homegrown talent, enough by 1930 that the US national team reached
the semifinals of the first World Cup in Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
   And the best of those young Americans was an inside right
halfback from Fall River, Mass. named Adelino ``Billy'' Gonsalves,
considered the greatest native-born player in US soccer history.
Gonsalves was nicknamed ``The Babe Ruth of Soccer,'' though had he
chosen differently he might have become ``The Pele of Baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Gonsalves displayed a unique combination of
composure, strength, and staying power. His skills were recognized
internationally and he attracted offers from the best teams in both
baseball and soccer, which were then the only viable professional
sports on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Gonsalves is probably the only person ever to be offered
contracts by Brazilian (Botafogo), Italian (Roma, Lazio), and
Scottish (Celtic, Rangers) clubs, as well as the New York Yankees,
who wanted to sign him as a pitcher, and the St. Louis Cardinals,
who projected Gonsalves as a first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Gonsalves chose the World Cup over the World Series, a decision
that relegated him to the fringes of the sporting scene
domestically but allowed him to be a part of international history.
</P>
<P>
   On July 13, 1930, Gonsalves was a 21-year-old in the starting
lineup as the US defeated Belgium, 3-0, in the first World Cup game
ever, at the Parc Central Stadium in Montevideo. Four days later, a
20-year-old from Fall River named Bert Patenaude converted the
World Cup's first hat trick as the US blanked Paraguay, 3-0. In the
semifinal game in the new 100,000-capacity Estadio Centenario,
Argentina virtually disabled three US players. Center back Raphael
Tracy departed with a broken leg in the first half, and since no
substitutes were allowed, Gonsalves took Tracy's position as the
team continued with 10 players in a 6-1 loss.
</P>
<P>
   The US was awarded third place on goal differential over
Yugoslavia, and the future seemed bright for American soccer. But
the Depression devastated the ASL, and Gonsalves and his peers fell
into a sort of limbo, fending for themselves in semiprofessional
situations and gathering for what would be a final appearance on
the international stage at the 1934 World Cup in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the demise of the ASL and the US national program,
Gonsalves would transcend his time. In end-of-the-century ratings
by the International Federation of Football History and Statistics
of Wiesbaden, Germany, Gonsalves was No. 6 among players in North
America, the only US player in the all-time top 10.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gonsalves was born Aug. 10, 1908, in Portsmouth, R.I., the son
of immigrants from the Madeira Islands. He grew up in the
Portuguese section of Fall River and learned soccer from the
British, who were considered the masters of the sport. The lively
Fall River club soccer scene honed the skills of dozens of
top-flight players, starting a tradition that continued until
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In this cauldron of competition, teeming with seasoned pros from
Europe, Gonsalves passed his first tests as a teenager. He moved to
East Cambridge at age 18 and won the Boston and District League
with Lusitania Recreation, then became the youngest player to sign
with the Boston Wonder Workers, making his First Division debut in
a 3-0 win over the New York Giants Sept. 10, 1927.
</P>
<P>
   The Wonder Workers won the ASL championship, taking a 4-2
victory over the New Bedford Whalers at Battery Park June 16, 1928.
Gonsalves would win two more ASL titles with the Fall River
Marksmen and eight US Open Cup championships (a record he shares
with longtime teammate Alec McNab).
</P>
<P>
   But Gonsalves's most famous accomplishments were with the US
national team.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1930 World Cup, the US team toured Brazil, taking a
4-3 win over Santos, and the players later boasted that they had
defeated Pele's grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1934 World Cup, Gonsalves was established as the US' most
dominant player. When the US traveled to Rome for the finals,
though, Gonsalves threatened to leave the team unless Aldo ``Buff''
Donelli was in the starting lineup. Coach Elmer Schroeder obliged
and Donelli, who later played and coached in the National Football
League, scored all the US goals in a 4-2 win over Mexico and a 7-1
loss to Italy in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   As Gonsalves performed on the World Cup stage, interest from
foreign clubs poured in.
</P>
<P>
   Recalled US defender Peter Pietras in ``US Soccer vs. the
World'' by Tony Cirino: ``For Gonsalves there were representatives
from many teams in our hotel all the time. He refused all the
offers. He would say there's no place like home.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonsalves later regretted declining the offers, which were worth
as much as $10,000 plus expenses, a house, and bonuses for wins and
ties. He was well-compensated in the ASL, and he later remained in
demand, playing until 1953 as leader of teams as diverse in their
ethnicity as Brooklyn Hispano, Hakoah All-Stars, Kearny Scots,
Newark Germans, and St. Louis Shamrocks.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Gonsalves carried on a low-profile existence in Kearny,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Gonsalves married Mary McNab, the former wife of his teammate,
Alex McNab, who had been a Scottish national team player. The
couple did not have children, but Gonsalves did play on a team with
one of his stepchildren. Gonsalves died in Kearny July 17, 1977.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `He was ahead of his time,'' recalled his niece, Judith
Mitchell, who lives in Fall River. ``He was playing soccer when it
was not that popular in this country. He was looked up to, revered,
by a lot of people but if you met him you would never have known
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember him as very charismatic, with movie star looks. He
always wore a straw hat and polo shirt. He was powerful-looking,
warm, outgoing, with a sense of humility. He didn't make that much
money playing soccer, but for him that wasn't an issue. He was
doing what he wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, many of Gonsalves's greatest feats occurred in
baseball stadia. On May 30, 1931, he scored a hat trick for the New
York Yankees' soccer team in a 4-3 victory over Scottish Cup
champions Celtic at Fenway Park. Legendary Celtic manager Willie
Maley called this ``the greatest performance I have ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   He was powerfully built (estimates of his size range from 5 feet
11 inches to 6 feet 1 inch and from 185 to 210 pounds) with a
strong shot (among his nicknames was ``Ol' Piano Legs'') and,
apparently, a strong throwing arm.
</P>
<P>
   Among Gonsalves's teammates was goalkeeper Johnny Reder, who
also played first base for the Red Sox. Gonsalves recalled a tour
to Mexico in which his team not only won in soccer but also
defeated the Mexicans in a baseball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But it is difficult to place Gonsalves's accomplishments in
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of his peers say he was the best,'' said Colin Jose,
historian for the National Soccer Hall of Fame in Oneonta, N.Y.
``But there are no films of him playing, so it is hard to say. You
can't really go by stats, like in baseball, but I would say he was
one of the great American sportsmen. But like a lot of soccer
people, he gets lost in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he were a young player today, he would probably be playing
in Europe. They say he was offered contracts in Europe, but he
didn't go. You have to play at the top level to develop your
skills, and when Gonsalves was playing I don't think anybody else
was paying what they were paying in the ASL.''
</P>
<P>
   The program for the May 14, 1944, US Open Cup final at the Polo
Grounds, which would be Gonsalves's eighth and final title, noted:
``Gonsalves is without any shadow of a doubt the greatest player in
the game today, with the most terrific shot in history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always regarded Bill Gonsalves as the closest thing we
saw to the ideal, complete player,'' the St. Louis Dispatch's Dent
McSkimming said in the '70s. ``As a reporter, I always asked the
foreign players the inevitable question, and in total they agreed
that Gonsalves would win a place and be a star in any team in the
world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
