<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW-YIELD PORTFOLIO LACKS A FIXED-INCOME SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We hope to retire in two years and expect $40,000 to be a
comfortable retirement income. What do you think of the feasibility
of retirement with no part-time work?
</P>
<P>
   D.A., Concord, N.H. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Certainly there will be plenty of assets on hand to supply
your target income, but delivering it from your portfolio will
require some adjustments. My tally of the actual yield _ estimating
that your cash investments will average 5 percent _ comes to a
little more than $12,000, with your money market and savings
accounts, the DPL holding, and Janus Balanced being the only
investments providing a significant income stream. Most of the rest
yield less than 1 percent. Average yield for the entire portfolio
is less than 1.9 percent. While the portfolio is nicely designed
for long-term growth, I suggest that in the next two years you
gradually build a real fixed-income side to the portfolio. You now
have $297,000 in 10 funds that are focused primarily on large-cap
domestic stocks.
</P>
<P>
   By the time you retire, I'd like to see about $100,000 in a
fixed-income portfolio. If you were to divert all of your current
yields in the next two years to such investments, you would need to
move only about $74,500 from the stock funds to the fixed-income
side to reach that goal. I would take all of that sum from the
various domestic stock funds, timing your sale of shares in the
funds you now hold so as to minimize the tax effect _ probably best
achieved by selling $25,000 worth of stock fund shares in each of
tax years 2000, 2001, and 2002.
</P>
<P>
   There are many solid fixed-income funds. My suggestion would be
a three-legged portfolio, such as putting half of the fixed-income
money in Vanguard GNMA, and a quarter each in Vanguard Short-Term
Bond fund and Vanguard High-Yield Corporate bond fund. Almost every
major fund family has similar offerings. You should expect a yield
of about 6.5 percent from this segment of the portfolio, raising
your overall income stream to nearly $18,000 in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Other than making that move, I think you have a nicely designed
portfolio which should supply the income you will need in
retirement and provide plenty of growth of principal, to keep pace
with inflation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have no investments, but plan to ``max out'' contributions
to my company's 401(k) plan when I begin participating in the near
future. After the real estate sale, I plan to apply $100,000 toward
the purchase of a house and invest $500,000. I would then retire
when my investments would be able to yield $50,000 in today's
buying power. How do you suggest I proceed, and when can I retire?
I'm willing to accept moderate risk. I plan to speak to a financial
planner eventually, but I would like your suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   P.L., Bridgeton, Maine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, you could probably retire fairly comfortably in 10
years, but I like the numbers much better if you considering
waiting 12 years, when you will be 50 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the math: If you contribute to your 401(k) at a $10,500
annual rate, and if all of your investments average 10 percent
annual returns, you would have $1,532,563 after 10 years. To
maintain a lifestyle that now costs $50,000 a year, you would need
$70,592 if inflation averages 3.5 percent for that decade. If you
calculate that a fixed-income portfolio will yield you 6.5 percent,
you would thus need a bit less than $1.1 million to provide your
income stream, leaving you with only about $430,000 in growth
vehicles that could protect you against the inflation of the later
years of your retirement.
</P>
<P>
   That may seem like a lot of extra money, but bear in mind that
inflation can really gnaw away at your resources, and retiring at
age 48 is very early retirement; the earlier you retire, the more
protection against inflation you will need. After the first decade
of your retirement, you would need $99,489 a year to maintain your
lifestyle. A decade further along, the figure would be $140,339. So
I would like to see a bigger buffer fund.
</P>
<P>
   If you follow the same projection for 12 years, you would have a
$1,893,677 accumulation and you would need $75,553 to maintain your
current lifestyle. A fixed-income portfolio of $1,175,000 would do
the trick, which would leave you with $718,677 to put in
growth-oriented investments to protect you against future
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good idea to approach a financial planner on this,
especially if you can find a planner whose long suit is tax
expertise. Obviously with such large projected accumulations, taxes
will be a problem, and you will want to take advantage of the many
routes available to defer taxation. Depending on whether your
employer will provide matching funds, you might find that your
overall tax situation would be improved by diverting $2,000 a year
from the 401(k) contributions to a Roth IRA.
</P>
<P>
   If I were to suggest a portfolio that's likely to deliver this
growth, I'd look at a portfolio dominated by Vanguard index funds.
You might consider putting half of your money into Vanguard Index
500 fund, then dividing the remainder evenly among Vanguard Mid-Cap
Index, Vanguard Small-Cap Index, Vanguard Health Care, and Vanguard
International Growth funds.
</P>
<P>
   Would such a portfolio represent ``some degree of moderate
risk''? In truth, no. It would probably be better characterized as
having a normal degree of risk for a long-term investor. If you
wanted to ratchet the risk level downward, you might consider 35
percent in Vanguard Index 500, 30 percent in Vanguard Balanced
Index, 10 percent each in Vanguard Mid-Cap, Small-Cap and
International Growth funds, and 5 percent in Vanguard Health Care
funds. But if you did that, you should also expect that portfolio
growth would be a bit slower than what is projected above.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What would happen If I had a capital gain of about $500,000
from selling long-term stock holdings now? How and when would be
the best time to send estimated tax payments to the IRS? How long
can I delay without being penalized?
</P>
<P>
   S.D., Andover, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This is a problem that you might want to take to a tax
professional. The editors of ``J. K. Lasser's Your Income Tax, 2000
edition,'' are not easily daunted by tax complexities, but they
warn that penalties on underpayment of the estimated tax payments
may be eliminated or reduced only by using a method called the
annualized income installment method. They then add, ``The
computation is complicated and its use may be discouraged by the
complexity, despite the potential benefits.'' I don't know about
you, but when J. K. Lasser is daunted by tax complexities, I am
daunted as well.
</P>
<P>
   If you use the normal method of calculating estimated tax
payments, the rules call for equal payments of your tax liability
on April 17, June 15, Sept. 15, and Jan. 15 (although you can wait
until Jan. 31 if you file your completed return and pay the tax due
by that date).
</P>
<P>
   If you were to make a payment on Sept. 15 that included the
balances that should have been paid on April 17 and June 15, there
will be no penalty for underpayment relating to the third and
fourth payments.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to explore the annualized income installment method,
Lasser's guide suggests you request Form 2210 and IRS Publication
505.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you could always take the chance of waiting until
early next year to make the sales, thus providing you with a close
idea of what your tax liability for tax year 2001 before the first
payment is due, guaranteeing that you will avoid the penalties _
but of course if the market should take an adverse turn during the
remainder of this year, you could end up in worse shape than if you
sold now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 1339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9921 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     07-12 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATCH HAS LOST SPARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They did it. It took more than 60 years, but Major
League Baseball finally succeeded in sapping all significance out
of the All-Star Game. The hardball elements that made the midsummer
game special have been officially eliminated from the festival.
</P>
<P>
   How do we tell today's kids that baseball's All-Star Game used
to be a really big deal? In not-so-long-ago days, baby boomer ball
fans actually anticipated the clash and cared which team won. In
Boston, we took pride in being American League People. There was
great mystery about the National League, and the July joust
provided a rare view of that other league. The National League's
eight-game winning streak (1963-70) really hurt, and it was great
to see Reggie Jackson lead the AL back to victory in Detroit in
1971.
</P>
<P>
   There were quintessential American League guys like Al Kaline,
Carl Yastrzemski, Brooks Robinson, and Luis Tiant. And there were
National League guys like Stan Musial, Ernie Banks, Joe Morgan, and
Sandy Koufax. It was a big deal when Frank Robinson came to the
Orioles from the Reds because he was a National League-type player.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's all neutralized or diluted. Two distinct factions have
merged into one body, governed by a powerful, all-inclusive Players
Association. Baseball is like football, basketball, and hockey.
There's no identity to either league. No mystery, either. Free
agency, cable TV, and interleague play have combined to strip the
thrill of a once-a-summer meeting of American and National League
All-Stars. Players change teams every hour, the Mets play games
against the Yankees, and you can watch every player every day on TV
if you've got a big dish and nothing but time.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, a Hall of Famer who played all but one of his big league
seasons in the National League, said, ``I think of myself as a
National League player. There was always an identity, and I think
that's what made the All-Star Game special. A lot of things have
changed. Mark McGwire and Ken Griffey Jr. are now National League
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be an identity, I really believe that. I believe
that fans should say, `This is a National League player' and `This
is an American League player.' And that way I think the All-Star
Game would stay where it deserves to be. We've definitely lost some
of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Zimmer, a veteran of 51 years in baseball, said, ``I think a
lot of things are different today. Years ago, you knew every player
and you knew 'em for seven straight years. Today, they bounce
around so much, you don't know one player from another. Players
change around so much today, it's hard to remember what league
you're in.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Winfield was honorary captain of the American League team.
That's Dave Winfield, who played in four All-Star Games for the
National League. Like so many other modern players, Winfield played
long stints in both leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Winfield said, ``They change so much today, you can't really say
that he's an American Leaguer or a National Leaguer. I'm a good
example. I had six teams, two leagues, two countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox fans could hardly be wowed by the sight of Atlanta
Braves first baseman Andres Galarraga, the NL starting first
baseman. Boston fans saw Galarraga homer at Fenway last Friday
night. They also saw Chipper Jones, Andruw Jones, and Tom Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really a proponent of interleague play,'' said
American League (Yankees) manager, Joe Torre. ``I think it takes a
little bit away from the All-Star Game. I guess we're going to have
to change with the times and understand. But I think it takes a
little bit away.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bud Selig, who would deny that today is Wednesday
if he thought the admission might hurt his sport, countered with,
``This is still the National League vs. the American League. I
don't think we should even consider changing the format. It's
wonderful and we're not going to change it.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, Bud. But how are kids supposed to identify with the alleged
rivalry? Griffey played for eight AL All-Star teams. This year,
Junior plays in the Senior Circuit. But he still plays games in
American League ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson _ the man who hit the monstrous homer off the
transformer in Detroit for the American League 29 years ago _
agrees with Selig.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an American Leaguer and that's important to me,'' said
Reggie. ``But our All-Star Game is still the best one. I know this
argument goes to the idea of interleague play. Well, I wish there
was interleague play when I played. I wish I could have played
against Morgan, Rose, Bench, and Perez. I never played in Atlanta.
I never played against Willie Mays or Clemente. I never got to face
Bob Gibson and I would have loved it and I don't see anything wrong
with it. As a fan, I want to see good players.''
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of good players on display at Turner Field.
But there was no league identity. Next year they should just wait
till game time and choose up sides. Or do what hockey does and have
American-born players against the rest of the world. American
League vs. National League means nothing anymore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by
e-mail at dshaughnessy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
