<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9923 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     07-12 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEGASYSTEMS WRESTLES WITH ACCOUNTING DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why do some battles spin out of control and take on costly lives
of their own?
</P>
<P>
   The dispute in question involves Pegasystems Inc., the
Cambridge, Mass. software company, and a large chunk of the public
accounting world. It began years ago over a mistake involving
comparatively small change and has since exacted a huge toll on
everyone involved.
</P>
<P>
   No one has suffered more than Alan Trefler, the brainy and
generally affable founder of Pegasystems who owns more than 70
percent of the company's stock. We've documented the rise of his
personal stock fortune, approaching $700 million at one point, and
numbing paper losses of about $500 million suffered in a period of
months. How's that for motivation?
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who happened to stop by the Pegasystems annual meeting in
Cambridge two weeks ago would have witnessed a shareholder
ratification of the accounting firm Deloitte &AMP; Touche as its new
independent auditor.
</P>
<P>
   Two months earlier, Arthur Andersen had informed Pegasystems
that it would decline to stand for reelection as the company's
outside accountant. In other words, Arthur Andersen was dumping its
client.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever friction exists between Pegasystems and Arthur Andersen
(there is no reference to any specific dispute in public documents
on the subject), it surely must pale in comparison to the company's
long-running animus toward yet another big accounting firm, Ernst &AMP;
Young.
</P>
<P>
   Though the event that first sparked their dispute occurred
nearly three years ago, Pegasystems has recently filed a new
lawsuit against Ernst &AMP; Young alleging malpractice, business
defamation, and breach of fiduciary duty, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of both Pegasystems and Ernst &AMP; Young declined
to talk about the case.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute involves ``revenue recognition,'' a bugaboo in the
software world a few years ago and certain bait for US Securities
and Exchange Commission officials on a campaign against dubious
accounting standards.
</P>
<P>
   Deciding when a software company can count revenue in its
financial statements isn't as easy as it sounds. Many companies
have had to restate their results after they had been published,
usually because software can involve licensing deals and other
complicated business arrangements that must be recorded gradually
over time.
</P>
<P>
   But most of those companies took their hit and moved on, even
the ones that were saddled with shareholder class-action suits.
</P>
<P>
   Pegasystems didn't just fall into the revenue recognition trap
once. A year after the first problem, it again had to restate some
of its financial results over similar issues.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Pegasystems continues to face two separate shareholder
class-action suits and has publicly acknowledged a formal SEC
investigation of its accounting for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   In routine company documents, Pegasystems has warned that it may
have to pay ``substantial damages or settlement costs'' to make the
civil suits go away. The company also concedes that past events and
the bad publicity that followed has hurt demand for its products
and services.
</P>
<P>
   And that brings us to the latest round of litigation, the
Pegasystems suit against Ernst &AMP; Young. Perhaps its just bad blood,
or part of a broader blame-game legal strategy, or even just
another example of the trendy pattern of companies suing their
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Pegasystems lays out in detail its version of who said and did
what when it came to the decision to record $5 million in revenue
from a licensing agreement with sometimes-competitor First Data
Resources.
</P>
<P>
   That's the really amazing part of the entire Pegasystems story:
Hundreds of millions of dollars in stock market value vaporized and
lawyers were set loose over how much of a $5 million deal could be
recognized at one time.
</P>
<P>
   It was a function of the high prices investors put on popular
tech stocks and how quickly they abandoned those momentum stocks at
the first hint of bad news.
</P>
<P>
   Pegasystems and Ernst &AMP; Young argued in public about who was
responsible for the company's first gaffe from the very start,
which is unusual, and the accounting firm quit the account.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Pegasystems had recovered most of its lost stock
value, but was struggling again with accounting issues. The
eventual second restatement was no disaster, but Pegasystems had
burned through whatever confidence remained in the company's stock
and it hit rock bottom in fall 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, Pegasystems' stock staged a comeback during the hot
technology stock market early this year, only to get hammered down
again in the spring. It's stayed down ever since _ closing Tuesday
at $5, off 12.5 cents _ and we can only wonder how much it hurts to
have all that baggage in tow.
</P>
<P>
   Good luck, Deloitte &AMP; Touche.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
