888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (Includes recipes)  
 FAMILY MEALS MADE SIMPLE _ THE ITALIAN WAY  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HINGHAM, Mass. _ You don't have to be Italian to take a dozen
beautiful ingredients _ two of which, invariably, are tomatoes and
olive oil _ and turn them into a fine, quick dinner.
</P>
<P>
   But it helps.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Tosi qualifies, being Italian on his father's side and
preferring Italian food to all other cuisines. And these days,
especially when it's his turn at the stove, Tosi is happy only with
instant meals. He has too many other interests, which include
playing with his daughter, Arianna, who is almost 4; spending time
with his wife, Bonnie Anderson, a model; working on the expansive
flower and vegetable gardens behind their 1822 house; and clamming
on Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen in the Tosi household is very large, the result of a
recent renovation in which the small pantries that used to abut the
19th-century kitchen were incorporated into the main area. It was
one part of a major overhaul that occurred while the family still
lived in Charlestown. They've been in this house almost a year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Arianna can drive her tricycle on the washed-out
terra-cotta flooring while her mother or father prepares dinner at
a 3 1/2-by-9-foot black-granite-topped island _ large by any
standard. On any given evening, the cooking island is bound to be
heaped with spaghetti and other Italian ingredients from the
Pastene Companies, which Arianna's father and uncle own.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Tosi and his brother Christopher run a family business that
began informally on a pushcart in Boston's North End in 1848. Until
a decade ago _ when Americans discovered the Mediterranean diet _
Pastene's customers mostly consisted of a strong ethnic following.
``People tell me their great-grandmothers used our tomatoes,'' Tosi
says. Now, with pasta and olive oil on supper tables far outside
the Italian community, the privately held Canton, Mass. company is
in a boom.
</P>
<P>
   Even with all the canned tomatoes he wants, the tomatoes Tosi
prefers above all others come from the garden behind his house. He
points out dozens of plants. ``I have 36,'' he says, ``red, yellow,
cherries, Big Boys, plums.'' Those and other vegetables are growing
in a bed that used to be covered in vines. The grounds of the
house, which he bought two years ago, hadn't been maintained for
many years, he says. The work is cut out for him.
</P>
<P>
   Still, time constraints are only part of the reason for the
family's quick meal strategy. As it happens, many Italian dishes
are uncomplicated by nature, says Tosi. ``Italian food is peasant
food, based on simple ingredients with wonderful flavors.'' When
Tosi is traveling in Italy (his company has an office in Naples)
and he eats something he likes, it goes into the repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   One is a dish based on lemon and pasta that Tosi ate at a winery
outside Florence in Chianti country. It does not contain tomatoes,
but rather onions sauteed in olive oil with garlic, and a generous
amount of grated lemon rind and juice. Those few ingredients are
tossed with spaghetti or another pasta and then, at the table,
sprinkled with Parmesan cheese. ``Some people add cream,'' says
Tosi. ``But we don't. It's light, and delicious with grilled veal
or pork chops and a salad.''
</P>
<P>
   Tosi also makes a highly seasoned sauce from canned and
sun-dried tomatoes seasoned with capers, crushed red peppers, and
flakes of tuna. When the sauce is finished, he drains pasta, often
spaghetti, and adds it to the sauce. ``I always put the pasta into
the sauce,'' he says. ``Otherwise the sauce will not stick.'' He
admits it looks nicer to tip the freshly cooked pasta onto a big
platter and spoon the sauce on top, ``but it'll never coat it
properly.''
</P>
<P>
   There is almost always pasta for dinner, some sort of salad, and
often something grilled. At home, Tosi uses a gas grill. In
Chatham, where Tosi's mother and stepfather live, everyone joins
the family's clammers _ Tosi among them _ for a cookout on the
beach on a little hibachi filled with charcoal.
</P>
<P>
   They dig for cherrystones and littlenecks. ``We stick the clams
right on the grill so they're cooking in their own juices,'' he
says. Once the clams open, he puts them on a plate and drizzles
them with a mixture of melted butter, olive oil, and garlic.
``People eat dozens.''
</P>
<P>
   Tosi doesn't apologize for the gas grill he uses at home, even
though some cooks consider gas inferior to charcoal. ``It's easy.
It's right outside the back door,'' he says. ``We grill four days a
week, all year, in the rain, shine, snow, and sleet.'' He calls his
Weber ``the standard every-house model.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing else about the house or kitchen is standard. The
cupboard doors are made from distressed pine, so the place doesn't
have a brand-new feeling. The same black granite that covers the
center island is on all the counters, and a very large sink _ ample
enough to hold several restaurant-size pots at once _ is also made
of granite. Like many wide sinks, his custom-made sink didn't drain
very well. But it was already installed when Tosi discovered that.
So the workmen had to plane it in place. ``Now it drains from every
corner,'' says Tosi, which seems to suggest he drove the workmen
crazy. ``I was on site every day,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   On either side of the window above the sink are pine racks that
hold beautiful, colorful ceramic plates from Ravello, a village in
the hills above Amalfi. Tosi has them packed in the shipping
containers that hold his imported foods.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike inexpensive Italian pottery, which chips if something
touches it, these plates are durable. ``We run them through the
dishwasher on a regular basis,'' he says. There are two
dishwashers. On the side of the island that faces the sink, there
are also two Sub-Zero refrigerator drawers (these in addition to a
Sub-Zero refrigerator-freezer). When Anderson and Tosi cook for
parties, which they do a lot, the top drawer holds food they're
cooking. The bottom drawer holds juices and snacks for Arianna, who
can open it and help herself.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson does most of the weekly meals. ``He courted me with his
cooking,'' she says, ``then something happened.'' They've been
married almost five years. Arianna was born when they lived in
Charlestown, in another old house that Tosi had lived in for 20
years. He had driven along the historic district in Hingham from
the time he was a boy growing up in Cohasset. ``I always wanted to
live here,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Debbie Rogers, comes from an English family who
settled in Boston in the 1600s. His late father, Jerome, was so far
removed from his immigrant heritage that he didn't understand
Italian. ``You didn't want to be known as Italian back then,'' his
son says.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Tosi went to Italy after high school and during college
spent summers there. He spent some time working in vineyards in
Tuscany. Before he was married, he spent every September in Amalfi.
``It's just spectacular. The whole coast is amazing.'' He returns
two or three times a year, though not with Anderson since Arianna
was born. After years of traveling without children, and sometimes
being disturbed by them on flights, he didn't want to fly with a
crying baby.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his company, he still goes to Italy. He considers the
Italian diet _ particularly in Amalfi _ healthier than his. ``They
sit down as a family for a one-hour lunch. Then there's an hour
nap. They work late, eat dinner from 8 to 10, then they do the
promenade. It's very relaxing. They don't seem to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Tosi's own diet isn't all that bad, but his portions are large.
He wrestles with his weight. When he reached ``my worst weight
ever,'' the man who imports pasta as his livelihood decided to go
on a low-carbohydrate diet. ``No pasta. No bread. No rice.'' It
nearly killed him. ``I hated that diet.'' He went off it, and half
the weight came back. But pasta is in his life again, which is the
important thing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
RED TUNA SAUCE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sun-dried tomatoes in oil, drained and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup capers
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon crushed red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   1 can (28 ounces) chopped or ground tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons chopped flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dried pasta (spaghetti or linguine or another shape)
</P>
<P>
   2 cans (6 ounces each) light tuna in olive oil, drained
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese (for serving)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet, heat the oil and cook the onion and garlic
for 8 minutes or until soft. Add the sun-dried tomatoes, capers,
crushed red pepper flakes, chicken stock, tomatoes, vinegar,
parsley, salt, and pepper. Bring to a boil, then lower the heat and
simmer the mixture for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, cook the pasta in plenty of boiling salted water for
6 to 8 minutes or until it is cooked but still has some bite. Drain
it.
</P>
<P>
   Stir the tuna and basil into the sauce. Add the pasta, toss well
and serve at once with Parmesan cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 3.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
CLAMS WITH GARLIC AND OIL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 pounds littleneck or cherrystone clams
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons ( 1/2 stick) butter
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rinse the clams until they are no longer sandy.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a charcoal or gas grill. When the grill is ready, use a
spoon to spread the clams on the rack. Cover with the lid and steam
the clams for 1 to 2 minutes or until they open.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a small saucepan, melt the butter with the oil and
garlic. Add black pepper. Cook the mixture just until it is warm.
</P>
<P>
   Use the spoon to transfer the clams to 4 large bowls. Sprinkle
them with the butter mixture. Serve at once with crusty bread.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
PASTA WITH LEMON SAUCE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dried pasta (spaghetti, linguine, or another long, thin
cut)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   Grated rind and juice of 3 lemons
</P>
<P>
   Freshly grated Parmesan cheese (for serving)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cook the pasta in plenty of boiling, salted water for 6 to 8
minutes or until it is cooked but still has some bite.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a large skillet, heat the oil and cook the onion
and garlic for 8 minutes or until they are soft but not brown. Add
the lemon rind and juice.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the pasta and, without shaking off the excess liquid, tip
it into the skillet. Add pepper and toss the pasta with the lemon
and oil mixture. Serve at once, sprinkled with Parmesan cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
