<SLUG> BC-WASHINGTON-MOTTO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D.C. PLANNING BUMPER PROTEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The announcement sounded pretty unremarkable at
first. After years with a bland motto, ``Celebrate &AMP; Discover,''
members of the D.C. City Council agreed last month to change the
slogan on local license plates to something a little catchier.
Something more historic.
</P>
<P>
   What they ended up with was downright revolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes as planned, new tags in the nation's capital will
soon be emblazoned with the phrase ``Taxation without
Representation,'' a marker of the city's unique political status.
The city's half-million residents, who are unable to elect voting
representatives to Congress despite paying more than $2 billion in
federal taxes a year, will at least be able to drive their
longstanding frustration past the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials insist the move is purely ``educational,'' a
lighthearted attempt to correct nationwide misconceptions about the
plight of those living in the District of Columbia. But according
to some, the license plate initiative, which was welcomed
enthusiastically by Mayor Anthony A. Williams and the entire City
Council, is also part of a slow reawakening of the movement for
democracy in D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's public relations,'' said City Council chairwoman Linda W.
Cropp, who introduced the idea at the suggestion of a local
resident. ``And public relations, and information, and education,
can often play a major role in change.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, change has been hard to come by in the nation's
capital, where activists have spent the last 200 years trying
everything, from lawsuits to constitutional amendments, to gain
fuller voting rights.
</P>
<P>
   They have had some successes, most notably the 1968 legal change
that granted D.C. residents the right to vote in presidential
elections. Six years later, the city was also permitted limited
control over some municipal functions.
</P>
<P>
   But a 1978 attempt at a constitutional amendment to allow
complete representation failed to get the necessary 38-state
approval, despite massive support in the District and approval by
both houses of Congress. In 1993, a bill to grant D.C. statehood
never made it that far. With just 153 supporters, it was voted down
in the US House.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, advocates have continued the struggle, often with
little public support or national notice. Most recently, in 1998, a
D.C. coalition filed a lawsuit arguing for full representation;
earlier this year, a federal appeasl court ruled against them, 2-1.
The advocates have since appealed to the Supreme Court, where the
case could be heard as early as this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The drawn-out court proceedings and lulls in legislative
maneuvers, however, have often caused the local furor over voting
rights to die down. ``There is no such thing as a movement that can
sustain itself for 200 years,'' said Eleanor Holmes Norton, the
Democrat who is the District's delegate in the US House but is not
allowed to vote on bills that come to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Which may be the reason the catchy license plate slogan shot
straight into local headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamed up by Sarah Shapiro, 49, who lives in the Northwest
section of Washington, the motto became an instant hit on local
radio talk shows and newspaper columns, capturing the imagination
of residents weary of decades of defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro, who is out of work on disability leave, had felt the
full effects of living without a fully enabled representative a few
years earlier when she sought the kind of assistance most members
of Congress provide: help with gaining Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro said she contacted Norton, her congresswoman, and
Norton's staff members ``did what they could do,'' which, in her
case, was not much. They could only tell Shapiro the status of her
case, which she already knew. But when Shapiro's mother, who lives
in Brooklyn, contacted her congressman, Democratic Representative
Anthony Weiner, about the same matter, she got a letter back signed
by the Social Security commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little different, isn't it?'' Shapiro said. ``What a
different reaction a voting congressman gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Norton, she added: ``It's not only unjust and
revolting and degrading and humiliating that she doesn't vote. It's
also very different for those she represents.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro didn't just get mad. She sent an e-mail to a local radio
show on politics. The broadcaster, Mark Plotkin, in turn, took her
``Taxation without Representation'' idea public.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Norton says, if the city doesn't adopt the
Revolutionary-era slogan, ``people are going to put it on their own
cars.''
</P>
<P>
   That may not be necessary. In late June, after receiving wide
public support, the D.C. City Council passed a ``sense of the
council'' resolution, which, unlike regular council votes, does not
require approval in Congress. Instead, it gives the nod to the
mayor to sign an executive order putting the new slogan onto the
city's license plates.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress have given no indication they will take the
awkward step of overruling that order once Williams signs it,
although Congress has the right to control virtually everything the
District of Columbia does. Representative Thomas M. Davis III, the
Virginia Republican who heads the House Government Reform
subcommittee on the District, has expressed support for the
slogan's content, although a spokesman said Davis was less certain
about the tactic.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of opposition from Republicans, who have historically
opposed giving the overwhelmingly Democratic city any congressional
voice,is encouraging to many D.C. residents and is helping add fuel
to the D.C. rights movement overall. According to one recent poll,
55 percent of Americans are unaware of the voting rights status of
the nation's capital. Nearly three-quarters said they believed D.C.
residents deserved to vote the same as everyone else, according to
Joseph Sternlieb, president of D.C. Vote, an advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our task is outside of Washington,'' Sternlieb said. ``We have
to convince the patriots around the country to expand our
democracy, to include the citizens who live in D.C.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
