<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK TO THE SPIRIT OF '76 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The previews featured Martian mischief, menacing mutants, and
creepy cyberthugs. The main feature focused on people. Its special
effects were sacrifice, determination, and courage.
</P>
<P>
   It stumbles and falls, but ``The Patriot'' has legs. Its
artistic and financial success demonstrates that while Hollywood is
no hotbed of patriotism, it is always desperate for good stories.
Rocky and Bullwinkle? Gone in 60 seconds. If a recent,
self-absorbed past bombs at the box office, moguls will happily
rediscover the rocket's red glare.
</P>
<P>
   The American Revolution has inspired only 10 movies, according
to the Internet Movie Base, compared to 401 for World War II, 197
for the Civil War, and 72 for Vietnam. ``The Patriot'' is already
historic for reversing this trend.
</P>
<P>
   More inspiration will arrive next year with David McCullough's
biography of John Adams. The nation's second president,
overshadowed by other patriots, is a chattily expressive, emotional
gold mine of character development. Jack Nicholson should fight to
portray him. Thomas Jefferson, alas, is elusive. Ken Howard was a
more persuasive TJ in ``1776'' than Nick Nolte was as ``Jefferson
in Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   In the title role of ``The Patriot,'' Mel Gibson plays Benjamin
Martin, a peace-loving farmer who suddenly becomes as impetuous as
Jimy Williams hooking a Red Sox pitcher. Gibsonesque road-warrior
mayhem ensues, but a human story, not war or politics, animates the
narrative. A teen-age heartthrob, Heath Ledger, also helps sell
tickets. ``Gone With the Wind,'' after all, was not about Robert E.
Lee and Stonewall Jackson, but Scarlett O'Hara and Rhett Butler.
</P>
<P>
   After any drama based on history, nits and their pickers
multiply. British punditry has its knickers in a twist because of
the movie's view of redcoat behavior. While the British army's
conduct has often been atrocious, the script did invent
over-the-top, cinematically unnecessary atrocities. As the Duke of
Wellington said before Waterloo, war is heck.
</P>
<P>
   A suitable consolation prize would be a supporting-actor Oscar
for Tom Wilkinson, whose portrayal of Lord Cornwallis rivals that
of Laurence Olivier's depiction of Gentleman Johnny Burgoyne in
``The Devil's Disciple'' in 1959. That movie, based on a Shaw play,
starred Kirk Douglas and Burt Lancaster, the Mel Gibsons of their
time.
</P>
<P>
   The character in dispute, based on a Liverpool lout nicknamed
``Bloody Tarleton,'' was played by Jason Isaacs, who can be the
Basil Rathbone of the 21st century. And a villain he was, ordering
the bayoneting of wounded colonial soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Brits are understandably distressed at any departure from
slobbering Anglophilia, which first infected Hollywood when Warner
Brothers, RKO, and MGM discovered that Shakespeare, Dickens, and
those guys had no agents and didn't require royalty payments.
</P>
<P>
   When film rediscovers the American Revolution, ``Oliver
Wiswell'' by Kenneth Roberts, is a miniseries waiting for the
cameras. Also adaptable is ``The Braintree Mission'' by Nicholas E.
Wyckoff, published in 1957, about a British attempt to bribe John
Adams with an earldom. Both novels have scenes on the
still-preserved field in Milton, Mass. of Thomas Hutchinson, the
royal governor.
</P>
<P>
   Americans may be ready for real characters with real
motivations. The leaders of the 1770s can lay claim to tales of
bravery as compelling as those of ``the greatest generation'' of
the 1940s. Jacques Barzun has observed that when American educators
consigned history to the scrap heap of ``social studies,'' they
encouraged ignorance. But the tide is turning.
</P>
<P>
   The history-is-bunk attitude of early baby boomers is losing its
grip in faculty lounges and at the box office. Does Oliver Stone
have an audience anymore?
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood needs scripts and can find many in the Declaration in
which Jefferson and others offered to themselves and to the world
``our lives, our fortunes, and our sacred honor.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
