<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9938 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-JAFFE-ART-BOS &LR;      07-12 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-JAFFE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 ISN'T SHE ROMANTIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Two years ago, when Michele Jaffe earned her
doctorate in comparative literature of the Renaissance from Harvard
University, she faced two career options.
</P>
<P>
   She could teach Renaissance literature to college students,
helping them analyze the poetic structure of Petrarch's ``Scattered
Rhymes'' and the metaphoric underpinnings of Dante's ``Divine
Comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Or she could write historical romance novels.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffe went the route of the bodice-ripper, and today she's as
ecstatic as her lovestruck heroine, Sophie Champion. Her second
book, ``The Water Nymph'' (Pocket Books) _ a sensual story of
seduction set in Renaissance England _ was published this month,
and Jaffe is ``over the moon'' with the enthusiastic response.
Letters have been pouring in from readers, with comments like
``Your book is a wonderful story I could not put down.'' Publishers
Weekly calls it a ``rollicking adventure'' and ``great read'' and
marks Jaffe as ``a writer to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more important, considering her readership, ``The Water
Nymph'' got a rave rating of four and a half stars out of five in
last month's Romantic Times, a fanzine for devotees of romance
books. And she is already engrossed in ``The Firefly,'' her next
installment in an anticipated seven-book series, all featuring the
Arboretti cousins, a half-English, half-Italian family of merchant
princes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Water Nymph'' takes place in England in 1588, on the eve
of the battle of the Spanish Armada. The protagonists are Sophie
Champion, an intoxicating, if phobic, beauty with a pressing
mystery to solve, and the smooth and charming Crispin Foscari, earl
of Sandal, one of Queen Elizabeth's secret and most trusted
operatives. They are enemies, yet passionate lovers. The book takes
more twists and turns than a labyrinth in the English countryside.
</P>
<P>
   But for all its historical intricacies _ informed by Jaffe's 8
1/2 years as an undergraduate and graduate student at Harvard _ the
book is a romance novel through and through. That is, it satisfies
the definition laid out, in writing, by the 8,200-member Romance
Writers of America. To wit: The main plot ``concerns two people
falling in love and struggling to make the relationship work'' and
it has ``an emotionally satisfying and optimistic ending . . .
which ``makes the reader feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   And proudly so. Jaffe has little patience for the ``snob
element'' out there _ readers who snub her genre as ``tawdry'' or,
even worse, who suspect she writes these books as a kind of joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say to me, `Of course, you are writing ironically,
aren't you?' '' says Jaffe. ``But I don't. I think of these as
adventure stories for women, with a love element. It's just that
cynicism is a much more acceptable posture, especially in the
pseudo-elite world of Cambridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaffe, originally from Los Angeles, knows this world intimately.
At Harvard, she studied the history and literature of the
Renaissance and Reformation in Italy, England, and France; her
senior thesis was on 16th-century courtesans in Venice _
``fascinating women,'' she says, ``who make their money in the
company of men.''
</P>
<P>
   Her addiction to romance novels started accidentally. Six years
ago, when Jaffe was 24, her mother died of breast cancer. She was
in graduate school at the time, and a roommate recommended a few of
her favorite romance novels to help Jaffe lift her spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``They helped me through a very difficult time,'' says Jaffe.
For weeks, she devoured a book a day, discovering that the novels
were ``the best and easiest way for me to access my emotions. The
key thing for me was knowing the books would end happily. They were
a safe place to feel sad, because at the end, I could have this
redemptive moment. I was sobbing a great deal, although there was
this confusion of whether I was sobbing for the characters or
myself or my mother. You can sort of go through all stages of
grieving in the life of a romance novel _ anger and guilt and grief
and frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaffe is a quick-witted woman who defies any stereotype of the
modern romance writer in America. ``I don't think there are many
people like her out there,'' Susan Ginsburg, her literary agent,
puts it.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, she's an Ivy League alum who has an
intellectual romance with language. She passionately despairs of
what she sees as ``the end of punctuation'' in contemporary
English, for example, and is accumulating theories for an article
she plans to write about the Internet's effect on speech patterns.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, she pens a mean historical romance. Her long
curly red hair _ no, make that her dangling ruby tresses _ and the
4-inch fuzzy pink stiletto mules she fancies are evocative of the
world of her characters. If she wrote her books in a turret, you
wouldn't be surprised. In fact, the color scheme of her home office
in her Cambridge apartment is a startling, sensuous pink _ walls,
telephone, velvet couch, and even computer printer.
</P>
<P>
   She maintains that she still doesn't completely understand why
she fell in love with the lush and lurid Renaissance period, having
grown up in a ``minimalist home, which my parents decorated all
Scandinavian and teak. Maybe there was something about the
voluptuousness of it. Or maybe it's because I have curly hair. I
don't know if it was something latent, or if in another life I was
a Renaissance courtesan.''
</P>
<P>
   But the summer after her sophomore year, she took a trip to
Venice, which clearly seems to have ``sealed my fate. That was it.
I knew I was home. I spent the rest of my academic career getting
back there; I visited Venice every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Her first book, a 1999 novel called ``The Stargazer,'' is a
murder mystery set in Renaissance Venice. She wrote it in 1996, the
year she and her husband, a consultant in the field of physical
oceanography, lived in Venice ``while I was supposed to be doing
research for my dissertation.''
</P>
<P>
   In both books, her characters tend to struggle with their sexual
impulses, and they generally lose the battle. Her books are ``not
pornographic, but they are sexy,'' says Ginsburg of Writers House,
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffe adds that her mother-in-law called her after reading ``The
Stargazer,'' saying she had blushed and could ``never look you in
the face again.''
</P>
<P>
   She laughs. ``I didn't think it was very steamy. But it turned
out I was a poor judge of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
