<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9945 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ARAFAT-WINNIE-POOH-RE     07-12 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARAFAT-WINNIE-POOH-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORRUPT HISTORY DOGS NEW PALESTINE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for this week's Camp David summit...RESENDING from 7-11)   (This timely 800-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By PHIL REEVES  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Like Winnie the Pooh, Yasser Arafat loves honey.
Some of his colleagues believe his daily intake of the stuff,
bought at some expense in Yemen and poured into his tea, is the
reason that he is still in action, travelling from country to
country, tirelessly pressing his cause.
</P>
<P>
   He also sleeps well _ five hours at night, three in the
afternoon _ and eats heartily. Though watery of eye, and troubled
by an oscillating lower lip brought on by Parkinson's disease, the
Palestinian leader is still in fairly good fettle, given his
advanced years, his exhausting and dangerous career and his heavy
workload.
</P>
<P>
   Which is just as well. Because the same cannot be said of the
Palestinian state that may, or may not, now be approaching birth _
depending on the outcome of the tripartite summit in Camp David,
Md., which began on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   If Israel and the Palestinians reach an agreement and Arafat,
69, declares his state _ perhaps on Sept. 13, perhaps later _ it
will be shackled from the start.
</P>
<P>
   When the Soviet Union collapsed, it produced a litter of new
``democracies'' most of which were commandeered by Soviet-era
leaders even before the cheering had died out in the West.
</P>
<P>
   These hard men _ Alexander Lukashenko of Belarus, Haidar Aliyev
of Azerbaijan, and others _ quietly restored their nations to their
true colors as corrupt dictatorships. Palestine is also in danger
of making a poor start.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not so much the human-rights abuses that have
characterized Arafat's rule (though it seems unlikely, he can
always ease up, arguing that tough measures were necessary in the
transition to independence).
</P>
<P>
   The real issue is mismanagement and corruption. This is a
product of Arafat's practice of concentrating power on himself,
shored up by a plethora of security services and supporters who
have been rewarded for their loyalty _ and particularly for keeping
Islamic militancy at bay _ with stakes in big business monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   You need only to drive around the Gaza Strip to see the results.
On a headland overlooking the long, straight beach _ where
penniless Gazan fishermen stand in the surf _ stands the palatial
home of one of the biggest fish in the security services.
</P>
<P>
   Not far away, there are more small palaces, wreathed with
balconies, belonging to top officials. Fed with perks and
sweetheart deals, these men will do all they can to protect their
interests when Arafat eventually goes.
</P>
<P>
   As there is a good chance that no one among those tipped to
succeed him will command enough support to win a fair election,
there is a real risk that the security forces will decide the
outcome _ in favor of their chosen candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Questions such as these are preying on the minds of the
Palestinian intelligentsia almost as much as those that will be
under discussion in the United States this week when Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak, Arafat and U.S. President Bill Clinton gather
at the presidential retreat and attempt to recreate the history
made by Menachem Begin and Anwar Sadat just over two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   The issues are momentous: how much of the West Bank will Israel
return (90 percent is the most commonly quoted figure) and how much
will it keep for the 180,000 Jewish settlers who have illegally
seized Arab land in the name of religion and Zionism?
</P>
<P>
   And what about Gaza, where Israel still holds 40 percent of the
land? How much water will Palestine control? Will it get any of
East Jerusalem _ and if not can there be a deal? Will refugees have
the right to return, and will they get compensation?
</P>
<P>
   And _ when all is said and done _ will the new, independent
Palestine ultimately be anything more than a hodgepodge of land,
without a real army, linked frailly together by bridges or tunnels,
whose population cannot live without the menial jobs on offer from
the mighty consumer society next door?
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians are entering the talks in a pessimistic mood.
They will be seeking a symbolic recognition from Israel that their
new state is based on the terms of U.N. Resolution 242 (which
restores the borders prior to June 1967), even though they will get
less.
</P>
<P>
   They also want an acknowledgement from Israel _ again, in
effect, symbolic _ of the right of return of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The risk is that these matters will obscure discussion about the
quality of the new Palestinian society.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people fought for so long just to be another
stereotype Arab country,'' said Raji Sourani, director of the
Palestinian Center for Human Rights in Gaza. ``We want to be a good
example to the rest of the world and we deserve it.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
