<HEADER>
A9950 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-JUMP-ROPE-HNS &LR;      07-12 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUMP-ROPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GIRLS' JUMP ROPE DREAM TAKES ON ADULT DIMENSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KRIS WORRELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ When Tahira Reid was in the third grade at Public
School 97 in the Bronx, she entered a contest at school in which
students had to make a poster of something they wished they had.
Reid drew a picture of two poles with ropes (made from glued yarn)
and a girl jumping in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called it an automatic double-Dutch jump rope turner, which
was kind of a long name,'' Reid said of her childhood design. ``I
was frustrated. I used to like playing double Dutch but I could
only play when I got to school because that's when a lot of girls
were there to turn the ropes.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 23, Reid has finally seen her girlhood dream materialize. As
a sophomore at Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, three years ago
she and some classmates created the Double Dutch Jump Rope Machine,
a device that uses two motors about 12 feet apart to turn two ropes
in opposite directions.
</P>
<P>
   The prototype consists of motors and gears atop two carts from
the student machine shop, balanced with plywood and cinder blocks.
It does not always work perfectly. Sometimes one of the motors runs
slower than the other, tripping up Reid as she tries to
demonstrate.
</P>
<P>
   But when it works properly, the ropes clack against the floor in
that familiar rhythm and Reid jumps and spins and counts, 1, 2, 3,
4, and she looks as if she's back on some Bronx block, playing with
the other girls.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Reid sees the double-Dutch machine as something people
should use together, as well as solo.
</P>
<P>
   ``People could jump and not worry about having to turn or
getting tired,'' she said, noting that not everyone is as precise a
turner as the machine will be. And let's face it, everybody wants
to jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like another treadmill. No one has this,'' said RPI
Professor Burt L. Swersey, who taught the class in introduction to
engineering design, where Reid devised her machine. ``This is like
the Wright brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid, who with co-inventor Andrew Burdick was assigned a patent
for the machine, received a $10,000 grant from the National
Collegiate Inventors and Innovators Alliance. Out of those funds
she developed two more prototypes and paid for patent lawyer fees.
Reid, who graduated from RPI in May with a bachelor's degree in
mechanical engineering, is now looking for more sources of funding
so she can continue working on the prototype and eventually start
her own business.
</P>
<P>
   When she was a kid, she learned to double Dutch from her aunt,
who is only six years older than Reid.
</P>
<P>
   Even after she won first prize for her poster depicting the
``automatic double-Dutch jump rope turner,'' it was some time
before she pursued the invention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't mechanically inclined,'' said Reid, who graduated as
high school valedictorian. ``I wasn't a tinkering type of child
that took things apart.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Swersey told her class to come up with something
that ``challenged the limits of sports and recreational
activities'' that Reid recalled her third-grade idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideas come to fruition if you're in an environment that's
conducive to creativity,'' said Reid, who is by turns serious,
modest and enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tahira is one of my heroes,'' said Swersey. ``She's so
serious, so determined, so personable. And she's very creative.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid believes that there is a strong market out there for a
machine like hers, which she envisions selling to corporate
sponsors who will then donate the machines to community groups such
as YWCAs and Boys and Girls Clubs of America. Other potential users
are professional jumping teams and even fitness enthusiasts who
want something different.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the next Microsoft we're talking about here. But it
is an interesting approach to a niche market,'' said Phil
Weilerstein, director of the National Collegiate Inventors and
Innovators Alliance. ``Maybe this will be the new Hula-Hoop and
there'll be one on every street corner.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to Bud Pickett, executive director of the United
States Amateur Jump Rope Federation, there are lots of eager fans
out there who would jump at the chance to practice jumping.
Thousands of jumpers participate in competitions each year, he
said, and more than 600 competed in the national contest, held
earlier this month at Disney World. Competitions are aired several
times a year on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think it'll be successful,'' Swersey said. ``The
machine's actually going to be better than turning by hand. This is
a way of being precise and giving a whole new level to the sport.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
