<HEADER>
A9965 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-`TRAITOR'-TOMB-RAZED-     07-12 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`TRAITOR'-TOMB-RAZED-INDEPENDENT-FISK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLING THE DEAD: HEZBOLLAH BLOWS UP COLLABORATORS' MEMORIAL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 600-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London. Correspondent Robert Fisk was recently named
``Amnesty International Print Journalist of the Year.'')  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   MARJAYOUN, SOUTHERN LEBANON _ Was this what victory was for? Was
this why the Hezbollah lost their hundreds of ``martyrs'' in their
18-year conflict with Israel and its Lebanese militia allies? To
blow up a war memorial?
</P>
<P>
   True, it wasn't much of a garden of remembrance; a domed,
half-eggshell building decorated with a cross and a half-moon and
the names of almost 300 ``South Lebanon Army'' militiamen engraved
on brass plates that had been screwed into a set of concrete walls.
</P>
<P>
   It stood on the top of a hill within sight of Israel, the
foreign land whom the SLA men had been paid to defend. And over the
entrance were written the words: ``Eternity to Our Heroic
Martyrs.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they were collaborators, Lebanese working for their
country's enemy. Some of them were brutal, cruel men who had been
present at _ perhaps even participated in _ dreadful deeds of
torture within the walls of Khiam prison, now a museum of human
darkness on the hill opposite.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the dead were blackmailed by the Israelis into
joining the militia, boy-soldiers whose brothers or fathers would
have been imprisoned if they had not served Israel's cause in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   And I suspected, when I first saw the memorial garden six weeks
ago, that it would fall victim to liberation, that it would be _ I
quote my report that day in the Independent _ ``the first place to
be destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, I discovered just how total a victim it had become:
blasted by explosives, pulverized into dust, even the trees cut
down by the power of the bombs planted around it.
</P>
<P>
   Before the destruction, every brass name had been torn from the
concrete, every reference to the town from which the dead had come;
even the roses from the garden had been stolen. Then explosives had
been primed at the center of each memorial wall and within the
cupola with its legend about eternity.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose I should not have been surprised. When I last came
here, I found a Shiite man cutting away at a brass plaque with a
knife, gouging from the wall the name of Ali Ibrahim Hashem, one of
the most senior SLA officers, a father of three children blown up
by a Hezbollah mine on Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am taking this one because it is still fresh,'' the Shiite
had told me with a laugh. Killing the dead, I called it.
</P>
<P>
   So what was I to make of all this rubble and burned trees and
blasted walls? Yes, it was an occupier's memorial. They were
collaborators. Some of them _ not all, but some _ were wicked men.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Hezbollah could have called it a ``traitor's''
memorial but left it intact. Because the dead were Lebanese. Of
both Muslim and Christian faith.
</P>
<P>
   A few local Christians were timidly videotaping the evidence
while I was there, capturing on film this surreal attempt to erase
history. What was it supposed to achieve, I wondered? And what
comes next?
</P>
<P>
   Are the SLA's enemies now going to dig up the dead? Already, the
Hezbollah are erecting their ``memorials,'' banners at the site of
each guerrilla ambush, listing the name of each anti-Israeli
suicide bomber and the date of his death.
</P>
<P>
   In days to come, it's possible their enemies will destroy those
banners too. And one comes back to the old Lebanese question: if
you do what the bad guys do, what is the difference between you and
them? &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 600-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
