even the roses from the garden had been stolen. Then explosives had
been primed at the center of each memorial wall and within the
cupola with its legend about eternity.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose I should not have been surprised. When I last came
here, I found a Shiite man cutting away at a brass plaque with a
knife, gouging from the wall the name of Ali Ibrahim Hashem, one of
the most senior SLA officers, a father of three children blown up
by a Hezbollah mine on Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am taking this one because it is still fresh,'' the Shiite
had told me with a laugh. Killing the dead, I called it.
</P>
<P>
   So what was I to make of all this rubble and burned trees and
blasted walls? Yes, it was an occupier's memorial. They were
collaborators. Some of them _ not all, but some _ were wicked men.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Hezbollah could have called it a ``traitor's''
