<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, July 13:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RACE SERIES &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   This story was filed Tuesday night, in full and abridged
versions:
</P>
<P>
   RACE-HOUSTON (Houston) _ In Houston, the fourth-largest city in
the U.S., blacks, Anglos and Hispanics each make up roughly a third
of the population. So the election in 1998 of Lee P. Brown as the
city's first black mayor was more than a celebration of victory for
blacks. It was also a testament to how racial and ethnic groups in
Houston had put aside their suspicions and rivalries and come
together largely out of self-interest to achieve power. By Mireya
Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteenth and last in the series, ``How Race Is Lived in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ Ledeall on the talks and related
developments: Israel, under pressure from U.S., cancels sale of
radar plane to China. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Israel's Supreme Court on
Wednesday jailed former Shas leader Aryeh Deri for three years on
corruption charges, sending into political exile an ultra-Orthodox
rabbi who was long a maker and breaker of Israeli governments. By
Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-RAID (Moscow) _ Crackdown on oligarchs continues as tax
police raid office of auto magnate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ANTHRAX-VACCINE (Washington) _ The Senate Armed Services
Committee questions senior Pentagon officials about safety and the
supply of anthrax vaccine for American military personnel. By
Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-U.S.-ABORTION (Washington) _ In order to get congressional
Republicans to pay the U.S. debt to the United Nations last year,
the Clinton Administration agreed to restrictions on international
family planning organizations that receive American funds. Now
pro-abortion rights groups are seeking to end those restrictions
and are wondering if the White House will stand with them in the
end. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NH-IMPEACH (Concord, N.H.) _ The New Hampshire House will debate
three atricles of impeachment against Chief Justice David Brock,
who is accused of lying under oath, calling a lower-court judge
about a case involving a state senator and soliciting comments from
a fellow justice about that judge's divorce case. By Carey
Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   MISS-HANGING (Undated) _ Janet Reno and Rep. John Conyers are to
meet with the family of a black Mississippi teenager found hanged
from a pecan tree a few yards from his home last month. The family
insists he was lynched, though local officials say autopsy findings
show the death was a suicide. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-NAACP (Baltimore) _ Vice President Al Gore speaks at the
NAACP convention. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DEATH-PENALTY (Houston) _ Folo on reports that new DNA
tests have failed to clear Ricky McGinn, a death-row inmate given a
reprieve last month by Texas Gov. George W. Bush. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes from the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-SPERMICIDE (Durban, South Africa) _ The United Nations
is warning women at high risk of infection with the AIDS virus not
to use a widely sold spermicide that is being tested for its
ability to kill the virus in the vagina. The warning came after
scientists reported at the 13th international conference on AIDS
that the spermicide, nonoxynol-9, failed in the largest trial of
its effectiveness as a vaginal microbicide. The findings dealt a
sharp blow to those who expected it would work and thus be the
first vaginal microbicide against HIV. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MISSILE-DEFENSE (Undated) _ Following the recent test
failure, a look at what's next for the antimissile testing program.
By James Glanz. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AIRBUS-JUMBO-JETS (Toulouse, France) _ Airbus Industrie is
getting closer to production of a gigantic double-decker jumbo jet,
known as the A3XX, for use on long distance routes like those
between Asia and Europe or the United States. With a minimum
capacity of 555 passengers, it would carry at least 140 passengers
more than the largest Boeing 747. And its development cost would
exceed $10 billion. It is a huge gamble for Airbus, which is
recasting its corporate structure to prepare for the project. There
are a number of obstacles, and it is not clear whether Airbus can
get enough orders to make the project ultimately profitable. But
the potential rewards are huge. For one, the A3XX would challenge
the long, lucrative dominance of Boeing's 747. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   UBS-PAINEWEBBER (Undated) _ Looking at the challenges that await
UBS as it announces its $12 billion acquisition of PaineWebber, the
fourth-largest brokerage firm in the United States. European banks
have had success on Wall Street, but none have tackled the retail
brokerage business. By Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   UBS-IMPACT (Frankfurt, Germany) _ UBS, the world's biggest bank
in terms of assets under management, follows other big European
banks in making a Wall Street deal. Looking at what the deal means
to UBS, which still has some difficulties stemming from its 1997
merger with Swiss Bank, and whether it presages a big push into
retail brokerage services in Europe. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   RITE-AID (Undated) _ Looking at the continued troubles of Rite
Aid. On Wednesday, the company agreed to sell its drug
benefit-management unit to Advance Paradigm for $875 million,
nearly half of what it paid in January 1999. Late Tuesday, Rite Aid
said it had overstated its profits by more than $1 billion for two
years and had a loss of $1 billion for its latest fiscal year. By
Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   ESTATE-TAXES (Undated) _ Small-business owners and farmers who
say they favor a Republican-backed plan to repeal the estate tax
seem largely unaware that President Clinton _ who has vowed to veto
the Republican proposal _ has said he would sign legislation that
would exempt nearly all of them from estate taxes. The Democratic
plan that the President favors would keep the levy only for the
fewer than one in 1,000 people whose wealth exceeds $8 million. But
some of these entrepreneurs say they distrust proposals to lift the
estate tax threshold, fearing that any revision would be encumbered
with rules that deny the benefits to them. A look at how some
practical business people from upstate New York to Oklahoma view
what all of them call the death tax. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIAONE-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily feature: Looking at
the choices being offered MediaOne shareholders. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   MOTOROLA-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Motorola reports second-quarter
earnings after the stock market closes. The forecast is for 23
cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-CITIZENS (Undated) _ Global Crossing has agreed to sell
its local-phone operations to Citizens Communications for $3.65
billion in cash. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   HUTCHISON-ALLIANCE (Tokyo) _ Hutchison Whampoa of Hong Kong
forms a strategic alliance with NTT DoCoMo of Japan and Royal KPN
of the Netherlands to bid jointly for next-generation wireless
licenses in Germany, France and Belgium and to operate a wireless
network in Britain. As part of the alliance KPN and NTT DoCoMo will
buy 35 percent of the Hutchison Whampoa Ltd. subsidiary that holds
a license for wireless services in Britain for $3.2 billion. By
Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The Economic Scene column. By Virginia
Postrel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Bob Herbert's ``In America.''
</P>
<P>
   William Safire is on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET _ A rundown of culture, lifestyle, sports, and
special section stories will move by 3:00 p.m. ET.
</P>
