<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9982 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-TEXAS-BASTILLE-HNS &LR;      07-12 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BASTILLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     VIVE LA FRANCE, VIVE LA FETE! 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BONNIE WALKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ While watching fireworks last week, it came to me.
Why stop the festivities on the Fourth of July, for an entire year,
when another holiday that's rich with party possibilities follows
right on its heels?
</P>
<P>
   You guessed it _ that would be Bastille Day, the French national
holiday that commemorates the revolution. In France, food, music
and fireworks are a very big part of the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Because the French have great food and because most of us like a
party, a Bastille Day celebation makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   Let's examine the basic elements of what might make up a South
Texas Bastille Day celebration, for example.
</P>
<P>
   First, a quick history lesson tells us that July 14, 1789, was
the day the people of Paris rose up en masse to storm the Bastille,
a state prison that symbolized the French monarchy. Two days later,
the French Revolution had succeeded, marking the beginning of the
First Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The battle cry on July 14, ``Tous a la Bastille!'' (Everyone to
the Bastille!) was echoed the next year when delegates from all
parts of the country flocked to Paris to celebrate the ``Fete de la
Federation'' and proclaim their allegiance to the new republic.
</P>
<P>
   To mark our own celebration of ``liberty, equality and
fraternity,'' we don't have to pretend to be French. But, we might
consider uncorking a bottle of Texas Barbecue Red, making up a
batch of Frito pie (we'll explain how this fits in a minute),
throwing some croissants on the grill and turning on some Tejano
CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Second, since we are a multicultural kind of town, we should
note that a very diverse group of people celebrates Bastille Day,
which offers plenty of possibilities for customizing our own
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   To plan your party, you might take a few tips from Santa
Barbara, Calif., which has the western United States' largest
Bastille Day celebration, the French Festival.
</P>
<P>
   They've been celebrating French independence for the past 13
years, but not because the French population there instigated it,
says festival organizer Steve Hoegerman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French are pretty independent folks _ not really joiners.
So, when it came to organizing the French Festival it took me,
Steve the gringo, to do it,'' says Hoegerman, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day festival draws about 20,000 people who dine on
French bread and cheese, fruit, escargot, crepes, quiche and other
French foods. There is music, from Cajun to cabaret, a poodle
parade, a mock Eiffel tower, dancing, arts and crafts and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal was to capture the mythic France, and for that you
need two things wafting through the air _ accordion music and
good-smelling foods. So you have all the elements that create the
France of your dreams,'' Hoegerman says.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio chef Damien Watel, who grew up in Lille, a city in
northern France, remembers the Bastille Day celebrations of his
childhood. These, he says, were almost always spent at his mother's
island vacation home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wild island, about five miles long, and there would
be a huge celebration. The whole island would gather at the port,''
says Watel, who will be celebrating Bastille Day in his own style
by hosting a Chef's Summit on July 17 at his restaurant, Bistro
Vatel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fireworks were a giant part of the 14th,'' says Watel, as is a
diversity of regional foods. One of Watel's food memories is the
hearty Carbonnades de Boeuf or a beef stew resembling the classic
Beef Burgundy. ``They would pour it over pommes frites (french
fries) and stir it around. Actually, it was kind of like a Frito
pie,'' admits Watel.
</P>
<P>
   So the food part of the Bastille on the Rio doesn't have to be
hard. Pick up some cheese and fresh breads. Tart, with raspberries,
blueberries and white chocolate mousse, honoring the colors of the
French flag.
</P>
<P>
   Then, throw together some spinach crepes, roast a chicken with
fresh herbs, or make a pot of chili and create Frito pies.
</P>
<P>
   Put Tchaikovsky's ``1812 Overture'' on the stereo and enjoy the
patriotic strains of the French national anthem, the Marseillaise,
which occurs about halfway through.
</P>
<P>
   Then, spread a red-and-white-checked tablecloth on the back lawn
or your patio or the living room floor, pour the wine and _ ``Tous
a la Bastille!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
