<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9989 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DECKS13-COX     07-12 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DECKS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pressure-treated lumber isn't only option for decks
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - When we think of decks, we automatically think of
the most common type of deck seen in this area: pressure-treated
lumber.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're interested in building a deck, it makes sense to
at least be aware that there are alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure-treated lumber is popular for decks, mostly because
it's relatively inexpensive. But the typical wooden deck has to be
refinished regularly, and the expense and hassles of maintenance
make a few homeowners opt for other materials.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Cook of T.E. Cook Deck Builders said the vast majority of
the decks he has built have been pressure-treated lumber, but he
expects that to change eventually.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year I get more requests for plastic decks because
people are tired of maintaining their wooden decks,'' Cook said.
``But when I quote a price for a plastic deck that's three times
more than a wooden deck, they go with wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually the price of plastic decks is going to drop, and
that's going to be what people want.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few basics to consider when you're contemplating
building a deck:
</P>
<P>
   Pressure-treated lumber is wood, typically pine, that has had
chemical preservatives forced deep into the cellular structure of
the wood. According to the American Wood Preservers Institute, the
process enables the preserved wood to maintain a chemical barrier
against termites and decay for 40 years or longer.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure-treated wood, especially wood that is not properly
sealed, can absorb water, causing it to twist, warp or cup. As the
wood loses its moisture, it can split.
</P>
<P>
   Wood meant for residential uses such as decks usually is treated
with water-based preservatives such as Chromated Copper Arsenate
(CCA), Ammoniacal Copper Quat (ACQ) and Ammoniacal Copper Zinc
Arsenate (ACZA), the institute said.
</P>
<P>
   The institute said the preservatives are not harmful in normal
usage, but treated lumber should not be used in applications that
come into direct contact with food, such as cutting boards. Also
normal precautions, such as wearing eye protection and a dust mask,
should be taken when cutting treated lumber.
</P>
<P>
   Treated lumber grays naturally as it weathers, and it should be
sealed to prevent deterioration. Depending on several variables _
how much sun and rain, what type of sealant is used _ you should
expect to reseal the deck every two to five years.
</P>
<P>
   Check out www.awpi.org for more on pressure-treated lumber.
</P>
<P>
   A deck of plastic, typically polyvinyl chloride similar to the
material used in plastic plumbing pipes, doesn't deteriorate in the
same way that wood does when exposed to the weather, but no
building material lasts forever. Check the warranty and care
guidelines for any plastic deck product you are considering.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers of plastic decks point out that their decks
require no scrubbing, bleaching, waterproofing, staining or
painting. They are generally white but can be ordered in other
colors.
</P>
<P>
   Sources disagree on the point, but plastic-deck manufacturers
claim their products are cooler to the touch on sunny days. They
are also splinter-free and not prone to splitting.
</P>
<P>
   Composite deck products combine recycled materials such as
sawdust and shredded plastic. Perhaps the best known composite
brand is Trex, which is made of waste woods and scrap plastic such
as recycled grocery bags.
</P>
<P>
   The combination creates decking boards that are stiff like wood
but damage-resistant like plastic.
</P>
<P>
   Trex decking boards are brown when installed but quickly turn
light gray and maintain that shade for life. They can become
stained or develop a spotted appearance after a few years. Normal
deck cleaners will return them to a uniform color.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturer claims it will not rot, crack or deteriorate
because of moisture, insects or the ultraviolet rays of the sun. It
also never needs sealing, does not splinter and does not become
slick when wet.
</P>
<P>
   Trex usually is more expensive than pressure-treated lumber, but
lower than plastic. Visit www.trex.com for more details.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure-treated lumber retains the natural look of wood grain,
which is important to some homeowners. Redwood also has an
attractive grain, plus a rich reddish-brown color that many find
attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Redwood, cedar and other woods are suitable for building decks,
and they can be strikingly beautiful, but they tend to be
expensive. Cook said the ones he has built have been about three
times as expensive as pressure-treated lumber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Redwood is a high-end product for decks,'' said California
Redwood Association spokeswoman Pamela Allsebrook. ``It is more
expensive, but it has lots of advantages.''
</P>
<P>
   Allsebrook said redwood decks are less prone than
pressure-treated lumber to warping and cupping. It is naturally
resistant to insects so chemical additives aren't needed. She said
redwood should be sealed regularly to extend its life.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said people with redwood and cedar decks usually use clear
sealants so the beauty of the wood shows through. He said clear
sealants don't last as long as types with some pigment, so
redwood-deck owners tend to seal more often.
</P>
<P>
   He also said redwood and cedar are softer than pine, so they
tend to dent when objects are dropped on the deck floor.
</P>
<P>
   Contact James Cummings at jamescummings(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
