<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0013 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-6     07-12 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-675(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE LAPTOP, WILL TRAVEL _ WITH EXTREME CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Airports require certain survival skills under any
circumstances, what with summer crowds, delayed flights, overpriced
and stale food, lost baggage, overhead bins crammed with holiday
loot and the dreaded 300-pound, perspiring tourist with a duffle
bag heading for the center seat next to you.
</P>
<P>
   Add your laptop computer to the mix, and things can become
complicated. So if you must carry a computer with you, here are
some tips for how to get through airports a little more smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   HOLD ON TO IT: To start with the obvious, but most important,
rule: Never, ever, check your laptop computer as baggage. Have you
ever watched the crews loading and unloading baggage? They often
compete to see who can throw the bag the farthest. If your laptop
is not mangled, it will be stolen. Maybe not on this trip, but
eventually.
</P>
<P>
   INSURE IT: If you use your laptop primarily for business, it is
probably not covered under your standard homeowner's insurance
policy. Your agent can add a laptop to your policy to cover the
loss of hardware. Safeware (www.safeware.com) is an insurance
company specializing in the coverage of laptops. One popular policy
covers up to $3,000 of the replacement cost of a lost, stolen or
damaged computer for $75 per year. And best of all, said David
Haase of Safeware, ``there is no stupidity exclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if you are dumb enough to put the laptop in your
checked baggage or drop it off the side of a cruise ship, it's
still covered.
</P>
<P>
   BE PREPARED: Before you take your laptop to the airport, try
destructive visualization. Somebody steals your laptop. Do you have
a current backup copy of your data? Have you encrypted sensitive
information?
</P>
<P>
   Laptop thefts are rampant in airports. Some of the thefts are
opportunistic, occurring when the traveler leaves the computer
unattended for one reason or another. It takes just a second or
two, and the laptop has a new owner. Why is it that people who
would never leave a purse or wallet unattended while they visit the
restroom still occasionally leave their $2,000 laptops up for
grabs?
</P>
<P>
   But some thefts are orchestrated. One of the more common scams
involves a pair of grifters who select the victim at the security
checkpoint where bags are placed on a conveyor belt to be X-rayed.
The bag man (or woman) goes through first and loiters at the end of
the conveyor.
</P>
<P>
   The second thief waits for the victim to send a laptop through
the X-ray machine, then causes a distraction while passing through
the metal detector. The owner of the laptop is delayed on the other
side of the checkpoint long enough for the first thief to snatch
the computer bag and disappear into the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce the chance of theft by conveyor-belt thieves, you may
want to ask the security guard to hand-check your laptop, unless
you are late for a flight. (By the way, the X-ray machine will not
harm the data on your hard drive or floppies.) Of course, a
hand-check means that you will have to appease the guard by turning
on the computer to prove that it is not a bomb. If you use
slow-booting Windows, allow extra minutes to get to your gate.
</P>
<P>
   According to Safeware, more than 300,000 laptops were reported
stolen last year.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T FORGET: Some otherwise sharp travelers simply forget their
laptops on the plane. You can help a Good Samaritan return your
computer by taping a business card to the bottom of the laptop,
engraving your driver's license number (not your Social Security
number, which could be used to steal from your online accounts) on
the top of the case or having contact information pop up when the
computer is first turned on.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T BE OBVIOUS: Many people carry their laptops in a carrying
case labeled ``Dell,'' ``IBM'' or some other obvious computer name.
The bag might as well say ``Steal Me.'' My bag preference is a
padded backpack. It is slightly less conspicuous, and is also
easier on the shoulders.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   LOOK FOR WIRELESS: And now, some good news. There are few things
more pathetic than the sight of a grown man sitting on the floor of
the airport waiting room beneath a pay phone with a phone wire
stretched between the modem and the phone, the laptop teetering on
his knee, as he tries to send a file on deadline. Yes, I was that
man.
</P>
<P>
   Wayport Inc. (www.wayport.com) has just completed unwiring the
airport that serves Silicon Gulch in Austin, Texas, to allow
travelers to get high-speed Internet access via wireless networking
anywhere from the gate to the baggage claim area. Just relax in a
comfortable place anywhere in the airport, pop open the notebook,
log on to the Wayport portal, and say goodbye to squatting under
the pay phones for an Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   Two terminals at Dallas-Fort Worth will go wireless next week.
Wayport says LaGuardia, Kennedy and Newark airports will be
wireless by the end of the year, along with Seattle-Tacoma and
others. Wayport has set up its wireless networks in some 600 hotels
and plans to more than double its base next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Wayport system is based on the 11-megabit IEEE 802.11b
wireless Ethernet standard used by Apple, IBM, 3Com, Cisco and
others. It requires a wireless networking card, about $99 to $179
in most stores, and costs a flat fee of $3.50 each time the
traveler logs on to the network, although there is no time limit
for the connection. Wayport has waived the connection fees for the
first 50 times the traveler connects.
</P>
<P>
   BYO MOVIES: On longer flights, some airlines show movies that
you probably did not want to see when they were at the theaters.
Some offer passengers a portable DVD or Hi-8 video player with a
dinky screen and bad sound. But if your laptop has a DVD drive,
simply rent or buy your choice of DVD movies before the trip and
enjoy them on the big screen. Make sure that you have sufficient
battery life, though. Your seat neighbors will stare in awe as you
fire up ``The Matrix'' on your 15-inch TFT screen.
</P>
<P>
   If you are planning ahead, NEC has just released in Japan the
first laptop with Dolby Headphone, a new sound technology that
recreates the 5.1-channel surround-sound effects of a home theater
system through a pair of ordinary stereo headphones. The Dolby
Headphone technology is expected to be available in the United
States by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   SKIP THE TRAYS: Some airlines are adding an inch or two of space
between rows in coach, which is welcome, but they have not done
anything to make it easier to use a laptop on the little trays that
fold down from the back of the seat in front of you. Grab an extra
pillow or blanket from the flight attendant and _ here's a novel
idea _ use the laptop on your lap. If the lout in front of you
suddenly lurches backward, your computer will not be harmed.
</P>
<P>
   AND SKIP THE BINS: It is a good idea to store the computer under
the seat in front of you rather than in an overhead bin. I saw a
laptop fall to its death recently when a passenger decided to
rearrange the overhead compartment to make room for her oversize
bag, and _ oops! Her seatmate's computer bag fell 5 feet to the
floor. Luckily, it did not land on someone's head. Also, a bag at
your feet is harder to forget than a bag in the overhead bin, and
no one is trying to jam a suitcase against your bag down there.
</P>
<P>
   FOLLOW INSTRUCTIONS: Does your portable electronic device really
interfere with sensitive avionics on the aircraft, jeopardizing
everyone's safety during takeoffs and landings? The evidence is
inconclusive. But if the pilot is happier with devices turned off,
you should be happy, too.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if you'd like to ignore all these tips, you could ask
yourself a fundamental question before you start out on your trip:
</P>
<P>
   Do I really need to take a computer with me on vacation?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
