<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0026 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-X-MENGUIDE-COX     07-12 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-X-MENGUIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Can't tell an X-Man from an X-File? It's time to consult our
excellent X-Men guide
 &HT;    By David Thomas
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - It started in 1963 as The Uncanny X-Men.
The comic book by Stan Lee introduced five pupils at Xavier's
School for Gifted Youngsters. They possessed a mutant ``X gene''
that gave them special powers that humans fear and distrust.
Professor Charles Xavier teaches these five X-Men to control their
emerging powers to fight evil and help mutants and humans coexist.
</P>
<P>
   While the comic book has been a top seller for decades and
spawned a popular Fox cartoon, not many people know just who the
X-Men are. That may change with Friday's big-screen movie
``X-Men,'' starring Patrick Stewart, Ian McKellen and Halle Berry,
and directed by Bryan Singer (''The Usual Suspects'').
</P>
<P>
   So, you're not a cult comic book reader. Here's a guide to the
characters and story of the superhero tale:
</P>
<P>
   Professor X/
</P>
<P>
   Charles Xavier
</P>
<P>
   (Patrick Stewart)
</P>
<P>
   Mutant Power:
</P>
<P>
   Telepath
</P>
<P>
   Bio: Founder of Xavier's School for Gifted Youngsters.
Wheelchair-bound, he developed an advanced computer called Cerebro
to detect mutants like himself. He recruited the X-Men to help
defend humankind from evil mutants like his arch-enemy Magneto.
</P>
<P>
   Magneto/
</P>
<P>
   Erik Lehnsherr
</P>
<P>
   (Ian McKellen)
</P>
<P>
   Mutant Power: Can manipulate any metal substance.
</P>
<P>
   Bio: The Master of Magnetism is Charles Xavier's philosophical
rival. He believes mutants are meant to rule humankind, not coexist
with them as Xavier does. A child when his family was killed in a
Nazi concentration camp during World War II, Magneto has a deeper
reason to see his kind escape persecution. He heads the Brotherhood
of Evil Mutants.
</P>
<P>
   Cyclops/
</P>
<P>
   Scott Summers
</P>
<P>
   (James Marsden)
</P>
<P>
   Mutant Power: A high-powered optic blast. Think Superman's heat
vision on overload.
</P>
<P>
   Bio: The stoic leader introduced in the first issue of The
Uncanny X-Men must wear a protective visor, made of ruby red
quartz, at all times to control his mutant power.
</P>
<P>
   Wolverine/Logan
</P>
<P>
   (Hugh Jackman)
</P>
<P>
   Mutant Power: A healing factor and superhuman senses.
</P>
<P>
   Bio: The most popular of all X-Men. Wolverine doesn't know much
about his own past, and his age is a huge question mark because his
mutant power keeps him young. He has no scars and is extremely hard
to kill. His skeleton is made of the strongest metal on earth,
adamantium, and features three claws on each hand that can be
retracted into the arm at will. He has a soft spot for fellow X-er
Jean Grey.
</P>
<P>
   Storm/
</P>
<P>
   Ororo Monroe
</P>
<P>
   (Halle Berry)
</P>
<P>
   Mutant Power: Weather control.
</P>
<P>
   Bio: When the original X-Men were being held captive by an evil
alien, Professor X had to search for a new group of heroes to save
them. This changed the face of the series (See Uncanny X-Men 94 if
you can afford the $500 issue) and placed Storm in a leadership
position to compete with Cyclops.
</P>
<P>
   X Fact-ers
</P>
<P>
   Even though they aren't all in the movie, there are hundreds of
other X-Men characters. Some favorites: Iceman, Colossus, Beast,
Banshee, Longshot, Forge, Angel, Havoc and Polaris.
</P>
<P>
   Though the comic emphasizes action and evil-fighting, the
characters also fall in love (often with each other), break up,
lose friends, have children and face all the other highs and lows
of life.
</P>
<P>
   -Creator Stan Lee began the series in the era of civil rights as
a social commentary on bigotry with the mutants as a hated
minority. Even today, the X-Men battle racism.
</P>
<P>
   -If the movie does well, there's lots of buzz about an expanded
cast for the sequel, which may feature Sentinels, robots designed
to hunt down and kill mutants.
</P>
<P>
   -How do the X-Men fight evil across the globe? They hop in the
Blackbird, a superfast jet that can hover over any target
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   -How valuable are early copies of the comic classic? The Uncanny
X-Men 1 usually sells for $6,000, with No. 2 going for $1,700.
</P>
<P>
   -Past, Present and Future comics in West Palm Beach, the largest
comic retailer in the county, reports that X-Men comics are flying
off the shelves. ``There are at least 10 different X-Men titles and
we usually sell 200 a month, which is more than any other title,''
said manager Chris Emmersi. ``But lately, new customers have just
been snatching up copies.''
</P>
<P>
   More of the X-Men:
</P>
<P>
   Rogue
</P>
<P>
   (Anna Paquin)
</P>
<P>
   Mutant Power: She can absorb other mutants' powers and memories
by touching their bare skin.
</P>
<P>
   Bio: The comic book version of Rogue is a busty and strong young
woman who can steal other mutants' powers with a touch. Making all
her sexual allure quite deadly, since she'd steal even a mortal's
memories and strength. Unfortunately the sexpot role has been
filled by adolescent Anna Paquin.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Grey
</P>
<P>
   (Famke Janssen)
</P>
<P>
   Mutant Power: Telekinesis and telepathy.
</P>
<P>
   Bio: Originally named Marvel Girl, Grey dropped the moniker in
the 1970s around the same time NOW began. Grey was later abducted
by a powerful cosmic entity that impersonated her for years without
anyone catching on. During that time she (or was it the alien?)
married her high school sweetheart Scott Summers. And you thought
the ``who shot JR'' storyline had a twist.
</P>
<P>
   Sabertooth(Tyler Mane)
</P>
<P>
   Mutant Power: Possesses superhuman strength and animal senses
much like Wolverine's.
</P>
<P>
   Bio: Little is known about this evil mutant killer except that
he might have worked as a government agent.
</P>
<P>
   Mystique
</P>
<P>
   (Rebecca Romijn-Stamos)
</P>
<P>
   Mutant Power: A human chameleon who can take on the appearance
of anyone she comes in contact with.
</P>
<P>
   Bio: This sly mutant is known for her deception, and not just in
physical form. You never know what side she's allied with.
</P>
<P>
   Toad
</P>
<P>
   (Ray Park)
</P>
<P>
   Mutant Power: Extreme dexterity and leaping ability.
</P>
<P>
   Bio: Once a side-show attraction, the Toad seems to enjoy the
role of supervillain lackey. He lives only to serve his master
whether it be Magneto or Mystique. And, oh yeah, he has a 15-foot
tongue.
</P>
<P>
   X-Men on the Web:
</P>
<P>
   ``Unofficial X-Men'' at www.xmansion.com has an extensive
gallery of X-Men comic art, chats and forums.
</P>
<P>
   The official site for the movie is www.xmenthemovie.com
</P>
<P>
   www.mutantwatch.com features the fictional Senator Kelly's
paranoid political tirade against the mutants among us.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
