<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0035 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-KASELL13-COX     07-12 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KASELL13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    50TH YEAR IN RADIO FINDS VETERAN NEWSCASTER IN A PLACE HE LIKES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's a tad after 7 a.m. _ the middle of the workday
_ and Carl Kasell is sipping coffee from a sky-blue coffee mug
commemorating the Tar Heels of the University of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Half a century has passed since the newscaster for National
Public Radio's ``Morning Edition'' began his career as a high
school reporter for WGBR-AM in his home town of Goldsboro, N.C. But
Kasell is proud that a trace of the South lingers faintly in his
familiar voice.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 66, he relishes his roots.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in the tobacco country of eastern North Carolina. His
dad ``was a guy who kind of bounced from job to job,'' and money
was sometimes scarce in a family with four children.
</P>
<P>
   A young Andy Griffith, just out of college himself, was his high
school drama teacher. After casting Kasell in the lead of ``Father
of the Bride'' during his senior year, Griffith urged him to
consider a theatrical career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, 'No, I'm going to be a radio star,' `` Kasell
recalls with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   The 1950s had just begun, and television was in its infancy.
Kasell had grown up listening to Jack Benny and ``the Lone Ranger''
and ``Superman'' and ``the Hermit.'' News bored him, but he aspired
to an on-air career as a quiz show host or actor in serial drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Radio was still king,'' he said. ``I always wanted to be a
part of it. It just fascinated me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an industry that can be so creative. Whereas TV plays to
your eyes, we play to your mind. When radio is done right, it can
create images that are far superior to what television can show you
with pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasell sips his coffee and glances at a studio clock. Every hour
from 5 a.m. through 11 a.m. ET, he delivers a five-minute newscast
as ``Morning Edition'' airs _ live or taped _ across the nation's
time zones. Every newscast must be updated.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two decades, Kasell has arisen an hour after
midnight on weekdays in his home in suburban Annandale, Va. By 2:15
a.m., he's usually chatting with ``Morning Edition'' host Bob
Edwards at the NPR Headquarters in downtown Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The conversations are ``seldom about work,'' he said. They share
a passion for college football _ Edwards for the University of
Louisville Cardinals and Kasell for the Tar Heels.
</P>
<P>
   After high school, he had headed to the scenic campus at Chapel
Hill. Coincidentally, UNC graduate Griffith moved back there at
about the same time, leaving teaching and beginning his night club
act. Kasell majored in English and worked at the campus radio
station, sometimes with classmate Charles Kuralt.
</P>
<P>
   After four years of college, he was drafted into the Army.
Stationed in Italy, he met the woman whom he would marry shortly
after his discharge. They celebrated a 37th wedding anniversary
before her death several years ago. Their married son lives in
Reston, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Having always worked an early morning shift, Kasell adjusted his
schedule to accommodate family life. After leaving work about 11:30
a.m., he would sleep from 2 p.m. to 5 p.m. Then he awoke for
several hours to watch his son play baseball from Little League
through high school or for other family activities. Then he slept
again from 9 p.m. to 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining NPR in the mid-1970s, he worked for commercial
radio stations in North Carolina and Virginia. He played pop and
country music and worked for an all-news station that switched to
rock 'n' roll. He sees public radio as his salvation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care for shock radio. I think it's an insult to our
industry,'' he said. ``Ranting and raving and talking about obscene
topics is not what I envisioned radio to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Literate, leisurely, non-commercial NPR, with its entertaining
whimsy and thoughtful news and analysis and assorted cultural fare,
comes closer to being the radio of his youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite an organization,'' he said. ``I'm glad I found it,
or glad they found me. However that worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Edwards, Kasell has been on ``Morning Edition'' since
its birth 20 years ago. The popular program is broadcast by more
than 520 NPR stations. More recently, Kasell has fulfilled his
boyhood ambition of hosting a radio quiz show _ NPR's weekly
``Wait, Wait ... Don't Tell Me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like old-time radio,'' he enthuses. ``I'm official judge
and scorekeeper'' for panelists that include humorist Roy Blount
Jr. and Washington Post columnist Roxanne Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Kasell has also traveled to NPR stations around the country,
giving his audience a chance to see as well has hear him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in a while, you'll meet somebody who says 'You know, you
look exactly like I thought you would look,' `` he said. But that's
not the usual reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I probably sound younger than I am because a woman in
San Francisco last year said 'You know, you are really more mature
than you sound,'' he said. ``I said, 'You mean older, don't you?'
``
</P>
<P>
   But in his 50th year of broadcasting, he has no plans to leave
the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider this work,'' he explained as 8 a.m.
approached and legions of commuters tuned into ``Morning Edition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fun.''
</P>
<P>
   For online information: www.npr.org
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
