<HEADER>
A0082 &Cx1f; ttx-z
u a BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-     07-12 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`QUICK-RESTORE' ERASES PROBLEM _ AND MORE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY   
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I have a Compaq with Windows 98. I tried to
download an antivirus program, and it caused my computer to crash.
I used the Compaq ``quick-restore'' CD, but in the process lost
Microsoft Word and Microsoft Works and a few other programs and
files.
</P>
<P>
   _ Overkill
</P>
<P>
   Dear Over: Ummmm, I think you might have overreacted a tad. The
only time you want to pull out one of those quick-restore CDs is
when you've hammered your system so badly that there's just no
turning back.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe that a bungled download was enough to kill
your PC, although almost anything is possible. I certainly would
have asked the office geek to take a quick look at it before
dropping the big one, though.
</P>
<P>
   A restore CD usually reformats and rebuilds the computer to its
pristine, out-of-the-box state. That may or may not include any
bundled applications like Word or Works. Generally, if the
applications aren't included in the restore disc, there's some sort
of utility that allows the buyer to create a set of installation
floppies. I guess it's sort of late for that.
</P>
<P>
   If you have the original documentation and product registration
numbers, you might be able to wheedle a copy of the software out of
Compaq _ or maybe even Microsoft _ for a nominal fee. If not, I'd
suspect that some local software store will be more than happy to
take your check for a whole new set of programs.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I added a 3-megabyte hard drive to my computer
and made it a slave to Drive C. I am now having problems with space
on C. Is it possible to use a program called ``Uninstaller'' to
move DOS to the second hard drive, leaving only Windows on Drive C?
Is this the best solution to the problem?
</P>
<P>
   _ Too Much Stuff
</P>
<P>
   Dear Too: Nooooooooo. Does that answer your question?
</P>
<P>
   First, those uninstaller programs usually require that they be
installed before you install an application. They keep a record of
which files are loaded where so they can find them all later.
</P>
<P>
   Second, you could use some geek tweaks to boot from a secondary
drive, but why clog up the plumbing? And, all you Poindexters out
there, don't start writing me with duct-tape-and-spit solutions.
Sure, maybe you can get it to work, but this guy is a normal human.
</P>
<P>
   Third, DOS and Windows are used to being in the same place,
since they're all part of one happy operating system. Well, not
that happy, but you get the point. Trying to scatter them over two
drives is just going to give you a major headache.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what you want to do: Uninstall any application on the
primary hard drive that you can, then reinstall it on the new one.
Leave the operating system alone.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: What is your insight on all these sweepstakes?
Are they actually giving away all that money? Do you by any chance
know which ones are legitimate?
</P>
<P>
   _ Barnum Was Right
</P>
<P>
   DEAR BARNUM: The only truly legitimate sweepstakes I can fully
endorse is the Bombay Institute's Cash-a-Palooza, in which entrants
are asked to put their names and addresses on 10-dollar bills and
send them to my Cayman Islands address. Some lucky winner could
receive as much as $20 if I draw his or her name out of a hat. Or
not. I'm not sure where I put my hat.
</P>
<P>
   (About 30 attorneys want to make sure that you know Dr. Emilio
Bombay's last answer was a joke. Get it? Please don't send him
money. However, you can write to him at
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: (817)
390-7257. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-07-00 1223EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 1528EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0083 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-BROWN-COMPUTER-CO     07-12 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING THE LEAP TO DIGITAL PLANNING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By LONNIE BROWN  The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years and years and years, Larry Becker ran his life with a
paper-based planner. Perhaps more correctly, a paper-based planner
ran Larry Becker's life. In fact, he used to teach courses in how
to effectively use the popular paper planners.
</P>
<P>
   You know the kind: Available in office-supply stores and by mail
order, their pages hold notations for meetings, to-do lists, phone
numbers, follow-ups and other personal and business items.
</P>
<P>
   Becker, who runs a Web marketing company in Lakeland, Fla., and
gives time-management seminars, never went anywhere without his
planner.
</P>
<P>
   Then about four years ago, the paper scales fell from his eyes,
and he saw the digital world of handheld personal information
managers. He never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   And that brings us to Becker's recent endeavor: A two-hour video
tape, ``Time Management in the Palm of Your Hand.'' The tape, as
the name implies, is centered around the Palm personal information
manager, but the system can be used with other digital planners.
(Since Handspring's Visor uses the Palm operating system _ and was
designed by the same people who brought out the original Palm _ it
works seemlessly with that planner.)
</P>
<P>
   Briefly, personal digital assistants (PDAs) are small devices _
about the size of a deck of cards so they fit easily in pocket or
purse _ that store and retrieve to-do lists, a daily calendar with
alarms, memos, addresses and telephone numbers. They can store
several years of activities, thousands of names and hundreds of
memos.
</P>
<P>
   Using a search feature, users can instantly locate anything
anywhere in the device.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the beauty of it,'' said Becker, 37. ``If you've ever
written something in a paper planner and then try to find it again,
you know it's not very efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Some planners are divided so that users carry one month with
them at a time. ``If you're out somewhere and need to refer to
something from a previous month, you're in trouble,'' said Becker.
Finding such information using a digital device is quick and
painless.
</P>
<P>
   Becker came up with the idea for a training film for Palm users
after he gave a seminar to employees whose company had purchased
Palm for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found they didn't even know the basics for using the Palm,''
said Becker. ``Some of them were using the keyboard (a screen
display of a keyboard that is used for entering text by tapping on
letters) instead of the Palm's handwriting recognition because they
didn't understand how to use it.'' Using a stylus, letters drawn on
the Palm's glass screen turn into typed text. With a little
practice, it's a fast way to enter text.
</P>
<P>
   The $49.95 tape is professionally done. Becker has used shots of
the Palm's screen extensively, so users can see what's going on as
information is being entered. That approach has also kept the
``talking head'' format to a minimum. A time sheet has been
included with the tape so viewers can quickly move to one of the
six sections covered for review.
</P>
<P>
   The first section gives users some of the basics of operating
the Palm. (''You'd be surprised the things people miss because they
don't read the manual,'' said Becker as a way of explaining why
seemingly basic information is included in the first few minutes.)
The second section deals in setting up the Palm for time
management. Becker recommends users create various to-do lists so
items can be classified in groups: today, tomorrow, soon, later,
morning, weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The third and fourth sections cover commitments to
time-management success and how to keep on target by using the
to-do list.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth section explains techniques for improving efficiency
with the Palm's calendar and appointment manager. The sixth section
takes users through a typical day in a busy life by demonstrating
how time management can be adjusted to handle unscheduled events
and keep track of ongoing projects.
</P>
<P>
   Becker recommends two programs to add to the Palm. While not
necessary to time-management techniques, they do add some
improvements to the Palm's date book and to-do list. Links for both
programs are available on Becker's Web site, www.palmplanning.com,
under the software section.
</P>
<P>
   The first, and least expensive, is BIG To Do. Palm's to-do list
has five levels of priority for items. BIG To Do allows items to be
ranked one through 10 in importance.
</P>
<P>
   Becker had a friend write the program, to make it easier to make
the transition from paper planner to the Palm. With only five
levels, there wasn't an easy way to fit in with the A-B-C-1-2-3
priority system used in paper planning, said Becker.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a big change, but it saves having a group of ones or
twos on a list. The program has a 30-day trial period. To continue
using it costs $4.95 to register.
</P>
<P>
   The second program is DATEBK3 ($20 from Pimlico Software). It's
very much like the Palm's date book program, but provides some
welcomed additions. One of those is a ``floating'' item: With
Palm's date book, an item that you didn't want to forget to do on a
Tuesday _ but didn't get done on that day _ would not automatically
move to Wednesday. The item had to be moved manually. DATEBK3 will
keep moving the item forward until it has been checked as done.
</P>
<P>
   Another nice feature: DATEBK3 displays high-priority items in
the to-do list on the daily appointments screen. That way, you're
reminded of items that need to be done as the day progresses.
</P>
<P>
   Users of Handspring's Visor don't need DATEBK3 because it's the
one the company used for its date book program. And although there
is a DATEBK4 version, Becker notes that it takes up nearly a half a
megabyte of Palm memory _ a lot more than DATEBK3 _ while not
adding substantial time-management functions. ``If memory is a
factor, DATEBK3 is the best one to use,'' said Becker.
</P>
<P>
   Becker has a book coming out in October, ``Teach Yourself Palm
Today,'' which will be published by the Sams division of Macmillan
USA.
</P>
<P>
   For information, visit the Web site (www.palmplanning.com) or
call 863-413-0728.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. The
Ledger is a member of the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
<P>
