<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEB-B2B-ANTITRUST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS EXCHANGE SITES RAISE QUESTIONS FOR REGULATORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As companies in practically every industry rush to
join business-to-business exchanges on the Internet, regulators are
growing concerned that they will face a rash of new antitrust
questions for which they are not prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Known as B2B Web sites, the exchanges create a place for
companies in the same industry, be it automobiles or grain, to buy
and sell goods, potentially saving millions of dollars in
back-office costs by setting up a national marketplace online. But
the sites, which can compile huge amounts of sensitive data and are
often jointly owned by corporate rivals, also create opportunities
for collusion and price-fixing that did not exist before, antitrust
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Both regulators and executives agree that the stakes are
enormous. B2B sites already account for about $150 billion in
annual sales, significantly more than the better-known consumer
sites like Amazon.com. And that number is expected to grow
exponentially as businesses move more and more into buying and
selling to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antitrust has never had this kind of factual scenario to look
at before,'' said Susan DeSanti, the Federal Trade Commission's
director of policy planning.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the commission took the unusual step of holding a
two-day conference to which it invited executives, lawyers and
consumer advocates to advise it on how to regulate B2B
marketplaces. Already, the commission is examining Covisint, the
site planned by the nation's Big Three carmakers, and last month
the Department of Justice said it was investigating one led by six
large meatpacking companies. The Senate Commerce Committee also
plans to hold a hearing this month on the airline industry's joint
Web sites. And law firms are doing a brisk business in advising
business-to-business exchanges on how to organize themselves so as
to avoid regulatory scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials are beginning to take notice now because in
recent months one group of major companies after another has
announced plans to form exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, legal experts say B2B exchanges are likely to present
the next major forum _ after the Microsoft trial and the proposed
Worldcom-Sprint and America Online-Time Warner mergers _ for the
debate over how century-old antitrust laws should be applied to the
new world of the Internet. As in the previous cases, lawyers say,
the questions are not new: What is collusion and how can it be
stopped? When are competitors allowed to cooperate with each other?
Which rivals can they exclude from an alliance?
</P>
<P>
   The new twists are the speed with which companies are able to
communicate with one another and the the frequency with which
longtime rivals, such as DaimlerChrysler and General Motors and
Ford, are setting up joint ventures. Legal experts say those
ventures _ the B2B exchanges _ will give suppliers the opportunity
to signal each other about price increases, for instance, or
manufacturers a chance to conspire to pay artificially low prices
for their supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the issue that came up with Microsoft,'' said Andrew
I. Gavil, a professor at the Howard University School of Law. ``Is
antitrust up to dealing with technology?''
</P>
<P>
   Corporate executives, for their part, say the exchanges will
increase competition by giving companies access to the most
updated, accurate information about prices. That in turn will lower
businesses' costs, increasing profits for efficient companies and
eventually bringing lower prices to consumers, they add.
</P>
<P>
   For now, regulators say they are trying to learn as much as they
can about the B2B sites before issuing any far-reaching policies or
bringing suit against individual exchanges. ``We at the FTC are
very much in a learning phase,'' Sheila F. Anthony, a federal trade
commissioner, told executives and lawyers at last week's
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The promise of huge efficiencies is certainly tantalizing,''
Anthony added. ``On the other hand, I can't help but wonder if
there might be a serpent in the garden of efficiencies.''
</P>
<P>
   And Orson Swindle, another federal trade commissioner, said:
``We must get this right. Otherwise, we could do terrible harm.''
</P>
<P>
   The sites take any number of forms, from auctions that resemble
eBay to online catalogs that allow buyers to sift through products.
Some, like Covisint, are set up by the companies doing the buying.
Others, such as MetalSite, which is owned mainly by steel
manufacturers, are run by sellers.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, though, regulators' worries fall into two
general areas, DeSanti said. In shorthand, Gavil added, the issues
can be thought of as ``exclusion'' _ who is allowed to participate
in the exchanges, under what conditions _ and ``collusion'' _ what
the participants are able to do with the information they gather.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the regulators' concerns is how the rapid
exchange of information on the Web sites will affect the companies'
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In almost every sector of the economy, industry groups now spend
weeks collecting aggregated data on prices and sales volumes. On
the B2B exchanges, by contrast, companies will be able to see
current information immediately. That could make it easier for them
to coordinate the pricing of goods without ever speaking to each
other about it, a practice legal scholars call ``conscious
paralellism.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacking detailed, current information, a company might decide to
cut prices in a few markets and hope it can steal some market share
before a rival catches on, said Jonathan B. Baker, a former trade
commission official who teaches at the law school at American
University. On a business-to-business Web site, however,
information travels more quickly and could eliminate the price
wars.
</P>
<P>
   The worry is more than than just hypothetical, antitrust experts
say. In 1992, the Justice Department sued the nation's large
airlines, accusing them of using their computer reservation systems
to send up trial balloons on price changes. Smaller airlines also
opposed the system, saying they lacked the money to buy computers
that had suddenly become necessary to compete.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the suit, the airlines agreed to stop publishing
information about future changes in fares.
</P>
<P>
   Though the legal proceedings surrounding it ended years ago, the
airline reservation system has become a frequent topic of
discussion among executives, corporate lawyers and government
officials today. The central questions it raised in the early '90s
about the ways a network can cause collusion and exclusion are the
same ones at the core of the new B2B debate, lawyers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fair analogy,'' said Mark L. Walsh, the chief executive
of VerticalNet, which owns 56 B2B marketplaces.
Business-to-business exchanges offer ``a similar potential for
abuse,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates also say that because so many of the
exchanges are owned by competitors, the Web sites will allow rivals
to make decisions jointly about production levels and inventories,
becoming de facto cartels in the mold of OPEC. ``These are serious,
structural issues,'' said Mark Cooper, the research director of the
Consumer Federation of America.
</P>
<P>
   To address the concerns _ and avoid regulatory run-ins _ the
companies setting up the exchanges are including antitrust lawyers
at almost every stage of the planning, executives say. The lawyer
for MetalSite has attended all of the company's board meetings, and
MetalSite executives avoid giving specific data to its board
members, who work for the steel companies that own the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably show our board less information than most boards
see. They only see aggregated data,'' said David B. Bordo, the
company's chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the exchanges is to convince their customers that
they are independent of the companies that founded them. Covisint,
for example, is now negotiating with the trade commission over the
terms of its formal separation from the car companies that created
it, said A. Alan Turfe, the General Motors executive who is the
exchange's interim co-chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The customers, meanwhile, are concerned that proprietary
information _ such as how much aluminum they are buying and at what
price _ will become available to rivals or clients.
</P>
<P>
   Francis P. Lopez, the chief executive of Aztec Manufacturing
Corp., an auto industry supplier in Romulus, Mich., said B2B Web
sites can cut costs and offer ``tremendous, tremendous
advantages.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are a lot of gray areas people are concerned
about,'' Lopez added. ``We have to make sure we have the ability to
protect privacy'' of companies' sensitive data.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-06-00 2045EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 1532EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
