<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0094 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i BC-ANTI-HIV-GEL-HNS &LR;      07-12 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTI-HIV-GEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STUDY SHOWS GEL FAILS TO PROTECT AGAINST AIDS VIRUS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Also filed in ``l'' category)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa _ A common spermicidal gel not only failed
to protect women from the AIDS virus, it apparently helped promote
new infections among Thai and African prostitutes, according to a
study released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are a setback to efforts worldwide to come up with
a germ-killer that could be used by women to protect themselves
against the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV). In many countries
hit hardest by AIDS, women have trouble insisting their male sex
partners use a condom.
</P>
<P>
   It could also serve as a warning to homosexual men who may have
thought lubricants containing the spermicidal gel Nonoxynol-9 might
help defend against HIV transmission during anal sex.
</P>
<P>
   Although not marketed as an AIDS prevention product, many
manufacturers have added Nonoxynal-9 to lubricants. Studies have
shown that Nonoxynol-9 kills HIV in a test tube and in animals, and
has proved to be safe in humans.
</P>
<P>
   The findings announced Wednesday at the 13th International AIDS
Conference in Durban come from Nonoxynol-9's use in the vagina.
Still, Grant Colfax, director of clinical studies in the HIV
research section of the San Francisco Health Department, said the
results are sobering for men, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reinforces the need to use condoms no matter what,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The acquired immune deficiency syndrome is an affliction in
which HIV weakens the immune system, subjecting the body to serious
infection. AIDS is most often spread through sexual contact,
sharing contaminated needles and infected blood products.
</P>
<P>
   Like other prevention researchers, those seeking to cut
transmission among gay men have been focusing on Nonoxynol-9 as the
most promising candidate as a germ killer. Other potential
microbicides are in the pipeline but none are as far along in
testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to re-examine the research agenda at this point,''
Colfax said.
</P>
<P>
   Very little of the world's HIV research is focused on
microbicides, and it has been difficult to attract interest from
pharmaceutical companies in developing such products.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier study in which prostitutes in Cameroon inserted
Nonoxynol-9 impregnated film into their vaginas showed that there
were roughly as many infections among the group that used the
product, compared to the group that used a placebo.
</P>
<P>
   Those results were disappointing enough. But when researchers
last month decoded the findings from a study conducted among
prostitutes in South Africa, the Ivory Coast and Thailand, they
found that 59 women who used the gel became infected with HIV,
compared to 41 who were in the placebo group.
</P>
<P>
   The figures were even higher among women who came in for regular
follow-up exam. Sixteen percent of those using Nonoxynol-9 tested
positive, compared to 9 percent of those who got the placebo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an understatement to say we were extremely
disappointed,'' said Lut Van Damme, a Belgian researcher who
presented the findings. ``The results are a serious setback.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Perriens, who heads the microbicide effort at the United
Nations' AIDS agency, issued a warning to anyone thinking of using
Nonoxynol-9 as protection against sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're wasting your money and you might possibly be wasting
your life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The data suggest that Nonoxynol-9 contributed to small sores in
the women's vaginas that may have provided an easier way for HIV to
enter their bodies. Women who used Nonoxynol-9 had more such sores,
and the number of sores was correlated to the risk of infection.
</P>
<P>
   The gel is marketed as a contraceptive in the United States
under the name Advantage S. Howard Levine, a spokesman for Columbia
Laboratories of Miami, maker of the product, said the findings only
apply to the group of women studied _ prostitutes who used the gel
many times a day, day after day. The gel has passed safety tests,
and Nonoxynol-9 has been on the market for many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say it is harmful is an overstatement,'' Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, researchers who had been gearing up for further tests of
Nonoxynol-9 are expected to change their plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to scrutinize this very carefully,'' said
Nancy Padian, director of international programs at the AIDS
Research Institute of the University of California at San
Francisco. She had been planning to embark on a study of
Nonoxynol-9 in Zimbabwe. ``I'm grateful to be able to make the
decision now, before the study got under way.''
</P>
<P>
   In the research pipeline are five other potential microbicides
that rely on various ways to combat HIV. Some interfere with the
ability of HIV to attach itself to the body's cells, others attack
germs generally, and some make the vagina more acidic, which is
toxic to HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers also are looking at introducing anti-retroviral
agents, similar to those taken orally, as a way to prevent HIV from
gaining a foothold.
</P>
</TEXT>
