 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    WEB MAKES BIG-TIME DEBUT AT POLITICAL CONVENTIONS
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In 1948, the television networks broke new ground
by broadcasting the national political conventions from
Philadelphia. People in five East Coast cities were able to watch
the live proceedings via a cable hookup at a time when there were
fewer than 400,000 TV set owners in the whole country.
</P>
<P>
   This year, as the once huge influence of the TV networks on
political coverage wanes, the upcoming Republican and Democratic
national conventions are emerging as a battleground for the
increasingly robust political Internet culture.
</P>
<P>
   Around each meeting hall, pool cameras operated by C-SPAN will
beam images that can readily be accessed on tens of millions of
computers in every corner of the planet already linked to the
Internet. While most onlookers will lack a TV-quality picture, they
will be free to choose their own camera angles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big difference between now and four years ago is video,''
said Chris Long, director of new media for C-SPAN, which will offer
pooled convention coverage for both the networks and Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers in both convention cities have set aside ``Internet
Alleys'' for about 40 online news organizations, including such
political Web sites as Voter.com, America Online Inc.,
Pseudopolitics.com and Slate, a political journal owned by
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these video-equipped sites will also offer tailored
coverage of what onetime Watergate author Carl Bernstein, now
executive editor of Voter.com, calls ``the shadow convention _ all
the stuff that goes on whenever tens of thousands of political
activists, lobbyists and journalists get together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our approach will be to stay off the podium to give people the
sound and the feel of what's going on behind the scenes,''
Bernstein said. ``In looking at our potential audience, it will be,
above all else, the 40,000 people who have come to Philadelphia or
Los Angeles as players so they can see what everybody else is up
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Voter.com, a for-profit outlet that also aggregates
coverage from other political sites, will issue ``smart cards'' to
delegates and their associates. The cards can be used to gain
access to Web consoles that will tell them where late evening
parties are taking place _ with links to online maps that show them
how to get there.
</P>
<P>
   The Web has even edged its way into those once haughty symbols
of convention coverage: roof-hugging skyboxes. This year, for the
first time, the five veteran networks and their four all-news
commercial cable rivals have new dot-com neighbors ensconced in
customized booths high above the convention floors. Voter.com,
Pseudopolitics.com, AOL and USAToday.com, among others, have
booths.
</P>
<P>
   While the major networks have steadily cut back on their
coverage, the conventions will still each attract upwards of 15,000
traditional media personnel from some 1,500 news outlets. They
include 440 newspapers, 330 television stations, 220 radio stations
and 190 magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the major Internet outlets that have joined them in
depth on the 2000 political scene will seek to create a ``brand''
presence for future years, much as the networks once jockeyed at
these quadrennial affairs to forge a dominant position among
viewers for their overall news programming.
</P>
<P>
   Fledgling broadcast Internet sites will share facilities with
their venerable network relatives. In many cases, they will be
double-teaming coverage, offering viewers their choice of watching
either TV sets or computer monitors.
</P>
<P>
   Some network reporters will roam the convention floor with
compact digital video cameras. When a story or a hot interview pops
up, it will be uploaded at once to a cooperating Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, which lacks a direct cable affilianvention.com) and its
Democratic counterpart in Los Angeles (dems2000.com) have both been
designed as abundant multimedia digital products with lots of
interactive features as well as video and audio clips from the
presidential candidates and other party stalwarts.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have used their Web site to give ``netizens'' a chance
to help craft the party platform, while Republicans are pushing
what they call a chance to become a ``virtual dot-com delegate.''
</P>
<P>
   During the four-day conclave, GOP registrants are promised
exclusive access to chat rooms with ``key convention
participants,'' tailored news from their state delegations, and
reports on the areas of interest that they had chosen in entering
their ``basic contact information.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Republican National Committee chairman Jim Nicholson:
``Innovations like these will establish a new standard for all
future conventio
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-11-00 1106EDT &QL;
</P>
