<SLUG> BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SEARCHERS COME UP EMPTY IN HUNT FOR MISSING ATHEIST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ For the third time since April 1999, federal
agents searched a remote Texas Hill Country site for the remains of
vanished atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair and two of her children. And
for the third time, they came up empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They completed their search around noon today and did not find
the remains of the O'Hairs,'' said FBI spokesman Darren Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were acting on newly acquired information, looking at the
same campground but in a different area than we did on previous
trips,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes said the latest search began around 8 a.m. Tuesday and
involved about 15 people from state and federal agencies and four
cadaver dogs.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair, her son Jon Garth Murray and daughter Robin Murray
O'Hair vanished from San Antonio in late 1995 along with $500,000
in gold coins.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities believe they were kidnapped and murdered for
the coins, and later were dismembered and possibly buried at the
site near Camp Wood.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Karr, 52, was convicted last month of four federal counts
relating to the O'Hair disappearance. Last year, Karr gave police a
map of the site purporting to show where the bodies were buried.
David Waters, another suspect, has not been charged in the case but
is serving two long prison sentences for other crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Two earlier searches at the Real County ranch, one involving
nearly 100 agents backed by cadaver dogs and sophisticated
detection equipment, also were futile.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear what new information the FBI might have.
</P>
<P>
   Karr's lawyer, Thomas Mills, said he was surprised by the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't come from us. My client has had no communication
with
</P>
<P>
   them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Karr is to be sentenced Aug. 4 in Austin and faces a mandatory
life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
