</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-SKILLS-AUCTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET AUCTION BRINGING TOP PAY, PERKS TO INDEPENDENT CONTRACTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DIANE E. LEWIS   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a employment agency denied her request for more flexible
hours, Lisa Williams sought a marketing job on an Internet site
that offered to auction her skills to the highest bidder. Days
later, the 33-year-old Web marketing professional walked away with
a $35-an-hour contracting job, $10 an hour more than she had been
making. And she was able to telecommute.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was with the agency, a lot of the companies were
insisting that I work 8 a.m. to 6 p.m., but I wasn't making as much
and I had a long commute,'' said Williams, of Hood River, Ore. ``I
was a divorced mother of three who was just starting out (in the
labor market) and didn't have the networks to find my own jobs. The
auction put me in contact with employers I would have never met.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' annual earnings have increased, too, from $30,000
three years ago to about $100,000 including overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a year after 16 Internet engineers tried to auction their
services on eBay for $3.14 million, the concept has been
transformed from an online spoof by a bunch of geeks to real-live
marketplaces for independent contractors seeking to sell their
skills for the right pay or perks.
</P>
<P>
   Internet talent or skills auctions have entered the market with
a flourish, vying with job sites, Internet resume sites,
traditional advertisers, and brick-and-mortar recruiters for
freelancers. Some of the most recent players in what is fast
becoming a saturated field: eLancer.com; Monster.com; Advoco.com;
Bid4Geeks.com, an auction site for technical professionals; and
HotDispatch.com, for finding techies here and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 30 percent of the nation's 130 million work force are
nonstandard workers, a category that includes temporary workers,
on-call workers, day laborers, independent contractors, leased
workers, and the self-employed _ in short, all individuals who do
not have a regular, ongoing tie to an employer. Of those, 6.4
percent are independent contractors, according to economist Edie
Rasell of the Economic Policy Institute, a policy research
organization in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Rasell says there has been a fourfold increase in temporary help
agency workers since 1982. And, although government statistics do
not go back far enough to fully trace the trend, she believes the
number of other nonstandard workers has increased, too.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, the number of temporary help agencies
increased to 1,405 in 1998 from 431 in 1980. At the same time, the
number of people employed by these companies rose to 71,365 from
25,473, according to a report by the Campaign on Contingent Work, a
coalition of unions and community groups.
</P>
<P>
   For employers, the growth in the nation's nonstandard work force
has been a boon, assuring companies of a readily available pool of
flexible employees who can work on demand. For employees, however,
the trend is a double-edged sword: While high-tech and computer
professionals often command top salaries and perks, other
freelancers must scramble for work in a market where the next
paycheck is hardly guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Monster.com and other companies hoping to capitalize on
the rising friction between freelancers and the middlemen who
market their services, by creating sites that permit the freelancer
to set his own terms. They envision a day when nonstandard workers
of all kinds will control how and where they work by simply logging
on to a computer and tapping yes, or no, to an offer.
</P>
<P>
   Monster.com's TalentMarket auction works like this: Freelancers
submit profiles as well as pay and other requirements. They specify
the duration of the job they are seeking. Employers, meanwhile, can
list projects for which contractors are needed. If the employer
hires a freelancer after placing a bid, the employer pays a fee to
Monster.com. The fee is determined by the size of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, people do not need an intermediary anymore,'' said
Linda Natansohn, senior vice president of ventures at Maynard,
Mass.-based Monster.com. ``If free agents can negotiate directly
with employers, more will go directly into their pockets than if
they go to a staffing firm that marks up wages 30 percent and then
keeps a good portion of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Marion McGovern, president of MSquared, a California-based
executive recruiting firm, bridled at the thought.
</P>
<P>
   She maintains that agencies specializing in brokering the
talents of corporate executives and highly sought-after technical
professionals tend to work with employers less likely to take a
chance on an auction, where the talent they get might not be the
talent they want or actually need.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look for the cream of the crop. We do a verification
process. People who are looking for true value still want expert
appraisers who can sell that Renoir for them,'' said McGovern, who
likened the executive recruiters' screening process to a critical
appraisal at Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we use the online world to come up with consultants
for clients,'' she acknowledged, ``but it certainly is not the
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Three months after launching Web magazine Gate39 in September
1999, publisher Shane Stiles of Chicago turned to an auction site
called eLancer.com for freelance writers who were knowledgeable
about Japanese customs and culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the conditions of my bid was that the writer could
write about Japan,'' said Stiles, who hired three writers last
year. ``Last month, I chose five writers out of a pool of 15. I put
in an initial bid of $25 for each short article, plus any banner
ads they wanted to put on the site. That allows them to advertise
themselves.'' He concedes the pay was quite low, but ``through our
Web site, people have been able to funnel traffic to their own
personal Web sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the hoopla about talent auctions, observers say
there have been fewer placements than originally anticipated.
Visits to 30 randomly selected auction sites last week supported
that. On each site, free agent computer professionals and
architectural engineers had specified bid pay rates ranging from
$30 per hour to $60 per hour over the last few weeks. In each case,
no offers had been made by employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``With an auction, you could ask for $1,000 per day, but you
really have to go with whatever people are willing to bid on you,''
said Wayne Cooper, president of New Hampshire-based Kennedy
Information, publisher of the Recruiting Trends newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The auctions started with a lot of fanfare last year, but
there are not a whole lot of placements,'' he said. ``If you go to
these services you will find that a high percentage of the job
listings are actually coming from brick-and-mortar recruiting
companies. So the Web is also making it easier for some of the
middlemen by automating the matchup.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, workplace experts say the trend could bode well
for independent contractors and the self-employed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably a small step in the right direction for these
people,'' said Louis Maltby, president of the National Work Rights
Institute in Princeton, N.J. ``When you can get offers from several
employers, you have bargaining leverage. And that means more
negotiating room.''
</P>
<P>
   Mimi Nishioka can attest to that. Nishioka, 24, of Baltimore,
does niche and target marketing for Web sites and then tracks the
results of the ads she places.
</P>
<P>
   Nishioka, who identified herself on Monster.com's TalentMarket
as ``Mimi the Advertising Queen,'' says she landed a contract job
as director of marketing for picSmart in Washington, D.C., after
posting her profile. She also has a full-time job at an advertising
agency in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning I received bids, but I haven't had any
more,'' she said. ``I think it's gotten really saturated. When
Monster first launched, there was a curiosity factor that caused
interest to go up. Now there are five or six other services that do
the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Monster.com says it has more than 200,000 ``free agents''
registered with the site. They range from IT professionals and
engineers to creative artists and salespeople. Most are new to
freelancing, but some have been consulting for years.
</P>
<P>
   Since she began using a talent auction a year ago, Williams, the
Web marketer from Oregon, has accepted five bids, including one
that led to a six-month job with a Utah company whose
representatives never met her in person.
</P>
<P>
   Williams landed her latest position in March after a
Boston-based human resources manager for Avery Dennison spotted her
profile on Monster.com's TalentMarket auction. Her contract with
Avery Dennison has since been extended to April 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started thinking about doing my own thing, I called an
agency and told them my requirements,'' recalled Williams. ``It
said, `Your requirements are not our concern. Our concern is with
the employer and no employer is going to want to give you the
flexibility you want.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The agency was wrong. After posting my profile, I had calls
from some pretty big firms, and they were completely open to
telecommuting and flexible hours.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
