<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-AOL-MEXICO12-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    AOL, STRUGGLING ABROAD, LAUNCHES SERVICE IN MEXICO
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ America Online Inc. began offering Internet access
service in Mexico ON Tuesday, hoping to boost its lagging
subscriber base in Latin America while expanding its ranks of
Spanish-speaking U.S. customers.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said AOL needs a ``win'' in Mexico to show investors it
can get people in poorer countries to pay monthly fees for online
services, even as other companies offer free Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``All eyes are on them,'' said Will Landers, director of Latin
American technology research for Credit Suisse First Boston.
Analysts question whether AOL can succeed south of the U.S. border
because the company is ``very much tied to the subscription model.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Vienna, Va.-based online giant launched AOL
Brazil. But ``the rollout in Brazil was slower than what the market
expected,'' Landers said. Today, AOL is still running a distant
fourth among Internet providers in the Portuguese-speaking country,
in part because many Brazilians are getting free Internet access
from companies that rely solely on advertising for revenue.
</P>
<P>
   AOL Mexico plans to offer a 90-day free trial period, compared
with one free month in the United States. Mexican customers getting
unlimited access will be billed in pesos and will pay about $22 a
month, the same rate as U.S. customers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the price, some analysts believe AOL's emphasis on
``home grown'' content and child-friendly monitoring services may
attract paying customers. ``They're aiming at Mexican families,''
said Gabriel Moreno, a high-tech industry analyst for the
International Data Corp. research firm in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Because AOL offers subscribers seven user names under one
account, it opens up access to a whole family. ``Everyone can have
their own log-in and password, so parents can't read their
children's e-mail,'' Moreno said. ``But they can control what their
children look at.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL is the world's largest online service, with more than 23
million subscribers. But while the company has been phenomenally
successful in the United States, only a fraction of subscribers
lives abroad.
</P>
<P>
   After years of branching out into Europe, Asia and Latin
America, AOL is still seeing mixed results. In some European
countries, AOL dominates as an Internet access provider. But it has
done poorly in Japan, Australia and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is the poorest country where AOL has offered service.
Despite a population of roughly 100 million, only about 1.5 million
Mexicans have Internet accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Latin America is the fastest-growing Internet market in
the world. Analysts estimate that region's the number of users will
shoot from 8.5 million today to 29.4 million by 2003, according to
International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish-language content of AOL Mexico will be available at
no increased cost to U.S.-based AOL subscribers, which means
Mexican-born residents in this country will have access to content
produced by 70 AOL staffers in Mexico City, spokeswoman Tricia
Primrose said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the number of Spanish-speaking people in the United
States, this will be an exciting development here, too,'' Primrose
said.
</P>
<P>
   AOL Mexico will be operated as part of a joint venture with the
Cisneros Group, a Venezuelan media company that produces popular
soap operas and owns Univision, the largest Spanish-language
television network in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   AOL Mexico's competitors include Telefonos de Mexico (TelMex),
Spain's Terra Networks SA and Starmedia Network Inc.
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Mexico correspondent Susan Ferriss contributed to this
article.)
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
