 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Calling all techies
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Remember ``Walkie Talkies,'' those flimsy kids' toys that banged
around the backyard or weighed down the belts of park rangers and
security guards? Well they're back, slimmed down and tricked out
for the go-anywhere, do-anything age. Motorola's palm-sized,
lightweight TalkAbout Two-Way Radio ($160; www.motorola.com) with a
NiMH rechargeable battery, offers a solid two-mile communication
range that works in or outdoors. The radio is ideal for trade show
teams scouring the show floors, family members on camping trips,
even for the college convoy on that road trip to the annual kegger
off the beaten path. Utilizing the 14 channels of FRS (Family Radio
Service) _ as opposed to the inconsistent CB (Citizen's Band) _
these units offer high-powered, short-range communication of
professional caliber. With 38 subchannels per channel on which to
stake a claim, the airwaves promise to be traffic-free somewhere
within the allotted range. Best of all, the TalkAbout is inherently
compatible with any FRS radio, meaning it's easy to augment
Motorola's high-end units with less expensive models from any
brand.
</P>
<P>
   A LOGICAL CASE FOR A CD PLAYER AND ACCESSORIES
</P>
<P>
   A combination of elastic strapping, Velcro, a zipper, a clip and
wee bit of nylon makes Case Logic's CD Player TranSport ($10;
www.casedirect.com) the epitome of less-is-more functionality. This
innovative portable CD companion piece allows one's diminutive disc
spinner to assertively attach to a bicycle, backpack, belt,
treadmill or what have you while still allowing easy access to the
player's buttons. There's even an accessory pocket for spare
batteries, locker key, photos and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
