</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-GAMER0711-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Screenshot for Shogun: Total War from totalwar.com
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   We've written a lot about Tony Hawk Pro Skater with good reason
_ it took the world by storm in 1999 as the best skateboard game
ever. Previously available on the Sony PlayStation and the Nintendo
64, the super thrasher has come to Sega with a Dreamcast version
($50; www. dreamcast.com; for the Dreamcast). It might very well be
the best all-around video game, ever. Extending an elemental law of
physics to include ``what goes up must pull off a Varial before it
comes down,'' Tony Hawk Pro Skater brings all the superlative
joyousness and raunchy implied pain of real life skating to video
game land with a large arsenal of tricks and stunts as well as
vivid skull smacks and magnificent blood spurts should one crash
and bail aggressively. Super console graphics and sound heighten
what was already -- cringingly painful looking game on the
PlayStation and a fluffy, bloodless extravaganza on the
family-friendly N64. This is by far the best version yet.
</P>
<P>
   While it's extremely rare to see an original video game concept
in an industry more famous for its peel, steal and market-like-hell
m.o., unique games have been known to pop up now and again. Sega's
Space Channel 5 ($40; www.sega.com; for the Dreamcast) is one such
game, but that's where the righteousness ends. ``Space'' is a
bizarre, damn-near-creepy disco dancing game featuring scantily
clad nymphs and groovy dudes hypnotizing and defeating foes by
mimicking perky, alluring dance steps to the beat of retro-techno
funk. It's got all the charm of the lingerie section of your mom's
Sears catalogue and a Dr. Rhythm drum machine. Rife with clunky
gameplay reminiscent of the electronic toy version of ``Simon,''
this title targets a ``broader'' demographic; actual video game
buffs need not bother. Kudos for trying, though. The next Sears
Catalogue is due out this fall.
</P>
<P>
   If you've played Gauntlet Legends at the arcade, you know how
addictive the game can be. With multiple players going on a hack
and slash quest (here's a wizard, an archer and a barbarian,
slicing through orcs and looking for treasure chests), it was
quarter-plunking video game nirvana. After a blurry two-player-only
PlayStation version and a blotchy-looking translation for Nintendo
64, it took the hardware muscle of the Sega Dreamcast to unleash
the definitive home version. Gauntlet Legends for Dreamcast ($40;
www.midway.com; for the Dreamcast) is pixel-perfect, gorgeous,
fast, and fun. The game is as sharp as the arcade, with four-player
mode, 41 levels and characters taken from the new ``Gauntlet Dark
Legacy'' arcade game. It's one of the most fun cooperative games
out. You can also get free pewter figures in the mail from Midway
after buying the game. So the only question is, if you don't
already have a Dreamcast to enjoy the raft of great games available
for the system (I loved Space Channel 5, by the way), what's
stopping you? The Playstation 2? Happy waiting.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   When you join the thick of battle in Shogun: Total War ($40;
www.totalwar.com; for Windows), it's hard to keep phrases like
''instant classic'' and ''sets a new standard'' from the back of
your mind. This simulation of 15th-century feudal Japanese warfare
has captured the Grail of PC gaming with its immersive 3-D
horizon-to-horizon battles, lovingly detailed from the glint of
sunlight on distant spears to the horror of watching your
1,000-samurai army break and run. Amid these riches, any complaints
_ the skimpy mapless manual comes to mind _ are mere quibbles. For
thinkers who savor strategy, an engaging but optional turn-based,
''Risk''-style campaign game with cinematics provides
empire-building intrigue and context. But the real rush is on the
battlefield. Blizzards howl, lightning strikes and the crackle of
muskets produces a line of drifting smoke amid the gabble and
clatter of pitched fighting. An eight-multiplayer option rounds out
this little masterpiece. Shogun: Total War is a detailed, endlessly
replayable, smooth-running depiction of the earnest struggle for
control of an empire. We've been waiting for this great game all
along and just didn't know it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
