<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-CENTERPIECE0711-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Don't be afraid to buy online; take precautions _ and never use a
debit card 
 &HT;    By Mary Jo DiLonardo
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For some people, shopping online is akin to handing
their credit card to a shifty-looking stranger and inviting him to
have at it.
</P>
<P>
   It's scary, stupid and they're just not going to do it.
</P>
<P>
   While experts say you should take precautions when delving into
the wonderful world of e-commerce, they also agree it's often no
more risky than buying something the old-fashioned way.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are all concerned about Internet security think
nothing about giving their credit card to a waiter who disappears
with it into the back room for 10 minutes,'' says computer author
Mark Minasi, whose most recent book is ``The Software Conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The old advice that we got from our grandfathers _ don't use
credit cards, period _ doesn't really apply in this day and age,''
says Rob Clyde, vice president of security management for Axent
Technologies, a Rockville, Md.-based information security firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you use a true credit card number, not a debit card number,
you're already pretty protected by Visa or MasterCard or American
Express, so your liability is $50 maximum. That already leaves you
at a starting point where you don't have to be all that worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Which doesn't mean don't worry at all. There are some important
measures you should take before keying in that long list of numbers
and expiration date.
</P>
<P>
   First, be sure to use a credit card, not a debit card, when
shopping online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Debit cards are much more risky than are conventional credit
cards. You should never, ever use a debit card on the Web,''
cautions George Hellyer, senior consultant for Janus Associates, a
Stamford, Conn.-based firm that specializes in information
security.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone gets your debit card number, they can drain all
your bank accounts. With a credit card, you're protected after the
first $50 of fraudulent use. You are not guaranteed that protection
if you use your debit card. All your savings can be wiped out. It's
a very frightening thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Next, credit card in hand, be sure you shop only on secure
connections. That's where sites use encryption, which basically
scrambles the information as it goes careening around the Internet.
In order to confirm the site is safe, look for that little padlock
on the bottom of your browser. If it's locked, the site is secure.
If it's open, all bets are off. You can also configure your browser
to offer a prompt that alerts you to the fact that you are entering
a secure connection.
</P>
<P>
   Advises Minasi: ``If the lock's not there, don't send the credit
card, period. That's just too easy to steal.''
</P>
<P>
   There are various levels of encryption a site can offer _
usually ranging from 56 bits to 128 bits. The higher the number,
the better. But don't lose sleep over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically what you want to see is over 96 or 128 bits,'' says
Clyde. ``But if it's a legitimate company, 56 is OK. It's important
to put the risk in the proper context. If it's a company you'd do
business with over the phone, it's probably safe to do business
over the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're concerned, you can update your browser to a higher
level of encryption. But even if you're using 128, a site could
still be encrypting at 56, says Minasi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does this mean you should worry? At 56, the chance would still
be one in one with about 19 zeroes after it,'' he says, laughing.
``I don't know of any significant credit card fraud on the Internet
involving people punching in credit cards on secure sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it's not always easy to find out at what level a
company is encrypting. Sometimes it's in the privacy statement.
Often, you have to send an e-mail asking at what level the company
encrypts.
</P>
<P>
   Still worried? You can configure your browser to accept only
sites with 128-bit encryption, so lower-level sites won't even be
accessible. That'll show 'em!
</P>
<P>
   Besides the secure connection, there are other things to
consider before.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't rely on a professional-looking Web site as proof
that it's a reliable company,'' warns Holly Cherico, spokeswoman
for the Council of Better Business Bureaus, the umbrella
organization for the nation's 132 Better Business Bureaus.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have the skill, you can make a very sophisticated Web
site look like it's backed by a Fortune 500 company.''
</P>
<P>
   If it's a well-known site _ like amazon.com _ or a company with
a reputable physical presence _ like Sears _ your worries should be
few.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 1, know who you are buying from,'' advises Hellyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's someplace you've never heard of, try to find more
information. Do a search to see what you can find. Ask for
references. If someone is going to install windows for you or
aluminum siding, you ask for references, so it's the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, be sure there's a way to contact the company offline with
a listed phone number or address. If the only way you can reach the
company is via e-mail and the company disappears, you have no other
way of trying to track it down.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've trusted a site with your credit card data, question
what they are going to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of companies store credit card information, which
troubles me,'' admits Minasi. ``AOL keeps your credit card number
on file even if you get rid of the service. There are only 5
million people who work for that company. I'm sure no one would
think about stealing that information!''
</P>
<P>
   Some companies give you the option to let them keep your credit
card info to save the hassle next time you shop. You'll get a
prompt along the lines of, ``Would you like us to remember this
credit card so you don't have to enter it again later?'' Then the
choice is yours.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK AT PRIVACY STATEMENT
</P>
<P>
   To find if the company stores your credit card information,
check the privacy statement. If there is no privacy statement, just
flat-out don't do business with the company, Minasi says. If they
store the information without giving you a choice, take action, he
advises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Send them a politely worded e-mail saying, `Give me the choice
like other vendors do,' '' he says. ``Don't just walk away. Tell
them it's an inappropriate lack of protection of your privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if you trust the company name and are using a secure
connection, limit the information you are willing to provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never provide your Social Security number or date of birth
over the Internet,'' says Hellyer. ``If they have your name, your
date of birth and your Social Security number, they can counterfeit
your identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the best of intentions, a company just has no business
having that information, says Shirley Rooker, president of Call For
Action, a nonprofit consumer helpline based in Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're doing a transaction online, that company has no
right to ask you for your Social Security number, your mother's
maiden name, any information like that,'' she says. ``If they're
asking you all that information, they're collecting it for some
reason, and you just shouldn't give it. That's a sure sign you
should go someplace else.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, click on the privacy statement for more information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does the company post a privacy policy about how it's going to
use the information it collects about you?'' questions Rooker.
``Are they going to share it with a third party and, if so, how do
you feel about it?''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes when you type in information on a Web site _ most
often a password _ asterisks pop up on your screen instead of the
letters or numbers you are typing. Don't be lulled into believing
this is encryption. The company is merely protecting your privacy
from someone who may be looking at your screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``That only protects you from people peeking over your shoulder
while you're typing,'' says Minasi. ``It doesn't save you from
people on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   REPORTING FRAUD ON THE NET
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the National Consumers League reported a 38 percent
increase in the number of e-complaints, with more than 10,000
reported. Here's where you can go if you think you've been had:
</P>
<P>
   Better Business Bureau, www.bbb.org _ In addition to awarding
more than 5,000 sites the BBB Reliability Seal online, the consumer
organization has bestowed its Privacy Seal on more than 50 sites.
You can search those vendors and also report e-commerce problems
online at the BBB's site.
</P>
<P>
   Call For Action, www.callforaction.org _ This nonprofit consumer
advocacy group allows you to report problems and helps you solve
them. You can also call locally 678-422-8466.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet Fraud Complaint Center, www.ifccfbi.gov/ _ This is
a partnership between the FBI and the National White Collar Crime
Center through which consumers can report suspected cases of
e-fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
