<HEADER>
A0134 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-LARRYKING-TWOFER-TEX     07-12 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LARRYKING-TWOFER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHOREHOUSE' AND `DEAD PRESIDENTS' CLUB' GET SIMULTANEOUS FORT
WORTH RUNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ In his wilder days, a double for Texas
author/playwright/actor Larry L. King involved whiskey. But this
month in downtown Fort Worth, the relatively clean-living King
achieves a truly rare double in the theater. Two of his plays,
``The Best Little Whorehouse in Texas'' and ``The Dead Presidents'
Club,'' will be presented simultaneously at Bass Performance Hall
and Circle Theatre, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a first, at least for me,'' King said by phone from
his home in Washington, D.C. ``It just sort of occurred, but I'm
pleased it did. I'm coming down with my wife and two children to
see both of them. I guess if you last long enough, things like this
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whorehouse,'' a Broadway smash in the '70s that Casa Manana is
staging July 11-23 at Bass Hall, is King's best-known work.
</P>
<P>
   ``That includes plays, books, everything,'' King said. ``
`Whorehouse' is in its 22nd year, and it's about to go out on a
national tour that will last three years more. I suspect it will
always be the thing I was involved with that most people remember
me for.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whorehouse,'' which became a 1982 movie starring Burt Reynolds
and Dolly Parton, celebrates a real-life house of ill repute in La
Grange, Texas. The musical is known for lavish production numbers
and larger-than-life characters.
</P>
<P>
   The latter element is also present in King's ``The Dead
Presidents' Club,'' which will run at Circle Theatre from July
19-Aug. 26. But, in the case of this new play, characters even more
controversial than prostitutes are on stage: presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say that of all my plays _ `Whorehouse,' `The Night
Hank Williams Died,' `The Golden Shadows Old West Museum,' `The
Kingfish' _ `The Dead Presidents' Club' is the one I derive the
most satisfaction from,'' King said. ``I've always been a political
animal, ever since I was 9 years old and making stump speeches in
West Texas for a candidate named Arch Bint _ who won, by the way. I
worked in Congress for 10 years, mostly for (former House Speaker)
Jim Wright, and I saw politicians, including presidents, pretty
close up.''
</P>
<P>
   King says he first thought of ``The Dead Presidents' Club'' in
1989, ``while I was acting in `The Night Hank Williams Died.'
Darren McGavin had been the lead, but he couldn't remember his
lines. I replaced him for several weeks. So I was sitting backstage
one night and started wondering, `What play am I going to write
next?' and decided I would try first to think of the most
fascinating person I had ever met. Then the play could be about
him.''
</P>
<P>
   King decided that Lyndon B. Johnson fit the bill, ``but Nixon
did, too. So I thought, `Why not pair them up? The afterlife! OK,
what would they be doing there? ... They'd pretend to have an
alliance, but would just be waiting to (betray) each other.''
</P>
<P>
   King began writing the play in 1994, adding former Presidents
Calvin Coolidge and Harry S. Truman to the cast, along with God.
``Coolidge and God are the two I haven't met, at least yet,'' he
says of the characters.
</P>
<P>
   A first reading of the play was staged in 1995 at Southwest
Texas State University in San Marcos, Texas, the alma mater of
Lyndon Johnson, and a full production was staged in Austin in 1997.
Then, dogged by its political subject matter and the difficulties
inherent in casting such well-known characters, it more or less
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Despite good audience and critical reaction to ``Dead
Presidents','' King said: ``I've had trouble getting it produced.
But I hope it will catch on, because it is funny and has something
to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose Pearson, executive director of Circle Theatre, said King
and area producer Sharon Benge urged her to read the ``Dead
Presidents'' script.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd done `The Night Hank Williams Died' and `The Golden
Shadows Old West Museum,' '' Pearson said. ``So we read the script
and thought it was hysterical. It fit perfectly into our 1999-2000
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the overlap between Circle Theatre's ``Dead
Presidents''' and Casa Manana's ``Best Little Whorehouse,'' Pearson
said she doesn't think either production will lessen ticket sales
for the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theater feeds on theater,'' Pearson said. ``While `Whorehouse'
is better known, it may also steer some new audience in our
direction.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
