A0135 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-GOSPEL-COX     07-12 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOSPEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stirring gospel music just doesn't just roll off in the street
 &HT;    By Khalid Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - Although their followers and target audiences
don't always mingle, urban gospel, contemporary Christian and
Southern hymnal music all serve the same purpose: to uplift the
listener (and the performer) to a rarefied plateau of spiritual
awareness so the message of a higher power can sink in.
</P>
<P>
   But stirring spiritual music doesn't just roll in off the
street. It has to be carried in on the voices of talented artists
who have the ability to anoint as well as entertain. The Miami
Valley is blessed with a rich vein of gospel performers who,
regrettably, don't get the exposure they deserve. Thankfully, a
handful of these performers _ along with a splash of national and
regional artists _ will have the chance to showcase their talents
this weekend at three gospel extravaganzas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Visions of Faith'' is an inspirational talent show that takes
place Saturday at Memorial Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The program is the brainchild of a Cincinnati native,
24-year-old Isaiah Lowry, president of the sponsoring organization,
Visions of Faith entertainment agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are an entertainment company trying to bring wholesome
entertainment to the Dayton area,'' he said from his Centerville
office. ``We had our first successful talent show in May of 1999 at
Memorial Hall and drew about a thousand people. At this year's
showcase we have solicited talent from Lima, Columbus, Dayton and
Cincinnati along with our national guest artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Karen Clark-Sheard headlines the show. Before Sheard
went solo, she was a member of the award-winning contemporary
gospel trio, the Clark Sisters. Last year, Sheard's debut album,
``Finally Karen,'' was nominated for a Grammy in the category of
Best Contemporary Soul Gospel Album. Also appearing will be Charles
Fold, New Harvest, Robert Skinner, spiritual poet Dorothy La'Velle
and local singers and dancers who will compete for cash prizes.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th annual Gospel Days by the Mad River unfolds Saturday
and Sunday at Eastwood Metropark, Ohio 4 and Harshman Road. This
mammoth gospel blowout, sponsored by Five Rivers MetroParks and the
Coming Together community event groupd, features food, crafts, a
car show and gospel acts covering styles associated with bluegrass,
Southern gospel and their more urbanized cousin, contemporary
Christian music.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Shiveley is founder and president of Coming Together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our festivities start at noon each day and go until it gets
dark,'' Shiveley said. ``We'll have three stages, maybe four. We're
still working on the last one, but basically the stages will
feature bluegrass, contemporary and Southern gospel music. We also
will have a youth area set up for the tots.''
</P>
<P>
   Shiveley said it takes about a year of planning to bring the
festival together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a whole lot of meetings,'' he said. ``At our meetings
we decide what groups to bring in and how many stages we need. We
use mostly local groups but we try to bring in many full-time
groups, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing will be Crimson River, Dumplin Valley Boys, The
Freemans, Zionheirs, Graceway Quartet, The Hall Family, Roarks,
Forgiven, Leta Stroud, Royalty and the Kings Road Quartet.
</P>
<P>
   The contemporary stage will feature the music of Spark, 50,000
Hub Caps, Featherweight, Blind Man Walking, Mindset, Herman's Drew
and Top Flight.
</P>
<P>
   Blankets and lawn chairs are welcome, alcoholic beverages are
not.
</P>
<P>
   And Vandalia Baptist Temple will be the host for a gospel
concert to benefit the Franklin Baptist Church Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
   On April 12, Franklin Baptist Church was destroyed by fire.
Since then, Franklin's pastor, Dale Chambers, and his congregation
have been rebuilding their spiritual home. The Rev. Troy Todd,
leader of Vandalia Baptist Temple, said the concert is a gesture of
fellowship, friendship and support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rev. Chambers and I have been the closest of friends for 32
years,'' Todd said. ``This benefit is a helping hand from a
congregation who cares deeply about them. We know it (the fire) was
a low blow, but we've got a couple of singing groups in our church
and we kno
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
