<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0139 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-ST-PETERSBURG-DEVELOP     07-12 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ST-PETERSBURG-DEVELOP-1,070(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE LEVITTOWN ON THE NEVA 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN VAROLI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ Several homeowners, cell phones at
hand, tend their lawns and gardens. Others are firing up a barbecue
in the backyard, while on the street children ride mountain bikes
or skate by on Rollerblades. Two little girls talk about going with
their mothers to get a bite to eat at McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   It could be Pleasantville, but the pork shish kebab on the
grill, cooked faithfully every weekend instead of hamburgers, is
just one sign that it probably is not. This is Kolomyaga, a
condominium development on the fringes of St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   The sight of four tidy rows of eight town houses, aligned in a
square, has shaken this previously poor village, but not because it
is luxurious. Neighboring brick mansions, with Mercedes-Benzes
parked out front, have already numbed local residents to displays
of wealth.
</P>
<P>
   What is turning heads at Kolomyaga is the novelty of
American-style suburban architecture transplanted onto Russian
soil. The signs are small but telling. Lawns neatly manicured where
they used to run wild. A 5-foot security fence and guards to keep
out the riffraff. Volleyball areas for children. Aluminum siding on
the houses. Fords in the driveway. And fast food is a mere
10-minute drive.
</P>
<P>
   No one is saying that St. Petersburg has solved its decades-old
housing problem. Most of the city's 5 million inhabitants still
live in prefab high-rises, a Soviet-era legacy, in which three
generations in a tiny apartment is not uncommon. By the 1990s, the
few with money built year-round country mansions. But beyond the
country house and city apartment, a third way is emerging _ the
small family house _ with some things lost and some gained.
</P>
<P>
   As the American suburban dream infiltrates Russia's second
largest city, it is giving added legitimacy and visibility to
Russia's version of the middle-class homeowner. There is even a new
Russian word for condo: Town khaus.
</P>
<P>
   Entrepreneurs and small-business owners, mainly couples in their
30s with small children, the town khausers of Kolomyaga are well
enough off to choose a new $75,000 condo 20 minutes from downtown.
(A nice city apartment costs no less than $50,000, with $20,000
more in renovations.)
</P>
<P>
   ``These condo residents want their house to be their castle, so
they can retreat away from the rest of the world,'' said Viktoriya
Ukhalova, a St. Petersburg architect and interior designer. ``This
is a reaction to decades of forced communal living. Now people have
a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the two-story houses, there is little that impresses. The
goal is basic comfort and function: Kitchen, office, master
bedroom, two bedrooms for the kids and a living room. The big
change is adjusting to country living. Though living rooms are
large, residents still entertain their guests in the kitchen, an
ancient habit of peasant origins, when the warm kitchen was the
most hospitable room during the long, cold Russian winters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must tend the yard, and there are added travel costs,''
said Vasily Ryzhkov, 32, who owns a dental clinic downtown. ``But
it is worth it to live in the fresh air and have your own house.''
</P>
<P>
   As pleasant as life can be outside the inner city, Russian
suburbs have disadvantages. They lack good schools or stores
nearby. Life is still rustic, and the city remains the sole source
of civilized amenities.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kolomyaga residents relish being able to retreat into
their spacious homes, some 1,500 square feet of living space on
three floors. Each unit has a small yard in front and back, and
wives groom their tiny plots, something rare in Russia, where yards
tend to be weedy or dedicated to growing food.
</P>
<P>
   While necessity forces women to work, some successful Russian
businessman regard a working wife as an insult to their
masculinity. ``Here my wife sits home with the children, can sit in
the yard or walk around the area, and is not cooped up,'' Ryzhkov
said proudly.
</P>
<P>
   The emerging professional class, with leisure to tend gardens
has even led to the appearance of a retail outlet called Maxidom,
Russia's answer to Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Suburban settlements began in Moscow about five years ago, but
they are just starting to sprout in St. Petersburg. Kolomyaga was
conceived in 1997 by Vladimir Lubomirov, and the first families
moved in a year ago. Lubomirov, 32, who was raised in St.
Petersburg, built his first family home (for a Finnish buyer) in
1991 while still studying for a master's degree in physics.
Kolomyaga is his first large-scale project.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are surprised there are such nice suburban
housing complexes, and here just within the city limits,''
Lubomirov said, giving a tour of the complex one sunny weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers slow down to gawk. Some people remark that the aluminum
siding, banned by zoning laws until a few years ago, makes the
houses look fake, like a toy village. Indeed, the contrast between
old and new is surreal. Across the street from the complex stands a
row of dilapidated wooden shanties, built just after World War II,
yards overgrown with bushes and trees.
</P>
<P>
   Farther down the road are two new brick mansions, viewed by many
as emblems of capitalism's criminal element. Looking like medieval
keeps but oddly known as kottedzhi, or cottages, they are
surrounded by 8-foot brick walls.
</P>
<P>
   Change and progress have always been painful in Russia, and old
and new sometimes have trouble coexisting, even at Kolomyaga.
Symbolic of the conflict is a 50-year-old village house, in
relatively good condition, inhabited by a couple in their late 50s.
It, and they, stand in the way of completing a row of condos.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way my wife and I plan to give up our home in the
country, in this place, where she grew up and where I've lived for
the last 30 years,'' said one of the owners, who would give only
the name Igor. ``I don't have any ill feeling toward the new
neighbors, and I understand it's progress, but it's too bad that
what was once a real village is now disappearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Lubomirov's offer of a condo could not sway Igor, who said
there is something special about living in a primitive wooden
house. Indeed, sentimental fondness for the simple rustic life and
a desire to be close to nature run deep in the Russian soul, one
reason that urban Russians, even wealthy ones, retreat to their
dachas on weekends.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   As one indication of what has been lost in the transition from
village life to suburbia, Kolomyaga has not only a 5-foot metal
fence around its five acres but also two uniformed police officers,
who stand guard around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Russia, the law does not effectively defend private
property, and people do not respect the property of others,''
Lubomirov said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, there are no dens of vice that attract a bad element,''
said Dmitri Rakovshchik,'' a resident and vice president of a
Russian insurance company. ``Before, we lived in a nice apartment
in the city center, but our building entrance was filthy and
dangerous. Here, it's safer because in the center there are always
problems with vandals and hooligans.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryzhkov said, ``You can park your car in front of your house and
not worry it will be stolen.''
</P>
<P>
   At Kolomyaga, each household owns at least one car, compared
with Russia's national average of 20 percent of households. (Local
roads, dusty and cratered with gaping ditches, do a job on them,
however.)
</P>
<P>
   Living in a condo complex raises issues that hark back to Soviet
living, like communality. Most condo owners escaped from the city
to be masters of their own castles but are finding they must pull
together.
</P>
<P>
   General meetings are held when the need arises _ to collect
money for repairs or improvements _ but no one seems to mind
because they all have interests at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Though Kolomyaga's main selling points are space and security,
the condos are also marketed with a strong element of class
consciousness (middle class in the American understanding but rich
for Russia, where the average person lives on $50 to $100 a month.)
Most marketing was done through word of mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the pluses that attract buyers to our complex is that
we offer more social homogeneity,'' Lubomirov said. ``In Russia, it
is common for poor and rich to live in the same building. And this
is not always pleasant, for many reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is tempting to see such economic segregation as part of
a turn to American-style class divisions, it confirms Soviet habits
predating the mixed-income high-rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soviet housing was highly segregated, where the ruling elite
lived in large apartments in the best districts, while the masses
lived in communal apartments and prefab high-rises,'' said Lev
Savulkin, a senior analyst at the Leontieff Center for Social and
Economic Research here.
</P>
<P>
   The freedom of the last 10 years has allowed acquiring wealth to
become a personal affair, not tied to a ruling party. And now the
newly rich are banding together.
</P>
<P>
   Lubomirov, however, is careful to keep out those who are too
rich. ``No shaven heads'' _ meaning Russia's mafia elite _ he said.
He has strict face control at Kolomyaga.
</P>
<P>
   Today, demand for middle-of-the-road housing is growing faster
than supply, and he has bought and plans to level a half dozen
shanties, creating space for what he hopes will be 200 units and a
dozen houses in the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   Near Kolomyaga, are about six other such suburban settlements.
Indeed, the city government has set the area aside for condo
residences. ``The strong demand indicates how housing tastes, not
to mention income patterns, have changed over the last eight
years,'' said the developer, whose pony tail, soft voice and gaunt
features suggest a struggling artist more than a businessman.
</P>
<P>
   He seems to be right. Two miles from Kolomyaga, dozens of new
high-rises stand empty, while most condo complexes in the area fill
quickly. Yet as suburban as Kolomyaga may look, its 32
owner-residents have not totally adopted the American way of real
estate.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it is difficult to get a mortgage in Russia,
which means buyers make quarterly payments during construction to
pay off the purchase price before they move in.
</P>
<P>
   As the demand for suburban housing expands, local government is
responding with new programs. Moscow and St. Petersburg are both
beginning to offer mortgages, giving home buyers a chance to spread
housing costs over many years.
</P>
<P>
   St. Petersburg is going even further, saying it will provide
roads, sewer hookups and schools on some 1,300 acres of forest land
at the north end of the city, to be called Severnaya Dolina
(Northern Valley), so developers can build hundreds of condos and
houses. This will be the city's first large-scale suburban housing
development.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Valley is only on the drawing board. In a country given
to sudden financial crises like that in August 1998, which wiped
out an emerging middle class, it is too early to say that
American-style suburban living will become widespread in Russia.
Some habits and ways of behavior will never change, no matter how
affluent people become.
</P>
<P>
   Though Russians with money enjoy lavishing it on status symbols
like nice cars, they will cut costs on basics. ``It's funny how
people in the area, even those with money, are too cheap to pay for
garbage removal,'' Lubomirov exclaimed with exasperation. ``So,
what do they do? They load up their Mercedes or Fords with their
garbage and haul it off to a dumpster in one of the nearby pre-fab,
housing projects.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``In some ways, Russians will probably never change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
