<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0143 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-HEALTH-SAFETY13-COX     07-12 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-SAFETY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOME HEALTH CARE SAFETY EFFORTS OUTPACE FEDERAL RULE MAKERS
 &HT;    780&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as Congress and the Clinton administration
spar over new safety rules for the workplace, a handful of
hospitals and nursing homes are already acting to ease the
heavy-lifting burden for nursing personnel, who have long suffered
from high numbers of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In one experiment, the University of Washington's Medical Center
in Seattle set up a two-person ``lift team'' to take over the most
injury-prone part of health care work, moving patients.
</P>
<P>
   In U.S. health care, lifting patients from bed to chair and from
wheelchair to bath is nearly always assigned to nurses and nursing
assistants, who sometimes suffer career-ending back damage.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing personnel reported more than 600,000 work-related back
and muscle injuries in 1998, more than any other major job
category. The high incidence has been blamed for reducing the
already scarce supply of trained nurses.
</P>
<P>
   To remedy that problem, the system in Seattle aims at shifting
all the heavy lifting to two workers who have been trained in the
latest techniques and furnished with portable mechanical devices.
The lift team moves around the hospital as their services are
requested by nursing staff.
</P>
<P>
   After the first six months, back injuries had dropped by 63
percent during the day shift, when the lift team was on duty. Work
days lost from injuries during patient transfers plummeted by 86
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only injuries during the day shift occurred when
staffers in three cases tried to move patients without the lift
specialists, said Challie Kraus, the registered nurse who oversees
the program.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was the experiment a success, but the hospital is now
using the lift team as an important recruiting tool in hiring
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speaking as a nurse myself, we don't like lifting,'' Kraus
said. ``It puts our backs at risk. Knowing that there's a team that
can come and perform these tasks is a huge selling point.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that this system improves patient care by freeing up
nurses for duties that require their expertise instead of their
muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Such voluntary safety reforms, including some that rely more on
high tech devices, have been tested with similar results in a
handful of U.S. hospitals, most of them on the West coast, and in
some nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, much of the health care industry and its allies in
Congress are fighting the federal Occupational Safety and Health
Administration's proposal to require nearly all of the nation's
work sites to operate by an ``ergonomics'' standard _ meaning that
worker tasks must be redesigned to reduce the risk of back and
muscle damage.
</P>
<P>
   But at a hearing Thursday, the head of the largest trade group
of corporate nursing homes will testify that no new federal
mandates are needed to combat back injuries, since the injuries
have already begun to decline by about 17 percent since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the current system and voluntary efforts to reduce
MSDs (muscular-skeletal disorders) are working,'' Charles H.
Roadman, president of the American Health Care Association, said in
remarks prepared for delivery to the Senate Health, Education,
Labor and Pension Committee's employment safety subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Roadman has said that each nursing home would have to spend an
average $60,000 for mechanical lifts and training to comply with
the new federal regulation. Moreover, he argues in his statement,
mandated use of lifting equipment might conflict with requirements
``that ensure a resident's dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the new safety rules counter that safety measures
would pay for themselves in the long run, improve patient care and
create a more stable work force, which now has a 93 percent
turnover rate in long-term facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could save $10 for every $1 spent,'' asserted Bill
Borwegen, health and safety director for the Service Employees
International Union, the largest union of U.S. nursing home
workers. The union was not invited to address the Senate hearing,
which was called by Sen. Michael Enzi, R-Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   Nor were any patient groups or advocates asked to speak, said
Sarah Green Burger, an official with the National Citizens
Coalition for Nursing Home Reform, a private group that advocates
better patient care.
</P>
<P>
   Burger questioned the claim that using more mechanical equipment
for moving patients would interfere with the ``dignity'' of
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is a wheelchair undignified? No,'' she said. Lifting devices
give residents more freedom of movement, such as allowing them to
be taken to a bath, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Such lifts can be frightening for those suffering from dementia,
she said. ``For other people, it really gives them security because
they know it's a safest way to move from one place to another.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Some nursing homes that have instituted voluntary ergonomics
programs report major savings in workmen's compensation costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Lincoln Lutheran nursing home in Racine, Wis., for example,
instituted a rule in 1994 forbidding its staff to lift more than 30
pounds, except in emergencies, without using a mechanical device.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, the annual number of injuries from patient
care duties dropped by half, the lost work days to injuries fell
from 830 to 90 per year. The cost of worker injuries fell from
$211,000 to $58,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Service Employees International Union:
seiu.org/nursing/dignity/care.html
</P>
<P>
   American Health Care Association at
www.ahca.org/brief/ISS-Ergo.htmTopOfPage
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
