<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0150 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV1     07-12 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV16-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TOO FEW OF US EXERCISE A VITAL PRIVILEGE _ OUR RIGHT TO VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     For release Sunday, July 16)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON  &Cx1f; _ In the arsenal of rights bequeathed to us by the
Constitution to encourage broader participation in our democracy,
none is more valuable than the right to vote.
</P>
<P>
   That single privilege allows us to help shape the destiny of our
nation and to record our approval or disapproval of candidates and
political parties.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, to millions of Americans, this sacred right is
not valuable enough to stir them from their homes, jobs or
recreation to cast their ballots. Their oft-repeated refrain is,
``My vote won't change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is wrong. A single vote may not decide the outcome of
an election. but it does provide voters with the satisfaction of
knowing that they have played a role _ small though it may be _ in
the unfolding saga of America.
</P>
<P>
   It is rare for an election of any kind to be settled by a single
vote. But it is not uncommon for elections to be determined by a
small number of votes.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 69 million Americans voted in the 1960 contest that
pitted John F. Kennedy against Richard Nixon and featured the first
televised debates between presidential nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's margin of victory was not quite 15,000 votes. The
shift of a few votes in Texas and Illinois would have made Nixon
the victor.
</P>
<P>
   In 1884 the showdown was between Republican James G. Blaine, a
former congressman, senator and secretary of state who had been
implicated in graft from railroad interests, and Democrat Grover
Cleveland, the New York governor who had fathered a child out of
wedlock.
</P>
<P>
   Republican partisans chanted, ``Ma, Ma, where's my Pa? Gone to
the White House, Ha, ha, ha.'' The Democratic battle cry was,
``Blaine! Blaine! James G. Blaine! Continental liar from the state
of Maine!''
</P>
<P>
   Blaine probably would have won had he not listened passively at
a meeting of Protestant ministers when the Rev. Samuel D. Burchard
branded Democrats as the party of ``rum, Romanism and rebellion.''
Catholic voters were offended and many voted for Cleveland, giving
him New York.
</P>
<P>
   If Blaine had carried New York, he would have won the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   That election clearly demonstrates how a few popular votes can
determine who will be president.
</P>
<P>
   In the current campaign, the issues are so blurred that it is
almost impossible for some would-be voters to decide which
candidate to choose.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, both Al Gore and George W. Bush have vowed to
protect Social Security, reform Medicare and education, reduce
taxes, continue economic expansion, bolster international trade and
improve health care. Each has his own plan to achieve those goals.
</P>
<P>
   Today's situation is similar to that 40 years ago. As Nixon
explained in accepting his first presidential nomination in 1960,
he and Kennedy generally agreed on their objectives. Where they
differed, he said, was on the means of achieving them.
</P>
<P>
   Today Bush has shrewdly moved to the center of the political
spectrum and forced Gore to the left.
</P>
<P>
   But the election is three-and-a-half months in the future, and
millions of voters have not yet decided who they want as their 43rd
president. If the election were held this week, Bush would probably
win because his smiling, low-key manner has appealed to more voters
than has Gore's attack-dog approach.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president appears to have decided to emulate Harry
Truman, who won a stunning upset victory in 1948 with his
give-'em-hell attacks on the Republican-controlled 80th Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But thus far Gore's campaign strategy has reduced rather than
increased his standing in public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   Many would-be voters are turned off by a campaign that begins
shortly after the first of the year in Iowa and New Hampshire and
continues non-stop until Election Day in November. Many of them do
not pay much attention to the presidential battle until after Labor
Day. Some never do.
</P>
<P>
   Although the voting age was lowered from 21 to 18 by the 26th
amendment, which was added to the Constitution in 1971, the vote
among young people is sparse. They either are turned off by what
they see and hear or they lack interest in the issues being debated
by the candidates. Seniors vote in far greater numbers than young
people.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the 1968 presidential election, in which Nixon
defeated Hubert Humphrey, has the turnout of eligible voters soared
to more than 60 percent. In the 1988, 1992 and 1996 elections, the
turnout of eligible voters was a bit more than 50 percent, 55
percent and 49 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Those are poor performances for citizens of a nation that prides
itself on being the world's only superpower and one whose tradition
of participatory democracy stretches back to 1789.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert E. Thompson can be reached at 202-298-6920.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
