<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0162 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS0713-FI     07-12 1817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS0713-FILE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that James Carville and Dick Morris spent some
time in Mexico before the recent presidential election there.
Apparently they were campaigning for one of the candidates. Can you
tell me which party?
</P>
<P>
   A: The political consultants indeed were involved as
behind-the-scenes players in Mexico's presidential race _ but on
opposite sides of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Carville was there to advise the PRI (Institutional
Revolutionary Party) and its candidate, Francisco Labastida. Morris
was aligned with the winner, Vicente Fox, candidate of the PAN
(National Action Party).
</P>
<P>
   As reported by the Associated Press last January, the idea of
Mexican politicians taking advice from U.S. advisers was a
sensitive issue, because any hint of U.S. influence could be blown
up into a sovereignity issue. So there wasn't a lot of publicity
for Carville and Morris, or several other American political
operatives reportedly involved in the campaign. There were no news
conferences and no photo ops, and the candidates appeared to hide
the fact that they even talked to the American advisers.
</P>
<P>
   When Morris said he had worked with Fox, the Fox camp hotly
denied it. And at a primary debate, when the last-place candidate
challenged his opponents to say whether they had U.S. advisers,
none answered.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Atlanta Track Club claims that the Peachtree Road Race is
the largest 10K in the world with 55,000 participants. My husband
and I were in the Bay to Breakers race in San Francisco several
years ago, and I'm sure it had more than 55,000 people. Can you
explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Bay to Breakers, sponsored by the San Francisco Examiner,
is a 12K race. It attracted about 75,000 people this year, down
from a peak of 100,000-plus in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Medeia Cohan, a spokeswoman for the race, called it ``the
largest race in the world,'' but added that a half-marathon
somewhere in Europe _ she didn't know where _ may break the record
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Information online: www.baytobreakers.com/. Next race date: May
20, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article quoted Vice President Al Gore as ``speaking
favorably of the fractals,'' and the word ``fractals'' appears in
the article three more times, never defined. I checked seven
dictionaries and can't find this word. What does it mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a mathematical term. Fractal geometry examines the
irregular patterns that repeat and are similar at all size scales.
In nature, an example is a mountain range.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've heard many stories about how kudzu came to the
Southeast. One was that it was brought from China to stop erosion.
Is that really the case?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's about it. The plant _ which belongs to the pea family
and whose scientific name is Pueraria lobata _ is native to China
and Japan. It was long grown there for its edible, starchy roots
and for a fiber, kohemp, made from its stems.
</P>
<P>
   It was transplanted to North America in the late 1880s and first
was grown as an ornamental porch vine and for livestock feed. In
the 1930s, farmers in the South began to plant kudzu as ground
cover to prevent soil erosion. And we all know what has happened in
the decades since.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article about electric vehicles not catching on with
consumers didn't mention one I have been hoping to see for several
years. It's a sports can manufactured by Zebra Motors in
California. Do you have any information about the car and its
status _ performance, availability, price?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Zeba apparently didn't make it into production. Although
there's a Web site for Zebra Motors _ http://zebramotors.com/ _ and
lots of photos of the handsome car, e-mail messages sent to the
company for information didn't go through, and the telephone number
listed on the Web site reaches a recording saying it no longer is
in service.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has anything about it appeared in the media in several
years, and even then mentions were brief and couched in terms such
as ``a fledgling company'' trying to bring a new product to market.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the recent interest in alternative-fuel vehicles, if
the Zebra had caught on we surely would have heard about it by now.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've heard several people mention an incident that supposedly
occurred a couple of years ago. It involves an American couple
vacationing in Australia who went scuba diving and were mistakenly
left out in the open water by the dive boat. They weren't
discovered missing until several days later, and nothing ever was
found except some diving gear. Is this another urban legend?
</P>
<P>
   A: No urban legend. The incident occurred Jan. 25, 1998, when
Thomas Joseph Lonergan, 33, and Eileen Cassidy Lonergan, 28, of
Baton Rouge, La., went diving off the boat Outer Edge at St.
Crispen Reef, 45 miles northeast of Port Douglas, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   They were among 26 people diving at the reef, but weren't aboard
the vessel when it returned to dock later that day. Crew members
didn't report the couple missing until more than 48 hours later,
after finding their personal items on the boat.
</P>
<P>
   At a preliminary inquest in July 1998, a coroner found that the
Lonergans were left behind and drowned. Their bodies were never
found, and were thought to have been taken by a shark.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1999, a 12-day trial in Australia ended when a jury
found the skipper of the Outer Edge not guilty of manslaughter.
``I'm absolutely shocked,'' said Nancy Weir, Lonergan's sister, in
New Orleans. ``I think it's a terrible injustice.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does the RMS in RMS Titanic stand for? How about SS in
SS Minnow?
</P>
<P>
   A: RMS: Royal Mail Steamship. SS: steamship.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In a newspaper photo of an airplane with its nose to the
ground, the caption said a student pilot was the only person on
board when the nose gear collapsed. Doesn't the FAA require an
instructor to fly with a student pilot?
</P>
<P>
   A: At some point in training a pilot must fly solo. Without
directing her comments toward this particular incident, FAA
spokeswoman Kathleen Bergen said it is one of the requirements that
a student pilot must fulfill before earning a private pilot's
certificate.
</P>
<P>
   Once the student pilot has received instruction and met certain
proficiency requirements, and has been endorsed by the instructor
to make solo flights, then the student flies alone as the next
step. So there's no impropriety or illegality involved when a
student pilot flies alone.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The recent book, ``Flags of Our Fathers,'' briefly mentions a
young Marine, Jack Lucas, who won the Medal of Honor as a
14-year-old on Iwo Jima. The book provides no followup on his life.
Can you provide a brief biography?
</P>
<P>
   A: To clarify one point, Jacklyn Harold Lucas was barely 17 when
his act of ``conspicuous gallantry and intrepidity at the risk of
his life above and beyond the call of duty'' occurred on Iwo Jima.
He was 14 _ he lied about his age _ when he enlisted.
</P>
<P>
   It was on Feb. 20, 1945, when the Marine Corps private and three
other men were ambushed by an enemy patrol that attacked them at
Iwo Jima with rifle fire and grenades. Lucas saved the others by
hurling himself atop a grenade, then pulling another one under his
body, absorbing the blasting forces. He suffered wounds to his
chest, right arm and hand, right thigh, neck and chin that required
months of hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   President Truman, who conferred the Medal of Honor on Lucas,
later helped him get a job with the Veterans Administration in
Winston-Salem, N.C. Lucas finished high school and college and
pursued several business ventures.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, he enlisted in the Army, saying he was eager to go to
Vietnam, but was assigned to train troops at Fort Bragg, N.C. He
was discharged as a captain in 1965. He was married three times.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1995, Lucas was one of the heroes President Clinton
introduced during the State of the Union address, and he was in the
news again last month when he joined several other Medal of Honor
winners participating in the National D-Day Museum opening in New
Orelans.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, 72, lives in Hattiesburg, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I received a call from someone who claimed to be with the
Census Bureau asking more questions than were on our original form.
We were told that if we didn't answer by the 14th time we were
called, we would be arrested. Is this a scam from someone or some
organization trying to get information?
</P>
<P>
   A: Mary Vetter of the U.S. Census Bureau said that while
responding to the census was mandatory, she didn't know anything
about any arrest threats, ``and for nonresponding households, we
called three times and visited three times to obtain the
information.''
</P>
<P>
   She did say, however, that several census ``operations'' are
continuing, including the Accuracy and Coverage Evaluation Survey,
a follow-up to the 2000 Census intended to see if anyone was missed
or counted twice; and the American Community Survey, which will be
used to provide accurate, up-to-date profiles of American
communities every year.
</P>
<P>
   If there's uncertainty about the legitimacy of a caller claiming
to represent the Census Bureau, call your local office of the
bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article said video poker machines were being banned in
South Carolina. I enjoyed playing the machines at Harrah's Cherokee
Casino. Are they banned, too?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Harrah's Cherokee Casino is on a tribal reservation in
western North Carolina. Its video poker operations are not affected
by South Carolina's laws. Information: 1-800-427-7247.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you explain why Kenyans always seem to do so well in
marathons and 10Ks? Do they have some kind of special training or
diet? Are they tested for steroid use?
</P>
<P>
   A: Kenyans, and other East Africans, certainly do well. The
perennial success of the Kenyans in running has nothing to do with
drug use or gene pools or anything like that, in the view of Julia
Emmons, director of Atlanta's Peachtree Road Race and the Atlanta
Track Club.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a combination of factors makes many of them superb
athletes, she said, including ``a rugged existence and challenging
life'' from childhood, in which youngsters typically run back and
forth from school, with no motorized transportation available; an
intense focus on this one sport, compared to many countries in
which gifted athletes can choose from a number of sports; and an
``extraordinary work ethic.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenya's altitude also is a factor. That aspect is a draw for
American runners who go there to train. ``But it's attitude, more
than altitude, that makes the Kenyans great runners,'' Emmons said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
