<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0164 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     07-12 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING THE BEST FROM WINDOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first windows were holes in the walls that allowed an
exchange of stagnant interior air with fresh outdoor air. Since
they also allowed heat to escape they were probably small and
covered with cloth, reed mats or leather. With the introduction of
glass panes, windows became larger to let light in and provide a
view. These windows had to be custom made for each house. Yet they
were not well sealed, and they let cold drafts inside during the
winter months. Still a window was a valuable commodity and in
Colonial times, homeowners would remove their windows and take them
along when they moved to a new house.
</P>
<P>
   Today, windows are mass produced from durable weather-resistant
materials. They come in a variety of styles and sizes. This makes
it easy to replace a worn, outmoded window when it starts to
deteriorate or change to a more stylish window when you want to
remodel.
</P>
<P>
   If you are simply replacing an old window, then you will
probably choose a new window of the same style, size and shape. If,
however, you are remodeling, then there are other options you may
want to consider.
</P>
<P>
   You could, for example, reposition a window to reflect the
daylight that is coming into the room. Do this by moving the window
closer to an adjacent perpendicular wall. The wall then becomes a
reflector that bounces the light at a different angle from the
incoming rays of the sun. This brightens the room by removing
shadows and at the same time tends to diminish the difference
between the interior and exterior, thus creating the illusion of a
larger living space.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, if you move the window away from the adjacent wall,
less light is reflected and a dark area develops in the corner.
This creates a cooler, more subdued atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The size of windows can also affect the mood of the interior.
Large windows in a room admit a lot of light, provide a view of the
outside and brighten a room. But overly large windows may offer too
much of a good thing. They can create a feeling of agoraphobia and
destroy the intimacy of the room. It's best to install large
windows in sunrooms and activity rooms, and smaller windows in
libraries, dens and formal dining rooms.
</P>
<P>
   You can also group different size windows into an overall
composition that becomes the focal point in a room. One large
window can have a row of smaller windows on either side; or a
rectangular window frame may be topped with a semi-circular fan
window. Beware of having too many window combinations around the
house. It is best to place a single large window composition in the
main room and use similar but smaller patterns in the other rooms.
</P>
<P>
   If you decide to replace your old windows with new ones, you may
be surprised at number of options available. First there are five
basic window styles to choose from: Double hung, casement, awning,
gliding and fixed.
</P>
<P>
   The double-hung window is still the most popular style. It
consists of two sashes that slide up and down in a frame. Casement
windows have sashes that are hinged at the top and bottom. They
swing out (like a door) by means of a crank mechanism. Awning
windows have sashes that are hinged at the top. They swing outward
from the bottom and when open resemble a storefront awning. Gliding
windows contain two sashes that slide horizontally in tracks in the
frame. Fixed windows cannot open and are installed to provide a
view (like picture windows) or as decorative accents (like oval or
circular windows).
</P>
<P>
   Besides selecting a style, you will want to choose windows that
are durable and resistant to the onslaughts of the weather. Windows
with metal frames are especially rugged, but some homeowners find
they lack the warmth and elegance of wood frames. Many
manufacturers offer windows made of wood but with exterior surfaces
clad in maintenance-free vinyl or aluminum. Aluminum- or vinyl-clad
windows will cost more than windows made of wood, but they will
help save time and money that would be used later to scrape and
repaint wooden sashes.
</P>
<P>
   Modern windows are more energy efficient than older windows. In
the past, no matter how well the sashes were sealed around the
jambs, some heat was lost through the glass. Now manufacturers
offer windows with thermal panes _ essentially an envelope of glass
_ filled with inert argon gas.
</P>
<P>
   They also apply a low-E coating to the surface of the glass; it
adds even more insulation value to the window. The low-E coating
acts like an invisible two-sided mirror that reflects heat in
either direction. During the summer, it reflects the hot rays from
sun to keep them from entering the house. In the winter, the glass
contains the house heat and helps keep fuel bills down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
