<HEADER>
A0165 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS0713-FI     07-12 1537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS0713-FILE2-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: It was reported that the Lower Snake River Navigation in
Idaho is No. 7 on a list of 10 worst Army Corps of Engineers
projects. How is the Corps of Engineers involved, since the Lower
Snake River is under the Bureau of Reclamation?
</P>
<P>
   A: Four dams on the Lower Snake River were built in the 1960s
and '70s by the Corps of Engineers for multipurpose benefits, said
Jerry Gregg of the U.S. Bureau of Reclamation's Pacific Northwest
Region. These dams are managed by the Corps of Engineers. The
Bureau of Reclamation doesn't have any facilities on this stretch
of the river.
</P>
<P>
   According to Taxpayers for Common Sense and the National
Wildlife Federation, which produced the list of ``Troubled Waters
Top 10,'' the Corps spends about $32 million each year relating to
the four dams to subsidize navigation. The two organizations, which
endorse retiring the dams, say that they're the major cause of the
decline of five endangered species of salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How does one submit a name for consideration for a MacArthur
Foundation ``genius grant''?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you mean how do people apply for themselves, that isn't
possible. Applications for fellowships are neither solicited nor
accepted. That was among restrictions imposed by the IRS in
approving the MacArthur Fellows Program.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason is that the individuals sought as MacArthur
Fellows often don't work in categories established by conventional
funding agencies, so the foundation relies on a network of
nominators to bring those people to its attention.
</P>
<P>
   Nominators invited by the foundation are identified for their
expertise and familiarity with ``exceptionally creative people'' in
their respective fields, the foundation says. It invites a new
group of nominators every year to bring ``fresh perspectives.''
Nominators write a letter to the program director describing the
person being nominated and their reasons for doing so. No one,
obviously, can nominate oneself.
</P>
<P>
   Information online: www.macfdn.org/programs/fel/faq.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A mentioned that Supreme Court vacancies can occur only
when a justice dies, resigns, retires or is removed through
impeachment. Has a justice ever been impeached?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes _ but not removed. A Supreme Court justice can be removed
from office only through impeachment in the House of
Representatives and conviction by two-thirds of the Senate. While
no justice has been removed by impeachment, Justice Samuel Chase
was impeached in 1804 and tried in the Senate on charges of
injudicious behavior. The trial ended in 1805 in an acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   Two other justices, Abe Fortas and William O. Douglas, have
faced serious attempts at impeachment, but neither was actually
impeached. Fortas resigned in 1969 after some House members laid
plans for an inquiry into charges of financial misconduct. And the
House investigated impeachment charges against Douglas in 1953 and
1970, but rejected the resolutions after subcommittee hearings.
</P>
<P>
   There were scattered calls in the 1950s and '60s for the
impeachment of Chief Justice Earl Warren, but no serious
impeachment effort ever was initiated in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read recently that scientists have discovered something new
that will destroy kudzu without harming the foliage that it clings
to. Can you elaborate?
</P>
<P>
   A: Progress is being made, but don't look for it on the market
in the near future, said Doug Boyette of the Stoneville, Miss.,
Southern Weed Science Research Unit of the U.S. Department of
Agriculture's Agriculture Research Service.
</P>
<P>
   His agency is conducting research to develop plant pathogens as
``bioherbicides'' to control various weeds. One of the fungal
pathogens being developed is Myrothecium verrucaria for controlling
kudzu. It kills leaves and stems of kudzu as well as some other
weeds.
</P>
<P>
   Field test plots reveal that the fungus is highly effective in
controlling this weed, Boyette explained. His agency, meanwhile,
has applied for a patent to use it as a bioherbicide. The material
then will require Environmental Protection Agency registration,
followed by commercial development, before it's available to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   More immediate kudzu control can be accomplished by starving it
(cutting off all foliage for several years in a row) or with such
herbicides as glyphosate (RoundUp) and triclopyr (Brush-B-Gon),
said University of Georgia Extension Service horticulture educator
Walter Reeves. Or you can cut the vine where it emerges from the
ground and paint the stump with either of those chemicals to
minimize resprouting.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A report about endangered historic sites mentioned Abraham
Lincoln's Anderson Cottage retreat in Washington. I'm not familiar
with this. Do you have more information?
</P>
<P>
   A: Also known as The Soldiers' Home, Anderson Cottage was
Lincoln's summer residence. He spent one-fourth of his presidency
at the home, and it is where he drafted the Emancipation
Proclamation. It's on the grounds of the 320-acre campus of the
U.S. Soldiers' and Airmen's Home just north of the U.S. Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1842-43 as the home of George Riggs Jr., the retreat
was bought in 1851 by the federal government to form the core of
the U.S. Soldiers' Home. The 14-room Gothic Revival cottage served
as the summer residence of the Lincoln family from 1862 to 1864. It
later was named after Maj. Robert Anderson, who commanded Fort
Sumter at the outbreak of the Civil War and was an advocate for
establishing a home for soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson Cottage is the only major Lincoln site in the United
States that hasn't been restored, said Richard Moe, president of
the National Trust for Historic Preservation. Donations are
welcome: 202-588-6308 (Sophia Lynn, project manager).
</P>
<P>
   Q: When will the new South Carolina commemorative quarters be
minted? My bank has no information.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Mint says the S.C. coins went to the Federal Reserve on
May 22. A Mint spokeswoman said they should be ``readily
available'' at banks by now. Information online: www.usmint.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently read that the military vehicle that came into wide
use in early World War ll was called simply General Purpose. People
used the initials GP, which became ``jeep.'' However, in past years
I also heard that it was a ``peep.'' Could you clear this up?
</P>
<P>
   A: The term ``jeep'' was applied to a rugged, four-wheel-drive,
four-cylinder 1 1/4-ton ( 1/4 ton in carrying capacity) vehicle in
the armored forces of World War II. In those units and forces, a
smaller vehicle was called a ``peep.'' The latter term didn't catch
on, however. When capitalized, Jeep is a trademark for a civilian
automotive vehicle that was patterned after the military forces
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   While some sources say the term jeep derived from GP, another
theory traces the origin to the comic strip ``Popeye.'' It had a
character with extraordinary powers named Eugene the Jeep.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A reported that the Boeing 717-200 is that company's newest
commercial aircraft. But on a recent trip to Paris on a 777-200, we
were told that was the newest. Can you clarify? Also, how big is
the 777? It had the longest wingspan I've ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   A: The first model of the initial version of the 777-200 was
delivered in May 1995, Boeing says. The first extended-range
version was delivered in February 1997.
</P>
<P>
   What is the present Boeing 717-200 started life as the MD-95,
introduced by McDonnell Douglas in October 1995. Boeing reassigned
the 717 model designation to it in January 1998, and AirTran
Airways began taking deliveries in September 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The 777-200 has a wingspan of 199 feet, 11 inches, an overall
length of 209 feet, 1 inch, and a passenger capacity of 305-328.
The 717-200 is much smaller: wingspan, 93.3 feet; overall length,
124 feet; capacity, 100-106.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you tell the many fans of ``The Andy Griffith Show''
about the name of Sheriff Andy's son, Opie? Was it short for
something? Also, was the death of Opie's mother ever mentioned?
</P>
<P>
   A: The story goes that Opie (played by Ronny Howard) was named
for Opie Cates, a prominent bandleader of the '40s-'50s whom Andy
Griffith and producer-director Sheldon Leonard both admired. Opie
Taylor spelled his name that way in two episodes, on the love note
he wrote to Miss Crump in ``Opie Loves Helen,'' and on the board he
burned his name into in ``Barney's Sidecar.''
</P>
<P>
   Opie's mother's death was mentioned first on the pilot for ``The
Andy Griffith Show,'' which appeared on ``The Danny Thomas Show.''
After Opie's pet turtle, Wilford, was stepped on and killed by a
Mrs. Balford in front of an ice cream parlor, Opie wanted Andy to
arrest her for ``murder,'' give her a fair trial, and ``hang her.''
Andy tried to help Opie deal with the loss by talking about how it
was when Opie's ``ma'' died. Opie looked to Andy and said, ``Who
stepped on Ma?''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Wedding Bells for Aunt Bee,'' Opie asked Andy, ``Did you
and Ma have that kind of love?'' Andy replied, ``Yes, son, we
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans can find such tidbits online at ``The Andy Griffith Show''
Rerun Watchers Club's Web site: www.mayberry.com/tagsrwc/index.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
