<HEADER>
A0169 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-NIRELAND-MARCHES-0713     07-12 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-MARCHES-0713-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEFIANT ORANGE ORDER SHOWS SOME DIVISIONS OVER PROTESTS
 &HT;    (550&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Their fifes and bass drums
reverberating through the city's shuttered streets, thousands of
members of the Orange Order paraded Wednesday, the climactic day of
the annual rite to celebrate winning a war that ended three
centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to avoid a sectarian confrontation, security forces in
the morning installed a massive, drab green steel wall on the
Ormeau Bridge to prevent the Protestant Orangemen from marching
into a hostile Catholic neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   When the Orangemen reached the steel wall, they stated their
objections to being permitted to carry on. An Anglican minister,
the Rev. William Hoey, stood in front of the wall to lead the crowd
in the Lord's Prayer _ and an attack on Catholic politicians and
the British government. Many Protestants believe that British
politicians trying to resolve the ancient sectarian dispute have
been siding more often with the minority Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no peace in this land so long as republicanism calls
the shots,'' Hoey said, referring to militant Catholics associated
with the Irish Republic Army. ``We say to the government, take them
on and put them down once and for all.''
</P>
<P>
   Police and politicians hope the close of a particularly riotous
marching season will bring an end to a 10-day spasm of violence
that has caused millions of dollars in lost business and reminded
everyone that peace has still not taken hold in this troubled
province.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 80,000 members of the Orange Order marched throughout
the province. Most of the
</P>
<P>
   parades like the ones here in Belfast were uneventful. Thousand
of supporters, many wearing or waving the British Union Jack flag,
lined the routes.
</P>
<P>
   With a police helicopter keeping watch from a gray cloudy sky,
the mood of the crowd was sour. There were few cheers as the crowds
watched the parade of grimly serious men carrying banners and
swords.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot deny that I hate the Catholics _ even though I have
some friends who go to the Pope church _ and now the police too,''
said Charles Moye, a car mechanic who brought his two small
children and their mother to the parade. ``The police should be
with us as we are loyal to the same things they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``They aren't letting us March on the queen's road, which is our
sacred right,'' he added. ``All that's happened here that we've all
seen on TV every night is because of the Parades Commission. It's
all on their heads.''
</P>
<P>
   For three years straight, the government's Parades Commission
has forbidden the Protestants from marching through Catholic
neighborhoods. The commission's most controversial decision has
been to forbid the Orange Order from marching into a Catholic
neighborhood in Drumcree near Portadown.
</P>
<P>
   The Drumcree stand-off has become a sacred cause for the
Orangemen, who called for widespread demonstrations against the
decision. These demonstrations evolved into nightly outbursts of
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Orange leaders had appealed for protests to stay peaceful but
their pleas fell on deaf ears.
</P>
<P>
   Denis Watson, an Orange Order leader, condemned the violence.
``Violence cannot be justified as we have witnessed in recent days,
and it does nothing to enhance the cause of Orange-ism,'' Watson
told a crowd Wednesday. ``Those who wish to infiltrate and attend
the protest for their own ulterior motive have no part to play in
support of the Orange Order.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, riots in Portadown left 21 policemen injured.
Near a bonfire in Larne, north of Belfast, a man was found dead
from gunshot wounds. Police believe he was killed by Protestant
paramilitaries.
</P>
<P>
   Police used water cannons overnight on rioters in Portadown who
rained gasoline bombs, bottles and bricks at security forces near
two Protestant neighborhoods. At one point a home-made pipe bomb
was tossed at security forces.
</P>
<P>
   In an unsettling development, masked guerrillas from the
outlawed Ulster Freedom Fighters came out of the shadows near at
least two Belfast bonfires and fired repeated volleys in the air
with handguns and semi-automatic assault rifles. The organization
is supposed to be observing a cease-fire in support of the 1998
Good Friday peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Sectarian tensions intensify each year in the run-up to July 12,
the anniversary of the day when Protestant William of Orange
triumphed over Catholic King James II at the Battle of the Boyne in
1690.
</P>
<P>
   Some moderates within the Orange Order complained their
provocative protests made the violence inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't wear my (Orange) collarette with the pride I used to,
not when I see people blocking roads with pipes in their hands,''
William Brown, a one-time senior Belfast Orangeman, told the
Associated Press.
</P>
