<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0181 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ALLSTATE-AGENTS-NYT &LR;      07-12 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLSTATE-AGENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAGING A BATTLE AGAINST INDEPENDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Idaho, Ore., Ill.)   By GREG WINTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 14 years as an agent for the Allstate Insurance Co., Gene
Romero thought he had mastered the art of keeping quiet. When the
company required him to work weekends, he says, he did not
complain. When it cut back on office help and had him do his own
paperwork, he uttered no protest. At 51, Romero thought that his
silence would pave the way to an easy retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The job had been a good one. Though most insurance companies
have long relied on independent contractors to sell their policies,
Allstate was among the few to hire agents as employees with
benefits, arousing a fierce loyalty from its sale force.
</P>
<P>
   But, last November, Romero, in Kansas City, Mo., and about 6,000
other employee agents were told that their jobs would be terminated
on June 30, their benefits canceled and their pensions frozen. They
could stay with Allstate and earn higher commissions, but only as
independent contractors who paid their own expenses, got no
benefits and could be dismissed at any time. Or they could leave,
taking a severance package or selling their business to fellow
agents. In all cases, the agents had to waive their rights to sue
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Romero signed the waiver and sold his business. But all he could
think about, he says, was how difficult it would be to find a new
job with the same security and perquisites. ``I felt betrayed,'' he
said. ``Ever since I have been with Allstate, they've always said
the agent is the backbone of the company, but now they've changed
their story.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, Romero filed a complaint with the Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission over the waiver, starting a feud that has
spread around the country. Since then, at least 50 agents have
filed similar complaints, contending that Allstate, the nation's
second-largest insurance company after State Farm, violated federal
law by forcing them to surrender their civil rights to keep their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has yet to rule, but it calls the number of
complaints fairly large and cause for concern, considering how
rarely unhappy employees overcome fear of repercussion and take
action.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute is the latest skirmish in a long-simmering conflict
over the use of independent contractors in the American workplace.
The practice has long been scrutinized by the Internal Revenue
Service because it enables businesses to escape payroll taxes, and
labor unions attack it as a means for employers to evade benefits
like pensions, sick pay and paid vacations.
</P>
<P>
   But independent contractors have become an increasingly popular
option for businesses in recent years, in part because Congress
pressured the IRS to scale back its 20 restrictions governing their
use.
</P>
<P>
   After paying severance packages and higher commissions, Allstate
says the move is actually costing the company money. As independent
contractors, though, agents will be free from the many restrictions
typically imposed on employees, the company says, allowing them
greater flexibility in an increasingly competitive marketplace that
has been recast by the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The disgruntled agents, Allstate adds, are but a small fraction
of the thousands who have stayed with the company. Hundreds of
agents were so bullish on their prospects that they bought out
departing employees, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not investing large sums of money into a company
that they are not happy about,'' said Barry L. Hutton, a vice
president for sales for Allstate, which is based in Northbrook,
Ill.
</P>
<P>
   But many agents say they agreed only reluctantly to remain, in
hopes of preserving careers that span 10 to 20 years or more. To
them, the waiver represents the collapse of a relationship that was
once the envy of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went with a company that I thought would be there for me,''
said Leanne McCurley, 52, an agent of 17 years in Brookings, Ore.,
who also filed an EEOC complaint. Before joining the company,
McCurley read employee surveys indicating a 99 percent satisfaction
rate among Allstate agents. Skeptical, she herself interviewed
about 20 agents, all of whom poured out praise for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Morale only rose in the mid-1980s after Allstate ventured beyond
its box-like booths at Sears department stores to set up
neighborhood branches. With allowances provided by Allstate, agents
could rent offices, advertise and build their own customer bases
with virtual autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like having your own business, but completely without
the risk,'' said Dick Roberts, 54, who left the company in May
after 26 years in Lewiston, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   But the office allowance remained flat, agents contend, and as
inflation drove their costs up, many began dipping into their own
pockets. Then, Allstate began cutting back on its support staff,
leaving agents to take up the paperwork slack. Some brought in
their spouses to help at no pay. Others hired staff at their own
expense.
</P>
<P>
   To recoup costs, many agents began deducting the expenses on
their income tax returns, a common practice for independent
contractors. But in 1998 the IRS ordered them to stop the practice
to retain their status as employees.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials say that the productivity of its employee
agents began to fall at that point. Without the flexibility to
invest in their businesses, the agents could no longer compete with
Allstate's corps of about 9,000 independent contractors.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster sales, Allstate then ordered offices to be open for
set hours every day except Sunday, putting a huge burden on agents
who worked alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I went to lunch and closed my office, if I went on
vacation, if I was sick and couldn't go to work, I was told I would
be fired,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite growing tensions, many agents say they remained with the
company for fear of losing their benefits, especially their
pensions, since most of them are over 45.
</P>
<P>
   Now the pensions are frozen, meaning that the accounts accrue no
interest or additional contributions from the company. Nor can
employees take the money and invest it elsewhere until after they
turn 65.
</P>
<P>
   Some agents also say that the new commissions are lower than the
industry average and hardly offset the cost of going into business
for themselves. ``We were in good hands up until now,'' McCurley
said. ``Then somebody dropped us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
