A0182 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-RAPE-DIARY-HNS &LR;      07-12 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAPE-DIARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     14-YEAR-OLD'S DIARY DEEMED ADMISSIBLE IN NEW RAPE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A former university student who spent nearly two
years in prison for a rape he has denied committing has been
granted a new trial by an appellate court that said the jury should
have heard evidence from the alleged victim's diary.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling made public Tuesday, California's 1st District Court
of Appeal said the diary might have undermined the credibility of
the young woman whose testimony sent Brendan Loftus to prison.
</P>
<P>
   In one diary entry, written more than nine months after the
alleged rape, the 14-year-old described a recent sexual encounter
and said she was ``no longer innocent.'' The court said the jury
could have interpreted that language to mean she had just lost her
virginity and had not been raped previously.
</P>
<P>
   Loftus was 23 and a senior at the University of California at
Berkeley, with no criminal record, at the time of the incident at
Konocti Harbor in Lake County, Calif., during the July 4 weekend in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   A young woman identified by the court as Melissa F. testified
that Loftus and another UC-Berkeley student, Arvind Balu, had raped
her in a motel room where she and some friends were staying. Balu
was also convicted and is appealing separately.
</P>
<P>
   Loftus testified he had left the room before any attack
occurred. Two women testified Loftus had been with them at an
outdoor swimming pool all afternoon, including the time Melissa
said she was raped.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Robert Crone denied a defense request to
let the jury hear about Melissa's March 1997 diary entry in which
she said she had just had sex with a friend, was ``no longer
innocent'' and feared she was pregnant. Crone said the evidence was
irrelevant and likely to mislead the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Loftus was sentenced to five years in prison but was freed on
bail last
</P>
<P>
   September after the appeals court said the diary was relevant to
the case and ordered Crone to reconsider its admissibility.
</P>
<P>
   However, after a hearing at which Melissa reaffirmed her account
of
</P>
<P>
   rape and said the word ``innocent'' referred to consensual sex,
Crone again
</P>
<P>
   ruled the diary inadmissible and reinstated Loftus' conviction.
In its 3-0 ruling Tuesday, the appeals court said he was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Describing Melissa's original testimony against Loftus as
``vague, uncertain and self-contradictory,'' the court said that
``the diary entry could have raised a reasonable doubt about
exactly what happened in the motel room.''
</P>
<P>
   The opinion by Presiding Justice Gary Strankman also noted that
the prosecutor had argued that Melissa's emotional distress at the
time of the trial tended to prove she had been raped. The diary
entry, which showed her confusion and anguish shortly before she
told police she was raped, would have allowed the defense to offer
an alternative explanation, Strankman said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Loftus was entitled to offer evidence of the diary at a
new trial. But Loftus' appellate attorney, Dennis Riordan, said
Lake County prosecutors should drop the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the diary is admitted, as it always should have been, the
case is untriable because it shows (Loftus) is innocent,'' Riordan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy District Attorney Jon Hopkins said his office had not
decided on its next step.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 1656EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0183 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-TV-NASHVILLE-NETWORK-     07-12 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NASHVILLE-NETWORK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASHVILLE NETWORK NOT JUST COUNTRY, ANYMORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember when the Nashville Network was all about music?
</P>
<P>
   This fall, the transition will be pretty much complete when TNN
_ please don't call it The Nashville Network _ wrestles away from
USA Network the highest-rated weekly series on cable.
</P>
<P>
   Yup. TNN is the new home of WWF, the World Wrestling Federation,
and with a remarkably straight face, Brian Hughes, vice president
of programming for TNN, says that while the direction of the
network has changed, ``we haven't departed from any of those brand
elements the network had previously.''
</P>
<P>
   Okeydokey. Whatever you say, Mr. Hughes. Except anyone looking
for Crook and Chase will have to be content with smash and grab
from now on.
</P>
<P>
   TNN's metamorphosis, which began last year after CBS acquired
the channel, has since been hastened by CBS's merger with Viacom,
which now throws TNN (and sister channel CMT) into the MTV Networks
family with MTV, VH1, Nickelodeon and TV Land. Indeed, WWF's new
five-year deal with CBS/Viacom has Monday night's ``Raw Is War''
and the weekend morning shows ``Livewire'' and ``WWF Superstars''
airing on TNN, while ``Sunday Night Heat'' moves to MTV in October.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about chasing the young male viewing demographic, the
new darling of broadcasters, narrowcasters and flycasters. That
means more ``high-energy'' sports and sports/entertainment shows on
TNN, plus a continuation of testosterone-soaked series like old
``Starsky &AMP; Hutch'' reruns and new ``18 Wheels of Justice''
episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said the $28.6 million WWF deal wouldn't be possible if
TNN weren't part of a huge company. Although its subscriber base _
nearly 77 million households in the United States, 6.3 million in
Canada _ puts it among the 10 largest cable channels, TNN's
audience lagged behind as long as it was rooted in programming
preferred by older viewers. Last year, in terms of viewership, it
ranked 12th.
</P>
<P>
   USA Network, the top-rated cable operation in prime time, lost
the WWF franchise when a court said it failed to match CBS/Viacom's
bid. The matter is still in litigation, so USA Cable president
Stephen Chao wouldn't comment yesterday on the half-nelson being
administered by TNN, other than to say: ``With or without WWF,
we're forging forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 20 years old, TLC _ please don't call it The Learning
Channel _ will never be confused with MTV or VH1. But knowing that
music can be a powerful educator and motivator, the Discovery
Channel sibling leaped at the chance to present ``Stand and Be
Counted,'' a four-hour documentary about raising consciousness
through music.
</P>
<P>
   Hosted by activist/musician David Crosby and scheduled to air
Aug. 22 and 23 at 9 p.m., the special looks at music and the
artists behind it who have worked for social change. It grew out of
a book, also titled ``Stand and Be Counted,'' that Crosby and David
Bender wrote about the artists and causes that changed America.
</P>
<P>
   Featuring performances by and interviews with dozens of artists,
from The Weavers to Jewel, from Bob Dylan to Bob Marley, ``Stand
and Be Counted'' traces the origins of protest music and follows
along as the torch is passed to the next generation of musical
messengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing more powerful in the world than an idea,''
Crosby said, ``and the idea of a human being doing exemplary acts
of humanity inspires other people. ... If you believe in something
strongly enough, and you are willing to stand up for what you
believe in, it will affect people around you in a ripple that
spreads out. You can affect the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Game-show mania isn't dead yet. ESPN is tooling up a quiz show
for sports nuts (more on that tomorrow), and even The History
Channel has succumbed. In the wake of its ``Great American History
Quiz,'' which will continue as a quarterly special, History Channel
will introduce ``History IQ'' on Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Aimed at the history buff with a mind for arcana, the half-hour
show is scheduled to air daily at 7:30 p.m., directly opposite
``Jeopardy!'' in the Seattle area and many other markets around the
country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
