A0185 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CAPITOL-SLAVES-0713-C     07-12 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SLAVES-0713-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recognize slave labor in Capitol construction, congressmen urge
 &HT;    By Miriam A. Garcia
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The payroll stub from the late 1700s documented the
$5 the U.S. Department of Treasury paid Joseph Forest for work on
the U.S. Capitol building.
</P>
<P>
   Only the $5 wasn't for work done by Forest. It was for work done
by his slave. Forest's servant was one of 400 enslaved African
Americans, between 1792 and 1800, who helped build the Capitol
while their masters received the checks.
</P>
<P>
   Standing before the Capitol Wednesday, several congressmen stood
beside an enlarged copy of Forest's payroll stub and called for
recognizing the contributions of African American slaves in the
construction of the historic building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should take the history books and add another page,'' said
Rep. J.C. Watts, R-Okla.
</P>
<P>
   Watts and Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., introduced a resolution
Wednesday that calls for the creation of a task force to study the
history and contributions of slaves in constructing the nation's
``most prized symbol of freedom.'' The congressmen hope the task
force will recommend the construction of a monument in the Capitol
building to honor the slaves whose efforts have been ignored by
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to find a fitting and lasting memorial for these men
in the building they built,'' said Lewis. ``It is strange and very
sad that the men that laid the very foundation of the best known
symbol of our democracy were denied the right to participate in our
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution follows a report from Washington's NBC Channel 4
reporter, Edward Hotaling, documenting the role African American
slaves played in building the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the legislation would like to see this type of
recognition spread throughout the country. Rep. Jack Kingston,
R-Ga., held a deteriorated book in his hand and said there are
missing chapters in history books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today in Savannah, Georgia, we do not have a monument to our
African American heritage,'' Kingston said. ``Once we can rewrite
this chapter in history without fear and preservation, but with
openness and honesty on a bipartisan and biracial basis, then we
can go back to the cities and say ... slave contributions are all
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Watts said ``it is time to recognize the people who made that
possible'' this year during the bicentennial celebration of the
arrival of Congress in the District.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's resolution comes four weeks after Rep. Tony Hall,
D-Ohio, and Lewis co-sponsored a resolution calling on Congress to
apologize for America's role in slavery.
</P>
<P>
   On the net: http://www.house.gov/johnlewis/welcome2.html
</P>
<P>
   Miriam A. Garcia's e-mail address is miriamg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
