<HEADER>
A0186 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-CHRISISAAK-SHOW-TEX     07-12 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISISAAK-SHOW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRIS ISAAK DOES A GOOD, GOOD THING WITH NEW TV SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKI TURNER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA Calif. _ Speak of the devil.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Isaak, best known for talents in the recording studio, has
joined the ranks of ``reality'' television. The man who penned
``Baby Did a Bad, Bad Thing'' and ``Speak of the Devil'' has
decided to get real with a self-titled show that will premiere on
Showtime in December.
</P>
<P>
   Although it tips its hat to lava-hot shows like ``Survivor'' and
``The Real World,'' ``The Chris Isaak Show'' won't feature the rock
star getting voted off an island or sharing his San Francisco flat
with 20 strangers. Instead, it will provide viewers with an
up-close and personal look at this mad, mad rocker doing a good,
good thing. Namely, following a script. Well, at least most of the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Executive producer and writer Andrew Schneider, who spoke
Saturday at the annual Television Critics Association gathering,
said the show is an almost-real behind-the-music look at the life
of a prolific rock icon.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, it's not a documentary show,'' Schneider says.
``It is not following Chris Isaak around with a camera. They're
fictional stories _ some of which are based on incidents in his
life. He plays a version of himself. He
doesn't really play himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The differences between the real Isaak and the TV Isaak can be
subtle. In real life, Isaak is an avid surfer, so we'll see him
riding some waves. In his fictional life, he's a bumbling idiot who
tries to make a dead rabbit appear alive with his blow dryer.
(Believe it or not, the rabbit act makes sense, in a twisted kind
of way.)
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the mix, members of Isaak's real-life band _ Kenney
Dale Johnson, Hershel Yatovitz, Rowland Salley _ and a motley crew
of created characters will also be featured.
</P>
<P>
   It all seems to be working out exactly the way Isaak imagined,
meaning that the rocker and his gang are going where no rock band
has gone before _ at least on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, we're church people, so we know we're going to have
kind of a family values show,'' Isaak said just before he and his
band performed an impromptu gospel hymn called ``Tell Me When Was
Jesus Born'' via satellite at a news conference Saturday. Then he
deadpanned, ``But on the same hand _ or not on the same hand ... we
also want to make sure we delve into ... bestiality right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Isaak bypasses the chance to sully rock 'n' roll's image
by going there, his would still be one of the most talked-about
shows on display at this year's gathering, which is the TV
industry's annual opportunity to present its wares to a captive
News media audience. Which seems to be as much a surprise to Isaak
as to anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime ``came to me and they said, `Chris, you have relatively
little or no talent,' '' Isaak said with a smile. ``Well, they
actually didn't say that. They just said, `You have no talent.' And
they said maybe rock 'n' roll wasn't the place for me. Maybe TV was
where I'd be better used.''
</P>
<P>
   So Isaak loaded up his boys and headed for the hills of San
Francisco, where the series will be shot. Showtime has ordered 17
episodes. Although the show is based on his life, and Isaak hints
that some of it will be made up as they go along, he says they
aren't trying to take advantage of the present reality-TV craze.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to copy or kind of hop on (that) bandwagon,''
he said. ``Although every week we do vote out one'' band member.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Isaak says, he plans on taking full advantage of his
writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you know, they're going to script it so that for the
first time I will be leading a normal life,'' Isaak, who is also an
executive producer, deadpanned.
</P>
<P>
   Although it might appear that the San Francisco native got his
start at the Comedy Store, Isaak actually gained minor fame as a
semipro boxer before launching his music career in the mid-'80s
with his first album, ``Silvertone and Chris Isaak.'' His sultry
blend of rock and pop quickly caught on in the Bay Area, where he
was a favorite at Folsom Street clubs such as Boz Scaggs' Bimbo's.
</P>
<P>
   His breakthrough came in 1989, with the hit single ``Wicked
Game,'' from his ``Heart-Shaped World'' CD. He quickly followed
that with ``San Francisco Days'' and ``Forever Blue.'' He released
his next effort, ``Baja Sessions,'' in 1996. In the middle of all
of that, Isaak began moonlighting as an actor, appearing in such
films as ``Married to the Mob,'' ``Silence of the Lambs'' and
``That Thing You Do.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all of his successes, a few folks have never heard the
name Chris Isaak. But television being the powerful medium that it
is, that might just change soon. Isaak says he's ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I figure more people will know me, but you know, I'm not
breaking any laws or anything,'' he says. ``It's not like I'm
running from the cops, so I'm really not worried about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But how does he think his peers in the music industry might
react?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're musicians, you know,'' Isaak says. ``They'll see it
and they'll go, `How are you here? I saw you on TV.' We'll be lucky
if they don't take a little hammer and break it open and try and
take us out of the set.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
