<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`SHEBAA-FARMS'-FLAK-INDEPENDENT-800&AMP;add-FISK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFIANT SHEBAA FARMERS OF SOUTH LEBANON WON'T SURRENDER  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE two trims, 275; 1,200 uncut)   (This 925-word (trimmed) ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London. Correspondent Robert Fisk was
recently named ``Amnesty International Print Journalist of the
Year.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (ATTN. EDITORS: THIS STORY OFFERS TWO OPTIONAL TRIMS, TOTALING 275
WORDS. FULL UNCUT VERSION IS 1,200 WORDS.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   SHEBAA, SOUTHERN LEBANON _ Like everything else in Lebanon, land
is about history. And in the case of the hot, jagged, grey rocks
above Shebaa, it's about occupation and war and annexation and a
half-century-old trail upon which Jews were once smuggled into
mandate Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Shebaa farms,'' they call these walls of stone and
windswept trees and unkempt fields and _ since they may yet cause
another war in southern Lebanon _ it's as well to visit the little
village of Shebaa where an old man remembers history with the
coldness of a book.
</P>
<P>
   High up above Assad Khalil Farhat's grape-vined roof garden, on
the slopes of Mount Hermon, an Israeli early-warning station winks
at us in the morning sun.
</P>
<P>
   A dish or parabola must be swaying in the hot breeze, for two
great searchlights burn down across the wadis, bright white even in
the midday light.
</P>
<P>
   But Farhat _ the ``mukhtar'' of Shebaa _ is not interested in
technology as he squints through the haze opposite his concrete
home. ``They're on Lebanese land,'' he says. ``And it is our
principle that our land is our honor and our dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the Israelis don't want to discuss what the world now
calls the ``Shebaa farms'' or the square miles around them.
</P>
<P>
   How many millions went into building this state-of-the-art
listening station high above us? And how many hundreds of square
dunums lie through the narrow, tree-fringed ravine to the right
where, more than three decades ago, 15,000 Lebanese farmers and
goatherds and fruit-pickers lived and worked?
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis say the land is Syrian, occupied and subsequently
annexed by them after the 1967 war. The Syrians say the land is
Lebanese. So do the Lebanese. And all the evidence suggests the
Lebanese are right.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, like everything else in Lebanon, the ``Shebaa farms''
are not quite what they seem; not really farms at all, more like
Irish townlands.
</P>
<P>
   They are 14 parcels of territory worked over for generations by
men and women who were once Ottoman Syrians, then Lebanese, who
kept sheep and goats and cattle and _ when the Israelis took the
land in 1967 _ tried to make the untended fields yield olives and
cactus fruits and prickly pears and almonds on the high, bright
land behind the ravine.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis must leave Shebaa, the Lebanese government say, if
they wish to complete their withdrawal from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, say the Israelis. And it's true that Israel was
already established on the Shebaa farmlands nine years before its
first ``invasion'' of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you the whole story and I remember what happened,''
Farhat says. ``Before the war between the Palestinians and the Jews
_ when the land up there was the frontier between Palestine and
Lebanon _ there was a smuggling group which took Jews from Damascus
to Palestine. It was 1947 and they used to cross the mountains at
night, using jackasses and mules.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to take money from the Jews who wanted to immigrate
illegally into Palestine. Then the Syrian government told the
Lebanese government in Beirut that they wanted us _ the Lebanese _
to close the smuggling trail to stop the Syrian Jews leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Chebaa villagers, Lebanon's first president,
Bishara Khoury, foolishly ignored the Syrian protest _ a fatal
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our policemen used to go onto the farms to get taxes but we
couldn't patrol them,'' Farhat says. ``The farms were in Lebanon,
on the edge of the border of Syria and Palestine _ and my father
helped delineate the border; there was an olive tree with two
trunks, one trunk pointed to Syria, the other to Lebanon. That was
the frontier.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when Syria got no reply about the Jewish immigration from
our government, it built a police station on the land. The Syrian
policemen who had to stop the Jewish smuggling were put into a
house at Zibdin three kilometers on the Lebanese side of the
frontier.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took a room which they turned into a gendarmerie and put
up a Syrian flag and over the top of the house. They erected a sign
that said: `The Temporary Police Station of Zibdin.' I saw the sign
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting their way up the Golan Heights in 1967, the Israelis
probably didn't see it _ or if they did, assumed it was Syrian
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from two Lebanese farmers who clung onto their land _
Mohamed Zahara and Ali Abdullah, who remain there to this day _ the
hundreds of other Lebanese farmers were dispossessed by the
Israelis. The Shebaa farms _ ``mazraa'' in Arabic _ were then
annexed, along with the Syrian Golan Heights, to become part of
Israel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 100 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 800) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Farhat understands the politics of Lebanon all too well, just as
he knows the worth of Shebaa. ``If you sleep for two hours here,''
he says, sniffing the cool mountain air at 6,000 feet, ``you wake
up as if you've been asleep for 24 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Lebanese government, ``it was its duty to submit a
complaint to the U.N. in 1967 when we lost these lands _ even if
the complaint ended up in a U.N. drawer.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Yet now, suddenly _ after all those years _ the Shebaa farms
have acquired new importance to the Lebanese authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli withdrawal cannot be regarded as complete until the
Israelis hand back the Shebaa lands, the Beirut government insists.
The Syrians _ who have never before been so keen to claim that
territory regarded as theirs belonged to someone else _ insist that
the farms are Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
   And behind this, as everyone here knows, lies a threat: if
Israel remains on Lebanese land, then the occupation of Lebanon has
not ended and the Hezbollah guerrillas have reason _ if they choose
to do so _ to fire at Israeli troops inside that early warning
station high above us on Mount Herman.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N., needless to say, acknowledges three continued Israeli
infringements of Lebanese territory but says that the problem of
the Shebaa ``farms'' must be resolved in a final Lebanese-Syrian
agreement. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 1,025, OR CONTINUE TO 1,200) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Up the road from Farhat's home, however, lives a man who
disagrees. Mohamed Mustafa Deli still holds the land deeds to his
father's property on the Shebaa lands, the last of them dated May
28, 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Until last year _ the final full year of Israeli occupation in
southern Lebanon _ the Israelis allowed him a few weeks in every 12
months to work on his old family land: proof, surely that Israel,
too, acknowledges the territory to be Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israelis gave me a pass and I picked the olives on our
farm and made olive oil from it,'' Deli says. ``The Israelis then
took the pass away when I left to come back to Shebaa village in
October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to get my pass to go there from the Israelis in the
Lebanese town of Hasbaya. But now that the rest of the Israeli
occupation has ended, it will be difficult to get that permission.
Maybe I'll never get it again.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
