r a BC-SREBRENICA-SCARS-INDE     07-12 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SREBRENICA-SCARS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SREBRENICA: `CLEANSED' OF MUSLIMS, BUT NOT OF SERB HATRED  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 775-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By RAYMOND WHITAKER  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   SREBRENICA, BOSNIA _ ``I will never forget this plae,'' said
Tima Mehmedovic, trembling on the verge of hysteria. ``It was where
I saw my husband for the last time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mehmedovic, 47, came Tuesday to a wrecked battery factory
on the outskirts of Srebrenica to mark the fifth anniversary of the
worst war crime in Europe since the Nazi era, and the worst
humiliation that United Nations peacekeepers have suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the 3,000 Bosnian Muslims brought in by bus were
women: at this spot five years ago they were separated from their
husbands, brothers and sons, never to see them again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just by the entrance there they took my husband, Smajl, and my
son, Asmir, and told me to get on a truck to be evacuated,'' said
Mrs. Mehmedovic. ``Then a Serb sent my son back to me. He said: `My
name is Zoran Ilich. Remember I let you both go.'''
</P>
<P>
   Asmir had not come Tuesday from Tuzla, where they now live. ``He
is too afraid,'' said his mother, ``but even though this is hard, I
am not scared of anything anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 11, 1995, the U.N.-declared ``safe area'' of Srebrenica
fell to Serbian troops as several hundred Dutch peacekeepers,
denied reinforcements, stood by helplessly.
</P>
<P>
   In the days that followed, 7,000 to 8,000 Muslim men were
killed.
</P>
<P>
   War-crimes investigators have filled 4,700 bags with remains
found on the hillsides around the town or buried in mass graves but
only 80 victims have been identified. Smajl Mehmedovic is not one
of them.
</P>
<P>
   The ``ethnic cleansing'' achieved its aim: Srebrenica is now
deep in the Serbian half of Bosnia and the town's former
inhabitants had to pass Tuesday along roads lined with jeering
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of peacekeeping troops and police were mobilized to
prevent trouble at the ceremony, which was purely religious,
despite the presence of Bosnia's President, Alija Izetbegovic,
international officials and diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   As an imam read from the Koran, distant whistling could be heard
from Serbs on the hillside above, watching from the porches of
homes they had taken over from their Muslim owners. They in turn
were drowned out by the clatter of an Apache helicopter keeping
watch on the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other towns in the Serb-run ``Republika Srpska,''
Srebrenica still looks much as it did in 1995, with almost every
building marked by the thousands of shells and mortars fired into
the town during the two-year Serbian siege.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Paganini, a human-rights worker in Srebrenica with the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, said the
town's history had delayed the process of reconstruction and
bringing back former inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the damage and lack of running water, Srebrenica has
filled up with Serbs displaced from Muslim and Croat areas who fear
events like Tuesday's commemoration might mean they will be
displaced again.
</P>
<P>
   At the factory Hajrudin Nalic, 45, was greeting his former
neighbors. Apart from one other elderly couple, he is the only
Muslim to have returned to Srebrenica in the past five years.
Sitting in his reclaimed apartment earlier, he chose his words
carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came back on May 19th and I have no problem with the Serbs I
used to know. I walk around the town, I drink coffee with people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We left in 1992, when the war started, because we could see
the way things were going,'' he said. ``I think that makes it
easier for my Serb friends. They know I did not see what happened
here in 1995. But we never discuss those things.''
</P>
<P>
   It took persistent questioning before he disclosed that his
elder brother, Ibro, was killed five years ago, with several
cousins.
</P>
<P>
   Nalic, a former worker with the Srebrenica municipality, also
owned a coffee bar in the town. What happened to it? Reluctantly he
disclosed that it was still functioning when he returned but after
he began efforts to get it back, it was demolished ``brick by
brick.'' Despite this, he is planning to bring back his wife and
two daughters from Tuzla.
</P>
<P>
   Other heads of families have come back to explore the
possibility of returning but in recent weeks four houses belonging
to Muslims have been burned.
</P>
<P>
   A group of Serb men was loitering at a kiosk near the battery
factory to watch Tuesday's comings and goings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can never live together again,'' said one. ``If Muslims
come back here, there will be another war after 10 years.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
