<SLUG> BC-`TOUR-DE-FRAUD'-MEXICO-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEVER MEXICAN `COYOTE' PUTS NEW SPIN ON BORDER SMUGGLING  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, California)   (This 750-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JAN MCGIRK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ When border police in Texas stopped a team of
racing bicyclists in lycra jerseys and helmets it was the end of
the road for one of the most innovative ``coyotes''_ people
smugglers on the Mexican frontier.
</P>
<P>
   His ingenious scheme was finally halted last week when patrolmen
operating near Laredo found that the ``cyclists'' were all
undocumented Mexican migrants who had allegedly paid the smuggler
to take them across the border.
</P>
<P>
   They were not the first. Over the past year, hundreds of
clandestine Mexican migrants have allegedly paid the ingenious
smuggler $1500 each to take part in what Texan analyst John Tedesco
terms a ``Tour de Fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the area had become accustomed to seeing clusters
of lycra-clad cyclists zip along the narrow access road that runs
between the official checkpoint at Laredo and the I-35 highway
leading to San Antonio, the nearest big city.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from local ranchers and cycling teams training for
endurance, there was rarely any traffic on this unmarked strip.
</P>
<P>
   Three times a week, Pedro Gonzalez, a wealthy San Antonio
resident, would direct groups of up to four cyclists in borrowed
gear to ride past.
</P>
<P>
   By putting their water supply in sporty clip-on bottles rather
than in the plastic jugs which illegal migrants usually carry on
their way north from Nuevo Laredo, and then suiting up in the
latest cycling attire, these bogus bikers avoided detection even
though their cycling skills were sometimes distinctly wobbly.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of them were young men, between the ages of 18 and
40.
</P>
<P>
   According to John Smietana, a border patrol agent, the novel
scheme took advantage of a constant backlog of bulky recreational
vehicles and trucks at the main checkpoint that effectively blocked
the officials' view of the access road.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, 42, would regularly haul his collection of ten-speed
racing bicycles in the back of his pickup truck along with his
human cargo and unsuspecting officials recognized him and waved him
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would drop the aliens south of the checkpoint, drive
through, and wait up north for them,'' Smietana said. ``They'd
pedal past on the access road. Then about a mile up the road, he'd
pick them up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez was arrested on charges of aiding and abetting illegal
entry after undercover agents, tipped off to the scheme, witnessed
two cyclists stashing their equipment inside his pickup on July 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're always looking for innovative ways to beat us and this
was very innovative,'' said Al Moreno, the head intelligence agent
along the Laredo frontier. ``They will stop. Their method has been
revealed.''
</P>
<P>
   The cycling scam apparently was limited to the main highway into
San Antonio. At lonelier outposts, groups of amateur cyclists would
have been much more conspicuous.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Texas border patrolmen have intercepted over
120,000 undocumented Mexicans and say there has been a 23 percent
increase in illegal migrants who pay smuggling rings.
</P>
<P>
   With standard border crossings reinforced with extra security,
and an outbreak of volunteer ranchers who stop migrants at gunpoint
and hand them over to the border patrol, job-seekers sneaking into
the United States rarely go it alone.
</P>
<P>
   They regularly risk crossing unpatrolled barren stretches with
the help of unscrupulous ``coyotes,'' who are apt to abandon them
if officials approach.
</P>
<P>
   In the past nine months, 238 Mexicans have died of exposure
while trying to cross high desert, and surveillance planes used by
the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service patrols are
increasingly deployed for search and rescue.
</P>
<P>
   To boost their chances of arrival, many cross-border immigrants
are willing to pay ``coyote'' guides large sums for their
expertise. The $1,500 fee charged by Gonzalez represents a full
year's savings for most of these would-be workers.
</P>
<P>
   Once they find jobs in the United States, Mexican migrants send
home an annual $8 billion in revenues to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's new president-elect, Vicente Fox, said ``You will never
stop immigration with guns or by building fences'' and promotes an
open border and rapid economic growth that will eventually increase
wages on both sides of the frontier.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-business politician envisions a common market and single
currency economy in place within decades. Rocio Culebro, Amnesty
International's director in Mexico, has urged the new president to
guarantee the human rights of citizens crossing the border when he
assumes office in December. &QL; 
