r a BC-PATTY-HEARST-INDEPEND     07-12 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTY-HEARST-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATTY _ OR PATSY _ HEARST?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (This 475-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANDREW GUMBEL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Patty Hearst made her stunning transformation
from society heiress to urban terrorist in the mid-1970s, she
described her family as ``capitalist pigs'' and urged them to
redistribute their ill-gotten millions to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a society heiress once again, she is embracing her family
with open arms just as her guerrilla past is rushing to catch up
with her.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, a U.S. cable station announced she would be conducting
guided tours of Hearst Castle, the extravagant Californian dream
mansion built by her grandfather, the press magnate William
Randolph Hearst, for a two-part television special to be aired
early next year.
</P>
<P>
   That will coincide with the start of a high-profile trial in Los
Angeles which promises to re-examine the whole sordid history of
the Symbionese Liberation Army, the guerrilla group that abducted
and then recruited Hearst in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hearst will be a prosecution witness, not a defendant,
the trial is likely to raise many old questions about how willingly
she went along with the SLA's string of bank robberies, kidnappings
and murders.
</P>
<P>
   Having long since served her own jail time, she has complained
bitterly about being called to testify against her erstwhile
comrade-in-arms Sara Jane Olson, and has spent the past few months
working furiously to hone her image as a respectable socialite and
housewife.
</P>
<P>
   The television special will take her right to the heart of her
family's fanciful capitalist values.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst Castle, which sits on a clifftop on the central
Californian coast, was the model for Xanadu in Orson Welles' film
``Citizen Kane'' _ a vast expression of egocentric opulence on the
outside concealing a great spiritual emptiness within.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Travel Channel said Tuesday that the
televised tours would be ``a labor of love'' for Hearst and an
opportunity to relive her idyllic childhood memories.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers flicking through the channels next spring will thus be
presented with a bizarre choice of imagery: on the news channels,
Hearst as the gun-toting class warrior known by the nom de guerre
Tania, and on cable, the perfumed, middle-aged daughter of wealth
talking about her grandfather's passion for European art and
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   The accuracy of each of these images will be at the heart of the
trial, which Olson recently described as a credibility contest
between herself and Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly, the case is about the attempted bombing of two
police cars in Los Angeles in 1975, the charge on which Olson was
arrested last year after 25 years on the run.
</P>
<P>
   But the prosecution has turned the case into a major rehash of
history, filing more than 15,000 pages of deposition papers and
issuing subpoenas obliging Hearst and others to testify. The trial
is expected to last at least eight months. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 475-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
