r p BC-POL-TICKER0713-COX     07-12 2501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0713-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Talk about him _ he likes it that way
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush, dismissing Al Gore as ``the same old sequel,''
pledged today to close a ``tired episode'' in U.S. politics by
winning the White House in November. But he also predicted the race
would be ``hard and close.'' Bush confessed he's been ``somewhat
surprised'' by the reaction of Gore and President Clinton to his
campaign: ``They seem to be talking about me a lot. They're talking
about me, and I'm talking about me, and that's the way I like it.''
</P>
<P>
   RAH-RAH AND POLL NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   Although George W. Bush leads Al Gore in national polls, state
GOP party leaders in swing states remain cautious about Bush's
chances, saying it's too early to get overly confident. ``There are
a large percentage of people who haven't made up their minds,''
said Alan Novak, the Pennsylvania GOP chairman, one of about 150
state party leaders and worker bees convening in Texas today.
Besides a lot of pep session to energize the troops, they were
concentrating on how to push Bush's poll numbers up into more
comfortable ranges.
</P>
<P>
   CLEARLY THE NAACP'S FAVORITE
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of NAACP members leapt atop chairs as Al Gore entered
the convention hall in Baltimore today with a dance in his step,
grabbing hands, hugs and high-fives two or three at a time. He
swiped at George W. Bush, suggesting his opponent's interest in
black voters is pure politics. ``I am a member of the NAACP. It's
good to be home,'' he said. Speaking two days after Bush addressed
the civil rights group, Gore said, ``I have come here not just in
an election year, but year after year. I have worked with you. I
have stood with you. I am proud to have won some battles alongside
you.''
</P>
<P>
   PASSIONATE ABOUT COMPASSION
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton jabbed at George W. Bush's Republican mantra of
``compassionate conservatism'' while delivering an energetic
endorsement of racial equity in a speech to 2,000 NAACP members in
Baltimore. ``Just talking the talk doesn't get us where we need to
go,'' she said. Clinton, locked in a close race with Rick Lazio for
a Senate seat from New York, didn't mention Bush by name during her
35-minute spech. But on several occasions, she said more than
``compassion'' is needed for a leader to achieve racial equity and
justice.
</P>
<P>
   BYGONES, AS THEY SAY ON `ALLY MCBEAL'
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign press releases rehash weekly one of Bill Bradley's
most notable successes during his primary run against Al Gore:
labeling him a first-class fibber. ``Why should we believe you will
tell the truth as president if you don't tell the truth as a
candidate?'' Bradley asked Gore on Jan. 26. When Bradley announced
his withdrawal from the campaign on March 9, he pledged to support
Gore, but immediately went into seclusion. But now, after months of
travel, reflection, writing, family time and even a bit of mountain
climbing, Bradley is ready to campaign Thursday in Green Bay, Wis.,
for his former arch rival.
</P>
<P>
   A BIG DEAL FOR CABLE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   After seeing a report on the reluctance of broadcast networks to
pre-empt prime-time entertainment for the national political
conventions, CNN's Bernard Shaw let it be known that things were
different on cable. CNN, he said, ``will cover the Republican and
Democratic conventions until the lights burn out.'' That's because
the same economic factors that punish ABC, CBS and NBC for covering
politics reward the cable stations for every hour on the air. CNN
vows to spend nearly 100 hours on each convention, nearly a third
more time than in 1996. Fox News Channel plans about 10 hours a day
on its first conventions. MSNBC, in its infancy in 1996, also
promises an increase.
</P>
<P>
   URGING BLACKS TO GO GREEN
</P>
<P>
   Green Party presidential candidate Ralph Nader urged NAACP
members to join his progressive brand of politics, saying liberals
aren't appreciated as much by the Democratic Party. ``When you are
taken for granted, you are being taken,'' he said. Nader, a
longtime consumer advocate, said the two-party system ignores those
who want social change more radical than either the Democratic or
Republican parties have offered. In stark contrast to the rousing
address moments earlier by Hillary Clinton, Nader's talk to a
smaller audience of about 1,500 centered more on statistics chosen
to illustrate the striking gaps between the haves and have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   GOING TO MINNESOTA? YOU BETCHA
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura has become a visit for presidential
contenders, and Ralph Nader, the Green Party nominee, plans to come
calling on Friday. Nader said he asked for a meeting with Ventura
because he has ``a lot of ideas for him as governor.'' Nader also
wants to seek Ventura's counsel on ballot access matters _ and on
finding his way into the presidential debates. Does Nader want an
endorsement, too? He said he never asks for endorsements, and that
Ventura is not about to make one. But, Nader said, ``You don't have
to leap a chasm of logic to realize I'd like that.''
</P>
<P>
   RALPH DOGGY-DOG?
</P>
<P>
   The adman whose irreverent work helped propel Jesse Ventura into
the governor's office in Minnesota, has signed on with Ralph Nader.
William Hillsman created a series of offbeat, funny and ultimately
successful ads for Ventura. It's unclear whether Nader will have
enough money to mount much of a TV campaign, but Hillsman says
he'll work with whatever budget he's given. And it's highly
unlikely that Nader's TV spots will feature him rapping a tune or
portraying an action figure battling Evil Special Interest Man, as
Minnesota voters saw two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   PAT IN THE PEACH STATE
</P>
<P>
   The volunteer Buchanan Brigade was busy announcing by e-mail the
news that Pat Buchanan has qualified for the ballot in Georgia.
Georgia Buchanan backer Glenn Jackson thanked the volunteer core
for ``working gun shows, flea markets, shopping centers _ you name
it _ in this Georgia heat'' to ensure Buchanan's name would appear
on the November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   STAPLING TOGETHER A LABOR ACCORD
</P>
<P>
   The last remaining group of workers without a union contract at
the site for next months' Democratic convention in Los Angeles has
resolved a labor dispute, calming fears that Staples Center
employees could disrupt the Democrats' big party. The International
Union of Operating Engineers Local 501 accepted the latest contract
offer from Sempra Energy, said union president Don Mear. Specifics
of the deal were not released. The engineers are responsible for
the arena's heating, cooling and electrical systems. The Democrats
now hope for a final deal with all the unions by the end of July.
</P>
<P>
   A RIDGE TOO FAR?
</P>
<P>
   The Pennsylvania presidential race remains close, but a poll
released today suggests George W. Bush could gain an edge there by
picking popular Gov. Tom Ridge as his running mate. The Keystone
Poll, conducted by Millersville University's Center for Politics
and Public Affairs (4 percentage point margin of error) showed Bush
with 44 percent support and Al Gore with 40 percent. But the poll
also showed that if Ridge were on the ticket, Bush's support
climbed to 51 percent and Gore's dropped to 39 percent. Ridge's
support for abortion rights, however, is at odds with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   STRONG WATTAGE FOR KEATING
</P>
<P>
   Rep. J.C. Watts Jr. of Oklahoma, the only black Republican in
Congress, gave a plug for the vice presidential hopes of his home
state governor, Frank Keating: ``I think he'd be a good debater.
He's pro-life, so that helps. He's probably much safer than a
pro-choice candidate.'' Watts said he is encouraging Bush to select
an anti-abortion candidate. Oklahoma borders Texas, but Watts said
the Bush campaign told him early on that geography would not be a
factor in selecting a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   SHOW-ME STATE SHOWS FOR BUSH
</P>
<P>
   Up by only two points in February, George W. Bush has surged to
an 11-point lead over Al Gore in Missouri, one of the key swing
states in the presidential race. A new Mason-Dixon poll conducted
for the Kansas City Star (4 percentage point margin of error) shows
Bush leading Gore by 48-37 percent as the candidates approach their
party conventions. Third-party contenders barely registered. Reform
Party's Pat Buchanan and the Green Party's Ralph Nader both
attracted 2 percent support. Undecideds totaled 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   NECK AND NECK IN NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   A new poll shows Hillary Clinton and Rick Lazio still in a dead
heat in their New York Senate race. The survey, conducted by the
Quinnipiac University Polling Institute (3 percentage point margin
of error) found the first lady and the Long Island congressman each
favored by 45 percent of voters statewide. Other polls have shown
the race to be equally close since Lazio declared his candidacy May
20. The Quinnipiac breakdown: Lazio has a slim lead upstate, 47-41
percent. Clinton leads in New York City, 61-30 percent. Lazio is
ahead in the New York City suburbs, 59-33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   DEBATES FOUND TO BE CRUCIAL
</P>
<P>
   Debates played critical roles in this year's presidential
primary contests, according to findings of a huge polling project
conducted by the Annenberg Public Policy Center of the University
of Pennsylvania. Nightly tracking polls of voters in Iowa and New
Hampshire, for example, showed that Al Gore's Jan. 5 debate attack
on Bill Bradley over health care and his Jan. 8 blast over a
Bradley vote on flood relief had a distinct effect on Democratic
voters, and halted the former New Jersey senator's momentum. ``In
two debates, Bradley effectively lost the nomination,'' said
Kathleen Hall Jamieson, director of the Annenberg center.
</P>
<P>
   BUT WHEN YOUR WALLET'S FATTER _
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, each of the major presidential candidates
has given a greater percentage of his income to charities than has
the average American household, according to records released by
the candidates. From 1991-99, Al and Tipper Gore have donated at
least $120,365, or 4.2 percent, of their $2.9 million income during
that period to charity. Over the same period, George W. and Laura
Bush gave $702,451, or 3.14 percent of their $22.4 million income.
Said Sara E. Melendez, head of Independent Sector, a nonprofit
group that studies and encourages philanthropic efforts: ``When
they practice what they preach, the message is more powerful _ and
they both do.''
</P>
<P>
   REVERSAL OF FORTUNE
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats, who once believed Republicans might
enjoy a permanent financial advantage in campaigns, say they're
stunned to find that their campaign committees have more money
going into this fall's elections, despite their minority status in
both chambers. Fund-raisers attribute this partly to heavy spending
by the two GOP campaign organizations on overhead expenses such as
consultants, and partly to the unprecedented amount of GOP money
that George W. Bush has siphoned into his own campaign. But the
Democrats, according to the Washington Post, also say they've been
``more ruthless'' in demanding that their members raise big dollars
for the party.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR EXECUTIVE DECISIONS
</P>
<P>
   Both major parties have been looking to corporate America to
help pick up the tab for their convention costs. The Austin
American-Statesman reports that 16 corporations have given at least
$500,000 for the Republican convention, and 10 corporations have
been at least that generous to Democratic convention organizers.
</P>
<P>
   FOR SOME, BUT NOT ALL, TEXANS
</P>
<P>
   The American Jewish Congress scolded George W. Bush for
declaring a ``Jesus Day'' in Texas. Said the New York-based
organization, which works to maintain the separation of church and
state: ``The principal problem ... is not that it acknowledges the
important civic contributions of a particular faith, but that it
assumes that the profound regard in which the teachings and person
of Jesus Christ are held by the Christian community are the norm
for all residents of the state of Texas.'' The Bush proclamation
was issued in conjunction with June 10 ``March for Jesus,'' an
annual event.
</P>
<P>
   CAN YOU CALL FOR JUST 5 CENTS A MINUTE?
</P>
<P>
   Continuing his attack on the Republican Party leadership, Al
Gore wagged an accusing finger at George W. Bush, holding him
accountable for Congress' failure to pass a patients' bill of
rights. ``If he is willing to pick up the phone and call the
leadership of Congress, he can help us pry loose that one last
Republican vote'' to approve the legislation, Gore told health
professionals at the University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences in
Little Rock. Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett countered that Gore was
refusing to take responsibility for ``his own failure to provide
leadership in Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   BUT RONNIE'S V.P. DIDN'T GET ELECTED
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's new campaign chairman, William Daley, said that
Democratic convention organizers hope to convince voters that Gore
is not ``just a boring stiff.'' Daley said President Clinton will
kick off the convention Aug. 14 in Los Angeles with a speech
designed to be ``a celebration'' of his eight years in office while
offering a ``look into the future.'' Hillary Clinton is tentatively
scheduled for the same night, leaving the spotlight to Gore after
that. Daley compared Clinton's role to Ronald Reagan's appearance
at the GOP convention in 1988, when then-Vice President George Bush
got the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   FOR RENDELL, THE CONVENTION JOB'S OVER
</P>
<P>
   He, more than anyone else, snagged the Republican National
Convention for Philadelphia against formidable odds, but the party
now will go ahead without him. Democratic ex-Mayor Ed Rendell will
not be stopping by the First Union Center the week of July 31,
avoiding a potentially awkward moment born of his new job:
defeating George W. Bush. Now general chairman of the Democratic
National Committee, Rendell will be making TV appearances from
Philadelphia during the convention, said Holly Kinser, a Democratic
adviser, presumably portraying Al Gore as the superior candidate.
</P>
<P>
   A WIDDLE ADVICE FOR PHILADELPHIANS
</P>
<P>
   You want to be a good host to the folks arriving in town for the
Republican convention? A little tip on being a good host in
Philadelphia, straight from the convention organizers who were
coaching 250 volunteers at a massive training session at Drexel
University: When out-of-towners ask where they can get a pack of
cigarettes, don't say, ``Go to the Wawa _ they're going to look at
you like you're 4 years old,'' said Mark Beyerle, head of volunteer
training for Philadelphia 2000, the nonprofit bipartisan host
committee organizing the convention. Wawa is a major convenience
store.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
