<HEADLINE>
AFRICAN AIDS BABIES ABANDONED AT CHURCH'S `DOOR OF HOPE'  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for this week's AIDS Conference, Durban, S.A.)   (This 675-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ALEX DUVAL SMITH  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   DURBAN _ The hatch slams shut, a bell rings and Raphael Kayamba
has the future of yet another anonymous individual on his hands.
</P>
<P>
   A deacon at Berea Baptist Mission in Johannesburg, Kayamba deals
with the living, kicking proof of the South African AIDS crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mothers who are abandoning their babies are young,'' said
Kayamba, a 39-year-old engineer who for the past year has dedicated
his life to finding homes for infants left at his church's ``door
of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The mothers come here almost as soon as they are out of labor
at Johannesburg Hospital nearby, bringing their small children. The
reason is AIDS. But some of the babies are so small that you can
tell they were brought to us even before the mother received the
result of her child's HIV test.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe some of the mothers have AIDS and are worried about
their child's future. We do not really know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the year since the ``door of hope'' has been installed in the
white brick wall of the inner-city church, 32 mothers have lifted
the aluminium hatch and lain their newborn on a thin layer of white
foam beneath which a mechanism triggers a bell in a house in the
church compound. On hearing the bell, which usually rings at night,
a church volunteer collects the child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miraculously, only four of our babies have tested HIV
positive, and I think that proves that the mothers generally do not
know their child's status,'' said Kayamba.
</P>
<P>
   Not all children born to women with the human immunodeficiency
virus (HIV) test positive at birth, and other infants shake it off.
But in South Africa mother-to-baby transmission of HIV is a
lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Due to government resistance, there is only limited access to
the single-dose drugs, AZT and Nevirapine, which many studies have
shown can banish the virus from the child's system at birth.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 22.4 percent of women attending South African
antenatal clinics were HIV positive. In KwaZulu-Natal, the province
hosting this week's Durban AIDS Conference, the figure was 32.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that, unless they are given powerful
anti-retroviral drugs, between 30 and 40 percent of HIV-positive
mothers pass the virus on to their children.
</P>
<P>
   In Durban this week, it has been the failure of the South
African government to provide those drugs _ a measure it could
afford because the anti-retroviral drug regimen is short and costs
only $4 per birth _ that has met with the most criticism both from
international experts and AIDS activists.
</P>
<P>
   The government claims that to provide AZT or Nevirapine would be
too expensive, but most observers disagree, pointing to the
devastating economic cost to South Africa of allowing a generation
to be born with the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, as part of a growing program it has initiated for
Africa, the Bill &AMP; Melinda Gates Foundation gave a United States
charity over $60 million to reduce mother-to-child transmission in
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Kayamba, whose church is linked to and funded by the U.S.
Baptists' Union, said the idea for the ``door of hope'' came from
Latin America and is to be expanded to other South African cities.
He admitted it is controversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We introduced the door of hope because 100 babies are
abandoned every month in the streets of Johannesburg and 55 percent
of them are HIV-positive. They are abandoned in dustbins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say the door encourages women to abandon their
babies. But we just care about saving lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the year that the ``door of hope'' has been in operation, the
church's reputation for finding foster homes for abandoned babies
has grown. ``Most mothers do not want to leave their babies
anonymously. They come during the day and hand them to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eleven babies were brought to us in this way last month and it
is much better because we can counsel the woman and fill in the
correct paperwork,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The children taken in by Kayamba are taken to a baby home while
foster parents are found through the church. ``We find parents
pretty quickly. We even found a couple who agree to take one of the
HIV-positive babies,'' he said. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
