u a BC-AIRLINE-DELAYS-NYTR &LR;      07-12 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-DELAYS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL REGULATIONS OFFER LITTLE TO ALLEVIATE AIR TRAVEL DELAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN HIELSCHER   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether you're a frequent flier or an occasional vacationer,
chances are that someday your airline flight will be delayed or
canceled. Although the major U.S. airlines pledged last year to
treat customers better, complaints about commercial jet service has
soared.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Transportation Department said it received more than
6,900 passenger complaints in the first four months of 2000, a 74
percent increase over last year. The No. 1 gripe was delays in
arrivals and departures. Federal officials estimate that airlines
receive 100 to 400 complaints for every one filed with the DOT.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines say they are working to improve service. Last year,
in an effort to avoid federal legislation that would enforce
passenger rights, the carriers and the Air Transport Association
vowed to reduce flight problems and to do a better job of informing
passengers about delays or cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   But travel agents say the airlines' initiative is not working.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes as no surprise to travel agents that the voluntary
plans put forth by the airlines have not yielded satisfactory
results,'' said Joe Galloway, president of the American Society of
Travel Agents.
</P>
<P>
   ASTA has called for a moratorium on airline mergers until the
industry solves passenger service problems. The trade association
also is calling for passage of a federal Air Travelers Bill of
Rights, which it says would establish a national policy of fair
treatment for passengers and travel agents.
</P>
<P>
   DOT said complaints about flight delays are up 84 percent over
last year. Airlines don't guarantee schedules, and problems such as
bad weather, air traffic delays and mechanical repairs are hard to
predict.
</P>
<P>
   When flights are delayed or canceled, each airline has its own
policy about what it will do for passengers at the airport. In the
deregulated airline industry, there are no federal rules forcing
airlines to compensate passengers whose flights are delayed or
canceled. Compensation is required by law only for those who are
bumped from an overbooked flight.
</P>
<P>
   Under the ``contract of carriage'' on each ticket _ that
small-type legalese few people read _ passengers are given an
abbreviated version of their rights on flight delays, cancellations
or misconnections.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers should not assume they are automatically entitled to
meals, hotel rooms and other amenities if they are stuck at an
airport because they miss a connection or their flight isn't
departing.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines responsibilities and passenger rights are governed by
the federal General Rule 240. It spells out what the carriers'
obligations are for a ``schedule irregularity'' _ a flight delay
that causes a missed connection, a flight cancellation, a
substitute of equipment to a different class of service or a
schedule change that requires rerouting.
</P>
<P>
   When a flight is delayed or canceled, or the passenger misses a
connection under those circumstances, the airline is required to
offer the following:
</P>
<P>
   _ It must confirm you on the next flight, if space is available,
at no additional cost.
</P>
<P>
   _ If an alternate flight on the same airline will get you to
your destination earlier than the alternate you have been offered,
you can take that flight at no additional cost, even if first-class
space is all that is available.
</P>
<P>
   _ If the airline's alternate flight is unacceptable to you, you
have the right to be seated on a flight of a different airline at
no additional cost.
</P>
<P>
   _ If the different airline has a flight that will arrive at your
city earlier than the one offered, you can take that flight, even
if only first class is available, at no additional cost.
</P>
<P>
   _ If no alternate flight on any airline is acceptable to you,
the airline must refund your money, even if you have a
nonrefundable ticket.
</P>
<P>
   _ If a flight is canceled for reasons beyond the airline's
control _ weather, acts of God, labor disputes, shortage of fuel _
the airline's only obligation is to refund your ticket. (Most major
carriers will try to reroute such passengers to an alternate
flight, but under Rule 420, they are not required to do so.)
</P>
<P>
   Airlines also have guidelines they follow when providing hotel
rooms and meal vouchers to passengers whose flights are canceled
when other flights are unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Delta will provide a hotel room if the delay will
exceed four hours from 10 p.m. to 6 a.m. Delta and some other
airlines offer this even if bad weather is the cause for delay,
although they are not required to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Delta implemented a 12-point ``Customer Commitment'' last year
in response to the travel agents' effort at federal passenger
rights legislation. Other airlines have similar customer service
statements. They include trying to contact ticketed passengers
ahead of time about time changes or canceled flights.
</P>
</TEXT>
