<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUBURBS-CELEBRITIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRITY NEIGHBORS? LET'S TALK REAL ESTATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE QUEENAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the least examined mysteries of modern suburban life is
the impact a small community experiences when its most famous
citizen suddenly ups and leaves. Did residents of Nyack, N.Y., feel
they had failed last year when Rosie O'Donnell packed up her three
children and moved to Greenwich, Conn.? Will they feel redeemed if
she indeed buys a house nearby and returns to the greater Nyack
area?
</P>
<P>
   Do house prices in Bedford, N.Y., go up or down when Mariah
Carey leaves town? And would Americans once again start confusing
Chappaqua with Pound Ridge should Hillary Clinton lose her
senatorial race and grab the next train to a place called Hope? Or,
for that matter, a place called Chicago?
</P>
<P>
   Although I am as concerned about the psychological well-being of
Nyackers, Bedfordians and Chappaquii as the next person, it is the
impact of celebrity defections on house prices that has consumed my
waking hours. As a 17-year resident of historic Tarrytown, an
intermittently idyllic, but celebrity-deprived Hudson River hamlet,
I've been spending a lot of time wondering whether luring a Celine
Dion or at least one of the Backstreet Boys to our
headless-horsemanlike community might not put some juice into house
prices.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, I have given much thought to whether
Tarrytowners could withstand the devastating blow of having a
mega-deity _ say, Regis _ briefly alight among us, only to turn
around and blow town a few months later. But mostly I've been
thinking about those house prices.
</P>
<P>
   As is usually the case when I begin to fantasize about sudden
Croesian windfalls, my dreams are cruelly dashed as soon as I
subject them to the sober review of seasoned professionals. Real
estate agents in Bedford, Chappaqua and Nyack are unanimous in
their belief that the peregrinations of celebrities have little or
no effect on house prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might make an impact on the ultra-ultra top level of the
market,'' says Lois Barnett, the owner of Vincent &AMP; Whittemore Real
Estate in Bedford. But for every Mariah that high-tails it back to
Manhattan, 10 more will spring up in her place. And, in some cases,
already have. As Barnett noted: ``When Martha Stewart moves in,
Michael Crichton and George Soros already live right down the
street.''
</P>
<P>
   Bedford is not the only village that can fall back on its
daunting reservoir of equally radiant celebrities when a Mariah
Carey defects. The same is true of Nyack. When I visit this quirky,
quasi-Bohemian village that seems to taunt stolid, un-quirky
Tarrytown from across the Hudson, it is clear that residents had
been cushioned from the blow of Rosie O'Donnell's departure by the
presence of myriad celebrities of comparable luminosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first person I ever waited on, 23 years ago, was Helen
Hayes,'' said Kenneth Kral, ``assistant everything'' at the
Pickwick Bookshop. In fact, it was Hayes' beloved house, Pretty
Penny, that O'Donnell purchased for $770,000 in 1996, remodeled for
hundreds of thousands of dollars with things like security cameras
and then abruptly unloaded for something like $2.75 million. Yet
locals did not seem chastened, slighted or rebuked by her
departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Murray was in here last week,'' said a waitress at a
pastry shop called The Runcible Spoon, located not far from Edward
Hopper's boyhood home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see William Hurt, Al Pacino and one of the Baldwins all
the time,'' added another merchant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Hollywood on the Hudson!'' chimed in a second waitress
from The Runcible Spoon, located not far from Carson McCullers'
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had Edward James Olmos sitting right in that very chair,''
observed a man in a local thrift shop.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, a town frequented by the likes of Edward James Olmos
(most of the famous people sighted in Nyack actually live in nearby
villages) does not need a Rosie O'Donnell to bolster its image.
Even if she should decide to buy that new $2 million house on 25
acres on top of a mountain in the adjoining Valley Cottage, for
Nyackers, this will only be icing on what is already quite a
remarkable cake.
</P>
<P>
   But what about an equally charming, much more upscale, yet less
overtly cool community like Chappaqua? Does the arrival of the
Clintons substantially boost the town's self-esteem? Would that
self-esteem evaporate if they suddenly vamoosed? And what about
those house prices?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely seen as a victory for Chappaqua,'' said Colin
Calhoun, the owner of Calhoun's Restaurant. ``People feel
validated.''
</P>
<P>
   But would the locals feel de-validated if Hillary Clinton lost
the senatorial election and left?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Calhoun said. ``If she loses, 90 percent of the people
would expect her to leave. But the Clintons being here is already a
victory for Chappaqua.''
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Atkinson, a real estate agent at Houlihan Lawrence in
Chappaqua, agreed that having the president of the United States
and an aspiring U.S. senator as neighbors has given the Chappaquii
some sort of psychological boost. But she doesn't see how that
affects house prices. Instead, she mentioned the excellent schools,
the easy commute to the city, the guaranteed parking spaces at the
train station and other unquantifiable quality-of-life elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come to Chappaqua because it's very child-oriented,''
she explained. ``It's an easy town. Who wouldn't want to live
here?''
</P>
<P>
   Good question. But here's an even better one. Tarrytown is also
an easy town. It is also a child-oriented town. And it is a town
that offers an even easier commute to the city than Chappaqua.
Moreover, it is not a snooty town, not the sort of town that acts
as if celebrities are no big deal. Indeed, I would be willing to
wager that if an Al Pacino or a Bill Murray or even a Jonathan
Demme were willing to ford the Hudson and set down roots in our
community, most of the locals would be ready to lay out the red
carpet.
</P>
<P>
   Why then the delay? Is it possible that Tarrytown's
well-documented parking problems are all that is keeping
celebrities away? Were these parking problems eased, might not
Mariah Carey be willing to give Westchester County a second chance?
And if so, wouldn't that do wonders for house prices? Specifically,
mine?
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, a knowledgeable real estate agent blithely
dismisses my dreams of imminent Tarrytownian cultural and economic
suzerainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrities don't raise house prices,'' she said. ``SAT scores
raise house prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but I still think Madonna could help.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
