<SLUG> BC-GUIDANT-BOSS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABBAGE, COAL AND INTEGRITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)   (Ronald Dollens is chief executive of Guidant, a medical technology
company; this was written with Patricia R. Olsen)  
 By RONALD DOLLENS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a teen-ager growing up in Indiana, I worked in my father's
grocery for 75 cents an hour. Since I was the boss' son, I got all
the lousy jobs, like cleaning up spilled milk that had soured in
the refrigerator, so that no one would think I was getting special
treatment. I was paid for a 40-hour week, but I was working my
father's hours. We'd get up at 5:30 a.m. to stop by a market and
pick up the produce, and we didn't get home until 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   On the hour drive to the store and on the trip home _ at least
the times I was awake _ I learned life's lessons from my father. He
taught me about integrity and respecting people no matter what
their stature. He had a wallhanging in the kitchen: ``Don't try to
teach a pig to sing. It wastes your time and annoys the pig.'' I
have that saying framed in my office. It reminds me that you have
to start with a certain amount of capability or you're pretty
limited in what you can do.
</P>
<P>
   Every Memorial Day at our backyard barbecue, we'd listen to the
Indy 500 on the radio and keep track of who was leading. I had
oversized postcards of all the drivers on my bedroom wall, and I
still remember the year _ 1955 _ that Bill Vukovich, who had won
two years in a row, was killed while leading a third consecutive
time.
</P>
<P>
   Working at Eli Lilly had a special aura in my town. One summer I
asked a neighbor who worked there as a trucker if he knew of any
jobs. I got a summer job unloading coal cars and cleaning boilers,
and I worked weekends there while attending Purdue. In my junior
year I learned that they were only hiring pharmacists, so I
switched my major from chemistry to pharmacy. After Purdue I went
straight to Indiana University for my M.B.A. in marketing, but when
Lilly recruited on campus I couldn't get an interview. Now they
were only hiring accountants. Luckily, I had developed a few
contacts, so I got a job.
</P>
<P>
   Then they asked my geographical preference, and I said Denver or
Dallas or San Francisco. They came back with Terre Haute, and I
said ``no thanks,'' assuming I had a choice. The second time, they
explained it so that there could be no doubt _ I'd be going to
Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   When Eli Lilly was spinning off the division that became
Guidant, I went to J.P. Morgan in New York to seek debt financing.
My daughter, a high school senior, had quite a reputation as a
cross-country runner and soccer player. One of the bankers came up
to me afterward, and I thought he wanted to acknowledge me. Instead
he asked: ``Are you Stephanie Dollens' father?''
</P>
<P>
   For the IPO road show, a few of us went on a 10-day trip and
gave 55 presentations. By the 55th time I spoke, I even bored
myself. On one trip, from Boston to New York, we hadn't eaten all
day, so we ordered a pizza on the way to the Lilly corporate plane
and told them what hangar we'd be in. We persuaded the pilot to
hold the plane so we could have the pizza delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Once, in San Francisco, we had a new person in human resources.
He was a corporate type who was from the Midwest like me. He wanted
to fire a scientist found sleeping under a workbench in the R&AMP;D
lab, and he needed my approval. I asked the man's name.
</P>
<P>
   When he told me who it was, I suggested he go and look at the
patent wall and count the number of times the man's name appeared.
I said that the scientist had probably been working all night and
that the next time he saw him under the bench he might want to get
him a pillow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
