<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORTURE-EXTRADITION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT AFFIRMS JUDGES' POWER OVER EXTRADITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The federal appeals court in San Francisco says
judges can enforce a ban on extraditing foreigners who face likely
torture in their homelands.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals rejected arguments by the
Justice Department that the secretary of State has the last word on
extraditing immigrants accused of crimes abroad. An immigrant can
ask a federal judge to overrule the State Department's decision
that a claim of torture is unfounded or unlikely to recur, the
court ruled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, in a case from Orange County, could help immigrants
fighting deportation as well as extradition to numerous countries
where police torture has been reported, said Marc Van Der Hout, an
immigration lawyer in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   He said some illegal immigrants who face abuse in their
homelands might not qualify for political asylum in the United
States, because of their criminal records or inability to prove
political persecution, but could avoid deportation under Tuesday's
ruling if they showed a likelihood of torture. Judicial review is
crucial because government decisions on extradition or deportation
are often driven by politics, Van Der Hout said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Linda Aouate, who argued against court
review of extradition decisions, was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The case involved the 1984 United Nations Convention Against
Torture, which bars nations from returning or extraditing people
who are likely to face torture. The treaty defines torture as
severe pain or suffering, inflicted with government participation
or consent, for such purposes as intimidation, discrimination or
obtaining a confession. The United States ratified the convention
in 1994 and implemented it with a federal law that took effect last
year.
</P>
<P>
   It was invoked by Ramiro Cornejo-Barreto, a Mexican-born legal
U.S. resident in the Orange County community of Dana Point, who was
charged with the May 1989 robbery of a jewelry store and killing of
a state policeman in Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Cornejo was arrested in California in 1996 on an extradition
warrant based on his confessions. In federal court, he denied guilt
and said he signed blank papers after the Mexican police shoved
chili up his nostrils, beat him with fists and rifle butts,
deprived him of food and water, hooded him with a plastic bag until
he passed out, hung him by his wrists, shocked him with electrodes
and threatened him with death.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer also offered medical evidence that he had been
tortured, as well as reports by the State Department and Amnesty
International finding instances of police torture in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Magistrate Elgin Edwards found that Cornejo was likely to
be tortured if extradited to Mexico. But he said there was evidence
of his guilt, apart from the purported confessions, that justified
extradition. That evidence consisted of new eyewitness statements
submitted seven years after the fact by the Mexican government,
said Cornejo's lawyer, Deputy Federal Public Defender Craig Wilke.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's ruling means that Cornejo can return to court with a
new appeal if the State Department decides he should be extradited.
That decision has not been made, but Wilke said he knows of no case
in which the department has refused extradition because of torture.
</P>
<P>
   The department has also adopted regulations saying the secretary
of State's decisions on extradition are final and not subject to
court challenge. However, the appeals court said judicial review
was provided by the new federal law, which requires the government
to abide by the terms of the U.N. Convention Against Torture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The individual's right to be free from torture is an
international standard of the highest order,'' said the opinion
written by Judge Betty Fletcher. ``The secretary's duty to
implement the (law) is non-discretionary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
