<HEADLINE>
`BIG BROTHER' IS WATCHING _ SHOULD YOU? 
</HEADLINE>
   By LONNIE BROWN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   I am not sure why television
viewers might want to put aside an hour of their lives each
weeknight to watch television as it watches the lives of 10
strangers cooped up in a house for three months.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At least the 10 people in the house have lives to live _ mainly
because they don't have a television to watch. So they have to
interact with each other.
</P>
<P>
   What a novel concept. CBS _ the network with, appropriately, a
big, unblinking eye for a logo _ introduced its ``Big Brother''
program to viewers last week. It's the urban version of
``Survivor,'' which precedes it by an hour on Wednesday evenings.
</P>
<P>
   CBS won the bidding war for what was originally a Dutch program
that the Netherlands Institute of Psychologists called
``irresponsible and unethical.'' But when a program's successful,
the idea is to spin off as many imitators as possible. So just as
``Greed'' is a knock-off of the chart-busting ``Who Wants to be a
Millionaire'' program, so is ``Big Brother'' the copycat of
``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   For those not content to watch merely five hours a week, there
is an official Web site where the cameras are always available:
www.bigbrother2000.com. (AOL users can simply type ``big brother''
_ without the quotes _ into their browser.) Finding it with a
search engine isn't easy, for in this paranoid world, there are
abundant sites concerned about Big Brother. But they're all antsy
about government watching people. This effort is a capitalistic
corporation doing the eavesdropping.
</P>
<P>
   Why anyone would want to watch live video feed connected through
a telephone modem on the Web is even a further mystery. The screens
are matchbox size. The resolution is far below television quality.
</P>
<P>
   But the viewing is unscripted. And that brings us to note of
another Web site mentioned on the Big Brother one:
www.getnetwise.org. (Note the ``.org'' ending instead of the more
common dot-com one.)
</P>
<P>
   GetNetWise is a consortium of Internet corporations and
public-interest organizations designed to help parents determine
how much access their children will have to Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Established about a year ago, the site has four major areas. It
provides Internet safety tips to parents, teen-agers and children.
There are links to more than 100 tools that parents can use to
filter or block Internet activity, or to limit the amount of time a
child spends on the Web. Most are commercial programs available for
purchase; the site gives detailed descriptions of the software.
</P>
<P>
   Parents can learn how to report trouble online and information
about the Exploited Children CyberTipline. And finally, there is a
guide to ``green spaces'' that provide content appropriate for
children.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a link to the American Library Association's 700
Great Web Sites for Children
(http://www.ala.org/parentspage/greatsites/amazing.html).
</P>
<P>
   There are some very interesting sites there for children. And if
adults can turn off the television long enough, they, too, might
find some things of interest. Who knows: Once the television is
turned off, you might find you've been living with strangers in the
house all this time.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. The
Ledger is a member of the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
