<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-HAMMER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HAMMER THROWER ON OLYMPIC THRESHOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Being the second-best hammer thrower in the
United States confers no special status for Kevin McMahon. He
throws the darn thing, he has to retrieve it.
</P>
<P>
   It's like playing fetch with your dog . . . minus the dog.
</P>
<P>
   One recent afternoon on a neglected practice field adjacent to
the running track at San Jose City College, McMahon went through
his lonely preparations for this week's U.S. Olympic Track &AMP; Field
Trials in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   He wound his body through four ever-faster rotations in the
7-foot cement throwing circle and released his 16-pound implement
at the peak of his momentum so as to take advantage of the
centrifugal force he generated.
</P>
<P>
   Or something like that.
</P>
<P>
   Once airborne, the hammer _ iron ball, steel cable and handle _
sailed out near a line of trees at ir,6p9,14l 230 feet. Once in a
while he nails a tree dead-on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate doing that,'' he said, practically wincing at the
thought of wreaking damage to a living organism. Better a tree than
a person, a visitor suggests.
</P>
<P>
   At the Prefontaine Classic three weeks ago in Eugene, Ore.,
McMahon was witness to one of the horrors of the hammer throw. An
unwary official was struck on the arm by the cable of a flying
implement and suffered a compound fracture. McMahon saw the
accident as he waited his turn to throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I watched it, I fell to the ground. It was sickening,''
he said. ``My legs literally came out from under me. It was a
shock, a reality check. It's just a game and here this guy's life's
in danger. This is the only time I've seen that happen, and I've
been doing this 14 years.''
</P>
<P>
   McMahon's is one of those stories that emerge in an Olympic
year, even though he's been at this arcane pursuit since he was 15.
Now 28, McMahon has been on three World Championship teams and one
Olympic team. He'll try for his second Olympic team on July 21 at
Sacramento State's Hornet Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's on the threshold now of stepping up and making the final
in Sydney,'' said Ed Burke, McMahon's coach and himself an Olympic
hammer thrower in 1964, '68 and '84. ``That would be a huge
accomplishment for him. I know what he's capable of and he'll get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year McMahon extended his personal best to an even 260
feet, making him No. 2 in the country behind Lance Deal, whose
American record is 270-9. With Deal set to retire after the
Olympics, McMahon is poised to become No. 1 in the least glamorous
event in track and field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get in a competition with Lance and see how far we
can throw,'' McMahon said. ``He's retiring and that puts me in a
good spot. But I'd like to beat him before he retires.''
</P>
<P>
   McMahon described throwing the hammer as a ``counterintuitive,
Zen movement,'' and explained by saying, ``You're doing less and
more is happening. You're letting go and the ball is throwing
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, a little old-fashioned encouragement helps, too. Before
throwing his personal-best 260-0 last year, McMahon was going
through his paces in practice and not feeling too good about
himself. Then he noticed an indigent soul pushing a shopping cart
down the sidewalk next to the practice field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This homeless guy stopped to watch me,'' McMahon said. ``He
said, `Keep it up,' and kept going. I believe in signs. It was one
more push in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a little Zen, a little Up With People or a word of
encouragement from a stranger, McMahon will take it. Being the
second-best hammer thrower in America doesn't come with many perks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 1742EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
