<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0224 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-350&AMP;A     07-12 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI HIGH COURT UPHOLDS CONVICTION OF ORTHODOX POLITICAL
LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Supreme Court ruled Wednesday that the
once-powerful leader of the strictly Orthodox Shas Party, Aryeh
Deri, should be jailed for three years, upholding his conviction
for bribery and fraud.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 years of investigations and litigation, the ruling
dashed Deri's hopes of returning to the party leadership and
disrupted what had been a meteoric career at the helm of the third
largest party in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept the sentence with love and happiness,'' said Deri,
41, as he left court surrounded by weeping and shouting supporters.
``This is from heaven. Although the judges are flesh and blood and
have free will, I believe that this is another test from God that
has to be passed.''
</P>
<P>
   The case of Deri, for years a power broker whose support was
vital for governments of the left and the right, has riveted
Israelis and inflamed ethnic passions, exposing rifts between
Sephardic and Ashkenazic Jews as well as secular and Orthodox
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   The court scenes were broadcast live on television and replayed
on radio, overshadowing reports from the talks at Camp David, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling on an appeal by Deri, the court confirmed most of his
conviction by a lower court last year for bribery, fraud and breach
of trust. But it took a year off his four-year sentence, citing the
time elapsed since the crimes were committed and the damage already
inflicted on Deri's career. He will begin his term on Aug. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Deri had been convicted of accepting bribes from three
associates in return for channeling large sums of public money to a
yeshiva in the late 1980s, he was director-general of the Interior
Ministry and interior minister.
</P>
<P>
   He is now barred from being a cabinet minister for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Deri has been sidelined from active politics since he resigned
as party chairman after the elections last year. Prime Minister
Ehud Barak made Deri's departure a condition for adding Shas to his
governing coalition, although Shas left the coalition this week to
protest Barak's participation in the Camp David talks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Drawing on religious sentiment and ethnic resentment among
working-class Sephardic Jews of Middle Eastern and North African
origins, Deri, who was born in Morocco, built Shas into a party
able to make or break governments with its 17 seats in the
120-member parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his investigation and prosecution for corruption,
Deri had portrayed himself as a victim of religious and ethnic
persecution by secular Ashkenazic Jews of European origin, and he
mined feelings of resentment to reap gains at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   After news of the court ruling filtered to his supporters, they
denounced the sentence as another example of ethnic and
anti-religious oppression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only are there trials against Jews in Iran, in the holy
city of Jerusalem Jews are judged in show trials,'' said Aryeh
Gamliel, a legislator from Shas. ``Secular judges, elites. If he
had blue eyes, he would have been acquitted.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Shas, Eli Yishai, compared Deri's conviction to
the handling of suspicions of bribery against former President Ezer
Weizman, who was not prosecuted, but resigned this week. ``This is
an indication of serious discrimination,'' Yishai said. ``It leaves
the Sephardic community with very hard feelings. As far as we're
concerned, Aryeh Deri is innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   Deri went from court directly to the house of Rabbi Ovadia
Yosef, his mentor and the spiritual leader of Shas. Rabbi Yosef
declared that according to religious law Deri was innocent, and he
pronounced the Supreme Court judges ``wicked,'' Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Although Deri will be politically crippled, it is far from clear
that he will be permanently removed from political life.
Commentators noted that his sentence could eventually be reduced by
a third for good behavior and that he could be free in two years,
ready for a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   A Shas statement said that Deri would ``continue to lead the
Sephardic community'' under Yosef's guidance. Yair Peretz, a
legislator who read the declaration, added that Deri would remain
``an active partner,'' but did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Yishai, the party chairman, who is generally expected to
consolidate his leadership with Deri's departure, took pains to
declare his loyalty. ``When Aryeh Deri is released from jail,'' he
said, ``I'm handing him the leadership of the movement.''
</P>
<P>
   For the party faithful, Deri became something of a martyr.
``You're a righteous man, Aryeh,'' a supporter told him as he left
the courtroom. Another shouted, ``You're innocent and a political
scapegoat!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
