<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0226 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-NAACP-GORE-0713-COX     07-12 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-GORE-0713-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE DISMISSES BUSH'S NAACP SPEECH AS ``CHEAP TALK''
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Vice President Al Gore, in an unusually spirited
appearance before a jubilant NAACP audience Wednesday, urged the
nation's largest and oldest civil rights organization to judge
Republican foe George W. Bush by his efforts on their behalf rather
than by his compassionate rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk is cheap _ it is deeds that matter,'' Gore, the
soon-to-be Democratic presidential nominee, said in reference to
the Texas governor's appearance at the NAACP's national convention
two days earlier, an appearance widely criticized for its lack of
specific proposals for combating racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you heard some nice sounding words,'' Gore, a former
seminary student, said as he created an old time Southern church
revival atmosphere in the dark cavernous meeting hall of the
downtown Baltimore Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   With some delegates shouting ``preach,'' the vice president then
quoted Christian scripture, from the New Testament Book of James:
``Yeah, a man may say thou has faith and I have works. Show me thy
faith without thy works, and I will show thee my faith by my
works.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is MY text today,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, repeating the phrase ``talk doesn't cost much,''
contrasted his positions with Bush's on the issues most important
to the NAACP, noting his support for affirmative action, hate
crimes legislation, gun controls, an increase in the minimum wage,
expanded health care and combatting AIDs in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to offer you generalities,'' he said. ``I want to
offer you specifics.''
</P>
<P>
   He repeated his vow to end racial profiling by police, to
increase funding for school construction and teachers, to oppose
school voucher systems and to build on the economic policies of the
Clinton administration that has produced the lowest unemployment
among African Americans since the federal government began keeping
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Gore compared Bush's speech to the NAACP to his refusal to
support hate crime legislation in Texas at the request of the
family of James Byrd Jr., the African American who was dragged to
death by three white men in Jasper, Texas, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``When James Byrd is dragged to his death behind a pickup truck,
then the governor of his home state ought to at least heed the
family's plea for action,'' Gore said. ``One brief sentence that
said the word 'yes' would have mattered a whole lot more to the
cause of justice than a whole speech that didn't even mention hate
crimes, the future of the Supreme Court, taking down the
Confederate flag, ending racial profiling, or defending affirmative
action, or Bob Jones University.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing off the broken anti-tax-increase promise of Bush's
father, former President George Bush, Gore said, ``I'm not asking
you to read my lips. I'm asking you to read my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   He also took aim at actor Charlton Heston, who is the president
of the National Rifle Association (NRA) and the leading critic of
Gore's gun control proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Heston's most famous role, as Moses in ``The Ten
Commandments,'' Gore again cautioned the NRA against counting on a
Bush victory in the fall election. In a line he has used before,
Gore said, ``The last time Moses took advice from a bush, his
people wandered in the wilderness for 40 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the only one of the four major presidential candidates who
is a member of the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People, referred several times to ``our people'' and
``marching together'' and opened his remarks with: ``It's good to
be home.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in reaction to the vice president's speech, NAACP
President Kweisi Mfume pronounced Gore ``a family member.''
Similarly, NAACP Chairman Julian Bond called Gore ``an old friend''
of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   William Lucy, an NAACP board member and fellow Tennessean,
introduced the vice president as someone who, ``unlike a lot of
people, has not just discovered the NAACP, has not just discovered
the problems of poor people, African-American people and people of
color.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucy's remarks apparently sought to contrast Gore's numerous
appearances at previous NAACP conventions with the refusal of the
two most recent Republican presidential nominations to attend the
organization's annual gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, on Monday, contrasted himself with other Republicans who
``have avoided the NAACP.'' But beyond vowing to enforce existing
civil rights laws, Bush did not specify to the NAACP how he would
combat racism in America.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's email address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   www. algore200.com
</P>
<P>
   www.georgewbush.com
</P>
<P>
   www.naacp.org
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
