<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0230 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS13-COX     07-12 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS13-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   CD mini reviews
</P>
<P>
   By Sonia Murray, Nick Tate and Chris Riemenschneider
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryde or Die Vol. II''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Ruff Ryders/Interscope. 18 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   This supposed return of the hip-hop collective Ruff Ryders is
really just rap trio the Lox _ more specifically, Jadakiss _
sluggishly boasting over Swizz Beatz's muscular tracks. Ruff Ryder
Eve shows up beside him on the likable Caribbean-tinged retread
``Got It All.'' And the rapid fire of Twista and Drag-On's
``Twisted Heat'' should have instant down-South appeal. But when
you think ``Ryde or Die Vol. II,'' you think follow-up to the
compilation on which Jay-Z and DMX were such standouts. Jay-Z's not
on this. And DMX only rears his barking head on the second to the
last song, as if an afterthought. Meanwhile, lesser storyteller
Jadakiss has basically released his upcoming solo album under
another title.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Ruff Ryders : www.ruffryders.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere to Elsewhere''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas. Magna Carta. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Reunion albums like this one typically come in two varieties:
nostalgic dreck that merely relives a band's glory days or a strong
return that enhances, rather than tarnishes, its reputation. This
outing by these veteran Atlanta prog-rockers is squarely in the
latter camp and may be the best album Kansas has produced since
1976's ``Leftoverture.'' The first record in 16 years with original
composer-guitarist Kerry Livgren, ``Somewhere'' seamlessly fuses
Brit art-rock textures with an American-heartland sound and ranks
with the band's best. Four tracks are 7-minute-plus orchestral-rock
suites _ critics will hate them, fans will relish the '70s-style
workouts. And two standout tracks, ``Icarus II'' and ``When the
World Was Young,'' emphasize the band's unabashed return to form by
quoting themes from earlier Kansas masterworks, ``Icarus'' and
``Magnum Opus.''Kansas plays Lakewood Amphitheater with Yes on July
30.
</P>
<P>
   _Nick Tate
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Kansas : www.kansasband.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rising Tide''
</P>
<P>
   Sunny Day Real Estate. Time Bomb Recordings.
</P>
<P>
   11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   London prog-rockers Yes are still the best reason to deprogram
classic rock from your car stereo, but there's a point on the new
album by Sunny Day Real Estate that the Seattle-born band really
makes you appreciate Yes. It's in the flowery but mighty song ``The
Ocean.'' Sunny Day's humorless singer Jeremy Enigk raises his voice
falsetto-like over some crisp, electrified guitar chords, sounding
like Jon Anderson had he been a Husker Du fan (Husker producer Lou
Giordano is at the helm). The tune is powerful, arty and emotional,
but it's largely unlike anything SDRE has ever done. The band is
mixing things up like never before. The music is mellower, but the
differences are more complex. Sunny Day Real Estate performs
tonight at the Masquerade.
</P>
<P>
   _Chris Riemenschneider, Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Sunny Day Real Estate, Time Bomb
Recordings:
</P>
<P>
   www.sunnydayrealestate.com
</P>
<P>
   www.timebombrecordings.com
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray, Nick Tate and Chris Riemenschneider write for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0231 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-HURRICANE13-COX     07-12 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-HURRICANE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Washington packs a punch as boxer
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Part bio, part revisionist hogwash, ``The Hurricane'' is the
hard-hitting story of boxer Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter, a talented
1960s middleweight contender convicted of three murders he didn't
commit and who, once railroaded, ended up serving nearly 20 years
behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   Director Norman Jewison's film often ducks, dodges and dances
around the truth. But it does have Denzel Washington, whose
performance as the sometimes punchy, sometimes spiritual pugilist
is darned near perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Was Washington robbed of a best actor Oscar? (He lost this year
to ``American Beauty's'' Kevin Spacey.) Many think so. As Carter,
Washington is often a revelation. The actor spent months beefing up
his body and preparing for the wonderfully filmed fight sequences.
And mentally, he captures both Carter's toughness and his spiritual
awakening with remarkable believability.
</P>
<P>
   `The Hurricane'
</P>
<P>
   Rated R / Our critic's grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For more on the movie:
www.universalpictures.com/hurricane/
</P>
<P>
   OTHER NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``All About My Mother'' (R) _ Spain's bad-boy filmmaker Pedro
Almodovar grows up with this humane, Oscar-winning celebration of
nurturing women. A tribute to actresses (of all kinds), ``All About
My Mother'' is a virtually male-free fable with a title inspired by
that backstage classic, ``All About Eve.'' It's a movie that can
wink at its own campy sensibility while still grabbing you by the
gut. Dark and tender in equal measures, the movie beautifully
balances humor and heartache. In Spanish with subtitles. Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Boiler Room'' (R) _ A high-powered descendant of ``Wall
Street'' and ``Glengarry Glen Ross,'' this study of muscle-mouthed
stockbrokers aiming to make their first million before getting
their first wrinkle pays onscreen tribute to those two movies. It's
a bracing reminder that greed is still good _ so long as you don't
get caught when you pretzel the rules. Grade: B +
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``My Dog Skip'' (PG) _ Good dog movie. Based on the late
Willie Morris' best seller about growing up in small-town 1940s
Mississippi, this family film is a gentle remembrance of how things
can pass from our lives but never really leave us. Nine-year-old
Willie (``Malcolm in the Middle's'' Frankie Muniz) is a shy only
child whose life changes when his mother (Diane Lane) gives him a
Jack Russell terrier puppy, despite dad's (Kevin Bacon) objection.
Priced to buy: $22.96 VHS, $24.98 DVD. Grade: B +
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Mansfield Park'' (PG-13) _ A bit clueless. Patricia Rozema's
contemporary take on Jane Austen's third novel adds dollops of
lesbianism, feminism and social consciousness to Austen's
19th-century tale of Fanny Price (Frances O'Connor), a poor girl
shipped off to live with her wealthy relatives, the Bertrams, at
Mansfield Park. Rozema extrapolates bits of Austen's journals into
Fanny's own writing. The result is a kind of grad student thesis,
melding character and author. It seems that Rozema didn't trust her
material. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For upcoming video release dates:
www.comingsoon.net/videos.htm
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
