A0232 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-SPOTLIGHT12-COX     07-12 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-SPOTLIGHT12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hollywood trains wary eye on television
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will we survive ``Big Brother''?
</P>
<P>
   Well, we made it past George Orwell's ``1984'' _ and two film
versions of it. So, with luck, television's ``Survivor,'' ``Making
the Band,'' ``The 1900 House,'' ``The Real World'' and ``Road
Rules'' won't do us in.
</P>
<P>
   When Hollywood isn't spending time being afraid of television,
it makes movies about television. Like ``EdTV'' and ``The Truman
Show.'' Anybody wonder anymore whether Jim Carrey's big-screen
dramedy was too far-fetched or that a U.S. network would be dumb
enough to re-create it?
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few more videos that take a harder look at TV:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Being There'' (1979) _ Peter Sellers plays the childlike
Chauncy Gardner, a man who knows life only through television and
whose odd, near silent responses are perceived by powerful people
as luminous. It's a biting, sometimes savage, depiction of modern
America adapted by Jerzy Kosinski from his own novel.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``A Face in the Crowd'' (1957) _ Or, perhaps, the life story
of ``Survivor's'' Richard Hatch. Andy Griffith plays a homespun
gadabout who gets discovered and is put on TV. His ego soars into
the stratosphere. ``This whole country's just like my flock of
sheep,'' Griffith's Lonesome Rhodes says. ``Hillbillies, hausfraus
_ everybodies that got to jump when somebody blows a whistle!
They're mine!''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Videodrome'' (1983) _ James Woods is plagued by
hallucinatory transmissions in David Cronenberg's out-there tale of
a throbbing TV set. Andy Warhol reportedly called the film ``The
`Clockwork Orange' of the '80s.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Manchurian Candidate'' (1962) _ Director John
Frankenheimer's intriguing Cold War tale of politics and
brainwashing includes a riveting Capitol Hill scene illustrating
television's potential as a means to power. It's a televised press
conference with plenty of McCarthy-like grandstanding. Insider
fact: All the platoon members held in Korea were named after the
cast and crew of 1955's ``The Phil Silvers Show.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Pleasantville'' (1998) _ Two modern teens (Tobey Maguire and
Reese Witherspoon) are sucked into their TV and transported to the
swell world of a '50s black-and-white series.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``THX 1138'' (1971) _ George Lucas expanded upon the short
film he made at the University of Southern California, depicting a
futuristic world where sex is not allowed and mankind is closely
monitored via television.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Network'' (1976) _ We're mad as hell, and not going to take
this anymore. Paddy Chayefsky's devastating black comedy marries
news and entertainment, features a mad prophet of the airwaves
(Oscar winner Peter Finch's Howard Beale) and bitterly displays how
and why a network will do anything for ratings.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Quiz Show'' (1994) _ Based on the TV game show scandal of
the 1950s, it's Robert Redford's ``Who Wants to Be a Cad?'' with a
solid performance from Ralph Fiennes and a remarkable one from John
Turturro. Memorable lines: ``Sixty-four thousand dollars for a
question. I hope they're asking you the meaning of life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``My Favorite Year'' (1982) _ Live television of the '50s gets
skewered in this comedy about an alcoholic action-adventure movie
star (the Oscar-nominated Peter O'Toole) guest-starring on 1954's
top comedy show.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie's video column will return soon.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For more information:
www.reel.com/reel.asp?node &QC; dvd/comingsoon(backslash)
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
