<HEADER>
A0235 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-BRUSCHETTA13-COX     07-12 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BRUSCHETTA13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bruschetta: A slice of heaven, with love from Italy
 &HT;    By Susan Puckett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Still riding the high of a two-week vacation in Italy, my
husband and I contemplated what to have for dinner our first night
back in the real world.
</P>
<P>
   We weren't up to any heavy-duty cooking or multi-course
feasting, but we did hope to prolong our euphoria at least a little
longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll come up with something,'' Jim offered.
</P>
<P>
   When I got home from work, Jim was outside grilling. I saw what
he had in his tongs: a slice of bread. I smiled. We were both
craving the same thing: bruschetta.
</P>
<P>
   He rubbed the hot bread with a cut garlic clove and doused it
with our best extra-virgin olive oil, just as they do in Italy.
With the topping, though, he took a few creative liberties; to the
usual chopped tomato and fresh herb base, he added diced grilled
Japanese eggplant and grilled corn kernels.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, that was one combination we never encountered in our
travels. But since bruschetta toppings tend to reflect the best of
the region's bounty, to me it remained true to the spirit of what
we sampled everywhere we went _ from Venice to Florence to Rome,
and everywhere we stopped in between.
</P>
<P>
   Before our vacation, I thought I pretty much knew everything
there was to know about bruschetta. For the past couple of decades,
Italy's version of garlic bread has shown up in some form at just
about every Italian-influenced restaurant and
trying-hard-to-be-trendy cocktail party in America. So mainstream
is it nowadays that even Betty Crocker has an interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for me to realize _ thanks to a polite
Florentine waiter who corrected me _ that I didn't even know how to
pronounce it (broo-SKETT-ah, not broo-shett-ah). Or that nearly all
my previous bruschetta encounters were but pale imitations of the
real thing: flame-toasted, rustic bread, redolent of fresh garlic,
grill smoke and fruity, peppery-tasting olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   That is bruschetta at its most elemental _ as it has been for
hundreds of years.
</P>
<P>
   In her award-winning book, ``The Italian Country Table,'' Lynne
Rossetto Kasper writes that making bruschetta (derived from
bruciare, meaning to burn or toast) has long been a ritual at
olive-harvesting time in the fall and winter. When the farm
families haul the olives to the local mill to be crushed into oil,
there's usually an open fire nearby to warm cold hands, and to
toast bread.
</P>
<P>
   As the fresh oil pours from the mill's spigot, the farmers rub a
little oil onto their hands and inhale its fragrance. They taste it
from a spoon to discern its individual flavor qualities. Then they
saturate freshly toasted bread with the brand-new oil and eat it
with reckless abandon. In their homes throughout the year, they
take it a step further, rubbing the bread first with garlic before
adding the oil, then topping it with whatever they like.
</P>
<P>
   I got hooked on the most popular version, in which the sweet,
summery juices of perfectly ripe, diced scarlet tomatoes saturate
the bread and intermingle with the oil and garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Often the topping was flecked with a few shreds of basil or
arugula, as well as a sprinkling of coarse-grained sea salt,
intensifying the flavors all the more. I found myself ordering it
as a starter to a four-course dinner in white-tablecloth hideaways,
as well as for a quick bite from a snack bar in a tourist-packed
piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Even in clearly mediocre eateries, I discovered, bruschetta was
generally a safe bet.
</P>
<P>
   So was the crostini (``little toasts'') _ similar to bruschetta
but usually thinner and crunchier, with somewhat more refined
toppings that usually are warm: a chicken liver spread, a spicy
tomato sauce, or tapenade covered with melted mozzarella. But there
are so many interpretations nowadays of each that the words are
often used interchangeably.
</P>
<P>
   Marco Betti knows the difference. He and his chef brother,
Alessandro, serve both _ often as part of an antipasto platter _ at
Antica Posta, the popular Tuscan restaurant they opened in Buckhead
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Just as their family still does at its other restaurant back
home in the Chianti region near Florence, they keep the toppings
brazenly simple _ tomatoes or cannellini beans for the bruschetta;
chicken liver spread or sauteed wild mushrooms for the crostini.
</P>
<P>
   While crostini has been around at least as long as bruschetta,
its heritage is more aristocratic than agrarian, Betti explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``At even the best tables, it was very common for meals to be
served without plates or utensils. Instead, the food was placed on
slices of bread, and people would eat with their hands. The
crostini bread was normally baked only once a week, so it was hard
to bite. But back then, food _ especially inexpensive cuts _ were
cooked for a longer time, and the sauce that collected at the
bottom of the pot would help soften the bread and make it easier to
eat.''
</P>
<P>
   The chicken liver spread, which they flavor with anchovies,
capers and sage, is his favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crostini and chicken liver has been around forever in Italy,''
he points out. ``There is a reason it has lasted so long: It is the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   In the summertime, he also likes bruschetta (Tuscans call it
``fettunta'') that's been rubbed heavily with the cut side of a
tomato.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people take the seeds out first; I don't _ I love them,''
he says. ``It's a personal thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Or he'll chop the tomato and let it marinate in olive oil with
salt and pepper, along with a whole, peeled garlic clove _ then
heap it on toast the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an Italian breakfast, good for when you're too busy to
sit down and eat,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, bruschetta is a healthy, delicious alternative to
convenience food if we're eating on the run, especially during hot
weather, when appetites wane.
</P>
<P>
   But it also adapts easily to just about any type of
entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   While you've got the grill fired up for a cookout, toss a few
bread slices on and whip out a near-instant appetizer before you
put on the steaks.
</P>
<P>
   Or pack them for a picnic: Most are best eaten at room
temperature, making them ideal candidates for toting.
</P>
<P>
   A friend recently told me about her mom's fabulous bruschetta
parties: She sets a buffet with trays of olive oil-slathered toast,
along with bowls of toppings and garnishes, and invites guests to
assemble their own.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like the perfect plan to lure our friends over for the
Italy vacation picture show.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Puckett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
