r d BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE13-COX     07-12 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cultivating Caribbean cuisine
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps this won't be your year for that dreamed-of Caribbean
vacation. Or maybe you got that wonderful white island sand between
your toes already and want to keep the feeling alive. Besides
looking longingly at travel brochures or vacation pictures and
listening to steel drum CDs, one effective way to sustain the magic
of the Caribbean is to bring the taste of the islands into your
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   While more ethnic and specialty markets make acquiring
ingredients much easier, Caribbean cuisine is difficult to
pigeonhole. The culinary influence and traditions of the French,
Spanish, British, Dutch, Indian, West African, Portuguese, Italian,
Moroccan, Chinese and others have co-mingled with the luscious and
abundant native fruits, vegetables, seafood and spices to produce a
heady melange that is hard to define. And to this worldly pastiche,
don't forget to add the contributions of the original inhabitants
of the Caribbean, the Arawaks and the Carib Indians. Food
historians credit them with bringing to the world nothing less than
the gastronomic institutions of spicing food with chili peppers and
barbecuing.
</P>
<P>
   If the seasonings are bold and unique, the rubs and marinades
ambrosial, colors bodacious, sauces light, with imaginative and
unexpected pairings of fruits and vegetables with fish and meat, it
just might come from one of the islands of the Caribbean. Finding
out exactly what Caribbean cuisine encompasses can lead you on a
pleasant voyage of discovery.
</P>
<P>
   SITES TO VISIT
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Global Gastronomer at
www.cs.yale.edu/homes/hupfer/global/regions/cam.html shows the
breadth of Caribbean cuisine island by island. Click the island of
your choice and find information, recipes and historical tidbits
about the foods, spices and native dishes specific to that island _
from the carnival foods of Trinidad to the Maya cuisine of
Guatemala, to the Creole cooking of Guadeloupe, to the West Indian
flavors of Dominica, to the nutmeg laced dishes of Grenada.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   If you fancy culinary history, don't miss The Global Gourmet's
www.globalgourmet.com/destinations/caribbean/cariback.html which
presents an excellent backgrounder on the origins and regional
differences of Caribbean cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   We don't know who Calmer Chatoo is but his home page Welcome to
Caribbean Cuisine - A Virtual Potpourri of Recipes from the
Caribbean is a good place to visit at
www.acsu.buffalo.edu/(tilde)chattoo/caribcuisine.html. In the
process of familiarizing yourself with the food of the Caribbean,
you will encounter at least four languages, untold numbers of
dialects and the influences of a variety of cultures; so make sure
you click on the glossary, which provides a valuable listing
ingredients and terms.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   At www.latina.com/new/magazine/books/99/apr/cocina.html you will
find ``Caribbean cuisine goes low-fat,'' an article by Laura
Milera, author of ``The Flavor of Cuba,'' who says that although
Caribbean cuisine has a fatty reputation you can still have your
arroz y frijoles and eat them too.
</P>
<P>
   For an insider's look at what's happening in Caribbean kitchens,
see Paul Franson's article ``Finding the New Caribbean Cuisine'' at
www.franson.com/caribean.htm. The author -- uggests that if you
want to find the real food of the Caribbean you won't find it at
many tourist restaurants. Franson says that ``nobody has ever gone
to an English (or Dutch) island for the food,'' which is not the
case with the French islands. He also sheds some light on how
politics and history influence what visitors eat. He sites Antigua,
which revolted against slavery 150 years ago, but the local people
still don't like to work in the fields picking food they know will
be consumed by wealthy tourists. As a result, the most common food
on Antigua is chicken imported from Georgia or Arkansas. Franson
offers authentic recipes including roti, an East Indian burrito
that has become popular; akkras, a spicy fritter composed primarily
of black-eyed peas that suggests falafel of the Middle East;
avocado and papaya salad and the classic conch chowder.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Caribbean Connoisseur at www.caribcon.com/caribkit.html
starchefs.com skips the history lesson and gets right to dozens of
wonderful-sounding recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   For hundreds more recipes, see the California Antilles Trading
Consortium at www.calantilles.com/Products/prod04.html
</P>
<P>
   We couldn't find any recipes at Caribbean.com at
www.caribbean.com/ but there is a listing of all the islands and
info about each. If you are planning a visit soon, this is a good
place to stop. Even if you are not planning to visit, the beautiful
island pictures at www.tropicalislandvacation.com/caribbean.html
will get you in the mood for your own kitchen version of an island
getaway.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   For a great springboard to all things Caribbean, see
www.spupr-afscme.org/links/Caribbean%20Studies.htm
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Curried Coconut Shrimp With Sweet Potato Fries
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 appetizer servings Preparation time: 35-50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 12 to 15 minutes, plus 2 to 3 minutes per batch of
fries
</P>
<P>
   Oil for deep frying
</P>
<P>
   2 sweet potatoes, peeled and cut into long flat ribbons
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds large shrimp, peeled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper, cored, seeded and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 Scotch bonnet pepper, seeded and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon mild curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1 (14-ounce) can coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 small bunch cilantro, finely chopped, plus additional leaves
for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Place oil in a large saute pan or Dutch oven over medium-high
heat. When oil is hot but not smoking, season the sweet potatoes
with salt and pepper and deep fry them in batches until cooked and
crisp, about 2 to 3 minutes per batch. Drain on paper towels and
keep hot until ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Place the 1/4 cup olive oil in a large skillet over medium-high
heat. When hot, add shrimp, garlic, bell pepper and Scotch bonnet
pepper. Cook, stirring constantly, for about 3 to 4 minutes. Add
the curry powder and cook for an additional minute; then add the
coconut milk. Increase the heat to high and continue cooking,
stirring constantly, until the sauce has thickened and reduced
somewhat. Stir in the chopped cilantro and remove from heat. Serve
at once with the sweet potato fries, garnished generously with
cilantro leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 534 calories, 27 grams protein, 38 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 63), 25 grams carbohydrates, 172
milligrams cholesterol, 220 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
