<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0237 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-EGGS13-COX     07-12 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-EGGS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hold the mayo? With pasteurized eggs, not anymore
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've discovered mayonnaise.
</P>
<P>
   I realize this is a bit like saying Columbus discovered America,
never mind the folks who were already here. And I know some are
wondering how I could possibly be a true Southerner if I'm only now
discovering mayonnaise.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is I grew up on Miracle Whip. But I'm not talking about
Duke's or Hellman's anyway. I'm talking about the real stuff,
homespun with just the right drizzle of oil and squirt of lemon
juice.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I started venturing beyond cooking basics, health
safety experts were bellowing raw-egg warnings full blast. So
making something that consisted largely of raw eggs seemed like a
full-blown invitation to salmonella enteritis.
</P>
<P>
   Enter pasteurized eggs. Currently, Harris-Teeter grocery stores
have the exclusive rights on the eggs, sold under the brand name of
Davidson's. Soon they'll be offered in most major grocery store
chains. The eggs have been gently rolled through a series of warm
water baths to kill bacteria, making them safe for such once
forbidden delights as meringue, mousse and mayonnaise.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe tester Margaret Ann Surber and I recently put the eggs to
the test, to see how well they'd perform in a number of recipes
from simple scrambled eggs to a genoise.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the eggs performed well, with only slight differences
detectable in side-by-side taste tests. The home cook, of course,
is unlikely to be offering side-by-side samples. More likely, folks
will pick up a dozen to make a recipe calling for raw eggs and then
wonder if it's cool to use the rest in daily cooking.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is yes. With one exception, the differences are
slight. The pasteurized eggs have cloudy whites, a paler color and
a tad less flavor than regular eggs. This is most noticeable with
scrambled eggs, less so with baked goods.
</P>
<P>
   We tried the eggs in two different cakes _ a dense flourless
chocolate cake and a lighter, spongy genoise. In both cases, the
pasteurized egg batter puffed up more by about 20 percent. But once
cooled, it fell and was shorter than the cake made with regular
eggs. The taste was virtually the same.
</P>
<P>
   The big difference came with whipping egg whites. The
pasteurized eggs are harder to separate and the whites take much
longer to whip. We whipped five regular eggs to stiff peaks in 1
minute and 10 seconds, yielding 6 cups. The pasteurized eggs took 8
minutes and yielded only 3 1/2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   We used the whipped whites to make a chocolate mousse and found
both versions tasty, though the pasteurized egg version was thinner
because of less egg white volume.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, mayonnaise. Here, the pasteurized eggs work like
champs, accentuating the flavor of the oil and lemon. So, now that
it's safe, why not give homemade a try?
</P>
<P>
   Mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   Pour 1 3/4 cup oil into a measuring cup and set aside. It can be
vegetable oil or olive oil or a combination. In a blender or food
processor, add 1 whole egg, 2 egg yolks, 1/4 teaspoon dry mustard,
1/2 teaspoon salt and 1 teaspoon fresh lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   Begin blending on a medium speed and slowly drizzle in the oil.
It should take about 3 minutes to drizzle in 1 cup oil. Stop the
blender, stir and taste. Add more lemon juice if desired. Begin
blending again, taking another 2-3 minutes to drizzle in remaining
oil. You'll have about 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
