<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cobb salad isn't always what you think
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Usually a Cobb salad's a plateful of lettuce topped by your
favorite ingredients. Restaurants often serve them in the style of
the original, born at Hollywood's Brown Derby restaurant _ with
pretty lines of grilled chicken, avocados, blue cheese, bacon, eggs
and tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   June Florence of Douglasville, Ga., saw an all-fruit version on
a TV cooking show, but couldn't jot down the ingredients. So she
asked our readers for help.
</P>
<P>
   No one came forward, and a quick search at foodtv.com proved
futile.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, we came across a main-dish version that's Chicago
chef Charlie Trotter's favorite _ mesclun mix lined with grilled
beef, prosciutto, avocado and quail eggs. It's certain to appeal to
those with heartier summertime appetites for meatier toppings.
</P>
<P>
   As for the lighter fruit toppings, we'll keep searching.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Grilled Beef
</P>
<P>
   Tenderloin Cobb
</P>
<P>
   Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Trotter, known for his five-star namesake restaurant in
Chicago, five cookbooks and a television series called ``The
Kitchen Sessions With Charlie Trotter,'' says laying out the
ingredients in artful rows creates a striking composition that's
worth the extra trouble.
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup freshly squeezed lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh chives
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cups peeled and diced (see directions) red and yellow
tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   8 cups (about 1/2 pound) mesclun mix
</P>
<P>
   8 slices prosciutto
</P>
<P>
   16 quail eggs (available at Harry's Farmers Markets)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cups diced avocado (about 2 large, or 1 pound)
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces beef tenderloin, grilled, cooled and diced
</P>
<P>
   12 grilled green onions, chilled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cups crumbled blue cheese
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons 1-inch pieces chives
</P>
<P>
   To make the vinaigrette: Place shallot and lemon juice in a
small bowl. Slowly whisk in olive oil, fold in chopped chives and
season to taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare the salad: Bring a small pot of water to a boil.
Using a paring knife, cut a small X at the bottom of each tomato.
Put tomatoes in boiling water and let boil approximately 5 minutes.
Remove tomatoes. Peel and dice. Toss with 2 tablespoons vinaigrette
and season to taste. Set aside. Toss mesclun mix with half the
vinaigrette and season to taste. Set aside. Cut prosciutto into
narrow strips and set aside. Place quail eggs in a small pot of
water. Bring to a boil and cook for 5 minutes. Cool, peel and
quarter. Set aside. Peel and chop avocado and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place tenderloin on hot grill and cook for 15 to 20 minutes,
depending on thickness. Place green onions on grill and cook for 5
to 8 minutes, turning often and watching carefully because they can
burn quickly. When cool, cut tenderloin into cubes and chop onions.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange some of the mesclun greens in the center of each plate.
Place some of the prosciutto in a vertical line along the left side
of the greens. Next arrange some of the quail eggs, avocado,
tomatoes, beef, blue cheese and green onions. Top with freshly
ground black pepper and sprinkle with chive pieces. Drizzle with
remaining vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 698 calories, 35 grams protein, 55 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 71), 18 grams carbohydrates, 382
milligrams cholesterol, 1028 milligrams sodium, 8 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   Maybelle Mundy of Salley, S.C., has lost a recipe for a snack
made by putting together two pecan halves with a filling.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlatna Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
