<HEADER>
A0239 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-APARTMENT-REDO13-COX     07-12 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APARTMENT-REDO13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Apartment makeover that goes from drab to fab
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Little apartment, little furniture, little money? No problem.
With a little creativity, you can still turn the space you're in
into the home you want.
</P>
<P>
   Begin by picking a theme that reflects your personal style and
that makes the most of the furnishings you already have.
</P>
<P>
   If what you own is a product of garage sales, thrift shops and
hand-me-downs, think eclectic. When done right, the look can be hip
and Bohemian.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is to go for an ethnic theme that incorporates
accessories such as African sculptures, Asian screens or Indian
batik prints. One suggestion: Avoid the United Nations approach and
stick to one country.
</P>
<P>
   Got a sense of humor and a collection of offbeat whatnots? Go
kitsch. Or, if you prefer a chic, clean look without knickknacks,
try a minimalist theme.
</P>
<P>
   Defining your home's look is the easy part. The challenge is
putting it together without breaking your bank account.
</P>
<P>
   To demonstrate how to create your home's personalized look, we
consulted the professionals: Interior designers Candace A. McNair,
of Bright Ideas Interior Design in Marietta, Ga., and Heriberto J.
Brito and Margaret Gilchrist Serrato, of the Atlanta design firm
Brito Serrato.
</P>
<P>
   On a budget of $500 per room, the team transformed a dark,
sparsely furnished, one-bedroom unit at the Post Stratford
apartments in Buckhead into an inviting pad with an urban
contemporary theme. If $500 is too much for you right now, set a
figure that you can live with and take your time decorating.
There's no need to buy everything at once.
</P>
<P>
   The key to shopping is looking for merchandise that makes a
statement that's uniquely yours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always personalize with something nobody else has, whether
it's handmade or something from e-bay,'' advises Brito.
</P>
<P>
   LIVING/DINING ROOM
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The challenge: ``The room was very dull and cold,'' says
McNair. ``My job was to warm it up and give it personality and
character.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The solution: McNair created a boundary between the living and
dining areas by placing a brown print throw rug under the coffee
table. The colors in the rug coordinate with the gold-brown, green
and blue shades in the sofa and pillows. This helps draw attention
away from the mousy gray wall-to-wall carpet. Two of the four
dining table chairs were placed in the living room against a wall
facing the sofa. Fewer chairs made the dining area appear more
spacious. McNair placed multicolor square tableware on the dining
room table. The green bowl, yellow salad plate and blue dinner
plate complement the colors in the area rug and pillows on the
sofa. The square shape of the dishes resembles the square patterns
on the pillows, creating an effect of repetition. McNair made life
imitate art by putting fresh irises in a vase on the dining table,
to mirror a scene in a van Gogh print she hung on the dining room
wall. Faux grass in square metal containers was placed on either
side of the table settings to add a splash of greenery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every space needs a sense of humor. This brings a
little outdoors in, and it's just kind of fun,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other accessories purchased to jazz up the living/dining room
include metal picture frames for family photos, two pieces of
contemporary art for the walls, coffee-table books on Atlanta and
abstract art, an antique compote of Italian fruit, a rock fountain,
a silver vase and coaster set, and a trio of candles with glass
candleholders and decorative rocks.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Total for two rooms: $847.56
</P>
<P>
   BEDROOM
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The challenge: ``To work on a room that was claustrophobic,
dark and awkward to circulate in,'' says Brito.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The solution: He gave the room more space by removing a large
chest of drawers that swallowed an entire wall and by rearranging
the bed so the headboard can be seen from the hallway. Black
plastic modular drawers were placed side by side at the foot of the
bed, providing nine drawers for personal belongings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to have something at the end of the bed to hold bed
linen,'' Brito said.
</P>
<P>
   Brito and Serrato thought the room's table lamps were clunky, so
they replaced them with an adjustable goose-neck lamp for the night
table. A mirror was placed on the other night table to create an
illusion of space. They also put a floor lamp in a corner to bounce
light toward the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   The animal-print bedding gives the room a strong graphic pattern
and blends with the candles on the night stand.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of one large picture, Brito and Serrato put three
similarly themed pictures on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``They add a certain horizontal effect,'' Brito said.
</P>
<P>
   For final touches and to make the room feel homier, they added a
bed tray and a small handful of flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``One fresh flower can do more than two static arrangements,''
Brito said. ``You want to create visual impact by using quality,
not quantity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Total: $484
</P>
<P>
   KITCHEN
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The challenge: ``The kitchen was bland. It was black and
white, and it needed to have some personality and zip,'' McNair
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The solution: Fresh flowers and fruit placed in colorful
ceramic bowls and a miniature metal shopping cart add color,
texture and shape to the kitchen. Artificial fern and grape ivy
were spread on top of the cabinets to soften the room without
cluttering it. A teapot designed by architect Michael Graves and a
set of knives in a butcher-block holder from J. A. Henckles
International are both decorative and functional.
</P>
<P>
   McNair made the kitchen more inviting by adding cookbooks, a
miniature wicker chair that doubles as a conversation piece and
bookend, a framed mirror, a wall clock, a black leather throw rug,
checkered dish towels, a decorative olive oil set, a small black
easel that can be used for recipes or messages and a framed picture
of a chef.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Total: $418.23
</P>
<P>
   Photos shot on location at Post Stratford apartments in
Buckhead; flowers courtesy of Atlanta Wildflowers
</P>
<P>
   Decorating your pad
</P>
<P>
   Whether your pad is small, medium-sized or large, some general
things to take into consideration when decorating are:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lighting. Use it for warmth and function. Low voltage light is
clear and crisp and can be directed where it's needed most.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Furniture: Make sure the size of furniture fits the space.
Don't put large, oversized pieces in a small room unless you limit
it to one or two items. A sectional couch has limited use because
it is designed to fit an ``L'' shaped space and the units don't
separate well.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Think flexibility and dual-function when buying and arranging
furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Continuity: Don't send mixed signals when decorating. For
example, don't do one room in a contemporary theme and country in
another because it confuses the eye, especially in small
apartments.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mirrors reflect light and make a room feel more open. Candles
soften a room and provide a sense of peace and tranquility.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Area rugs can be used to define space, provide color and
texture or mask badly stained or ugly carpets. When using more than
one rug, make sure they are compatible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Eliminate clutter. Edit your rooms by removing objects you
don't use or that don't blend with the decor. Keep it simple,
whatever the theme.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When decorating on a thin budget, visit garage sales, thrift
shops, Dollar stores and discount chains. Furniture that requires
assembly looks good and can tide you over until you can afford
better quality items. Go to stores out of your price range to scout
for items you like. Then look for knockoffs at stores you can
afford.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Deep warm colors such as reds, oranges and yellows make a room
feel intimate and cozy. Cool colors such as blues and greens make a
room seem more spacious. If your landlord won't let you paint white
or neutral toned walls, play up your color scheme with curtains,
pillows, lamps, candles, throws, rugs and other accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.apartmentstyle.bigstep.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.soyouwanna.com
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
