<HEADER>
A0240 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE13-COX     07-12 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Neighborly chats now extend beyond the fence
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gardeners always have known that talking about plants, sharing
experiences, is a large part of what makes digging in the dirt such
a powerful connection. What gardener hasn't chatted with a stranger
at a nursery, making a comfortable acquaintance _ and sometimes a
friend?
</P>
<P>
   These days, gardening chats extend beyond the neighborly fence
and the plant nursery and the words on paper. Now, more and more,
we chat electronically. Not that our e-chats ever will replace
face-to-face ones, but what a pleasure it is to read impassioned
words about the natural world, transmitted through technology so
different from a shovelful of dirt. Thankfully, such chats make the
technology seem more a part of life, natural life.
</P>
<P>
   Here's some of my electronic gardening talk with Alice Bengel of
Norcross, Ga., who writes about her coneflower conversion and a
revealing visit to an area store:
</P>
<P>
   I stood before an outdoor display of sun-parched perennials,
mostly coneflowers, that had been badly neglected. Bone dry, the
soil in their one-gallon pots was cracked and had pulled away from
the edges. Many were wilted to the point of being crisp, but as I
picked through them, I saw that some were merely limp and perhaps
salvageable. For the others, most of which were echinacea's stately
'Bravado' variety, I had simply arrived too late.
</P>
<P>
   When we purchased our first house in the winter of 1996, we
unknowingly inherited several perennial beds and a mailbox full of
gardening catalogs addressed to the former occupants or ``current
resident.'' The gorgeous blooms in the catalogs hypnotized me, and
it was in those catalogs that I saw my first purple coneflower. It
did not impress me. It was too simple, not showy enough, weedy
even, and I allowed myself to be seduced by more delicate and
graceful flowers as I eagerly filled out the order forms, sans
coneflowers.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, though, I found myself turning back to the
coneflowers. I studied the catalog photos and looked up echinacea
in my brand-new gardening books. Drought-tolerant, I found. Grows
in full sun or part shade. Tolerates poor soil. As I continued to
study the pictures and pore over their descriptions, I felt a
conversion taking place. I planted my first purple coneflowers last
summer _ in the voids left by the more delicate and graceful
flowers that had failed me -_ and they have exceeded my
expectations. I am hooked.
</P>
<P>
   I have found a kinship with these plants, seen their inner
beauty even asl as yet, and with the rest of a parched summer ahead
of them, they are not out of the woods. As forecasts call for much
sun and little rain, planting perennials over July 4 weekend is
barely short of reckless. Still, I could no more have left them
where they were than I could have left a friend in a pit of
alligators.
</P>
<P>
   Hello, Alice Bengel,
</P>
<P>
   I do understand. Many a time I've rescued suffering but not yet
dead plants from killer nurseries.
</P>
<P>
   Your conversion is familiar. And I predict it will intensify. I
am drawn to natives for all the reasons you know _ their hardiness,
drought-tolerance. Increasingly, I love them for their essence;
native plants dispense with frills but don't skimp on beauty and
fragrance. Their sharp smells and lean profiles and natural angles
provide pleasures unrivaled by cultivated cousins.
</P>
<P>
   While your holiday weekend focused on planting rescued
coneflowers, mine was spent on my spit of land in Fannin County,
Ga., putting in gift plants from friends across the ridge in Rabun:
mountain mint, big-leaf trillium, ginseng, bee balm. Great joy. For
you, too, with coneflowers, I hope.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
