r l BC-TV-EXPERT13-COX     07-12 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-EXPERT13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lifetime's Katie Brown puts paint, borders in prime spot
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Katie Brown, a lifestyle expert and host of Lifetime
TV's ``Next Door With Katie Brown,'' knows how to decorate a home
on the cheap. For her, it's all about color.
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite decorating tool when you don't have much money is
paint,'' Brown said during a recent visit to Atlanta. ``You bring
more life in with shades of yellow, blue and colors you find in
nature.''
</P>
<P>
   If you can't paint an entire room or accent wall, you can
improvise by designing your own border.
</P>
<P>
   They are easy to make with brown packing tape, Brown said. The
adhesive backing is strong enough to stick to walls without
buckling and can be removed without chipping paint.
</P>
<P>
   To create a border: Trace the pattern you want to use; cut out
the pattern and glue it to a sanding block; dip the block in paint
and blot it on the smooth side of the tape until the strip is
covered. When it dries, apply the tape to the wall as you would any
border.
</P>
<P>
   Other tips from Brown:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Paint mismatched wood furniture with a colorful, high-gloss
marine paint to make the pieces look uniform and coordinated.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Have photos or postcards enlarged to be used as pictures.
Purchase inexpensive picture frames from a discount or thrift
store. Border the glass on the frame with etching cream to create a
mat effect. Let dry, then insert the photo or postcard in the frame
and hang.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Give a bed without a headboard a new look with a curtain rod.
Install the rod behind the bed and drape a sheet around it that
matches your bedding or decor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make reversible curtains using winter and summer fabrics. Sew
the two sides together and hang on top of blinds, with the pattern
appropriate for the season facing the room.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Improve the lighting in your home by purchasing inexpensive
lamps from garage sales or thrift stores. Then replace the shades
with new ones that blend with your decor.
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
