<HEADER>
A0242 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-INTERNET-ALOFT-2T     07-12 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-INTERNET-ALOFT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-BANDWIDTH WEB CONNECTIONS WILL LET PASSENGERS SURF AS THEY
FLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By IAN AUSTEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many people have fallen for the lure of high-speed Internet
access only to find it hard to get. Now Boeing is promising to make
it available to people traveling 500 miles per hour at 30,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Airplanes stopped being a refuge for business travelers when
satellite telephones were installed. On many planes, passengers can
make calls or send and receive e-mail messages (to some extent).
</P>
<P>
   The next step, according to a partnership led by Boeing Co., is
to develop Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at this major piece of time that could and
should be more productively used,'' said Kenneth Medlin, vice
president and general manager of Boeing Commercial Information
Systems, a unit of the Boeing Space and Communications Group.
</P>
<P>
   This broadband access, expected to become available on some
domestic flights late next year, will let people surf the Web and
send e-mail messages and other files at an impressive rate:
messages will be uploaded at 1.5 megabits per second _ about the
same speed as a T-1 line found in many offices _ and Web pages will
be downloaded at 5 megabits per second, the rate of a smooth
functioning cable modem link.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in a world where maintaining a reliable link to the
Internet from a fixed desk is sometimes a challenge, trying to do
the same thing in an airplane is particularly daunting.
</P>
<P>
   Even though some planes allow passengers to make calls and send
and receive e-mail, such service is spotty and slow, limited on
some systems to 64 kilobits per second. The key to the increased
capacity of the Boeing system is the antenna, Medlin said.
</P>
<P>
   A system like this, he said, must rely on the use of satellites
to relay signals. Communications satellites have large coverage
areas, and transmissions from airplanes would generally be
unobstructed. To achieve the speed needed for high-bandwidth
connections, the Boeing system will rely on high-frequency
satellites, which are now primarily used by television networks to
beam their broadcasts to local stations and cable companies as well
as by telephone companies for moving large numbers of long-distance
calls.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a catch. Satellites, unlike most ground-based radio
systems, can send and receive signals only through relatively
narrow, focused radio waves.
</P>
<P>
   To make things simple for customers on the ground, most
communications satellites are placed in geostationary orbits. That
is, they match Earth's rotation so they stay above the same spot.
Because of that, ground-based satellite users aim their dishes at a
single fixed point in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Airliners, of course, are anything but stationary, so a
geostationary satellite becomes a moving target. Space shuttles
avoid the problem by communicating with ground-based satellite
dishes that move mechanically to follow their flight. But designing
a conventional dish that is light enough to install on aircraft but
can respond to every twist and turn is impractical.
</P>
<P>
   Instead Boeing and its partners are using an antenna technology
that can electronically steer its radio beams. One thousand small
antenna modules, each shaped more like a jumbo pizza box than an
antenna dish, are joined into a single grid. Boeing began
developing these phased-array antennas 16 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   A computer on the aircraft directs the beam by altering the
synchronization of the individual radio waves generated by the
antenna modules. The signals from the individual antenna modules
ultimately combine into a single beam in much the same way that a
pianist combines several notes to create a chord. The antenna's
computer alters the beam's direction by changing the pattern that
joins the signals into the final beam.
</P>
<P>
   The antenna computer's work does not stop there. Just as a cell
phone switches from one transmitter's territory to another's, the
antenna computer must be able to jump from one satellite to another
as the aircraft moves. A link between the system and the aircraft's
flight control systems allow it to monitor the airplane's motion,
adjusting the signal to compensate for turns and altitude changes.
</P>
<P>
   A prototype of the Connexion system is being tested, and the
final version is expected to consist of two phase-array antennas,
each about 18 inches long, 15 inches wide and 2{ inches thick, on
the top of the fuselage. One is for receiving, the other for
transmitting. A cable connects the antenna to the computer inside
the aircraft, and the computer is linked to a conventional Web and
e-mail server.
</P>
<P>
   All of that will be invisible to passengers. What they will see,
Medlin said, are two jacks on back of the seat in front of them.
One would be for users with conventional modems in their laptop
computers. Their Web surfing would be limited to the maximum speeds
of their modems. The other jack would be a standard Ethernet
connection, like those commonly found in offices. People with
Ethernet cards will be able to plug in to those jacks to get the
system's full high-speed experience.
</P>
<P>
   Such service is likely to cost $20 to $25 per hour, Medlin said,
but Boeing and its partners _ Loral Space &AMP; Communications,
Mitsubishi and Finmeccanica _ must still work out details with
airlines. Some services, like online duty-free shopping, travel
information and live television programs, will probably be offered
for free, Medlin said. CNN Inflight Services and CNBC are also
expected to provide news programs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Before service begins, Boeing would have to show the Federal
Aviation Administration that the system would not interfere with
the aircraft's communications or electronic operations. The system
is designed for installation on all major airliners, including
those made by Airbus Industrie, Boeing's rival.
</P>
<P>
   While Medlin expects service to begin in the United States late
next year, the rest of the world will take a bit longer. That is
because there are few television viewers _ and therefore few
geostationary satellites _ in the middle of the oceans. Medlin said
Loral was developing satellites that would be able to deflect a
portion of their signals into regions not served by high-frequency
satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing will not be alone. Inmarsat, a satellite operator in
London that said it provides phone service in 78 percent of the
world's long-haul airliners, is developing a system that would be
based on a new generation of satellites. Until that system becomes
available in 2004, Inmarsat plans to offer a service beginning next
year that allows Web browsing and e-mail exchanges at 64 kilobits
per second, slightly faster than the best dial-in modems.
</P>
<P>
   And some airlines are looking at systems that at least simulate
the experience of on-board e-mail by gathering messages in an
on-board server, which then downloads the messages and sends them
on after the plane lands.
</P>
<P>
   What about those business travelers who view airplanes as a
place to rest rather than as a flying office? Medlin insisted that
high-bandwidth connections will make their lives even better.
</P>
<P>
   When he returns from a long flight, Medlin said, the first thing
he does is go to a home office to exchange e-mail messages with his
office. But once he is able to do that while flying, Medlin said,
he will be able to devote that time to his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really gives people back time,'' he said. ``I would
rather have my leisure time when I want it, rather than have it
forced into two or three hours on an airplane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
