<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0246 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-RAID-NYT &LR;      07-12 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-RAID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXECUTIVES OF RUSSIA'S BIGGEST AUTOMAKER CHARGED WITH TAX EVASION 
</HEADLINE>
   By SABRINA TAVERNISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Russian authorities brought tax evasion charges
Wednesday against top executives at the country's biggest
automaker, as part of President Vladimir Putin's stated campaign to
loosen the grip of Russia's richest men on the country s most
profitable enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   The charges came a day after the authorities filed suit against
managers at Russia's biggest oil company, also on charges of tax
evasion. Since May, the authorities have swept through offices of
media and oil companies, and have brought charges against others.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's against the carmaker AvtoVAZ targets another of
Russia's most influential men, Boris Berezovsky. A member of
Parliament and a friend of former President Boris Yeltsin s family,
Berezovsky helped create the company that owns a third of AvtoVAZ.
</P>
<P>
   In his election campaign earlier this year, Putin vowed to limit
the influence of Russia s oligarchs, the handful of businessmen who
amassed fortunes during the sale of prize assets over the last
decade, and who at times have influenced government policy. But
critics say the crackdowns could lead to another selective
distribution of property.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a saying about catching fish in muddy waters,'' Putin
said in a television interview with Reuters. ``There are fishermen
here who have already caught a lot and want to keep the situation
as it is for a long-term historical period. I don't think this is
acceptable for the Russian people or for our partners abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   AvtoVAZ, a longtime tax deadbeat, also was raided in May. The
company last year handed the government a controlling stake in
exchange for delaying the payment of about $100 million in tax
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the tax police accused the company of hiding sales by
duplicating car serial numbers to avoid taxes. A company spokesman
denied the charges and said AvtoVAZ had already filed suit against
a previous tax audit.
</P>
<P>
   With a factory in southern Russia built by Fiat of Italy,
AvtoVAZ produces about three-quarters of Russia's cars. The company
has been in talks with General Motors on setting up a joint
venture, though GM has refrained from setting a starting date.
</P>
<P>
   Investors and ordinary citizens have applauded Putin's efforts
to curb the influence of the oligarchs. The benchmark RTS stock
index rose 2.8 percent Wednesday, and Putin's popularity ratings
remain high.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, top executives at Lukoil Holding, Russia's biggest
oil company, were accused of tax evasion, while investigators
demanded that Vladimir Potanin, who has vast holdings in Russian
banks, metals and media companies, reimburse the state for losses
incurred during a privatization in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In comments carried on Russian television, the tax police chief,
Vyacheslav Soltaganonv, said the police planned to bring charges
against another company on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 1757EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
