<SLUG> BC-FBN-NINERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NINERS NAME NEW PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRUCE ADAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ The San Francisco 49ers on Wednesday named
a former toy company executive to take over the franchise as
president.
</P>
<P>
   Peter L. Harris, who in 1985 resurrected failing FAO Schwarz,
will run business operations, while General Manager Bill Walsh will
continue to oversee the football side of the business.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of Harris' agenda will be the ambitious football
stadium and shopping mall proposed by former owner Edward DeBartolo
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the project at Candlestick Point were reborn _ and the
search for the new president intensified _ in March, when the lines
of team ownership finally were cleared.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo, who owned the team for 23 years, and his sister,
Denise DeBartolo York, agreed then that she would take full
ownership of the team while he would assume the majority of the
family's substantial real estate holdings.
</P>
<P>
   She took control of the team in 1997 when her brother took a
leave after becoming involved in a federal gambling probe in
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, the NFL prohibited DeBartolo from being
involved with the team while that fraud investigation continued.
(Former Louisiana Gov. Edwin W. Edwards was convicted of
racketeering and fraud in May, largely on DeBartolo's testimony
that he paid Edwards $400,000 to facilitate a gambling and real
estate project in the state.)
</P>
<P>
   The franchise's leadership was further set back when Carmen
Policy resigned as president July 21, 1998, to accept a similar
position with the start-up franchise Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Larry Thrailkill acted as president. But his primary
job remained chief operating officer for the DeBartolo Corp. Most
recently, York's husband, John York, has run the team under the
title of vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the new stadium stalled during the family fight over
team ownership, including a dispute over who held the rights to
developing that project.
</P>
<P>
   At the NFL owners meeting in March, York said that the 49ers
were ready to get moving on the stadium project and replace aging
Candlestick Park with a football-only facility. He said the first
order of business would be to try to restore the combination
stadium-shopping complex as envisioned by his brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, 56, brings a reputation as a strong businessman. At FAO
Schwarz, he increased profits fourfold in five years. He heads
Picture People, a studio portrait chain based in Foster City,
Calif., that has grown to 183 franchises in 19 states. Before that
he worked at Accolade, a video game company in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The Yorks live in Youngstown, Ohio, and have said all along they
intended to hire a full-time president to take over at the team
headquarters in Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   Others considered in the search included Carl Pascarelle, chief
executive and president of Visa U.S.A., and Gene Washington, a
former 49ers player and the NFL's director of operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
