<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, July 13, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a comfortably cool dawn, humidity will gradually increase
over the Northeast, setting the stage for unsettled weather in the
next several days. Thursday will have sun mixing with increasing
clouds, especially over the interior. Scattered thundershowers will
develop near the central Appalachians as moist air flows north
along the west slopes of the mountain chain.
</P>
<P>
   Some sunshine and sultry air will combine to promote scattered
strong thunderstorms from the Carolinas to the Gulf Coast States.
Meanwhile, dull conditions and patchy rain will occur near the
southern Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   The very warm air mass that has covered much of the eastern
Rockies and southern Plains for the past two weeks will remain in
place. Afternoon thunderstorms will erupt over the mountains of New
Mexico and Colorado and will drift into parts of the western Plains
before sunset.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: COLD DAYS IN JULY
</P>
<P>
   In Albany, N.Y., the first 10 days of July were colder than any
such period since records began in 1874. The average temperature of
67.3 degrees was nearly 5 degrees a day below the seasonal average.
The early summer pattern near North America has been dominated by
two prominent zones of warm high pressure; one centered in the
Plains and another near Bermuda. Cool air masses from eastern
Canada regularly have been able to flow south between the two
bubbles of heat bringing refreshing air masses into parts of the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
