<P>
   VIETNAM-U.S.-TRADE (Undated) _ After more than four years of
negotiations, the United States and Vietnam plan to sign a historic
trade pact later this week or early next week, trade sources said
Wednesday. (Summary from wires) By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   This story was filed Tuesday night, in full and abridged
versions:
</P>
<P>
   RACE-HOUSTON (Houston) _ In Houston, the fourth-largest city in
the United States, blacks, Anglos and Hispanics each make up
roughly a third of the population. So the election in 1998 of Lee
P. Brown as the city's first black mayor was more than a
celebration of victory for blacks. It was also a testament to how
racial and ethnic groups in Houston had put aside their suspicions
and rivalries and come together largely out of self-interest to
achieve power. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT150-156, moved 7-11.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteenth and last in the series, ``How Race Is Lived in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ On the second day of the Camp
David summit meeting, Israel announced that it had canceled its
sale of a sophisticated airborne radar system to China, a decision
that came after harsh congressional criticism and personal requests
from President Clinton to halt the $250 million deal. The move
appeared carefully calibrated to improve the mood in Congress for
Israel's request for increased military assistance if some kind of
peace accord is reached between the Palestinians and Israelis. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-PRICES (Undated) _ Gasoline prices have risen sharply, but
the owners of gasoline stations are not benefiting from higher
prices at the pump. Elsewhere along the supply chain, however,
higher gasoline and oil prices have meant staggering profits: Major
oil companies are expected to report earnings growth of 117 percent
on average for the second quarter, compared with the quarter a year
ago. Such prosperity has attracted the notice of a number of
politicians, including Vice President Al Gore, and the Federal
Trade Commission has started an inquiry into possible industry
collusion. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   GENERIC-DRUGS-SUIT (Washington) _ Mylan Laboratories, the FTC,
and 35 states announce they are on the verge of completing a $147
million settlement to resolve the lawsuit that had accused the
company of violating antitrust laws by cornering the market on raw
materials and then jacking up the price of generic drugs. By
Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DEATH-PENALTY (Houston) _ Folo on reports that new DNA
tests have failed to exonerate a Texas inmate, Ricky McGinn, who
given a reprieve by Gov. George W. Bush last month. McGinn is
fighting convictions on rape and murder charges and his lawyers had
sought additional DNA testing. (Summary from wires) By Jim Yardley.
</P>
</TEXT>
