<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0264 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-CHAPTER&AMP;VERSE-TEX     07-12 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF RELIGIOUS BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Owl, the Raven, &AMP; the Dove'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By G. Ronald Murphy, $25 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Oxford University Press) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before Harry Potter was a twinkle in J.K. Rowling's literary
eye, Wilhelm and Jacob Grimm were telling magic stories now
familiar to all: Snow White and the evil queen who must dance in
red-hot shoes until she dies; Cinderella and her two stepsisters,
who mutilate their feet to try to win the prince ...
</P>
<P>
   Not so familiar after all? Well, these are the versions of the
Brothers Grimm, not Walt Disney; and G. Ronald Murphy's ``The Owl,
the Raven, &AMP; the Dove: The Religious Meaning of the Grimms' Magic
Fairy Tales'' has other surprises in store, as well.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers saw their stories as ``precious crumbs of ancient
faith,'' writes Murphy, a Jesuit priest and Georgetown University
professor. Murphy's quest is to tease out the symbols that he sees
therein, so that Hansel and Gretel's nibbling on the crone's house
echoes the forbidden fruit episode in Eden, and Red Riding Hood's
gift looks much like Holy Communion.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy makes a fair case for his thesis, and he keeps things
lively by recounting other versions of the tales. (One
Cinderella-esque story dates to the first century B.C.) ``The Owl,
the Raven, &AMP; the Dove'' is an interesting bit of literary
investigation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Salvador'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Salvador &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Myrrh Records &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Christian music marketplace owes a debt of thanks to a
couple of decidedly secular acts, Ricky Martin and Santana. Latino
music is hot, and that paved the way for one of the most refreshing
albums to hit Christian music in a while.
</P>
<P>
   The album is the self-titled debut from Salvador, a five-member
group based in Austin. Brothers Nick and Art Gonzales and cousin
Josh Gonzales, along with Eliot Torres and Adrian Lopez, deliver a
fun, high-energy album of Latin-infused pop, heavy on horns and
percussion.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of slower, introspective songs, including the
powerful ``Cry Holy,'' which was written by Bill and Gloria
Gaither's son, Benji. But the emphasis is on the up-tempo stuff,
songs meant to capture the joy of Christian life. ``Lord I Come
Before You,'' the first song on the CD, has a Santana-type feel,
with pounding drums and guitar solos.
</P>
<P>
   Salvador _ Spanish for ``savior'' _ pays homage to their
heritage by including a couple of songs in Spanish, including
``Montana,'' an upbeat version of an old Spanish song of faith.
</P>
<P>
   In any language, this is an outstanding album. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Simon Gonzalez
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
