<HEADER>
A0267 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FORLOVE-OFMUSIC-1800(     07-12 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORLOVE-OFMUSIC-1800(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL-TIME MUSICIANS DON'T LONG FOR THE BIG TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: food or beer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for the Gospel Swingers, an over-the-top,
punk-meets-R&AMP;B outfit led by Fort Worth resident Quincy Holloway,
who is also a member of the dub-rock band Sub Oslo. Every member of
the Swingers, which formed two years ago, is or has been affiliated
with other underground rock outfits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never included myself in the mainstream of anything,''
Merlick says. ``That's definitely gonna be reflected in the music
that I play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gospel Swingers are definitely an acquired taste. At a
recent show opening for Dallas alternative-country giants the Old
97's, a good chunk of the crowd either turned away or looked
horrified, the band's noisy mingling of rock and R&AMP;B apparently too
unconventional for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in the band is the same way, fortunately. We've never
listened to mainstream rock or FM radio,'' Merlick says. ``We're
not interested in what's popular or what most people like.''
</P>
<P>
   The band _ which, in step with its anti-popularity disposition,
refused to have traditional photos taken for this article _ plays
gigs at small, punk-rock venues such as Rubber Gloves Rehearsal
Studios in Denton; their day jobs, mostly computer-related, pay the
bills. The swingers are among the few high-profile local bands that
do not have a CD.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say the Swingers are unambitious; the band _ which
is rounded out by bassist Alex Sargent, organ player Kari Luna and
drummer Steve Adkins _ simply does things on a smaller scale than
other bands.
</P>
<P>
   They have two singles scheduled for release this year, but
they're on small labels, one of which is Swedish. If a larger label
approached, Merlick says, they would at least hear it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would at least entertain the idea'' of signing, he says.
``But that's not what I'm looking for. Right now, this band is just
a way to express myself creatively. If I was doing this to make
money, I would have given up a long time ago.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An African-American man with hair as white as the ice in his
drink, Al Dupree sits at his grand piano at Dallas' Balcony Club,
gently plucking its keys. Drummer Bobby Samuels and bassist Charles
Nugent are nearby, surveying the room, which is filled with an
older slice of Dallas' yupscale population, most of whom drink and
smoke and talk loudly. At least they clap when the trio is finished
playing a song.
</P>
<P>
   On the piano sits a tip jar; it has about three ones in it.
</P>
<P>
   This is how the 77-year-old Dupree makes his living these days,
playing four to five nights a week at this quaint club tucked
inside Dallas' historic Lakewood Theater. He gets a regular check
from the club, plus tips. Combined with his retirement check from
the Postal Service, Dupree says, he makes enough to scrape by,
occasionally help out his three kids.
</P>
<P>
   Dupree is the epitome of the musician who has absolutely no
desire to become popular. He has played in uncelebrated bands all
his life _ since 1937 to be exact, when he was 13 _ and he says
he's had no reason to change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``My philosophy is and has always been, if I can pay my bills
and have a dollar left over, I'm happy,'' Dupree says. ``Because
you don't take anything with you when you're gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Trained in piano at age 5, clarinet at 11 and saxophone at 12,
Dupree grew up in the Dallas area and attended school at Booker T.
Washington, where he joined his first group; he looks back at his
beginning years with a combination of fondness and longing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started playing, you could bring your children to the
clubs and enjoy a good show without worrying about what's reaching
their ears,'' he says. ``You wouldn't wanna take your children to a
show today; the music's so sexist now. Unless you just don't
care.''
</P>
<P>
   Dupree's music then, as now, was steeped in the roots of jazz.
He names Duke Ellington as a major influence. At the Balcony Club,
that influence is evident, as he and his band play romantic,
complex ballads and upbeat free-for-alls.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunities for him to cash in have come and gone throughout
his career; he didn't jump on any of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music is something that's a part of me. It's just like my
right arm or my eyes,'' he says. ``But frankly, I've never seen any
point at being popular. I just don't even worry about it. I've been
like this all my life. To hell with it if people don't understand
that. That's the way I am.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
