<SLUG> BC-FORLOVE-OFMUSIC-1800(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL-TIME MUSICIANS DON'T LONG FOR THE BIG TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not every musician makes it big. Not every musician wants to.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of people play music simply for the love of it. They're
not concerned about signing with a big record label. They don't
hound the news media for coverage. Money to pay the bills _ that's
good enough for them.
</P>
<P>
   These are the musicians and singers who play the gigs that no
one else will: a Wednesday night at a hole-in-the-wall, a punk-rock
club hidden on the outskirts of town, a hotel bar, a restaurant.
They're so far in the background as to be almost invisible, their
music buried under loud conversation, bar glasses clinking,
obnoxious, inattentive audiences.
</P>
<P>
   As Al Dupree, George Norris and the members of the Gospel
Swingers will tell you, it can be a tough life, especially if
performing is their only income source. But shying away from the
music industry in favor of doing things independently does have its
rewards. And in the eyes of these musicians, those rewards are far
more important than fame. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a Wednesday night at the White Elephant Saloon in the Fort
Worth Stockyards, and George Norris is playing to, well, virtually
no one. Two guys sit at the bar and smoke. A table full of rowdy
yahoos orders several rounds of drinks. Tourists peek in and out.
</P>
<P>
   The night after July 4 is notoriously slow for live music, but
Norris is undaunted. For 20 years, he has had a regular gig at the
Elephant, playing early, weekday shows, afternoon matinees, the
occasional Friday or Saturday night; he has seen his share of empty
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   And some full ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heck, we used to be the only thing on the block,'' says the
52-year-old singer, who started playing the Elephant a few years
after it opened, way before Billy Bob's Texas and all the other
clubs in the Stockyards arrived.
</P>
<P>
   His set is a simple one: He plays solo, accompanied only by an
acoustic guitar and a drum machine, which he controls with the
twist of a knob. Most of his material belongs to someone else:
Willie Nelson, Johnny Cash, George Jones, all the country greats.
</P>
<P>
   There's no original material in his set, and Norris has never
released a CD of his own. ``I don't write,'' he says
matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   But Norris is not a novelty act, nor should he be dismissed as a
one-man cover band; he is an apt musician, a strong, robust singer,
and he has stage presence to spare. On a dead night, he cracks
jokes, and the few listeners are
</P>
<P>
   immediately entranced.
</P>
<P>
   Performing is old hat to Norris; he's been on stage since he was
14. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my first show was my 14th birthday,'' says Norris.
``I've played in all kinds of bands: rock bands, jazz bands,
country bands. But everything I did had a country sound to it, so I
thought I'd just go back to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brushes with fame have come and gone. In the late '60s, Norris
and a drummer friend moved from Texas to Hollywood, searching for
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't find very much,'' Norris says, laughing. ``I was a
country boy in the wrong place. It was a good experience, but I
really couldn't make a living out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Norris moved back at just the right time _ when a new club was
opening. ``Two weeks after I got back home, a guy called and asked
if I wanted to play a new private club that was opening in a
hotel,'' he said. ``From then on, I've been working pretty
steadily.''
</P>
<P>
   Solo and with a band, Norris played a local-music circuit that
took him to clubs, hotels and piano bars. His other brush with fame
came in Abilene, where he and his band often performed with
then-unknowns Johnny Bush and Johnny Paycheck. In the late '70s the
Elephant opened, and Norris has since taken up permanent residence.
</P>
<P>
   When he was younger, Norris admits, fame was an issue. Today,
with a wife and two boys in their late teens, it's not.
</P>
<P>
   Success ``has always been on my mind,'' he says. ``But I know as
you get older, the chances of becoming successful go down. So it's
not the driving force in my life anymore. You know what I'm
concerned about now? Going to Little League baseball games with my
kids. I mean, I'm able to make a living at a place that I like,
around people I like, doing what I like. That's good enough for
me.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chris Merlick started playing in bands in 1984; he's been broke
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 20 years, Merlick has been in bands that buck the
mainstream. He is a longtime Dallas-based musician who has played
drums and guitar for several area punk-rock and underground groups
_ bands whose left-of-center sensibilites are not rewarded with a
lot of money. What little his bands have made is spent on gas, food
or beer. MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
