<SLUG> BC-CIR-DAIKANTANA-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A SHOOT-'EM-UP, THREE'S COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By PETER OLAFSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; John Romero's ``Daikatana,'' from Eidos Interactive; for
Windows 95, 98 and NT; $39.95; for mature players. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I will say this for John Romero's ``Daikatana'': For better or
worse, it has kept me company.
</P>
<P>
   One of the defining qualities of three-dimensional shoot-'em-ups
has been solitude. Invariably, you are on your own in a
persistently evil world. Enemies are everywhere, friends are rare
and allies rarer.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, ``Half-Life'' adjusted that equation. While still
centered on the player's character, it allowed you to recruit
security guards and scientists who would obligingly follow you
through the ravaged Black Mesa complex, opening locked doors and
fighting to the death on your behalf. But these helpers operated
within a limited area, accepted a narrow range of commands and
ignored all the weapons and supplies lying around on the floor. And
they didn't have much personality. Indeed, they were pretty much
interchangeable.
</P>
<P>
   Allies with personality is the defining feature of
``Daikatana,'' which gives the main character two sidekicks, named
Superfly Johnson and Mikiko Ebihara. They are more than interactive
flotsam and jetsam. Once recruited by the player, they follow the
main character, Hiro Miyamoto, from level to level. You can order
them to fight, back off, hold position, follow the player or
retrieve equipment for their own use. (Just as Hiro does, each
sidekick has levels of health and armor.) You can't complete a
section of the game without the sidekicks' accompanying you in
close formation, and if one of them dies, the game ends.
</P>
<P>
   This long-awaited shooter sends the player through 24 enormous
levels in four time periods _ ranging from ancient Greece to
25th-century Japan _ to seek out a mythic sword of power and
restore life to a dark and decimated world. I found Johnson _ a
bald bruiser with revenge in his heart _ suspended from a torture
machine in a prison in the Japanese segment. (Mikiko turns up in a
frozen laboratory toward the end of the same segment.) Johnson, a
former security chief at the jail, proved pleasantly adept at
clearing a room, obeying orders and keeping pace with my character.
He climbed ladders, rode elevators and vaulted over gaps without
special handling. Following me (as Hiro) at a significant distance,
Johnson made his way through a series of rooms, jumped onto two
wall fixtures and then a bookcase and crouched to enter the duct
where I was waiting. When I sought to retrace my steps to the duct
entrance, he turned around before I reached him and headed back the
way we had come. Along the way, he commented on the grisly
discoveries our little party made, and if I bumped into him, he
told me off. He also gave me a hard time if I took too long to find
a way out of a dead end.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Johnson had his faults. He lacked a certain level of
self-awareness, and I had to guard against random acts of
stupidity. Although he was initially unarmed, he took off with a
vengeance after the first enemy he spotted and took him out, only
to be immediately blindsided by a giant, missile-firing robot.
</P>
<P>
   When I dropped down an elevator shaft, Johnson failed to follow.
And he was nowhere in sight when I finally made my way back to the
top of the shaft. I had to restore a saved game and order him to
stay at a crucial location.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I found it agreeable to look after someone else's
welfare. Even in a shoot-'em-up with the noblest of story lines,
you can wind up feeling as if you are on a one-man killing spree _
an ugly sensation. Shepherding other characters through this
gantlet lends the game a sense of community. It was not so much you
against them as us against them. And this sense of community became
even more palpable when the two sidekicks started talking to each
other.
</P>
<P>
   The sidekicks are not ``Daikatana's'' only strong point. The
layout of the levels recalls classics like ``Doom'' and ``Quake'' _
games Romero helped create before leaving Id Software to become a
founder of Ion Storm, the company that developed ``Daikatana.''
These levels use space creatively. They abound in side roads,
hideaways and secrets within secrets, and they dare and defy you to
explore them thoroughly. Occasionally, wandering through explored
terrain, I would wend my way to a place that I did not recognize,
and that was a nice feeling.
</P>
<P>
   But although I am almost a quarter of the way through the game,
``Daikatana'' has yet to mature into the sum of its interesting
parts. It may have to do with the game's soporific opening
sequence. It may be the background noise. Johnson's idle chatter
quickly became annoying and the high-pitched screaming that issued
from the industrial workers in the Japanese levels when they saw a
monster almost induced me to join them. Maybe it was the monsters
themselves, which for all the effort put into the artificial
intelligence of your allies were as dumb as the monsters in any
shooter I have played. (I have yet to find a monster that puts the
fear of God into me.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the other innovations were not as effective as
``Daikatana's'' use of sidekicks. The gems you will need to find to
save a game are a clever twist that entices the player into
``Daikatana's'' many remote and secret areas. But they can also be
infuriating. Every time you save, it costs you a gem. You may not
find another until you have completed a run of difficult action
sequences, and hence will have to repeat the tougher sections until
you find one. In the apparently gem-free bowels of one level, I
must have fallen to my death a dozen times or more while trying to
cross a volcanic chasm.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ``Daikatana'' borrows a page from role-playing
games. For each kill, Hiro receives experience points that allow
him to advance to higher levels. At each level, the player can
assign a point to make him faster or to enhance one of four other
skills. But this tends to reiterate, rather than supplement,
tendencies that occur naturally within ``Daikatana.'' For example,
even without an enhanced attack skill, the weapons you find grow
more powerful as you progress into the game. The ability to
increase the player's maximum vitality doesn't feel meaningful in
an environment strewn with health-replenishing supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Romero has hit upon something with the sidekick
idea, and it will be interesting to see where he goes with it. I
would like to see interactive dialogue _ perhaps via an ``advise''
command that would allow the sidekicks to offer tips within their
areas of expertise _ and the ability to direct a character to a
specific location.
</P>
<P>
   I also envision a wider variety of sidekicks with specialized
abilities. A given sidekick's participation or nonparticipation
could have a genuine impact on how the game plays out. You might
find that you had inadvertently killed an expert hacker who might
have smoothed your path through a difficult sequence, or enlisted a
coward or a traitor. The possibilities are inviting.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, I'm at least grateful to have some company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
