<HEADER>
A0271 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BRITAIN-MUM-$ADV16-CO     07-12 1418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-MUM-$ADV16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT 100, BRITAIN'S QUEEN MUM SHOWS NO SIGN OF SLOWING DOWN
 &HT;    (800&AMP;ADDS)
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., July 16 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ After making a brief _ and rare _ public speech at a
lavish luncheon the other day, the Queen Mother asked the guests to
drink a toast their hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone at the event organized at Guild Hall to celebrate the
Queen Mum's upcoming 100th birthday complied by raising a glass.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, that is, except the guest of honor, who couldn't find
her wine. After glancing around her place setting at the head
table, the Queen Mum fixed a stare at the archbishop of Canterbury
and pointed at the glass of red wine he clutched in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's mine,'' she said, sweetly but sternly, to the head of
the Anglican Church, who instantly relinquished it to the senior
royal.
</P>
<P>
   The guests were charmed by this moment, which reminded them all
that the plucky matriarch of this country's often troubled,
occasionally unwieldy first family continues on _ a rock in a time
of sometimes wrenching change.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 4, Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth the Queen Mother _ she
demanded the two royal designations in her official title _ will
celebrate her birthday at a quiet family gathering at Clarence
House, her longtime London home. An official celebration will be
held July 19.
</P>
<P>
   At a thanksgiving service for her Tuesday at St. Paul's
Cathedral, George Carey, the archbishop of Canterbury who pinched
her wine glass, said her place in the hearts of Britons is secure.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when such a premium is placed on the young and the
new, it is glorious indeed to be celebrating the birthday of
someone who can help us travel that country called 'life' _ and
someone, indeed, who so fully continues to inhabit it,'' he said.
``For we cherish in you, ma'am, a continuing openness and
responsiveness to people, not just of all backgrounds, but of all
ages.''
</P>
<P>
   After the service the Queen Mum, aided by a walking stick and
handrail erected for her, walked the length of the massive
cathedral and down its 22 front steps. Prince Charles hovered near,
but she walked on her own, smiling demurely at people in the crowd
as she passed.
</P>
<P>
   With her warm smile and spry personality the mother of Queen
Elizabeth II remains by far the most popular royal _ for many the
personification of an ideal of ``British-ness'' that is fading
rapidly in the new century. She has seen two world wars, the
dissolution of an empire and counted among her friends Sir Winston
Churchill and President Franklin D. Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, she is most revered for her easy, relaxed style that allows
for a fondness for gin, jokes and race horses.
</P>
<P>
   The country is full of people with memories of her, like a young
Manchester policeman who once guarded her parade route. Peering
into the Queen Mother's car, he noticed that she seemed to be
chewing on something. She saw him staring and the next thing he
knew, she had tossed him a
</P>
<P>
   caramel.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the other royals, the Queen Mum relishes a good joke with
the press and seems to not take it all so seriously. Lunching with
Queen Elizabeth some years ago, she was reportedly surprised when
her daughter, who normally doesn't drink, ordered some wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you sure you should, dear?'' teased the Queen Mum, who is
known to enjoy a G&AMP;T now and then. ``After all, you have to reign
all afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   She also holds a grudge. Biographies suggest she will never
forgive Wallis Simpson, the American divorcee who King Edward VIII
surrendered his throne to marry. The abdication of her husband's
older brother in 1936 forced him to become King George VI and her
to become queen _ a role she never wanted. She blames Simpson for
her husband's early death in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   She also is said to be annoyed with Jimmy Carter for kissing her
on the lips at a 1977 meeting _ the first man, she complained, to
do so since the death of her husband.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The sun had not yet begun to set on the British Empire when she
was born to an aristocratic Scottish family. Elizabeth Angela
Marguerite Bowes-Lyon was the ninth child of the Earl and Countess
of Strathmore. The family's Glamis Castle in northeast Scotland is
the legendary home of Shakespeare's Macbeth.
</P>
<P>
   When the First World War started _ coincidentally on her 14th
birthday _ Glamis Castle became a hospital. One of her brothers,
Fergus, was killed at the battle of Loos in 1915.
</P>
<P>
   Her family periodically entertained King George V and Queen Mary
and their children _ among them Albert. After twice refusing
Albert, Elizabeth married him in 1923.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years later, the bashful and stuttering Albert became
King George VI.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   She became queen in the turbulent pre-war years with the
monarchy severely shaken by the abdication. She is credited with
restoring stability to the royal family and transforming her shy
husband into a people's king.
</P>
<P>
   During Word War II, she became a symbol of Britain, refusing to
leave Buckingham Palace, which was hit nine times by the German
bombers. She ignored then-Prime Minister Churchill's suggestion to
send her daughters Elizabeth _ the future queen _ and Margaret, to
the safety of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children won't go without me,'' she responded. ``I won't
leave the King. And the King will never leave.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   She sent the princesses to Windsor Palace outside London. And
with King George she roamed the country in the royal train,
cheering factory workers on, visiting army camps and hospitals, and
inspecting bomb damage.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for the prospect of a German invasion, the Queen
learned to use a revolver, practicing on a shooting range
constructed at Buckingham Palace. She and the king went often to
London's frequently bombed East End. She picked her way through the
rubble in high heels to offer
</P>
<P>
   encouragement to East Enders.
</P>
<P>
   After one bombing attack left the palace substantially damaged,
she responded: ``I'm glad we've been bombed. It makes me feel we
can look the East End in the face.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1952, George died of lung cancer, leaving her a widow at age
51. She moved out of Buckingham Palace to make way for her daughter
and went into seclusion until Churchill cajoled her into returning
to public life.
</P>
<P>
   She still refers to her husband as ``the king'' and declines
public appearances on the anniversaries of his birth, marriage, and
death.
</P>
<P>
   Even now she continues a rigorous public schedule, which she is
said to regard as a sacred duty of her position. Unlike other
royals, she seems to enjoy the regimen of tree plantings, plaque
dedications and visits to old folks homes _ mostly occupied by
people much younger than she is. She has made more than 40 trips
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   She always wears pearls, even when salmon fishing in Scotland _
a passion she still enjoys when she's up to it.
</P>
<P>
   The Queen Mother awakens each morning to the sound of bagpipe
music from her own recorded collection, and reads an assortment of
newspapers before meeting with her private secretary.
</P>
<P>
   On the rare occasion when she is lunching without family or
friends, she snacks with the staff at Clarence House, her London
residence.
</P>
<P>
   Her biggest pleasure comes from horse racing. She is so devoted
to the sport that she had a ``blower,'' a device used by bookmakers
to provide live race commentary, installed in her home.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   She is said to have no intention of retiring after her 100th
birthday. Local newspapers say she has opened discussions on her
role in the bash being planned for the Golden Jubilee of her
daughter's ascending the throne. That would take place in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   As she was leaving the recent luncheon in her honor, the Queen
Mum stopped her party to listen as a small group guests began
singing one of her long-time favorite songs, ``If You Were The Only
Girl In The World.''
</P>
<P>
   She smiled and urged them to sing louder. The rest of the crowd
joined in as the royal guest of honor beamed in pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s e-mail address is BertR(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.royal.gov.uk/family/mother.htm
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
