<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-CITIZENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBAL CROSSING SELLS PHONE SERVICE TO CITIZENS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Iowa, Minn., N.Y., Pa., Wis., Bermuda)   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Global Crossing, the telecommunications company,
agreed on Wednesday to sell its local phone operations to Citizens
Communications for $3.65 billion in cash, which Global will use to
further its construction of a worldwide communications network.
</P>
<P>
   The deal transfers to Citizens about one million phone lines in
Iowa, Minnesota, New York, Pennsylvania and Wisconsin and about
3,000 employees. Citizens, of Stamford, Conn., is increasingly
focused on telecommunications as it sheds its utility businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing, of Hamilton, Bermuda, acquired the local phone
business last year in its takeover of the Frontier Corp. Global
Crossing decided to get out of the local phone market to
concentrate on building a network capable of handling huge amounts
of Internet and data traffic worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The downside of this deal is that it removes an important
source of cash flow for Global Crossing,'' said Michael Hodel, a
telecommunications analyst with Morningstar, the mutual fund and
stock analysis company. ``But at least it alleviates some concern
over funding since the rest of their operations are burning through
cash.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors responded by bidding up Global Crossing shares
$2.9375, to $32.0625.
</P>
<P>
   The company's shares have been slumping, down more than 30
percent this year, amid concern over problems in raising money in a
dampened capital market for unprofitable companies focused on the
Internet. In the first quarter, Global Crossing posted an operating
loss of $234.1 million as it scrambled to build its network.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the deal with Citizens, investors and analysts
absorbed reports that Global Crossing was considering selling
GlobalCenter, its business that offers storage and maintenance
facilities for Web sites and other Internet services, to the rival
Exodus Communications for as much as $7 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing and Exodus declined to comment on the reports,
which said a deal would give Global Crossing a substantial equity
stake in Exodus.
</P>
<P>
   While it builds its network, Global Crossing has also been
trying to expand through acquisitions, although an overture to buy
Equant of the Netherlands, the owner of the world's largest data
network, ended abruptly last month when the two companies could not
agree on terms.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Hindrey Jr., who recently joined Global Crossing as chief
executive, did not support that deal, people close to the
negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   Given Global Crossing's wide-reaching strategies, some concern
has emerged. In addition to acquiring Frontier last year, Global
Crossing bought the cable installer Global Marine Systems and Racal
Telecom of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Global Crossing is not doing a great job of articulating
strategy,'' said Jeffrey Kagan, an independent telecommunications
analyst. ``It's a young company that seems to still be deciding
what they'll do when they grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally aimed at linking the two sides of the Atlantic,
Global Crossing operates or is building 12 fiber optic networks
connecting Asia, the Americas and Europe in an effort to set up a
worldwide, broadband network to meet the growing demand for
Internet and data services.
</P>
<P>
   While Global Crossing grows globally, smaller companies like
Citizens Communications are seeking to fill gaps in local services.
Earlier this year, the company sold its electric utilities business
and changed its name from Citizens Utilities to Citizens
Communications to reflect its switch in emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Citizens looks like they're becoming the Wal-Mart of phone
service, getting into a lot of small communities,'' Kagan said.
``The people living in those places will probably benefit from the
attention they will get from a Citizens, as opposed to a Global
Crossing.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Citizens rose 12.75 cents, to $18.8125.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
