<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0273 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-PARENTHOOD-BUSH13-COX     07-12 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENTHOOD-BUSH13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Planned Parenthood ad campaign to target Bush on abortion issue
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Planned Parenthood, eager to blunt Gov. George W.
Bush's compassionate conservative mantra, is launching a $2.5
million advertising campaign aimed at Republican and independent
women who support abortion rights and at swing voters in key
Midwestern states.
</P>
<P>
   The Planned Parenthood Action Fund, the group's political arm,
commissioned a poll of 1,000 registered likely voters earlier this
year. The group identified 300 of those surveyed as ``compassionate
conservative'' voters because they like Bush, call themselves
conservatives and tend to vote Republican. They also said they
support abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five percent of the compassionate conservative sample told
Planned Parenthood pollsters that they would not vote for a
candidate who would ban abortion. Sixty five percent said they
would be less likely to support such a candidate. The margin of
error was 5.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When these voters are introduced to Gov. George W. Bush's
positions on family planning and abortion, they move solidly
against him,'' Planned Parenthood President Gloria Feldt said
Wednesday. ``Compassionate conservative women have the ability to
turn this election and, armed with the truth, we believe they
will.''
</P>
<P>
   The group's first television ad will run on national cable
stations in time for the Republican National Convention, which
begins July 31 in Philadelphia. A second round targeted at swing
states such as Ohio and Michigan will be launched closer to the
November election.
</P>
<P>
   Bush opposes abortion except in cases of rape or incest or to
save a mother's life. He has said he won't make abortion a litmus
test for his vice-presidential choice or for nominees to the U.S.
Supreme Court. These positions have left both abortion supporters
and opponents suspicious of where Bush really stands.
</P>
<P>
   Feldt said she is not heartened by speculation that Bush is
considering Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge, a Republican who supports
Roe v. Wade, as his running mate. Ridge opposes government funding
for abortion and late-term procedures called, ``partial birth'' by
opponents. Like Bush, Ridge backs requiring minors to obtain
parental consent before having abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is so beholden now to the hardline right wing of the party
that my guess is, when push comes to shove, he will go with an
anti-choice running mate,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Feldt characterized Bush's abortion stance as hardline, a fact
she said abortion rights supporters don't fully understand because,
``he doesn't make these positions the centerpiece of his
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Jena Heath can be reached at jenah(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
