<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0277 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-SUMMIT-PERSONAL-0713-     07-12 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMIT-PERSONAL-0713-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN MIDEAST DIPLOMACY, PERSONALITIES MAY PLAY MAJOR ROLE
 &HT;    (500&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0713.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ With the cool breath of morning on his face and
his chocolate retriever, Buddy, at his side, President Clinton
began his day Wednesday with a solitary stroll along the wooded
mountain pathways running through the presidential retreat at Camp
David.
</P>
<P>
   He joined Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat for breakfast inside a pale green clapboard
lodge, where they helped themselves to warm eggs, chicken sausage
and, in a nod toward Mideast cuisine, cashew nuts.
</P>
<P>
   They laughed about the news photos of Arafat and Barak jostling
at the lodge doorway the day before, and doubtless shared a chuckle
over how little the reporters gathered in this Catoctin Mountain
hamlet know of what's really going on inside the secluded compound
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Is that any way to begin a day of high-stakes negotiations
centered on matters of war and peace?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I think it is, because you want to create a sense of
partnership,'' said Mideast expert Jon Alterman. ``The way to start
is to create good atmospherics.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton, Arafat and Barak got down to brass tacks on day two
of the Camp David summit, the Mideast foes were focused on the
life-and-death issues at the core of their 52-year conflict.
</P>
<P>
   There's more to statecraft, however, than the search for an
acceptable territorial and security formula.
</P>
<P>
   Personal diplomacy, simple human relations, will play a key
role.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something that the president will work hard on,'' said
Alterman, a program director at the U.S. Institute for Peace, a
Washington think tank. ``I am certain that it will be Clinton's
personal relationship with both these leaders that will be the
decisive factor if the summit is successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's relationship with Arafat dates to Sept. 1993, just
eight months after the president took office, when he hosted Arafat
and Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin for the South Lawn signing
of the historic Israeli-Palestinian peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Arafat and Clinton have met more than a dozen times,
at the White House, at the Wye River Plantation where Clinton
hosted Mideast peace talks two years ago, and even in Gaza City,
where in 1998 Clinton became the first U.S. president to visit
Palestinian-controlled land.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hosted Barak at the White House just days after the
Israeli leader took office last July. Since then the two have met
repeatedly, in Washington, twice in Europe, and over the course of
the week-long Syrian-Israeli talks Clinton hosted last January in
Shepherdstown, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   It might be a stretch to call the three men friends. Over the
span of their relationships, however, they've learned how to
communicate and, essentially, how to do business with each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The President has a very good relationship with both Chairman
Arafat and Prime Minister Barak,'' said White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's now worked with them extensively. I think just watching
the interaction, you can see that they believe that they can engage
in discussions and that there is a certain level of trust,''
Lockhart told reporters Wednesday. ``That is something that's
essential to this process here.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   It was critical, certainly, to the success of the Camp David
summit President Jimmy Carter hosted in 1978. That summit produced
a breakthrough peace accord between Israeli Prime Minister Menachem
Begin and Egyptian President Anwar Sadat, but not without first
hitting a roadblock that took intensive personal intervention by
Carter to circumvent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the impasse arose at Camp David I, as is inevitable in
this kind of negotiation, Carter turned to his friend Sadat and
imposed extremely heavy pressure on him to get an agreement,'' said
William Quandt, who was the senior Mideast expert on Carter's
National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Clinton follows suit, at a crucial moment he will press
Arafat to settle for less than he is asking for,'' said Quandt, now
professor of government and foreign policy at the University of
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   And, as Clinton has repeatedly advertised, he'll also inveigh
upon Barak to strike a deal that falls shy of the Israeli's wish
list.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be no success without principled compromise,''
Clinton warned on Tuesday. ``The road to peace, as always, is a
two-way street.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Clinton shows a politician's gifts for compelling with
charm, or the force of reason. Behind closed doors, however, he has
a reputation as a master arm-twister, as former negotiating
partners have testified.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Clinton spent 82 hours over nine days and eight
nights in grinding negotiations between Arafat and then-Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu at the Wye River Plantation on
Maryland's Eastern Shore.
</P>
<P>
   The talks hit a last-minute snag when the Israeli balked at the
terms of a framed-up accord, and Clinton worked on Netanyahu for
seven hours to bring him around.
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon at a White House ceremony, Netanyahu, depleted
after 28 hours of sleepless negotiations, called Clinton ``a
warrior for peace,'' and portrayed Clinton as a tireless, even
pesky advocate who used Wye ``to nudge and prod,'' the parties to
make peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean,'' said Netanyahu, ``he doesn't stop.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The title for personal diplomacy in the quest for Mideast peace,
however, probably still belongs to Carter, who rescued the
Begin-Sadat talks from certain failure by signing a handful of
photographs.
</P>
<P>
   With leaders angered after 11 days of difficult talks, and both
packing their bags to leave Camp David in failure, Carter
remembered that Begin had requested an autographed photo of the two
men together as a souvenir for his grandchildren back in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   An aide brought Carter eight photographs, the former president
recalled in a speech at the University of Maryland two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of just signing Jimmy Carter, I put, 'With love,' to
every one of his grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Begin was ''hardly speaking to me,'' Carter recalled, when he
dropped by the Israeli leaders' cabin to deliver the souvenir
photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said 'Thank you, Mr. president,' and turned around,
dismissing me, in effect,'' said Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then he looked down and he read the first photograph, and
he called out the name of his granddaughter,'' Carter said. ``And
then one by one he read out the names of his grandchildren. And
tears ran down his cheeks. And, when I saw them, I also cried. And
he said, 'Why don't we try one more time.'''
</P>
<P>
   Said Carter, ''To make a long story short, we concluded the
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
