<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0279 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-INFORMATION-ARCHI     07-12 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-INFORMATION-ARCHITECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDING A BETTER WEB WITH CONTENT BLUEPRINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you ever gone to a Web site to find a specific piece of
information and found yourself falling through a series of pages
while clicking around helplessly, trying to find what you want? Do
you feel as if you have opened the door to the basement of your new
house only to find that the architect forgot to design the
staircase that leads to the lower level?
</P>
<P>
   A good architect won't forget your staircase, and a good
information architect _ a job that is becoming increasingly more
important as the world moves to the Web _ will make sure that
visitors to a site will be able to find their way around easily as
well. Although some in the new-media industry have lumped the job
with that of a Web site's graphic designer, the role of an
information architect in the creation of a site is actually much
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``With apologies to `Shoeless Joe,' the maxim `If you build it,
they will come' simply does not apply to the Web,'' said Colin
Furness, a senior information architect at Iguana Studios, a Web
design company in New York that has designed sites for the Zagat
restaurant guides and the American Society for the Prevention of
Cruelty to Animals. ``And many storefronts have not figured this
out yet. Poor usability that alienates users _ especially mom and
pop _ is cheap and easy, which is perhaps why it is so plentiful.''
</P>
<P>
   The information architect's job, Furness says, is to organize
the structure and content of all the material on a Web site, as
well as figure out how users can effectively navigate through the
site to find the one or two things they might be looking for _ say,
for instance, a pair of khaki pants on a large clothing retailer's
site. Once this blueprint has been laid out, the Web site's graphic
designer will concentrate on the visual look of the site. Or, to
put it back into building terms, the information architect decides
where the window will go, and the designer decides what the window
will look like.
</P>
<P>
   The look and feel of a Web page itself, including, for example,
where the site puts its search box for users to quickly seek out
specific words on the site, still lack uniform standards, Furness
said. He noted that while some Web page conventions, like colored,
underlined hyperlinks to other Web sites, are quickly understood by
most new users, other inconsistencies in design and layout may make
the Web hard to grasp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules for navigation, information classification and
hierarchy and widgets such as drop-down menus _ and there are
actually rules _ have not been consistently applied,'' Furness
said, ``so no standards have emerged, and this has hindered users'
abilities to learn and master cyberspace.'' He likened it to the
early days of automobiles, when dashboards varied so widely that
drivers had to learn a new set of controls before they could
operate a car.
</P>
<P>
   Information architecture may also be aimed at a specific
audience. Older users, said Furness, who may have less familiarity
with computers as well as the Web, are likely to respond
differently to an e-commerce site that features loud, snazzy
animations and graphics than someone who is more used to the visual
style of the online world. In his work, Furness has noticed that
newer users tend to feel more comfortable ``when clickable links
are larger, when there is less information density per page, when
colors are softer, and things are explained in more detail using
suitable language and symbolism.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web itself is barely a decade old, and standards are bound
to emerge as it evolves. Once the technology is in place, it is
just a matter of adapting it to suit the needs of people, instead
of the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world has been slow to realize that the Web is nothing
more than a very big information system that can benefit from the
same attention to human factors,'' Furness said.
</P>
</TEXT>
