<HEADLINE>
PRO-BRITISH LOYALISTS IN ULSTER CLASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENNISKILLEN, Northern Ireland _ On the day of their biggest
cultural celebration, when a premium is placed on solidarity,
pro-British loyalists turned on each other Wednesday, focusing
their anger and violence on themselves rather than their
traditional enemies.
</P>
<P>
   A rash of stabbings broke out at the traditional bonfires held
overnight to celebrate the victory in 1690 of the Protestant king,
William of Orange, over the Catholic king, James II, the biggest
annual gathering of Northern Ireland loyalists. And a leading
Protestant unionist politician, appealing for an end to the
violence, was heckled.
</P>
<P>
   Some Orangemen have denounced leading Protestant clergy for a
call to end the violence accompanying a protest by the Orange
Order, a Protestant fraternal group. The order is denouncing a
refusal to let it march through a Catholic neighborhood in
Portadown.
</P>
<P>
   According to seasoned observers here, including some prominent
loyalists, the dissension has never been greater within the
unionist community.
</P>
<P>
   David Ervine, a former loyalist paramilitary leader who has
sworn off violence and has embraced democratic politics, said he
was disgusted by the internal fighting and recrimination. For
years, he said, the unionist community had blamed republicans for
their problems. Now, Ervine said, it was time to look into the
mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enemy is within. We're commiting hara-kiri,'' said Ervine,
leader of the Progressive Unionist Party, the political wing of the
Ulster Volunteer Force paramilitary group.
</P>
<P>
   Just after midnight Wednesday, a man was murdered in what police
said was part of a feud between loyalist paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Cairns, 22, was chased, by as many as a dozen men,beaten,
then shot in the back of the head, according to Detective Inspector
George Montgomery of the Royal Ulster Constabulary. Police said
Cairns was a member of the Ulster Volunteer Force. His attackers
are believed to be members of the Ulster Defense Association, the
largest loyalist paramilitary group. Those sources suggested that
Cairns had been arguing with his attackers at a loyalist drinking
club.
</P>
<P>
   Cairns was attacked as loyalists gathered around a bonfire in
Larne, a harbor town north of Belfast. Bonfires are the traditional
venue where those who want Northern Ireland to remain part of the
United Kingdom express solidarity, and celebrate their British
heritage and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Ervine said the murder of Cairns, and the stabbings of two other
men, one of whom was critically injured, at other bonfires, had
made a mockery of the annual celebration of loyalism, and had
exposed deep rifts in the pro-British community in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the unionist community feels our culture is under attack
from outside, the reality is it is under attack from within,''
Ervine said. ``Andrew Cairns was murdered as he celebrated his
culture. I am disgusted.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Ulster Volunteer Force of which Cairns was reputedly a
member staunchly supports the peace process, many members of the
Ulster Defense Association, including those who appeared at a
bonfire in West Belfast early Wednesday and fired shots from
automatic weapons into the air, want to keep fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The two loyalist groups have feuded for the past two years,
while a leading member of the Ulster Defense Association, Johnny
Adair, has aligned himself with loyalist dissidents who vow to keep
fighting. Adair has been a presence at Portadown since Orangemen
began the protest there almost two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The divisions within loyalism were in evidence not just at the
bonfires. When Orangemen and other loyalists gathered at Ormeau
Park in Belfast, Jim Rodgers, an Ulster Unionist councilor, was
heckled after he said that the violence that has accompanied Orange
Order protests for the last 10 days, especially attacks on the
police and British army, is ``totally unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers said that Orangemen risked leaving themselves without
allies. The British government, which has traditionally represented
the interests of unionists, is furious with what it sees as the
Orangemen's intransigence over refusing to negotiate the parade's
terms with Catholic residents who live along the disputed route in
Portadown, and with the cozy alliance between Portadown Orangemen
and loyalist paramilitaries.
</P>
<P>
   In Portadown, meanwhile, loyalists burned an effigy of a
policeman early Wednesday and had running battles with police and
soliders _ the security forces of a government to which they
profess loyalty. A ``blast bomb,'' like the one loyalists used to
kill a police officer last year, was thrown at police lines
Wednesday, but no one was seriously wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Many, if not most, mainstream Protestants found the burning of
the police in effigy outrageous, given that one of the biggest
grievances of the unionist community is its demand that the Royal
Ulster Constabulary keep its name and its ethos. A change in the
police force, which is more than 90 percent Protestant, is a
cornerstone of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Ervine said the effigy burning reflected the counterproductive
mentality of the Portadown protesters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no concept of the widows, the wives and daughters,''
he said, referring to the more than 300 police officers killed by
the Irish Republican Army and other republican paramilitary groups.
``What are we coming to if we have to burn, beat and even kill our
own people?''
</P>
<P>
   The Orange Order staged 18 parades and celebrations across
Northern Ireland, the largest in Belfast. There was little reported
trouble at any of the events. But police feared that as night fell,
violence would resume, as has been the pattern for nearly two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   David Jones, a spokesman for the Orange Order in Portadown,
vowed that their protest would continue indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   At the spot where Cairns was murdered, meanwhile, someone left
behind a bouquet of flowers with a card that read, ``A true
loyalist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
