u s BC-BOX-BOTHA-BOS &LR;      07-12 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOTHA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTHA OUT TO PROVE LEWIS'S CHIN MADE OF GLASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Francois Botha is about to enter the glassware
business. Lennox Lewis thinks that's fitting.
</P>
<P>
   For the record _ not that it's likely to matter _ the man who
will challenge the undisputed heavyweight champion Saturday night
before beginning to sell champagne glasses that light up when you
turn the stem doesn't agree.
</P>
<P>
   For Botha, this is his third foray into heavyweight championship
boxing and his first into the glassware business, a venture he got
involved in through a Paris company that liked his idea and now has
him ready to hawk his wares on QVC as well as at his three Las
Vegas restaurants and at several casinos. Lewis is of the opinion
the latter business is the better long-term venture for his
opponent, a 15-1 underdog who will wander into London Arena with
few people besides himself believing he will fare any better
against Lewis than he did in his other big fights _ stoppage
defeats at the hands of Michael Moorer and Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, Botha was briefly the International Boxing
Federation heavyweight champion in 1995, a title he won from Axel
Schulz and then lost to a lab test that said he had been using
steroids at the time. But since then he has had two major fights
and was stopped in both. As boxing resumes go, that's one that
resembles Swiss cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Since Lewis (36-1-1, 28 KO's) stopped Shannon Briggs in five
rounds a year before Botha fought him to a draw and has not lost
since he was upset by Oliver McCall in 1994, he is confident no
glassware salesman can offer up much for him to fear. The gamblers
feel the same way.
</P>
<P>
   But the 31-year-old Botha has always fought bravely in his
defeats and made clear Wednesday he will be throwing more than
stemware at Lewis Saturday, a fact he says could make a difference
because Lewis has shown signs that while his body may be made of
steel his chin is of china.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't be intimidated,'' said Botha (42-1-1, 24 KO's).
``Everyone saw that. Mike Tyson saw that'' _ after Botha easily won
the first four rounds of their 1999 fight before walking into a
knockout punch because of cockiness more than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think I came here as an easy fight but this is a great
opportunity for me. This is a chance of a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unless Botha's chin turns out to have the same consistency
as his stemware, and frankly there is no reason to believe that
because although he has a penchant for losing his big fights, he
does not tend to go quickly into the night.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, considering his resume, go it seems he eventually
must. Go into that good night without the IBF, World Boxing
Council, and International Boxing Organization belts that Lewis
will carry into the ring.
</P>
<P>
   That may be why barely half of the 12,000 tickets available for
Lewis's first fight in his hometown in six years have been sold and
it may explain why Lewis disdainfully made Botha wait for more than
an hour Wednesday before finally showing up at a press conference
at a place called the Isle of Dogs.
</P>
<P>
   From where Botha stood it was the Isle of Underdogs and he well
understood that, even while insisting he had not bought into the
role he has been brought here to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not angry,'' Botha said of his situation and the public's
perception of it. ``Even against Mike they said I was a sacrificial
lamb and look what happened? My foolishness is what put me down
against Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they think this is an easy fight and that's what I want
them to think. Boxing has already opened up a lot of doors for me.
Now I have to use this one.''
</P>
<P>
   The champion believes if Botha does get some use out of this
fight, it will be to sell a few extra glasses back in the States,
but in the mind of an entrepreneur like Botha, there is another
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'll pick up three belts on Saturday night,'' Botha
said. ``I know I'll do that. Boxing has opened a lot of doors for
me. I have to make use of this. I am a symbol of the American
dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Botha, the owner of three Chinese restaurants and a passel of
real estate in Las Vegas as well as the champagne glass business,
is certainly all of that after having left a life of poverty in
South Africa to become a million-dollar heavyweight punching bag
for several world champions.
</P>
<P>
   So whether his chin cracks like his glassware might if Lennox
Lewis dropped a bomb on it, that part of Frans Botha's resume will
remain intact because even if he fails to win the WBC, IBF, and IBA
titles, there's always QVC to fall back on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
