r s BC-FALCONSCAMP13-COX     07-12 0347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONSCAMP13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Santiago, Anderson question marks as Falcons report to camp
today
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - As National Football League training camps go, today
will be boring for the Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Players report to Furman University in Greenville, S.C., but
they won't suit up until Friday. The lone practice that day will be
at 3 p.m., after morning meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The only topics of importance today will be decisions on whether
tight end O.J. Santiago and running back Jamal Anderson are
sufficiently recovered from injuries to participate Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has tendinitis in the surgically repaired right knee
that kept him out of 14 games last season. Santiago has been
limited since surgery four months ago to repair a torn chest
muscle.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a 5 p.m. softball game pits coaches and staff
members against the media.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches won in 1997 and '99, but then the team went 7-9 and
5-11. After the media won in 1998, the Falcons went 14-2 and ended
up in Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   Superstitions aside, the hope is for a better start than last
year, when lightning forced everybody from the field the first day.
</P>
<P>
   The same day, former defensive end Chuck Smith badly sprained a
toe to begin a staggering string of injuries that carried through
camp and to the end of a 5-11 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be able to practice without worrying so much about
injuries,'' said Reeves, who begins his 20th season as a head
coach. ``I've liked our attitude in the offseason, but I thought
our attitude was good last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Terance Mathis is eager to put 1999 behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If training camp goes smooth, the season usually goes
smoother, and we had a rocky training camp last year,'' he said.
``There's a lot of enthusiasm around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Practices Saturday are at 9 a.m. and 3 p.m. All sessions are
open to the public and free. For details, call 864-294-2550 or go
to the Internet at www.furman.edu.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
