<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SHEET-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEET MUSIC ON CD AND ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By LISA GUERNSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Theodore Presser Co. started publishing sheet music in 1783.
This week it will start to publish sheet music in a different form,
as .pdf files on CD-ROM disks.
</P>
<P>
   The company has teamed up with a CD-Rom company called CD Sheet
Music to put thousands of pages of classical scores in digital
form. The first 15 CD-Roms _ which include the complete piano solos
of Beethoven, Brahms, Chopin, Mozart, Schumann and many others _
are showing up in music stores this week.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 2002, the company plans to sell a series of 110
disks. Most of the disks will sell for about $15 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are talking about is something akin to the world's
greatest music library,'' said Tom Broido, president of Theodore
Presser. ``We're giving people the opportunity to have it in their
own home.''
</P>
<P>
   Each CD-Rom includes Adobe Acrobat software that enables people
to view the sheet music on their computer screens and print it out
on 8{ by 11 paper without reformatting. It also enables searching
and browsing by a composer's name or a score's title. The software
can be used on either Windows or Macintosh computers.
</P>
<P>
   Sheet music is offered online by other companies. Sheet Music
Online (www.sheetmusic1.com) and Music-Scores.com
(www.music-scores.com) offer sheet music that can be viewed on Web
pages and printed at no cost.
</P>
<P>
   But searching through the archives on free music sites can
sometimes be cumbersome and finding rare works is unlikely. Those
are two problems that the Theodore Presser Co. hopes to rectify
with its CD-Roms, which use a simple interface that enables users
to click on titles in a table of contents and immediately view the
music in printable form.
</P>
<P>
   Broido said that the company was also intent on making its disks
as inexpensive as possible, which is why they include nothing but
black-and-white sheet music. They do not include any sound files or
interactive graphics.
</P>
<P>
   They do, however, enable users to print as many sheets as they
want. Broido said he expected that piano teachers, for example,
might buy the CDs and print sheet music for students to sample. As
long as people are not reselling the printouts or making a business
out of their use, Broido said, they are free to use them as they
would like.
</P>
<P>
   The music is all in the public domain, and Broido said that he
was not concerned that people would bootleg the CDs because buying
a disk is probably less of a burden for most users than figuring
out how to burn a new copy. ``The price of the product is its
greatest protection,'' Broido said.
</P>
<P>
   The disks might also be seen as protection against overstuffed
piano benches, since each package includes many volumes of scores.
The CD-Rom titled ``Beethoven: The Complete Works of Solo Piano,''
for example, includes more than 1,500 pages of music. The disk
featuring the complete keyboard sonatas of Haydn and Scarlatti
includes more than 2,500 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The company's biggest one-disk collection is ``The Ultimate
Collection of Piano Studies and Exercise,'' which features staples
of piano practice like mind-numbing finger exercises.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one is every pianist's worst nightmare,'' said Dwight
Munroe, the advertising manager. ``It is over 3,000 pages.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
