<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS: ADDING PROGRAM ICONS TO WINDOWS 98
TASKBAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Is it possible to add icons to the Windows 98 taskbar for
programs that I frequently use?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, icons can be added in just a few steps for frequently
used programs or files to the Quick Launch toolbar in the taskbar.
On many Windows systems, you will already see some icons, like the
one for Internet Explorer. Right-click on an empty area of the
Quick Launch toolbar, and make sure that Quick Launch is checked on
the pop-up menu.
</P>
<P>
   Locate the program or file that you would like to place in the
Quick Launch toolbar. You can either go through My Computer or the
Windows Explorer to find your desired items; program files will
have an .exe extension.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once you have found the item, drag the file onto the Quick
Launch toolbar and let go when you see a small vertical black bar
flash in the toolbar. A shortcut to the original file will be
created in the taskbar, and a small icon should appear. (Remember,
a shortcut is not a copy but rather, a pointer. It can be moved or
deleted without harming the original.)
</P>
<P>
   To delete programs or files from the Quick Launch toolbar,
right-click on the unwanted icon, select Delete and click on OK in
the alert box that asks if you want to move the shortcut to the
Recycle Bin.
</P>
<P>
   If you would like to clean your desktop of clutter, you can drag
the shortcuts onto the Quick Launch toolbar and then delete them
from the desktop.
</P>
<P>
   If you would prefer to open files from desktop icons instead of
tiny taskbar icons but do not have existing shortcut files, it is
simple to create them. Locate the original program or file,
right-click on the icon and select Create Shortcut. You can then
drag the shortcut file to wherever you would like.
</P>
<P>
   Q. My version of the Netscape browser for Macintosh does not
display pictures on Web pages unless I click on the Images button
on the toolbar. Is there a way to fix this so the pictures
automatically show up?
</P>
<P>
   A. For those who prefer to surf for text and not wait for images
to download, most browsers provide an option to block the pictures
and graphics. You can check Netscape's Preferences to see if this
no-images option is turned on.
</P>
<P>
   To do this in the latest version of Netscape for the Macintosh
and Windows, go to Edit in the menu bar and select Preferences.
When the Preferences box pops up, click on the advanced category in
the left side of the box and make sure the ``Automatically load
images'' option is checked.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How can I change my Windows password?
</P>
<P>
   A. If you would like to change your existing Windows password,
go to the Start menu and select Settings and then Control Panel.
Double-click on the Passwords icon, click on Change Windows
Password and then click on OK. You will be asked to type in your
old password first, and then to type in the new one you wish to
use. You will need to type the new password a second time to
confirm it, and then click on OK.
</P>
<P>
   Q. When talking about the Internet, what is meant by the term
``backbone?''
</P>
<P>
   A. Much like the nervous-system signals that are transmitted
along the spinal cord, the backbone of a network is the pipeline
that handles most of the major traffic for computers connected to
it. The backbone is often the longest physical part of the network
and usually contains cable capable of delivering data at the
fastest speeds. Several communications companies, like UUNet,
Sprint, MCI and GTE, own the biggest networks that help make up the
Internet backbone.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller networks connect to the backbone at various points,
giving users the ability to communicate. And just as an injury to
your back can slow you down, a problem with part of the Internet
backbone can make your connection sluggish or even put it out of
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
e-mail to Q&AMP;A(at)nytimes.com or mail to Questions, Circuits, The
New York Times, 229 West 43rd St., New York, N.Y. 10036-3959. This
column will answer questions of general interest, but letters
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
