<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: There are photos available with this story.
 &HT;    Redneck Games: 'Good family fun'
 &HT;    By Dianne Stepp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ga. _ Spittin' a watermelon seed more than 39 feet ain't
easy.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Braswell of Wrightsville, Ga., shucked her floppy
chicken hat, reared back and let fly but didn't come close to
14-year-old Eric Smith's expert expectoration once judges found the
pits in the grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secret's curling your tongue like a funnel and blowing,''
demonstrated Eric, gripping his Budweiser can-topped trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got beat by a girl last year,'' said Mac Davis, general
manager of Y-96 radio station, sponsor of the 2000 Redneck Games.
</P>
<P>
   The contest warmed the crowd up for the armpit serenade. Blake
Nimmons, 12, of Soperton, Ga., furiously pumped his arm to squeeze
out a crowd-pleasing rendition of ``Dixie.''
</P>
<P>
   Winner J.W. Young added a new twist, blowing air under his
armpit through a straw while pumping away.
</P>
<P>
   Still dripping from a cooling plunge in the Oconee River, rising
second-grader Brandon Denton checked to ensure that his painted on
``Little Redneck'' had'nt washed off. ``He's hoping to get in the
mud pit belly flop contest,'' said his mother Sherryell Denton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good family fun. Southerners have the unique ability to
laugh at themselves. That's what this is all about,'' she said.
``I'm waiting to bob for pigs' feet.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5th Annual Red Neck Games started early Saturday at Buckeye
Park in East Dublin with a six-mile homemade raft race down the
Oconee and ended with fireworks in the evening. Rick Hunter rode
his motorcycle five hours from DeLand, Fla., to be there. ``I'm
looking for a woman bobbing for pig's feet. I've never seen a woman
with a pig's foot in her mouth except my mother and she was eating
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands braved the Middle Georgia heat to go for beer can
trophies in events such as the hubcap hurl, the Dumpster dive and
bug zapper spitball.
</P>
<P>
   Randy ``L-bow'' Tidwell, wearing a T-shirt with his picture on
it and ``Genuine Redneck'' printed across the top, officially
opened the games. Tidwell, known as Middle Georgia's ``best known
redneck,'' began the festivities by lighting a beer can torch.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day festivalgoers were entertained by live music
by various local groups, including The Southern Touch Band, arts
and crafts, barbecue, watermelon and boiled peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   The games began in 1996 as a counterpoint to the Olympics held
in Atlanta, drawing a crowd of 3,000. This year more than 8,000
people were expected at the park on the banks of the Oconee.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
