<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-STATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS HAILED FOR PROTON LAUNCH DESPITE FINANCIAL HURDLES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Russia was praised by its foreign partners Wednesday for
overcoming economic adversity to launch the long-delayed crew
module for the U.S.-led international space station, but its
officials hinted that future contributions to the project still
were in peril.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-foot module, designed by the Russians to furnish living
quarters for the station's first resident astronauts, made its
first orbits of the Earth on Wednesday after a flawless liftoff
from Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's mission control said the new module's many electronic
and mechanical components had responded to commands. More tests and
at least eight major maneuvers will be necessary to set up the
automated docking July 25 with the two station components already
launched. A NASA shuttle crew mated those two pieces in December
1998.
</P>
<P>
   After the module is connected, the outpost will be ready for its
first resident crew of astronauts and cosmonauts in late October.
</P>
<P>
   A 16-nation alliance that includes the space agencies of Europe,
Japan, Canada and Brazil as well as the United States and Russia is
counting on the linkup to allow a succession of 15 station assembly
and supply missions in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   The backlog of missions was caused by a 27-month delay in the
fabrication of the crew module, also known as Zvezda, Russian for
``star.'' The delay was caused by economic and political turmoil in
Russia following the breakup of the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Russian module's seamless trip to orbit aboard
a Proton rocket was reason for top-level participants to both
rejoice and look ahead with new skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore termed the launch an ``important
milestone'' in the station partnership he helped to formulate with
the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians are a resilient, tough, tough people,'' said NASA
administrator Dan Goldin, who has had to fend off critics for his
enthusiastic endorsement of the 1993 Clinton administration
decision to assign the Russians a prominent role in the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've come through economic crisis after economic crisis,
political crisis after political crisis, tackled technical problem
after technical problem and never gave up,'' said Goldin. ``I like
showing the skeptics they are wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a long hard journey for them,'' said Frank
Longhurst, space station program manager for the European Space
Agency, which represents 11 of the project's international
partners. ``They are to be admired.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russians, however, seemed reluctant to speculate about what
the milestone will mean for their role as a major contributor to
the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have great problems with the funding and paying for
construction of space vehicles, and in the coming months we will
have to resolve these issues,'' said Yuri Grigoriev, the deputy
chief designer for RSC Energia, the most powerful of the Russian
Aviation and Space Agency's aerospace contractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the program of the Russian segment of the international
space station should be reconsidered. We should revise our plans
and make adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the one-of-a-kind habitat module, the Russians
have promised to provide a half-dozen Progress cargo and Soyuz crew
transport capsule launches annually.
</P>
<P>
   The Progress missions are needed to supply fuel and some of the
propulsion that will be required to keep the expanding space
station at a safe altitude.
</P>
<P>
   Until NASA completes its own delayed development of an American
lifeboat for the station, the orbital outpost will require a Soyuz
launch every six months. Functioning as temporary lifeboats while
they are docked to the station, the Soyuz capsules could whisk a
small resident crew to Earth if a meteor penetrated the walls of
the orbital outpost, fire erupted or one of the occupants suffered
from a life-threatening illness.
</P>
<P>
   Those demands will leave Russia with few resources to expand its
own segment of the new station, as the better-financed Americans,
Europeans and Japanese plan to do.
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of the Russians' financial plight in space, a Pizza
Hut insignia graced the side of the crew module's towering, white
Proton launcher. Though terms of the unusual advertisement were not
disclosed, the Wall Street Journal placed it at about $1 million
when the deal was struck last fall.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Russians will have no difficulty launching a
Soyuz and up to three of the Progress capsules, Grigoriev said.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted trouble next year, though, if Russia attempts eight
station launches, including spring delivery of a spherical
compartment that would serve as a connecting point for future
Russian research modules.
</P>
<P>
   Grigoriev pointed out that work has stopped on a towering
complex of power-generating solar arrays because of a lack of
funds. Slated for a 2002 liftoff, the so-called Russian science
power platform is now an unlikely addition.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the space station will continue well into 2006.
The orbital complex will stretch to the size of two football fields
placed side-by-side and house seven people.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
