<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ HAS BIGGEST GAIN IN FIVE WEEKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Internet and other computer-related stocks surged on
Wednesday, propelling the Nasdaq market to its biggest gain in more
than five weeks and back into positive territory for the year, a
perch it has not held since mid-April.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index rose 143.17 points, or 3.62 percent,
to 4,099.59 _ the best finish since April 10, the beginning of a
disastrous week when the index fell 25.3 percent over five
consecutive days. Analysts and strategists attributed the sharp
rise to fading concern about higher interest rates and a
better-than-expected earnings report from Yahoo, an Internet
bellwether, issued after exchanges closed on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo helped set the stage,'' said Andrew Brooks, chief trader
at T. Rowe Price Associates, as revived strength in high technology
shoved cyclical stocks, which briefly rallied earlier in the week,
into the background once again.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average posted its fourth consecutive
gain, rising 56.57 points, or 0.53 percent, to 10,783.76. J.P.
Morgan, up 4 5/8, to 122 9/16, accounted for more than half the
advance. Brokerage stocks, benefiting from the announced takeover
of PaineWebber by Switzerland's UBS, joined high technology as the
session's best-performing group. PaineWebber soared 16 15/16 to 66
7/8.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index gained 12.04 points, or
0.81 percent, to 1,492.92, lifting its gain so far this year to
1.61 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real concern is earnings, not interest rates,'' said
Charles J. Pradilla, strategist at SG Cowen Securities. ``And
there's a growing conviction that you're looking either at the last
or the penultimate tightening'' by the Federal Reserve Board.
</P>
<P>
   Applied Micro Circuits, up 11 11/16, to 125 7/16, reported after
the close that revenue more than doubled and profits, after
allowing for merger costs, beat expectations. Bestfoods, to be
acquired by Unilever, matched Wall Street profit estimates.
Motorola said after the markets closed on Wednesday that its
earnings met expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo clearly led the market and convinced people that the
fundamentals of Internet stocks, which have been acting sickly
lately, remain vibrant,'' said Thomas M. Galvin, chief investment
officer at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   Having erased the steep losses of the spring, the Nasdaq is now
ahead for the year, by a scant 0.74 percent, after an 85.6 percent
leap in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq has also become far less volatile, with the average
intraday trading range over the latest 30 sessions moving below 100
points on Wednesday for the first time since Jan. 20, said Fane
Lozman, a researcher in Chicago; the average range peaked at 226.69
on April 18.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow narrowed its loss so far this year to 6.2 percent. After
J.P. Morgan, the biggest positive contributors were Intel and IBM,
each up more than 2 points. Johnson &AMP; Johnson, Exxon Mobil, Merck
and Wal-Mart each lost a point or more.
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks were weak as the Senate considered adding
prescription benefits for Medicare recipients, with investors
worried about possible price controls that could more than offset
the benefit of greater sales.
</P>
<P>
   Airline stocks, however, joined technology and brokerage issues
as prominent winners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
