<HEADER>
A0309 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-MEDIA-NYT &LR;      07-12 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. OFFICIAL SEEN RETREATING FROM PLAN TO CURB NEWS MEDIA IN
KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Under pressure from local Albanian
journalists and international news media watch-dogs, the United
Nations administration is likely to abandon plans for a formal code
of conduct for the news media in Kosovo, a senior U.N. official
says.
</P>
<P>
   But a law that provides for the fining, suspension or closing of
print or broadcast media will remain on the books, the official
said. The regulation, signed by the U.N. chief here, Bernard
Kouchner, is intended to prevent the publication or broadcasting of
personal details about people who might become targets of Albanian
or Serbian vigilantes.
</P>
<P>
   The frustration of the U.N. authorities is evident as
inter-ethnic attacks continue, especially on the Serbian minority
in Kosovo, while a system of international judges to deal with such
crimes is just beginning to function.
</P>
<P>
   Kouchner issued the regulation after an Albanian-language
newspaper, Dita, published an article on April 27 accusing two
Serbs, Petar Topoljski and his father, of being paramilitaries.
Petar Topoljski, 25, still lived in Kosovo and worked as a
translator for the United Nations; the paper published his address
and photograph. Three weeks later he was found murdered, stabbed
with a wire wound around his neck.
</P>
<P>
   His death seemed an example of the press feeding the cycle of
vengeance against Serbs, with no recourse to the police or the
courts. While there could be no direct connection drawn between the
Dita article and the murder, Kouchner decided to act, judging that
news media self-regulation was not working.
</P>
<P>
   Kouchner, whose word is law here, shut down Dita for eight days.
</P>
<P>
   More moderate Albanian newspapers, like Koha Ditore, criticized
the suspension of Dita as an arbitrary act of personal power.
Dita's publisher, Behlul Beqaj, justified publication of the
information by saying that the system of justice in Kosovo was not
working, and that there had been no punishment for people accused
of war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the suspension was over, Beqaj republished the
article. Kouchner then issued his regulation on June 17 covering
broadcast and print media, naming a temporary news media
commissioner with the power to impose sanctions, including a
warning; the requirement to publish a reply, correction or apology;
a fine of up to 100,000 German marks (about $50,000); seizure of
equipment or printed material, and suspension or closing down of
the entire operation.
</P>
<P>
   Appeals are subject to a board appointed by Kouchner.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner, a former U.S. diplomat, Douglas Davidson, was
also given the power to, ``in special circumstances,'' issue
``temporary codes of conduct'' for journalists after consultation _
codes that Kouchner could decide to turn into law.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson defended the codes as common in European countries and
necessary to deter the use of ``hate speech.'' But it is the effort
to draw up those codes _ after long and frustrating meetings with
local editors who oppose them as a new, undemocratic order _ that
the United Nations is now likely to abandon.
</P>
<P>
   The regulation itself caused a furor. It was condemned by the
World Press Freedom Committee and other international news media
watch-dogs, and Beqaj tested it on June 26, publishing the names of
two Serbs from the town of Kosovo Polje accused of attacking ethnic
Albanians. One of those Serbs is in close contact with the
municipality and the United Nations. This time, Dita went to the
police first, but did not heed U.N. requests to delay publication.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson then issued a warning to Dita and called for
clarification, saying the paper appeared to have violated the
regulation on publishing personal details that ``would pose a
serious threat to the life, safety or security of any such person
through vigilante violence or otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Davidson said: ``Publishing names can put
people's lives at risk. It is also violating a fundamental
principle of Western journalism that someone is innocent until
proven guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   After receiving one letter from Dita, Davidson is seeking
further clarification. He may then decide to impose another
sanction.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, on July 5, Dita published the names, prewar
addresses and photographs of 15 more Serbs it accused of committing
crimes against ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Beqaj is unrepentant. In a meeting with Davidson and other
editors to discuss a temporary code of conduct, he said that Dita
``is accused of involvement with the death of one man.'' But who is
to blame ``for the other 498'' or so murders in Kosovo since NATO
forces took over the province, he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson, Kouchner and other U.N. officials say they must have
some way to stop hate speech and the incitement to murder
individuals on the basis of uncorroborated accusations printed or
broadcast by the news media. ``This is not yet a normal place,''
Davidson said to the editors. ``The international community must
have some control and if it wants to lower the level of hatred and
tension here, not make it worse, then one thing you must look at is
the media.''
</P>
<P>
   But Baton Haxhiu, the editor of Koha Ditore, said that Albanian
news executives are able to police themselves. ``All this just
shows that the internationals are becoming Balkanized, trying to
put restrictions on the freedom of the press,'' he said. ``This is
a bad precedent, and it will be used against us by some political
party in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   What Kosovo needs instead is a functioning police and court
system to provide justice, Haxhiu said, and it is the job of the
United Nations, not the local news media, to produce one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
