<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A fine feathered fix for Georgia couple
 &HT;    By Andrea Jones
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Found: One stray emu. A little scuffed up after a long
walk, since the birds don't fly. Likes dog food, bottled water.
Seems to answer to ``Gertrude'' _ Gertie for short. Needs good
home, preferably one with other emu pals to play with.
</P>
<P>
   Conyers, Ga., resident Gordon Hart has been looking for the
rightful owners of one of the blue-necked birds since July 3, when
it wandered through his yard and into a nearby pen.
</P>
<P>
   But local experts say it's possible no one's pining for their
flightless friend. When the bottom dropped out of the emu breeding
market a few years back, some financially strapped bird ranchers
started turning the animals out like stray cats.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon and Cecelia Hart aren't sure whether that's what happened
to the emu they've dubbed Gertrude, but they say it's been slow
going to find a permanent home for the six-foot creature.
</P>
<P>
   Local emu farmers say breeding pairs, which sold for nearly
$20,000 10 years ago, are now worth only about $100.
</P>
<P>
   Noah's Ark, a home for neglected animals in Henry County, has
collected a gaggle of the birds _ 63 at last count. Staffer Kathy
Padia said disenchanted farmers drop them off. Shelter operators
said they'd be willing to take Gertie in if someone will offer to
transport her.
</P>
<P>
   The nearest registered emu farmer, Jackie Paul of Conyers, said
the bird isn't hers. But she said it could have come from an
unregistered breeder somewhere nearby.
</P>
<P>
   With emus out of favor and the Harts nearly out of hospitality,
the couple are hoping for a quick solution to their emu enigma.
``It's been a riot having her,'' Cecelia Hart said as she watered
the gangly animal Wednesday afternoon. ``But Gertie's got to go
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
