<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-TAX-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;   &QL;  &UR; The Case Where the Rich Get Less &QL;   &QL;  &UR; Pennsylvanians are rated
less wealthy. &QL;   &UR; By Laura J. Winter &QL;  &QC;  C. 2000 States News Service &QL;  &QC; 
WASHINGTON (July 12) - Pennsylvania is going to get back more for
its dollars from Washington, than it gives, so says a tax
foundation report. If it is a trend, this might not be good news,
according to economists.
</P>
<P>
   In a report published by the Tax Foundation, for every
Pennsylvanian dollar surrendered to the Internal Revenue Service
last year, $1.05 in services, infrastructure and direct payments
was returned to Keystone State residents. In fact compared to
Connecticut, the biggest loser in this spending-to-tax ratio - a
return of 65 cents for every dollar - Pennsylvania is not losing_.
Or is it?
</P>
<P>
   The IRS is expecting this year to raise $951.6 billion, or 49.7
percent, of the $1.914 trillion expected in tax collections from
personal income tax. The authors of the foundation report based
their findings on Census Bureau data.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, the federal government is estimated to
collect this year from each citizen an average of $6,981, 5.9
percent more than the 1999 average of $6,589. Individual
Pennsylvanians are expected to open their pocketbooks for $6,932
this year, just 4.7 percent more than the $6,616-burden of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really interesting that Pennsylvania's tax burden has
not grown because of the booming economy,'' said Scott Moody, a
foundation economist and author of the report. ``It could be some
sort of indication that they are growing at a lesser rate than most
states.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that traditionally Pennsylvania's tax burden has hovered
above the national average, until now.
</P>
<P>
   While the report is expecting Pennsylvania to pay less than the
average in federal taxes, the latest numbers available for 1999 put
the state's average income of $26,797 slightly above the national
average of $26,416. Projections on what individual Pennsylvanians
will make this year were unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   Some wealthy states - like Connecticut, New Jersey and New
Hampshire - will give much more than they will take in, the report
said. Others - like New Mexico, Montana and West Virginia - will
pay a whole lot less than they will get back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the way that the system is designed there is a
whole lot of wealth redistribution,'' Moody said. ``Higher income
states will be paying more into the system. The Northeast will be
paying more than the South.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's individual federal tax burden for this year is
expected to be $11,604. It ranks last in the amount of dollars it
receives back. West Virginia, which has the smallest tax burden at
$4,416, will get $1.72 for every dollar its residents send to
Washington, authors said in the report.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania is ranked 29 in the spending-to-tax ratio for 1999,
up in the money-receiving line from a decade ago when it came in at
35.
</P>
<P>
   Of the states getting a good deal from Uncle Sam, New Mexico
gets loads of federal money because it houses federal facilities,
like Los Alamos National Laboratory. While its $19,936 median
income, ranked 49th in the nation in 1999, it gets the highest
return for the dollar at $1.97. In contrast, most of the states
losing money in Washington simply have high concentrations of
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two families in two different states that have the same
incomes will have the same federal taxes,'' said William Gale, an
economist at the Brookings Institution. ``There are some sale taxes
but the main difference there is income.''
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
