<SLUG> BC-LAWN-RANGERS-2500(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THESE CONCERTGOERS, IT'S SPLENDID IN THE GRASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It's a cool Friday night at Smirnoff Music Centre, and
rocker Steve Miller is minutes away from performing. Fans in the
reserved seats calmly wait, making idle chatter, laughing. The
section isn't crowded.
</P>
<P>
   Behind them, in the music amphitheater's lawn area, it's a very
different story. The lawn section is utterly jammed; people are
sprawled on blankets and towels and rented lawn chairs, hiding
every last blade of grass.
</P>
<P>
   When the lights go down and the Dallas-based Miller takes the
stage, pot smoke begins to drift, sending clouds of gray across the
green. Pockets of college kids dance. Couples kiss and grope.
Teen-agers run through the grass, leaping over people staring at
the stars.
</P>
<P>
   Near the north tip of the lawn, a man starts to do something you
certainly would not see in the reserved section of the Smirnoff,
which, until this month, was known as Starplex: He pulls five toys
shaped like bowling pins out of a bag and begins juggling them.
People around him laugh, egging him on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different world out here,'' says the juggler,
22-year-old Jason Christensen of Dallas. ``You can come out here
and relax, smoke a little weed, listen to music, do whatever you
want. Out here, you're free.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every concert at Smirnoff attracts a crowd like this one:
concertgoers who aren't there to see the show so much as to be part
of a unique social group. They prefer to be on the lawn, where they
can almost create their own world, outside the rules of daily life.
Security is present, of course, but there are so many people that
lawn-goers know they're unlikely to be hassled by authority
figures, at least not for anything that's not obviously dangerous
to others. They can hang with friends, relax, get high, socialize,
make out, drink and, as Christensen puts it, be free.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel trapped in a seat,'' he says, juggling the pins. ``The
lawn is like a universe of its own, a free universe.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawn-goers exist almost as a subculture, a members-only club as
exclusive as any Prohibition-era speakeasy and as open as a public
library. All you need to get in is a ticket with the words
``general admission'' stamped on it, but you need much more for
acceptance. Each Smirnoff show draws its own distinct and typically
separate group _ young and old, straight and stoned, drinkers and
thinkers.
</P>
<P>
   Acts like Steve Miller and Jimmy Buffett draw a thirtysomething
audience that seeks to put day jobs and grown-up stresses behind
for an evening. On the lawn, the green of margaritas can cloak the
green of the grass. Despite the rowdiness and alcohol, these are
usually rather tame affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Alternative rock bands also draw white suburbanites, but they're
younger and even rowdier. Removed from the Big Brother constraints
of school and home, the teen-agers roam the lawn like wolf packs,
showing off the latest in Old Navy and Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch wear,
looking for someone to ``hook up'' with and trying to adults to buy
them a $7 beer. Mosh pits and impromptu make-out sessions are the
norm.
</P>
<P>
   Country shows attract a Wranglers, boots and cowboy-hat
contingent that often turns the lawn into a dance floor; dancing in
the aisles is forbidden in the reserved section.
</P>
<P>
   Jam bands such as Phish and Widespread Panic bring out the
stoners, those who lie out on the lawn, perhaps because they're so
out of it they can't move.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the metal shows, Smirnoff security's worst
nightmare. Bonfires, fistfights, drunks, people passed out and in
various stages of undress _ all business as usual when Ozzfest or
any other big metal show roars through Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a whole different scene on the lawn,'' says
Fred Downey, the security coordinator for D&AMP;L, the Dallas-based
security firm that staffs Smirnoff. ``Once you think you've seen it
all, something out there happens that makes you think otherwise.
Heck, we once had a baby born out there.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On a warm day in April, the lawn at Starplex (as it was known
then) is a sea of sunburned flesh. The sky is slightly overcast,
but the sun slices through the clouds enough during the day to cook
the skin of unprotected lawn-goers, a mostly cheery, young, white
crowd gathered for Edgefest 2000, a daylong alternative rock
festival.
</P>
<P>
   Around 7 p.m., attendance peaks at about 20,000; half of those
have settled on the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   It's a mixed bunch: Twentysomething guys and girls with tattoos,
colored hair, body piercings and little clothing mingle with
teen-agers spiffed up in Gap T-shirts, Old Navy Passenger shorts
and $100 Doc Marten sandals.
</P>
<P>
   But they all have one thing in common: They're all looking at
the same thing _ and it's not the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone's attention is directed at a pack of about 100 people
who have gathered around something on the lawn, creating a circle
that expands every time someone else steps up to vie for a look.
Security is called.
</P>
<P>
   The commotion is a fight that has broken out between two
twentysomething guys.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Melton doesn't even bat an eye. MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS: bat an eye. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's nothing,'' says the 22-year-old Richardson fast-food
employee. The last time he was at Starplex, he saw three guys
beating up a man who they thought was making advances toward one of
their girlfriends.''It's a mess up here, but I love it. There's
never a dull moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Not today, at least. Starplex's lawn is a continuous, often
entertaining blur of suburban teen life. Despite the occasional
shoving match and the rare fight, everyone seems to be getting
along.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about being here is the people-watching,'' says
Amber Baggett, 17, of Garland. ``You see some wild stuff up here.
It's kind of like a rave. Everyone's worried about getting caught,
but they do stuff anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Baggett is with her 14-year-old sister, Stacy. Together, they
sit on the lawn for nearly the entire concert, largely oblivious to
the chaos around them _ the people who step over them, occasionally
dripping nacho cheese or beer, the guys who size them up and maybe
even ask for their phone numbers, the people behind them screaming
at the bands or at one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's not that different from going to the mall,'' Amber
says. ``People act like idiots there, too, you know. You go to the
mall for the same reason you go to concerts, to get away from
parents and school and just escape from everything. But up there
(in the reserved section), they're stricter on what you can do. No
one really cares out here, unless you're, like, beating someone
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, 19-year-old Ben Vardeman of Grand Prairie and four of
his buddies are relaxing in the grass, smoking cigarettes, watching
a never-ending stream of girls wearing shorts and halter tops. Some
of the young women glance at the boys; others try not to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why am I on the lawn? Dude, to hook up,'' Vardeman says.
``This is where all the girls are, man.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, teen girls whose braces glimmer in the Texas sun are
in no short supply. Most travel in packs or with male escorts. A
subtle sense of danger lingers in the air for the more aware young
women, perhaps the result of recent assaults at other outdoor
concerts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone here is cool and nice,'' says Nicki Foster, 15, of
Plano. ``But I'm not gonna walk around the lawn by myself. I mean,
it's the lawn.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starplex opened in July 1988 with a concert by pop singer Rod
Stewart. Over the course of the following decade, the venue went
from hosting pop and classical concerts to what it does today:
everything, from country to hard rock. The lawn has also evolved.
It was supposed to be simply a cheaper place to watch live
performances. No one expected it to become a self-contained world,
where the concert on the distant stage is simply pleasing
background music, a soundtrack to the lawn-goers' activities.
</P>
<P>
   D&AMP;L's Fred Dunway has been there since the day it opened. He has
broken up fights, carried out those who have passed out, been
attacked by intoxicated or drugged-up fans and been caught in the
middle of crowds rushing the stage; he has many horror stories to
share.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of those horror stories is slowly dwindling, he
says. Bands and the venue are cracking down on what fans can bring
into Smirnoff, which he says should trim the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like blankets. At some shows, you can bring them in. Some,
like Nine Inch Nails, you can't,'' he says. ``And that's because
the kids used to burn them. We used to have so many bonfires on the
lawn.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunway says that security presence is constant at Smirnoff, no
matter the show. And police officers are always present, though
it's D&AMP;L security that usually patrols the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Big metal shows like Ozzfest, he says, are the hardest to
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``Metal shows can be a nightmare,'' he says. ``Lots of fights on
the lawn, lots of arrests for P.I. (public intoxication), lots of
people smoking things that they shouldn't be smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans caught doing drugs are usually taken to the main security
office, where police officers decide their fates. ``They're usually
arrested and hauled off,'' he says. ``But we can't catch
everyone.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not every lawn audience at Starplex/Smirnoff is party- and
hormone-driven. Teen acts such as the Spice Girls, Backstreet Boys
and the annual KISS Party concerts attract crowds heavily made up
of families.
</P>
<P>
   At KISS Party 2000, In June, Frisbees and beach balls drifted
across the lawn, taking the place of cigarette smoke. The sound of
laughter _ as well as the occasional parental ``Get over here!'' _
filled the air.
</P>
<P>
   For this group, the lawn represents the past, a time when they
were the ones out partying, exchanging phone numbers, listening to
music and trying to sneak gulps of beer while the security guard's
head was turned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to go to concerts all the time when I was a kid,'' says
Dana Mejia, a 41-year-old Dallas mother of three who ducks when a
toy football buzzes her way. ``We'd sit in the general admission or
outdoor section, drinking or whatever. It was a world of our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those assembled today stopped going to concerts years
ago, when mortgage and car payments took the place of beer and
T-shirt money, and their babies took the place of their friends,
but they still embrace the lawn's ethos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone out here has families. We're a little older. We have
to get up in the morning and take our kids to school and go to
work,'' Mejia says. ``But I guess that means we're also all in a
world of our own.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
