<HEADER>
A0315 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-FRANCE-CHALLENGES13-C     07-12 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-CHALLENGES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    French diplomat upbeat about conditions in his country
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - As they do every July, the world's best bicyclists are
wending their way through the verdant French countryside in the
Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, it seems that not only the cyclists but all of
France is on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it reflects that the French have more confidence in
themselves,'' says Jean-Paul Monchau, his nation's Atlanta-based
consul general and trade commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Consider some recent developments:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On July 1, France took over the rotating presidency of the
European Union _ a high profile role as the 15-member confederation
prepares to absorb new member nations and moves ahead with
development of its unified currency.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Vivendi, a French water utility, is transforming itself into a
telecommunications and entertainment giant and has just negotiated
one of the largest media deals ever in agreeing to acquire Canada's
Seagram Co. Ltd. with its Hollywood-based Universal Studios. &QR;  At
home, polls show consumer confidence is at record highs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And the French are even having a banner year in sports. Not
only did French citizen Mary Pierce thrill Paris by winning tennis'
French Open , but the French national soccer squad started this
month by becoming the first team to hold both the European and
World championships simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   All of this gives the French special reason to celebrate as
their biggest national holiday, Bastille Day, approaches Friday.
Monchau will be leading the charge at a reception at his Buckhead
home and at a smaller gathering in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the French diplomat noted in an interview this week,
challenges also loom for his country. Here are excerpts edited from
a transcript of the conversation:
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you account for France's recent successes?
</P>
<P>
   A: I remember I arrived here in June '97, and what struck me at
that time was the difference in the mentalities between the French
and Americans. In France, we were struggling to respect the
criteria of the Euro (Europe's unified currency) and we were making
sacrifices and the mood of the people was not good. When I arrived
in the States, I was struck by the fact that here people were sure
that tomorrow will be a brighter day and they were very confident
in themselves. What is happening now in France, I think, is what
happened a few years ago in the States. People are more and more
confident, and in fact we have good reasons in our economy. And
maybe the most important thing for the French people is that
unemployment is going down.
</P>
<P>
   Q: France is assuming the European presidency for an important
six months.
</P>
<P>
   A: It is true that we take the presidency at a very important
time because in Europe we are in the process of opening the door to
other members. We are 15 members, and we are in the process of
opening the door to maybe five and then 10 and then 12 other
members. ... So the French presidency comes at that time when we
have to modify the rules in order for the European Union to be able
to work well in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are France's priorities for the E.U.?
</P>
<P>
   A: The first one is economic growth and employment. That means
to reconcile economic growth with reinforcement of the European
social model. This is very important for us. And we wish to adopt
at the end of the presidency _ that is in December _ in Nice, the
city in the south of France, what we call a European social agenda.
What does it mean? It means that we want to assure ... economic and
social justice for all the people in Europe. We are much concerned
by the exclusion of some people who are still now left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the scenario for enlargement?
</P>
<P>
   A: All together you have 12 or 13 countries, which already have
said we are candidates. ... It means that the European Union is an
idea and a body that works, that gives benefits to its members.
Take the example of Spain or Portugal or Greece. They have
benefited a lot by being a member of the Union. And other countries
now knock at the door and say we want to be part of this. And for
us Europeans, if you look where we are coming from _ I mean, after
the Second World War _ all of us have benefited from the European
Union. So I believe that our interest, as members already, is to
welcome these new members when they are able to join this club. ...
Of course, they have to make some sacrifices to join. ... If you
read the different treaties ... you see that the economy is not the
only objective of the European Union. These countries must also
respewe know that the U.S. is a light for many people for
democracy, for freedom, and, in the meantime, there is still the
death penalty here. ... We believe it is a question of human
dignity and human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some trade issues also have cropped up between the E.U. and
the U.S., but in general how would you characterize the
relationship?
</P>
<P>
   A: The partnership is very, very strong. You know, if you add
the GNPs of the two unions you will see that it is something like
60 percent of the world GNP, so of course the exchanges are so
important. Cooperation is so important. You cannot exclude to have
conflicts, to have problems. But fortunately we have a very, very
strong dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : The European Union: europa.eu.int/ ; France's
consulate general in Atlanta: www.consulatfranceatlanta.org/
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
