<HEADER>
A0334 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-KRACKER-PREVIEW-LADN &LR;      07-12 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KRACKER-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE BUS WITH UNCLE KRACKER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Uncle Kracker put some miles on his music. He recorded his debut
album in the back of a bus.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't your average Greyhound, though. Known to family and
friends as Matt Shafer, Uncle Kracker is the guy behind the
turntables in Kid Rock's Twisted Brown Trucker band.
</P>
<P>
   His ``Double Wide'' (Lava/Atlantic) was cut in a makeshift
studio set up in Kid Rock's tour bus during cross-country treks
with Limp Bizkit and Metallica.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the only way we could do it,'' Shafer said. ``The
engineer made it so easy. He assembled this whole thing so we could
work on the bus and in hotel rooms. It was one big distraction,
that's for sure: between shows and rehearsals and photo shoots and
interviews ... not to mention the stuff that goes on in the bus.
But it kept me sober because I knew there was work that had to be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't only about work, of course. This is Kid Rock _ the guy
whose manic stage show includes strippers, a pint-size sidekick
named Joe C. and other assorted oddities.
</P>
<P>
   The laid-back yin to Kid's thunderously metallic yang, Shafer
serves up rock `n' roll that blends a bit of soul, country,
Southern blues-rock and hip-hop, topped off with the Michigan-bred
DJ's loose-limbed story-telling raps.
</P>
<P>
   Kid Rock and Uncle Kracker appear Saturday at the Los Angeles
Memorial Coliseum as part of the Summer Sanitarium Tour with
Metallica, Korn, Powerman 500 and System of a Down.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out the members of Metallica, who put the stadium tour
together, are among Kid's biggest fans. Kirk Hammett, the band's
lead guitarist, said it was an easy decision when choosing acts to
take on the road this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted someone who could really get the crowd going, who
everyone knew,'' Hammett said. ``Kid Rock puts on an amazing show.
You can't help but have a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   As you'd expect from two longtime friends _ Kid Rock and Shafer
have been pals since 1987 _ they share similar tastes. ``Double
Wide'' features 11 tracks co-written by Kid and Kracker, including
the stomper ``What 'Chu Lookin' At?'' used in ``M:I-2,'' and ``Yeah
Yeah Yeah,'' which ended up in the new Jackie Chan flick ``Shanghai
Noon.''
</P>
<P>
   Shafer was 13 when he hooked up with Bob Ritchie, the kid who
would be Kid, at a Michigan nightspot where Rock was spinning in an
all-ages DJ competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and my brother were competing against each other,'' Shafer,
25, recalled. ``They became friends after that, but then me and him
became best friends. I pretty much sat around for 10 years as
friends more than anything else. I was one of his biggest fans. And
I'm still one of his biggest fans.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kid Rock issued his debut album in 1991, he invited Shafer
to join his band as DJ. The only problem: The new DJ had no idea
how to work the turntables.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know how to scratch records or anything,'' Shafer
said. ``But I pretty much learned by playing shows. I never set up
in my bedroom and practiced _ my parents would freak if I turned it
up. We did shows, and it was do-or-die.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, Shafer learned his trade, serving as musical
foil to Kid on each project, including the mega-platinum ``Devil
Without a Cause'' album.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to do my own thing and being with Kid Rock
is a great outlet,'' Shafer said. ``Y'know, two heads are better
than one. We write together, we play together. But we've always had
a plan, to branch out and keep it all in the family. After 'Devil'
happened, it was the right time for me to do my own record.''
</P>
<P>
   Shafer has been performing some of his solo tracks as part of
the Kid Rock show but plans to take it on the road himself later
this year using the Twisted Brown Trucker group.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get burned out on the road,'' he admits. ``It fools you
because you come off tour and go home for five days and think,
`This is nice.' Five days later, you can't wait to get back out
there. It's weird. This whole thing has been like a fantasy anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like winning the lottery.'' &QL; 
--- &QL; 
Who: Summer Sanitarium Tour with Uncle Kracker (joining Kid Rock),
Metallica, Korn, Powerman 500 and System of a Down. &QL; 
Where: Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum, 3939 S. Figueroa St., Los
Angeles. &QL; 
When: 4 p.m. Saturday. &QL; 
Tickets: $45 and $65. &QL; 
Information: (213) 480-3232. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 1908EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
