<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service is planning full coverage _
text, graphics and photos _ of the Republican National Convention
in Philadelphia from July 31 to Aug. 3 and the Democratic National
Convention in Los Angeles from Aug. 14 to Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   A biographical series on Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President
Al Gore, written by New York Times political writers, has been
filed during the last two months, and the stories are available for
retransmission; the slugs are: BUSH-BIO, BUSH-BIO-II, BUSH-BIO-III
and BUSH-PARENTS; GORE-BIO, GORE-BIO-COLLEGE and GORE-MILITARY;
abridged versions and photos are available. For repeats, call
212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   Coverage of the political scene by New York Times reporters,
columnists and photographers will continue up to the opening of the
convention. For the first two days of the convention, the Times
editors plan three to four pages of stories, which will then expand
to five or six daily pages. The News Service will list these
stories on a daily convention budget (BC-GOP-BUDGET-NYT,
BC-DEM-BUDGET-NYT), which will include all Times stories and will
also spotlight stories from Times partner and regional newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for coverage include: a daily convention overview
(GOP-RDP-NYT), an analysis (GOP-ASSESS-NYT) and a scene or color
story (tentatively, GOP-SCENE-NYT or GOP-DIARY-NYT). The Times
editors are considering a schedule that includes profiles of
candidates and families, politicians and delegates; analyses of
issues, platforms and historical background; and sidebars on
business, economics and media, as well as polls and surveys. Times
columnists will attend the conventions and will also be writing on
political developments and issues.
</P>
<P>
   All convention stories will be filed in the ``p'' category and
will carry a convention designation in the slug; e.g.,
BC-GOP-BUSH-NYT or BC-DEM-GORE-NYT. All stories are for use by New
York Times News Service clients. Look for updated and more detailed
advisories closer to the opening of the convention.
</P>
