<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0342 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-CHURCH-BURNINGS-AZR &LR;      07-12 1672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-BURNINGS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-CHURCH-BURNINGS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    MEDIA IGNORED, THEN OVERSIMPLIFIED, BLACK CHURCH ARSONS (a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: Moving in ``A'' and ``K'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By Sharon Bramlett-Solomon (a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the national crisis over the burning of Black churches
has abated
</P>
<P>
   and the attention of the media is no longer focused on it, the
retreat of this
</P>
<P>
   news story from the spotlight may be a blessing. For the truth
is, an analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the nationwide phenomenon shows that newspapers did a
disturbingly poor job
</P>
<P>
   of explaining the church-burning ``conspiracy,'' reporting it
opaquely and
</P>
<P>
   strewing the issue with highly volatile implications,
particularly when it
</P>
<P>
   came to race.
</P>
<P>
   In short, news coverage of the idea of a conspiracy was unclear,
undefined,
</P>
<P>
   unenlightening, and it may have helped to escalate racial
tension.
</P>
<P>
   The evolution of the story shows how easy it was for the
conspiracy idea to
</P>
<P>
   be picked up by the press. From January 1995 to December 1997,
at least 142
</P>
<P>
   largely Southern Black churches were set on fire by arsonists.
Federal law
</P>
<P>
   enforcement officials and the U.S. national media began to focus
on these
</P>
<P>
   arson-caused fires in the spring 1996, after their swelling
numbers became too
</P>
<P>
   difficult (and too regional) to ignore. Pressure on federal
officials to
</P>
<P>
   investigate the church burnings came from community leaders,
politicians and
</P>
<P>
   ministers, both Black and White, across the country. The
torching of almost 40
</P>
<P>
   Black churches in 11 Southern states over this 18-month period
signaled a
</P>
<P>
   crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The series of Black church burnings in the south has special
historical
</P>
<P>
   resonance. Many Americans saw the fires not only as racially
driven, but also
</P>
<P>
   as a stark reminder of America's dark era of racial strife in
the 1950s and
</P>
<P>
   1960s, when church burnings were a major form of White terrorism
against Black
</P>
<P>
   Americans. During the civil rights movement, scores of Black
churches that
</P>
<P>
   were rallying points for civil rights demonstrations were bombed
or set on
</P>
<P>
   fire. Black Americans tended to see church burnings as a symbol
and reminder
</P>
<P>
   of racist America as well as a sign of deteriorating race
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Frances Berry, chairwoman of the U.S. Commission on Civil
Rights,
</P>
<P>
   labeled the Black church fires ``a wake-up call'' for Americans
to deal with
</P>
<P>
   the nation's race-relations issue. Berry reported that federal
investigations
</P>
<P>
   revealed 70 percent of the Southern Black church fires were
racially
</P>
<P>
   motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to growing outrage over the church fires, President
Clinton in
</P>
<P>
   June 1996 created the National Church Arson Task Force,
including 200 members
</P>
<P>
   from the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, the FBI and
the U.S. Justice
</P>
<P>
   Department. It was the largest federal task force in history. A
major question
</P>
<P>
   federal officials explored was whether the Black church arsons
were set by
</P>
<P>
   racists, conspirators, copycats or others.
</P>
<P>
   Deval Patrick, U.S. assistant attorney general for civil rights,
who headed
</P>
<P>
   the church task force, said investigations revealed that race
was only one of
</P>
<P>
   several causes. He said some fires had been set by church
members trying
</P>
<P>
   fraudulently to collect insurance money, others by burglars and
some by
</P>
<P>
   pyromaniacs. In a handful of cases, he said, the arsonists
involved were in
</P>
<P>
   hate groups.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick said investigation over a 15-month period found nothing
to show
</P>
<P>
   there was a national conspiracy targeting Black churches. Arsons
at White
</P>
<P>
   churches, he said, approached the number at Black churches, with
both taking
</P>
<P>
   place at record numbers.
</P>
<P>
   However, Patrick said although no organized conspiracy was
found, ``an
</P>
<P>
   intense climate of racism behind the church fires'' did exist.
Profiles of
</P>
<P>
   those arrested, Patrick said, revealed they were generally
White, male and
</P>
<P>
   young, low-income, poorly educated, frequently drunk or high on
drugs, rarely
</P>
<P>
   affiliated with hate groups, but often deeply driven by racism.
In other
</P>
<P>
   words, although conspiracy theories were largely debunked by the
task force,
</P>
<P>
   racist motives were not.
</P>
<P>
   Two prominent figures increased national press coverage. Clinton
drew media
</P>
<P>
   attention with a speech given at the site of a burned church in
June 1996 in
</P>
<P>
   Greelyville, S.C. He vowed that the church burnings would not be
tolerated and
</P>
<P>
   would be intensely investigated by federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   An unprecedented victory
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1997, with increased national press attention,
stiffer
</P>
<P>
   punishments and a louder public outcry, the arson-caused fires
at Black
</P>
<P>
   churches began to decline after about 15 months of National
Church Arsons Task
</P>
<P>
   Force investigations.
</P>
<P>
   In an unprecedented victory for burned Black churches, a South
Carolina
</P>
<P>
   jury of nine Blacks and three Whites in July 1998 ordered the
Klu Klux Klan to
</P>
<P>
   pay $12.6 million to Macedonia Baptist Church. The jury deemed
the Klan's
</P>
<P>
   rhetoric of hate had motivated four Klansmen to set the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, several journalists questioned the media coverage's
accuracy and
</P>
<P>
   fairness, charging the press with initial indifference to the
burnings,
</P>
<P>
   simplistic treatment of a complex story, stereotyping the
arsonists as largely
</P>
<P>
   White racists, and escalating public hysteria by hyping the
story as a return
</P>
<P>
   to the tactics of the segregation era.
</P>
<P>
   Despite critics, at least one press defender addressed the
topic. American
</P>
<P>
   Journalism Review writer Joe Holley noted that over a
seven-month period,
</P>
<P>
   journalists prudently ``connected the dots'' in the fires. They
tended to take
</P>
<P>
   place at Southern Black churches in isolated or rural areas with
most of the
</P>
<P>
   arsonists being White. ``It's an example of how the media can be
distracted,
</P>
<P>
   even misled for a while, but given time, are able to right
themselves, regain
</P>
<P>
   their balance, and tease out the complex truth,'' Holley wrote.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Birmingham Post Herald reporter Ted Bryant
criticized
</P>
<P>
   the press for moving from ``indifference'' to ``hysteria'' and
charged that
</P>
<P>
   reporters inaccurately promoted stereotypes of the arsonists as
White
</P>
<P>
   hate-mongers. Michael Kelly, New Yorker magazine writer, also
noted coverage
</P>
<P>
   problems. He said that at first, reporters paid little attention
to the fires
</P>
<P>
   but later went overboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a case of overreaction that seems to have been inspired in
roughly
</P>
<P>
   equal measure by genuine concern, guilt and self-interests, they
leaped on the
</P>
<P>
   bandwagon with near-hysteria as misplaced as their previous
indifference,''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly wrote. Detroit Free Press religion writer David Crumm also
took the
</P>
<P>
   press to task, charging that reporters ignored motives other
than racism and
</P>
<P>
   ``often relied heavily on stereotypes supporting the idea that a
pack of
</P>
<P>
   church-burning racists could be on the loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, none of these critics addressed the fact that one of the
most
</P>
<P>
   confusing aspects of the reporting was the focus on whether they
were part of
</P>
<P>
   a national conspiracy. Although federal investigators say they
found no
</P>
<P>
   national conspiracy at work (such as KKK or militia groups),
coverage of the
</P>
<P>
   issue was confounding rather than informative. This writer's
research study of
</P>
<P>
   newspaper editorials from the Nexis Lexis database and
Editorials on File
</P>
<P>
   showed that only a third of the 109 editorials published on the
burnings
</P>
<P>
   addressed the conspiracy issue and that what was written was
poorly explained
</P>
<P>
   and highly ambiguous.
</P>
<P>
   Making an unclear point
</P>
<P>
   For example, a St. Louis Post Dispatch June 12, 1996, editorial
stated that
</P>
<P>
   church fire investigations ``turned up no interstate
conspiracy'' even though
</P>
<P>
   ``several fires have been linked to people with KKK ties.'' But
the editorial
</P>
<P>
   writer's point about the conspiracy issue was unclear. Because
the KKK has
</P>
<P>
   members in chapters across the nation, why would KKK or Aryan
Nation member
</P>
<P>
   involvement not constitute a local (if not a national)
conspiracy? This
</P>
<P>
   unanswered question should have been addressed to help readers
put facts into
</P>
<P>
   perspective.
</P>
<P>
   In a more radical perspective, Noah Chandler of the Center for
Democratic
</P>
<P>
   Renewal in Atlanta, a civil rights watchdog group, called media
focus on the
</P>
<P>
   conspiracy question ``racist conspiracy itself.'' Other
conspiracy labels also
</P>
<P>
   were noted in the press, including what the Houston Chronicle
called a
</P>
<P>
   ``conspiracy of silence'' and the Bergen Record called
``conspiracy of
</P>
<P>
   hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the press conspiracy discussion was short on clarity
and showed
</P>
<P>
   that, though well-intentioned, American journalists were unable
to deal with
</P>
<P>
   racial motivations that lie deep in the culture; so deep, in
fact, that they
</P>
<P>
   can be expressed spontaneously, without coordination and over an
extended
</P>
<P>
   period of time. Such coverage shows journalists have difficulty
handling
</P>
<P>
   subtle events and reporting on complex social events without
jumping to sudden
</P>
<P>
   conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Although current reports from the Church Arson Task Force reveal
the Black
</P>
<P>
   church fires have greatly declined, Assistant Attorney General
Patrick says
</P>
<P>
   investigations of the arson cases and vigorous pursuit of the
arsonists
</P>
<P>
   continue. But it may be blissful that national news headlines on
the fires
</P>
<P>
   have ceased. For although press perspectives on the rates,
arrests and
</P>
<P>
   deep-seated and complex racial motivations behind the arsons are
warranted,
</P>
<P>
   what is not are poorly explained ideas and speculation of a
national
</P>
<P>
   conspiracy targeting Black churches that may help to incite the
very racism it
</P>
<P>
   seeks to expose.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sharon Bramlett-Solomon is a professor of journalism in the
Walter
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite School of Journalism &AMP; Telecommunication at Arizona
State University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
