</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-WILDFLOWER-TOURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILDFLOWER FESTIVAL MAY BE GETTING TOO POPULAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT CRESTED BUTTE, Colo. _ Ever so slowly, the secret is
getting out.
</P>
<P>
   This time of year, the fields and mountain slopes here explode
into color, with more than 1,000 varieties of wildflowers poking
through the grasslands in a dazzling crazy-quilt of brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   Residents always knew about the wildflowers, but not many others
did until it occurred to a group of local leaders nearly 20 years
ago that the flowers might be an ideal way to show off a town known
almost exclusively as a ski resort. So they began the Crested Butte
Wildflower Festival as a summer weekend of wildflower hikes led by
experts who knew a harebell from a fringed gentian and a sneezeweed
from a little sunflower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then,'' said Nan Buxton, a visitor from Oklahoma City who
has attended the festival almost every year, ``you could just come
down and sign up.''
</P>
<P>
   Now look: The festival has grown so big and popular that
participants call weeks in advance to reserve space for nearly 150
hikes, workshops and evening programs that have turned the festival
into a week-long event. In addition to nature walks, activities
include classes on nature photography, medicinal plants, edible
plants, organic gardens, insects, butterflies and ecosystems. Some
fill up so quickly that people are turned away.
</P>
<P>
   And that is beginning to worry festival organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Not unlike the region itself _ Mount Crested Butte and the
larger town 3 miles below, Crested Butte _ the wildflower festival
has reached a critical point, forcing organizers to confront
questions of how to manage growth while preserving the reasons for
which the festival became so popular. In its early years, about 100
people attended. By the end of this year's events on Sunday,
organizers say 2,500 will have participated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We began with a handful of people, and we ended up getting
bigger every year,'' said Dana Bradley Spencer, a wildlife
biologist who is the festival's board president. ``If we get too
big, we can't really offer the quality and specialness of teaching
people about the flowers. Visitors want a quaintness, stylized to
fit their enjoyment of flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, groups of a dozen or so seem manageable. Leading a
2-and-a-half-hour hike on Tuesday, Alison Gannett, a botanist from
the University of Vermont, had plenty of time to spot more than two
dozen varieties of wildflowers, discuss their characteristics,
answer questions and keep group members from trampling too many
other flowers to see the ones she was pointing out.
</P>
<P>
   With a group that size, Gannett never had to raise her voice
when explaining that yarrow, a purple flower, is a natural
antibiotic, or that according to folklore, sheep that eat false
skunk cabbage, a pale green plant, give birth to offspring with
only one eye _ ``sheep cyclops,'' she said. In a larger group, some
might have missed that.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Spencer said organizers would have to review this year's
festival to decide how much, if at all, it could grow next year,
the owners of the ski resort are also contemplating how to expand
without overwhelming a region that visitors have always appreciated
for its charm and community spirit.
</P>
<P>
   As a ski area, Crested Butte cannot match the size or glitz of
the larger ski resorts in Colorado, like Aspen, Vail and
Breckenridge. Former President Jimmy Carter visits here annually,
and James MacArthur, the actor who played Danno on ``Hawaii
Five-0,'' lives here. But that is about it for the town's famous
connections.
</P>
<P>
   What Crested Butte does have in common with nearly every other
Colorado ski resort is a recent downward economic trend. Warm
winters and a lack of snow have cut sharply into the number of
skier-visits, which is defined as one skier skiing per day. Over
the last two winters, the number at Crested Butte has fallen by 24
percent, compared with the statewide average decline of 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Callaway family, which owns the ski resort, has known for
years it has to change to remain competitive. It helps that the
wildflower festival and dozens of other cultural events are drawing
more people into the area in summer. But the ultimate health of a
ski resort depends upon skiing facilities, amenities and ease of
access to the slopes. Expanding them has become no less perplexing
to the Callaway family than the same issue on a smaller scale is to
the wildflower organizers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you put in a new lift or a new hotel, it echoes
down the valley,'' Edward C. Callaway, the resort's president and
chief executive, said Wednesday, explaining why the family has
taken a slow approach to growth that preserves open space, rather
than adopt an aggressive strategy that could choke the region with
traffic, overwhelm the supply of housing and drive out ranchers
whose families have worked land in the valley for generations.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, the resort needs a second mountain for
skiing, and it has one nearby, Snodgrass Mountain. By adding
intermediate ski runs to Snodgrass to complement the beginner and
expert runs that Crested Butte Mountain has in abundance, the
resort would become more attractive to more families.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, Callaway said, that will wait. Instead, the owners
are planning to spur growth at a more modest rate, with new
amenities on the existing slopes and a new town center that will
include retail space, a town hall and a recreation center. Beyond
that, there are plans for expanding public transportation and
building housing that would be affordable for people who work in
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Then, maybe then, Callaway said, when the family is convinced
that adverse impacts on the region would be minimal, Snodgrass
might be developed. There is no rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to grow but we want to grow smart, by putting in
development where it exists, not where it doesn't exist,'' Callaway
said. ``We've drawn a line in the flowers, and we never want to go
over it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 1915EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
