<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0366 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BKN-DEMARR13-COX     07-12 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DEMARR13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks' rookie Johnson, mom trying to adjust to life in NBABy
Maiya Hayes
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - It's not easy being a young man with big NBA dreams.
But try being his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Powell said she saw her son DerMarr Johnson only twice
during his senior year in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson spent his 1998-99 school year at Maine Central
Institute, while Powell continued to live in their hometown of
Riverdale, Md., more than 600 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later and Powell still can't see her 20-year-old son
that often. Johnson, the Hawks' top-draft pick, is still working
hard on his NBA dreams.
</P>
<P>
   This week, he has endured three draining days of practice during
the team's camp for rookies and free agents. Today, Johnson and the
other players in the Hawks' camp play the Indiana Pacers' team at
Life University in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Powell said she is proud of her son and thinks he can handle
living in Atlanta on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has a beautiful personality,'' she said. ``He's
quiet, he's sensible, he's giving. He's just D.J.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he has been disappointed with his performance so
far in practice. Adjusting to the NBA level has been tough for the
6-foot-9, 200-pound guard. He has been hampered by foot blisters
since Monday and has yet to reach his comfort level.
</P>
<P>
   But Powell also has had a tough time adjusting to the distance
between her and her middle child. ``It does hurt as a mother to see
him go so far away,'' said Powell, who calls her son every day.
</P>
<P>
   It took a lot of persuading on Johnson's part to get his
mother's permission, but she eventually agreed to let him spend his
senior year in Maine. Playing there turned out to be a great
experience for Johnson, who averaged 26.1 points, 6.3 rebounds and
3.9 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson then took his skills to the University of Cincinnati,
which allowed his mother to attend more of his games. Johnson chose
Cincinnati because he thought that Bearcats' coach Bob Huggins
would help prepare him for the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been preparing for the league since I was a sophomore,''
Johnson said. ``Back when I was coming out of high school, the
skills were there, but I needed coaching under coach Huggins to get
some toughness, to get stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   In his freshman year at Cincinnati, Johnson averaged 12.6 points
and 3. 8 rebounds per game. He made 37 percent of his 3-pointers
and shot almost 48 percent from the field. He was named Conference
USA freshman of the year and was third-team all-conference.
</P>
<P>
   But after one year at Cincinnati, Johnson decided that it was
time to rise to the next level.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so athletic that in college he just beat people off his
athleticism,'' Hawks guard Dion Glover said. ``On this level, he's
got to realize that everybody's athletic. But I think DerMarr is
going to be a great player on this level.''
</P>
<P>
   Glover, who left Georgia Tech early, said the college
experiences Johnson will miss don't outweigh the chance he's been
given to play in the NBA. Hawks coach Lon Kruger said he has been
impressed by Johnson's ball-handling abilities, his athleticism and
his shooting range. With a little time and a lot of effort, Johnson
can succeed in the league, Kruger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all relates to investing time and effort every day,'' the
coach said. ``Realizing that it's a process. It's not going to
happen this week. It's a combination of working extremely hard and
being patient and just staying after it every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he will work hard and plans to show the team how
grateful he is to be a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that this team needed scorer and a shooter,'' he said.
``And I still think I can provide that for them once I get more
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
