<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0369 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-AIDS-MOTHERS-HNS &LR;      07-12 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-MOTHERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDS DOCTORS DEMAND S. AFRICA PROVIDE ANTI-HIV DRUGS TO PREGNANT
WOMEN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Editors: Friday in 7th graf refers to July 7.) 
 
By LEIGH HOPPER 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa _ For the fourth straight day, researchers
in South Africa on Wednesday demanded the government immediately
begin providing drugs to HIV-positive pregnant women to prevent
thousands of new infections in babies every year.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has been the overriding, controversial theme of this
week's contentious 13th International AIDS Conference. New data
reported at the meeting underscored the promise of the prevention
strategy, as well as obstacles to providing it, and fueled
conviction that the country's president must implement a national
program for distributing the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the most practical and feasible option for the majority
of women in the world today,'' said Dr. Chewe Luo, in her address
to the delegates Wednesday morning. She said the current rate of
1,800 HIV-infected children born each day worldwide ``is
unacceptable, knowing we have an intervention to reduce this
trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Without preventive treatment, there is a 25 percent to 30
percent chance that a woman with HIV, the virus that causes AIDS,
will infect her newborn, either during pregnancy, delivery or
through breast-feeding.
</P>
<P>
   A three-part AZT drug regimen can decrease the rate of perinatal
transmission by approximately two-thirds. But the regimen costs
$800 to $1,000, putting it out of reach for poor nations. Two years
ago, researchers at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
in Atlanta found that a shorter _ and cheaper _ course of AZT was
also effective, reducing the rate of transmission by 50 percent at
a cost of about $80.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a simpler and even less expensive regimen _ a single
dose of nevirapine for both mother and baby _ was shown to cut the
baby's risk of infection by 47 percent. This anti-AIDS drug, which
can be stored at room temperature and costs just $4 per
mother-child pair, holds tantalizing possibilities for countries
such as South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the German drug manufacturer Boehringer Ingelheim
announced that it is offering nevirapine free to developing
nations. So far, the South African government has not accepted the
offer. Pretoria's hesitation has fed a furor that began late last
year when President Thabo Mbeki voiced an interest in the ideas of
scientists who deny that HIV is the cause of AIDS. He has also
alarmed doctors by calling AZT a toxic drug, refusing to provide it
to pregnant women.
</P>
<P>
   This week, findings from an ongoing study in Soweto, South
Africa, involving 1,212 mothers taking AZT or nevirapine, showed
that both regimens are similar and safe.
</P>
<P>
   Questions, however, have been raised in a Ugandan study about a
small percentage of mothers becoming resistant to treatment with
nevirapine and the drug not working in subsequent pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   The South African Department of Health released a statement
Wednesday that it is encouraged by the benefits nevirapine seems to
offer, particularly because of the relative ease of administering
the drug. But officials noted ``more work is needed to confirm
safety and efficacy. That is particularly so in regard to the
development of resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   The department repeated its intention to meet soon after the
conference to review the data and the implications for public
policy.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the three-part AZT regimen has reduced the
rate of mother-to-child transmission of the AIDS virus to less than
2 percent in cities such as Houston. More healthy HIV-positive
couples are taking combination drug therapy and are conceiving and
delivering HIV-negative children.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the world, mostly in poor countries, half a million
babies are born with HIV each year. In South Africa, where millions
face death because AIDS treatment isn't available, many believe
preventing maternal transmission represents the best hope to slow
the disease's progress. A study published last month in The Lancet
suggested that if all pregnant women in South Africa took a short
course of antiretroviral medication during labor, as many as
110,000 infant HIV infections could be prevented over the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Soweto study's lead author, Dr. James McIntyre, said he is
hopeful that Mbeki will give the green light to a national
nevirapine program. ``The health department can't move until they
have that data,'' McIntyre said. ``We have to make sure they have
the information they need.''
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre is director of the perinatal and HIV research unit at
Chris Hani Baragwanath Hospital, one of the largest in the southern
hemisphere. The hospital tests 8,000 women for HIV annually;
one-fourth of them are positive.
</P>
<P>
   His team is now moving into a large-scale pilot project with the
government's blessing. The program aims to enroll 6,000 women in
Soweto, and 4,000 more in other provinces over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   A huge hurdle remains even if the drug becomes widely available:
HIV transmission by breast-feeding. Of all babies infected by their
mothers, one-third acquire the virus through breast-feeding.
Despite the risk, breast-feeding in Africa is an economic,
religious and cultural necessity for many women. In some areas,
women who formula feed are stigmatized as having HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Even when formula is acceptable, lack of clean water to mix it
with can lead to fatal diarrhea for babies.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the dangers posed by formula-feeding, scientists have
hoped that the drugs used to prevent maternal transmission might
have a lasting protective effect, allowing babies to nurse but not
entirely reversing the gains from anti-HIV drugs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
