<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0370 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH0713-COX     07-12 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH0713-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BBy Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ George W. Bush campaign strategists are
convinced their guy is right on the issues, but, in a message
pushed Wednesday at a meeting of GOP leaders in Austin, they
believe that image and feel will put him in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush team is crafting a campaign reflecting months of polls
showing Democrat Al Gore running ahead of Bush issue by issue, but
Bush leading on the all-important leadership question.
</P>
<P>
   Don Evans, the campaign's general chairman, wasted no time in
hitting that note in his introduction of Bush at the Wednesday
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message I've heard all across America this last 14 or 15
months is, `We are ready for new leadership. We are ready for a
leader of total integrity,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has spent the past few months offering positions and
policies on a wide variety of issues, also talked about an
electorate looking for something less tangible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can feel it when I go to your states. I can see it in
people's eyes. I feel it on the rope lines,'' he said. ``People of
this country want something different and this campaign is going to
give it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said it's working, and ``I feel great about our chances in
every state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a hard, close campaign. The good news is
I'm leading some of the polls. The bad news is the election isn't
tomorrow,'' he said. ``So we've got a lot of work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's event was organized by Victory 2000, an arm of the
Republican National Committee. Bush offered the opening remarks
before the GOP leaders went behind closed doors for an afternoon of
briefings from campaign officials. The day ended with an evening
reception at the Hyatt's 16th-floor ``Presidential Suite.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Bush met for an hour at the Governor's Mansion
with former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger, who said the two
men share ``comparable views'' on foreign policy topics.
</P>
<P>
   Both men declined to comment on the ongoing Middle East peace
talks orchestrated by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important time and it's important for Republicans
to wish the administration well,'' said Bush. ``There would be
nothing better than a lasting peace in the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   Between sessions at the political gathering at the Hyatt
Regency, strategist Karl Rove said the campaign is ready to
capitalize on the Bush image as a ``a strong leader and somebody
who is straightforward, somebody who is plain spoken, somebody who
is approachable and likeable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And Gore comes across as somebody who, as the governor said,
reinvents himself every week. And after awhile that sort of wears
on people,'' Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush frequently works to portray Gore as a standard-issue
politician who will ``say anything to get elected.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of reinventing government, Vice President Gore
continues to reinvent himself right in the middle of a campaign,''
Bush said Wednesday, branding Gore as ``more of the same . . . The
same old sequel to a tired period of time, four more years of a
president at war with Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove said the campaign plans to showcase the differences with
events tailored to make the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay tuned,'' said Rove, hinting at ``open, free formats where
people get a chance to get a real sense of who he is in sort of an
unscripted environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove, tuned into the feel of campaign events, said a Tuesday
appearance in Detroit highlighted Bush's strengths. The policy du
jour was a $2.3 billion, five-year plan to improve child welfare
services and adoption procedures.
</P>
<P>
   But a day later, Rove said the high point of the event was feel,
not substance. He recalled how Darryl McGee, a 19-year-old former
client of the foster care facility that hosted the event, talked
about how Bush helped him feel calm enough to discuss very personal
matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most compelling thing that came out of the adoption thing
was not so much what the governor said, but the kid who said, `I'm
really nervous, but the governor sort of helped me feel like I
could talk about it,''' said Rove.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to confidence in their candidate's leadership
quotient, Bush aides are buoyed by polls showing him making
progress on issues long controlled by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are anywhere from a dozen to two dozen or better points
ahead of where a Republican should be on some of these traditional
issues like health care, education and Social Security,'' said
Rove. ``On some of them we have not only closed the gap but we also
have moved ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas businessman Fred Meyer, chairman of Victory 2000, said
Bush reminds him of Ronald Reagan, another Republican who rode
perceived leadership skills _ not a set of stands on issues _ to
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think George W. has got the right position on the issues
that are important to the voters, big time,'' said Meyer. ``But
most important of all is leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
