A0378 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MOTOROLA13-COX     07-12 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTOROLA13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Motorola reports solid sales and earnings growth
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - Motorola Inc. delivered solid sales and earnings
growth Wednesday, reporting record sales of $9.26 billion, up 22
percent, and record earnings before special items.
</P>
<P>
   The Schaumburg, Ill.-based communications equipment company
reported stronger sales across a broad range of products including
networking equipment, Internet access devices and semiconductors.
Excluding special reserves for restructuring, Motorola reported
earnings of $515 million, or 23 cents a share, from ongoing
operations, before adjustments, up 91 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   After reserves were taken, net earnings were considerably less
-- $204 million, or 9 cents a share, but analysts said the
company's performance was in line with their expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall it looked pretty good,'' said analyst Greg Teets with
A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis, ``but I didn't see anything that
was really outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorola's results were released after the close of the market,
in which its stock closed up $2.69 a share to close at $36.25 a
share in New York Stock Exchange trading. Internet and
computer-related stocks helped the Nasdaq composite index gain
143.17 points, or 3.62 percent, to close at 4,099.59 -- its best
finish since April 10. Analysts said there is fading concern about
higher interest rates and better-than-expected earnings from Yahoo
Inc., an Internet bellwether.
</P>
<P>
   At Motorola, chief executive Christopher Galvin said his company
continues its recovery from a deep business slump in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our eighth consecutive quarter of delivering on our
promises to achieve a significant turnaround, improved
profitability and a strategic refocusing of Motorola around
wireless, broadband access and the Internet,'' Galvin said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Austin-based semiconductor business, showed
continued improvement as it recovers from a severe slump in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Chip sales totaled $2 billion in the quarter, up 27 percent from
a year ago, and new orders rose 31 percent to $2.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Operating profits rose to $166 million compared with $24 million
a year ago. Sales were up significantly in semiconductors for the
networking, computing, wireless, imaging and entertainment, and
transportation markets.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola employs about 10,000 workers in Austin who design,
manufacture and sell many of the company's most advanced chips.
</P>
<P>
   In other product areas, Motorola reported sales of wireless
phones rose 20 percent to $3.3 billion and operating profits were
$132 million, up from $125 million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of networking equipment grew 23 percent to $2.0 billion
and operating profits were $256 million, up 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Broadband communications equipment sales totaled $768 million
and operating profits totaled $215 million.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Kirk Ladendorf at kladendorf(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
