<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-COLLEGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB FIRM HAS PLAN TO BUILD COLLEGE SAVINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A Massachusetts dot-com Wednesday unveiled plans to
turn Americans' lust for spending into a productive pastime.
</P>
<P>
   UPromise Inc., backed by some big names and even bigger money,
aims to create a network of companies that give rebates in the form
of college savings plan contributions. President Jeff Bussgang said
the system would be in place this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding money for college is one of the biggest problems
families face these days,'' Bussgang said. ``Our goal is to help
solve that problem, taking advantage of the fact that companies are
desperate for programs that will create customer loyalty.''
</P>
<P>
   UPromise is like a frequent-flier program, with a scholastic
twist. People who sign up and then buy products from participating
companies can have up to 5 percent of their purchases invested in
the tax-free college fund of their favorite prospective student.
</P>
<P>
   A family with a typical income and spending pattern could expect
to save $50,000 over 15 years in the plan, Bussgang said. That
would cover more than half of the expected tab for four years of
tuition, room and board at a public university, starting in 2015.
</P>
<P>
   Families could save even more if they convince friends and
relatives to join UPromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great idea,'' said Joseph Hurley, a certified
public accountant in Pittsford, N.Y., and author of ``The Best Way
to Save for College.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody is prepared to jump on the UPromise bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Kristin Davis, senior associate editor at Kiplinger's Personal
Finance Magazine and author of ``Financing College,'' said she's
skeptical the program will make much of a difference for most
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're already in one of these savings plans, I suppose it
couldn't hurt to join,'' Davis said of UPromise. ``But it strikes
me that it would be awfully foolish to base all of your college
plans on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bussgang said UPromise isn't designed to replace other forms of
college savings, but to supplement them _ to the tune of $50
billion in additional projected savings in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   At least a handful of high-profile venture capitalists are
convinced. Greylock Management of Boston and General Atlantic
Partners of New York were among the firms that pledged $34 million
in first-round
</P>
<P>
   financing for UPromise.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Schulman, chief executive of Priceline.com, is on the board.
Outside advisors include Kim Clark, dean of the Harvard Business
School; George Fisher, chairman of Eastman Kodak; Nick Nicholas
Jr., former chief executive of Time Warner; and, John Whitehead,
former chairman of both Goldman Sachs and the Federal Reserve Bank
of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a phenomenal group of people,'' Bussgang said.
</P>
<P>
   UPromise founder and chief executive Michael Bronner is
responsible for bringing most of those people on board. At his
previous company, Boston-based Digitas Inc., Bronner headed
direct-marketing campaigns for AT&AMP;T and American Express, among
others, and built a name for himself as a marketing whiz.
</P>
<P>
   Bronner, who had a family emergency and wasn't available for
comment Wednesday, sold half of his stake in Digitas for $123
million. He still owns shares of stock worth another $131 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bussgang would not disclose the names of potential corporate
partners Wednesday, but said UPromise would do so ``closer to the
launch date this fall.''
</P>
<P>
   He did say, though, that companies in the network will have to
agree to donate a portion of customers' payments to a UPromise
scholarship fund for low-income students.
</P>
<P>
   Both he and Bronner have promised to donate half of their
personal stakes in the company to the fund, as have the venture
capital investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
