<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: FREEZE-OUT AT POLICE PLAZA 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Here's the thing you need to know about Sandra Marsh,
who is 57 years old and a lawyer: She did nothing wrong. Absolutely
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   And yet Howard Safir and his boys ruthlessly destroyed her
career and forced her out of the Police Department, where she had
spent 13 years doing work that was valuable and that she loved.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh was the deputy commissioner responsible for handling
complaints of employment harassment when she left the department in
1998. She had served with distinction under five police
commissioners. She was the department's highest-ranking black
official, and the only black deputy commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Former Police Commissioner William Bratton, in a telephone
conversation Wednesday, said: ``I thought a lot of her and the
staff she had there. She had an extraordinarily difficult
assignment, and my experience with her was excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   Marsh's problems started with a particularly bitter sexual
harassment case that erupted in Staten Island in 1997. There were
complaints that female police officers had been harassed, that they
had been punished for filing complaints, and that retaliatory
action had been taken against other officers who offered support
for the original complainants.
</P>
<P>
   The case was investigated by Marsh and her staff. She said in
her report that she had been unable to substantiate the sexual
harassment claims. But she also found that the case had been
improperly handled, and that top officials in the department had
indeed engaged in retaliation, and had tried to impede her
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The report specifically criticized Assistant Chief Eugene
Devlin, the Staten Island police commander, and his second in
command, Deputy Chief Phil Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh's career was not doomed at that point. She was on shaky
ground, but her boss, Safir, gave her an opportunity to recover.
All she had to do was revise her findings. In short, take the heat
off the chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Devlin and Phil Erickson were big shots in the
department, fair-haired boys with powerful connections and thus
big-time clout. They didn't outrank Marsh, who reported directly to
Safir, but they might as well have. Their toes were not to be
stepped on.
</P>
<P>
   Safir ordered the case reinvestigated, and it was made clear
that a different result was desired.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh did reinvestigate the case. But the only way she could
have saved herself was to betray herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``She went back and honestly re-evaluated the case,'' said her
lawyer, Richard Emery. ``And she came up with the same results. And
then they crushed her.''
</P>
<P>
   Marsh and her top aide, a police captain, had to give an oral
report of the results of the second investigation. In an interview
this week, Marsh said, ``We mistakenly thought that once they saw
the evidence, and once they understood how we reached this
decision, that they would understand and all of this would go
away.''
</P>
<P>
   She was so wrong. Safir, furious, stopped meeting with her and
stopped talking to her. He ordered the investigation done yet
again, but not by Marsh. That investigation dutifully cleared Chief
Devlin and Chief Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh's top aide was transferred to a post in Queens, working
nights. A new aide was imposed on Marsh, and he began running _ and
even remodeling _ her office.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh's career was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was still the deputy commissioner,'' she said, ``but I
wasn't being consulted about anything.''
</P>
<P>
   She left the department in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Her case was taken up by Emery, an old friend who founded the
law firm Emery Cuti Brinckerhoff &AMP; Abady as a vehicle to _ among
other things _ curb the abuse of governmental power. This case, so
clearly outrageous, was a natural.
</P>
<P>
   They sued. And they won.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago the city agreed to pay Marsh $1 million to settle
the suit.
</P>
<P>
   The money will not resurrect her ruined career in the Police
Department, or undo the hurt, the sadness or the emotional
devastation that resulted from the cruel and unconscionable way she
was treated.
</P>
<P>
   But the white flag of a settlement was a signal, in some sense,
that what happened to Sandra Marsh was indefensible. That it was
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
