<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0387 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-KILLEEN-BOS &LR;      07-12 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-KILLEEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLEEN SURFACES AT N.Y. MARKETING FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last time Web maven Stephen Killeen was in the news he was
talking layoffs. Now he's telling a new dot-com story.
</P>
<P>
   The former chief of stock chat site RagingBull.com has been
named president at Marketing Services Group Inc., a New York
marketing company that, like his last employer, counts CMGI Inc. as
a big investor.
</P>
<P>
   At Marketing Services, 13-year-old publicly traded company,
Killeen will oversee acquisitions and the Internet side of the
business. The company counts among its clients Walt Disney Co.,
Citigroup, and most Broadway theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Said Marketing Services chief Jeremy Barbera, ``I'm a firm
believer that old-world marketing and new-world marketing are the
same thing. They just use different mediums.''
</P>
<P>
   Killeen, 38, always seems to land on his feet. He made his name
at the online trading company that's now DLJ Direct and then helped
Fidelity Investments get serious about online stock trading. It was
a stunner when he left the mutual fund giant two years ago, as the
dot-com craze was heating up and day trading became a national
hobby.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Killeen and his colleagues sold Raging Bull to
AltaVista for an undisclosed sum. Killeen was offered a big job at
AltaVista but declined, because his family didn't want to move to
California. So he took his options and stayed on for six months to
help with the transition.
</P>
<P>
   Then came April's market crash, when lots of Web companies got
more cost-conscious, including AltaVista and other CMGI companies.
In May, Killeen had to fire 50 people and scrap a fledgling news
operation he was trying to launch at Raging Bull.
</P>
<P>
   Killeen rejects any notion that the business is troubled,
however. ``Raging Bull is doing very well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under his watch, monthly unique page visits to the Raging Bull
site jumped to 350 million from 4 million and membership eclipsed
500,000. He said the company, which makes money on advertising and
partnerships, was profitable in March and April. Alan Alper, an
analyst with Gomez Advisors, said that as stock chat sites go,
Raging Bull is seen among the success stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the right name. They came out at the right time,''
Alper said. Raging Bull also brings half a million users to
AltaVista, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   As for Killeen's new gig, he's not exactly dealing in a hot
stock. Marketing Services' shares have plummeted 73 percent this
year, based in part on losses in its Internet unit, and now trade
below $5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
