<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0388 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-UNLICENSED-0713-COX     07-12 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNLICENSED-0713-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IMPROPERLY LICENSED DRIVERS INVOLVED IN MANY FATAL ACCIDENTS
 &HT;    By ROB O'DELL
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Up to one in five fatal car accidents involves an
improperly licensed driver, according to a study issued Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The study by the AAA Foundation for Traffic Safety found that 20
percent of all fatal car accidents involved drivers whose license
was invalid or nonexistent, or whose license status was unknown.
Many of the drivers of unknown status are believed to lack valid
licenses, foundation officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From 1993 to 1997, more than 42,000 people have been killed by
drivers who were suspended, unlicensed or unknown,'' said David
Willis, president of the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which was performed for the foundation by Dr. Lindsay
Griffin of the Texas Transportation Institute, examined five years
of car accident data from the U.S. Department of Transportation's
fatality analysis reporting system and identified each driver's
license status at the time of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers studied 278,078 drivers involved in 183,749
fatal crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Of these drivers, 3.7 percent were unlicensed, 7.4 had an
license that had been suspended, revoked or was otherwise invalid,
and 2.7 were of unknown license status. These drivers were involved
in 20 percent of the fatal crashes over the five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only were these people driving with suspended licenses,
but 28 percent of these people had their licenses suspended or
revoked three or more times in the three years prior to their
crashes,'' Griffin said. ``These are not just ordinary people who
forgot to renew their licenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin cited a University of Michigan study that found that 30
to 70 percent of drivers who had their license suspended or revoked
continued to drive afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like a revolving door,'' Griffin said. ``In the study,
drivers with invalid licenses were far more likely to have been
convicted of drunk driving, been involved in a hit and run, or have
had multiple suspensions prior to their crashes.''
</P>
<P>
   The incidence of driver operating with invalid licenses varied
widely from state to state. Maine had the lowest incidence of
drivers with invalid licenses who were involved in fatal crashes,
6.9 percent, while New Mexico had the highest, 23.9 percent, the
study said.
</P>
<P>
   Willis suggested several policies that would help prevent
drivers with suspended or revoked licenses from driving their cars.
</P>
<P>
   He said one approach is vehicle immobilization or impoundment
for drivers who have their licenses suspended. Another promising
solution is an electronic ``smart-card'' driver's license without
which a car cannot be started, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully the introduction of this study will alert people to
the huge scope of this problem, and start the ball rolling on a
solution,'' Willis said. ``Suspended and unlicensed drivers are a
menace to society, and they need to be prevented from driving.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   AAA Foundation for Traffic Safety, www.aaafoundation.org
</P>
<P>
   Rob O'Dell's e-mail address is rodell(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
