<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AirTran shows 51 percent increase in profits despite rise in
fuel costs
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - AirTran Airways' second-quarter profit rose 51 percent
from a year earlier despite an even sharper rise in fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran, Atlanta's second-largest carrier, posted a $22.6
million profit, or 33 cents a share, vs. a prior-year profit of $15
million, or 22 cents a share. The result surpassed analysts'
forecasts of 29 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran Chairman Joseph Leonard noted the quarterly profit was
the sixth in a row for AirTran, which had previously struggled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to see steady growth in both the business and
leisure markets,'' Leonard said. He said both ridership and
revenue-per-passenger are increasing. AirTran ridership jumped 13
percent in the quarter on a 5 percent rise in seat capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue was $160.8 million, up from $140 million from the second
quarter last year. Unit costs rose almost 4 percent, but the
increase was due to a 72 percent jump in the price of fuel, Leonard
said.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran plans to boost seat capacity 12 percent in the second
half of this year and 15 percent next year. It will do so mainly by
slowing the retirement of older DC-9s while taking delivery of new
Boeing 717s that are slightly larger.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the capacity growth will go to additional flights on
existing routes, but an undisclosed destination will be added this
fall, executives said.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts, Leonard conceded that the
strong second-quarter financial results were offset by service
problems associated with a restructured schedule at the carrier's
Atlanta hub.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran a very good airline up through April, and then with the
new schedule we really fell off the cliff,'' he said. ``It took us
about six weeks to figure out how to run the thing. But in July
we've run the best airline since I've been here.''
</P>
<P>
   AirTran recently replaced its top customer service executive and
added curbside check-in service to reduce logjams at ticket
counters.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier faces an April 2001 deadline to restructure about
$234 million in debt _ the top financial challenge facing the
company. President Robert Fornaro told analysts the carrier is ``in
active discussions with several lenders.''
</P>
<P>
   He also disclosed that AirTran is switching to the Amex stock
exchange because it did not meet Nasdaq financial requirements at
the end of last year. The airline unsuccessfully sought a waiver.
AirTran stock will trade on the Amex starting Friday, under the
symbol AAI.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
