<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0395 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-335&AMP;A     07-12 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-335&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN PARTY, OUSTED FROM POWER, TRIES TO QUELL INFIGHTING 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ After 10 days of chaotic infighting, the elder
statesmen of the recently defeated governing party agreed on a
formula aimed at maintaining internal discipline as its long
monopoly over Mexican power and wealth draws to a close.
</P>
<P>
   The Institutional Revolutionary Party, whose traditions were
based on submission to the whims of Mexico's successive presidents,
seemed suddenly to spin out of control last week after Mexicans
voted the party from power for the first time since its 1929
founding.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Labastida, the party's defeated presidential
candidate, went into seclusion, the party's top leader, Dulce Maria
Sauri, resigned her post, several hardliners shattered a taboo by
harshly criticizing President Ernesto Zedillo, and at least three
rival factions lunged for control.
</P>
<P>
   But late on Tuesday, leaders of the party, known as the PRI,
announced measures to restore some order, signaling that the
internal coup attempts had failed, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   After a six-hour meeting with Zedillo at the presidential
compound, the PRI's 21 state governors announced that they had
persuaded Sauri to remain in her post for a few months while the
party decides how to pick her replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Sauri's dozen top party aides, all of them appointed by
Labastida, were allowed to resign, however, and in their place, the
governors announced the creation of an advisory committee, composed
of the party's 15 or so living ex-presidents. The committee will
help mediate a discussion over how to nurse the PRI back to health
after its stunning defeat at the hands of Vicente Fox, the
president-elect who will take office on Dec. 1
</P>
<P>
   ``Several factions tried to seize control, and they all
failed,'' said Jose Antonio Crespo, a political scientist who
authored a 1999 book analyzing scenarios for the PRI's future.
``The governors have bought some time. Now the urgent task is to
decide on a way to pick a new leader with the legitimacy to guide
the party as it seeks new foundations.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some factions have suggested that the PRI's National Political
Council, a group whose current members were picked by Zedillo,
should select the party's new leader. Some are proposing to elect
the leader this fall in what would be the party's first national
convention since 1996. Others are calling for the new leader's
selection in nationwide, grassroots balloting, in which hundreds of
thousands of party members would be eligible to participate.
</P>
<P>
   The governors' meeting with Zedillo seemed to bring a temporary
truce to the infighting. Among the factions appearing to contend
for power was one allied with Interior Minister Diodoro and one led
by Roberto Madrazo Pintado, the governor of Tabasco state who came
in second to Labastida in the party's primary election last year.
</P>
<P>
   Party graybeards appear to have succeeded in imposing some
order, partly because of a dawning sense of the extraordinary
challenges ahead _ local elections are scheduled in three states
before the end of the year, the PRI must choose legislative leaders
for the new Congress that begins work on Sept. 1, and the party
must decide what posture to adopt toward the incoming president,
Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Some leaders are urging that the PRI should do everything
possible to hobble Fox, whose center-right party will control
neither the Chamber of Deputies nor the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to head the kind of government that delights an
opposition _ with limited powers _ extremely limited,'' Manuel
Bartlett, the former governor of Puebla, said last week. ``And we
PRI members have the power to impose those limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett has been among the most outspoken critics of Zedillo,
blaming him for Labastida's defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Zedillo has lost the capacity to lead,'' Bartlett
told PRI leaders at party headquarters the day after the July 2
vote. ``He should not lead our party for even one minute more!''
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett's comments stunned Mexico, since PRI leaders have
rarely criticized a sitting president. But in recent days Bartlett
has appeared to be a faction of one, and several of his colleagues
have spoken out in Zedillo's defense. For his part, the president
has urged cooperation with Fox's government, in the pursuit of
Mexican prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   That was the line Labastida adopted Tuesday night, when he
appeared in a television interview for the first time since the
balloting. Reflecting with considerable dignity on the lessons of
his defeat, Labastida wished Fox success. ``If his government does
well, our country will do well,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
