<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0396 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-UNDOING-RACISM0713-CO     07-12 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNDOING-RACISM0713-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Workshops aim to change racist attitudes
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No matter how good their hearts or how open their
minds, white people in this country can't help but be racist, says
veteran civil rights leader Rev. C.T. Vivian.
</P>
<P>
   Since the pilgrims arrived, they've been told black isn't
beautiful. It's what mothers told their children, preachers told
their flocks and schools told their students.
</P>
<P>
   That's the history of racism Vivian has taught in nationwide
workshops for The People's Institute for Survival and Beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the institute celebrates its 20th anniversary by opening
a community training school at its New Orleans headquarters. The
school's more intense classes will teach activists how race favors
whites in their communities.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 50,000 people already have attended institute workshops.
Vivian and others encourage social change by demonstrating, he
says, how white privilege has become as deeply rooted as a Southern
oak.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're black in America,'' Vivian said, ``you'll never know
what you might have been, what you might have done for yourself,
for your family, for your children, for your community or for your
nation. You will never know because of what you've been denied.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than two decades after the 1963 ``Bloody Sunday'' civil
rights march in Selma, Ala., Vivian carried the idea of teaching
activists what fuels racism.
</P>
<P>
   But the immediate battles of the 1960s put the idea on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't any time,'' said Vivian, an adviser to Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr. ``Who could be involved in that when we were on the
front line itself?''
</P>
<P>
   Vivian helped launch the institute in his Atlanta living room.
At the time, he was a board member for two groups that championed
civil rights. Their leaders approached Vivian with the idea of
teaching the history of racism.
</P>
<P>
   Under the institute's guidance, Greensboro, N.C., Duluth, Minn.,
Flint, Mich., and Seattle have started citywide anti-racism
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, the institute has trained nearly 2,000 employees
from the city's lead social service agency. They learn how to serve
everyone in a vast melting pot, stirred daily by the influx of
Pacific immigrants and refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racism can deny access by poor people,'' said Sili Savusa, a
city employee who monitors social service grants awarded to
Seattle's public schools. ``The thing that was so powerful was that
it talked about being accountable to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta hosts one of the institute's regional organizing
committees, which teach introductory anti-racism workshops.
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Nibs Stroupe, 53, pastor of the Oakhurst Presbyterian
Church in Decatur, has taken the workshop.
</P>
<P>
   A white native of rural Arkansas, Stroupe learned racism from
``the best person'' he knew _ his mother.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was just like generations of people in the Deep South
raised before and after him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're taught that white folks are supreme, and they're
taught that by people who are loved and trusted, so it's hard to
divorce yourself from those notions,'' Stroupe said. ``We were
taught that whites were on top and that blacks were a little bit
human _ but not human like us.''
</P>
<P>
   That helps explain, Stroupe said, why supporters of the
Confederate battle flag _ an emblem blacks say is a symbol of
oppression _ passionately confront those who deride the banner.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about their mamas and their daddies,'' he said.
South Carolina just lowered the flag from its Statehouse dome. In
Georgia, black legislators are working to remove the same Rebel
insignia from the state flag in the upcoming session of the General
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   For Stroupe, the institute's workshops were eye-opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It showed me that racism was a social construct and was not
fixed in biology,'' said Stroupe, 53. ``If it's not fixed in
biology, then it's not something unnatural'' to set aside ingrained
racism.
</P>
<P>
   During the colonization of America, European church leaders
viewed dark-skinned people as savages, said David Billings, one of
the Institute's chief trainers in New Orleans. Churches idealized
white Christians while they degraded ``heathens'' from far off dark
continents.
</P>
<P>
   In the 18th century, teachers later recognized as
anthropologists, began classifying the world's people by color,
Billings said. Again, they taught white was good, black was bad.
The color line stands today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Academicians would lay the foundation,'' said Billings, a
white minister for the United Methodist Church. ``Those who
constructed society would use this thesis, this world view, to say
why it's OK'' to hold down people of color.
</P>
<P>
   Later, racism was codified by government and today permeates
institutions. For instance, he says, Congress authorized a
preference for whites in previous Census counts, when Indians were
ignored and blacks counted only as three-fifths of a person.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racism in this country is about a power arrangement, a
systematic arrangement that institutionalizes preferences for those
of us who are called white,'' said David Billings, one of the
institute's chief trainers in New Orleans. ``Whites benefit from
the arrangement and blacks fight against it. What we try to do is
demystify all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
