<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0398 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELTA-BLACKS0713-COX     07-12 0337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-BLACKS0713-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black pilots group brings 30 teenagers to aviation camp at Delta
Air Lines
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Thirty Atlanta teenagers with an interest in aviation
will be on cloud nine next week.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization of Black Airline Pilots is hosting its third
Atlanta Aviation Career Education Camp. For the first time, this
year's camp is sponsored by Delta Air Lines and will be conducted
primarily at the carrier's headquarters near Hartsfield
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The weeklong camp, also conducted in other U.S. cities, is for
students ages 14 to 18 selected by OBAP. They must meet grade point
average requirements and submit essays about their aviation
interest.
</P>
<P>
   OBAP said the Delta sponsorship in Atlanta enables the group to
offer a more intensive camp with special events. The camp is free
to participants.
</P>
<P>
   The camp includes instruction in aviation history, aerodynamics,
meteorology and navigation, plus flight simulator sessions. This
year's Atlanta camp also includes an orientation flight on a Delta
757 to Washington, where the students will tour the National Air &AMP;
Space Museum.
</P>
<P>
   They will also have a chance during the week to talk to members
of the famed Tuskegee Airmen, a group of black fighter pilots
formed in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Mac Armstrong, executive vice president-operations at Delta,
said the airline views the camp as a worthy cause but also has a
practical motivation for the sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Statistics tell us that the need for aviation professionals,
especially pilots and maintenance technicians, will remain robust
for the next five to 10 years,'' he said. ``So supporting this
initiative makes good business sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The camps are one way OBAP seeks to boost the tiny percentage of
black pilots at U.S. airlines. A Delta spokeswoman said all
minorities account for about 3 percent of the carrier's 9,100
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
