r s BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-RANGERS-     07-12 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NO FLUKE RANGERS ARE LAST IN AL WEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a relative newcomer to the ranks of major-league-baseball
owner, Tom Hicks is experiencing, for the first time, the dark side
of the business.
</P>
<P>
   Turn out the lights, Tom. The season is over. Your $70
million-plus investment might make a good mushroom patch. Those
things do grow well in the cellar, right?
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Hicks has been remarkably supportive of the
engineers responsible for this train wreck, Mr. Doug Melvin and Mr.
Johnny Oates. Ask not if all this is their fault. It happened on
their watch. Therefore, the blame falls accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, says Hicks, will be fired after this season. OK, that's
more than fair. Nobody should be fired after back-to-back
divisional titles, which were followed by the current plunge off
the deep end.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, management lip service is being provided about the
Rangers doing a bounce back starting tonight, finishing strong in
the season's second half and making the playoffs for a third
consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   As long as it's only lip service, and nothing else, then that's
OK, too. But as general manager, Melvin knows better than to
attempt to salvage something that is not working. Compared to a
year ago at the All-Star break, the Rangers are just as bad
defensively, just as bad fundamentally, worse in run production,
about the same with a below-average pitching rotation, and in a
total reversal, the bullpen has spit the bit.
</P>
<P>
   Considering everything, it is rather remarkable that a 42-43
record is that ``good.'' A variety of warts were hidden last season
by stellar bullpen work and a club that could outscore many
shortcomings. The bullpen alone is the difference between being
nine games over .500 at the break last season, and one game under
this time. Maybe, however, it's all a blessing. A new urgency is
now prevalent for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Melvin needs to save his own butt, and Oates'.
Another season of this, and Hicks won't be benevolent.
</P>
<P>
   Starting tonight in Arizona, the Rangers open an 11-game road
trip against four clubs, all of them on the plus side of .500.
Nothing has been seen thus far to suggest the Rangers will return
to Arlington any better off than 8 1/2 games out of first place in
the American League West. If this trip doesn't go well, Melvin will
certainly be very public in setting up the July 31 trading deadline
deals that he hopes will benefit the 2001 cause.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland ... Loaiza ... Segui ... Oliver ... Pudge. All right,
I'm just kidding on that last name. But who does go, and for what
in return? As Melvin ponders all this, he also must confront some
drastically changing priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Entering this season, the Rangers' major obsession was how to
deal with Yankee-phobia. Getting by the Yankees in the first round
of the playoffs has consumed almost every off-season thought for
four consecutive years. But no more.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Melvin must first game plan for a suddenly potent
division. The rest of the AL West has not only caught up with the
Rangers, but passed them by.
</P>
<P>
   Poll his peers in both leagues, and I'd say Melvin would rank in
the top five of GMs most respected by other GMs. That expertise,
combined with Hicks' money entering the equation two years ago,
gave the Rangers a hammerlock on the rest of the division.
</P>
<P>
   But when Pat Gillick took over as GM at Seattle, Melvin had an
equal to work against. Billy Beane at Oakland can now be considered
right there with Melvin and Gillick. Beane has done wonders with a
chump-change payroll. And while the Angels were long considered a
team of underachieving malcontents, new GM Bill Stoneman and new
manager Mike Scioscia are changing that image.
</P>
<P>
   It's no accident the Rangers dropped to the cellar in the
division. The Rangers were simply the AL West's worst team in the
first half. And for the immediate future, those other three clubs
figure to get nothing but better, particularly with the youth in
Oakland and the deep and young pitching rotation in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   If timing is everything, the clock blew up on Melvin last
winter. Outside of Kenny Rogers, he didn't make one roster change
that helped the Rangers this season. Losing Aaron Sele to Seattle
was a double disaster. Not retaining Todd Zeile was a hindsight
mistake. The Juan Gonzalez package is thus far empty.
</P>
<P>
   Not that any of us saw it coming, but the AL West quickly moved
forward as the Rangers backed up.
</P>
<P>
   Dig in, Doug. You've got plenty of catching up to do, and that
doesn't mean this season. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
