<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARRIAGE-PENALTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP PUSHES MARRIAGE-PENALTY BILL THROUGH HOUSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Knowing that a presidential veto looms, the
Republican-controlled House nevertheless passed legislation
Wednesday that would provide $182 billion over 10 years in tax
relief to dual-income couples hit by the so-called ``marriage
penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats, who largely opposed the legislation, accused
Republicans of being more interested in creating a presidential
campaign issue than in improving U.S. tax policy. But GOP sponsors
of the tax-repeal measure hailed its passage as a victory for the
institution of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican majority is so bent on making political
statements,'' said Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., who led the
unsuccessful Democratic opposition to the measure. He predicted
that the GOP-led Senate will pass the legislation quickly, making
the proposal a rallying point at the Republican national
convention, which begins July 31 in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they want to say in Philadelphia is that they passed the
bill and the president vetoed it,'' said Rangel, the chief Democrat
on the tax-writing House Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, dismissed the charge that his
party was playing politics, noting that 48 Democrats joined 221
Republicans in voting for passage.
</P>
<P>
   No Republicans opposed the legislation, which would repeal
tax-code provisions that force 25 million dual-income married
couples to pay more in federal income taxes than they would if they
were single.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is wrong to take money from the pockets of wage-earning
Americans just because they're married,'' said Archer, who chairs
the ways and means panel and sponsored the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The 269-159 vote marked the second time the House has approved
the legislation to repeal the marriage penalty. After the first
vote in February, the Senate's Democratic minority conducted a
successful filibuster, refusing to allow senators to vote on it.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the House GOP avoided that possibility by passing the
measure as part of budget-reconciliation legislation, which is not
subject to Senate filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to vote on the legislation this month and
send it to President Clinton's desk before the GOP convention. In
addition, senators this week are expected to pass and send to
Clinton legislation that would repeal the federal estate tax over
the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the two measures to the Democratic president before the
convention could make the proposed tax breaks major issues at the
event, where Republicans are expected to nominate Texas Gov. George
W. Bush as their presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has threatened to veto the Republican-backed repeal of
the marriage penalty unless it also contains the $250 billion in
Medicare prescription drug coverage he seeks for seniors during the
next 10 years. The president also has said he would veto the
proposed estate-tax repeal, saying the GOP measure would largely
benefit only the wealthiest 2 percent of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In a last-ditch effort to stop the vote on the marriage-penalty
repeal, House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., failed to
persuade Republicans to attach Clinton's prescription drug proposal
to their legislation, saying that such a step would garner the
president's signature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's work together,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   During the spirited House debate on the proposed Marriage Tax
Penalty Relief Act, Democrats roundly accused the GOP of playing
pre-convention politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to go to Philadelphia (and) say, `Look at what the
Democrats won't let us do,'' said Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Added Rep. Sander Levin, D-Mich.: ``Philadelphia is what's on
their mind.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans were just as vocal in charging the Democrats
with ignoring the legitimate financial concerns of married couples
stung by the higher tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington needs to stop penalizing the cornerstone of
American society,'' said Rep. Sam Johnson, R-Texas. ``Mr.
President, the time has come to sign this legislation and, for
once, to put American families first.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mac Collins, R-Ga., added that Democrats view marriage as
``an excuse to raise more revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The House-passed measure would increase the standard deduction
for married couples to twice the deduction allowed for singles. For
tax year 2000 that would mean rasing the standard deduction from
$7,350 to $8,800, an increase of nearly 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats pointed out that more than half of the tax breaks in
the GOP bill would go to families that don't suffer from the
marriage penalty. Families living on one income already enjoy a tax
break and would receive an additional tax cut under the proposal,
the Democrats said.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Rangel, the Democrats supported a smaller, 10-year, $95
billion plan. But the House rejected that proposal 228-198.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
