<HEADER>
A0404 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBA-SECONDHALF-HNS &LR;      07-12 1389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SECONDHALF-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Despite struggles, Yankees primed for second half
<TEXT>
<P>
   By RICHARD JUSTICE
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Just when the New York Yankees seemed on the verge of coming
undone, they got Roger Clemens and Orlando Hernandez back from
injuries, acquired David Justice from the Cleveland Indians and got
a surprisingly decent performance from Dwight Gooden.
</P>
<P>
   And after their first losing month in three years and a brief
stay in third place, they won seven of their final nine games
before the All-Star break and will begin the symbolic second half
of the season tonight atop the American League East standings.
</P>
<P>
   If all of that weren't enough, they also ended a long search for
a starting pitcher Wednesday by acquiring steady lefthander Denny
Neagle from the Cincinnati Reds for four prospects. Neagle has had
a tremendous first half and entered the All-Star break with three
straight victories and an 8-2 record. He has pitched at least seven
innings in seven of his last nine starts and will team with
Clemens, Hernandez and Andy Pettitte to give the Yankees arguably
the American League's best starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   So meet the new boss _ same as the old boss. That the Yankees
are only percentage points ahead of the Toronto Blue Jays and have
looked extremely vulnerable during the first 3{ months of the
season may not matter. Because they know how to win and because
their clubhouse is the industry standard for professionalism and
work ethic, the Yankees were already the team every other was going
to be watching over these final 2{ months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think because of what they've done in the past, you have to
respect them,'' Chicago White Sox first baseman Paul Konerko said.
``No one is going to overlook them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the White Sox have won more games and the Seattle
Mariners have looked like a better all-around team, the Yankees
still have Bernie Williams and Derek Jeter, they still have the
most reliable closer on earth in Mariano Rivera, and they still
have a manager who remains the unflappable calm in a storm
constantly swirling with tabloid headlines and combustible owner
George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   Not that they haven't had serious problems. Yet because of those
problems, it's an even greater tribute to their resilience that
they're in first place.
</P>
<P>
   Until Justice arrived, the Yankees had gotten little offense out
of their left fielders. Their third baseman, 1998 World Series MVP
Scott Brosius, is hitting .251. First baseman Tino Martinez (.261,
eight home runs) seems a shadow of the player he was. And there has
been a revolving door of designated hitters since Darryl
Strawberry's drug-related suspension and Chili Davis' retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the pitching, which has been the best in the game
over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees knew they were dealing with a house of cards when
they based their hopes on Hernandez and a pair of 37-year-old
starters _ Clemens and David Cone. Cone has been sent to the
bullpen after winning one of 16 starts. He hasn't lost much
velocity, but some of his command _ that is, the ability to change
speeds and arm angles and to work every corner of the strike zone _
is gone.
</P>
<P>
   As for Clemens (6-6, 4.33 ERA), he had two of his best
performances of the season upon leaving the disabled list 11 days
ago. Before that, he turned in just seven quality starts (six-plus
innings, three earned runs or fewer) in 14 turns. Even with the
acquisition of Neagle, a lot of the Yankees' hopes will depend on
Clemens staying healthy and pitching well.
</P>
<P>
   Everything else seems to be falling into place. Hernandez (8-6,
4.22) appears healthy, and Pettitte (9-5, 4.38) has had a solid
first half. The bullpen remains spectacularly reliable, and Rivera
is as close to a sure thing as the game has.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to put some wins together and not be surprised to win
three or four in a row,'' manager Joe Torre said. ``We have to get
on a roll and get that confidence going.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were tested at times last season as well. They
didn't take over first place for good until June 22, and the Red
Sox were within three games as late as Sept. 21. But New York held
on and then sailed through the postseason by winning 11 of 12.
Having gotten well before the break, they have a chance to take
command of the American League East while opening up the second
half with 21 straight games against losing teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it's our time to step up,'' Pettitte said. ``Starting
pitching's been the strength of this team for the last three, four
years, and we're the guys they count on.''
</P>
<P>
   This time it has been different. Even as the Yankees toyed with
the idea of trading for Sammy Sosa or Juan Gonzalez and worked on
the deal that brought Neagle, Torre has made more moves than in his
previous four years combined.
</P>
<P>
   He sent Cone, one of the most respected Yankees, to the bullpen.
He dropped Martinez in the batting order. He used Chuck Knoblauch
as a designated hitter when his throwing problems at second base
worsened. And he spent most of the season searching for pitching,
even using guys named Jake Westbrook and Ben Ford in important
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can talk about our position-by-position guys,'' Torre said,
``but if we can't throw a starter out there every day to give us a
chance to win, it negates all that other stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays may not stay in the race unless they acquire
another starting pitcher. But for now, they've ridden David Wells
(15-2, 3.44 ERA) and Carlos Delgado (80 RBIs) into first place.
Wells leads the majors in victories, and only Mark McGwire has more
home runs than Delgado's 28.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are a patchwork of reclamation projects and young
players. If Pedro Martinez (9-3, 1.44 ERA), who has been on the
disabled list, stays healthy down the stretch, Boston probably will
stay close even if it doesn't have enough to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   As for the American League's other divisions, the White Sox have
a 10-game lead over injury-decimated Cleveland in the Central and
have given no indication of slowing down. They play with energy and
a youthful enthusiasm that has made them perhaps the most
entertaining team in the game.
</P>
<P>
   They've got thunder throughout their lineup. Frank Thomas (.333,
26 home runs, 75 RBIs) and Magglio Ordonez (.330, 21, 74) are
terrorizing pitchers, and Carlos Lee, who almost always has hit in
the bottom third, has 59 RBIs. The Chisox also are deep, allowing
manager Jerry Manuel to rest everyone. Keith Foulke (18 saves) is
the best closer you never heard of, and they are loaded with hard
throwers in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're looking for reasons the White Sox will not fold,
look at a starting rotation that leads the American League with 41
victories. James Baldwin and Cal Eldred, who had 14 wins combined
last season, have 21.
</P>
<P>
   Eldred, who once led the American League in innings pitched
before undergoing Tommy John surgery, is 10-2 with a power fastball
and a first-rate curve. Baldwin is 11-4, and Jim Parque and Mike
Sirotka have eight wins apiece.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, Seattle has a three-game lead over Oakland and
perhaps the deepest rotation in the American League. The Mariners
have enough starters that general manager Pat Gillick may trade one
to acquire the lefthanded bat he desperately needs.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have their starting rotation intact for the first
time since mid-April. Freddy Garcia, a 17-game winner last year,
came off the DL on Saturday. Kazuhiro Sasaki, Jose Paniagua, Jose
Mesa and Arthur Rhodes are at the heart of an outstanding bullpen.
That bullpen is good enough that Lou Piniella is one of only two
managers who hasn't allowed a starter to throw 120 pitches in a
game this season (Montreal's Felipe Alou is the other). The
Mariners will have a nervous few days until shortstop Alex
Rodriguez and his aching right knee return to the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   No team has better pitching at the front of the rotation than
Oakland. Tim Hudson (10-2) and Mark Mulder (5-4) are two of the top
young starters in the game, and 1999 No. 1 pick Barry Zito may be a
telephone call away from the majors.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners and White Sox look good enough to win a World
Series, and a postseason matchup with the Yankees would make for
marvelous October theater.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
