<HEADER>
A0405 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AMEDIA-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-12 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMEDIA-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN-AMERICAN MEDIA COMPANY BRANCHES OUT ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE LEVERE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A print media company specializing in the Asian-American market
is branching out online to broaden its audience and advertising
potential.
</P>
<P>
   Privately held aMedia, publisher of the bimonthly aMagazine,
introduced a new Web site, aOnline.com, in June. The site is part
of aMedia's long-term strategy to develop a multimedia empire that
includes production and distribution of online video, film and
music.
</P>
<P>
   Like the magazine, aOnline.com caters to the English-speaking
Asian-American market, which research shows is younger, better
educated, and more affluent and technology-oriented than many other
ethnic groups in the United States. These qualities make
Asian-Americans desirable to marketers, even though they constitute
only 4 percent of the nation's total population.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report by Forrester Research, based in Cambridge,
Mass., found that Asian-Americans ranked higher than white
Americans, African-Americans and Hispanic Americans in both income
and education: Asian-Americans had a median annual household income
of $65,000, and 60 percent of them were college educated. More than
three-fourths were technologically inclined, also the highest
rating of the four groups, while their median age was 36, the
youngest of the four groups.
</P>
<P>
   AMedia, which has published aMagazine for 11 years, opted to go
online because ``there were limitations inherent in the print
product,'' said Jeff Yang, founder and chief executive. ``To create
a mass medium for Asian-Americans, you have to go where they are.
Seventy percent of them, 7.5 million, are online.''
</P>
<P>
   Yang said aMagazine had a circulation of 180,000, with
advertising sales of $1.1 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to leverage the resources we have off-line, and
address the frailties of traditional media,'' he added. ``The
Internet allows interaction and feedback, flexibility and
customization for advertisers, and constant contact with our
readers.''
</P>
<P>
   AOnline contains original editorial content as well as articles
from aMagazine, various chat rooms for visitors of different ages,
and an electronic calendar. Online chats are also being held with
Asian-American celebrities like Deepak Chopra.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, aOnline is developing a network of other sites of
Asian-American student, civic, service and professional groups
that, like aOnline, will be sold to advertisers; the Asian-Pacific
American Medical Student Association, for example, is already part
of it. AMedia, which has Web design and development capabilities,
will help these groups build their sites, if needed, either at a
reduced price or free, depending on their finances.
</P>
<P>
   According to Yang, aMedia's next step will be to add streaming
audio and video to aOnline, thus creating a multimedia,
multichannel menu of options for marketers. He also eventually
plans to add an e-commerce component, to sell books, music, videos,
food and other items, and to expand overseas.
</P>
<P>
   So far, three advertisers are buying space on aOnline _ Verio, a
provider of Internet and Web site operating services; Ford Motor, a
longtime supporter of aMagazine; and the Army. The Army began
advertising in aMagazine last spring and is running banner ads on
aOnline to recruit for its active and reserve units.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Nicholls, a corporate advertising executive for Ford,
said her company was working with aMedia's magazine and Web site
because ``the Asian market is so diverse in and of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Asian-Americans are a fast-growing community, an affluent
community, and aMagazine does a good job of reaching them,'' she
said. ``I look at the Internet as added value.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford is spending $110,000 this year on advertising in both
aMagazine and aOnline, a slight increase over previous
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   Ekaterina O. Walsh, an analyst with Forrester Research,
generally praised aMedia's online business strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're on the right track when it comes to targeting
Asian-Americans online, because they're significantly more likely
to be there,'' she said. ``Between Asian-Americans' significantly
higher income and the fact that they're much younger, they'll also
be an attractive target to advertisers. They're also more open to
novelty, which will make them a good launch pad to test new
products.''
</P>
<P>
   Len Fong, director of cross-cultural marketing for e21corp, a
Fremont, Calif., marketing communications firm, said that although
aMedia faced competition from older Asian-American sites like
Click2Asia.com, it has ``10 years of history behind it. They've got
good connections and know the Asian-American marketplace fairly
well. Their chances of success are pretty high.''
</P>
<P>
   For aOnline to make the most of its advertising potential, Walsh
said, it should create specialized Web sites on individual subjects
like music or finance, perhaps joining forces with financial
institutions like Charles Schwab or Fidelity, rather than develop
as a general-interest portal for Asian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The era of the broad-based portal is coming to an end,'' she
said. ``Forrester expects that only three will remain by 2004.
Niche sites hold the best chance of survival, and this trend
applies to ethnic sites, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Eliot Kang, president and chief executive of Kang &AMP; Lee
Advertising in New York, a unit of Young &AMP; Rubicam that specializes
in the Asian-American market, warned that aMedia faced tough
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do one thing really well in the general market, you can
do really well,'' said Yang, who is also president of the
Association of Asian-American Advertising Agencies. ``But in the
Asian market, you've got to do everything well. AMedia's got to be
eBay and Amazon.com and Priceline.com and CNBC in the aggregate to
provide enough income and revenue and be a stable business. There's
not much room to make mistakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
