<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP BILLS TO CUT TAXES FACING VOTES IN SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)   By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans in Congress moved closer Wednesday to
passing their two main tax-cutting bills, with the House finishing
work on a previously passed tax reduction for married couples and
the Democrats and Republicans agreeing to a vote in the Senate this
week on a plan to repeal the federal estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 269-159, the House sent to the Senate a bill that
would cut taxes on married couples by $182 billion over the next 10
years. The bill passed the House by a similar margin in February,
but it was repackaged slightly by Republicans on Wednesday so that
it could be considered by the Senate under rules that would keep
Democrats from stalling the bill or loading it with amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the Republican leader in the Senate, Trent Lott of
Mississippi, said he intended to bring to the floor on Friday a
version of the bill that would cut taxes on couples by $248 billion
over 10 years. The legislation is likely to win support from all 55
Republicans and perhaps a few Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has made it clear that President Clinton will
veto the tax cut for couples, saying that the Republican plan costs
too much, is skewed to upper income brackets and should be
considered only after Congress and the administration have agreed
on a plan to add prescription drug coverage to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have packaged the legislation as a repeal of the
marriage penalty, the quirk in the tax code that leads some
two-income couples to pay a higher tax bill than they would if they
had remained single. But the bill would provide a tax cut to nearly
all couples, including those who receive a marriage bonus _ that
is, they pay a lower tax bill as a couple than they would if they
had remained single.
</P>
<P>
   Lott also negotiated an agreement Wednesday with his Democratic
counterpart, Tom Daschle of South Dakota, to bring the proposed
estate tax repeal to a vote in the Senate. The agreement permits
Democrats to offer amendments that would allow them to make their
point that full repeal of the estate tax would primarily benefit a
few very wealthy people each year. The Democrats also contend that
there are ways of reducing the tax while leaving money to address
other pressing issues that affect far more voters, like health
care, child care and college costs.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment to the estate tax bill that is likely to get the
most attention will be offered by a Republican, Sen. Spencer
Abraham of Michigan. It will call for suspension of all or nearly
all of the 18.4 cents-a-gallon federal gasoline tax for 150 days.
High gas prices have become a political issue this year, especially
in the Midwest, and Abraham is in a tight re-election race.
</P>
</TEXT>
