<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0408 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MINORITIES0713-COX     07-12 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITIES0713-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Report suggests tech training for minorities
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Because of the large pockets of female,
African-American and Spanish-speaking workers being bypassed by the
boom in technology job opportunities, the country faces critical
talent shortages that could weaken its economic power.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid a crisis that could harm scientific progress and blunt
the nation's competitive edge in the world economy, the country
must do a better job in attracting, preparing and retaining
minorities in technology industries heading into the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   These were key elements in a report released today by a federal
commission that has been studying the problem over the last year
and is now sounding a national call to arms to improve science and
math teaching.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based panel _ the Commission on the Advancement
of Women and Minorities in Science, Engineering, and Technology
Development _ was created by a bipartisan duo, Rep. Connie Morello
(R-Md.) and Rep. Zoe Lofgren (D-Calif.).
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation's economic prosperity is due, in large part, to the
significant growth in science, engineering and technology
industries,'' said Elaine Mendoza, commission chairman and
president of Conceptual MindWorks Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``As these industries, which already face worker shortages,
continue to expand, we will lose our global competitive edge if we
do not expand the talent pool accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   The thrust of the commission's findings is that the demographics
(population projections) of the next 20 years show a growing
percentage of the young population pool being comprised of
African-Americans, Latins and others, as well as women.
</P>
<P>
   If these groups, which have so far largely failed to be drawn
into careers in science and technology, continue to lag in
participation, the nation's companies developing high-tech products
and services will be severely short-handed.
</P>
<P>
   In order to head off that prospect, the commission recommends
strong steps to focus better teaching on minorities, women and _
another underrepresented group _ disabled people.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically the commission called for the following:
</P>
<P>
   Higher standards of math and science teaching and curriculum,
which would boost the number of students in science and technology
from all sources.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing improved teaching on minorities and women, where
achievement has lagged.
</P>
<P>
   Identifying minorities and women in community colleges, and
cultivating them in greater numbers to move on to four-year
colleges in science and technology.
</P>
<P>
   Calling on states and federal agencies to focus student aid,
including larger Pell Grants to a maximum of $6,418, to support
minorities in science and technology education.
</P>
<P>
   With regard to improving science and math teaching, the
commission said it looks for specific ideas and strategies to be
contained in a report by another commission, the Glenn Commission,
by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   On a more general level, the commission endorses a campaign to
get industry support for diversity programs, and also to wage media
campaigns to improve the attractiveness of science and technology
careers.
</P>
<P>
   In its report, the commission said surveys of companies toward
the end of the millennium disclosed the industry leaders pointed to
shortages in skills as the main barrier to growth.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that chief executives conclude that ``unless
U.S. firms can create home-grown technicians by increasing adult
training opportunities and by expanding college graduates in
computer and engineering programs, (companies) will move their
operations abroad or import talent from overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, industries are clamoring this summer for quick
passage of congressional legislation to expand the supply of visas
to allow more overseas technology talent to work in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The commission clearly placed the burden of improving science
and math teaching on states and localities, a major point of
emphasis in Georgia under Gov. Roy Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
