<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gather round at ice cream social and watch your cares melt away
 &HT;    By Sabine Morrow
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's little that brings immediate relief from summer's
oppressive heat and humidity quicker than America's favorite
dessert: ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   July is National Ice Cream Month _ the perfect time to share the
joys of this frozen treat with friends and family by putting
together an informal ice cream social.
</P>
<P>
   With the emphasis on fun and ease, this gathering should be as
hassle-free as possible. That means don't worry about cranking your
own ice cream. Instead, stock up on a variety of favorite flavors
and don't forget toppings galore. Provide plenty of napkins and let
guests create their own frozen extravaganzas.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you decide on an intimate group or a large affair, use
your imagination when it comes to containers in which to serve all
that vanilla, chocolate and pistachio nut.
</P>
<P>
   During a shopping trip to Cost Plus World Market on Ashford
Dunwoody Road, we gleaned five great serving ideas to get your
started.
</P>
<P>
   MOST POPULAR
</P>
<P>
   The 15 most popular ice cream flavors, as of 1998 (latest
available), with their gallon share of the market.
</P>
<P>
   1. Vanilla, 29.2 percent
</P>
<P>
   2. Chocolate, 9.8 percent
</P>
<P>
   3. Neopolitan, 8.1 percent
</P>
<P>
   4. Butter pecan, 4.2 percent
</P>
<P>
   5. Cookies and cream, 3.6 percent
</P>
<P>
   6. Strawberry, 3.3 percent
</P>
<P>
   7. Chocolate chip, 3.1 percent
</P>
<P>
   8. Mint chocolate chip, 2.8 percent
</P>
<P>
   9. Vanilla/chocolate, 2.4 percent
</P>
<P>
   10. Cookie flavor _ excluding cookies and cream, 2.3 percent
</P>
<P>
   11. Cherry, 2.2 percent
</P>
<P>
   12. Coffee/mocha, 2.1 percent
</P>
<P>
   13. Fudge Marble, 2.0 percent
</P>
<P>
   14. Almond, 1.4 percent
</P>
<P>
   15 Crunch/toffee, 1.3 percent
</P>
<P>
   All others, 22.2 percent
</P>
<P>
   Source: International Ice Cream Association
</P>
<P>
   THE SCOOP ON SCOOPS
</P>
<P>
   Whether you call them dippers or scoops, their mission is the
same: to transfer all that cool goodness to a bowl or cone.
</P>
<P>
   According to AntiqueWeek, the first ice cream scoop was patented
in 1876 by William Clewell of Reading, Pa. It was cone-shaped and
made of tin and steel. It used a key on the top of the cone to
release the ice cream and required both hands to operate.
</P>
<P>
   In 1895 the first swing lever round bowl dipper was made, and
today we still use one much like it.
</P>
<P>
   When shopping for a scoop, make sure you handle them a bit and
see how they feel. Some are more comfortable than others.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid plastic scoops, because they aren't nearly as sturdy as
metal.
</P>
<P>
   To make perfect ice cream scoops every time, immerse the scoop
in water before each dip.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the most common ice cream scoops we found.
</P>
<P>
   _Sabine Morrow
</P>
<P>
   MAKING IT YOURSELF
</P>
<P>
   Those who remember the nostalgic joys of homemade ice cream have
nearly limitless options in ice cream makers today. Prices range
from $40 to $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   When shopping for an ice cream maker, decide whether you want a
manual or electric unit. Here are a few popular ice cream makers
that are easily found either through local retailers or Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  White Mountain Ice Cream Maker. This venerable name in ice
cream makers continues to stand for top-notch machines that produce
ultra-smooth ice cream and frozen yogurt in 20 minutes. The ice
cream maker has a bucket handcrafted of thick New England white
pine, plus non-corrodible cast-iron dashers and a three-gear drive.
It comes in electric and manual, 4- to 6-quart models. Prices range
from $150-$199. Available through Williams-Sonoma and through
www.appliances.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Donvier Ice Cream Maker. This little 1-quart ice cream maker
is so easy to use and yields high-quality frozen desserts in no
time flat without electricity, salt, ice or much effort on your
part. Just freeze the Chillfast cylinder, then place it in the
cylinder holder, add your ingredients, place the cover on top and
turn the crank every few minutes and in about 20 minutes you've got
ice cream, frozen yogurt or sorbet. $40-$50. Available through the
Web site www.cooking.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cuisinart Ice Cream Maker. Homemade ice cream, frozen yogurt
and sorbet in as little as 20 minutes. This quick and powerful
machine features a transparent easy-lock lid, a wide ingredient
spout and easy cord storage. Holds up to 1.5-quarts of frozen
dessert. $59.99. Available at Bed Bath &AMP; Beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Frozen desserts come in many forms, including ice cream, frozen
custard or French ice cream, sherbet, gelato, sorbet, water ice,
tofu-based frozen desserts, frozen novelties, frozen yogurt and
frozen pudding. Each of these has its own definition, and many are
standardized by federal regulations. Here's a basic primer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ice cream consists of a mixture of dairy ingredients such as
milk and nonfat milk and ingredients for sweetening and flavoring,
such as fruits, nuts and chocolate chips. Functional ingredients,
such as stabilizers and emulsifiers, are often included in the
product to promote proper texture. By federal law, ice cream must
contain at least 10 percent milkfat, before the addition of bulky
ingredients, and must weigh a minimum of 4.5 pounds to the gallon.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Frozen custard or French ice cream must also contain a minimum
of 10 percent milkfat, as well as at least 1.4 percent egg yolk
solids.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sherbets have a milkfat content between 1 percent and 2
percent and a slightly higher sweetener content than ice cream.
Sherbet weighs a minimum of 6 pounds to the gallon and is flavored
either with fruit or other characterizing ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gelato is characterized by an intense flavor and is served in
a semi-frozen state. Gelato contains sweeteners, milk, cream, egg
yolks and flavoring.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sorbet and water ices are similar to sherbets, but contain no
dairy ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Frozen yogurt consists of a mixture of dairy ingredients such
as milk and nonfat milk which have been cultured, as well as
ingredients for sweetening and flavoring.
</P>
<P>
   Source: International Dairy Foods Association
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.benjerry.com. This animated site offers everything you
might want to know about Ben &AMP; Jerry's and includes the Flavor
Graveyard (Sweet Potato Pie and Dastardly Mash Ice Cream are dead
and buried here) and free e-cards, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.users.nwark.com/(tilde)piperw/icpage
</P>
<P>
   .htmtrivia. If you want to know whether or not President Clinton
likes ice cream (he does) or what flavor Elvis preferred (chocolate
milkshakes were the King's faves), this ice cream trivia site is
worth a peek.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.cowtunes.com/history.html. Sure, this site has the history
of ice cream, but visit with the kids and listen to the list of
amusing Cow Tunes, including ``Twenty Eight Scoops of Ice Cream''
and ``Welcome to Bermooda.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.sendicecream.com. This site bills itself as the store for
ice cream makers. If you make your own or want to, everything you
need is here: scoops, ice cream makers, glassware, supplies, books
and recipes. There is a good summary of the origin of ice cream in
the history section. If you want to know the top 10 ice
cream-eating countries, take a look at Facts &AMP; Trivia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
