<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-ADS0713-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Agency pushes for ads in airplane interiors
 &HT;    By Renee DeGross
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Airline passengers would see advertising messages when
they reach for the overhead bins if an idea touted by a specialty
ad firm takes off.
</P>
<P>
   Advent AirAds has Federal Aviation Administration approval to
market placards that would be stuck on overhead bins. It hopes
airlines will jump on the idea as a way of raising revenue from
advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   But so far the firm, based near St. Louis, has signed up only
tiny Vanguard Airlines, which will have the placards in all 15 of
its planes by Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Atlanta's two biggest carriers, Delta and AirTran, buy
into the idea remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delta has recently completed a tasteful refurbishment of all
the aircraft interiors,'' spokesman John Kennedy said. ``Delta
would probably not be interested in an ad scheme of this nature.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It clutters up the airplane,'' said Tad Hutcheson, AirTran
marketing director. ``We have new 717s, and we're not ready to
clutter up the interiors just yet. But if Vanguard were to make so
much money and lower their fares, we may have to revisit the
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Advent has FAA approval to place ad placards on bins in Boeing
737s, the most widely flown airliner, and is seeking approval for
other models as well. FAA approval is required to ensure the ads
wouldn't distract from safety-related information.
</P>
<P>
   Advent founder Bill Apel, who rarely flies, said the idea came
to him during a trip a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I was looking at the luggage bins, I thought, 'What a nice
place to put some logo if it's done in a classy way,' `` Apel said.
``It doesn't take a brain surgeon to think up this ad concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Airline passengers are a captive audience. Atlanta-based Delta,
for instance, boards more than 110 million passengers annually.
Advent figures big carriers could make more than $10 million
selling space on bins.
</P>
<P>
   Buses and subways have long sold billboard space, sometimes with
gaudy, obtrusive messages. But the airline industry has allowed
only more subtle marketing, such as the Sky Mall magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Advent Marketing Director Marck De Lautour said the ads would be
``tastefully done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not obtrusive,'' he said. ``The misconception is that
they're like hot pink flamingo ads.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one airline, now-defunct Western Pacific, sold space on
aircraft exteriors, turning some planes into flying billboards. One
plane was festooned with characters from the comedy show ``The
Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   Delta has a deal with Turner Broadcasting to paint a 737 flown
by its Florida-based Delta Express unit in a ``Powerpuff Girls''
design based on the Cartoon Channel show. Kennedy said it is a
``one-plane'' promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
