<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS SUMMIT CONTINUES, ISRAEL SCRAPS ARMS SALE TO CHINA
 &HT;    With SUMMIT-PERSONAL-0713.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Hoping to plough fertile ground for the seeds of
peace, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak gave his word to President
Clinton that Israel would suspend a planned sale to China of a
sophisticated airborne radar system.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension set the stage Wednesday for day two of the Camp
David peace summit Clinton is hosting between Barak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters at day's end
that the parties took up substantive talks on the issues at the
heart of a half-century of Israeli-Palestinian conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been real engagement today,'' Lockhart said. ``It's
been a very busy day on that front.''
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with a policy of not discussing the daily heave-ho of
the summit, Lockhart provided no further details on negotiations
centered on the question of Palestinian statehood, the future of
Jerusalem, borders, Jewish settlers, territory, security and the
fate of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   He said, though, that it's been slow going so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have known all along that this was going to be a
struggle,'' Lockhart said, ``and it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton _ accompanied here by his daughter Chelsea _ met with
Barak in the morning, spent much of the afternoon conferring with
senior U.S. aides, and took a long stroll through the wooded
presidential compound with Arafat Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The president planned to spend the night Wednesday at Camp
David, and then turn the two sides over to Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright to manage Thursday, while he travels to
Baltimore to address the National Association for the Advancement
of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's announcement Wednesday that it would halt the sale of
sophisticated radar technology to mainland China was an indication
that the talks were headed in a positive direction, and that
Israel, at least was in a concessionary mode.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had repeatedly urged Barak to scrap the planned $250
million sale of the Israeli-built Phalcon airborne radar system,
out of concern that it could upset the strategic balance of power
between China and its regional neighbors, particularly the island
state of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   There was also bipartisan opposition to the sale in Congress.
Rep. Sonny Callahan, R-Ala., had proposed cutting U.S. military and
economic aid to Israel _ nearly $3 billion this year alone _ by the
value of the planned sale to China.
</P>
<P>
   After Barak's announcement, there's ``no need to do that,''
Callahan told reporters on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Similar to the U.S.-built AWACS system, the Phalcon allows an
airborne command center to monitor air traffic over an area
covering several hundred square miles, essential to coordinating
the operations of warplanes in a combat situation.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing has criticized the U.S. position as unwarranted
intervention in Chinese affairs.
</P>
<P>
   With some 80,000 troops based in South Korea and Japan, however,
and strategic interests across the region, the United States
regards the system as a potential threat to Pacific Rim stability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think it's in the region's interest to see that
technology introduced,'' said White House foreign policy spokesman
P.J. Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent to inform Chinese President Jiang Zemin of the
suspension, Barak cited this week's peace talks, saying the
U.S.-sponsored summit involves Israel's ``vital interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who told Clinton of the decision on Tuesday night, said
he was not cancelling the sale altogether, but rather placing it on
indefinite hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel will continue to look for ways to implement the deal,
in understanding with the United States, if circumstances will
change,'' Barak's spokesman, Gadi Baltiansky, told reporters
gathered in this town to cover the summit at Camp David five miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton had sought to have the sale scrubbed, Lockhart
said the administration welcomed the decision to suspend the sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been an important issue to us and a subject of
continuing discussion at a variety of levels of the government,''
Lockhart said. ``Israel has made a decision here, they took into
account our security concerns. We appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   He stressed, though, that U.S. objections to the sale are
permanent.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our point of view,'' he said, ``those security concerns,
and our overall concern for that system in the region, will not
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about reports in the Israeli press that the United States
had offered Israel compensation for the loss of the sale, Lockhart
replied, ``I'm not aware of any such promise.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans's E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
