</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS SUMMIT CONTINUES, ISRAEL SCRAPS ARMS SALE TO CHINA
 &HT;    With SUMMIT-PERSONAL-0713.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Hoping to plough fertile ground for the seeds of
peace, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak gave his word to President
Clinton that Israel would suspend a planned sale to China of a
sophisticated airborne radar system.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension set the stage Wednesday for day two of the Camp
David peace summit Clinton is hosting between Barak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters at day's end
that the parties took up substantive talks on the issues at the
heart of a half-century of Israeli-Palestinian conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been real engagement today,'' Lockhart said. ``It's
been a very busy day on that front.''
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with a policy of not discussing the daily heave-ho of
the summit, Lockhart provided no further details on negotiations
centered on the question of Palestinian statehood, the future of
Jerusalem, borders, Jewish settlers, territory, security and the
fate of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   He said, though, that it's been slow going so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have known all along that this was going to be a
struggle,'' Lockhart said, ``and it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton _ accompanied here by his daughter Chelsea _ met with
Barak in the morning, spent much of the afternoon conferring with
