</P>
<P>
   ``Israel will continue to look for ways to implement the deal,
in understanding with the United States, if circumstances will
change,'' Barak's spokesman, Gadi Baltiansky, told reporters
gathered in this town to cover the summit at Camp David five miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton had sought to have the sale scrubbed, Lockhart
said the administration welcomed the decision to suspend the sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been an important issue to us and a subject of
continuing discussion at a variety of levels of the government,''
Lockhart said. ``Israel has made a decision here, they took into
account our security concerns. We appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   He stressed, though, that U.S. objections to the sale are
permanent.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our point of view,'' he said, ``those security concerns,
and our overall concern for that system in the region, will not
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about reports in the Israeli press that the United States
had offered Israel compensation for the loss of the sale, Lockhart
replied, ``I'm not aware of any such promise.''
</P>
