<HEADER>
A0428 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-UBS-IMPACT-NYT &LR;      07-12 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UBS-IMPACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE MOVE, UBS EXECUTIVE IS UNDER THE GUN 
</HEADLINE>
  (With PAINEWEBBER-MARKETPLACE) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Marcel Ospel, the chief executive of UBS in
Zurich, built much of his career by buying American. But while his
$12 billion deal to acquire PaineWebber Inc. gives his huge Swiss
bank a big new position in the United States, Ospel is in many
respects a man under fire.
</P>
<P>
   UBS, formed through the merger in 1997 of Union Bank of
Switzerland and Swiss Bank Corp., has spent much of the last two
years struggling to find its focus and balance. Its previous chief
executive, Mathis Cabiallavata, resigned after UBS amassed huge
losses lending money to the ill-fated U.S. hedge fund, Long Term
Capital Management.
</P>
<P>
   Ospel, 50, the former head of Swiss Bank, took over with the
goals of sharply reducing the bank's exposure to risk and
refocusing on what seemed to be its essential strength as a Swiss
bank with global reach: managing money for wealthy individuals.
</P>
<P>
   But Swiss banking is under siege from global competition, as are
banks across Europe. Much of that competition is from Wall Street
investment banks, which have moved aggressively into the role of
advisers to top European corporations. Much of the pressure also
comes from the simple fact that the United States is the biggest
and probably fastest-growing market for affluent financial
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Although UBS is one of the world's biggest banks, with roughly
$1 trillion in assets under management, its vaunted private banking
business slumped badly last year. On Wednesday, UBS disclosed that
profits in its private banking area dropped 18 percent in the
second quarter of this year compared with the first quarter. In a
terse preliminary release of its second-quarter earnings, UBS noted
that ``preliminary indications are that net new money and asset
growth remain disappointing.'' That news comes three months after
Ospel ousted the previous head of private banking and announced a
broad restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Ospel has also been under tremendous pressure, from investors as
well as from some executives within UBS, to sell its investment
banking business, Warburg Dillon Read. That did not happen, despite
a flood of public speculation, but UBS did scale back on its
trading activities in the United States and many Warburg executives
defected to other firms.
</P>
<P>
   PaineWebber is supposed to solve these and other problems. Using
PaineWebber's network of 8,500 brokers, Ospel hopes to reach a huge
market of wealthy Americans, shore up his wobbly private banking
business and sharply increase UBS's total assets under management.
</P>
<P>
   UBS is paying a high price for PaineWebber, 47 percent above its
stock price before the deal was announced. To keep valuable
executives from fleeing, UBS has already designated $875 million
for incentive payments. And it predicts that restructuring costs
will amount to about $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts predict that PaineWebber will not do much to help
Warburg take on the likes of Goldman Sachs or Merrill Lynch in the
frenzied arena of advising on mergers and acquisitions and in
corporate finance. Though Warburg has a strong investment banking
business in Europe, it is a secondary player in the United States
and PaineWebber's primary strength is as a retail broker.
</P>
<P>
   But industry experts said UBS did not have many realistic
choices in the United States, and PaineWebber's strengths should
complement those of UBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a lot of sense strategically,'' said Madeleine
Hofmann, banking analyst at rival Credit Suisse First Boston in
Zurich. ``UBS Warburg has very good people in private banking and
investment banking, but in the U.S. they really did not have retail
distribution. The major point is to build the affluent client
segment abroad, outside Switzerland.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were more lukewarm. ``It is not the ideal acquisition,
but realistically it is a close to the ideal as you can get,'' said
Bryan Crossley, a banking analyst at ABN Amro. ``It doesn't really
get them to the top level, but to do that you would have had to
acquire somebody like Merrill Lynch, which is a different
proposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Ospel has considerable experience with American acquisitions. At
the former Swiss Bank Corp., he played a central role in 1995 in
acquiring SG Warburg, then a dreary spin-off from Morgan Stanley,
and in 1997 he acquired Dillon Read, then a boutique corporate
advisory firm. Swiss Bank also acquired two small but valuable
firms in Chicago. One was a derivatives firm called O'Connor
Associates, which gave Swiss Bank a solid base in what turned out
to be a profitable area of trading. The second was Brinson Asset
Management, a thriving money management firm headed by Gary
Brinson.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives say that Swiss Bank, smaller and scrappier
than the Union Bank of Switzerland, did a good job of melding the
firms together and letting non-Swiss executives continue to build
those businesses on their own.
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, Warburg Dillon Read might have sold for as
much as $18 billion if UBS had decided to sell it last year.
</P>
<P>
   Some of UBS's problems reflect the rocky integration of Swiss
Bank and Union Bank. Cabiallavata came from the bigger but stodgier
Union Bank, while Ospel came from Swiss Bank. Cabiallavata pushed
through a grueling cutback, closing redundant branches and pushing
out many executives.
</P>
<P>
   When Cabiallavata resigned, taking responsibility for the losses
incurred on making loans to Long Term Capital, the hedge fund in
Greenwich, Conn., that lost billions on a failed strategy for
hedging global securities, Ospel took over and the bank came
largely under the management of former Swiss Bank executives.
</P>
<P>
   UBS's performance improved considerably in 1999, as net income
doubled from 6.3 billion Swiss francs, or about $3.9 billion. Much
of that gain came from Warburg's investment banking business, which
boomed along with the general boom in financial markets. But
profits in private banking shrunk 39 percent and the bank's
asset-management business lost many big customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
