<HEADER>
A0434 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-NY-SLAVES-FONER-     07-12 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-NY-SLAVES-FONER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SLAVES OF NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Thursday, July 13, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a separate-buy' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By ERIC FONER    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Retrospective apologies can be a kind of psychopolitics that
makes the apologizer feel good without doing anything concrete
about the enduring consequences of past injustices. But the recent
apologies by two Connecticut companies, Aetna and The Hartford
Courant, have a singular virtue: They remind us of the usually
glossed-over participation of the North in America's slave system.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, many college and even some high school textbooks make clear
that slavery was embedded in every aspect of American life _ not
just Southern life _ from the early colonial era to the Civil War.
But museums and popular histories rarely give this fact the
prominence it deserves.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna and The Courant were apologizing for profits their
companies derived from insuring and advertising slaves in the 19th
century. But the economic participation of the North in the slave
trade and the use of slave labor went much deeper, even after
Northern states no longer allowed slaveholding within their own
borders.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere did the connection go deeper than in New York. How many
New Yorkers today know that when the South seceded, Mayor Fernando
Wood proposed that New York declare itself a free city, so as to be
able to continue to profit from slavery, as it had from its
beginnings?
</P>
<P>
   Slaves built New York _ and the rest of the country _ from their
earliest arrival here at the beginning of the 1600s. In 1750,
slaves represented more than 10 percent of the city's population;
and in 1712 and 1741, New York was the site of slave conspiracies.
Accounts of the city's rise to commercial prominence in the 19th
century rightly point to the Erie Canal's role in opening access to
produce from the West, but they don't talk about the equal
importance to the city's prosperity of its control over the South's
cotton trade. Because of this connection, New York merchants and
bankers were consistently pro-slavery, pressing during the 1840s
and 1850s for one concession to the South after another in order to
maintain their lucrative access to cotton.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the North, too, textile factories relied on
slave-grown cotton, shipping interests carried cotton to England,
and banks and merchants financed cotton production.
</P>
<P>
   Some cities in Europe have begun to make a public display of
their historical connection to slavery. In Liverpool, England's
biggest slave-trading port, local museums candidly depict the role
of slavery in the city's growth. Nantes, France, another city where
much wealth derived from the slave trade, recently had a similar
exhibition. New York should more candidly acknowledge that much of
its early prosperity rested on slave labor.
</P>
<P>
   I am not proposing that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani issue a
retrospective apology. Far more valuable would be long-term
projects to increase the city's historical self-consciousness. For
example, when New York's history is taught in public schools, the
city's intimate link with slavery should receive full attention.
The city should have a permanent exhibition _ perhaps even an
independent museum _ depicting the history of slavery and New
York's connection with it.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the Civil War, the economic value of slave
property was $3 billion in 1860 currency, more than the combined
value of all the factories, railroads and banks in the United
States. Much of the North's economic prosperity derived from what
Abraham Lincoln, in his second inaugural address, called ``the
bondman's two hundred and fifty years of unrequited toil.'' Lincoln
was asking Americans to consider the obligations created by
slavery. The first of those obligations is to acknowledge the full
truth.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Foner, professor of history at Columbia University, is the
author, most recently, of ``The Story of American Freedom.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
