<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL SAYS IT WILL CANCEL SALE OF AIRBORNE RADAR SYSTEM TO CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MIDEAST-MEDIA) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Israel announced on Wednesday that it had
canceled its sale of a sophisticated $250 million airborne radar
system to China, a decision timed for the second day of the Camp
David summit and designed to improve the mood in Congress where
heated opposition to the deal threatened aid to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The move was carefully calibrated by Israeli officials so that
they would be better poised to receive increased American military
assistance if some kind of peace accord is reached between the
Palestinians and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel informed President Clinton
of the decision on Tuesday night during a session between the two
leaders at Camp David, a spokesman for Barak said here.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli statement said that the deal, which had been underway
for five years, was canceled ``with consideration of the need for a
continued intimate relationship with the United States,
Administration and Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who said recently he had spoken more than once to Barak
about the administration's concern over Israel giving military help
to the Chinese, welcomed the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel has made a decision here, they took into account our
security concerns, we appreciate that,'' said Joe Lockhart, the
president's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The cancellation was unlikely to have any direct effect on the
workings of the summit, where talks continued in what was described
as an informal atmosphere of casual dress and informal gatherings
at mealtime between Israeli and Palestinian negotiators. But in an
attempt to not overdo the informality, Lockhart said that reaching
a positive outcome was still going to be a ``struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent his second day with Barak and the Palestinian
leader, Yasser Arafat, but was scheduled to take a break for a
speech on Thursday before the NAACP meeting in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli decision to cancel the Phalcon airborne radar system
had been brewing for weeks as pressure mounted from senior members
of Congress, including some considered sympathetic to Israel, who
publicly criticized it. The planned sale of military technology to
China was particularly irritating, they said, given the strong
military relationship between Israel and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's assurances that it was not providing American
technology to the Chinese did not mollify the criticism.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the cancellation, the Israelis avoided what could
have been an embarrassing debate on the floor of the House of
Representatives on Wednesday, where the chairman of the House
Appropriations Committee, Rep. Sonny Callahan, R-Ala., was
preparing to bring up an amendment holding back $250 million in
assistance to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan said he was glad that ``for the sake of United States
national security interests and, in fact, in the national security
interests of all our allies, such as Israel'' that the sale had
been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan had already brought his proposal to hold back the $250
million in aid before the Appropriations Committee where it failed.
The amendment was not likely to pass in the House either, but each
airing of the legislation provoked negative remarks against Israel
at a time when the Barak government is seeking more assistance.
</P>
<P>
   One of Barak's objectives at Camp David is for Israel to come
away with an upgraded military relationship with the United States
as compensation for risks associated with compromises with the
Palestinians. If a full peace accord is reached at Camp David,
Israel expects to get a significant boost in its defense
capabilities from the United States, including radar to detect
missiles from Iran and Iraq. This year's $2.8 billion aid package
to Israel includes $1.98 billion for military assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the Israeli government had tried to modify the
sale with the Chinese to calm the growing storm in Congress. Israel
has earned billions of dollars in arms sales to China in recent
years, according to arms experts, and was reluctant to cut off the
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter from Barak to the Chinese president, Jiang Zemin,
laying out the cancellation, the Israelis expressed the hope that
there might be room for future cooperation, an Israeli official
said on Wednesday. The letter was delivered on Monday in Beijing by
the director general of the Ministry of Defense, Amos Yaron.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon began to protest to the Israeli government late
last year after a subsidiary of Israel Aircraft Industries mounted
the radar system on a Russian-made cargo plane destined for the
Chinese air force. The subsidiary, known as Elta, designed the
system Phalcon for the Israeli air force. A Chinese-owned
Ilyushin-76 outfitted with the radar has been parked at Ben-Gurion
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration said it was most concerned because
the system significantly increased the capabilities of the Chinese
to conduct operations in and around the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Israeli argument that a closer relationship with the Chinese
military would allow Israel to dissuade Beijing from supplying
weaponry to Iran and Iran did not win many converts in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress on Wednesday, there was wide support for the
cancellation but still caution. ``This is not a note of victory,''
said Fred Downey, a legislative aide to Sen.r Joseph Lieberman,
D-Conn. ``It's the Israelis coming to the right decision so we can
discuss the upgraded security arrangement,'' that would come in the
wake of a successful summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
