BBN-DODNOTE (Los Angeles) _ Los Angeles Dodgers notebook. 
By Brian Dohn. (Will move on the ``s'' sports file.) 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0444 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-MEDIA-NYT &LR;      07-12 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TV SHOWS FAMILIARITY BETWEEN ISRAELI AND PALESTINIAN
OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MIDEAST-TALKS) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREDERICK, Md. _ To American television viewers, it was probably
unremarkable to see Avraham Burg, the Israeli Parliament speaker,
and Dr. Hanan Ashrawi, a Palestinian legislator, bantering, teasing
each other and debating peace issues on CNN's Crossfire on Tuesday
night. That's what guests with opposing points of view do on such
shows: they furiously argue in a stagey way that makes it
absolutely clear that they are sparring intellectually, not
personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me finish, Avrum!'' Ashrawi said, using her opponent's
nickname, as she light-heartedly chided Burg, who bowed his
yarmulke-covered head, apologized profusely and smilingly bit his
lip, in perfect debate-show mode.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Middle East, Israeli and Palestinian officials do not
do this.
</P>
<P>
   The issues, bone-deep and highly personal, do not lend
themselves and the forums do not exist. Palestinian officials do
not traipse onto Israeli television shows and play bang-bang,
kiss-kiss. They do not appear at all.
</P>
<P>
   Close bonds between Israeli and Palestinian officials have
developed since the first peace agreement was signed in 1993. But
these relationships transpire behind closed doors; official
Israeli-Palestinian camaraderie is rarely publicly spied.
</P>
<P>
   So it was an absolutely startling sight for Middle Easterners
and Middle East hands here to watch the exchange on Crossfire, and
a similar one between Ashrawi and Yuli Tamir, the Israeli
immigration minister, on PBS's ``The NewsHour With Jim Lehrer'' .
</P>
<P>
   In the course of covering the Camp David peace summit, American
television was unwittingly exposing a reality that ordinary
Israelis and Palestinians do not get to see: the real familiarity
that is the fruit of a seven-year conversation between elite strata
of the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   The shows somehow made the conflict seem so manageable, like it
was just a disagreement over, say, defense funding between American
politicians. It made it seem like it could, after all, be resolved
by talk, by human contact between people who do live right down the
road from each other. It made it seem easier than it really is, of
course, but it pointed up just what makes this peace summit at Camp
David different from previous negotiations: the Israelis and the
Palestinians, unlike the Israelis and the Syrians or the two sides
before 1993, now know each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, you saw a transition from what goes on behind the scenes
to national television,'' said David Makovsky, a senior fellow at
the Washington Institute for Near East Policy. ``On the one hand,
it's remarkable. On the other, it's not such a big leap. To me, it
illustrates the best hope for why a summit like this could succeed.
Because each side knows the other, and knows the parameters of the
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   A clear illustration of how far things have come in a decade is
the first attempt by the American news media to place Israelis and
Palestinians together on television. In the late 1980s, Ted Koppel,
the host of ABC's ``Nightline,'' went to Jerusalem and tried to
engineer a conversation between the two sides at the Jerusalem
Theater. He succeeded, but only after agreeing to erect a kind of
fence between them on the stage, so that as Ashrawi then insisted,
the occupier could be separated from the occupied and it would be
clear that the conversation was neither routine nor normal.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the fences have truly come down.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, to see myself and Hanan Ashrawi, at the same studio,''
Burg said, shaking his head. ``We've been in the crossfire at home,
literally speaking, a couple of years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Press, the host, tried to understand. ``A Palestinian
Crossfire?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Burg said, ``It was ...'' Ashrawi finished his sentence,
``... real live.'' Burg continued, ``It was real live crossfire in
Ramallah. Both of us at her place.''
</P>
<P>
   Burg, who is a religious Jew and a dove, went on, effectively,
to recognize the Palestinian state. ``If it walks like a duck and
it talks like a duck and it sounds like a duck, it's a Palestinian
state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Ashrawi interjected: ``A lame duck.''
</P>
<P>
   A gregarious, ambitious Labor Party politician who got his start
as an anti-war activist following the Israeli invasion of Lebanon,
Burg said he was explicitly trying to ``create a kind of covenant''
with Ashrawi, ``us against the extremists of both sides, not to
enable them to veto the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   The show conveniently ended before Ashrawi, a seasoned media
personality who can speak cogently and passionately about the
Palestinian cause at the drop of a microphone, had a chance to join
or reject the covenant. Since she has been expressing a very
nuanced critique of the peace effort in her role as Palestinian
spokeswoman this week, it would probably not have been easy for her
to embrace Burg's enthusiasm as wholly as he would have liked.
</P>
<P>
   In her appearance with Tamir, a political philosopher and a
long-time peace advocate, Ashrawi talked with great familiarity.
``It was like a reunion of two girlfriends,'' said Gadi Baltiansky,
Prime Minister Ehud Barak's spokesman. But the two women diverged
strongly in their outlook, and their ideological differences served
to underscore how unusual was their social ease with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Ashrawi talked about breaking down the psychological legacy of
the occupation that still colors the Israeli-Palestinian
relationship. She talked about how Israelis are approaching the
peace table in what she sees as a patronizing fashion, describing
themselves as ready to grant the Palestinians a generous deal,
``take it or leave it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a problem with this kind of mentality and I'm sorry,
Yuli, I know you very well and I have tremendous respect for you as
a friend and a woman,'' Ashrawi said.
</P>
<P>
   Tamir, in turn, said, ``I am surprised that Hanan _ if I may
call you Hanan, because we are good friends _ talks about
unilateral attempts to sort of impose a solution. We are here in a
summit talking together. I mean, Prime Minister Barak and Yasser
Arafat are sitting together and trying to find the most suitable
compromise for all of us in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Their ideological differences served to underscore the
effortlessness of their rapport. The dynamic, so newly displayed on
American television far from home, suggested both how far Israelis
and Palestinians have come and how far they have to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
