<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRECTION-LINDSAY-FELTON-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESENDING TO CORRECT ACTRESS' NAME 
SUDDEN FAME LEAVES NICKELODEON STAR GRATEFUL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lindsay Felton is an upbeat teen-ager who talks quickly and
easily about her acting career and her plans for college and
beyond, speaking in sentences of a dozen independent clauses strung
together and sprinkling the conversation with girlish laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Caitlin Seegar, the sullen, streetwise girl she
plays on Nickelodeon's landmark drama series, ``Caitlin's Way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's it to you?'' Caitlin probably would snarl at a
reporter's questions. ``And tell that guy to get his camera out of
my face!''
</P>
<P>
   Quite a difference between the 15-year-old actress and her role.
Since she broke into series television at age 8 as Ed Asner's
granddaughter and Haley Joel Osment's sister on the sitcom
``Thunder Alley,'' Felton has been told by directors and
photographers, ``Smile, Lindsay!'' or more often, ``Great smile,
Lindsay!''
</P>
<P>
   Now she's playing a troubled teen-ager, an orphan from the
foster care system of Philadelphia who, after one too many brushes
with the law, was ordered by a judge to choose between juvenile
hall and moving to Montana to live on a ranch with her mother's
long-lost cousin, Dori Lowe, and her family. She chose Montana,
seeing it as just barely the lesser of two evils.
</P>
<P>
   Caitlin is given to scowling and often confrontational, the kind
of kid who feels she probably isn't entitled to real happiness and,
if she senses it approaching, treats it with suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Felton, who lives in Burbank, says she's put a bit of herself
into the Caitlin character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come out sometimes more than others, but I think there is
more than people realize, because I have to invest a lot to play
the character,'' Felton said. ``In some ways I'd like to be a
little bit more like Caitlin, and in some ways I would like Caitlin
to be a little more like me. We're both kind of rebellious, but she
just takes it to the extreme, whereas I am a little bit more mellow
about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   An illustration: Beside Lindsay's bedroom doorway is a small
piece of paper posted at eye level that reads, ``Do one thing every
day that scares you.'' Lindsay probably finds inspiration in it but
does not always comply. Caitlin, on the other hand, doesn't need
!ital!that kind of encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   The job, if not the role, has Lindsay leading a double life
these days. From December through early June, she lives in Burbank
with her parents, two cats and a squawky bird, working on
home-schooling assignments and spending her free time in movie
theaters, in front of a computer or hanging with a close circle of
friends, most of them students at John Burroughs High School. She
swoons over the boy bands Hanson and the Moffatts, both of whom are
enshrined in her room amid a few stuffed animals, collectible
Barbies and books ranging from the gory thriller ``Hannibal'' to a
two-volume set of Shakespeare's plays.
</P>
<P>
   Then, by mid-June, she's off with her mother, Deborah Felton,
for a six- month stint in rugged, remote Alberta, Canada, where all
of the next season's 26 episodes are being shot. There she works
odd hours around the fickle weather to complete a half-hour episode
in four days' time, crams in three hours of schooling each weekday
with a tutor and, for amusement, passes time with her co-stars and
the crew.
</P>
<P>
   But you won't hear her complain about the lifestyle, not much
anyway. It's tiring and stressful, she admits, juggling the job and
schoolwork and being away from her Burbank friends for such a long
time. ``But the good definitely, definitely outweighs the bad, and
if it didn't, I wouldn't be doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Felton very nearly missed out on this role of her lifetime _ not
because she was the wrong type, nor because she was one of hundreds
of girls trying out for it.
</P>
<P>
   Series creator Tom Lynch, who also has made ``The Journey of
Allen Strange,'' ``The Secret World of Alex Mack'' and ``100 Deeds
for Eddie McDowd'' for Nickelodeon, says the lead character in this
pet project of his was meant to be a boy. The role still was
considered a male part just three days before the pilot was to
begin filming in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lindsay came in to read for the Griffen part,'' Lynch said,
referring to Dori and Jim Lowe's teen-ager, created as a girl but
ultimately cast with Santa Clarita resident Jeremy Foley. ``And I
said, `Give her the male lead (script), and she read it and she
nailed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said even with his proven track record with the top-rated
cable network, selling Nickelodeon on a series for 8- to
14-year-olds centered on a dark anti-hero was tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I wanted to do the first teen drama,'' Lynch said.
``And they said, 'Tommy, Tommy, do that funny stuff you do.' And I
said, 'It's important to me to do this show. I'm just coming to you
guys first.' So they said, 'Write the script,' and I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said there was a lot of discussion with Nickelodeon's
executives on keeping the show true to his concept yet suitable to
Nick's family- friendly mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue always was how dramatic we can make it, how far can
we take it without alienating the Nickelodeon audience,'' Lynch
said. ``And we were both willing to challenge the audience and push
it further. But there are things we won't do. For instance, Caitlin
will never have sex, because your 6-year-old daughter may be
watching and I can't handle that responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch, father of five kids ages 12-19, and the other ``Caitlin's
Way'' writers so far have succeeded in keeping the teen-agers'
dialogue and situations credible without straying into territory
that raises parents' eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Nickelodeon's done a good job of making a rebel that
anyone literally can watch and parents don't have to restrict their
child from watching,'' Felton said. ``(Language is) one thing that
Nickelodeon totally draws the line on. We couldn't say 'snot' in
one of the episodes. They really definitely are very clean in what
they write.''
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon's gamble with teen drama and Lynch's execution of it
have paid off. ``Caitlin's Way'' attracted 6.5 million viewers for
its premiere episode last March, a record for any Nickelodeon
premiere.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining new episodes from the first season air beginning
July 23. Lynch says he has ``Caitlin's Way'' mapped out for 100
episodes or four full seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few months after the premiere, the series has raised
Lindsay's profile a bit, to the point where she occasionally gets
recognized in public, if not exactly mobbed. It could be a good
springboard toward her aspirations of studying at Yale or New York
University's Tisch film school, scoring a role or two in good
independent films, and ultimately hitting a Broadway stage.
</P>
<P>
   Her acting coach, Andrew Magarian of The Shop in North
Hollywood, said, ``She's a good actress, and it's within who she
is. I like her potential a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch, reflecting on the happy, well-adjusted girl he found to
play the brooding one he created, sounds like a beaming father.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's just a major star,'' he said. ``It sounds like a cliche
in the business, but she can really hold the camera. I don't mind
writing a three- page scene for her because I know she can handle
it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
