<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-SCIENTIFIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON SCIENTIFIC PLANT RESTRUCTURING TO IDLE 1900 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston Scientific Corp., seeking to lower costs to keep pace
with competitors, will idle 1,900 employees across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Natick, Mass. maker of medical devices said the move, which
will close plants in Watertown, Mass., Plymouth, Minn., and
Redmond, Wash., will be offset by some new hiring. Boston
Scientific will add about 800 jobs at its two factories in Ireland
and another 100 at its production site in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   In total, the restructuring will result in the loss of 1,000
jobs, or about 7.7 percent of the company's work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get any pleasure from having to disrupt 1,900 people's
lives,'' said James Tobin, the Boston Scientific president and
chief executive. ``But I have to do this to preserve those (jobs)
that remain.''
</P>
<P>
   With unemployment low and the job market brisk, Tobin said he
thought the workers let go ``will find their next jobs pretty
easily in this environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Operating with two shifts and a small overnight crew in four
separate plants, Boston Scientific's Watertown work force makes
angioplasty products used by doctors to clear clogged arteries. The
company attracted a large international work force, many of them
unskilled and new arrivals. The majority worked with their hands to
assemble surgical devices such as balloon catheters, stents and
guidewires.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin, who joined the company in March 1999, said the
restructuring was being done to cut costs and make Boston
Scientific more competitive. He said the cost savings will be used
partly to expand the company's research and development.
</P>
<P>
   One site to be abandoned in Watertown _ once the Boston
Scientific headquarters _ will house a corporate research and
development center, Tobin said. The building will also be home to
the company's Medi-tech division, which develops vascular surgery
and radiology products. Both Medi-tech and the corporate research
center are now on the Natick campus, and 100 employees from these
operations will move to Watertown.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the new hires in Ireland and Miami, the company
said it would contract out some components to low-cost
manufacturers around the world. That subcontracting will enable
Boston Scientific to pare 800 jobs. The company will eliminate the
other 200 jobs by reducing product overlap.
</P>
<P>
   One example of overlap is in guidewires _ hair-thin strands that
steer catheters and stents through blood vessels to treatment
locations. They are now made in Watertown, Plymouth and Redmond,
but in the future will be made only at the company's Miami plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plan arises out of a thoughtful and thorough analysis of
the strategic needs of the company,'' said Peter Nicholas, Boston
Scientific co-founder and chairman. Nicholas recounted how the
company has made a series of acquisitions and boosted employment.
Now with plans to eliminate 1,000 jobs, the company will employ
12,000 instead of 13,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring moves will cost the company $45 million in
one-time charges, shaving 10 cents a share off this year's
earnings, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The moves will result in after-tax savings of $70 million next
year, $145 million in 2002 and $180 million in 2003, according to
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas and Tobin said some these savings will be invested in
research and development to prepare for future growth. Boston
Scientific has been criticized for not boosting its research
spending, which has been around $200 million annually for the past
three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line here is that a lot of people will be cheered
by these moves, and it is clear that Tobin has to increase R&AMP;D
spending which is another part of his mandate for change,'' said
Daniel T. Lemaitre, an analyst at Merrill Lynch Global Securites.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts said Boston Scientific's profit margins still
trail far behind its major competitors _ Medtronics Inc. of
Minneapolis and Guidant Inc. of Indianapolis _ particularly in the
high-margin market for surgical stents.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin acknowledged that Boston Scientific still will rely on
Medinol Ltd. of Tel Aviv, Israel, for its most sophisticated
medical stents. Buying and reselling those stents results in lower
profits than its rivals which build their own devices. That won't
change much with Wednesday's manufacturing restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tobin is doing a credible job at bringing in operational
expertise to Boston Scientific and addressing long-standing
problems of high inventories, inventory obsolescence and high scrap
rates,'' said Andrew Jay, director of medical technology analysis
at First Union Securities in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a company whose founders (Nicholas and John Abele)
were good at identifying market opportunities, developing new
products and being savvy in acquiring premier medical device
franchises. But as they expanded, they lacked operational
expertise. And that's where Tobin comes in.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors also hope Boston Scientific shares _ once a leader
among New England area stocks _ will regain their luster.
Wednesday's announcement boosted the shares $2.1875 to $26 on the
New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
