<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GOP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH RETALIATES AGAINST CAMPAIGN SLAMS BY GORE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Breaking his usual stride of positive
campaigning, Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush
responded Wednesday to goading from Al Gore by accusing the vice
president of declaring war on Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of reinventing government, Vice President Gore
continues to reinvent himself,'' Bush told a national gathering of
Republican and Bush for President leaders in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just this week he decided to attack the Congress, even though
he himself is president of the Senate,'' Bush said. ``He offered
more of the same, the same old sequel to a tired period of time,
four more years of a president at war with Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said if elected president he will be a leader who unites
Republicans and Democrats in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``America understands if you want to get something done, you
must elect a president who can unite, who is willing to work with
both Republicans and Democrats to get something done.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush rarely mentions Gore by name in his campaign speeches, and
his campaign has put together a national convention that will avoid
traditional attacks on the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush strayed from the game plan during his speech as he
responded to an attack Gore had launched this week against the
``do-nothing-for-the-people Republican Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore focused on an issue especially sensitive to Bush _ patient
protections. Gore said Bush needed ``to show us whose side he is
on'' and urged him to call congressional leaders to break a
deadlock on a national patients' bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   The governor didn't specifically address Gore's attack, but
patients' rights have been a tender subject with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   His 1998 Democratic gubernatorial campaign opponent ran
television commercials attacking Bush for his 1995 veto of a
patients' protection act supported by the Texas Medical
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Bush defended himself by noting that his state insurance agency
had implemented many of the protections in the 1995 legislation and
that those rules were adopted as state law in 1997. The 1997 law
allowed individuals to choose doctors within their insurance plan
but did not require insurance companies to provide freedom of
choice for doctors outside of a plan's coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Last year in his autobiography, A Charge to Keep, Bush dedicated
an entire chapter to defending the 1995 veto. And in February of
this year he ran television commercials that said, ``While
Washington politicians deadlocked, I delivered a patients' bill of
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spoke to his campaign leadership Wednesday as part of his
preparation for the national GOP convention that begins July 31 in
Philadelphia. He also met with former Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told the Republican leaders they should not grow complacent
because of his lead in public opinion polls. He said Gore and
President Clinton will do whatever they can to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm running against a tough campaigner. This is going to be a
hard, close campaign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is I'm leading some of the polls. The bad news
is the election isn't tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
