u p BC-GORE-NAACP-HNS &LR;      07-12 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NAACP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE WOWS NAACP WITH SPEECH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Saying ``talk is cheap, it is deeds that matter,''
Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore won resounding applause
from an NAACP audience when he said that unlike his Republican
rival, George W. Bush, he has long championed their causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not asking you to read my lips. I am asking you to read my
heart and watch my feet and watch the work of my hands when joined
with yours,`` Gore told leaders of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   The remark alluded to the famous ``read my lips _ no new taxes''
pledge that George W. Bush's father, former President Bush, made
and broke before he lost the White House to Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president never mentioned the Bush name, but filled his
speech with comments the crowd clearly recognized as references to
the Texas governor, who addressed the prominent national black
organization Monday. The previous GOP presidential nominee, Bob
Dole, skipped the NAACP convention.
</P>
<P>
   Gore suggested that Bush's speech did not make up for past
slights to the black community, including his visit to Bob Jones
University, a conservative Christian institution that has had
racially divisive policies, and his failure to condemn the flying
of the Confederate battle flag in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the vice president said, he has long supported
issues of importance to African-Americans, such as affirmative
action, empowerment zones, education and health care reform. He got
especially strong applause when he vowed to fight racial profiling
as a law enforcement tactic.
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned black Cabinet members in the Clinton
administration, some of whom attended the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a member of the NAACP. It's good to be home,'' Gore said.
``I have come here not just in an election year, but year after
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP plans to spend $8 million on voter registration and
education before the November election, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   While the organization is officially nonpartisan, Gore clearly
was the favorite of the vast majority attending the convention. His
38-minute speech, almost twice as long as Bush's, was greeted by
cheers and numerous standing ovations.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was far more restrained in its reaction to Bush's
speech, where he acknowledged that the Republican Party had not
always been sensitive to blacks' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights leader Julian Bond said that while the group
treated Bush respectfully, in the case of Gore ``it was an old
friend coming back home.''
</P>
<P>
   In introducing Gore, NAACP board member William Lucy alluded to
Bush's speech saying, ``Al Gore, unlike a lot of other people, has
not just discovered the NAACP. He has not just discovered the
problems of poor people, African-American people and people of
color.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucy noted that Clinton has nominated more than 50
African-Americans for federal judicial posts.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks have been among the Democrat party's most loyal
constituencies, a voting pattern that even Bush and his advisers
conceded is not likely to be altered by the Texas' governor's
appeals to black groups.
</P>
<P>
   Kweisi Mfume, NAACP president, said Bush's address to the group
was more of a ``tactical decision'' designed to appeal to moderates
in both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Mfume said Bush's vague speech, in which he avoided hot-button
issues such as the Confederate flag and affirmative action,
probably went over better with those swing voters than with blacks,
who were looking for more specifics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a chance to hit a home run and he hit a single,'' Mfume
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, speaking with reporters at the Texas Governor's Mansion,
indicated he was pleased with his NAACP appearance _ and with
Gore's attention to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked from my heart at the NAACP. I was honored to be
there,'' Bush said. ``He's talking about me, and I'm talking about
me, and that's the way I like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, often criticized as a lackluster and disjointed speaker,
appeared energized by the enthusiastic crowd, and gave one of his
most animated and passionate pitches of the campaign season.
</P>
<P>
   Without naming the governor, he repeatedly suggested Bush has
been insensitive to black concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``When James Byrd was dragged to his death behind a pickup
truck, the governor of his home state ought to at least heed his
family's pleas for action,'' said Gore. Bush declined to support
hate crimes legislation despite a request from the family of Byrd,
who was killed by three white men.
</P>
<P>
   He also alluded to Bush's refusal to condemn the flying of the
Confederate battle flag over the South Carolina Capitol. During the
GOP primary last winter, Bush said the flag matter was a state
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The true test is whether you are willing to take a stand when
the Confederate flag is flying over a state capitol and you see it
needs to come down but you are afraid to speak out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of members who heard both speeches suggested they
believe Gore did a better job of addressing their specific
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush made a very safe speech. He did not make any commitments.
It's like `I'm here just to show my face,''' said Shirley McGee of
St. Louis. ``Gore had a different connection with the people. His
connection was `I care about you.'''
</P>
<P>
   After the NAACP speech Gore visited a ``brownfield'' site, where
he complained that the Republican-controlled Congress was holding
up legislation designed to make it easier for governments to
convert abandoned industrial areas into economically viable
projects.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 2031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
