A0463 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-TRADE0713-     07-12 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-TRADE0713-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves, Ashby bank on change
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They hope they're getting the All-Star, the
right-hander who won 31 games the previous two seasons, the pitcher
who twice locked them up during the 1998 playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Atlanta Braves hope. The Philadelphia Phillies
assumed much of the same when they, too, traded for Andy Ashby
during the winter. It didn't happen the first 14 weeks of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby comes to the Braves after enduring the worst funk of his
career. He was hustled out of Philadelphia after feuding with fans
at Veterans Stadium and informing team management he had no
intention of remaining once his contract expired after September.
</P>
<P>
   He also conceded that the fans at the Vet might have been
tougher than he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough place to play,'' Ashby said last month. ``I'm
not going to deny that. It's a tough place to play, especially when
you're scuffling. . . . It's frustrating when you put everything on
the line and still get booed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashby, a National League All-Star in 1998 and 1999, went from
May 7 to July 3 with just one victory. His fastball, his most
reliable tool, which bores in on right-handed hitters, had
abandoned him. He was making more money, $5.9 million, than anyone
on the Phillies' roster, including ace Curt Schilling, but he
wasn't effective.
</P>
<P>
   The situation boiled over June 28, with scouts representing six
teams at the Vet. Pulled after allowing six runs in six innings,
Ashby began trading blue language with fans who jeered him from
behind the dugout. The Phillies had been fielding offers all month
for Ashby. That moment settled the problem. He could not remain
with that team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was mad. That's not the type of person I am,'' he has said.
``I shouldn't have said anything. But I got caught up in the
moment. I said a few choice words, the way (they were) yelling at
me. . . . I'm trying to get right, and it's not happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Braves like the same things the Phillies liked
when they traded away three pitchers _ Carlton Loewer, Steve
Montgomery and Adam Eaton _ on Nov. 10 to get him. Just last
season, Ashby led the Padres with four complete games and tied
Baltimore's Scott Erickson for most shutouts in the majors with
three.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby had just strung together the first three 200-inning
seasons of his career. He managed his pitch counts so that he
worked into the seventh inning 40 times in his last 64 starts in
San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are hoping a clean break from Philadelphia will allow
that pitcher to re-emerge. Ashby just won consecutive starts for
the first time this year, allowing three earned runs in his last 15
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
