<HEADLINE>
DECIDING LEFT IS BETTER THAN RIGHT, ARMSTRONG PICKS PATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Bruce Armstrong spoke to Cleveland coach
Chris Palmer Tuesday, but it was obvious that if he signed with the
Browns he would be their right tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong is a left tackle. A move to the right side would be
akin to a shortstop moving to first base. Some do it to extend
their careers, but for Armstrong, it was left tackle or nothing.
</P>
<P>
   So late Tuesday, Armstrong decided to sign a one-year contract
with the Patriots. And if he appears in 11 games, he'll have played
the most games in Patriots history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing for the Patriots was more meaningful to him than
anything else,'' said Armstrong's agent, Dr. John Geletka. ``This
shows you how much he wanted to play for the Patriots.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line makes the Patriots look like prudent
businessmen. They cut Armstrong in February when he was scheduled
to earn $3.5 million, a $1 million bonus that was payable by March
1 and his $2.5 million salary. The Patriots elected to cut
Armstrong and absorb a $1.1 million salary cap hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots saved more money Wednesday by restructuring Vincent
Brisby's contract. The wide receiver, who will be starting his
eighth campaign with the Patriots, had his salary reduced from $1.5
million to $750,000 _ but with incentives that could bring it up to
$2.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who played the final eight games with a torn left
anterior cruciate ligament, signed a $440,000 base salary with a
chance to earn about $1 million in playing time incentives. If he
should make the Pro Bowl, he will make another $750,000; if he
makes the Pro Bowl and leads the Patriots to a Super Bowl victory,
he could wind up with a contract of $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way Bruce is looking at it is he's made about $8 million
the past two years (from his former deal with the Patriots) and
that this way he accepts this and he's able to stay a Patriot,''
said Geletka. ``Hopefully, there's a future there for him beyond
this year. If there isn't, that's something else we'll have to
handle.''
</P>
<P>
   Having signed Armstrong, do the Patriots intend on giving him
his old job? After all, the team made other plans, having acquired
Grant Williams as a free agent from Seattle and toying with the
idea of Max Lane moving to that spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're going to do something like that, I don't think
Bruce would stand for that,'' said Geletka.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong is expected to arrive in Foxborough Thursday to
undergo a physical.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots Wednesday began their four-day rookie camp. The big
camp begins Monday, with all players needing to report Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots announced the signings of lineman Greg
Robinson-Randall (fourth round), defensive tackle Jeff Marriott
(fifth round; three years, $896,000), defensive tackle David Nugent
(sixth round; three years, $862,000), and linebacker Casey Tisdale
(seventh round; three years, $849,000). Wide receiver Patrick Pass
(seventh round) had already been locked up.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive lineman Adriam Klemm (second round), running back J.R.
Redmond (third round), tight end Dave Stachelski (fifth round),
defensive back Antwan Harris (sixth round), and quarterback Tom
Brady (sixth round) are still not in the fold.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond, Klemm, and Stachelski are all coming off surgeries.
Klemm will miss most of training camp with a lateral collateral
ligament tear in his right knee; Redmond, who is close to signing,
is returning from surgery to repair an inflammed tendon in his
groin; and Stachelski had minor knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Geletka said, in the end, the Patriots altered some of
Armstrong's incentives, but there was no dramatic difference in the
contract the Patriots offered more than a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots offered a $440,000 base salary and increments of
$140,000 based on Armstrong playing 60 percent, 70 percent, 80
percent, and 90 percent of the offensive plays. If he accomplishes
that, he will earn $1 million, provided the team improves in one of
nine offensive categories (including wins, sacks allowed,
touchdowns, and the percentage of passes completed).
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots added $1.5 million in incentives related to the Pro
Bowl: $750,000 for making it, another $250,000 for making it and
the Patriots winning the Eastern Division, $250,000 more for making
it and the Patriots making the Super Bowl, and another $250,000 for
making it and the team winning the Super Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
