<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-lopez </SLUG>
 column-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
With jobs at stake, Astros' second half counts
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are trudging onto the back nine with a fizzle and a
whimper.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, doesn't every hack making the turn believe a
turnaround is just a 300-yard drive away?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exactly like golf,'' Astros skipper Larry Dierker said of
the post-All-Star-break breath of life. ``You can play so horribly
that by the time you get to No. 9, you almost don't care. But once
you get to the 10th tee, you think, `All right, I'll par this one
and then really start playing.'''
</P>
<P>
   This is presuming Dierker and the Astros haven't already torn up
the scorecard and thrown it in the drink. The Astros' front nine,
after all, was a steady progression of yips, pull-hooks, slices,
snowmen and snapped clubs.
</P>
<P>
   But today in Detroit the Astros approach what Dierker called
``our No. 10 tee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goals have changed,'' he said. ``Sometime soon, I'd like
to sweep a series. I know that doesn't sound like much of a goal,
but if we want to start thinking about playing .500 ball, we have
to start somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the theme of the once-contending Astros. This team known
for shooting at the flags suddenly finds itself in a scramble. The
ultimate goal is finding players who can set a foundation for 2001
and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Except for veterans Craig Biggio, Jeff Bagwell and to a degree
Moises Alou (although Alou continues to be mentioned in trade
rumors), the Astros' infield, outfield and pitching staff all will
be playing an entirely new game in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   It's a game of who will stay, who will go and about whom the
Astros still do not know.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Ken Caminiti is the most prominent veteran who
falls into the who-knows category.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti, 37, is on the disabled list after undergoing surgery
to repair a tendon on his right wrist and may well have to call it
a career at the end of this season. But Cammy's greatest qualities
always have been his toughness and a love for the game that never
seems to fade. Who knows?
</P>
<P>
   As for the who-will-stay part of the equation, no players have
done more to establish themselves than outfielder Lance Berkman and
catcher Mitch Meluskey.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no more doubt that Berkman belongs in this league,''
Dierker said. ``Mitch is right there, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But Berkman's progression in the second half should have a
definite effect on Daryle Ward's Astros career and, to a lesser
degree, Roger Cedeno's and Alou's. With Richard Hidalgo also a
rising star in the outfield, the Astros' toughest decision figures
to be one regarding Alou, Ward and Cedeno _ and Ward for now looks
like the odd man out.
</P>
<P>
   Alou has a no-trade clause in his contract, and Cedeno's speed
and defensive abilities offer more than Ward can provide. It's not
a stretch to believe Ward's future with the club hinges on how he
performs over the next 2{ months.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, it is Meluskey who has earned every-day status _ the
occasional defensive lapse notwithstanding. And though you wouldn't
have thought it last spring, Julio Lugo might be the 2001 regular
at shortstop, thanks to Tim Bogar's falling short of expectations
offensively and top prospect Adam Everett's still being at least
another year away.
</P>
<P>
   At third, Chris Truby will be in a make-or-break situation
similar to Ward's. Truby's defense has impressed, and he's hit for
average, but he needs much better power numbers.
</P>
<P>
   On the mound, the second-half focus will fall squarely on the
shoulders of Octavio Dotel, Jose Lima and Wade Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Lima, of course, simply needs to find the lost magic. Winning
his last game before the break was a good start. And Dotel has
Astros management practically giddy about the possibility of
teaming him with a healthy Billy Wagner in the bullpen next season
_ presuming Miller can establish himself as a big-league starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Dotel can throw 95 or 96 mph three or four times a week,
then we would have a great situation,'' Dierker said. ``I see the
light at the end of the tunnel, and it really doesn't look that far
away to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the young guys now, it's kind of got me going again.
I inherited a team that finished second three straight years and
didn't do very much at all except watch, and we won three straight.
But now it's more intriguing, more of a challenge and stimulating.
It's also exasperating and frustrating, but this team is not that
far away.''
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of months, much has changed about this Astros team.
In more ways than one, it's making the turn.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
