A0476 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TIME-REGAINED-REVIEW-     07-12 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIME-REGAINED-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCENIC FILM WORTH YOUR TIME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Time Regained'' does as smart a job as could be expected of
bringing Marcel Proust's allusive prose to the screen. It doesn't
entirely work as a movie, and those who are intimate with
``Remembrance of Things Past'' _ all 12 of you _ will probably find
some fault in casting, compression or correlation here.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Raoul Ruiz's French-language film intelligently
and imaginatively strives to approximate the style and feeling of
the book, which concluded the seven-part, semi-autobiographical
novel. Ruiz works in bits from earlier chapters and tries, often
but not always felicitously, to clarify the saga's numerous
characters and their complicated relationships.
</P>
<P>
   It can't all be done, of course, with complete satisfaction, a
difficulty that unfortunately becomes most apparent during the
film's extended, glacially paced climax. This is the point at which
the narrator and Proust stand-in (Marcello Mazzarella) finally sees
through the facades and pretensions of the social elites he's
devoted his ebbing life to joining and, thereby, affirms his
purpose in life. By then, viewers are way ahead of him, having long
ago grown fed up with the narcissistic twits despite how
intricately Proust has described them, and the sequence can't help
but overstay its welcome.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time leading up to that disappointing musicale,
however, Ruiz keeps the cinematically minded viewer intrigued with
a vast array of formal gambits that nicely approximate Proust's
ever-shifting narrative connections. Set elements move of their own
accord as the camera prowls through sumptuously decorated Paris
apartments. The ringing of a servant's bell initiates a riot of
clanging recollections, culminating at a long-ago, far-away church
tower. There is a magic lantern tableau, human statues,
superimpositions three layers deep, mismatched cuts and high-wire
lighting schemes, among many other, densely packed visual motifs.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, faces, costumes and locations seem to morph
indiscriminately. It's all fundamentally playful (although,
tonally, the film's attitude is persistently grave), certainly
showoffy and quite effective at evoking the Proustian basics: the
unruliness of memory, the chaos of emotion and the disillusionment
of maturity.
</P>
<P>
   Though the story jumps around time with unfettered promiscuity,
the primary setting is Paris during and for a few years on either
side of World War I. It would take, well, a volume to describe all
the key characters and incidents. We'll limit our discussion to the
big names.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Deneuve slips in and out of view, her self-possession
a suit of armor, as the aging, well-marrying courtesan Odette.
Emmanuelle Beart is sufficiently, sadly unreachable as Gilberte,
Odette's daughter and the former object of Marcel's infatuation.
John Malkovich is the very definition of effete as the withering
but voracious Baron Charlus, while Vincent Perez brings subversive
energy to the bisexual musician Morel, whom the Baron and many of
the other married men in the story just can't get over.
</P>
<P>
   Chilean avant gardist Ruiz has lived and worked in France since
the overthrow of the Allende government in the 1970s. He is highly
regarded in international art film circles and all but unknown to
the American public. He says of ``Time Regained'' that ``all my
films have been a way of preparing this one.'' There is indeed a
career's worth of aesthetic acuity, in service to the most daunting
of challenges, on display here. It's an impressive effort even if
all goals, perhaps inevitably, are not met. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
The film: ``Time Regained'' (NR; mild violence, erotic
situations). &QL; 
The stars: Marcello Mazzarella, Emmanuelle Beart, Catherine
Deneuve, Vincent Perez, John Malkovich. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Raoul Ruiz. Written by Ruiz and
Gilles Taurand, based on Marcel Proust's novel. Produced by Paulo
Branco. Released by Kino International. &QL; 
Running time: Two hours, 45 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
