<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOWDEN0713-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Auburn-Bowden feud continues to smolder
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Terry Bowden accepted a handsome financial settlement
to step down as Auburn's football coach in the middle of the 1998
season. Fans of the school hoped that the embarrassing episode
finally had ended.
</P>
<P>
   Not a chance.
</P>
<P>
   A war of words between the two sides recently played out in the
Alabama media has the potential to embarrass further a university
that already has taken many public-relations hits.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest controversy, Auburn contends that Bowden forfeited
parts of his settlement agreement, including the mortgage payments
on his $1 million home for the next three years, when he signed a
contract as a college football television commentator with ABC.
</P>
<P>
   That contract, according to a letter sent to Auburn alumni by
athletics director David Housel, pays Bowden about $225,000 a year.
Housel goes on to say that Auburn's settlement agreement with
Bowden expressly stated that Bowden would relinquish parts of the
settlement if he took a job related to athletics.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Bowden and his attorneys angrily countered by
accusing Housel of misleading Auburn alumni and withholding key
information about the settlement. In a letter sent to media
outlets, Birmingham lawyer Nolan E. Awbrey pointed out that the
settlement was negotiated specifically to allow Bowden to do
part-time work as a television analyst. Thus, the term
``full-time'' employment was inserted to describe circumstances
that would violate the agreement. Bowden contends that he works
part time for ABC as a ``free-lance artist'' and that his total
work load consists of about ``30 days a year.''
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Awbrey accused Housel and the Auburn attorney of
attempting to ``try its case in the media and sway public opinion
without making a full and fair disclosure of the true facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, the issue now will be settled
by binding arbitration. Each side will pick a member of the
three-member panel and will have to agree on the third. It might be
August before the hearing is held.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high for Bowden, who left Auburn on Oct. 23,
1998, after compiling a record of 47-17-1. If he loses, Bowden
either will be forced to move out of his home in Auburn or begin
making the $7,000 monthly payments on the mortgage. He also would
forfeit the use of two cars provided to him and his wife, Shyrl, by
the Auburn athletics association.
</P>
<P>
   On the advice of his attorneys, Bowden will not discuss the
matter. But according to published reports, he thinks Auburn's
attempt to oust him from the house has been orchestrated by Bobby
Lowder, a wealthy Montgomery banker considered to be the most
powerful member of the Auburn Board of Trustees. Bowden has gone
public with some criticisms of Lowder and former coach Pat Dye,
something expressly forbidden by his settlement agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Lowder has had no comment on Bowden's claims. Dye, who resigned
after the 1992 season, will only say that Bowden ``has talked
enough for both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Housel was on vacation Wednesday and could not be reached for
comment. But his letter to alumni and a letter sent to media
outlets by Auburn's attorneys, denies that the school is trying to
kick Bowden out of his home. Housel said the disagreement has
existed for more than a year and began when Bowden first went to
work for ABC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Auburn University has attempted numerous times to resolve this
matter amicably and in a businesslike manner for more than a
year,'' Housel's letter says. ``Auburn has lived up to the
agreement, and we expect Coach Bowden to do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
