<HEADER>
A0485 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-NY-SCAFFOLDING-NYT &LR;      07-12 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCAFFOLDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCAFFOLDS: SAY, WHO BLOTTED OUT THE SKY? 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN LELAND    
c .2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the ribbon of scaffolding and razor coils went
up around his building on 101st Street and Broadway a few months
back, Paul Byard took it as a harmless inconvenience. As an
architect, he'd been responsible for his share of those steel and
plywood constructions over the years. The awning was an eyesore,
but a temporary one. Then, walking down Broadway on a recent night,
he approached yet another makeshift overhang, this one more
isolated, an ad hoc darkened alley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was grungy, scary, not well lit,'' Byard, a partner in
Platt Byard Dovell, recalled. ``And it was richly inhabited by
people with social problems.'' He considered crossing the street
but soldiered through, more annoyed than genuinely threatened.
``It's a nuisance,'' he said of the structures casting a shadow
over an ever-greater part of the city grid. ``You have to walk in
the street to get around it. It cuts off diagonals. And it makes it
awkward to jaywalk.''
</P>
<P>
   It is becoming the signature profile for much of the city: not
the grand Deco kitsch of the Chrysler building or the telltale
green canvas of Starbucks creep, but the unlovely clump of plywood
and metal tubing known in the trade as the sidewalk shed or bridge.
The Department of Buildings, which regulates the structures, issued
1,806 permits for sheds in the first six months of 2000, up roughly
80 percent from the same period just five years ago. Obstructing
sightlines and walking paths, squeezing already congested
sidewalks, the sheds have become pedestrians' analog to squeegee
guys, a minor obstacle replicated onto every street corner, at
least when you're in a hurry. ``They're out of hand,'' said Vanessa
Gruen, director of special projects at the nonprofit Municipal Art
Society, referring not just to the sheds but to the giant
billboards screaming from many. ``I think they're terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Some sheds come and go in a few months; others, erected around
buildings caught up in litigation or other financial entanglements,
can linger for years, without any sign of repair work above.
</P>
<P>
   So where, you might ask, is the outrage? New Yorkers, especially
those who sit on co-op boards, can come to blows over carpet
samples. Yet they have been strangely accommodating on the scaffold
question, accepting the civic intrusion as a twist of providence,
like car alarms or private school tuition.
</P>
<P>
   ``One gets used to it,'' said Michael Blackwood, a documentary
filmmaker who has for more than a year lived behind a dark steel
mesh while workers restore the facade of his landmark 58th Street
co-op. Blackwood described the disruption as necessary and minor.
``It's like being sick for a while,'' he added. ``You go through it
and then you get better.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for shed spread are mundane. Contractors like Sal
Impieri, branch manager of Safway Steel Products in Brooklyn,
credit the strong economy for a boom in construction and
renovation. At the same time, the city's infrastructure is showing
the effects of a century of erosion and stress, developing
unfortunate creaks and cracks that threaten the pedestrians below.
There is no telling how many streetwalkers or billable hours have
been saved by a timely shed. Impieri, who works the high end of the
market, estimates that his business has grown 30 to 40 percent in
each of the last two years, a rise he described as common in the
industry. By his lights, the aesthetic impact of all that
scaffolding is not to be underestimated. ``When you're in the
business,'' he said, ``everything looks beautiful, whether I do it
or someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   But the main reason for all the sheds may be bureaucratic. In
1998, after a fatal accident involving a scaffold in Times Square,
the city passed a regulation known as Local Law 11, calling for
inspection of all facades over six stories. The deadline for
inspection was in March. Once up, sheds can linger, sometimes for
several years. Landlords run out of money for repairs; contractors
leave for more lucrative jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like dealing with contractors on my own house,''
said Gary Larson, executive vice president of the Scaffolding
Industry Association, a trade group. ``I'm ready to shoot them.''
Scaffolding contractors set up the sheds, then take them away when
all is finished: It is up to all the other parties to get the work
done. Though scaffold permits last only a year, landlords can renew
them by attesting that they have not done the repair work. As long
as the shed keeps the sidewalk safe, the city doesn't penalize
landlords for not finishing the work.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent stroll up the Avenue of the Americas toward Herald
Square, Neel Scott emerged from the shadow of one rusty overhang
like a swimmer coming up for air before diving under the next.
Scott is a campaign coordinator for Transportation Alternatives, an
advocacy group for pedestrians and bicyclists; strictly speaking,
this disarray is his metier. ``That's just what I'm talking
about,'' he said, trying to squeeze upstream against a rush-hour
tide heading down. The shed's support poles stood about 2{ feet
from the building and 1{ feet from the curb, trimming the sidewalk
by about four feet. Sidewalk vendors hawked cheap toys and gadgets
underneath; a man oblivious to the crush slept under a ragged
blanket in the shade.
</P>
<P>
   For Zoltan Lebovich, the building's superintendent, this scene
was a vision of progress. ``Everyone likes it, they hide from the
rain. Even the homeless,'' he said, adding that the shed would come
down in four to six months, once the building was repointed.
</P>
<P>
   David Barone, standing in the shadow before his empty shop, was
less enthusiastic about the obstruction and the community growing
beneath it. ``People are missing the store,'' he complained, his
awning obscured by the protective canopy. ``It hurts, but what are
you going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, some architects contend, is prettier scaffolding.
Michael Graves drew mostly positive responses to the aluminum and
blue polyester sheath he erected around the Washington Monument,
since removed in time for the Fourth of July festivities.
</P>
<P>
   Modeled after a 16th-century etching by the Roman architect
Domenico Fontana, the construction was a cover-up Washington people
could get behind; groups in Minneapolis and Richmond, Va.,
campaigned to move it to their towns for permanent display. Both
projects fell through, but Graves sees the restoration as a
possible lead to a new, decorative age of scaffolding. ``Think of
the advertising opportunities, or the opportunities for younger
artists,'' he said, speaking from a hotel phone in Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Graves considers New York's current scaffold glut
an emblem of dynamism, not an aesthetic blight. ``My worry isn't
about the scaffolding, but that what you see when it comes down is
a disappointment. You think maybe the scaffolding was better.''
</P>
<P>
   The British writer G.K. Chesterton proposed that ``there is
something strangely primary and poetic about this sight of the
scaffolding and main lines of a human building; it is a pity there
is no scaffolding round a human baby.'' A warming thought, perhaps.
But then, Chesterton never had to squeeze himself under a cramped
midtown awning at rush hour, or return home to find his apartment
swaddled in steel tubes and marquee-size ads for a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Which is to say, he did not live in New York City at the start
of the 21st century, looking up for the stars and seeing instead
the corrugated sheet metal of yet another sidewalk shed. If he had,
he might have viewed scaffolding differently. Or he might have kept
his head down and commented on it not at all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
