<HEADER>
A0488 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT &LR;      07-12 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAY TO RELAX, AND THINK ABOUT THE MOUNTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARPENTRAS, France _ The Tour de France took a day off on
Wednesday and the riders relaxed, slept late, did a little
training, entertained friends and families. Whatever else the 160
men left in the race did, anybody who said he did not spend some
time thinking about the giant of Provence, Mont Ventoux, was lying.
</P>
<P>
   Mont Ventoux, on the schedule for Thursday, is a 21-kilometer
(13-mile) climb past the treeline into a desolation of strewn rock.
It can be obsessive to Tour riders. Many of them have suffered
there, and one of them _ Tom Simpson, who suffered heat
asphyxiation, complicated by amphetamine use _ died there in 1967.
Few have climbed the mountain with the joy they find in the
Pyrenees and the Alps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ventoux is a god of Evil, to which sacrifices must be
made,'' wrote Roland Barthes, the French philosopher, pioneer of
semiotics, sometimes windbag and full-time bicycle racing fan. ``It
never forgives weakness and extracts an unfair tribute of
suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Lance Armstrong, wearing the yellow jersey as the overall
leader, may never have deconstructed Barthes' half-century-old
essay about the Ventoux in the collection ``Mythologies,'' but he
agrees with the sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a weird place, a very weird place,'' he said in a
recent interview, recalling his climb there in a race last month.
``It's the hardest climb in the Tour, bar none.''
</P>
<P>
   Barthes again: ``Physically, the Ventoux is dreadful. Bald, it's
the spirit of Dry: its climate (it is much more an essence of
climate than a geographic place) makes it a damned terrain, a
testing place for heros, something like a higher hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Over to Armstrong: ``Nineteen hundred meters up there is
completely different from 1,900 any place else. There's no air,
there's no oxygen. There's no vegetation, there's no life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no life,'' he repeated. ``Rocks. Any other climb
there's vegetation, grass and trees. Not there on the Ventoux. It's
more like the moon than a mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   Does the place spook Armstrong? It did not trouble Eros Poli, an
Italian rider who was notorious for his lack of climbing skills and
who won a Tour stage over the Ventoux in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a 25-minute lead at the bottom of the hill,'' Armstrong
said indignantly. ``If I had 25 minutes, I wouldn't let it spook me
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Cut to Poli, nearing age 37, retired three years from the sport
and is a driver now for Fiat's VIPs at the Tour: ``The Ventoux did
scare me, but those 25 minutes I had gave me enough time to climb
it. I felt much happier coming down the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the biggest day of my life,'' Poli said. ``It was a
dream and I realized it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another winner on the Ventoux is Tyler Hamilton, an American
teammate of Armstrong's with the U.S. Postal Service team. Hamilton
won the Ventoux stage, in which Armstrong was fourth, last month in
the Dauphine Libere, their final preparatory race for the Tour.
Hamilton also finished first overall in that prestigious race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very difficult climb,'' he said. ``You need to have a
lot of respect for it, a lot of respect.''
</P>
<P>
   He defined that quality: ``You need to ride within yourself,''
meaning the rider should not long violate such physical limits as
his anerobic threshold, as he sometimes must for other victories.
``Some climbs you can attack at the bottom and hold it all the way
to the top, but this is a climb that I think you need to ride
definitely within your limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last six kilometers are very difficult,'' Hamilton said.
``When I attacked there with about a kilometer to go, did the 100
percent effort, I was suffering.'' Barthes would understand and
probably approve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
