A0491 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-VERMEER-OPERA-REVIEW-     07-12 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERMEER-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHAOS OUTSIDE VERMEER'S QUIET ROOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In ``The Letter,'' the painter Jan Vermeer looks
through a threshold from a darkened room. The two women he sees
make no attempt to seduce the eye. Their presence is as
matter-of-fact as the domestic moment we have found them in, as if
they had joined the pictures on the wall and checkered floor tiles
as parts of a larger still life.
</P>
<P>
   It is the light that Vermeer casts on them, moving from left to
right and from an unseen window, that so fascinates us. As the
light brings the outside world in, it finds a seated woman holding
a letter, presumably just delivered. Letters preoccupy the handful
of pictures that survive this enigmatic 17th-century Dutch painter;
they reappear nearly as often as musical instruments and serve as
powerful metaphors. Indeed, the powerful tranquillity of Vermeer's
interiors is made possible by this very different message bearer
from without: The sunlight that filters in from a source beyond our
view. It makes sense that the painter's subjects so often write
letters, read them or receive them.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Andriessen's opera, ``Writing to Vermeer,'' which opened
this year's Lincoln Center Festival at the New York State Theater
on Tuesday night, wonders, as we do, what goes on beyond the walls
of Vermeer's parlors and kitchens. Peter Greenaway has provided a
libretto in which the women of his household write to the painter,
now on a two-week trip to The Hague from his home in Delft. The
imaginary letters bring everyday news, but this is 1672, perhaps
Holland's most cataclysmic year.
</P>
<P>
   The tulip market has collapsed. French and English enemies
threaten the republic. An accidental explosion has blown Vermeer's
hometown very nearly off the map. There is violence in the streets.
Andriessen and his co-directors, Greenaway and Saskia Boddeke, seek
to show us both the history and the art, as if the silence to which
Vermeer's pictures escape is best explained by the noise going on
around them. The stage flows with water, and occasionally milk or
blood. This large company, mostly women and children, bathe in it
or are doused from above.
</P>
<P>
   The finale is nothing short of a flood, pouring from above and
streaming down a raked stage that itself seems to float on a lake
of its own. Screens project fragments of Vermeer's work or a
writing hand. As the singers sing the letters (the text is in
English), we hear the scratching pen and read along as the words,
projected white on black, march across the stage floor.
Superimposed are animated scenes or intimate close-ups. Greenaway
does not wish us to be bored.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast is the watchword of ``Writing to Vermeer.'' The little
versus the big, the peace of isolation against public riot, time
brought to a halt against time racing frenetically forward,
theatricality next to modesty. These are not easy loads to bring
into balance, and one spends two hours in front of this opera
trying to figure out what it is about: A painter or a stage
director? Greenaway's audacity and imagination are usually welcome,
but here they bully Vermeer into inconsequentiality. If the
director's use of water represents the flood of events, it also
depicts the drowning of a painter under a high tide of theatrics.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is by design, the intention being to depict the
artist's peacefulness overwhelmed by sheer size. And this opera
does things big. Its three women are in turn played by three women
each. Such multiple images fill the stage with people as they
engage in busy, often spastic choreographies. Vermeer (who does not
appear) is presented in spirit with such bustle and crowding that
we soon lose sight of him. If ``Writing to Vermeer'' had become the
study in contrasts that it promises at the outset, Greenaway's
images would have had a point. Here they seem merely in
competition, and this is a director who has made sure we shall look
at him before we look at any picture on a wall.
</P>
<P>
   The opera is nearly rescued by its music, which is very
beautiful. There is a sense of song in Andriessen's writing that
for post-tonal composers has become both anachronism and anathema.
The lines are long, sinuous and gracefully balanced. The composer
has also transformed the sound and the style of early instruments.
The songs and dances of Sweelinck take on the Day-Glo of electronic
treatment or become warped and out of tune through the twist of a
dial. History is accented by synthesized explosions or sharp
thrusts. The Asko and Schoenberg Ensembles are in the pit,
conducted by Reinbert de Leeuw. Michel van der Aa has done much of
the electronic work. The singers are all women, and all do well.
Barbara Hannigan, Susan Narucki and Kathryn Harries are Saskia,
Catharina and Maria. Each has two dancing mirror images.
</P>
<P>
   Vivid and clever as this production is, and as musically
appealing as Andriessen makes it, ``Writing to Vermeer'' has a
difficult time deciding what it wants to be. I went home stuffed
with images of gushing waters and flowing blood and took another
look at ``The Letter.''
</P>
<P>
   Andriessen's original idea was for a smaller, more modest piece,
but ambition seems to have had its way. Ambition indeed created a
brilliant commotion at Lincoln Center on Tuesday night, but
afterward, one looked again at the source, remembered the events
onstage and wondered what if anything could persuasively connect
Tuesday's opera with this tiny masterpiece of stillness, barely 17
inches high and 15 across. There are three more performances,
Thursday night, Friday and Saturday. They are in any case worth a
trip.
</P>
<P>
   The production originates with the Netherlands Opera.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WRITING TO VERMEER'
</P>
<P>
   Opera in one act by Louis Andriessen, libretto by Peter
Greenaway; conductor, Reinbert de Leeuw; directors, Greenaway and
Saskia Boddeke; sets and lighting by Michael Simon; costumes by Emi
Wada; electronic music inserts by Michel van der Aa. Presented by
Lincoln Center Festival 2000, at the New York State Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Barbara Hannigan (Saskia de Vries), Susan Narucki
(Catharina Bolnes), Kathryn Harries (Maria Thins) and members of
the Netherlands Opera. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0492 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MOBSTER-DEAL-BOS &LR;      07-12 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOBSTER-DEAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUGITIVE MOBSTER'S `SURROGATE SON' NAMES HIM IN MURDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Six months after leading investigators to a grave where
three bodies were unearthed, gangster Kevin J. Weeks has struck a
deal with federal prosecutors implicating his boss, James
``Whitey'' Bulger, in those murders and two others.
</P>
<P>
   Under a plea agreement made public Wednesday, Weeks admitted
that after joining Bulger's crew as a teenager, he helped Bulger
and his longtime sidekick Stephen Flemmi commit crimes and cleaned
up after them.
</P>
<P>
   By his own admission, Weeks, 44, served as ``lookout'' on one
murder, held two men captive before they were killed by Bulger and
his cohorts, dumped murder weapons, and repeatedly buried bodies.
</P>
<P>
   When Bulger feared that the remains of three people he and
Flemmi had killed in 1983, 1984 and 1985 while working as FBI
informants might be discovered, Weeks helped exhume the bodies in
October 1985 and rebury them in a gully alongside the city's
heavily traveled Southeast Expressway, according to the documents
unsealed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The gravesite remained a secret until January, when Weeks, known
as Bulger's ``surrogate son,'' turned on his mentor in a bid for
leniency on federal racketeering charges brought in November.
</P>
<P>
   Bulger has been a fugitive for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, after months of secret negotiations, prosecutors
notified the court that Weeks will plead guilty July 20 to new
charges of racketeering, extortion, drug conspiracy and
money-laundering as a member of Bulger's criminal organization.
</P>
<P>
   He's also prepared to admit that he helped Bulger, Flemmi and
their associates in the slayings of five people between 1982 and
1985 while serving as a loyal deputy to Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for Weeks's cooperation, federal prosecutors have
agreed to recommend a prison term ranging from five to 15 years.
But Weeks's lawyer may argue for far less.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's decided to step up to the plate and square away his life
and move forward,'' said attorney Dennis Kelly, who represents
Weeks. ``He has no ax to grind against anyone and what he's going
to do is what the agreement requires: that when he's called upon,
he will tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Weeks is poised to plead guilty to charges that he served as
``lookout'' in the May 1982 murder of Brian Halloran, who was
gunned down just weeks after telling the FBI that Bulger and
Flemmi, both longtime FBI informants, were involved in a series of
killings.
</P>
<P>
   Also killed in the shooting was Michael Donahue, who had the
misfortune of offering Halloran a ride home from a bar along
Boston's waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   The charges say Weeks helped others, including ``John Doe 1,''
kill Halloran and Donahue. While Bulger isn't named in the charges,
it's apparent from prior court testimony that he is John Doe 1.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Robert A. George, who represents the Donahue family,
said the family hopes Weeks's cooperation will help confirm
suspicions that rogue FBI agents warned Bulger and Flemmi that
Halloran was cooperating against him.
</P>
<P>
   `I'm not going to cry foul about the deal with Kevin Weeks,''
George said. ``If it wasn't for Kevin Weeks at this point we
wouldn't know as much as we know today. And I'm sure as time goes
on we'll know more and more. It's only going to help the Donahue
family get past all this.''
</P>
<P>
   The other murders Weeks has admitted involvement in are those of
Arthur ``Bucky'' Barrett and John McIntyre, and Deborah Hussey, the
daughter of Flemmi's longtime girlfriend. The remains of all three
were discovered in January in the makeshift grave.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, who was 46 when he disappeared on July 26, 1983, had
been involved in the 1980 Memorial Day weekend robbery of $1.5
million in cash and jewelry from Depositors Trust in suburban
Medford. Friends believe his murderers tortured him, trying to get
him to turn over his share of whatever was left from the heist.
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre, who was 32 when he vanished on Nov. 30, 1984,
disappeared weeks after implicating Bulger in an ill-fated plot to
smuggle weapons to the Irish Republican Army aboard a Gloucester,
Mass. boat, the Valhalla.
</P>
<P>
   The new charges say Barrett and McIntyre were kidnapped and
brought to an undisclosed location, where Weeks helped hold them
captive while they were murdered by John Doe 1 and John Doe 2,
apparently Bulger and Flemmi.
</P>
<P>
   Hussey, who was 26 when she vanished in early 1985, was
kidnapped and murdered by ``leaders of the Bulger Group,'' then
Weeks assisted in burying her body, according to the superseding
information.
</P>
<P>
   Hussey was just a toddler when Flemmi began romancing her
mother, Marion, and moved them into his home in Milton, just
outside Boston. Marion Hussey and Flemmi had three other children
together.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement sources say Flemmi allegedly had been having a
sexual relationship with Deborah Hussey since she was a teenager
and they had had a falling out.
</P>
<P>
   The new charges against Weeks reveal that the bodies of Hussey,
Barrett and McIntyre were exhumed in October 1985 and reburied in
Dorchester ``to prevent the discovery of those remains.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett's wife, Elaine, declined to comment on Weeks's admission
that he played a role in her husband's murder, saying only,
``Whoever did it should be brought to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Kevin Glynn, who represents the Barrett family, said
he'll be issuing a statement on their behalf within the next week.
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre's brother, Chris, said, ``This is just too brutal to
put into words right now. He kills them and he buries them and he
digs them up and he buries them again. Can you imagine the horror
my brother went through that day.''
</P>
<P>
   US Attorney Donald K. Stern defended the deal with Weeks
Wednesday, saying, ``For the prosecutors and the investigators who
have worked on these matters for a long time, and we hope for the
families, this will be seen as an important step in the ongoing
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Ralph C. Martin II has agreed not to prosecute
Weeks for the murders of Halloran, Donahue, Barrett, McIntyre and
Hussey.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Weeks will be placed in security while in prison
and has the option of joining the witness protection program after
he's released.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said he'll urge a judge to sentence Weeks to less than
five years in prison, if Weeks fulfills his promise to the
government to cooperate with authorities and testify at upcoming
trials.
</P>
<P>
   Suggesting that Weeks played only a minor role in Bulger's
organization, Kelly said, ``To the extent Kevin is pleading to
participation in the murders, it should be clear that he's not
someone who pulled the trigger or did any affirmative act to kill
somebody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
