<SLUG> BC-BIG-RIGS0713-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gas prices, credit problems put brakes on truck sales
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A combination of easy credit, high fuel prices and
hard times is filling truck dealers' lots with slow-selling big
rigs and repossessed trucks, say industry sources.
</P>
<P>
   And while truck drivers, dealers, manufacturers and lenders are
feeling most of the pain, a shakeout in the trucking industry could
translate into higher shipping rates and price tags for consumer
goods, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got guys calling us up and saying 'The truck's parked
here. Come pick it up,''' said Tom Nacey, regional remarketing
manager for Conseco's transportation finance division. ``That's
happening on a daily basis.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Carmel, Ind.-based insurer's finance unit stopped
making new loans on tractor trailers last month after its inventory
of repossessed units doubled since January to about 700 rigs.
</P>
<P>
   About 6 percent to 7 percent of the units Conseco has financed
have been repossessed or returned voluntarily _ about quadruple the
typical level, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons why many owner-operators and trucking firms can't
make their trucks pay their way runs the gamut from higher
interest, fuel and insurance costs to claims that DaimlerChrysler's
Freightliner LLC unit has flooded the market with thinly financed
heavy-duty trucks that have driven down used-truck prices.
</P>
<P>
   But No. 1 on the list is the high cost of diesel fuel, which hit
$2 a gallon this spring in some regions _ about twice its level
this time last year. The national average is currently about $1.45.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard of a lot of small companies getting out because of
the fuel. (It's) a big killer for us,'' says Ron Pavuk, president
of Preferred Transport in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   He began adding a surcharge of 3.5 percent to 6 percent to his
shipping rates this year to help cover the higher cost of fuel for
his 40-truck fleet. But that doesn't cover it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel costs amount to 20 percent to 30 percent of
owner-operators' revenues, says Todd Spencer, executive vice
president of the Owner-Operator Independent Drivers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a glut of used heavy-duty trucks caused prices to
drop about 30 percent since January, he adds. Some drivers owe more
on loans than their trucks are worth.
</P>
<P>
   Some truckers were wobbling under heavy debt payments after
manufacturers, particularly Freightliner, dangled zero-down
financing promotions before them, Spencer says.
</P>
<P>
   Freightliner President Jim Hebe says his company, the leading
heavy-duty truck manufacturer in the nation, has been laboring to
solve the used-truck problem, not exacerbate it.
</P>
<P>
   Freightliner's zero-down payment program ``is not unique to us''
and was in place years before the recent developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is real simple,'' he says. ``What's killed these
guys in the last year is fuel costs and interest rates.''
</P>
<P>
   Some local dealers say they haven't seen many repossessions or a
big drop in sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still selling like hot cakes,'' says Gail Miller,
finance manager for Gainesville Truck Center.
</P>
<P>
   But Pavuk, who tries to replace his fleet every three years,
says it's a bear market for used trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The used truck market is really depressed right now,'' he
says. ``Because of fuel prices, nobody wants to buy right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The market for new trucks has weakened as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're projecting the market will be down a good 20-25 percent
this year,'' Hebe says. He expects Freightliner's sales to be down
10 percent to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of record sales, tractor-trailer sales dropped
in May for the second month. Freightliner's sales were down 15
percent in May compared to a year earlier, and 26 percent in April,
according to Ward's Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Hebe said Freightliner, which launched a network of used-truck
dealerships in 1996, will be ``doing some very dramatic things'' to
deal with the glut of used trucks, including remanufacturing and
exporting trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just too many trucks in the United States today,''
he said. ``We're going to be devoting significant manufacturing
resources to late-model used trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
