<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MISSILE-SCHWARTZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAKED SECRETS OR ANTI-MISSILE FRAUD? ENGINEER IS AT HUB OF
DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ohio, Calif., Iowa)   By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An engineer who leveled accusations of anti-missile fraud
against a big contractor is becoming caught in a federal clash.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon agents are trying to question her about leaks of
military secrets, even while congressional and criminal
investigators are gearing up to examine the merit of her
accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Nira Schwartz, a senior engineer in 1995 and 1996 at TRW, a top
military contractor, has alleged that the company falsified work
meant to help anti-missile interceptors to distinguish incoming
warheads from decoys. The company strongly denies the allegation.
Schwartz contends that TRW then fired her when she protested.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz objected Wednesday to Pentagon plans to have its
security investigators quiz her about information that she had
provided to anti-missile critics. She said the scrutiny was clearly
aimed at shielding the $60 billion anti-missile plan from scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to kill the messenger,'' she said in an
interview. ``Right now, the court case is the only way to bring
this issue to justice. The nation needs an independent evaluation
of the project. Otherwise, we're being taken for a ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Her case, which languished in U.S. District Court in Los Angeles
for years, rose to prominence in recent months as the Clinton
administration pressed ahead with plans to deploy the anti-missile
system and as scientists and critics backed her allegations and
broadened them to contend that the Pentagon had tried to cover up
the purported flaw.
</P>
<P>
   Her top scientific ally, Theodore A. Postol, an arms expert at
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, said that Pentagon
investigators were seeking to question Schwartz about declassified
documents that she shared with him, and apparently one in
particular. They are doing so simply to harass her, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is outrageous,'' Postol said Wednesday, adding that three
Defense Security Service investigators confronted him over the same
matter last month. ``It's very clear they know where the document
comes from. This is a transparent case of intimidation.''
</P>
<P>
   Retroactively, Pentagon officials in May classified as secret a
letter that Postol sent the White House containing Schwartz's
declassified document, and he promptly denounced the move as
political censorship.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Postol said the Pentagon document in question had
been declassified by the Defense Criminal Investigative Service in
the course of reviewing Schwartz's allegations. He said the
Pentagon was apparently going out of its way to avoid investigating
itself.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, David W. Affeld, Schwartz's lawyer, wrote to Lt.
Col. Bill Groves, general counsel of the Pentagon's anti-missile
program, to complain about Defense Department plans to interrogate
his client.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned,'' he wrote, ``that the `investigation' of Dr.
Schwartz is motivated not to preserve national security, but rather
to intimidate an outspoken critic of the program.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the White House is considering whether to press ahead
with the costly anti-missile plan. Postol provided a copy of the
letter; Affeld declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say that if Schwartz is found guilty of leaking
military secrets, her lawsuit may be crippled, especially if the
finding ends her ability to review classified documents needed to
prove her allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., who has called for congressional
and criminal inquiries into Schwartz's allegations, on Wednesday
denounced the Pentagon's interrogation plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously,'' he said, ``hits are being put out on anyone who
betrays this high-tech code of silence. It's like the Mafia.
They're attempting to silence anyone who tells the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur L. Money, an assistant secretary of defense in charge of
security policy, said Wednesday night that no decision had been
made on whether to contact Schwartz. ``Our focus is internal to the
Department of Defense on whether any leaks occurred,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Markey, and separately, Rep. Howard Berman, D-Calif., and Sen.
Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, the authors of 1986 false-claims
amendments, have called on the congressional General Accounting
Office to investigate the anti-missile allegations. In a July 5
letter, Berman and Grassley said the federal government's financial
recovery, if fraud was proven, could be its largest ever.
</P>
<P>
   Robert E. Levin, an accounting office official, said plans for
an investigation were so far unfocused. ``We haven't really started
interviewing witnesses or figuring out the scope of the effort,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Interested in whether laws were broken, 53 members of the House,
led by Rep. Dennis Kucinich, D-Ohio, a member of the government
oversight committee, wrote FBI director Louis Freeh in June asking
him to scrutinize the fraud allegations.
</P>
<P>
   John Collingwood, an FBI spokesman, said Wednesday that he could
make no comment on whether an inquiry was under way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
