u e BC-INDIAN-AMERICAN-THEAT     07-12 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-AMERICAN-THEATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FESTIVAL OPENS DOOR TO INDIAN THEATER  

</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: spellings of Aroon Shivdasani in second graf, Mahesh Dattani
in third graf and Vijay Tendulkar and Marathi in fifth graf are
cq.)  
 
 
 By FELICIA R. LEE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   NEW YORK _ For Indian playwrights,
involvement in New York theater has been more a flirtation than
anything serious. That has meant mostly short runs, small theaters
and few mainstream audiences, even for celebrated Indian
playwrights.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The growing population of Indian artists in New York hopes to
change this. Beginning on Friday, the TriBeCa Performing Arts
Center will present the Festival of Indian Theater, which will run
for three weeks and include 18 performances. The festival is
sponsored by the Indo-American Arts Council, whose director, Aroon
Shivdasani, says it is the first such festival in North America.
</P>
<P>
   The festival will feature the U.S. premieres of two plays, in
English with all-Indian casts, by two of India's leading
playwrights.
</P>
<P>
   Mahesh Dattani's ``Dance Like a Man'' is about the conflict
between two aging dancers who perform in the classical temple style
known as Bharata Natyam. Their careers are ending, and their
daughter's is taking off. It was written in English.
</P>
<P>
   Vijay Tendulkar's ``Once Upon a Fleeting Bird'' is an English
adaptation of a contemporary love story set in Bombay. It was
originally performed in the Marathi language.
</P>
<P>
   The Asia Society has organized a series of conversations with
the playwrights, directors and casts before and after selected
performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indian theater has been shown here, but it has been a
one-night stand,'' said Shivdasani, who is a founder of the small,
multicultural Bear Theater Company in Toronto. ``It's one night in
Queens, one night in New Jersey, then it's out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indian plays draw a niche audience, she said. That means
that American playgoers miss out on playwrights who are as well
known in their home country as Arthur Miller is here.
</P>
<P>
   The Indo-American Arts Council was formed two years ago to
introduce mainstream American audiences to Indian artists. A film
screening or performance is often accompanied by a discussion about
broader aspects of Indian culture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
