<HEADLINE>
CAPTAIN MCENROE WILLING TO PLAY DOUBLES IN DAVIS CUP SEMIFINAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN B. ADAMS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John McEnroe's star turn as the U.S. Davis Cup captain is not
exactly unfolding the way he envisioned. In the space of two days,
the capricious forces of injury and accident have deprived McEnroe
of Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi for the Davis Cup semifinal
against Spain, July 21-23, in Santander, Spain. Instead, the
first-year captain will take a team anchored by Todd Martin and
including Jan-Michael Gambill and Chris Woodruff.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe has also turned, at least temporarily, to the player he
knows he can depend on: himself. As player-captain of the U.S.
team, the 41-year-old McEnroe could play doubles _ and, he insists,
doubles only _ against Spain, unless he can find someone younger,
stronger and willing (perhaps Paul Goldstein or Vince Spadea).
McEnroe can substitute any of his four players up to 10 minutes
before the July 20 draw for the semifinal, which will be played on
slow red clay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't actually decided to compete,'' McEnroe said
Wednesday in a conference call announcing the U.S. team. ``There is
a good chance I won't play, but there is a chance I will play, and
if I take the court, I'm not going out there to lose. Until
yesterday, it wasn't even something I was thinking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I'm not in this to play,'' said McEnroe, who has a
59-10 record in singles and doubles and five Davis Cup
championships in 12 years of playing for the United States. ``My
plan is to work with younger players and make them better, not for
me necessarily to take a spot from someone. The situation is that
there's not a lot of guys that have gotten themselves into a
position where they should be playing.''
</P>
<P>
   And those who are in a position to play are bowing out. On
Tuesday, Sampras confirmed that the acute tendinitis in his left
shin that had plagued him throughout a successful run to his
seventh Wimbledon championship and a record 13th Grand Slam singles
title would keep him out of the matchup against Spain. Following
doctors' advice, Sampras will rest the injured leg for two to three
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how injured he is,'' McEnroe said Wednesday.
``Davis Cup was something that was a priority to me. But, who am I
to say? I wish he had made an effort to do it, and perhaps played a
doubles match and been there; that might have been inspiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows? Maybe he'd be risking further injury if he played
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sampras' withdrawal was not a surprise, Agassi's pullout
stunned McEnroe. Agassi, driving from the airport to his Las Vegas
home, strained his back when his car was rear-ended in a minor
automobile accident Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was obviously more shocking because it came out of the
blue,'' McEnroe said. ``We as a team, and myself as a captain, have
been banking on him to win a couple matches for us. To say that I
was disappointed would be a major understatement.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with Sampras and Agassi, the U.S. team would have faced an
imposing challenge against Spain. The host team includes
20-year-old Juan Carlos Ferrero _ ``one of the best clay-court
players in the world, bar none,'' according to McEnroe _ and two
other outstanding clay court players, No. 7 Alex Corretja and No.
22 Albert Costa. Now, McEnroe rated his team's chances at
``probably 10, 20 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans will be led into a 10,500-seat temporary stadium
in Santander by the game but gimpy Martin, who has competed in only
seven tournaments in 2000 after sustaining a knee injury early in
the season. Woodruff won the fifth and deciding match against
Zimbabwe in the first round of the Davis Cup competition. Gambill,
at No. 30, is the highest-ranked player on the American team. He is
a fit, strong but largely untested 25-year-old who reached the
quarterfinals at Wimbledon and was 1-1 in limited Davis Cup duty in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, McEnroe sounded both deflated and defiant while
discussing his captaincy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I haven't been that successful in getting the
players,'' McEnroe said. ``Todd was injured the first couple. Pete
was unavailable for the first match. Now Pete and Andre. Chang has
said no both times that I've asked him to play,'' he said of
Michael Chang. ``Jim Courier has recently retired. This has
certainly not turned out the way it was planned beforehand, at
least in my mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping that my presence there would make a real
difference. At this point, you either call it bad luck or it hasn't
made a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   In their last Davis Cup meeting, the United States defeated
Spain, 4-1, in the 1991 quarterfinals in Newport, R.I.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
