<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bar Code Software For Comparing Prices
</P>
<P>
   Most people never even think about looking at the bar code on
the book or CD they are about to buy. But new bar code software may
cause some shoppers to hunt for those black-and-white symbols
whenever they pick up a product.
</P>
<P>
   The software, which is designed to be downloaded to Web-enabled
handheld devices like the Palm VII organizer, allows people to
conduct online price comparisons the minute they spot a product on
the shelf.
</P>
<P>
   By entering the 12-digit number that appears below the thin
black lines of the bar code, a person sends a request for
information over the wireless Internet. A few seconds later,
several lines of information pop up on the screen, including data
on the prices offered at other stores.
</P>
<P>
   Barpoint.com, a company in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., developed the
software, which can be downloaded from www.barpoint.com. Its
databases include books, videos, music and software, and the
company plans to add categories like consumer electronics, office
supplies, toys, groceries, health and beauty products and
automobile parts.
</P>
<P>
   With the comparison data in hand, said Jeffrey Sass,
Barpoint.com's chief operating officer, shoppers will be able to
decide, for example, whether a higher price in a store is worth the
convenience of having the product in hand.
</P>
<P>
   The software cannot accept credit-card information, which would
allow people to order immediately from Web sites or purchase items
without walking through the check-out line. But eventually, Sass
said, ``you'll even be able to shop from the wireless device.''
</P>
<P>
   Netpliance Is Betting That Less Will Be More
</P>
<P>
   Netpliance, the first company to offer a simple Internet
appliance for people seeking something less than a full-fledged PC,
said it is significantly upgrading its i-Opener device in
preparation for a big holiday-season retail push. But the price is
quadrupling, to $399.
</P>
<P>
   The company, in Austin, Texas, had trouble meeting demand at the
promotional price of $99, which ended June 30, and it is declaring
an unusual moratorium while it catches up and revises the product
line. Online orders placed today will not be filled until October,
although the new i-Opener 2001 devices will be in stores by Sept.
1.
</P>
<P>
   The new i-Opener 2001 system, which requires a $21.95 monthly
Internet service fee but no long-term service contract, adds
instant messaging among i-Opener users, multiple e-mail accounts
and stock quotes.
</P>
<P>
   At $399, plus $21.95 a month, the i-Opener is no longer
significantly cheaper than a low-end PC with Internet access, and
yet it has more limited features. The company is betting that
customers will be willing to pay more for simplicity and ease of
use.
</P>
<P>
   Sending Digital Photos Directly From a Camera
</P>
<P>
   Shutterbugs with a passion for instantly shared experiences will
soon be able to send their digital photos by e-mail without ever
touching their computers. Wireless photo transmission is being made
possible by Digita Post software currently available in Kodak DC290
digital cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The software, developed by FlashPoint Technology, based in San
Jose, Calif., works with the company's Digita technology, which
functions as an operating system for digital cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Transmitting photos from digital cameras to cell phones to any
e-mail box anywhere in the world is expected to be particularly
handy for insurance adjusters, police officers and paramedics,
though the biggest market for the cameras is expected to be among
nonprofessionals, said Karen Meyers, a company spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Users insert a flash card into the camera and take standard
digital photos. Then they start up the Digita Post software in the
camera, which allows them to select which photos they want to send
and even attach text and sound messages (the Kodak DC290 has a tiny
microphone).
</P>
<P>
   The camera is then connected to a cell phone through a cable.
Another click and the photos are on their way. They arrive in the
receiver's e-mail In box as a message with an attached JPEG file.
Sounds arrive as WAV file attachments.
</P>
<P>
   Digita Post is expected to cost $199 and will be available in
late September on the FlashPoint Web site (www.flashpoint.com).
</P>
<P>
   Other camera manufacturers, including Minolta, Hewlett Packard
and Sharp, that offer Digita-enabled cameras are expected to
incorporate the Digita Post software, too, Meyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Dell Pulls Web-Based PC
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer of Round Rock, Texas, has pulled the plug on its
Web-based PC for computer novices. The WebPC, introduced in
November at $999, was neither simple nor inexpensive enough to
catch on with consumers, and it has disappeared from Dell's Web
site. Rather than continue to chase the market for inexpensive
Internet appliances, Dell this week introduced a line of midrange
computers for consumers called Dimension 4100. A Dimension 4100
with a 733-megahertz processor, 128 megabytes of memory, a
10-gigabyte hard drive and a 17-inch monitor costs $1,299.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, meanwhile, discontinued the sleek Presario 3500, which
fell flat with consumers and will be sold only in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
