<HEADLINE>
N.H. HOUSE VOTES TO IMPEACH TOP JUDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOIS R. SHEA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ The New Hampshire House of Representatives voted
overwhelmingly Wednesday night to impeach the state's top judge on
charges ranging from lying under oath to allowing justices to be
involved in cases from which they had been disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   Unless he resigns, state Supreme Court Chief Justice David A.
Brock will now face an unprecendented trial in the state Senate
next month to determine whether he will be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   As the emotional day of debate wore on Wednesday, Brock's fate
in the 400-member House became sealed. The House not only
overwhelmingly approved all three articles of impeachment
recommended by the Judiciary Committee, but added a fourth. Then,
after a final vote of 253-95 to impeach, House members rejected
proposals that would have allowed Brock to collect his $80,000
pension and benefits if he resigned before the Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   Brock has served on the court for a quarter-century, the last 14
years as its chief justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a solemn and difficult day for the state of New
Hampshire,'' Governor Jeanne Shaheen said in a statement. ``The
House conducted a thorough, thoughtful and dignified inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time since 1790 that a Supreme Court judge has
been impeached in New Hampshire. That judge resigned rather than
face a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Brock's attorney, David Barry, said, ``The House was entitled to
do what they did. Now they've done what they've done and they've
impeached the chief justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry criticized the impeachment articles as ``factually
deficient,'' and said he was confident that Brock would prevail in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Barry said that Brock ``has had no due process to date. And as
much as we had hoped that a Senate trial would not be necessary, it
now is clear that it is going to happen, and we and the chief
justice greatly look forward to the opportunity to vindicate his
name and his reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in the House proceedings, Brock or his lawyers will be
allowed to call and cross-examine witnesses during his Senate
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Brock watched the proceedings on television from his home.
</P>
<P>
   The New Hampshire constitution allows for four possible grounds
of impeachment: Bribery, corruption, malpractice and
maladministration. The articles against Brock dealt only with the
latter two.
</P>
<P>
   Brock was accused of lying under oath to the House Judiciary
Committee; allowing justices to comment on cases from which they
had been recused; and improperly intervening in a 1987 lower court
case involving a powerful state senator who at the time held sway
over a judicial pay raise.
</P>
<P>
   The votes, stressed state Representative John Pratt (D-Walpole),
a member of the House Judiciary committee, were not a finding of
guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not here to try Chief Justice Brock,'' Pratt said. ``Or
to convict him, or to reprimand him. We are here only to determine
whether...we should send this on to the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Henry Mock (R-Jackson), chairman of the House
Judiciary committee, said he was pleased that the House accepted
the recommendations of the committee, which has held a three-month
investigation before recommending three articles of impeachment
against Brock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's the Senate's ballgame,'' Mock said.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Liz Hager (D-Concord), said she was surprised by
the vote's wide margain and disappointed that many House members
seemed to have come into the proceedings with their minds made up.
</P>
<P>
   She predicted that Brock would not be removed from office after
a Senate trial. ``But it will be a long, expensive, very ugly
experience for a very nice guy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mock set the tone early Wednesday, opening the debate by saying,
``There has never been a more somber day.''
</P>
<P>
   Speakers' voices rose against the sound of giant fans intended
to cool the historic chamber, but the temperature continued to rise
as the day wore on.
</P>
<P>
   Some House members' voices cracked as they described
``agonizing'' over the votes before them. Others defended Brock's
character and said his actions, while perhaps foolish, did not rise
to the level of impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Barry said the votes on the original three articles against
Brock did not come as a total surprise. ``It is my understanding
that there is a great amount of deference paid by the House to its
committee reccommendations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The first article taken up Wednesday, which the House adopted by
a vote of 219-138, dealt with allegations that Brock had called
Superior Court Judge Douglas Gray in 1987 to inquire about the
status of a case involving the then-Senate majority leader at a
time the Legislature was considering judicial pay raises. Brock has
insisted that Gray called him and not the other way around. But in
an internal Supreme Court investigation, Brock's colleagues found
that the chief justice had made the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``He dialed the telephone,'' Mock said, adding, ``It was not to
discuss the Sunday golf game.''
</P>
<P>
   The second article, which the House adopted by an even wider
margin, 252-104, dealt with allegations that Brock allowed and even
encouraged justices to comment on the selection of substitute
judges to hear fellow Supreme Court Justice W. Stephen Thayer's
divorce; and with speaking with Thayer in a hallway about the
selection of judges to hear his case.
</P>
<P>
   Brock denies having had the hallway conversation with Thayer.
State Representative Martha Solow (D-Hanover) urged members to vote
against the second article.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comparing Chief Justice Brock's and Justice Thayer's
credibility, I have to come down on the side of Chief Justice
Brock,'' Solow said.
</P>
<P>
   Thayer resigned his seat on the bench rather than face criminal
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The last of the three initial charges alleged that he lied under
oath four times and deliberately tried to mislead the House
Judiciary Comittee during its recent investigation. The House voted
242-112 to adopt the perjury article.
</P>
<P>
   In an amendment vote at the dinner hour, the House adopted a
fourth article of impeachment against Brock by a measure of
244-108. Offered as an amendment by Representative Ralph Jacobson
(R-New London), the fourth article alleged that during his tenure
as chief justice, Brock permitted and oversaw ``a practice whereby
recused and disqualified justices were permitted to receive draft
opinions and to attend case conferences, thereby enabling them to
comment on and influence opinions in the cases from which they were
recused and disqualified.''
</P>
<P>
   State Senator Burt Cohen (D-Newcastle) called the entire matter
``sad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A government is weakened if any of the three branches are
weakened,'' said Cohen. ``And it's imperative that we rebuild
confidence in the court.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
