<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0392 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0505 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-REDS0713-COX     07-12 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS0713-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Neagle traded to the Yankees
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Jim Bowden, the man with the itchiest trigger
finger in baseball, pulled another shocker Wednesday when the
Cincinnati Reds general manager traded the team's No. 1 pitcher,
Denny Neagle, and minor-league outfielder Mike Frank to the New
York Yankees for four minor-league prospects.
</P>
<P>
   For most of this season, Bowden told everybody that not only did
he want to keep Neagle, but that he was searching for additional
pitching help to aid the team's chase of first-place St. Louis in
the National League Central.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, with the Reds eight games behind the Cardinals at the
All-Star break and 4 1/2 games behind the New York Mets in the wild
card, Bowden wrecked the rotation, sending the 31-year-old
left-handed Neagle to the Yankees for players not ready for prime
time.
</P>
<P>
   Obtained by the Reds were:
</P>
<P>
   _ Third baseman Drew Henson, 20, the Yankees No. 3 pick in the
1998 draft.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outfielder Jackson Melian, 20, a free-agent signee in July
1996, from Barcelona, Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   _ Right-handed pitcher Brian Reith, 22, the Yankees No. 4 pick
in the 1996 draft.
</P>
<P>
   _ Left-handed pitcher Ed Yarnall, 24, a former New York Mets No.
3 pick in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball America rates Henson, Melian and Yarnall as the third-,
fifth- and sixth best prospects in the Yankees system.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden decided it was time to deal when he offered Neagle, who
can become a free agent this season, a three-year $18 million deal
and Neagle and his agent, Barry Meister, said they preferred to try
the free agent route after the season. When Neagle saw the
Minnesota Twins sign pitcher Brad Radke to a four-year $36 million
contract, his mind was made up.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to realize we're a small- to middle-market team
and we don't have a $107 million payroll like the Yankees do,''
Bowden said. ``We have to make due with what we have and the best
way to do that is to stockpile young players. We took a lot of heat
when we traded Dave Burba for Sean Casey and Sean Casey became an
All-Star. We took a lot of grief when we traded John Smiley for
Danny Graves and Danny Graves became an All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope two of these four players might become All-Stars and
if it happens, we hope people will look back on this as a good
deal,'' Bowden said. ``It's a challenge when you are a small
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said the club is re-focusing on becoming a winner when
the new park opens in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Henson is a risk. In addition to playing baseball, hitting .287
in 59 games at Class AA Norwich this year with seven homers and 39
RBIs, Henson is the quarterback of the University of Michigan
football team. Going into his junior season, he is a Heisman Trophy
candidate and might opt for pro football.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what can be done to persuade Henson to stick with
baseball, Bowden smiled and said, ``A big losing year for Michigan.
I guess it is a matter of how well he does in football. He hasn't
decided which direction to go and he is going to play them both out
and see what works, what sport he excels in the most. At this
point, he has made tremendous strides in baseball _ at 20 years old
he is hitting .290 in Double-A.''
</P>
<P>
   Yarnall is closest to the majors and was penciled into the
Yankees rotation this spring but flopped. He was 13-4 with a 3.47
ERA at Class AAA Columbus last year and is 2-1 with a 4.56 ERA in
10 starts this year, plus he made two starts and three bullpen
appearances for the Yankees this season and is 1-0 with a 3.71 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was slated to be in the Yankees rotation this year, but had
some shoulder problems and arm problems and didn't have much
success,'' Bowden said. ``He is now healthy and threw a two-hitter
his last time out. We feel down the road he can be a 12- to 15-game
winner.
</P>
<P>
   Reith was 9-4 with a 2.18 ERA in 18 starts at Class A Tampa, his
fifth straight year in Class A.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our scouts compare him to a Tim Belcher, Brian Moehler type of
pitcher and a guy who can be a solid starter in the big leagues,''
Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   Meilian was hitting .252 with nine homers and 38 RBIs at
Norwich, his first year at Class AA after three years in Class A,
mostly because of his youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a right-fielder, a five-tool player, a Cincinnati
Reds-type player who can run, throw, hit, hit for power and has
potential to be an All-Star superstar type player,'' Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   None is ready to help the Reds overtake the Cardinals and Bowden
realizes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't comfortable keeping Neagle until the end of the
season and risk having him walk on us to free agency and we'd get
only two draft picks of which we don't even know if we can sign as
draft picks,'' Bowden said. ``This way, we get four players as part
of the deal who are far superior to two draft picks we'd receive if
Neagle signs somewhere else as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   And Bowden may not be finished.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds are scouting the Boston system for prospects because
the Red Sox reportedly are interested in outfielder Dmitri Young as
a possible designated hitter. And several teams indicate that
Bowden is determining what interest there is in shortstop Barry
Larkin, who is asking for a three-year, $28 million deal. Bowden
said trading Neagle does not free up money for Larkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're absolutely concerned about how the Neagle trade will be
taken by the fans, the media and our players,'' Bowden said. ``No
one wants to lose a No. 1 starter. You want to trade for more Denny
Neagles, not trade Denny Neagle away. It was a very difficult
decision, but it is big business. You can't let assets go and get
nothing for it. The players have to understand it's big business.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden agreed that trading Neagle also traded away hopes of
winning the division this year, but the club couldn't afford the
consequences of not doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our payroll, which is between $43 million and $44 million now,
would be between $70 million and $80 million next year and we can't
afford to do that. . .it's not there,'' Bowden said. ``We've traded
our No. 1 starter and we've hurt our chances of winning now. We
know this. That was our No. 1 starter and there were 15 games he
was going to start the second half. He won't be out there now, so
it hurts our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
