<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NEAGLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS SNARE NEAGLE FROM REDS FOR PROSPECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Making a pre-emptive strike for the best pitcher
available, the Yankees shipped a ransom in top prospects to the
Cincinnati Reds for the left-hander Denny Neagle, a two-time
All-Star whose style of pitching suits him perfectly to the
dimensions of Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scrambled to find quality pitching just two weeks
ago, but now their rotation is overstocked with six veteran
starters _ Orlando Hernandez, Roger Clemens, Andy Pettitte, Neagle,
David Cone and Dwight Gooden _ for five spots. Gooden, who pitched
five solid innings against the New York Mets Saturday and seemingly
earned a chance for more starts, will be moved to the bullpen to
work in long relief.
</P>
<P>
   In return for the 31-year-old Neagle, who was 8-2 with a 3.52
ERA for the Reds, the Yankees paid sticker price: Drew Henson, a
power-hitting Class AA third baseman and the quarterback for the
University of Michigan who has not decided whether he will
ultimately play baseball or football professionally; Jackson
Melian, the Yankees' most prominent outfield prospect; the
left-hander Ed Yarnall, who struggled when given opportunities to
establish himself in the rotation; and Brian Reith, a Class A
pitcher. The Yankees also received minor-league outfielder Mike
Frank, a fringe minor-league prospect, as part of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds had been expected to contend for the championship this
season, after acquiring Ken Griffey Jr., but they are far behind
St. Louis in the National League Central. The trade of Neagle,
their ace, signals their intent to retool for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle will be eligible for free agency after this season, but
the Yankees initiated negotiations Wednesday on a long-term deal
with Neagle, who could end up with a contract akin to the
four-year, $36 million agreement recently reached by Minnesota's
Brad Radke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely open-minded to signing,'' said Neagle, who will
join the Yankees Friday and could pitch Saturday or Sunday. ``You'd
be foolish not to entertain offers from the Yankees. Let's put it
this way _ they were definitely on my short list of teams to
entertain offers from after the season.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Barry Meister, Neagle's agent, the Yankees
``indicated they gave up good players and would like Denny long
term. I would expect to have substantive discussions sooner rather
than later.''
</P>
<P>
   Neagle is in the last year of a multi-year deal that pays him
$4.75 million this season. A clause in Neagle's current contract
provides that he will be paid $250,000 in the event he is traded,
and the Yankees will pay that sum.
</P>
<P>
   In less than two weeks, the Yankees have added the slugger David
Justice and Neagle, and although they will seek a veteran to help
fill the void created by Shane Spencer's season-ending knee injury
_ someone like Chad Curtis _ the major part of the midseason
makeover is completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to win this year,'' said Brian Cashman, the
Yankees' general manager. ``We've been careful about maintaining
our farm system, but we're going for it right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had been told repeatedly by the Phillies that Curt
Schilling was not available, and given Schilling's symbolic
importance to the franchise and his relatively low salary of $6.5
million for next year, Yankees' executives never believed that was
going to change. Mike Mussina is a free agent, but he has a
no-trade clause and has told the Orioles flatly he will veto any
proposed deal.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle was the top-rated pitcher on the Yankees' list of
prospective trade targets. About 10 days ago, after Cincinnati lost
a series against St. Louis, the Reds general manager, Jim Bowden,
called Cashman and asked if the Yankees were interested in Neagle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Cashman replied. Bowden dispatched assistants
Bob Boone and Al Goldis to scout the Yankees' farm system and told
Cashman that he would call with names of prospects he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, Henson was again asked if he would be willing to
give up his football career to play baseball, but Yankees'
executives knew he wasn't ready to answer the question. Henson is
set to be the start for Michigan this fall, and it seemed unlikely
he would change his mind after two years of working for that.
Henson indicated, again, that he hadn't made a decision which sport
he wanted to play.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, Bowden called Cashman with the names of the
prospects: Henson and Melian were at the top of his list. The
Yankees paid significant signing bonuses to both, but doubts about
each player have surfaced _ Henson, because he might play football,
and Melian, because of his long swing and propensity for
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees responded quickly, wanting to complete a deal
swiftly, sure in their assessment that Neagle was, far and away,
the best pitcher on the market, knowing that if they haggled and
dragged out negotiations, Bowden would be more likely to look
seriously at other offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you haggle,'' Cashman said Wednesday, ``then you have to be
prepared for the fact that the player is going to go to another
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Cashman and Bowden spoke about a dozen times on Tuesday, and
into Wednesday morning, settling on three prospects _ Henson,
Melian, and Yarnall. With the Reds concerned about Henson's
intentions, the Yankees agreed to give a fourth player, which
turned out to be Reith. The Yankees were in a position to trade
prospects because they never agreed to the Cubs' exceptional
demands for Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden called Cashman at about 10:45 Wednesday morning and
agreed to the trade. The Yankees landed the left-hander they
wanted. And, in doing so, by moving swiftly and agreeing to pay
Cincinnati's demands, they kept him away other potential suitors,
such as the Mets, Arizona Diamondbacks, Chicago White Sox and
Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle is 14-2 since the end of last August, with a career
record of 98-62. He won 16 games in 1996 for Pittsburgh and
Atlanta, 20 games for the Braves in 1997 and 16 games for Atlanta
in 1998. He had some weakness in the muscles of his rotator cuff in
1999 and was limited to only 19 starts, but has rebounded this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle's style is similar to that of Atlanta's Tom Glavine,
mixing a fastball of about 87-89 mph and a breaking ball, and a
phenomenal changeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's going to help them,'' said Bruce Bochy. ``He's got
three great pitches. He's like Glavine, uses his breaking ball a
little bit more, pitches inside with his fastball a little more.
Tony Gwynn said he's one of the two toughest pitchers he's ever
faced, and the other is Randy Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   Neagle generates an extraordinarily high ratio of fly balls,
which means he will fit in well in spacious Yankee Stadium. He
allowed only one run in 7 2/3 innings in his only start in Yankee
Stadium, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lefties have always had great success in that ballpark,''
Neagle said. ``With the deep center field and deep alleys, that's
going to suit me well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
