<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0508 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-BOS &LR;      07-12 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL DROPS PLAN TO SELL RADAR PLANE TO CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES AND CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has canceled
plans to sell a $250 million military radar plane to China,
eliminating a major irritant for Washington and easing the way for
Israel to obtain more US aid to secure a peace agreement with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Wednesday to reporters near Camp David, where US-led
peace talks are under way, Israeli spokesman Gadi Baltiansky said
Barak, in a letter to Chinese President Jiang Zemin, had expressed
his ``sorrow'' for scuttling the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Baltiansky said Barak had informed President Clinton of his
decision at a meeting Tuesday night, and that the move was based on
America's objections to the sale and the desire of Israel to
maintain ``intimate relations with the US.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing US security concerns over the sale, White House Press
Secretary Joseph Lockhart said, ``We welcome the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli announcement came on the second day of a summit at
the mountainous presidential retreat in northern Maryland, where
Clinton is trying to help Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat resolve some of the thorniest issues to confront Mideast
peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hardest issues to resolve are the status of Jerusalem
and ``the right of return'' of some three million Palestinian
refugees. Wednesday, a member of Barak's Cabinet expressed
pessimism in Jerusalem that a deal could be struck at the summit
regarding the city's status.
</P>
<P>
   Haim Ramon, the minister responsible for Jerusalem issues, said
in a briefing to the foreign press corps, ``I assume Jerusalem will
be on the table, and that there will be creative ideas on the
table. . . . But in the end it will be impossible for Israel to
give up full sovereignty. I will be very surprised if we reach an
agreement on Jerusalem now.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``In five to ten years maybe we could have creative
solutions. But both sides are not ready, and their people are not
ready now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon also outlined what he said was Barak's opening proposal on
partitioning the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials conceded the difficulty of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that we went into this knowing it would be a
struggle, we have not been disappointed by that,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   One complicating factor Wednesday was a request from Arafat that
members of the Palestine Liberation Organization's ruling Executive
Committee and ministers in the Palestinian Authority be allowed to
enter Camp David to lend support for his negotiating position with
Israel, according to Palestinian officials. Some of those who
Arafat wants invited in had opposed the 1993 Oslo accord which
paved the way for the summit.
</P>
<P>
   US officials scoffed at the idea, appearing to rule out any
possiblity that Palestinian officials other than those already in
the delegation would be invited or that Arafat would leave the
secluded retreat to meet with them. ``We agreed in advance on the
size of the parties, and those people are at Camp David now, and I
expect those people to stay there through the talks,'' Lockhart
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said US officials had not received a request from
Arafat to expand the delegation.
</P>
<P>
   For the second day in a row, Clinton met individually with
Arafat and Barak, using a stroll through the woods of the retreat
for his talk with the Palestinian leader. The three men and their
delegations also ate dinner together. Tuesday night, the group
dined on tenderloin of beef with sun-dried tomatoes and filet of
salmon with Thai curry sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton slept at Camp David a second night, and was planning to
return to the White House early Thursday. He is scheduled to speak
to the annual convention of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People in Baltimore and also attend a
congressional gold medal ceremony on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   While adhering to a news blackout on the substance of the talks,
Lockhart said Wednesday had been a busy day among all the parties,
adding, ``there's been real engagement.''
</P>
<P>
   At the press briefing in Jerusalem, Ramon detailed the plan for
a compromise on West Bank land that Barak brought with him to the
summit.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon said Barak had developed a formula for the percentages on
land return in the West Bank that he refered to as ``70, 20, 10.''
</P>
<P>
   --Seventy percent of the West Bank would come under full
Palestinian control. Currently, the Palestinian Authority has full
or partial control over 40 percent. The additional land would give
the Palestinian Authority a large area that is contiguous, and
closer to the parameters of a viable state. The Palestinian
Authority currently controls an archipelago of enclaves scattered
througout the chalky, terraced hills of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   --Twenty percent of the West Bank would fall under shared
control, with the Palestinians having administrative responsibility
and the Israelis having security control. Much of this land would
eventually be transferred to full Palestinian control provided
security guarantees were established.
</P>
<P>
   --Ten percent of the West Bank around the core blocks of Jewish
settlements, the Jordan River Valley, and military installations
would be annexed by Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Barak came back with something close to this, we would be
very happy,'' Ramon said.
</P>
<P>
   But this proposal for ceding West Bank land to Palestinians
still falls short of the Palestinian demand that Israel withdraw
from all of the West Bank and East Jerusalem, territory it captured
from Jordan in the 1967 Six-Day War.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians insist that the historic peace accord signed on
the White House Lawn more than six years ago was established within
the framework of Israel complying with UN Resolution 242, which
calls for Israeli withdrawl from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts, however, both Palestinian and Israeli, see the
two sides emerging from the summit with the broad parameters of an
agreement on borders.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts in the United States, meanwhile, said Israel's decision
to call off its sale of the advanced Phalcon airborne radar system
to China, as the administration and members of Congress have been
been insisting it do, would help its cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``It greases the skids a bit by removing what has really become
an obstacle,'' said Geoffrey Aronson, head of the foundation for
Middle East Peace. ``Assuming there is some sort of positive
outcome at Camp David, then when the day comes that Congess has to
consider a request for what will be called a peace package, they
will be more likely to approve it and less antagonzied over the
whole issue of Israeli arms sales to China,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, Baltiansky, Barak's spokesman, appeared to leave the door
open on some future sales. ``Israel will continue to look for ways
to implement the deal in understanding with the US if the
circumstances change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Scales reported from Thurmont and Sennott from Jerusalem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
