<HEADER>
A0509 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-MCCOY-COLUMN0713-     07-12 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCCOY-COLUMN0713-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Neagle trade called a business decision
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Jim Bowden pulled the plug on the Cincinnati Reds
for 2000. The patient, barely breathing as it was, officially
expired at 1:02 p.m. Wednesday when the general manager announced
the trade of No. 1 pitcher Denny Neagle to the New York Yankees for
four minor-league prospects, none of whom is ready to make a
contribution this year.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Bowden didn't try to put a positive spin on the
transaction, volunteering that when you trade your pitching ace you
are conceding, tossing in the rosin bag. It was business, he said,
big business.
</P>
<P>
   Just three days ago, Bowden coaxed Junior Griffey out of playing
in the All-Star game to rest a sore right knee and said, ``We want
him strong and ready for the second half run. We are only eight
games behind in our division and 4 1/2 behind in the wild-card.''
</P>
<P>
   What changed?
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said the Reds offered Neagle a three-year contract for
$18 million. Neagle, realizing he will get at least $18 million for
two years on the free agent market, didn't respond, other than to
tell Bowden he has never tested free agency and wanted to do it
after this season. Faced with losing Neagle without compensation,
Bowden chose to trade him for four young players who might make an
impact when the club moves into a new ballpark in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Why now? Why not wait until closer to the July 31 trade
deadline, when the Reds might be closer to the lead? Bowden said he
feared the Yankees might go elsewhere for a pitcher and yank their
offer off the table and he wanted the best he could get for Neagle,
who was 8-2 for the Reds this season and owns a 98-62 major-league
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we traded our No. 1 starter and we're hurting our
chances to win now and we know this,'' Bowden said. ``We're staying
with our goal of 2003, a championship club when we open the new
park. In order to do that, we have to make deals like this. I know
this deal with be unpopular, but the White Sox took a lot of grief
when they made a similar-type trade two years ago, but in the end,
that's how you win, by stockpiling young players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it definitely hurts our chances of winning now,'' Bowden
added. ``We all know that. He was our No. 1 starter and won't be
out there the rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden also conceded that one of the four players obtained for
Neagle is a major risk. Third baseman Drew Henson plays football
(quarterback) at the University of Michigan, starts his junior
season this fall, and is a threat to play pro football rather than
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden also said media and fans shouldn't assume that because
Neagle is gone there is more money to give shortstop Barry Larkin.
That isn't the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are totally separate issues,'' he said. ``We're not
letting one go to use money for the other. That's totally
unrelated. It is not done that way. We have to sign players for
numbers that work for us. You win with starting pitching, bottom
line. Denny Neagle is a pitcher we wanted to sign. We felt he would
negotiate off our offer, but he never gave us that chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden cited Minnesota signing pitcher Brad Radke to a four-year
$36 million deal, ``So I certainly don't blame Denny Neagle for
wanting to go see what he can get. When he told us he would not
sign, we felt we had no alternative but to make the best deal we
could.''
</P>
<P>
   Why so early?
</P>
<P>
   ``We had seven teams who were after Denny, so we did a lot of
scouting and research of their farm systems,'' Bowden said. ``There
was not a deal out there that was close to the Yankees and we
didn't want to get in a situation two weeks from now when the
Yankees offer might not be there, that they might go in a different
direction, and we couldn't get this much talent from other
organizations. So we made the best deal we possibly could.''
</P>
<P>
   Neagle was scheduled to pitch tonight in Denver against the
Rockies, which sends manager Jack McKeon and pitching coach Don
Gullett scrambling. Either a well-rested Steve Parris will step in
or Ron Villone, exiled to the bullpen last week, re-emerges into
the rotation. Bowden admits that when he traded Neagle he had no
contingencies for a rotation replacement.
</P>
<P>
   McKeon, bless his optimistic heart, refuses any unconditional
surrender terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now? No problem,'' he says. ``We'll put Villone back
into the rotation. No question, though, we have to get a pitcher or
two somewhere soon. Throw in the towel? I don't know about that.
They said that when we traded Dave Burba, our scheduled Opening Day
pitcher, in 1998. We just need somebody to step up. It's a golden
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   More like platinum.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
