</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-U.S.-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND VIETNAM REACH ACCORD ON TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States and Vietnam have completed a
sweeping trade agreement that would allow generally unfettered
commerce between the two nations for the first time since the end
of the Vietnam War more than a quarter-century ago, people involved
in the negotiations said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnamese and American officials reached the agreement in
Washington this week after nearly four years of fitful negotiations
and after Vietnam walked away from a deal last year that the
Clinton administration had considered sealed. The agreement was
expected to be signed and formally announced later this week or
early next week, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Vietnam and the United States restored full diplomatic
ties in 1995, it has been s cold peace commercially. The two
nations have miniscule trade flows of less than $1 billion. America
ranks ninth among foreign investors there despite an initial flurry
of interest in the Vietnamese market.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of major American multinational corporations,
including Cargill, Caterpillar and Nike, have invested in Vietnam.
Some independent economic analysts expect that companies like Nike
would immediately add thousands of jobs in Vietnam if American
tariffs of Vietnamese-produced goods are substantially lowered.
Vietnam's industrious but low-wage workers could begin producing in
bulk for the American market as workers in China do today.
</P>
<P>
   The trade agreement would also open Vietnam's market of 77
million people to a wide range of American companies as never
before, though it would not immediately eliminate the bureaucratic
inertia that has made that market impenetrable for all but the most
resilient foreign multinationals.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts also see the agreement as an indication that
Vietnam's top leaders are willing to push the economic reforms
started in the 1980s to a new level, perhaps because neighboring
China has accelerated its economic overhaul in preparation to join
the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The accord, if signed as scheduled, would allow President
Clinton to claim yet another milestone in trade liberalization
shortly after the House granted China permanent normal trading
rights, another of the administration's final remaining foreign
policy priorities. The Senate has yet to vote on the China trade
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Several people involved in negotiating the Vietnam agreement
said that it is likely to be signed this week if Clinton is able to
return from Camp David, where he is brokering peace talks between
Israeli and Palestinian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But Congress would still have to approve the agreement and
extend normal trade privileges to Vietnam, a vote that some
administration official believe is unlikely this election year.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement would require sharp reductions in U.S. tariffs on
sensitive Vietnamese goods _ like textiles, shoes and electronics _
a concession that labor unions have often fought bitterly against
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Some 58,000 American soldiers died and 2,000 are still listed as
missing in action in Vietnam from the war years, and anti-Vietnam
sentiment among some veteran groups and members of Congress still
runs strong, especially because the Hanoi government has not
embarked on substantial political change.
</P>
<P>
   But few expect strong resistance to the pact in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this should be viewed as a sign that they are
undertaking serious economic and political reform there, and that's
something we have to be in favor of,'' Sen. John McCain, the
Arizona Republican who was a prisoner of war in Vietnam, said on
Wednesday ``There's some negative sentiment left over, but I think
Congress would be happy to pass this.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement would grant Vietnam the same trading rights here
that most other nations have, including reductions of up to 90
percent in tariffs levied on Vietnamese exports. That would make
Vietnam a far more attractive place for manufacturing companies,
which have invested much less in Vietnam than in China and
Southeast Asian nations that have broader trading rights in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   American companies, in turn, could crack open areas that are
essentially off limits in Vietnam today, including
telecommunications, financial services, retail and distribution,
people involved in the talks said. Vietnam would also agree to
protect foreign intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials declined to release details of the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This trade agreement is absolutely necessary if Vietnam wants
to be connected to a globalized world,'' said Thomas Vallely, an
expert on the country at Harvard's Kennedy School of Government.
``It's just a huge problem for them to remain basically cut off for
the world's biggest economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was reached in principle after talks between U.S.
Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky and Vietnam's trade
minister, Vu Khoan.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam is expected to make use of the momentum created by the
deal to push for membership in the World Trade Organization. But
many analysts expect that process will still take several years.
</P>
<P>
   The people involved in the bilateral talks warned that there
could still be glitches before a final trade deal is signed.
</P>
<P>
   They said that translating trade language _ including some
seemingly straightforward financial terms like equity _ has proven
a stumbling block in the past, with Vietnamese negotiators agreeing
to the phrases in English but objecting to them when expressed in
their native language.
</P>
<P>
   A similar pact was initialed by trade negotiators last November
but then came to a dead stop after Communist leaders in Hanoi
apparently had second thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that while the Vietnamese government generally
support trade liberalization, some elements of the Communist party
and powerful leaders of state-run industries, combined with a
lingering distrust of the United States, have kept Vietnam several
steps behind China in adapting to capitalist ways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
