u i BC-MEXICO-LOBBYING-NYT &LR;      07-12 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-LOBBYING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS MEXICAN GOVERNMENT CHANGES HANDS, SO MAY ITS LOBBYING CONTRACTS
IN U.S.  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his office in Mexico City, Vicente Fox, Mexico's
president-elect, has already received a lot of callers from K
Street, Washington's corridor of political influence.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of law firms, lobbying groups and public relations firms
are preparing their pitches for the new government's business in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican government spends millions of dollars annually to
lobby the executive branch and Congress on trade, immigration, law
enforcement and other issues and to burnish Mexico's image in the
United States. But Fox, who is to be inaugurated in December, is
likely to pick a new team of Washington lobbyists to press the
political agenda of Mexico's new governing party, the National
Action Party, known by the Spanish acronym PAN.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably some of the lobbyists who have worked with the old
government will be cut,'' said Carlos Salazar, a foreign-policy
adviser to Fox. ``This is very natural.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be bad news for a number of firms in Washington with
six-figure retainers from Mexico's current government, controlled
by the long-governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as
PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Although it does not employ as many Washington lobbyists as
Japan or Hong Kong, Mexico has become one of the most prized
foreign government accounts since 1993, when it assembled a $20
million armada of law, lobbying and public relations firms to help
pass the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Mexico has pared its team to about a dozen
firms, including Public Strategies Inc., whose president, Joseph P.
O'Neill, was a lead lobbyist for Mexico on NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   In the last six months, the government of outgoing President
Ernesto Zedillo has paid over half a million dollars spread over
various firms for lobbying on trade, immigration, and law
enforcement issues, according to reports filed with the Justice
Department by the lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Public Strategies, the list of lobbyists registered as
foreign agents to represent Mexico's interests includes two
high-powered Democratic law firms, Manatt Phelps &AMP; Phillips, and
Verner, Liipfert, Berhard, McPherson &AMP; Hand. Manatt Phelps is
headed by former Democratic National Committee chairman Charles
Manatt, and Verner, Liipfert employs many prominent Democrats,
including former Senate Democratic leader George Mitchell, although
former Senate Republican leader Bob Dole is also a member of the
firm. The Mexican government also retains the law firm Shearman &AMP;
Sterling.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is not well known in Washington and has not yet established
ties on K Street. This week a small group of Fox's international
advisers, including Salazar, has been visiting Washington for a
three-day visit. The trip was packed with one on one meetings with
senators, congressmen and political scientists from local think
tanks, but Salazar did not leave any time for lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, definitely not,'' said Salazar.
</P>
<P>
   Since September, Salazar has made other goodwill trips here
because leading PAN officials believed the agenda and image of
their party was misrepresented in the United States by the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   In that time, he has never met with lobbyists to discuss the
possibility of new accounts with the PAN or the renewal of existing
accounts at firms, which have ties to the current government.
</P>
<P>
   During the election, Fox relied on some U.S. political advisers,
including Dick Morris, President Clinton's veteran political
adviser. That work is done, but Morris said of Fox, paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's anything he asked me to do, I certainly would do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fox government may decide to wait until after the U.S.
elections in November to replace its line-up of lobbyists. If the
Republicans win the presidency, Fox might want to retain firms with
more prominent Republicans. One thing is certain, he will not have
to look hard to find eager prospects for his business.
</P>
<P>
   The former U.S. ambassador to Mexico, Jim Jones, who is now a
consultant at Manatt, Phelps and Phillips and has been advising Fox
on the presidential transition, said that several prominent
lobbying firms have already flown to Mexico to court Fox as a
client.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
