<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA: EUROPEAN PANEL PICKED
</P>
<P>
   The European Court of Human Rights in Strasbourg named three men
to a panel that will study Austria's human rights record and the
political nature of Joerg Haider's far-right Freedom Party. They
are former President Martti Ahtisaari of Finland; a former foreign
minister of Spain, Marcelino Oreja; and a German professor, Jochen
Frowein, director of the Max-Planck Institute. Their review could
lead to an end to Austria's political isolation within the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: SPEAKER TO QUIT
</P>
<P>
   Betty Boothroyd, the first woman to be Speaker of the House of
Commons, whose cries of ``Order! Order!'' are familiar to
television viewers in Britain and abroad, announced that she will
retire this fall. Boothroyd, 70, a Labor Party lawmaker since 1973
and Speaker since 1992, said ``Be happy for me!'' in response to
groans of disappointment. She received a round of applause, rarely
heard in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: PROTESTANT CONFESSION
</P>
<P>
   The Protestant church admitted it used forced laborers in World
War II and said it would pay $4.9 million to a $4.9 billion
compensation fund for Nazi-era victims. The acknowledgment came
after disclosures that from 1943 to 1945, 26 Protestant and 2
Catholic parishes in Berlin ran a camp for about 100 forced
laborers from eastern Europe and Russia for work in graveyards. A
Catholic spokesman said the church had no plans to contribute to
the fund.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE: GERMAN PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Germany lodged a protest with Greece as bailiffs, guarded by the
police, moved to assess the value of German property in Athens to
be seized and sold in compensation for the massacre of 218 Greek
villagers by Nazi forces in 1944. The properties include the Goethe
Institute. The Supreme Court sanctioned the move in an April ruling
awarding $30 million to the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE: ANTITERROR MESSAGE
</P>
<P>
   Greek television broadcast a message against terrorism at noon
as lawmakers and civil servants held a minute's silence in tribute
to terrorist victims. The message, reading ``Terrorism is an insult
to Greeks, and a threat to Greece,'' comes a month after the
assassination of Brig. Stephen Saunders, Britain's top military
envoy to Athens.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: MADRID BOMB HURTS NINE
</P>
<P>
   Suspected Basque rebels set off a car bomb in central Madrid,
injuring nine people. Callers saying they were from the Basque
separatist group ETA warned authorities the bomb was to go off in
30 minutes, but it exploded after 15 minutes, leading officials to
believe the police clearing the area were the intended target.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: ABORTION ALERT
</P>
<P>
   The police have warned abortion providers to be on alert after a
man entered the office of a Vancouver gynecologist who performs
abortions and stabbed him in the back. Dr. Garson Romalis was
hospitalized after he was attacked by a young man in his 20's whose
face was obscured by a black sweatshirt hood. In 1994 a sniper shot
and wounded Romalis at his home.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: GUERRILLAS STAY JAILED
</P>
<P>
   A Tel Aviv court ruled two Lebanese guerrillas abducted and held
for years as bargaining chips for a missing Israeli airman should
remain in jail for three more months, until the case is decided.
The court accepted government arguments that Sheik Abdel Karim
Obeid of Hezbollah and Mustafa Dirani of the Amal movement were a
security threat. The state raised the security issue after the
Supreme Court ruled prisoners could not be held as bargaining
chips.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: POLITICAL MERGING
</P>
<P>
   A month after the two leading white political parties announced
plans to merge, officials from the Inkatha Freedom Party, the
country's second largest black political party, said they would
consider merging with the governing party, the African National
Congress. No formal decisions have been made yet. But the suggested
merger comes as parties position themselves for local elections,
scheduled for November.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS
</P>
<P>
   U.S. PAYS DUES
</P>
<P>
   The United States paid some of its back dues to peacekeeping
operations, including $40 million for Kosovo and $53 million for
East Timor. By international agreement, Washington is billed 31
percent for every peacekeeping mission, but Congress has ruled that
25 percent is the limit, and arrears continue to build. United
Nations accounts show the United States debt totals $1.65 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: COHEN VISITS
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen met China's vice president,
defense minister and senior military leaders in the first of three
days of talks. Cohen had a friendly reception, reflecting China's
desire to patch up relations with the United States, though it
expressed vehement opposition to Washington's proposed national
missile defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
