<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0520 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BRAVES0713-COX     07-12 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES0713-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On top, but not looking invincible
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ To comprehend baseball's power epidemic, look no
further than the Braves' midseason acquisition of right-hander Andy
Ashby.
</P>
<P>
   Others teams have blamed shrinking ballparks, the batters'
expanding biceps, the microscopic strike zone and an enigmatic
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves knew they needed pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-eight games into the 2000 season, the always
pitching-strong Braves had been exposed as weaklings. Despite the
best record in the National League, they were fortunate to have a
three-game lead in the East.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are counting on Ashby, a two-time All-Star with a
career record of 76-81, to shore up a starting rotation that has
struggled. Not even All-Star first halves by Greg Maddux and Tom
Glavine and a better-than-could-be expected contribution from John
Burkett could make up for the fact that ``The Untouchables'' just
aren't anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Big Three'' used to refer to Maddux, Glavine and John
Smoltz. At the moment, it could be used to describe the earned-run
averages of starters Kevin Millwood (5.34), Terry Mulholland (5.71)
and Burkett (5.05).
</P>
<P>
   At the break, the Braves' ERA of 4.31 is third in the majors,
behind Boston (4.19) and Arizona (4.21). Not since 1990 (4.58), the
year before their postseason streak started, have the Braves
finished a season with a staff ERA higher than 3.63.
</P>
<P>
   That team ERA shows the absence of Smoltz, a pitcher known best
for his October feats. The Braves are missing the 14 wins and 214
innings he averages a season. With Smoltz gone, Mulholland has to
start, which has contributed to the disarray in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, the Braves used 15 different pitchers in
relief. Included were two starters, Burkett and Mulholland; two
21-year-olds, Jason Marquis and Luis Rivera; two players turned
loose by other teams at the end of spring training, Greg McMichael
and Scott Kamieniecki; the best a losing AAA Richmond team had to
offer, Don Wengert, Dave Stevens and Ismael Villegas; one elbow
surgery survivor, Kerry Ligtenberg; and John Rocker, who, in
addition to his other problems, is fighting the worst control
problems the Braves have seen since Mark Wohlers.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux (hurt by a batting-practice flyball to the shoulder) and
Mike Remlinger (reaction to dye injection from an MRI) have had
freak injuries recently, to go along with the shoulder problems of
Luis Rivera, McMichael and Kevin McGlinchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken some unfair criticism this year,'' Glavine said,
``because you take Smoltz and (Rudy) Seanez and Rem out of the
equation, (and,) my god, what do you expect?''
</P>
<P>
   The surprise has been Millwood's problems. The 25-year-old, who
last year made his first All-Star team and contended for the Cy
Young Award contention, has rivaled Mulholland as the least
consistent starter. In his first two full seasons, he won 17 and 18
games; at the break this year, he has five. His eight losses
matched Mulholland for the most on the staff.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood and new outfielder Reggie Sanders _ .179 batting
average, 4 homers and 13 RBIs _ have been the biggest
disappointments so far.
</P>
<P>
   In April, however, the Braves went on the biggest run in
franchise history to win 15 games in a row, the most in the
National League in 51 years. Since then, however, the record has
been just 32-30.
</P>
<P>
   Over the first six weeks of the season, the Braves went 20-4
when scoring four runs or more. Over the next six weeks, they were
24-9 in those games. The Braves have gone from 18-6 in April and
17-10 in May to 13-15 in June and 4-5 in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very fortunate to be up (three) games,'' 1999 MVP
Chipper Jones said. ``The team that won 15 games in a row, this
team hasn't resembled that team in quite some time.''
</P>
<P>
   The toughest part of the Braves' schedule is still to come. They
have not played the other division leaders, the St. Louis Cardinals
and the Arizona Diamondbacks. They have played just four of the
scheduled 13 games against the Mets and have gone 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``As badly as we've played, in our minds or by our own
expectations, nobody else in our league has really taken advantage
of it,'' Glavine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottom line, to still look up and find you're in first place
is a big boost mentally. We're not dominating the pitching side of
things the way we have in the past, but to me, man for man, we're
still better than a lot of teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
