u f BC-PAINEWEBER-MARKETPLAC     07-12 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAINEWEBER-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: BROKERAGE HOUSES THRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also UBS-IMPACT) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Only a year ago, it seemed, the future of the
traditional brokerage firm was in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks of unprofitable, upstart electronic brokers had soared
while those of some Wall Street titans were sagging. Predictions of
the demise of the stockbroker ran rampant as investors flocked to
the Internet, attracted by cheap trades and the ability to control
their financial destinies.
</P>
<P>
   But, judging by the announcement on Wednesday that UBS, the
Swiss banking giant, will pay about $12 billion to buy PaineWebber
Group, the traditional brokerage firm is not dead yet _ far from
it. At a purchase price of $73.50 a share, UBS is paying a premium
of 47 percent over PaineWebber's closing price on Tuesday, before
the deal was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Although some analysts said they thought UBS was paying too
much, most agreed that PaineWebber's network of brokers who cater
to investors with at least $500,000 in assets is a franchise that
has proved far more valuable than its critics ever acknowledged
through most of the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   PaineWebber has capitalized on the shift away from traditional
pensions toward more reliance on individual retirement accounts,
401(k)s and the like, said Donald B. Marron, the company's chairman
and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've created a nation of individual pension fund managers _
50 million of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The firm earned more than $1 billion before taxes last year,
more than triple its pretax profit in 1995. Its momentum has slowed
recently. On Wednesday, PaineWebber announced second-quarter
earnings that were down 10 percent from a year ago before a charge
for expenses related to the firm's $620 million acquisition of
brokerage firm J.C. Bradford &AMP; Co. Including the charge,
PaineWebber earned $127.5 million, or 82 cents a share, down from
$163.5 million, or $1.02 a share, in the second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Still, its success is a direct result of its ability to persuade
wealthy investors to pay for advice on what they should do with
their money. Most of those clients could save several thousands
dollars a year by managing their money themselves through an
account at ETrade or Charles Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   But Marron has never wavered in his belief that they would not.
He has long preached the value of personal advice and has staunchly
refused to compete on price with the wave of discounters that shook
up the business over the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of PaineWebber came about six months after Schwab
acknowledged the importance of offering advice to wealthy investors
by agreeing to pay $2.7 billion to buy U.S. Trust, a New York-based
firm that manages private money in much the same way as UBS does in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Deals like that one demonstrate that ``You've got to keep moving
upstream,'' said Richard Strauss, an analyst at Goldman Sachs
Group. To gauge the threat posed to traditional brokerage firms by
the electronic challengers, he said, ``All you have to do is look
at where the pure e-brokerage stocks are trading today.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of ETrade are at $16.50, more than 70 percent below where
they were trading in May 1999. Meanwhile, shares of Merrill Lynch &AMP;
Co. closed on Wednesday at an all-time high of $131.5625.
</P>
<P>
   While turmoil in the market, particularly big plunges in some
technology stocks popular among individual investors, contributed
to the reversal, this turnaround did not happen automatically.
PaineWebber, along with its three bigger rivals, Merrill Lynch,
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and Salomon Smith Barney, all moved last
year to offer online trading. Even more important, they repriced
their basic brokerage accounts to narrow the cost gap between
themselves and the discounters.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than appearing endangered, stock brokers are in demand.
All of the major United States brokerage firms say they will
continue to expand their ranks of brokers and some analysts expect
PaineWebber's competitors to use the takeover as a reason to step
up efforts to lure brokers from other firms.
</P>
<P>
   The competition for established brokers with rosters of clients
is intense, and most firms offer brokers big cash bonuses to defect
and bring their customers' accounts with them. Those tussles often
wind up in court as the firms scramble to court the customers.
</P>
<P>
   An undisclosed part of the $875 million UBS set aside to retain
PaineWebber employees is earmarked for brokers. But holding on to
its best brokers will be a challenge for PaineWebber because they
tend to fear change and many of them will be cashing in restricted
stock and options that they would have lost if they had left the
firm before a buyout.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, Marron and Ospel played down the likelihood of a
clash of cultures when UBS takes control of the brokers in what
would be the first direct acquisition of a major United States
brokerage firm by a foreign company.
</P>
<P>
   He and other UBS executives and their financial advisers talked
up the potential increase in revenue from selling stocks and bonds
and other investment products created by UBS's investment banking
operations to PaineWebber customers. But that strategy runs the
risk that the harder UBS pushes its own products, the more it
threatens to alienate brokers and their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts argue that PaineWebber's success derives in part
from an image of giving generally unbiased advice because its
investment banking side _ where deals are struck and new companies
are taken public _ has never mounted much of a threat to its
competitors on Wall Street. Moreover, while PaineWebber has built a
strong asset management business, known as Mitchell Hutchins, the
firm's own mutual funds account for only about a quarter of the
funds sold by its brokers. In contrast, about three-fourths of the
funds sold by Morgan Stanley's Dean Witter brokerage unit are its
own.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of PaineWebber and UBS took pains to emphasize that
PaineWebber's management would remain in place and only the
investment banking operations of PaineWebber would be merged into
UBS. Even then, they said, the number of job losses would be
minimal because there is so little overlap between the two firms'
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Mr, Marron, 65, said he would stay on as chairman of
PaineWebber, which will keep its name as the brokerage unit of UBS,
and will take on the new title of chairman of UBS North America. He
said he also would spend more time on investments in private
companies and would retain responsibility for the impressive
collection of modern art that PaineWebber has accumulated during
his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Grano, PaineWebber's president, will run the brokerage
and money-management units of the combined companies in the United
States. Yesterday, Grano said that he did not intend to change the
firm's strategy of targeting what it calls the ``core affluent''
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he said, 7 percent of the households in the United
States controlled about two-thirds of the nation's investment
assets, or about $12.5 trillion. By 2003, he predicted, that group
will grow to include 11 percent of households that will control 78
percent of the assets, or about $24.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the sweet spot of PaineWebber,'' Grano said. ``That is
where we have focused our efforts more than any other place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
