<HEADER>
A0525 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DEBEERS-DIAMONDS-ART-     07-12 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBEERS-DIAMONDS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE BEERS PLANS TO STOP HOARDING DIAMONDS AND STEP UP ADVERTISING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   De Beers Consolidated Mines, the diamond company that reigned as
one of the most powerful monopolies of the 20th century, announced
Wednesday in London a seismic shift in the way it does business.
</P>
<P>
   It will retreat from its 70-year-old practice of manipulating
prices by hoarding the world's diamonds and charge into the
advertising-driven game of selling the stones as branded luxuries.
</P>
<P>
   The strategic overhaul, analysts say, is driven by the anemic
performance of De Beers stock in recent years and by public
relations fears that ``conflict diamonds'' from Africa are
poisoning a carefully nurtured image of De Beers stones as symbols
of ``love, beauty and purity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all need to become more customer-focused and recognize the
power of marketing to sell more diamonds,'' Nicky Oppenheimer, the
company chairman, said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
   De Beers, which was created 110 years ago in South Africa,
controls two-thirds of the trade in uncut diamonds and owns mines
around the world that produce about half the stones unearthed each
year.
</P>
<P>
   It has been embarrassed by disclosures that to prop up prices,
it bought millions of dollars of diamonds from rebels in Angola.
</P>
<P>
   The company has insisted that it bought the stones on the open
market and stopped all buying when a U.N. embargo was imposed in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   In London on Wednesday, De Beers made the most far-reaching of a
series of moves to back away from trading in diamonds mined by
African rebels who brutalize civilians. The company warned its 125
major trading partners that they would be barred from buying De
Beers diamonds if they trafficked in stones that originated in war
zones.
</P>
<P>
   ``De Beers is sending a clear signal to the rest of the industry
that it is no longer tolerable to profit from these diamonds,''
said Christine Gordon, a diamond industry analyst in London who
serves on a panel monitoring the U. N. embargo.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Security Council imposed a global ban this month on
diamond exports from Sierra Leone, where the stones have fueled a
savage rebel war. There are no sanctions, however, on stones from
Congo, where the scramble for diamonds helps sustain a war among
rebels, the government and armies from six African countries.
</P>
<P>
   While De Beers' move will further reduce the chances that
rebel-mined diamonds will trickle into American jewelry stores,
Gordon said there remained a large network of dealers who are not
beholden to De Beers. In addition, human rights groups are
skeptical about De Beers' ability to enforce its new rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one thing to announce all these changes, but it is
another thing to make it stick,'' said Ian Smillie, co-author of a
scathing report this year about how the diamond industry supplied
the money that made war possible in Sierra Leone. ``There are quite
a lot of diamonds coming from these areas, and somebody is going to
lose money if they stop dealing with the rebels.''
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch called the De Beers move ``an important
announcement,'' but said more remained to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental issue is verification,'' said Carroll Bogert,
a spokeswoman in New York for the group, which has closely
monitored the trade in rebel-mined diamonds. ``Unless you have an
independent monitoring mechanism, I think questions will remain.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of its shift in business strategy, De Beers executives
said the company would reduce its stockpile of uncut diamonds in
London from $3.9 billion to about $2.5 billion by the end of next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last seven decades, De Beers has used that stockpile _
which as recently as last year was valued at $5.2 billion _ as a
way to absorb excess diamonds from Africa, Russia or around the
world that might lower the cartel price of diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   With the money earned by selling off much of the stockpile, De
Beers officials said, they will expand spending on diamond
advertising, while insisting that the company's trading partners do
the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge untapped opportunity for all of us in the
industry to grow the diamond business and match the growth rates
enjoyed by leading luxury goods companies,'' said Gary Ralfe,
managing director of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Although diamond sales have soared in the last year, De Beers'
profitability has not. Much of the reason, company officials have
said, is that too much capital is tied up in the diamond stockpile.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond sales have grown far less robustly over the last 50
years than sales of other luxury goods. By reducing the stockpile
and increasing advertising, De Beers executives have said, they
hope to experience the sales growth of items like Gucci handbags.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
