u w BC-CONGRESS-DRUGS-NYT &LR;      07-12 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSAL ON PRESCRIPTION DRUGS GETS MIXED RECEPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Republicans carped Wednesday at a proposal
from one of their own, William Roth of Delaware, to add
prescription drug benefits to Medicare. But they praised him for
making the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Roth, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, is trying to
narrow the gap between Democrats and Republicans on the issue in an
election year. Under his proposal, the government would offer drug
coverage to all 39 million Medicare beneficiaries, but if they
accepted the offer, they would have to pay more for some services,
like home health care.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Senate Democrats greeted Roth's proposal
with some optimism. Conservative Republicans showed little
enthusiasm for the proposal, but were circumspect in their
comments. They said they feared that the cost of prescription drug
benefits would soar, and they said Congress should not rush to pass
legislation just to appease voters.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, a member of the Finance Committee,
expressed grave reservations about Roth's proposal, saying the
costs to the government ``could explode on us overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign for Medicare drug benefits may look unstoppable,
Gramm said in an interview, but he declared: ``The politics of this
issue are not as sweet as Bill Clinton thinks. There is not going
to be a major expansion of Medicare this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm suggested that Congress simply give money to the states _
$20 billion over the next five years _ so they could help
low-income people buy prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., the assistant majority leader,
expressed concern about the long-term cost of Roth's proposal. Many
beneficiaries need drug coverage, he said, but Congress should not
try to solve the problem by creating ``a big expensive program.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Majority Leader Trent Lott appeared ready to
let the Finance Committee work its will. Lott said the committee
had ``a green light'' to write legislation offering drug benefits
to elderly and disabled people on Medicare. Without endorsing the
details of Roth's plan, he said he hoped the full Senate would
address the issue later this year.
</P>
<P>
   A bill passed last month by the House would give subsidies to
insurance companies that provide drug benefits to people on
Medicare. Under Roth's proposal, the government would administer
drug benefits and bear the financial risk.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton welcomed Roth's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased that there is growing momentum on Capitol Hill to
provide a real Medicare prescription drug benefit, not a flawed
insurance model,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the White House press secretary, went further,
describing Roth's proposal as ``a sharp repudiation of what the
House Republicans proposed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Breaux, D-La., said Republicans ``appeared to be
astounded'' at Roth's proposal. ``It's unique,'' Breaux said of the
proposal. ``It has opposition from Democrats and Republicans
both.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans said they needed more details before they could
comment on the proposal. They did not embrace or reject it, but
said it might come in handy later this year if they saw a political
imperative to address demands from elderly voters clamoring for
relief from high drug costs.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic senators voiced other concerns, saying they worry
that elderly people with low incomes will not receive enough help
in drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   And they said the government should spend more than the $40
billion proposed by Roth for drug benefits over the next five
years. They also generally oppose Roth's proposal to make
beneficiaries who choose drug benefits _ those who select his
so-called high-option alternative _ pay 20 percent of the cost of
home health care visits.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D., said, ``I have a serious problem with
forcing seniors who need prescription drugs to leave Medicare as we
know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., told colleagues that the proposal
would create a two-tier system in which affluent beneficiaries
chose the high-option plan.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Bryan, D-Nev., expressed concern that under Roth's
proposal, people with very high drug costs would still have to pay
a substantial share of the costs, perhaps 20 percent. By contrast,
under many Democratic proposals, the government would pick up 100
percent of drug costs above some level, perhaps $4,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these concerns, senators of both parties, including
Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York, the senior Democrat on the
Finance Committee, welcomed Roth's effort. They said it could be a
vehicle for further action if the Finance Committee proceeds to
debate and vote on the issue later this month, as Roth wants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
