<SLUG> BC-FBC-JOYCE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOYCE'S PRIMARY GOAL: GET HEALTHY FOR UCLA SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cody Joyce sat in the New York New York Hotel in
Las Vegas and watched ``Michael Flatley's Lord of the Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated it,'' he said. ``Absolutely terrible. I was bored
after 10 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet through his suffering, he nonetheless saw the dancers moving
their legs quickly and thought of his knee and how he can't move
like that.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce, a UCLA junior receiver from Hart High of Newhall, had
arthroscopic surgery four months ago _ and no one knows exactly
what's wrong with his knee. It appears regular stress has affected
it, that and surgery revealed scar tissue and dead tissue around
his patella tendon. However, it's not as definite as a torn
anterior cruciate ligament.
</P>
<P>
   The injury follows an infected blister on a toe, which followed
the flu, which followed a hamstring injury, which together have
limited Joyce to just four catches for 56 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like to see him be successful,'' his receivers coach,
Ron Caragher, said. ``I don't see how the injuries can continue.''
</P>
<P>
   On the phone, Joyce sounds happy, laughing at his misfortunes.
He tries to stay positive.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates say he constantly smiles and says things are going to
work out. Yet it's not funny when he enters the UCLA locker room
and sees the countdown to the Bruins' Sept. 2 opener against
Alabama on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   He's 28 days away from the Aug. 10 start of fall camp and 51
days from Alabama and declares himself just 70 percent healed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knees are frustrating,'' he said. ``You've got good days and
bad days. If I push it hard for a day, it swells up and I have to
lay off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm basically happy-go-lucky. I dwell on the positive things,
but every once in a while, I get depressed for a day. I know if I
don't make in in camp, chances are I won't play.''
</P>
<P>
   He has healed enough to start running patterns with other
receivers and he has started lifting weights again. Jerry Owens,
his teammate at Hart and UCLA, himself rehabbing a hamstring pull,
sees Joyce at practice and knows he's frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being an athlete, deep down inside you want to get out
there,'' Owens said. ``He didn't come to UCLA to sit on the bench.
. . . I ask him about it occasionally. Guys don't like to talk
about it. I don't bring it up too often.''
</P>
<P>
   The question of quitting doesn't come up. Although Joyce
realizes perhaps rest is the only cure, he wants to play and
doesn't want this injury to get the best of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't going to beat me,'' he said. ``I have too much fun
playing with the guys. I won't rest until after my career's over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the playbook very well. The only issue is to get
healthy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 2125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0530 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-ART-ANDLIFE-2800(2ndT     07-12 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-ANDLIFE-2800(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTIST LIVES FOR THE BEAUTY HE ONCE TRIED TO IGNORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas: hours a day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not to say that I've been saintlike in my
self-appraisal and honesty,'' Grant says. ``But in this core issue,
this was essential to me. That's the one thing that I've been true
to. I'm willing to do anything to make it possible for my paintings
to exist.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of his first mature paintings was of a nude young man,
facing a wall in shadow with a rope around his neck. No
interpretation was going to be a happy one. One day, as Fort Worth
gallery owner Evelyn Siegel walked through Grant's home, she saw
the painting and told the artist that it was one of the finest she
had ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``She also said that she would rather have her fingernails
pulled out than to wake up to that painting every day, because
she'd want to keep taking him down, and hugging him, and telling
him that everything would be OK,'' Grant says. ``I took that as a
supreme compliment, that she was getting the story.''
</P>
<P>
   But the anecdote also illustrates the paradox facing Grant and
most other serious artists. Although his art has been critically
praised, most of his early paintings were darkly provocative, often
difficult to look at, and as a result, off-putting to many
potential collectors. A few years ago, critics raved when Grant's
work was featured at a show in Santa Fe, but not one painting was
sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love art that they don't have to think about,'' Grant
says. ``They want something that decorates their environment and
makes it pretty. Then I go doing something with a guy in a
strangely lit situation wih a rope around his neck and his back to
you, and that requires some thought.''
</P>
<P>
   But Grant says any paintings he's attempted with an eye toward
sales have been disasters, ``weak, watery and embarrassing.'' His
natural evolution, personally and as an artist, has only recently
led to subjects that would appeal to a broader audience: skyscapes
and still lifes. He cannot identify the source of the rage that
produced his dark, almost defiantly uncommercial early work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've often wondered about that,'' he says. ``I just think I
was a hypersensitive kid and terribly intuitive, overly intuitive
and overly aware of what was going on around me.'' That dark
world-view became increasingly exclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Among his earliest childhood memories, he says, was of a spring
day in the family car, when the ground had thawed ``and you could
smell that perfume, the rain and the musk of the ground. And I was
aware in that moment that we had gone from the dead season to the
time when things were going to open and bloom.''
</P>
<P>
   But somewhere, in his life and work, that sense of wonder at the
mysteries and beauty of nature had been lost. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, a small group of children would congregate on
Grant's front porch to watch him paint. Grant noticed one boy in
particular, a sweet-natured, handsome child, whose inner life as
Grant came to know it inspired the artist to render the boy's
portrait.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was born out of wedlock, ``and he was reminded of that
every day,'' Grant says. The boy has since left town with his
family. ``His mother and stepfather loved him _ in spite of the
fact that he wasn't legitimate. You could see that he knew that
this was bad, that something was wrong with him, something organic
was wrong with him.''
</P>
<P>
   After receiving permission from the boy's parents, Grant
sketched the boy and photographed him from several angles. But
before he did, Grant asked his young subject to let his face go
blank, to think of himself as an empty glass of water. The
transformation was remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see everything about him,'' Grant says. ``You could
read his emotional history in his eyes. What I read was that there
was this little 8- or 9-year-old kid who basically had as much
information as I did at 40 about how the real way the world can
operate, that it can be an intensely painful place.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant painted the boy against an evening skyscape. The
melancholy of the finished painting escaped the boy and his family,
who were delighted with the work. Grant, however, was unnerved by
the experience. In his young subject, he had been reminded of the
dichotomy of life, the intense pain on one hand, but also the
beauty and natural innocence on the other. It was no coincidence
that the blindfolds began to fall away from his subjects a short
time later. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is a time every year when, as the seasons change, sunsets
become particularly resplendent. During one such period last year,
Grant photographed several evening skies from a favorite open space
along Eighth Avenue in south Fort Worth, and tried to replicate the
colors with oils on canvas.
</P>
<P>
   The large, dreamlike skyscape that resulted, ``Looking North,''
was to be part of a Grant exhibit at the Campbell gallery last
spring. But Wendy Owsley Garrett, an art collector and Grant's
friend, had an opportunity to see the painting first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost fainted when I saw it,'' Garrett says. ``It's an
immortal painting. You see this very powerful skyscape and have the
very powerful experience of viewing heaven, but you can also see
yourself bound to earth by the landscape that's visible. That was
the kicker for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrett purchased the work for an undisclosed amount, and
proposed the painting to the Dallas Museum of Art as a gift
honoring her uncle, David Owsley, a prominent New York collector
and leading patron of the Dallas museum. The offer brought Charlie
Wylie, the DMA's curator of contemporary art, to Fort Worth for a
look.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't just a cloud in the sky, as beautiful as that would
have been,'' Wylie says. ``It was dreamlike, in a certain way, and
had a real incisive quality that I enjoyed looking at.''
</P>
<P>
   One day in April, Wylie interrupted Grant's work with the news
that the museum had accpeted ``Looking North'' for its permanent
collection. The artist says he spent the next several days humming
as he walked around his house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to talk about,'' Grant says. ``This is all I ever
wanted to do, and I almost killed myself trying not to do it.
Having someone respond is a very powerful thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But the ecstasy of that moment has passed. There are still times
when oatmeal cookies are his sustenance. There are dark, haunting
paintings to be done, for that is the way of life. But beauty has
now found an equally important place in Grant's life and work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to stop looking down and only look at the sky,
because then I'm doing bluebonnet paintings,'' he says. ``They only
have meaning in contrast to other paintings, the context of the
body of work. A lot of my paintings deal with what we are and what
we do to one another, and then other paintings deal with what we
can become, with God or beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the contrast between our conflict with each other and the
quiet of nature,'' he says. ``I know that sounds watery, but
there's a way to act naturally. Nature is up there, and it's out
there. It's very attainable and it's important.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a lesson Grant learned first as a young child. Years later,
it took another child to remind him.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
