<HEADER>
A0531 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-ART-ANDLIFE-2800(2TAK     07-12 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-ANDLIFE-2800(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTIST LIVES FOR THE BEAUTY HE ONCE TRIED TO IGNORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Sometime in the next few months, J.T.
Grant's skyscape will find a place on the walls of the Dallas
Museum of Art. That will be a significant moment in the life of the
Fort Worth artist who, as a young adult, nearly drank himself to
death while trying to stifle his creative impulses.
</P>
<P>
   Grant's painting, which the museum accpeted for its permanent
collection in April, is unabashedly beautiful and affirming, a
backlit finger of cloud coiling toward the heavens against the hues
of evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really loved it and hated to sell it,'' Grant says of the
painting titled ``Looking North, Fort Worth 1999.'' ``I could get
lost in it. I could sit and stare at it. It made me happy. It made
me feel serene... I think the beauty of it is its deeper spiritual
meaning. They're extremely violent things, clouds. Yet at the same
time, this perfectly natural system operating in a perfectly
natural way.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, Grant would have been largely incapable of such
art or sentiment. When his artistic career began six years ago, his
paintings were almost exclusively haunting, depicting human figures
bound or blindfolded, often-seething allegories of religious or
social intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Then his own blindfold fell away. He rediscovered the natural
world. He had spent too much time looking down, he realized,
peering into the earthly cesspool, and not enough looking up,
toward the clouds, toward transcendence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just knew I had to do something to clean myself out,'' Grant
says. ``It really sank in that there had to be something to look
forward to, and something to focus on outside of the pain.
Otherwise it was just pain for pain's sake.''
</P>
<P>
   So the images of bondage began disappearing. His work became,
instead, a dichotomy of existential darkness and light. Sometimes
both were incorporated in the same work. There were more still
lifes of fruit and sage, and skyscrapers at sunset, and finally the
stunning piece that found its way to the Dallas Museum of Art,
where it will be exhibited and cared for into perpetuity. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grant, a dark-haired, soft-spoken man of 44, is the
quintessential starving artist. On a recent day, he is subsisting
on a large batch of homemade oatmeal cookies. His kitchen cabinets
hold the ingredients for the cookies _ and not much else. He has
spent the last of his money shipping paintings to an art show in
New York and will be virtually penniless until a check from one of
his handful of art students arrives in a few days. His next full
meal, he figures, will be at a reception and dinner he is invited
to attend the next evening at the Dallas Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it romantic?'' Grant, who is single, says in the living
room of his home, a fix-it-up bungalow in Fort Worth's Fairmount
neighborhood. ``I hope that someday, sitting on a comfy stoop
somewhere, I'll think back on the great days when I ate oatmeal
cookies. I'd love that, and I don't mind it now. I mean, I eat
oatmeal cookies at home and then go out and rub elbows with
somebody who's got $750 million in the bank. And they feed me well.
It's kind of a bipolar existence.''
</P>
<P>
   But against the larger arc of Grant's life and career, those
current deprivations seem trivial, material scarcities he suffers
more or less gladly.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in North Carolina and Virginia in a household of
bankers and educators, ``so financial success was a big part of
their experience,'' he says. From an early age, however, he was
drawn toward a world where success was measured less tangibly.
</P>
<P>
   Grant remembers his intense fascination at age 6 with the
etchings of an older girl at a community art workshop. When he was
12, relatives paid him a dollar for his painting of the Matterhorn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just nice to be able to cause something to come into
being, even if it was just a copy,'' he says. ``I really liked the
smell and the touch and the feel.''
</P>
<P>
   But a career in art seemed impractical. Years later, Grant also
faced a crippling fear: that even if he tried to pursue painting,
he would lack anything worthwhile to say with his art. He dropped
out of several colleges, trying to find an alternative, then fell
into a well-paid job managing a document and price control
department for a retail chain on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   He was miserable. Although most of his friends at the time
didn't know it, Grant eventually consumed more than a case of beer
and two liters of wine a day while sitting alone at home in
Richmond, Va., watching television. Fifteen years ago this month,
feeling he could no longer conceal his addiction, Grant checked
himself into a treatment center. He's been sober ever since. The
decision to pursue art came a few months later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized so much of my drinking had been about my terror
that the one thing I wanted out of life was unavailable to me, that
I wouldn't have the talent to be a good painter,'' Grant says.
``That's when I was like, `I've got to find out.' Because if I
didn't, I figured I'd start drinking again just to cover up the
fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant quit his job and enrolled in the arts program at Virginia
Commonwealth University, pulling all-nighters several times a week
to paint. He then entered the master's program in the art
department at Texas Christian University in Fort Worth, where
relatives had recently moved. His works engendered immediate
enthusiasm from instructors, gallery owners and collectors; his art
had an edgy realism that was technically excellent. Within months
of graduating from TCU in 1994, Grant has his work featured in a
show at William Campbell Contemporary Art, the first of several
exhibits at the popular gallery in west Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of his images seemed to have some sort of a psychological
bent to them,'' William Campbell says. ``Nothing was explicitly
laid out, but something unknown was always implied. I just thought
it was all very, very interesting. He was a professional painter
and a nice guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant went on to supplement modest if steady sales with art
lessons, or with commissioned portraits and murals such as the rear
wall of The 8.0, the popular nightspot in downtown Fort Worth. He
otherwise has been free to pursue his artistic vision in his
upstairs studio, painting seven days a week, sometimes for 14 hours
a day. MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
