<SLUG> BC-NH-IMPEACH-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.H. LEGISLATORS VOTE TO IMPEACH STATE'S CHIEF JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
  By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ In a historic first, the New Hampshire House of
Representatives impeached the chief justice of the state Supreme
Court Wednesday, accusing him of four ethical lapses and handing
his fate over to the state Senate for trial.
</P>
<P>
   The 253-95 vote on Chief Justice David Brock culminated weeks of
constitutional agony in New Hampshire, triggered by a nasty
divorce.
</P>
<P>
   The divorce of one of the five Supreme Court justices led to an
inquiry by the state attorney general into the court's practices,
which led lawmakers to examine whether there were grounds for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly Wednesday, House members decided that there were
grounds to impeach Brock, though they spare two of his Supreme
Court colleagues, Justices Sherman Horton and John Broderick. The
House had last impeached a Supreme Court justice in 1790, and it
had never before impeached a chief justice.
</P>
<P>
   By approximately 2-to-1 ratios, not particularly along party
lines, the Republican-dominated House approved four separate
articles of impeachment against Brock. The articles accused Brock,
64, of making a phone call to a Superior Court judge 13 years ago
seeking to influence a case; allowing the divorcing justice to
influence the appointment of judges in his own case; allowing
judges to comment on cases from which they had recused themselves;
and repeatedly lying under oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``This investigation, if it accomplishes nothing else, has
lifted the skirt of Lady Justice and taken a peek,'' said Henry P.
Mock, the chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, which
recommended the impeachment. ``Did we see anything there that was
really, really naughty? Not too bad, but we have seen things that
were absolutely wrong. Not only that, but her blindfold slipped.
Justice is blind but she took a peek and she wasn't supposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Brock, who was not present Wednesday, has acknowledged that he
made errors of judgment. But, said David Barry, one of his lawyers,
Brock contended that they were not impeachable conduct, and that he
looked forward to the opportunity to clear his name.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote ``will be viewed as a historic aberration,''
Barry said, and possibly a dangerous one because ``it has lowered
the impeachment bar and put at risk the independence of the
judiciary.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, advised by former U.S. Sen. George Mitchell, is
expected to begin the trial next month, and even advocates of
Wednesday's impeachment are predicting that Brock is likely to
prevail there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll clean our clocks in the Senate,'' said Rep. Tony F.
Soltani, a Republican, pointing out that the Senate tends to be
more sympathetic to the judiciary than the 400-seat House.
</P>
<P>
   Some opponents of impeachment Wednesday complained in the House
hallways that they believed the impeachment was based not on the
facts but on festering anger against the state Supreme Court for
its 1997 ``Claremont'' decision requiring the state to revamp its
heavily local system for financing schools. The state is still
struggling to work out a new system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, because Brock was a substantial influence in getting
the Claremont decision passed, that this was in part a great
backlash against him,'' said Rep. Beth Rodd, a Democrat. ``I don't
feel that justice is being done. I feel there's a vindictive
spirit, a mob mentality has taken over.''
</P>
<P>
   But advocates of the impeachment said it was necessary to
restore public confidence in that court.
</P>
<P>
   The divorcing justice, W. Stephen Thayer III, could influence
the selection of judges for his divorce, while his wife could not,
Soltani commented, and that ``is repulsive to me, repulsive beyond
belief.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gov. Jeanne Shaheen, a Democrat, said Wednesday that she was
committed to doing all she could to restore confidence in the
courts, including pushing a constitutional amendment providing that
judges be appointed for set terms rather than for life.
</P>
<P>
   The New Hampshire standards for impeachment are lower than the
federal standards that became familiar to many during President
Clinton's impeachment proceedings. It is enough, under New
Hampshire law, for a judge to commit no ``high crime or
misdemeanor'' but merely ``maladministration'' _ a word that
lawmakers seemed to have trouble defining Wednesday. Some argued
that since it was listed together with bribery and corruption, it
must involve malice and ill-intent.
</P>
<P>
   Many speakers Wednesday pointed out that Brock's main error had
been one of compassion, in that he had felt sorry for Thayer, and
tried to help him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we going to hang a man for compassion?'' demanded one
lawmaker, Richard Kennedy, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates of impeachment depicted the chief justice's
misdeeds as too serious to be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   He was accused of making a phone call in 1987 to a superior
court judge who was hearing a contract dispute, and reminding him
that one of the litigants was a powerful senator who could
influence judicial pay raises. Brock has denied making such a call.
</P>
<P>
   He was also accused of committing ``maladministration'' in
February when he informed Thayer which judges he would appoint to a
special panel needed to hear the Thayer divorce case because the
Supreme Court justices had all recused themselves. When Brock made
that announcement, witnesses said, Thayer objected to one of the
judges, and Brock tried to hold back the court clerk from calling
that judge.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Brock has had little chance to mount his own defense.
But his day will come in the Senate, Barry, his lawyer, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The citizens of New Hampshire should make no mistake,'' he
said, ``this man has been on trial for three months now, and he's
had no due process, no rights and no voice. This `jury' that
convicted him today has acted as a result of a one-sided process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
