<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0538 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-LEARNING-TOFORGIVE-22     07-12 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARNING-TOFORGIVE-2200(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGIVENESS SETS YOU FREE, AUTHOR AND OTHERS SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even over the telephone, you can hear Rocky barking and the
deafening roar of jets flying up the Potomac River. Mariah Burton
Nelson brushes off the noise pollution as she might dust on her
desk.
</P>
<P>
   She is not easily annoyed; she won't rail against the dog or the
planes. This is typical of Nelson's new-found demeanor; she has
learned to be more tolerant, to forgive, whether it is the
noisemakers of the world or those guilty of far more serious
transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always that way. At one time, Nelson says, forgiveness
was out of the question. She held grudges. She was angry, arrogant
and acerbic.
</P>
<P>
   But that changed after she found the courage to reconcile with
the man who made her that way, who sexually abused her. Still, it
took Nelson two decades to forgive.
</P>
<P>
   The 44-year-old author and free-lance writer, who lives in
Arlington, Va., details her journey to forgiveness in ``The
Unburdened Heart: Five Keys to Forgiveness and Freedom'' (Harper
San Francisco, $22).
</P>
<P>
   The book is a poignant story of betrayal and reconciliation that
includes Nelson's conversations with the coach who molested her,
the emotional breakdown that ensued and, ultimately, her ability to
forgive him. The book is also about spiritual wisdom gleaned from
Scripture, poetry, psychological studies and interviews with others
who have forgiven offenses great and small.
</P>
<P>
   But more than anything, Nelson likes to think of ``The
Unburdened Heart'' as a love story, of love gained when, as she
says, ``we lay down our burdens of anger, rage, recrimination,
retribution and superiority.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Forgiveness frees us to love fully,'' Nelson says. ``It
requires loving and honoring yourself enough to do what's right
even though it can be scary and difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Her journey began with the willingness to be open to the
possibility of forgiveness and then working toward that goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was risk-taking, and it involved making mistakes along the
way,'' she says. ``Compassion did play a big part, as did humility.
I remembered that I'd hurt a lot of people, too, so I'm not just a
victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson says that by her 40th birthday, the question of whether
she was going to spend the rest of her life being angry about
something that happened in her teens weighed heavily.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, while researching the subject of coach-athlete abuse for a
book, Nelson began to wonder whether forgiveness might be possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone who engages in any sort of criminal or rude behavior
must be coming from a place of pain or ignorance or suffering,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson has made the transition to being what her friends call a
professional forgiver. ``I take a radical stand that nothing is
unforgivable,'' she says. ``The only limits on forgiveness is our
unwillingness, our inability to open our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, who was 14 when she was first abused, says she never got
an answer from her former coach about why he molested her. He told
her that he was in over his head in his job and that his marriage
was difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would've liked some neat answer, like he was molested when
he was a kid,'' she says. ``We're complicated human beings, so it's
not always clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Nelson says she is convinced that forgiveness frees
us to love again and live our lives to the fullest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to start a national conversation about forgiveness
... because forgiving people contribute a lot more loving, generous
energy to the world,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of interviews, the Star-Telegram talked to North
Texas residents who have found the courage to forgive. These are
their stories and the paths they took to forgiveness: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BARBARA ALLEN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She is ironing the shirt and slacks she will wear to her new job
at Catholic Charities. Her three sons saunter in and out of the
room, curious about the stranger visiting their mom.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Allen is 24 and mature beyond her years. Life has made
her that way. She was 15 when she left home and checked herself
into a Fort Smith, Ark., halfway house for teens. She says she had
become disgusted because her mom seemed to put the men in her life
ahead of her daughter. The family moved a lot.
</P>
<P>
   When her four-month stay in the halfway house was completed,
Allen called her mom to come get her. Her mom refused, Allen says.
``She said, `I'm sorry, you're on your own,' '' Allen says.
</P>
<P>
   Three years would pass before she would talk to her mother
again. ``I didn't want to talk to her until I could prove I was
somebody,'' Allen says.
</P>
<P>
   But when she was 18, Allen became pregnant. She decided to
swallow her pride and call her mother again. She needed support;
she wanted her son to know his grandmother. It was time for
reconciliation. MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED: time for reconciliation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Pride or no pride, I picked up the phone and called,'' Allen
says.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother was distant at first, Allen says. Allen kept calling,
and the day she went into labor, her mother showed up, as she said
she would.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the breakthrough, their relationship remained strained.
Allen would give birth two more times but still would fend for
herself, sometimes living on the street.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, feeling desperate, she prayed that her life would
change, that she would find a home for herself and her children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told God I was tired, emotionally and physically tired,''
Allen says. ``I told him this is it, if I leave my friends, their
(the children's) dad, the drinking, will you give me a home for my
children?
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks later, I got a letter that I'd been accepted for
conventional (Section 8) housing. Little by little, the miracles
started to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen went to Catholic Charities, earned a high school
equivalency diploma and got a job at the agency.
</P>
<P>
   The best part, she says, is that she recognized through her own
experiences that her mother had also tried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made plenty of mistakes,'' Allen says. ``I did the best I
could, just like she did the best she could for me. Our
relationship is so, so much better. We talk about once a week
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Allen says, her mother ended their conversation with,
``I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are words I wanted to hear forever,'' Allen says. ``They
mean I accept you for who you are, and I don't compare you to
anyone else.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VAL NANCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For years, Val Nance lived with the belief that his parents
favored his siblings. Even as an adult, he was angry with them,
believing that they had not loved him enough. He also was angry at
God for calling him to the ministry, only to seemingly abandon him.
</P>
<P>
   Nance was a church pastor but was struggling to make ends meet.
``I was teaching school, driving a bus and pastoring a small
church,'' he says. ``I was angry at God and my (congregation). What
I didn't realize was it was impairing me.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, when he was 50, Nance fell into a deep depression. ``My
first question was was I going crazy,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He sought help at a counseling center and discovered that the
anger was paralyzing him. But, he says, ``God began to deal with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   As a pastor, Nance knew that forgiveness was a major part of his
calling. ``God commands me to forgive even if I'm not ready to,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   It took time for Nance to understand that he would have to
forgive his parents, regardless of whether the slights were real or
imagined, or the anger would never diminish.
</P>
<P>
   He decided to let go. ``It opened up my life in a way that is
really indescribable,'' he says. ``And it makes it easier for me to
go and ask for forgiveness because I'm willing to forgive.''
</P>
<P>
   Nance, who is 68 and no longer a clergyman, lives in Azle with
his wife and 15-year-old granddaughter. He likened the ability to
forgive to a bridge across the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am on one side and God is on the other,'' he says. ``If I
don't forgive, I've removed one board of that bridge; I've impaired
my ability to reach God. If we don't forgive, God won't forgive
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Through counseling and heart-to-heart talks with siblings, Nance
says, he came to a better understanding of his childhood and his
calling.
</P>
<P>
   It was only later that his brother told him that Nance had been
his parents' favorite because he became a minister. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   YOLANDA TATUM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Yolanda Tatum's brother settled in a chair in her
den, shot heroin into his veins and died.
</P>
<P>
   Tatum sits in her living room now, a room apart from the
tragedy, and she cries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't even live here; why did he have to come here and do
that?'' she asks. ``Why come to my mother's home, why this house
where we grew up?''
</P>
<P>
   Tatum is angry. She doesn't understand. Her brother had a
bachelor's degree and was earning a master's. He was so handsome,
she says, that she often had to explain to other women that she was
just his sister. He was loved by his entire family.
</P>
<P>
   But for years, Tatum says, her brother Dandryea was
drug-dependent. He did time in prison for a botched armed robbery;
but after being released in 1998, he did well for a time and
appeared to be drug-free.
</P>
<P>
   Even as his problems resurfaced, Tatum says, she remained loyal
to her brother. She helped him every way she could, although he
pawned her personal belongings for $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   When Dandryea moved in with his girlfriend and started working
again, Tatum thought things might be different. And they were. Only
worse.
</P>
<P>
   On June 4, Dandryea pawned more of his sister's belongings and
used the proceeds to buy heroin. He returned to his childhood home,
wrote a two-page letter to Tatum and shot the drugs into his vein.
</P>
<P>
   When Tatum arrived home later that day, Dandryea was still
sitting in the chair, a syringe, the pawnshop receipt and the
letter lying on a stool next to his lifeless form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked into the den and said, `Dandryea, this CD player is
stuck,' '' Tatum says. ``I walked over and hit the power button to
turn it off.''
</P>
<P>
   When he didn't respond, Tatum says, she thought her brother was
asleep. She tapped him on the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``His head fell to the side and I ran to the phone and called
911,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Dandryea was dead. And Tatum was left with questions.
</P>
<P>
   What if she had come home sooner? Was there any way she could
have prevented this?
</P>
<P>
   She wishes that she had had even just 15 minutes more with him.
She knows that ultimately, peace of mind will come only through
forgiveness _ for him and for herself for not being there. But, she
says, ``telling myself to forgive and forgiving is two different
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Her journey toward forgiveness has yet begun. But there are no
other options.
</P>
<P>
   ``If God forgave the world, surely I can forgive him,'' Tatum
says.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
