<HEADLINE>
TWENTY-FIVE YEARS LATER, JAWS STILL HAS A HECKUVA BITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not safe to go back in the water.
</P>
<P>
   With his 1975 classic ``Jaws,'' which gets a 25th-anniversary
special edition DVD release this week, a 27-year-old upstart
director named Steven Spielberg did for the ocean what Alfred
Hitchcock's ``Psycho'' did for showers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jaws,'' based on Peter Benchley's bestselling novel about a
coastal town terrorized by a giant great white shark, went on to
become one of the highest-grossing movies of all time. (It would
eventually get nudged off the top 10 list by some of Spielberg's
later efforts.) The movie's unparalleled success invented the
concept of the summer blockbuster, forever transforming the season
into an FX- and action-oriented battleground for the biggest box
office take.
</P>
<P>
   In short, ``Jaws'' changed Hollywood _ and the art of making
movies _ overnight.
</P>
<P>
   It also changed us, and how we thought about the water. As a
9-year-old growing up in the coastal Texas town of Corpus Christi,
I watched ``Jaws'' with equal parts fascination and horror. For
months I wouldn't set one toe on the sandy, tar-streaked shores of
Padre Island. Lakes, rivers, even neighborhood pools gave me the
willies. I couldn't even relax in a hot bath unless the surface was
Mr. Bubble-free, to allow for maximum shark-spotting.
</P>
<P>
   And I wasn't alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have people say to me, `You wrote ``Jaws?'' ' I was a
diver and I wouldn't go in the water for months,' '' recalls
co-screenwriter Carl Gottlieb, who appeared in the original film as
the editor of the ``Amity Gazette.'' ``Or, `I was scared to take a
bath; I thought Jaws would come up through the plug.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jaws'' grip on the public consciousness was as relentless as
John Williams' deceptively simple and oft-imitated ``da-nun,
da-nun'' score. The poster showing the shark's open-mouthed jaws
rising to devour a hapless swimmer became one of the most
recognizable and widely lampooned images in the world, showing up
in everything from editorial cartoons to the cover of ``Mad''
magazine. The film was a regular source of comedy, from Dickie
Goodman's ``Mr. Jaws'' radio parody to ``Saturday Night Live's''
Land Shark.
</P>
<P>
   Awards followed, with the film taking home three Oscars _ for
Best Sound, Score and Film Editing. Despite its nomination for Best
Picture, Spielberg was snubbed for the director's prize.
</P>
<P>
   But Spielberg, of course, had the last laugh. Twenty-five years
later, ``Jaws,'' despite what are now considered somewhat crude
effects, continues to fascinate and frighten movie lovers,
including a new generation of fright seekers. So to honor the
landmark film, we take a fond look at the cast and the phenomenon
that is ``Jaws.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BIGGER FISH ...
</P>
<P>
   Many of the cast members of ``Jaws'' followed its dorsal fin to
fame, but where are they now?
</P>
<P>
   Roy Scheider (Chief Martin Brody), along with ``Jaws 2,'' made a
number of respectable post-shark films, including ``All That Jazz''
(for which he nabbed an Oscar nomination) and ``52 Pick-Up.'' He
even returned to the sea for the short-lived NBC series ``seaQuest
DSV.'' Last seen: Starring in ``Chain of Command,'' premiering July
22 on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Dreyfuss (Matt Hooper) leaped immediately from ``Jaws''
to his greatest critical acclaim in Spielberg's ``Close Encounters
of the Third Kind'' and Neil Simon's ``The Goodbye Girl'' (for
which he won an Oscar), both in 1977. Then came a down period.
Between lots of forgettable films, he appeared in a number of
crowd-pleasing comedies ``(Down and Out in Beverly Hills, What
About Bob?'' and ``Lost in Yonkers)'' and heart-tugging dramas
``(Stand by Me, Nuts'' and ``Mr. Holland's Opus).'' Last seen: As
the president in this year's TV remake of ``Fail Safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Shaw (Quint) Few knew that Shaw was an accomplished
author who scripted most of his now-legendary USS Indianapolis
speech in ``Jaws.'' He appeared as the Sheriff of Nottingham in
1976's ``Robin and Marian,'' as well as ``Black Sunday'' and Peter
Benchley's ``The Deep,'' both in 1977. Last seen: His final films,
``Avalanche Express'' (1979) and ``Force 10 from Navarone'' (1978)
were released posthumously after his death of a heart attack in
1978.
</P>
<P>
   Murray Hamilton (Mayor Larry Vaughn) Bounced back with
appearances in TV's ``Rich Man, Poor Man'' (1976) and ``Jaws 2''
(1978). He worked with Spielberg again in ``1941'' and also
appeared in ``The Amityville Horror,'' both in 1979. Last seen: His
final film was 1986's ``The Last Days of Patton.'' He died of
cancer that year.
</P>
<P>
   Lorraine Gary (Ellen Brody) Followed with appearances in ``Car
Wash'' (1976) and ``Jaws 2'' (1978). Also appeared in Spielberg's
``1941.'' Last seen: Hasn't been, not since 1987's awful ``Jaws the
Revenge.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
... BIGGER PONDS
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the folks in front of the cameras weren't the only
ones to ride ``Jaws'' to fame and fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Spielberg is still getting work. He followed up ``Jaws''
with ``Close Encounters of the Third Kind'' in 1977 and then
directed what would become the highest-grossing movie of all time
for a several-years period, ``E.T. The Extra-Terrestrial.'' His
early attempts to grow up proved disappointing until the success of
the dino epic ``Jurassic Park'' reaffirmed his clout, which allowed
him to direct Oscar darlings ``Schindler's List'' (which earned him
Best Director and Picture Oscars) and ``Saving Private Ryan'' (Best
Director).
</P>
<P>
   Peter Benchley (novelist/co-screenwriter) never matched the
success of his 1974 20-million-copy bestseller, but it wasn't for
lack of trying. Filmed versions of his novels ``The Deep'' and
``The Island'' failed to reel in audiences, and most of his
subsequent novels _ usually dealing with aquatic adversaries of
some kind or another _ came off as pale imitations of his most
memorable work.
</P>
<P>
   John Williams (composer) forged an incredibly successful
relationship with Spielberg, earning Academy Awards for his scores
to ``Jaws,'' ``E.T. The Extra-Terrestrial'' and ``Schindler's
List.'' His music for the ``Star Wars'' and ``Indiana Jones''
trilogies have become the stuff of legend.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
