<SLUG> BC-BUSTARHYMES-CDREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSTA'S HARDLY REVOLUTIONARY IN `ANARCHY'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Busta Rhymes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Anarchy'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elektra Records &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has seen rapper Busta Rhymes perform live knows that
he's a walking ``Animal House'' onstage, a guy who'll drop his
pants, talk trash about women and play all the usual shallow,
crowd-hyping games.
</P>
<P>
   When he's in the studio, though, Rhymes is often amazing. On his
past few efforts, the rapper-turned-actor (he has a role in
``Shaft'') has taken intelligent looks at the decay of
civilization, corruption in government, war and the sad state of
urban America. Rhymes is one of the few hip-hop stars to
sagaciously, sometimes savagely, address those subjects without an
it's-all-someone-else's-fault attitude.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of intelligence is hinted at on Busta's fourth disc,
the misleadingly titled ``Anarchy,'' but it's Rhymes' party-animal
attitude that rules. And it gets old. Like, real fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anarchy'' isn't rebellious at all. Rather, it's full of the
usual gangsta-rap boasts: Women get called derogatory names, racial
slurs are used over and over and, who's No. 1? Busta is, baby!
</P>
<P>
   Insert very long yawn here.
</P>
<P>
   What's even worse is the music. Usually, Busta has a dark,
terrorizing tone to his music that perfectly fits his razor-sharp
lyrics. Since many of the songs here _ ``Here We Go Again, Salute
Da Gods!!'' _ are party anthems, the music is upbeat but
excruciatingly elementary. Parts of ``Anarchy'' sound like Busta
rapping over the tinklings of a music box.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say there aren't a few good songs. ``The Heist,''
in which Rhymes is joined by Ghostface Killah, Raekwon and several
other prominent rappers, is a frightening scenario of a stickup
gone wrong, and the first single, ``Get Out,'' makes clever use of
a children's sing-along chorus, a la Jay-Z's ``Hard Knock Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Other strong moments are scattered throughout, but the disc is
75 minutes long, and you get kinda tired of looking for them.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
