<HEADLINE>
HEALTH PLAN MAKES ONLINE DRUG DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THOUSAND OAKS, Calif. _ WellPoint Health Networks on Wednesday
said it signed a five-year deal with drugstore.com Inc., which will
provide products and services to its pharmacy management unit
online.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership was signed through WellPoint's subsidiary,
WellPoint Pharmacy Management, and will offer the health plan's 22
million members discounts on over-the-counter products.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members want an Internet pharmacy option; drugstore.com
offers exciting opportunities to customize the online services we
offer our clients,'' said Michael Nameth, general manager of
Thousand Oaks-based WellPoint Pharmacy Management.
</P>
<P>
   Drugstore.com will also alert customers electronically of any
Food and Drug Administration or drug manufacturer warnings and
recalls through its eMedAlert program.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to specialized pharmacy services, WellPoint's
members will have access to 24-hour service seven days a week,
along with more than 17,000 products available for home delivery.
</P>
<P>
   In California, 5.3 million members of WellPoint's subsidiary,
Blue Cross of California, will be able to purchase their
prescriptions over the Internet if they choose, said company
spokesman Larry Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Nameth said as the site is developed, WellPoint members will be
offered discount coupons and frequent buyer plans on
nonprescription items.
</P>
<P>
   ``By working with drugstore.com, WellPoint saves the expense and
time associated with building a stand-alone online pharmacy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
