<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0563 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-TEXAS-DEATH-PENALTY-4     07-12 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DEATH-PENALTY-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIAL SAYS DNA TEST IMPLICATES INMATE GIVEN STAY BY BUSH
</HEADLINE>
  (EDITORS: this story, eliminated earlier, is now restored and
appears on Page 1)  
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A DNA test has failed to exonerate a Texas death row
inmate, Ricky Nolen McGinn, whose case took on political
significance last month when Gov. George W. Bush interrupted his
presidential campaign to grant the man a stay of execution,
according officials know familiar with the results.
</P>
<P>
   The case of McGinn, 43, who was convicted of raping and
murdering his 12-year-old stepdaughter, attracted national
attention when his lawyers urged that new DNA tests be conducted to
address doubts about his conviction. Bush, who has presided over
137 executions since taking office in 1995, granted McGinn a
reprieve _ the first time the governor had done so _ to allow the
DNA tests to take place.
</P>
<P>
   Now, one of a series of DNA tests being conducted in response to
Bush's reprieve has confirmed a match with McGinn, a law
enforcement official and a high-ranking Texas Republican said. In
June, following the reprieve, Judge Stephen Ellis in Brown County,
ordered tests on pubic hairs and semen collected from the victim's
body. Under the judge's order, the FBI is testing the hair, while
the Texas Department of Public Safety is testing the semen. DNA
experts hired by McGinn's lawyers also are conducting tests. The
law enforcement official did not say which test had confirmed the
match.
</P>
<P>
   The complete battery of tests are expected to be completed by
Aug. 15 when a hearing is scheduled and when Ellis could rule and
set a new execution date. USAToday reported Wednesday that the test
conducted by the FBI showed that the hair belonged to either McGinn
or a maternal relative, which officials see as an unlikely
alternative because none of his relatives were implicated in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   The test findings could provide some political ammunition for
Bush, who has come under heavy scrutiny and criticism for the
capital punishment system in Texas. Michael Jones, a spokesman for
Bush, said the governor's office had not yet been notified of any
DNA results and noted that the additional testing could take
several more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've said all along is that at least in Texas the
justice system has ample safeguards to make sure that only guilty
people are executed,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   McGinn had been scheduled to die by lethal injection on June 1,
and the state Board of Pardons and Paroles had voted against
recommending a reprieve for DNA testing. But Bush, who under state
law can override the board in such a case and grant a 30-day stay,
decided to do that. In doing so, he said McGinn could ``have his
full day in court.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The issue of DNA testing arose at McGinn's initial trial five
years ago. But DNA tests conducted at the time were inconclusive.
But because of advances in testing technology, McGinn's lawyers had
argued that new tests would now yield conclusive results. McGinn's
lawyers professed his innocence and argued in particular that DNA
testing could at the very least exonerate him of the rape. It was
the conviction that crime that when added to the murder conviction,
created the aggravated circumstances that qualified McGinn for the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor in the case, Lee Haney, did not return telephone
calls seeking comment. Lawyers for McGinn, citing a gag order in
the case, declined to discuss the DNA test. But speaking in broad
terms, one lawyer, Maurie Levin, said a test result from any single
case should not serve as an endorsement of the state's death
penalty system.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, Governor Bush's reprieve acknowledged problems in the
system,'' said Levin, who as the head of Texas Defender Service
regularly handles death row appeals.
</P>
<P>
   In June, state Sen. Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, announced that he
would introduce a bill the legislative session next year that would
allow convicted felons under certain circumstances to request DNA
testing if such testing could definitively prove their guilt or
innocence. Currently, only New York and Illinois have such a law.
</P>
</TEXT>
