<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ADVISER COUNSELED ISRAELIS BEFORE SUMMIT
</HEADLINE>
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the days leading up to the Camp David peace
talks, a foreign policy adviser to Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
counseled Israeli officials to accept only a comprehensive peace
agreement and to resist any efforts by the Clinton administration
to use the summit meeting in the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The comments by the adviser, Richard Perle, caused Bush to
distance himself on Wednesday from those views. Bush said Perle had
been ``speaking for himself'' and not the Bush campaign when he
talked with Yossi Alper, an aide to Prime Minister Ehud Barak, and
another Israeli official, Yoram Ben-Zeev.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish the administration all the best when it comes to
bringing peace to the Middle East,'' Bush said, appearing outside
the governor's mansion after an hourlong meeting with former
Secretary of State Henry Kissinger. Bush said that he opposed any
efforts to politicize the peace talks and that ``my campaign will
not do so.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that, ``This is an important time, and it's important
for Republicans to wish the administration well. There would be
nothing better than a lasting peace in the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that President Clinton ``deserves credit'' for his
efforts to try to achieve a lasting peace settlement between the
Palestinians and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Perle is one of a small circle of former State and Defense
department officials from previous Republican administrations who
advise the governor on foreign policy, though they are not paid
staff members of the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats seized on a report about Perle's action in Wednesday's
The New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are Governor Bush and his advisers interested in peace or
politics for Israel?'' asked Rep. Sam Gejdensen, D-Conn., the
ranking Democrat on the House International Relations Committee.
``We should all be hoping that Camp David is successful, not
figuring out how to score political points.''
</P>
<P>
   Perle said on Wednesday that he had long been involved in Middle
East policy. He said he had told the two officials in the days
leading up to the meeting between Barak and Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, that Israel should try to achieve a
comprehensive peace agreement resolving all outstanding issues,
including the final status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Officials on all sides of the talks have said that a good
partial agreement might be the only realistic end to themeeting at
Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the West Bank issues were separated from the Jerusalem
issue, I though it would greatly diminish the chances of a
resolution of the Jerusalem question,'' Perle said. He said
Jerusalem would then become the ``focal point'' of the conflict
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   He said that a Bush aide had called him about the article in The
Post and that he recounted what he had said and had not said. He
denied the contention in the article that he had told the Israelis
not to let Vice President Al Gore participate in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Perle said he did, however, tell the Israelis that they ought to
avoid being drawn into presidential politics. ``I said `the
administration may be tempted to inject a partisan note in this and
I hope you resist any such effort.'''
</P>
<P>
   Perle said he was not injecting politics into the meeting but
was trying to do ``exactly the opposite.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
