<SLUG> BC-TIMES-BOOKS-HOLTZBRINCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMES CO. AND HOLTZBRINCK AGREE TO REVIVE TIMES BOOKS  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Times and Holtzbrinck Publishers, the
U.S. arm of the German media company von Holtzbrinck Group, agreed
Wednesday to restart the Times Books imprint and expand the Times'
book development.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Holt &AMP; Co., a U.S. unit of Holtzbrinck, will publish in
cooperation with The Times a list of books under the Times Books
imprint, beginning next year with about 14 titles. The Times Books
imprint will eventually publish 20 nonfiction books a year about
current events, history, science, technology, business, health and
other subjects. Some of the first books will be based on coverage
in The New York Times, including ``How Race Is Lived in America,''
``Writers on Writing,'' ``The New York Times Management Reader''
and ``The New York Times Guide to Alternative Medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's Press, another unit of Holtzbrinck in the United
States, will publish other books bearing the New York Times brand,
like Times' crossword puzzle books. St. Martin's will also
distribute other books published by The New York Times. The Times
has previously published hotel, restaurant and museum guides as
well as yearbooks about the Yankees and a photographic history of
Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Co., a diversified media company that also owns The
Boston Globe, began publishing books in 1969, when the company
acquired Quadrangle Books, based in Chicago. In 1977, the company
changed its imprint to Times Books. From 1984 through 1999, the
Times licensed the imprint to Random House. The imprint ceased
publication when the license agreement expired in December 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
