u f BC-MOTOROLA-EARNINGS-NYT     07-12 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTOROLA-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTOROLA REPORTS STRONG RESULTS IN LINE WITH FORECASTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Motorola Inc., the telecommunications and
semiconductor giant, reported strong sales and profit growth for
the second quarter Wednesday that were in line with Wall Street
estimates, despite lingering weakness in the sale of its cellular
telephones in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which released its earnings after the close of
regular trading, reported revenue of $9.26 billion in the second
quarter, up 22 percent from $7.6 billion in the period a year
earlier. Profit from continuing operations nearly doubled, to $515
million, or 23 cents a share, from $269 million, or 13 cents a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola took an after-tax charge of $316 million, or 14 cents a
share, related to research and development and acquisitions
completed during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts, who had been worried about shrinking
margins in the cellular telephone business, said they were pleased
with the report. Though sales and profit margins were lower in
Europe, analysts said Motorola seemed to have stemmed the decline
and prepared for a rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Net net, people should come out of this positive, with a sigh
of relief,'' said Walt Piecyk, an analyst at PaineWebber Group.
``There were concerns they were going to miss the number, and they
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Motorola closed at $35.50, up $1.875. In after-hours
trading, the stock slipped to $33.0625 after the earnings were
reported, then bounced back to $36.25. Still, the shares are down
sharply, having started the year at nearly $50, after a huge run-up
over the last two years. Those share gains had been predicated on
the notion that Motorola was remaking itself for the ``wired
world'' and benefiting from enormous demand for microchips, digital
telephones and a host of other communications devices, like cable
modems.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola executives said Wednesday that the second-quarter
report represented the eighth consecutive quarterly profit gain and
was just the latest indication that the company was aggressively
moving ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola executives said sales and profits in many units were up
more than 20 percent. Sales of set-top boxes and cable modems were
strong; two-way radios and networking sales jumped; and
semiconductor profits were up, with improved margins.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pretty good story,'' said Albert R. Brashear, a
spokesman at Motorola, which is based in Schaumburg, Ill. ``All of
our businesses are hitting it pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   The company did acknowledge, however, that digital handset
revenue had slipped in Europe as the company has pulled out of some
lower-tiered products. Motorola is expected to offer further
explanation in a conference call on Wednesday, but executives said
Wednesday that profit margins in the cellular business were
expected to rise to 10 percent by the fourth quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the shift in strategy had been outlined by
Motorola months ago, and the report Wednesday seemed to indicate
that the company was moving in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``These numbers look pretty good,'' said Greg Teets, an analyst
at A.G. Edwards Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
