<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MEDICAID-CLINTON-N     07-12 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MEDICAID-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI ADMINISTRATION CRITICIZES MRS. CLINTON'S MEDICAID PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER STEINHAUER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pataki administration Wednesday criticized a proposal by
Hillary Rodham Clinton to increase the amount of money New York
state receives from Washington for Medicaid expenditures, charging
that she was far too late in addressing an issue state leaders have
complained about for years.
</P>
<P>
   Her proposal, about which she has offered few details, would
require the federal government to foot a larger portion of the
state's total annual Medicaid bill. Under her formula, New Yorkers'
taxes could be cut by an estimated average of $400 a year through
$3 billion in new funds.
</P>
<P>
   What annoys officials in the Pataki administration is not the
proposal itself, which they fully embrace, but its timing. New
York's elected officials have gone after federal increases for
years. And a proposal to increase the state's percentage of money
from the federal government was part of a bill vetoed by President
Clinton in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary Rodham Clinton is using this issue for her own
political benefit, just like her husband,'' said John Signor, a
spokesman for the state Health Department. ``This administration
has been fighting for this change for years and the Clintons have
not said boo about it since that veto. This is a credibility
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The criticism was echoed by the campaign staff of Rick A. Lazio,
Mrs. Clinton's opponent in the New York race for the United States
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a recycled broken promise,'' said Michael
Marr, Lazio's spokesman. ``Mrs. Clinton has been in a position of
influence for 7{ years and never spoke out on this issue. Now she
is having a deathbed conversion for the need to convert this
formula.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the current formula, the state and New York City generally
split 50 percent of all Medicaid costs, with the federal government
picking up the other half. This calculation has long bothered
Democratic and Republican politicians in New York, who believe that
the state shoulders too much of the burden and that its costs are
greater than those of other states.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, whose seat Mrs. Clinton desires,
has made many proposals over the years to change the formula in New
York's favor. Mrs. Clinton, whose plan involves the federal
government's picking up a 56 percent share of the state's total
costs, said this week that an expected increase in the federal
budget surplus would make her plan more viable than those of
previous years.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki officials say their attack on Mrs. Clinton's plan has
nothing to do with the governor's support for Lazio, and that their
ire is molded by policy rather than politics. ``This has been an
issue for us for the last five years,'' said Robert Hinckley, the
state's deputy commissioner for operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a large urban poor population and our taxpayers are
footing the bill for other states,'' he said. In an example, he
cited Arkansas as a state that receives 72 cents on the dollar from
Washington for its Medicaid expenditures. ``This is an issue for us
every single year,'' Hinckley said.
</P>
<P>
   Had Mrs. Clinton suggested that the current spending formula be
left as is, the Pataki administration would have been equally
unhappy, he conceded. ``We would have been opposed to that, too,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's staff disputed the assertion that the Balanced
Budget Act of 1995, which President Clinton vetoed, would have
allocated more federal Medicaid money for New York. Further, her
staff questioned why the state was bringing up the issue at all.
``It sounds like a political attack and they don't have their facts
straight,'' said Howard Wolfson, Mrs. Clinton's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   And he questioned the Health Department's motives in
conspicuously releasing a critique of the first lady's plan. ``I
can't imagine that this has anything to do with Governor Pataki's
support for Rick Lazio, because that would be a misuse of
government resources on behalf of a political campaign,'' Wolfson
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a fashion, both camps' accounts are factual. Under a
complicated formula in the 1995 bill, New York would have received
more money for Medicaid. But the bill also set a cap on how much
money each state would get each year. That amount would have risen
at roughly the rate of inflation, even though Medicaid spending was
then outpacing inflation. So in effect, New York would have ended
up footing a larger percentage of each year's Medicaid bill.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the overall Medicaid budget, as well as that for
Medicare, was reduced under the bill, cuts the president criticized
when he vetoed it. New York's hospitals and health care workers
strongly opposed the bill as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We very much wanted it to be vetoed,'' said David Rich, a
senior vice president at the Greater New York Hospital Association.
``There was a lot in it not to like.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
