<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL NEWS AND NOTES FROM AROUND THE NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NADER WORRIES GORE CAMP
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore's new campaign chairman, William M.
Daley, says that Ralph Nader, the Green Party presidential nominee,
poses a threat to Gore's campaign, and allies inside and outside
the campaign have made informal overtures to some key Nader
supporters. ``There's been some discussions,'' Daley told the
Associated Press on Tuesday, ``kind of just, `What is this? Why are
you over there?' Nothing official where we've approached the
candidate.'' Nader says at least three of his ``celebrity
supporters'' have been contacted, one by the vice president
himself, but he refuses to name them. Nader is drawing less than 10
percent in most presidential polls and is given no real chance of
winning. But he could hurt Gore because much of the support he has
appears to come at Gore's expense, especially in swing states.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE COMMITTEES ARE FLUSH
</P>
<P>
   The Republican and Democratic Senate campaign committees
released their June 30 fund-raising figures yesterday, with both
showing big bank balances. The Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee said it had $27 million in the bank on June 30 after
having raised $49 million since January 1999. The National
Republican Senatorial Committee reported $21 million cash on hand
at the end of June, having raised $55.7 million in this election
cycle. Both said they had more cash on hand at this point in the
election calendar than they had ever had in previous elections.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL GROUPS UNCLOAKED
</P>
<P>
   Political groups that until now have enjoyed the anonymity and
secrecy of Section 527 of the tax code will have to file disclosure
forms with the IRS by July 31. Moving quickly to implement a law
passed by Congress and signed by President Clinton on July 1, the
IRS sent word Wednesday to groups operating under Section 527 that
they must disclose their existence and intent to operate under the
tax provision, which governs political committees. The new law
requires such groups to disclose their contributors, spending and
the identities of senior officers, effective July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ADS STAR BUSH ON ABORTION
</P>
<P>
   Planned Parenthood plans $2.5 million in television advertising
spotlighting Gov. George W. Bush's anti-abortion views, hoping to
reach independent and Republican women who support abortion rights.
The group says its research suggests that many women respect
Planned Parenthood but are leaning toward Bush. ``We're focusing on
those `compassionate conservative' Republican and independent women
who are very pro-choice,'' said Gloria Feldt, president of the
Planned Parenthood Action Fund, the group's political arm. ``They
believe us when we tell them about George W. Bush's position. These
are the women who elected Bill Clinton twice.'' The first
advertisement will run nationally on cable TV beginning on Monday
and through the Republican National Convention, July 31-Aug. 3.
</P>
<P>
   GOP DUO PLAN BUS TOUR
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, the former Republican presidential hopeful,
will be revving up his Straight Talk Express this fall _ for House
Republican congressional candidates in at least half a dozen swing
states. McCain, a Republican of Arizona, and Rep. J.C. Watts of
Oklahoma, the fourth-ranking House Republican, are planning to team
up after their party's convention in Philadelphia later this month
to campaign by bus on behalf of candidates several states,
including Ohio, California, Florida, New York, Illinois and
Michigan. The campaign seeks to exploit the appeal of McCain and
Watts, the only Republican African-African in Congress, with
independents and other swing voters. The two would conduct their
bus tour in August and October, when Congress is out of session.
McCain and Watts will also start a Web site featuring online chats
with the two Republican leaders from their bus.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Pittsburgh and East Brunswick, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Green Bay, Wis., and Saginaw, Mich.
</P>
</TEXT>
