<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ORDERS IRAN TO PAY IN TWO DEATHS  

</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a ruling that may be largely symbolic, a federal judge has
ordered the government of Iran to pay $327 million to the families
of a New Jersey woman and a Connecticut man who were killed in a
1996 terrorist bombing in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the families of the victims, Sara Duker, who was 23, and
Matthew Eisenfeld, 25, ever see any of the money depends on several
factors, including whether legislation allowing the families to
seize Iranian assets in the United States is approved, and whether
the Clinton administration, which has blocked the families'
efforts, reverses its position that those efforts are counter to
national interests.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Eisenfeld's father, Dr. Leonard Eisenfeld, and
lawyers involved in his and similar cases, said they were concerned
about the government's admission, in a June 23 letter, that the
Treasury Department had destroyed documents being sought by lawyers
in an effort to locate Iranian assets in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The documents, which the government said were inadvertently
destroyed during a renovation and downsizing of the Treasury's
Office of Foreign Asset Control in Washington, involved more than
800 licensing applications to do business in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The documents had been subpoenaed in relation to the case of
Alisa Flatow, a student from New Jersey who died in a 1995 bombing
in Israel, but could have been relevant to the Duker and Eisenfeld
case, as well as other claims against Iran, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Other victims of terrorism and their families have been awarded
judgments against Iran, including $247.5 million in 1998 to
Flatow's family and $341 million to Terry Anderson, a journalist
held hostage by an Iranan-backed group in Lebanon. Those victims
still have not received any money.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenfeld, a neonatal specialist in West Hartford, Conn., said
he was ``encouraged'' by Tuesday's ruling, issued by Judge Royce C.
Lamberth in U.S. District Court in Washington, but not joyful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always have mixed feelings because for this particular issue
I don't like to be in the public eye. On the other hand, the issue
is worth it to deter terrorism and it's something that my family
and Sara Duker's family are interested in,'' Eisenfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not understand the government's opposition to the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it seems like almost a no-brainer that if countries are
doing terrorist activities in order to advance their political
agenda,'' he said, ``that we cut off their economic resources to
block their future terrorist activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Sara Duker's mother, Arlene Duker, could not be reached for
comment, but her lawyer, Thomas Fortune Fay, said he was happy
about the decision, despite the uncertainties surrounding it.
</P>
<P>
   Duker, who lived in Teaneck, N.J., and Eisenfeld were among 25
people who died in a suicide bombing of a bus on Feb. 25, 1996 in
Jerusalem. An Iranian-backed terrorist group, Hamas, has claimed
responsibility for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Miller, the Justice Department spokesman for the case,
was not available for comment on Wednesday, his office said, and
the State and Treasury departments did not return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have voiced concern that, in addition
to complicating relations between the two countries, allowing
individuals to claim Iranian diplomatic property could would invite
similar claims on United States property abroad.
</P>
</TEXT>
