<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK KILLS ARMS DEAL WITH CHINA AFTER PRESSURE BY U.S. 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Editors: Includes trim indicators) 
 
By GREG McDONALD 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Under pressure from Congress and the Clinton
administration, Israel called off the sale of a military radar
plane to China on Wednesday as negotiations aimed at finalizing an
Israeli-Palestinian peace accord continued at the Camp David
presidential retreat near here.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, encamped at the compound with
President Clinton and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, announced
his decision to abort the controversial $250 million sale of the
Phalcon aircraft shortly before the leaders opened their second day
of discussions.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli spokesman said Barak expressed ``sorrow'' about the
action in a letter to Chinese President Jiang Zemin, explaining
that it would be difficult to allow the sale to go through while
Israel ``is in the midst of an effort to achieve historic decisions
related to her vital interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Israeli officials denied that Barak had succumbed to
U.S. security concerns about the sale, they acknowledged that the
strong objections from Clinton and congressional leaders were taken
into account.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been an important issue to us and a subject of
continuing discussion at a variety of levels of the government,
including between the president and the prime minister. We are
pleased to see that they've taken our security concerns into
account in making this decision,'' White House press secretary Joe
Lockhart said during a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
   The pending sale of the Phalcon, similar to an American AWACS
plane, had been a concern as well on Capitol Hill, where Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and others had begun to
question whether Congress would be willing to provide the financial
assistance that will be needed to help the peace process succeed.
American aid will play a key role in paying for the possible
relocation of both Palestinian refugees and Israeli settlers if an
agreement can be achieved at Camp David. Military aid to help beef
up Israeli security after a deal is also at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is keenly aware that Congress will in many ways control
the purse strings of a final deal. So it was no surprise that he
not only informed Clinton of his decision to cancel the advanced
airborne warning system sale, but telephoned Lott as well.
</P>
<P>
   The United States had insisted that Israel scrap the sale
because of tensions between China and Taiwan and out of concern
that Beijing might use the sophisticated radar plane to track
American aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sonny Callahan, R-Ala., chairman of the appropriations
subcommittee on foreign operations, even threatened to cut aid to
Israel by $250 million, roughly the cost of one high-tech aircraft,
if the sale weren't canceled.
</P>
<P>
   While the Israeli announcement won U.S. praise, a Palestinian
official irritated U.S. officials when he turned up outside the
summit press center, housed at the elementary school in Thurmont,
and began talking to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official interrupted Nabil Amr, a Palestinian
Cabinet minister, in front of television cameras and accused him of
breaking the news blackout that Clinton, Barak and Arafat agreed to
before the start of their talks on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am only analyzing and repeating the known Palestinian
positions,'' Amr replied.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Lockhart would say only that the three leaders had
met again several times Wednesday in various formats, and had
touched on all of the core issues that have prevented the two sides
from finalizing the agreement they signed under the Oslo accords
seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The thorniest of the issues are where to draw the final
boundaries of a Palestinian state and how to redraw Jerusalem to
make room for a Palestinian capital. The two sides also have to
decide what to do about the 3 million Palestinian refugees who have
fled the region since Israel became a state in 1948, and the 40,000
Israeli settlers living in occupied territories scheduled to be
returned to Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of a substantive progress report, Lockhart spent
the day discussing atmospherics with reporters, telling them that
the informal living and working conditions at Camp David is adding
``some value to these discussions'' by bringing both sides closer
together.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the layout of the cabins at the presidential compound
makes it nearly impossible for the two sides to avoid each other
even when they're not working. Lockhart said they are not only
dining together in a common hall, but are often seen meeting
informally at various locations on the grounds and whipping about
in golf carts, the preferred mode of transportation at the
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart was quick to point out, however, that the friendly and
cordial atmosphere should not be taken to mean that the talks are
on the verge of a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was expected to leave the talks briefly this morning to
deliver a speech at the annual convention of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People in Baltimore and
then attend an awards ceremony at the U.S. Capitol. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright will oversee the discussions with Arafat
and Barak until the president returns this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   One White House official said Clinton believes that leaving
Barak and Arafat alone to talk from time to time might enhance the
chances of a breakthrough. But nonetheless, this official said,
Clinton has prepared a number of proposals to help bridge the
differences between them, which he may present later today. This
official, however, declined to give any details of what the
proposals will include.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said he would like to have at least the outline of
an agreement ready by July 19 when he departs for the so-called
Group of Eight economic summit in Japan. But the deadline Clinton
is most concerned about is Sept. 13, when Arafat has threatened to
unilaterally declare a Palestinian state in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip if a final settlement has not been reached.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
