<HEADLINE>
OBITUARIES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peter M. Cicchino, 39, a Professor of Law &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peter M. Cicchino, a professor of constitutional law and
jurisprudence at American University in Washington, died July 8 at
his home in the capital. He was 39.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was colon cancer, said his companion, Jonathan
Springer.
</P>
<P>
   Cicchino was born in Kearny, N.J., and graduated magna cum laude
in political science and philosophy from the University of Scranton
in 1982. He received a master's degree in philosophy at Fordham
University in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   From 1982 to 1988, as a lay member of the Jesuit order, he
served in prisons, hospitals, homeless shelters and soup kitchens,
working especially with young people. After earning his law degree
at Harvard University in 1992, he was a staff counsel on the
Lesbian and Gay Rights Project of the American Civil Liberties
Union in New York City and the founding director of a similar
program at the Urban Justice Center.
</P>
<P>
   A specialist in public-interest law and laws affecting the
needy, he taught in the Program on Lawyering at New York University
Law School before joining the faculty of American University's
Washington College of Law in 1998. The college honored him at a
conference in May and announced the establishment of an annual
Peter M. Cicchino Award for Outstanding Service in the Public
Interest.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Springer, Cicchino is survived by his parents, Peter A.
and Mary Jane Cicchino of Kearny; three sisters, Sally Rooney, Jane
Goretski and Jill Cicchino, also of Kearny; and a brother, William,
of Cranford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Ronne Wohl Wulwick, 85, Founder of Jewish Outreach Group
</P>
<P>
   Ronne Wohl Wulwick, a founder of Hineni, an outreach group that
encourages young Jews to reconnect to their heritage, died July 8
at her home in Old Westbury, N.Y. She was 85.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, her family said.
</P>
<P>
   Wulwick, a Bronx native who also lived in Palm Beach, Fla.,
helped establish Hineni in the early 1970s and remained an active
member. The organization is based in the Hineni Heritage Center on
the Upper West Side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Wulwick was also involved in Fight for Sight, an organization
that fosters vision research, and was active in groups for teen-age
suicide prevention. She helped raise money for Hadassah, the
Anti-Defamation League and the United Jewish Appeal. She also
helped start a fund-raising campaign for Long Island Jewish
Hospital in Hyde Park, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Wulwick's first husband, Joseph S. Wohl, to whom she was married
for 46 years, died in 1979. She is survived by Sam Wulwick, whom
she married in 1988; three daughters, Elinor Wohl of Manhattan,
Nancy Drake of Aspen, Colo., and Vicki Greenberg of Lawrence, N.Y.;
a son, Larry W. Wohl of Manhattan; a brother, Jack Jaffess of
Miami; and seven grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
