<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT POST IS SOLD ALONG WITH 5 SMALLER PAPERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Colo.)   By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. _ The Toronto-based company that owns The
Connecticut Post, the state's second-largest daily newspaper, said
Wednesday that it would sell the paper and five community
newspapers in Fairfield County to a chain based in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The Post's owner, Thomson Corp., did not disclose terms of the
sale to MediaNews Group _ a deal that had interested several of the
country's major newspaper companies. The Post's suburban market is
one of the wealthiest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut Post, which was called The Bridgeport Post until
1992, has a daily circulation of about 76,000, second in the state
to The Hartford Courant, which has a daily circulation of about
216,000. The Courant was also sold this year as part of Tribune
Co.'s acquisition of Times Mirror Co.
</P>
<P>
   MediaNews Group, which owns 130 newspapers in 13 states,
including The Denver Post, said it did not plan to make any staff
or management changes at the Connecticut newspapers, which include
weekly papers in Westport, Fairfield, Norwalk and Darien, and a
monthly publication called Inside Fairfield County.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, MediaNews announced that it had sold 4 daily
newspapers and 40 weekly newspapers in southern New Jersey and
Pennsylvania. William Dean Singleton, the president of MediaNews,
said the proceeds would be used to acquire the Connecticut papers
in a tax-free exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came down to size and position in the market,'' Singleton
said Wednesday. ``The New Jersey newspapers were scattered and were
small and were not in dominant positions and this is one larger
daily in a dominant position, and quite frankly in a better
market.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the Connecticut publications completes Thomson's
divestment of its newspaper holdings in the United States, which
had included 49 daily papers. Combined proceeds from all of the
sales totaled about $2.4 billion, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson announced earlier this year that it would leave the
newspaper business, except for publishing The Globe &AMP; Mail, its
flagship property in Toronto, which circulates throughout Canada.
The company is focusing on its fast-growing, Internet-based
information management businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph J. Lodovic, a spokesman for MediaNews Group, said that
the company had not been actively searching to buy newspapers in
Connecticut but that it became interested after Thomson's
negotiations with other potential buyers began to stall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sort of fell into our lap,'' Lodovic said.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Tribune Co. became the dominant newspaper company in
Connecticut when it reached a deal to buy Times Mirror, the parent
company of The Hartford Courant, The Advocate of Stamford and
Greenwich Time. Those papers have a combined weekday circulation of
more than 250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson Newspapers had purchased The Bridgeport Post and The
Telegram, evening and morning sister newspapers, in June 1988 for
$210 million from Post Holding, a company controlled by the Pfriem
and Flicker families.
</P>
<P>
   The name of the newspaper was changed in June 1992. The editors
said it was done to help the newspaper appeal to a wider audience.
But critics said the change was designed to cut ties with the city
of Bridgeport, which was suffering from high crime and deep
financial woes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
