u a BC-NY-CAB-VIOLENCE-NYT     07-12 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CAB-VIOLENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI SIGNS LAW TOUGHENING SENTENCES FOR LIVERY-CAB CRIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  By JOHN W. FOUNTAIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tougher sentencing laws have long been used to deter
violent crimes against minority groups or those in dangerous public
jobs, like police officers. But Wednesday, Gov. George Pataki
signed into law a bill meant to deter violence against a private
occupation: livery-cab drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was in response to the killings of 10 livery-cab
drivers this year. Pataki announced the signing at a news
conference at the offices of Seaman Radio Dispatch, a livery
company in the Washington Heights section of Manhattan, where he
was joined by the families of slain drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is in a sense a sad day,'' the Republican governor said,
``because when I look out in the front row I see the widows of
people, immigrants that came to this country with a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure directs judges to add three to five years to the
minimum sentence of anyone convicted of committing certain violent
crimes against on-duty livery-cab drivers, as well as yellow-cab
drivers and drivers with black car limousine services. The covered
crimes include assault, manslaughter, attempted murder and robbery.
The sentencing changes take effect Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   It is unusual for legislators to single out a private occupation
for protection, said Burt Newborne, a professor at New York
University School of Law. Laws of this sort have typically been
adopted for classes of people considered vulnerable to violence,
like members of ethnic groups or gays, who are protected by
hate-crime laws, he said, or government officials like tax
collectors, police officers and prison guards.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tradition in criminal law of identifying vulnerable
groups, particularly classes of people, for these types of
protections, in the hope that they will increase the deterrent, but
it's rare,'' Newborne said. ``It's extremely rare that it is done
by profession.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure is the latest attempt by public officials to help
New York City's estimated 41,000 livery-cab drivers, who work in
poor, high-crime neighborhoods where yellow cabs seldom venture.
They ``perform an enormously important service,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the livery-cab business praised the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not only right, it's fair,'' said Fernando A. Mateo,
president of the New York State Federation of Taxi Drivers, which
represents 15,000 livery drivers.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, several of the widows, surrounded by
their children, broke down in tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want justice,'' said Maria Lopez, whose husband, Cesar
Lopez, 42, was killed in Brooklyn in April. ``They have to make
people pay for what they did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
