<HEADLINE>
DNA TESTS OK'D FOR 2 MORE ON TEXAS DEATH ROW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Two more condemned men in Texas will get new DNA
testing in efforts to exonerate them, including one felon who had
been scheduled to die Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gray County District Attorney John Mann said Wednesday he has
decided to conduct additional DNA testing in the case of Henry
``Hank'' Skinner, who was convicted in a 1993 triple homicide.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Bexar County District Attorney Susan D. Reed joined
defense lawyers in asking that the execution of Caruthers Alexander
be postponed so that DNA tests could be performed. Alexander, 51,
was sentenced to die for the 1981 rape and strangulation of a San
Antonio waitress.
</P>
<P>
   His execution had been set for Wednesday. Instead, Orien Cecil
Joiner was put to death last night for the 1986 murders of two
women who lived in the apartment next to him in Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors' decisions, made independently of one another,
reflect a growing acceptance of DNA testing, said Maurie Levin of
the Texas Defender Project, a group that represents condemned
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is becoming more and more widely recognized that it is
important to have procedures in place to facilitate DNA testing,''
Levin said.
</P>
<P>
   There is a ``recognition . . . that the system is fallible and
makes mistakes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The additional DNA testing in the Skinner and Alexander cases
comes just six weeks after Gov. George W. Bush agreed to postpone
the execution of Ricky McGinn for further DNA testing in that case.
The reprieve was the first-ever during the Bush administration and
came just minutes before McGinn was to receive the lethal
injection.
</P>
<P>
   USA Today reported Wednesday that preliminary results of those
additional DNA tests failed to clear McGinn of the 1995 rape and
murder of his 12-year-old stepdaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper quoted anonymous sources close to the case as
saying the FBI test results point to McGinn or a maternal relative
as the source of a pubic hair found inside the body of Stephanie
Flanary. No other member of McGinn's family has been linked to the
case.
</P>
<P>
   McGinn's lawyers have the option of submitting the evidence to
separate labs for additional analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The USA Today report heartened the slain child's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me a little inspiration that justice is going to be
served _ not just for satisfaction of the murderer of my own
daughter to be killed,'' but also for victims of McGinn's other
crimes, said Steve Flanary, Stephanie's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've prayed and I've thought and I've prayed throughout the
last seven years and came to peace of mind that it's OK for me to
seek the man's justice and it's also all right for me to go ahead
and ask the Lord to forgive his soul that he may go in to heaven,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush declined to comment Wednesday on the McGinn case, saying he
would honor a court-imposed gag order.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors spared Bush from having to decide whether Skinner
and Alexander deserved reprieves.
</P>
<P>
   Mann did not wait for defense attorneys to request additional
DNA tests in court. Instead, he decided to have a private lab
conduct the tests to end ``speculation and public hysteria'' about
the case, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mann said it will be at least a week before he can get DNA
evidence to an independent lab and ``God only knows'' how long
before results will be known.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner's attorneys are leery of Mann's offer. The attorneys
wrote to Mann on Wednesday saying they would oppose any DNA testing
conducted without court supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Steve Losch of Longview said he fears Mann will destroy
the evidence if it comes back in Skinner's favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't trust John Mann to tell me the time of day,'' Losch
said. ``He is the least trustworthy prosecutor I've ever run into,
with the possible exception of (an assistant prosecutor) in
Lubbock.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner, 38, was sentenced to die for bludgeoning his live-in
girlfriend, Twila Jean Busby, 40, with an ax handle and fatally
stabbing her two mentally impaired sons, 22-year-old Elwin Caler
and Randy Busby, 20. The murders occurred Jan. 1, 1994, at Busby's
home in the Panhandle city of Pampa.
</P>
<P>
   Mann insists there is strong physical evidence linking Skinner
to the murders, including DNA tests of blood on Skinner's clothes
that ties him to two of the victims and a bloody palm print on a
door.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner contends he is innocent. He said he passed out after a
night of drinking and awoke to find the family murdered, which
would explain how he got the victims' blood on his clothes, Losch
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mann said demands by defense lawyers for additional DNA testing
have ``almost reached the point of hysteria.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush ``brought a lot of this on with his statement'' that no
innocent person has been executed in Texas while he was governor,
Mann said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those pushing for new DNA tests in the Skinner case is a
class of journalism students from Northwestern University near
Chicago. The students conducted their own investigation of the case
and claim they have uncovered evidence implicating someone else in
the crime.
</P>
<P>
   The students want hair found in Busby's hand, skin from under
her fingernails and the contents of a rape kit collected at the
scene to undergo additional DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   In the Alexander case, District Attorney Reed went along with a
defense request for further tests on hair samples in evidence. DNA
testing was unavailable at the time of Alexander's 1982 trial.
</P>
<P>
   Reed acknowledged the evidence against Alexander is
circumstantial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I don't think district attorneys who put up a
fight (about post-conviction DNA testing) are doing themselves a
favor,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in the McGinn case, where the victim's family protested
the delay posed by testing, the family of 19-year-old Lori Bruch
did not object in the Alexander case, Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't want to have to go through the Huntsville
circus,'' she said of protests that have been carried out at the
Texas state prison during executions of some high-profile cases.
</P>
<P>
   While only a very few death row cases are being subjected to
post-conviction DNA testing at this point, Skinner's attorney is
hopeful there will be more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the battle is virtually won,'' Losch said. ``I think
there is now a social and almost political consensus this testing
needs to be done, and if it wasn't it needs to be done before you
put someone to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle reporter R.G. Ratcliffe contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
