<HEADER>
A0596 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-WHITMAN-NYT     07-12 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WHITMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GOVERNOR WHITMAN'S GAFFE 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, July 13:
</P>
<P>
   A startling photograph has surfaced showing Gov. Christine Todd
Whitman of New Jersey grinning and frisking a black man who has his
hands up and is facing a wall. The picture was taken on a night in
1996 when she accompanied state troopers who were patrolling in
Camden. The man she frisked had apparently already been searched by
the troopers for weapons and drugs and then handed over to the
governor. The man had not been accused of any crime.
</P>
<P>
   The picture has caused a furor, and Whitman is now criticizing
her critics for taking the picture ``out of context.'' But the fact
remains that the posed look of the photograph and Whitman's smiling
expression add up to the appearance of a gratuitous insult. The
controversy over the photo may also help explain why Whitman has
had so much trouble putting the political problem of racial
profiling by New Jersey state troopers behind her.
</P>
<P>
   One reason the issue will not disappear is that racial profiling
_ the targeting and searching of motorists based solely on race _
has gone on for years, despite denials by political leaders like
Whitman. Also, the anger and mistrust in minority communities over
this issue are deeply rooted, despite Whitman's subsequent
acknowledgment of the problem and her efforts to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   The photograph simply feeds that anger and mistrust. Whitman
insists the episode had nothing to do with racial profiling. But
that does not change the fact that the man in the picture was
treated callously by the person who is chiefly responsible for
setting the direction and tone of law enforcement in the state.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, Whitman was the first New Jersey governor to
acknowledge that state troopers had engaged in systematic racial
profiling. In the past year she began efforts to combat profiling
as part of a consent decree entered into between the state and the
Justice Department. She has also conceded that state police
commanders have tolerated racial and sexual discrimination against
minority and female officers. In the face of numerous lawsuits
brought by former state troopers, she has ordered an overhaul of
the agency's hiring and promotion practices and its command
structure.
</P>
<P>
   But those bureaucratic reforms do not take the sting out of the
photo. Whitman's refusal to apologize for the conduct in the photo
adds to public skepticism that her administration will
energetically crack down on illegal policing practices. A lawyer
for two troopers who have been criminally charged for shooting
three unarmed minority men on the New Jersey Turnpike has already
said the photo would be used to support their contention that
racial profiling was encouraged by the police leadership. If the
governor cares to heal the mistrust, she needs to show that she
understands why the picture is offensive to so many people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0448 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0722 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-     07-12 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TO NAACP CONVENTION: `IT'S GOOD TO BE HOME' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Calif., Colo.)   (Eds: SUBS 8th graf, Gore's appearance ..., to CORRECT Bush's
percentage of black vote in poll to 17 percent, add CBS News to
poll.) 
By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ From his opening salutation _ ``I am a member of the
NAACP; it's good to be home'' _ to his closing motivational cry _
``I'm not asking you to read my lips; I'm asking you to read my
heart!'' _ a spirited Al Gore summoned black voters Wednesday to
support his presidential candidacy, reminding them of his long
commitment to their cause and deriding Gov. George W. Bush as
offering only words, not action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have come here not just in an election year, but year after
year,'' the vice president told several hundred members of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, the
nation's largest civil rights organization. ``I have worked with
you. I have stood with you. I am proud to have won some battles
alongside you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's message, threaded thickly with his policy positions, was
in deliberate counterpoint to Bush's speech to the same group on
Monday, when the Texas governor was criticized by many in the
organization who said he offered only breezy generalities. Bush was
the first Republican presidential candidate to court the NAACP
since his father spoke to the group in 1988; still, the governor
received a tepid response compared with the rousing and repeated
standing ovations that Gore drew Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president delved into details, from his support of
affirmative action and hate-crimes legislation to jobs and
education. He said he would defend affirmative action ``because it
is still needed in this country'' and it is ``good for our
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   He reiterated his opposition to raising the retirement age for
Social Security benefits and to Bush's proposal to divert some
Social Security investment into the stock market. Gore talked of
his support for a patient's bill of rights, gun control and a full
count of people in the census as opposed to sampling.
</P>
<P>
   Invoking the heroes of black history, from Frederick Douglass
and Harriet Tubman to Thurgood Marshall and Rosa Parks, Gore
promised to ban racial profiling so that people would not be pulled
over simply for ``driving while black.'' ``I will make the DWB
offense obsolete in America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He castigated Bush for invoking the notion of ``state's rights''
to avoid taking a position on whether South Carolina should remove
the Confederate battle flag from the Statehouse. And he reminded
his listeners of his longtime commitment to their concerns. ``I
have made more trips to Africa than I have to Asia,'' the vice
president said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's appearance came amid some concern among his staff members
that blacks have been left dispirited by the campaign. Black voters
account for about 15 percent of the electorate, and they usually
support Democrats overwhelmingly. A New York Times/CBS News Poll in
May showed Gore with 69 percent of the black vote and about 17
percent  &UR;  &LR; for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But President Clinton, by contrast, has more than a 90-percent
approval rating among black voters. Analysts said Gore could
probably claim that level of support by Election Day, but
questioned the commitment of black voters to get to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   David Bositis, chief pollster for the Joint Center for Political
and Economic Studies, said: ``He'll get 90-95 percent of the black
vote. The larger question for Gore really is black turnout as
opposed to his share of the black vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Bositis said Gore would inherit the good relations with blacks
that the president had built up, stemming from the record economic
expansion, low unemployment among blacks, numerous appointments of
blacks to administration positions and falling crime rates.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Bositis said, Bush's message of being a ``different kind
of Republican'' was aimed less at winning over black voters than
white swing voters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added, overall turnout in November is likely to be
low, precisely because the economy is doing so well, and Gore's
challenge is to activate his base, which he has had some difficulty
doing. While polls show Bush winning the support of 90 percent of
Republicans, Gore has the support of only about 70 percent of
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's event was aimed at drumming up enthusiasm among
voters who should be squarely behind him.
</P>
<P>
   This was evident in the introduction of Gore by William Lucy, an
NAACP board member, who said, ``Al Gore, unlike a lot of other
people, has not just discovered the NAACP.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucy also noted Gore's lineage as the son of Sen. Albert Gore,
who supported most civil rights legislation (though he did not back
the Civil Rights Act of 1964). ``He has drawn from that deep well
of public consciousness given to him by his father,'' Lucy said.
</P>
<P>
   And Lucy set a robustly partisan tone, although the NAACP cannot
endorse candidates because of its tax exempt status. In noting that
the Clinton administration had nominated 57 black judges to the
federal bench, he added, ``not a single Clarence Thomas among
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore easily assumed command of the audience. In imploring his
listeners to work hard to help the Democrats recapture the House,
Gore said: ``I want you to consider how much we can get done by
taking back the Congress, how much justice will be redeemed when
John Conyers is chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, how much
economic progress will be made when Charlie Rangel is chairman of
the Ways and Means Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   To gales of laughter, he prompted delegates to their feet with a
cadenced ridicule of Bush's talk of compassionate conservatism _
``Talk doesn't cost much,'' he said _ compared to his own record of
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that you heard some nice-sounding words on Monday
afternoon,'' Gore said. ``But I remembered what scripture teaches
in the Book of James, Chapter 2, Verse 18: `Yay, a man may say thou
hast faith, and I have works. Show me thy faith without thy works,
and I will show thee my faith BY my works.'''
</P>
<P>
   And he faulted Bush for repeated failures to respond to minority
voters, at one point offering a dramatized rendition of an imagined
chilly, monosyllabic Bush response _ ``No'' _ to the family of
James Byrd, a black man dragged to his death in Texas in 1998, when
the family asked the governor to support legislation against hate
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   NAACP officials seemed thrilled with Gore's performance. Julian
Bond, the chairman, said flatly: ``The vice president had substance
and Governor Bush had a drive-by photo opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Kweisi Mfume, the president of the organization, said he
appreciated the fact that Bush spoke to the group, but acknowledged
Gore's edge. ``Al Gore is pretty much a family member,'' Mfume
said. He told reporters he could forgive Gore's support for the
death penalty _ a subject the vice president did not raise _
because his stand was principled and not political.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates to the convention were pleased too. ``He's
beautiful,'' said Faye Sandle, 64, of Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Watson, 55, a meat cutter from Monterey, Calif., said, ``I
believe Gore is more for the people. I like what he said about
affirmative action, jobs and investing back in the communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Edith McDougald, 57, an elementary school teacher from Glen
Burnie, Md., said that she would not hold Gore's support for the
death penalty against him, since that was the only area where she
disagreed with him. ``Bush's reaction to the executions will be in
the negative for him,'' she said, referring to the recent execution
of a black man in Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 2311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0449 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0725 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WVA-SLAYING-BIAS-1STL     07-12 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WVA-SLAYING-BIAS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOURNERS INSIST SLAYING OF GAY BLACK MAN WAS A BIAS CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to give population of Fairmont, change locator
to Charleston; SUBS 4th graf, Stricker played ..., to change
`homophobic' to anti-gay.) 
By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRMONT, W.Va. _ At the edge of the crowd of mourners, a chorus
of Bible-quoting protesters began sounding off behind a police
cordon, proclaiming that the victim of a grisly fatal beating last
week, a young gay black man, had been dispatched to hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homosexuality is an enormous sin _ Read Leviticus 21:8,''
proclaimed one of the less vulgar signs bobbing at the fringe of
the street scene.
</P>
<P>
   David Stricker, a husky, 48-year-old local resident who is gay,
knew what he had to do. He strapped on an oversized pair of
theater-prop wings and used them to most politely block the
protesters' view of an otherwise peaceful evening memorial on
Tuesday in this city of about 20,000 people 115 miles northeast of
Charleston, the state capital. ``They say they're coming in the
name of God, but they're coming in the name of hatred,'' he quietly
explained above the protesters' din.
</P>
<P>
   Stricker played the protective angel, an anti-heckler role being
seen increasingly at gay rights gatherings. He helped reduce the
small band of anti-gay visitors to a minor nuisance on an
extraordinary night for this rural county seat in which hundreds of
gays and lesbians, blacks and whites, stood together in the streets
and demanded justice on behalf of Arthur Warren Jr., whose beaten
body was found last week on a back road near Paw Paw Creek.
</P>
<P>
   Warren, 26, was openly gay and his mourners, while conceding the
difficulty of plumbing the nature of hatred and homicide, demanded
a full investigation and disputed official insistence that neither
racism nor homophobia had been a motive in the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Warren was taken for a hit-and-run victim. But then a
conscience-stricken 16-year-old boy, who has not been charged in
the crime, went to the authorities. Two unidentified 17-year-old
white teen-agers were arrested and charged with the killing; the
authorities said the teen-agers beat and kicked Warren to death and
then drove a car over his body in an attempt to mask the crime.
</P>
<P>
   The battered corpse in an open coffin drew sobs and shrieks on
Saturday as local mourners demanded more information. Many were
incredulous when the police flatly insisted that hatred of gays and
blacks was not a motive in the slaying. Friends said Warren was a
gentle person and a church volunteer who had a summer park job and
other occasional employment. The friends said he occasionally told
of incidents of harassment stemming from both racial and sexual
bias.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no indication of a hate crime,'' Sheriff Ron Watkins
of Marion County said in a radio interview when asked about the
reported confessions of the defendants. ``There was no indication
anyone hated a particular group, especially gays,'' Watkins said.
He did not elaborate, saying the two teen-agers were subject to
closed juvenile proceedings until the court decides within the next
month whether they should be tried as adults.
</P>
<P>
   As human rights activists congregated from around the country,
members of the Tuesday night memorial crowd insisted that hatred
had to be at the heart of the slaying, whether it was racism,
homophobia or a combination of both. In any case, they heard
speakers complain that there were shortcomings in existing
hate-crime laws.
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia's hate-crime statute, like federal law, covers
race but not sexual orientation. A bill to remedy this passed the
state Senate but died in the House of Delegates earlier this year.
In Washington, a proposal pending in the Senate would include
sexual orientation under the hate-crime law and enable federal
prosecutors to step in when local authorities do not act.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dying from the inside out in this country because of
hatred,'' said Stricker, a social worker, his paper mache wings
stretched upward as he stood outside the county courthouse during
the memorial. ``We want this to be treated as a hate crime,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He argued, like many in the crowd of 400, that a clear law
against bias crimes would not be redundant in this first-degree
murder case and would be an object lesson against hateful practices
that can and do turn deadly.
</P>
<P>
   One speaker, David Smith of the Human Rights Campaign, a gay and
lesbian watchdog group, drew cheers as he told the crowd, ``There
is no doubt in our minds that hate was a factor in this crime _
hate based on sexual orientation and hate based on race.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in the crowd referred to their own experiences in
speculating about the hatred they insisted had to be at the heart
of the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason he was killed was because he was black,'' said
Lydia Robinson, a black woman who was born here and visits every
summer from Dearborn Heights, Mich. ``Being gay didn't help him
either, but if he had been white I don't think it would have gone
this far. Over the last 20 years I've seen a supremacy attitude
develop toward local blacks around here.''
</P>
<P>
   If convicted as juveniles, the two teen-agers could be freed by
age 21. If convicted as adults, they would face life in prison. In
the face of such extreme alternatives, plus the dearth of
information, the throng lighted candles, sang hymns and pledged
unity as they demanded that authorities not stint in prosecuting
the case against the victim, known to friends as ``J.R.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Ravenscroft, a white man and friend of the victim, told of
long-standing ties between some black and white families. Looking
over at the protest signs about hell, Ravenscroft declared, ``J.R.
Warren is my friend and where J.R. is right now is with love, and
the rest of us are just who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   In Grant Town, an old coal-mine hamlet near where Warren lived,
the Rev. Nelson Staples, his pastor at Mt. Beulah Baptist Church,
said ``J.R. was a gentle soul'' who confided in him some casual
instances of harassment that he was able to weather.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, the church has been firebombed, smeared with
racist epithets and shot at by night-riders, Staples said,
describing the incidents as ``this spirit of evil that occasionally
arises'' among some in the community.
</P>
<P>
   But he emphasized that the killing of Warren was the worst
possible reminder of the longstanding need for reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``J.R. had a great sense of humor but he must have lived a very
anguished life trying to find a place to fit in,'' Staples said, in
wondering whether the sudden burst of attention on Grant Town would
disappear just as suddenly as the crowd did after the memorial.
``One thing about J.R., he was always forgiving,'' the pastor
added. ``He was always forgiving.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
