A0728 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RUN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     07-12 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES HAS BENEFITED FROM HYPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Hype exploded out of the starting blocks, a little
too quickly if you ask us. We wouldn't be terribly surprised if all
of those involved in the race to anoint Marion Jones the breakout
performer of the 2000 Olympics are called back because of a false
start.
</P>
<P>
   The next 10 days will give the world's judges a clearer picture
with which to render their judgment. By the end of the U.S. Olympic
Track and Field Trials, which begin Friday at Cal State
Sacramento's Hornet Stadium, we'll know whether we and Mrs. Jones
jumped the gun in accepting the former Thousand Oaks resident's
pronouncement that she can win five gold medals in Sydney as if it
were a relay baton and running with it.
</P>
<P>
   No track athlete, male or female, has mined that much gold in
one Olympic fortnight, which is why the pursuit of history has been
her story for the past year. For those who lost track of Jones
after her Rio Mesa High and Thousand Oaks High days, it's possible
to get up to speed on her life by reading her recently published
biography or any number of magazine articles. Or you can dig the
basketball and track standout in bohemian television promotional
spots for her shoe-and-apparel company.
</P>
<P>
   It's all a bit dizzying. Lost in the publicity deluge is this
simple truth: Jones isn't the first female sprinter to try to run
down history at the Olympics, merely one of the first to attempt it
with Madison Avenue's full attention.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, a basketball player-turned-sprinter from a dusty town
in Georgia upset a U.S. teammate, Edith McGuire, whom she never
previously had beaten, to win the Olympic 100 meters. In Mexico
City four years later, Wyomia Tyus became the first Olympian, male
or female, to successfully defend the sprint when she prevailed in
the final of what was then the fastest field ever assembled.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, female athletes largely fell below the public's
radar. So there was no build-up for Tyus' feat; there was no shoe
company or network trumpeting her cause. In as much as people
mentioned her at all, it was to not-so-subtly suggest that Tyus, a
Tennessee State Tigerbelle, was too old to be chasing more Olympic
gold.
</P>
<P>
   Tyus was 23, one year younger than Jones is now, when she won
her second Olympic 100-meters crown in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   More than Jones' skin-tight hooded tracksuit, the advances that
have been made in her sport are manifested in the acceptance and
acclaim Jones wears like a birthmark. For perspective's sake, it's
worth remembering on the eve of these Trials a time not that long
ago when history wasn't rewarded before it was made and, in fact,
often got the short shrift afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Tyus had reason to wonder for the longest time whether her track
career wasn't one big riddle: If you make history but no one
notices, did you really do anything special?
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Tyus, an outdoor-education specialist with the Los
Angeles Unified School District, was tuned to the telecast of the
Summer Games in Seoul. She heard an announcer say American Carl
Lewis, the defending 100 meters champion, could become the first
sprinter to win back-to-back Olympic titles (he ultimately would
become the first male sprinter to do so after the apparent winner,
Ben Johnson, failed a drug test and was stripped of his gold
medal).
</P>
<P>
   Tyus didn't scream at the television. She simply laughed. What
else is a pioneer to do?
</P>
<P>
   By then Tyus was inured to slights. When she was chasing
history, she might as well have been running in a vacuum. ``Nobody
ever mentioned it,'' Tyus, a softspoken woman incapable of
self-aggrandizement, said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the Age of Aquarius was not to be confused with today's
Age of Awareness. ``If I look back at interviews,'' Tyus said, ``it
didn't really catch people's attention until years later, until
they really started to publicize women's sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyus wasn't just a step ahead of her competitors in 1968, she
was ahead of her time. To wit: Her clocking in Mexico City (11.08)
wasn't surpassed by an American in an Olympic final until 1984.
Thirty-two years later, Jones can break 11 seconds without breaking
a sweat. Her personal best in the 100 is 10.65, which is the
second-fastest time in history behind Florence Griffith-Joyner's
world record of 10.49 from the 1988 Olympic Trials.
</P>
<P>
   Tyus would be less than honest if she said she didn't
occasionally wonder how low she might have been able to go if she
had had the chance to continue running as a professional after
college, something that wasn't possible in her day when strict
rules of amateurism were enforced.
</P>
<P>
   She looks at the late Griffith-Joyner, who set the world
standard at the age of 28, and Merlene Ottey, who ran the 100
meters in 10.94 at the 1996 Games at 36 and is going strong at 40,
and ``I think, absolutely, what could I have done if I had had the
opportunity to stay with it?'' said Tyus, a naturalist who calls
the Angelus National Forest her office. ``I was not encouraged to
stay in the sport. There were people saying even before 1968 that I
was too old to be running. That just goes to show the state of mind
of people at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   That was then. Now we're perhaps a little too eager to mint
female sports icons. The sleek Jones is saddled with bloated
expectations at these Trials; a world is watching to see how she
manages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
