<HEADER>
A0730 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-MINORITIES-HEALTH-KAN     07-12 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITIES-HEALTH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITIES' HEALTH LAGS BEHIND THAT OF WHITE PEOPLE IN KC, DATA
SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ By almost every measure, the health of Kansas
City's African-American community lags far behind that of the
city's white population _ and the disparities are growing greater.
</P>
<P>
   A report issued Wednesday by the Kansas City Health Department
paints a statistical picture of minority groups that have not fully
benefited from a decade of improvements in health care.
</P>
<P>
   Over the period covered by the report, 1990 through 1998, black
Kansas City residents lived on average about 11 years less than
white residents. Their babies were three times more likely to die
in infancy. Their teen-agers were about 18 times more likely to be
homicide victims. And in adulthood, they had a 50 percent greater
chance of dying of heart disease or cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics fared better on many health measures, the report
found. But on average, they, too, died earlier than white people.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Council is expected to vote today on a
resolution establishing a mayor's minority health improvement task
force. The task force will make recommendations by March 2001 on
how to eliminate racial disparities in health.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are calling this issue to action,'' Health Department
Director Rex Archer told the council's Neighborhood Development
Committee on Wednesday. ``We are going to do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Archer said he hoped to have the task force appointed this
month. Eventually, it will involve hundreds of people in health
care, charitable organizations, businesses and church groups, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just city government. It's going to take every part
of our community to fix these problems,'' Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   The report findings parallel those of a recent report on the
health status of the Kansas City area issued jointly by the United
Auto Workers and Ford Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   Black people in the five-county area had an overall mortality
rate that was 63 percent higher than that of white people, the
UAW//Ford report found. And black people had higher death rates
from most chronic diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The divergent health status of racial and ethnic minorities and
white people long has been recognized as a serious and intractable
national problem.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, infant mortality rates are 2.5 times higher for
black people and 1.5 times higher for American Indians. Vietnamese
women suffer cervical cancer at nearly five times the rate of white
people, and Hispanics have two to three times the rate of stomach
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1998, President Clinton announced an initiative to
eliminate these disparities by 2010. He called for outreach
programs by the surgeon general's office, collaboration with
foundations and the strengthening of public health programs in such
areas as AIDS prevention, prostate cancer screening and diabetes
education.
</P>
<P>
   Some recent research suggests that doctors may not be treating
illnesses of minority members as intensively as they treat the
maladies of white patients.
</P>
<P>
   But the poorer health of minority members has much to do with
the disadvantages of poverty, such as poor education and little or
no health insurance, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the population we serve seeks health care at a
catastrophic point,'' said Benjamin Pettus, executive director of
the Samuel U. Rodgers Community Health Center, where many patients
are minority group members.
</P>
<P>
   That means patients often wait until a health problem becomes
critical before seeing doctors because they cannot afford regular
care, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Black people have higher cancer death rates at least in part
because they are diagnosed at later stages of their disease when
treatment is less effective, said Nancy Moylan, director of
outreach for the Heartland Division of the American Cancer Society
in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have equal access to a doctor or if you're poor
and don't have insurance, you're not going to use health care the
same way as someone well-to-do,'' Moylan said.
</P>
<P>
   By some available measures, the health status of minority
members in Kansas City was comparable to that in many other cities.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a report in 1997 by the Chicago Department of
Public Health found that the death rate among black people in
Kansas City was the 11th lowest among 44 cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's relatively good news,'' Archer said. ``But we clearly
want to be number one.''
</P>
<P>
   Archer said the task force probably would focus on seven problem
areas: cardiovascular disease, diabetes, infant mortality, AIDS and
sexually transmitted diseases, immunizations, cancer screening, and
management and injury prevention.
</P>
<P>
   To bring minority health up to that of white people may mean
catching a moving target. The health status of white people in
Kansas City appears to be improving steadily on some measures,
while that of minority groups has changed little.
</P>
<P>
   While the cancer death rate among white residents in Kansas City
declined by 24.2 percent from 1990 and 1998, it stayed the same for
black people.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of breast cancer, the death rate actually has been
increasing among black women while declining among white people.
</P>
<P>
   Over the same period, the stroke death rate among white people
decreased by 27 percent but remained steady among black people.
</P>
<P>
   Although new AIDS infections have been declining among all
racial groups, the decline has been less pronounced among black
people. They now account for more new AIDS infections in Kansas
City than any other group.
</P>
<P>
   Solving these problems will require the removal of barriers to
care such as a lack of transportation to a doctor's office or
clinic, and the lack of affordable care, Pettus said.
</P>
<P>
   And better education is needed about health risks and disease
prevention, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to really work to educate the population...that they
understand diseases for which they are at high risk,'' Pettus said.
</P>
<P>
   Some work along those lines already is under way in the Kansas
City area.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Kansas City Division of the American Heart
Association recently initiated a health promotion called ``Search
Your Heart'' in predominantly African-American churches.
</P>
<P>
   And the association also offers cooking classes and a cookbook,
Cooking South of the Border, with low-fat Mexican recipes.
</P>
<P>
   The Cancer Society has support groups geared specifically to
black people with breast and prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, the (health) messages haven't been culturally
sensitive,'' Moylan said. ``The messages were addressed to the
people who look like the members of the health-care system _ the
white middle class.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
