<SLUG> BC-LEGION-HONOR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN LEGION HONORS KC MAN FOR 80 YEARS OF MEMBERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN BURNES  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Front and center.
</P>
<P>
   That is where World War I veteran Urban Schick sat Wednesday
afternoon, as area officials of the American Legion lined up to
salute him at Bishop Spencer Place, a retirement-nursing center in
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Schick is the oldest known living member of the American Legion
with continuous membership, said Tony Curtis, adjutant of American
Legion Post 224, the Kansas City post that Schick joined in 1921.
</P>
<P>
   The American Legion formed only two years earlier, after the
conclusion of World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Schick's tenure is remarkable, said Del Snodgrass, state
commander of the American Legion's Department of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``We quite often refer to members of the American Legion as
family,'' Snodgrass said. ``Although Mr. Schick hasn't been able to
attend many functions lately, we still respect his membership and
past services to the American Legion.''
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Schick, who will turn 104 in October, appreciated
Wednesday's presentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chain of command,'' Curtis commanded. ``Move in.''
</P>
<P>
   One by one, officials came up and presented Schick with gifts,
such as a golden name tag and his 80-year American Legion
membership certificate.
</P>
<P>
   To each man Schick nodded, and sometimes shook hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are you doing during all this?'' asked Diane Schick, a
cousin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fine,'' Schick replied.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty Memorial officials consider Schick the Kansas City
area's one remaining World War I veteran, said Christie Green,
marketing director for the Liberty Memorial. And, in recent years,
Schick has done what he can for the memorial. Last summer he
attended a dedication ceremony celebrating the Kids for Liberty
campaign, in which Kansas City area children contributed to the
memorial's renovation.
</P>
<P>
   After World War I, Schick worked as a lawyer for many years in
Kansas City. Among his keepsakes are copies of pages from the
Kansas City School of Law's 1924 yearbook. Schick's photo appeared
there, as did that of Harry S. Truman, who as president signed the
yearbook for Schick in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Family members, however, are trying to find more documentation
on Schick's life and career.
</P>
<P>
   One example is his apparent career with the St. Louis Cardinals.
Bruce O'Neal, a nephew of Schick's from Arizona, recalls relatives
describing how they watched Schick pitch for the Cardinals before
World War I. But Schick's name does not appear in a recent edition
of The Baseball Encyclopedia, the standard player reference, and
family members have no solid evidence of his baseball career.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more important is Schick's service record.
</P>
<P>
   Documentation of Schick's wartime service cannot be found, Green
said, perhaps because of a fire in a national personnel records
facility in the St. Louis area.
</P>
<P>
   If records can be found documenting that Schick set foot in
France in World War I, he would be eligible to receive the Legion
of Honor from the government of France. French President Jacques
Chirac recently instituted a program to honor surviving members of
the U.S. armed forces who fought on French soil in World War I.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
