<HEADER>
A0733 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      07-12 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T FEAR HIRING THE DISABLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ If Karen hadn't kept a diary of her job
search, she would have lost track of how often she was rejected or
simply never heard back after her initial interview. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Karen's award-winning resume got her in the door, but she could
see in interviewers' eyes that she wouldn't get job offers. Why? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Karen has severe hearing loss, and what she saw in those eyes
was fear. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Americans With Disabilities Act guarantees workers with
disabilities the right to ``reasonable accommodation'' to help them
perform the ``essential functions'' of their jobs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What the law doesn't _ and can't _ mandate is attitude
readjustment to make employers less fearful of the costs of that
accommodation or less fearful of integrating workers with
disabilities into their work forces. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After months of searching, Karen finally has a well-paying
position that fits her professional expertise. Her accommodation is
special telephone equipment; listeners have no idea she's using
it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This week in Kansas City, the Association of Higher Education
and Disability is holding an international conference. The
organization's purpose is to increase participation in higher
education by people with disabilities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In today's work world, higher education is a vital step toward
fuller work force participation. Without it, the much discussed
``digital divide'' will continue to be an employment barrier for
people with disabilities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tony Coelho, chairman of the President's Committee on Employment
of People With Disabilities, is scheduled to speak Friday at the
conference. He's likely to sound what has been a common theme in
recent speeches: hiring trained (or trainable) people with
disabilities is good for the bottom line. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As more and more people with disabilities enter the workplace,
employers are seeing for themselves and hearing from others how
productive they can be. Prejudice crumbles in the face of
performance,'' Coelho said in a speech earlier this year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fear fades, too, as more employers see that the costs of
accommodation are not prohibitive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The national Job Accommodation Network says only 3 percent of
employers spent more than $5,000 to provide work site
accommodations for employees' disabilities. Some accommodations
cost as little as $5. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In return, employers get employees who typically stay on the job
longer and get equal or better performance reviews than their
nondisabled peers, at least one long-running study at DuPont
found. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Higher education and high-tech training will improve the
employability of many peoples with disabilities. But there needs to
be a parallel push to educate and train nondisabled workers to work
with them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many people with severe disabilities may be ready, willing and
able to work. They will never succeed in the workplace, though, if
they can't get past the interview because someone is afraid of the
challenges, costs or communication difficulties their employment
might bring. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 2334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
