<HEADER>
A0734 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-VAN-ALLEN-T     07-12 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-VAN-ALLEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERAN CENTER VAN ALLEN SIGNS WITH STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The signing of center Shaun Van Allen, a versatile role player
the past four seasons for the Ottawa Senators, highlighted a busy
first day of activity on the free-agent market for the
bargain-hunting Stars yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Van Allen signed a two-year deal worth $1.1 million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars also signed goalie Rick Tabaracci to a two-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   And two players, 6-foot-5, 225-pound defenseman Sami Helenius,
as well as Stars minor-league goalie Mike Bales, who backed up
Marty Turco last season, signed one-year deals. Terms of the
contracts for all three players were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Van Allen, a goal scorer a decade ago during his minor-league
days, has developed his game over a nine-year career into that of a
dependable defensive forward with good skills.
</P>
<P>
   His experience and versatility in penalty-kill and man-down
situations with the Senators made him a good fit to fill holes on
the third and fourth lines left by Guy Carbonneau and Brian
Skrudland.
</P>
<P>
   ``He suits a style of player we are going to be in need of,''
Stars general manager Bob Gainey said of the 6-foot-1, 204-pound
veteran. ``He is a centerman whose strengths are on the defensive
side of play.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Allen, 32, posted 28 points last season, his finest
offensive numbers with the Senators. His nine goals were two shy of
his career high in 1994-95 for Winnipeg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a defensive player first,'' Van Allen, a native of
Saskatchewan, said. ``I worry about my own end first and try to be
a consistent, physical force, take the body and play a simple
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Allen said his decision to sign with the Stars became an
easy one when the club informed him that they had located a school
for his autistic son to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas is such a quality organization,'' Van Allen said.
``They've been first-class all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Tabaracci, 31, might never wear a Stars uniform. A career
backup, Tabaracci earned $500,000 last season. He played in one
game for Atlanta and two for Colorado. He will challenge Turco to
back up Ed Belfour next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The backup job is Turco's to lose,'' Gainey said.
</P>
<P>
   Gainey said the Stars would send Tabaracci, who has played for
seven teams in 11 seasons, to the club's minor-league affiliate in
Salt Lake City if Turco maintains his edge, as expected. The Stars
needed goalie depth after losing Roman Turek and Manny Fernandez
the past two seasons in pre-expansion draft trades.
</P>
<P>
   Helenius, 26, played 33 games for Colorado last season, none in
the playoffs. In his two prior seasons with Calgary and Tampa Bay,
he never played more than eight games. Bales, who turns 29 on Aug.
6, will compete for the starting goalie job on the Stars'
minor-league squad.
</P>
<P>
   Gainey said he is in discussions with two other free-agent
forwards. The Stars also want to sign a defenseman. Unrestricted
free agent Dave Manson remains one possibility.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
