<P>
   OIL-PRICES (Undated) _ Gasoline prices have risen sharply, but
the owners of gasoline stations are not benefiting from higher
prices at the pump. Elsewhere along the supply chain, however,
higher gasoline and oil prices have meant staggering profits: Major
oil companies are expected to report earnings growth of 117 percent
on average for the second quarter, compared with the quarter a year
ago. Such prosperity has attracted the notice of a number of
politicians, including Vice President Al Gore, and the Federal
Trade Commission has started an inquiry into possible industry
collusion. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Price chart has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ESTATE-TAXES (Undated) _ Small business owners and farmers whose
Washington lobbyists are ardent backers of a Republican-backed plan
to repeal the estate tax seem largely unaware that President
Clinton _ who has vowed to veto the Republican proposal _ has said
he would sign legislation that would exempt nearly all of them from
the tax starting next year. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   PAINEWEBBER-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Judging by the announcement
Wednesday that UBS, the Swiss banking giant, will pay about $12
billion to buy PaineWebber Group, the traditional brokerage firm is
not dead yet _ far from it. At a purchase price of $73.50 a share,
UBS is paying a rich premium of 47 percent over PaineWebber's
closing price on Tuesday, before the deal was announced. By Patrick
McGeehan.
</P>
