   &UR; HOME (Moved in ``l'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ST.-PETERSBURG-DEVELOP (St. Petersburg, Russia) _ Several
homeowners, cell phones at hand, tend their lawns and gardens.
Others are firing up a barbecue in the backyard, while on the
street children ride mountain bikes or skate by on Rollerblades.
Two little girls talk about going with their mothers to get a bite
to eat at McDonald's. It could be a typical snapshot of American
suburban life, but the pork shish kebab on the grill, cooked
faithfully every weekend instead of hamburgers, is just one sign
that this probably is not Pleasantville. It is Kolomyaga, a
condominium development on the fringes of St. Petersburg. By John
Varoli.
</P>
<P>
   EARLY-NOVEL (Nashville, Tenn.) _ On Tony Early and his first
novel, ``Jim the Boy.'' By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SCAFFOLDING (New York) _ It is becoming the signature profile
for much of the city: not the grand deco kitsch of the Chrysler
building or the telltale green canvas of Starbucks creep, but the
unlovely clump of plywood and metal tubing known in the trade as
the sidewalk shed or bridge. The city issued 1,806 permits for
sheds in the first six months of 2000, up roughly 80 percent from
the same period just five years ago. Obstructing sightlines and
walking paths, squeezing already congested sidewalks, the sheds
have become pedestrians' analog to squeegee guys, a minor obstacle
replicated onto every street corner, at least when you're in a
hurry. By John Leland.
</P>
<P>
   SUBURBS-CELEBRITIES (Undated) _ One of the least examined
mysteries of modern suburban life is the impact a small community
experiences when its most famous citizen suddenly ups and leaves.
Did residents of Nyack, N.Y., feel they failed last year when Rosie
O'Donnell packed up her three children and moved to Greenwich,
Conn.? Do house prices in Bedford Hills go up or down when Mariah
Carey leaves town? And would Americans once again start confusing
Chappaqua with Pound Ridge should Hillary Clinton lose her
senatorial race and grab the next train to a place called Hope? Or,
for that matter, a place called Chicago? By Joe Queenan.
</P>
