 COMPUTING Q&AMP;A: ENETBOT ORGANIZES E-MAIL  &HT;     By DAVID EINSTEIN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: America Online's e-mail filing system is terrible. You can't
sort messages by name, date or size. Is there any other e-mail
software that I could use for my AOL mail?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: By themselves, third-party e-mail programs can't work with
America Online because that company doesn't use the standard POP3
Internet protocol for mail. However, an outfit called eNetBot
offers a $19.95 program by the same name that acts as a bridge
between your e-mail software and AOL.
</P>
<P>
   It can be used to send and receive AOL mail from any popular
e-mail program, including Outlook, Outlook Express, Netscape and
Eudora. And those programs let you sort your messages any way you
like. You can download eNetBot at  &LR; www.enetbot.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Cache All the News
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a problem getting the updated page on a couple of Web
sites. I first visited the sites about six weeks ago, and I am
still getting the same pages when I go back now. My friends' pages
are updated every time. I'm worried that I may be getting old pages
from other sites as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Browsers store permanent elements of Web pages the first time
you go to a site so that they'll load faster on subsequent visits.
But the dynamic elements, like news or sports scores, aren't
``cached'' this way.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear why the sites you mention don't get updated, but
you may be able to solve the problem by telling your browser to
check for new material every time it loads a page.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how: In Netscape Navigator, choose Preferences from the
Edit menu, then click the plus sign next to Advanced. In the
Advanced menu choose Cache, then click the option at the bottom
that tells the browser to compare the document in the cache to the
document on the network every time.
</P>
<P>
   If you're using Internet Explorer, choose Internet Options from
the Tools menu, then click Settings in the section on Temporary
Internet Files. In the Settings dialog box, choose the option for
checking newer versions of stored pages on every visit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Keep Internet Local
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently bought a new computer and signed on with Juno as
my Internet service provider. But when my telephone bill came, it
was a whopping $175. I could make monthly payments on a new car for
that kind of money. Is there an ISP out there that offers unlimited
access to the Internet for a fixed monthly fee? Or am I dreaming?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Juno does give you unlimited access, and it should cost you no
more than $9.95 a month. The problem isn't your ISP. It's your
phone number. You are obviously accessing Juno through a toll
number, not a free local number.
</P>
<P>
   Check with Juno to see if it has a local access number in your
area. And double-check with the phone company to make sure it's a
local number. If there is no local number, you'll have to switch to
an ISP that offers one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
2 Ways to Reformat
</P>
<P>
   Q: I need to reformat the hard drive on my Windows 98 computer.
What's the easiest way to do it?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: If your PC came with a ``recovery'' disc, you should be able to
use it to reformat your hard drive. In most cases the recovery
process also reinstalls Windows and all the software that was on
the computer when you bought it.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have a recovery disc, it's a little more
complicated, but still doable. First, create a Windows Startup Disk
(a diskette that lets you start Windows in the event that you have
a problem starting it from your hard drive).
</P>
<P>
   Click the Start button, point to settings and choose Control
Panel. Double-click the Add/Remove Programs icon, then tab over to
Startup Disk and follow the instructions. Once you've done that,
use your new Startup Disk to restart the computer. When the A:
prompt appears, type in format c: /s. This will start a formatting
program, which will erase your hard drive, reformat it and make it
bootable.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind, however, that this procedure will only reformat
the drive _ it won't reinstall Windows. For that, you'll need a
Windows 98 CD. And you can't use an ``upgrade'' version because
there's nothing to upgrade. You'll need the full version, which
will cost you a little more than $200.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Bought a new PC lately? Many come with Microsoft Works, but if
you're looking for a better office suite, try downloading the free
StarOffice from Sun Microsystems ( &LR; www.sun.com &LR; ). Sun just released
version 5.2, and while it's not as robust as Microsoft Office, you
may find that its word processor, spreadsheet, database and
presentation program are all you need.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail David Einstein at  &LR; computers(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
