r f BC-CONDO- &LR;      07-12 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONDO- </SLUG>
  
 BALLPARK UNITS PRICED TO MOVE  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For sale: the shortest commute in the city to
Pacific Bell Park _ first come, first served.
</P>
<P>
   Upscale condos at 1 Embarcadero South, right across the street
from the new baseball stadium, are now available for between
$700,000 and $2.3 million, the property's owner said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And in a rare twist for San Francisco, where bidding wars among
home buyers can send prices into orbit, Eikon Investments of Dallas
said each of the nearly 200 units available will go for list price.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no bidding wars, no auctions, no
see-how-high-we-can-jack-up-the-price schemes,'' said Zack
Davidson, Eikon's chief executive. ``It will be a civilized sales
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Civilized or not, luxury condos in San Francisco have been
getting snapped up almost as soon as they hit the market. Nearly
all the 142 units atop the still-unfinished Four Seasons Hotel on
Market Street _ some costing as much as $5 million _ were spoken
for within weeks of being offered.
</P>
<P>
   Prospective buyers at 1 Embarcadero South will want to move
quickly as well. Although the condos won't officially be up for
sale until September, reservations are now being accepted for
$5,000 per unit.
</P>
<P>
   80 Units Already Gone
</P>
<P>
   Davidson said 80 units already have been reserved, despite there
having been virtually no marketing to date, and he expects the
remainder to move quickly now that the project is being publicized.
</P>
<P>
   James Wiggs, a real estate broker with Pacific Union, said he
wouldn't be surprised if the condos at 88 King St. are bought up
almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very hot property,'' he said. ``Expensive, high-end
properties are going very fast south of Market.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of these properties, Wiggs added, are being purchased by
``the cyber-generation.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was surprised by the no-bidding-war aspect of the
sale. Luxury properties in San Francisco, Wiggs noted, frequently
go for as much as $1 million over the asking price.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very unusual,'' he said. ``Maybe these guys should be
investigated for lunacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Competing offers pushed up the median condo price in the city
last month to $542,000, according to the San Francisco Association
of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   Eikon bought the property in April from San Diego's Urban West
Associated for $131 million. The 233 condos were completed earlier
this year and about two dozen tenants moved in prior to the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Eikon is now completing the paperwork for putting the remaining
condos up for sale. Available facilities include 25 two-story
townhouses and a number of three-bedroom units.
</P>
<P>
   $2.3 Million View
</P>
<P>
   The top of the line is a $2.3 million, 1,360-square-foot unit on
the 14th floor of one of the complex's two towers. This condo
overlooks the yacht harbor, the Bay Bridge and even affords a few
glimpses of the downtown skyline.
</P>
<P>
   But the real selling point is its unique view of the ballpark.
From the condo's windows, tenants will look down on the giant Coke
bottle, the scoreboard and the left-field stands.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to watch the Giants in action, though, forget it.
Far-sighted city planning officials stipulated three years ago,
when the project was still on the drawing board, that no condos
provide a view of the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   But ever since a phone number was posted recently outside the
building, prospective buyers have been rushing to book appointments
for viewings.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those who view the condos make a reservation to buy
right there on the spot, said sales manager Randi Masotti.
``Actually,'' she said, ``we were caught unaware as to how popular
this location is.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents will be required to pay $700 in monthly fees.
Amenities include a pool, a Jacuzzi, a fitness club, high-speed
Internet lines and valet parking in an underground garage.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers will be able to move in as soon as their purchases close.
But if a buyer prefers slightly more upscale surroundings, an
in-house design crew will spiff up each unit to the owner's
specifications.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson, the Eikon executive, said he is having no second
thoughts about the no-haggle sales policy, even though his company
could have vastly increased its profits by allowing market forces
to rule the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objective was always to treat people fairly and make a
reasonable profit,'' he said. ``We're asking a certain price here,
and we're going to deliver it.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-00 2351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
