<DOCNO> NYT20000712.0467 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0749 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDIA-FOST-SFCHRON &LR;      07-12 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-FOST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA BYTES: SITE CREATOR THROUGH SUCKING UP _ OFF TO NETWORK
IN  NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAN FOST 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ So long, Sucksters.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Anuff, co-founder of the hip, irreverent Webzine Suck, has
moved to New York to help shepherd his site _ at long last _ into
the Internet big time. His co-founder, Carl Steadman, is no longer
involved but he said in an e-mail, ``I'm moving to the Hudson
Valley so I can pop in every so often and make a nuisance of
myself.'' (He may have been kidding, but it's hard to tell with
Steadman.)
</P>
<P>
   Although Suck was around before many other media sites even
thought of launching, it has stayed small. Anuff is one of only two
full-time staffers.
</P>
<P>
   uncx But now, after months of closed-door talks, a new venture _
Automatic Media _ was unveiled this week, with Suck, Feed Magazine,
and Alt.Culture forming the nucleus of a new Web network.
</P>
<P>
   What wasn't announced was the name of the network. It would have
been called Pop.com, but that bubble burst when Suck's erstwhile
parent, Lycos, sold that hot domain name to a new venture backed by
Hollywood directors Steven Spielberg and Ron Howard.
</P>
<P>
   But to understand how Lycos even came to own Suck and Pop, and
where those media properties are headed, a little history is in
order.
</P>
<P>
   x It all started at HotWired, the groundbreaking online arm of
Wired magazine. Anuff and Steadman worked in the production
department at HotWired in 1995, but they weren't able to actually
write for the Web site. ``There was a great big psychological
Berlin Wall between the production department and the editorial
department,'' Anuff said the other day. ``We knew we could do
better than those schmucks any day of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   uncx So Anuff, in his first inspired moment, bought the Suck.com
domain name. ``We realized, if we called ourselves `Suck,' our
tagline could be, `We admit it,''' Anuff said.
</P>
<P>
   Other pioneering concepts followed. Suck was the first Web site
to put black type on a white page, Anuff said; remember HotWired's
garish neon colors? Suck also updated its content daily; it put the
content right on the front page, instead of forcing readers to wade
through a table of contents; it reviewed Web sites with a harshly
critical eye; and, most startlingly, it did it all anonymously,
with the writing done under pseudonyms.
</P>
<P>
   It was so anonymous that even the HotWired staff didn't know who
was behind it. Anuff recalled a ``bold, bilious moment when half
the office was reading Suck. We'd walk around and see it on
people's computers, and they didn't know we were doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   After a few exhausting months, however, their cover was blown,
and they sold the company to Wired. ``We sold it for zero
dollars,'' Anuff said. ``It was an equity swap. We got equity in
pre-public Wired shares.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Wired tried _ twice _ to go public, but never got its
IPO off the ground. ``We made out like bandits,'' Anuff said.
``Incredibly stupid bandits.''
</P>
<P>
   (To be fair, when Wired magazine was sold to Conde Nast, and
later, when Wired Digital was sold to Lycos, Anuff and Steadman did
reap some financial gains. Steadman, in his e-mail, said, ``In the
end, I got an Audi TT out of the deal, with `MICRSTR' plates. Which
I promptly crashed.'')
</P>
<P>
   So Suck was part of Wired Digital, which last year became part
of Lycos. Meanwhile, Wired Digital stopped using Pop.com, which had
been its cultural site. Anuff knew the domain was a good one,
though, so when it was about to expire, he renewed it for Wired
Digital, paying for it with his own credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine his chagrin, then, when Spielberg came calling.
Spielberg's firm, DreamWorks SKG, and Howard's Imagine
Entertainment _ with backing from Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen _
announced last fall that they acquired  &LR; www.pop.com &LR;  from Lycos for
an undisclosed sum. According to press releases on the site, they
plan to put short videos online, mostly comedy.
</P>
<P>
   But Anuff pressed on, and with the help of Lycos exec Bo
Peabody, he helped hatch the plan for Automatic Media. Automatic
Media launches with $4 million in backing and a chief executive
officer, Lee deBoer, who is a 20-year veteran of Home Box Office.
</P>
<P>
   Automatic Media has already acquired a domain name for its
forthcoming online network, but no one will say what it is.
</P>
<P>
   Anuff, who will be a vice president of the network, said it will
use new technology to create ``the next generation of content
environments.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds great. But then again, it sounds like just the sort of
thing Anuff and Steadman would have mercilessly mocked several
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   LIMBO STOCK: How low can it go? Salon.com's share price is
heading for dangerous territory. It slid as low as $1.13 this week,
perilously close to the sub-$1 level. (Wednesday it rebounded
slightly, closing up 13 cents to $1.25.)
</P>
<P>
   It's dangerous, because if the stock dips below $1 _ and stays
there for 30 business days _ the company could find Nasdaq moving
to delist it.
</P>
<P>
   CEO Michael O'Donnell remains confident that's not going to
happen, figuring that sooner or later, Wall Street will notice a
spate of what he called good news. That includes its biggest ad
sale ever, to Ask Jeeves, for an undisclosed amount; the hiring of
Steve Reed as senior vice president of sales; and a forthcoming
announcement on the hiring of a chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, O'Donnell said, he's laying low. He has turned
down about 25 interviews in recent weeks, including one with Dan
Rather. (Other media want to ``make Salon the poster child for the
dot-com demise,'' O'Donnell said.)
</P>
<P>
   He focuses on the business, not the stock. ``I've gotten to the
point where I'm not even looking at the stock on a daily basis,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   And in looking at the business, O'Donnell is pushing for
profitability, because that's what Wall Street seems to want now.
When Salon went public last year, it said it did not plan to reach
profitability for two to three years. But O'Donnell now aims to
turn a profit in the next 12 months. ``We're focusing on how we can
get profitable without cutting to the bone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he'll just keep taking his lumps. He figures
Salon has it coming: After all, Salon's journalists don't pull
punches in their writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You throw stones,'' O'Donnell said, ``you've got to be
prepared to take a few.''
</P>
<P>
   FITTING TRIBUTE: Friends of the late Gary Brickman, a pioneering
tech journalist who died June 26, have set up a Web site in his
honor at, naturally,  &LR; www.garybrickman.com &LR; . The site contains
photos and memories of Brickman, as well as details on his
memorial.
</P>
<P>
   A service for Brickman will run from 1 p.m. to 7 p.m. Saturday
at 6971 St. Helena Road in Santa Rosa, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Contributions may be made to the Wellness Fund for Daniel
Brickman, care of Exchange Bank, P.O. Box 403, Santa Rosa, CA
95402. Further details are available at the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Dan Fost at  &LR; fostd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
