</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-ORACLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ORACLE'S LANE SAYS, `I JUST DIDN'T FIT'  &HT;     By KELLY ZITO 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After an hourlong phone conversation on June 30
with Larry Ellison, Oracle Corp.'s mercurial chief executive, Ray
Lane saw the company's future.
</P>
<P>
   And it didn't include him.
</P>
<P>
   While Lane, 53, Oracle's president and chief operating officer,
was on vacation with his two daughters in Oregon, Ellison called
him and essentially stripped him of most of his duties _ from the
departments that reported to him to the deals that Lane usually
cleared.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison, who has dramatically increased his role in the Redwood
Shores company's day-to-day operations in the past year, would
extend his control to the approval of ``every PC the company
bought, to every person the company hired'' under the new plan,
Lane said.
</P>
<P>
   So Lane resigned, fueling speculation of a rift with Ellison or
a tie-in to the now-infamous Microsoft-related Dumpster diving.
</P>
<P>
   But Lane, in his first interview since his resignation, told The
Chronicle that neither was the case. Lane said it was his decision
to leave, and he holds no bitterness toward the database software
company that helped make him a billionaire. ``I just didn't fit''
within Ellison's new hierarchy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, he conceded that the split ``wasn't amicable'' and
``doesn't sit well. I think the president (of a company) should
make decisions. I think the CFO should make decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a CEO micromanage every decision at a
company,'' Lane added. ``It's strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Still stranger was the timing of Oracle's announcement of Lane's
resignation before the July 4 holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the company gave Lane and four other executives hefty
bonuses to keep them with the company. Lane, rumored to be flirting
with posts at Hewlett-Packard and Compaq, received salary and
bonuses totaling $3.3 million _ 10 times more than he made the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, though Lane's retirement was rumored for several
months, the terse, two-line announcement released on the evening of
June 30 seemed hasty and didn't give any reason for the
resignation. And it occurred days after Ellison confirmed that
Oracle hired investigators to dig into possible financial links
between Microsoft and groups that support Microsoft's fight against
the Department of Justice's antitrust case against it.
</P>
<P>
   Both Oracle and Lane, who said he didn't know about the
investigation until he read several newspaper accounts, said there
was no connection between the espionage efforts and his departure.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Lane said the abrupt nature of the news release was
corporate protocol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made my decision, (Ellison) accepted it, and when you have a
material change at a company you have to send out a press
release,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To others, the alacrity of the decision signaled Ellison's
desire to effect a major, but quick, shakeup. It wouldn't be the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison, the self-made billionaire known for his flashy clothes
and daredevil sailing, has been on a rampage of sorts lately. Along
with shifting more responsibility onto his own plate, he's
streamlined the company's workforce and cut Oracle's operating
costs by $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The tactics appear to be working. Excluding investment income,
Oracle earned $926 million in the fourth quarter ended June 20, up
76 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison is ``the transformer, the samurai warrior,'' said Marc
Benioff, a former Oracle executive who founded Salesforce.com a
year ago. ``He's a very aggressive guy and if he thinks Oracle's at
risk and not as strong, he makes a change.''
</P>
<P>
   One source close to Oracle said Ellison ``wanted Ray out of
there'' and is now trying to smooth things over by offering Lane
additional money.
</P>
<P>
   Lane said ``there is no separation agreement or money on the
table.''
</P>
<P>
   Benioff, who recently removed Ellison from Salesforce.com's
board because the firm is developing products that compete with
Oracle, speculates that Ellison and Lane wanted to take the company
in divergent directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry is trying to plan Oracle's future around taking
(Oracle's software) and making it online services,'' he said.
``Ray's skills are much more that he's a strong relationship
builder and strong at running a sales and consulting force.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison and several other board members didn't return calls and
e-mails seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lane denies that any major disagreement preceded his
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, he understands Ellison's motivations for wanting to
exert more influence over the firm during what he describes as a
pivotal point in Oracle's evolution. And Lane says he believes
Oracle will continue to be a ``great, successful'' company under
Ellison's watch.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some investors appear worried that Lane _ who many
saw as Oracle's ballast _ would no longer balance out Ellison's
brash promises to the market and media. The company's stock dipped
nearly 10 percent on the first two days of full trading following
the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a minus to take out such a capable executive and Wall
Street wasn't pleased,'' said Bob Austrian, an analyst at Bank of
America Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Lane, a former Booz Allen &AMP; Hamilton executive who came to
Oracle eight years ago, was also credited with adding integrity to
Oracle and building strong relationships with customers at a time
when the company was known for its aggressive sales tactics and
efforts to boost market share at any cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``He coined the term the `Old Oracle,' '' Benioff said. ``Ray
took the cowboys off their horses and said, `We're going to play
fair.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Some wonder whether the company will revert to its former self.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oracle's going to become what Larry wants it to, and the fear
is that it will become what it was, an art-of-war company that's
not as focused on customers' success as it is winning,'' said
Terilyn Palanca, an analyst at Giga Information Group, a research
firm.
</P>
<P>
   However, some say Ellison's leadership is just what the company
needs as it works to tailor its software to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, Larry is delivering on what Oracle
needs most _ vision, e-business software _ and there's less focus
on execution and operations areas where Ray has been helpful,''
Palanca said.
</P>
<P>
   Lane, who says he is relishing additional time with his family
and pursuing a part-time venture capital career, believes Ellison
could make Oracle more profitable in the short term with his
immediate focus on cutting costs.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison may also better steer the company toward overtaking
arch-nemesis Microsoft as the No. 1 software company in the world _
a goal Ellison hasn't been shy about promoting. Oracle is No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Internet and Microsoft's problems, (Larry) saw it as
an opportunity to drive all the decisions in the company, and it
began giving me reason to say, `Why am I here?' '' Lane said.
``There needs to be one boss, one decisionmaker. There's no
question that at Oracle, that's Larry.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Lane isn't sure how long that can last.
</P>
<P>
   ``During times of great change, I think one person can make all
the decisions ... we'll have to see in two or three years if that's
still the case (at Oracle),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's making a lot of decisions based on profitability and
that's good now. Over the long haul, you have to fuel revenue
growth and people development.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Zito at  &LR; kzito(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
